<SLUG> BC-NFL-TEAM-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. KICKS FUNDING BALL BACK T NFL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Staff writer Steve Dilbeck contributed to this story 
BY RICK ORLOV 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Los Angeles officials sent a simple message to
the NFL Wednesday: Play or punt.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with demands for more money from the NFL to win a
franchise, Los Angeles officials developed a united front in
opposing any public subsidies beyond what's already been pledged.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the state, county and city levels, Democrats and
Republicans alike, issued the message in a variety of forums that
it was now up to the NFL to prove it really wants to come to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the NFL is truly concerned about how well an ownership
group can succeed, they should reduce some of their demands,''
Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky said following a meeting of the Coliseum
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can cut the parking in half (to 10,000) and save $75
million. They can make other changes in their demands to make a
team profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Commission President Sheldon Sloan suggested the league return
to its original proposal by Commissioner Paul Tagliabue that a
price be set on the franchise costs rather than start a bidding war
among different ownership groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they set a reasonable price, a new ownership group will be
competitive,'' Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Nate Holden predicted there would be an immediate
referendum to block the use of any public money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would qualify like that,'' Holden said, snapping his
fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Council President John Ferraro offered his own political
assessment. ``It would pass easily,'' Ferraro said. ``The NFL has
to realize that Los Angeles and California are different. They are
not going to use public money for professional football.''
</P>
<P>
   The tough talk came a day after investment banker Bill Chadwick,
whom Gov. Gray Davis had named as lead negotiator, sent a letter
asking to be relieved of his duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a ploy,'' Chadwick said. ``We had come up with an
exclusive negotiating agreement that the NFL didn't accept. I have
told the governor about what I think happened here and we shouldn't
be negotiating with ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we hear from the NFL, my usefulness is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis was in New York City and aides said he had not made a
decision on whether to accept Chadwick's resignation. Chadwick said
he would continue working on the deal if Davis so desires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still possible to do a deal, but it will be up to the
NFL to respond to the negotiating agreement,'' Chadwick said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In the meantime, representatives of the two ownership groups
were assessing the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, everyone is taking stock and waiting to see what
happens next,'' said Ron Hartwig, spokesman for the Eli Broad and
Ed Roski Jr. team.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fabiani said the Mike Ovitz and Ron Burkle group was in a
similar position.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really not much to comment on until we hear from the
NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Coliseum General Manager Pat Lynch said he has talked with some
NFL staff members, but has not heard anything on what will happen
next.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Aiello, vice president of public relations for the NFL,
said the league is ``in contact with the Governor's Office, and
we're awaiting direction on how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to work with Los Angeles to get this project
done. We have done what Los Angeles has asked us to do, which was
to come to the Coliseum, realizing it would be very expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The league has set a Sept. 15 deadline for a decision on Los
Angeles, even though it is not holding its next meeting until Sept.
22. It could call a special meeting or send out a group of owners
or staffers to meet with local officials at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick had developed a proposal under which the state would
advance $150 million to pay for parking structures to be reimbursed
by revenue and ticket tax money. It also would have given the new
owners naming and signage rights at the facility to raise more
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   NFL owners, however, said they felt more public money should be
contributed, and they want more for the franchise fee.
</P>
<P>
   Such actions, however, would result in a new team generating $25
million to $28 million a year in profits, making it difficult to
field a competitive team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our discussions with everyone in Los Angeles, we said we
were ready to build the stadium privately,'' Aiello said. ``But for
this project to work, it had to have parking. And the community
would have to step forward and pay for the parking and the
infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Aiello said funding solely from bonds wouldn't work because
``(the bonds) are being paid by revenue generated by the NFL games
which takes away our ability to pay for the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
