<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA IS OUT _ OR IS IT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Dodgers did the expected Wednesday and declined a
proposal given by the Fort McDowell Indian Community to build a
spring-training complex near Phoenix, but it doesn't figure to be
the end of the relationship or negotiating between the sides.
</P>
<P>
   It was also announced the Dodgers would return to Dodgertown in
Vero Beach, Fla., for their 52nd consecutive spring training, which
the Daily News reported June 12.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dodgers collect themselves and decide which route to
take in securing a spring-training home for the future, club
president and CEO Bob Graziano said they would continue speaking
with representatives from Fort McDowell because the situation isn't
dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to leave the door open if something makes sense
and I think they're going to leave the door open in case something
makes sense,'' Graziano said. ``We spent some time with the
governor's office and we will spend some time with the governor's
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort McDowell termed it's proposal ``final,'' but neither side
is viewing it as that.
</P>
<P>
   The core problem is with finance. Fort McDowell offered to build
a $40 million complex, complete with six practice fields, a
12,000-seat stadium with offices. But it didn't include on-site
housing, which the Dodgers have in Vero Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were worried about the economical impact of signing
on for the long term with Fort McDowell if it didn't have state
funding. To that, the Arizona legislature meets in January, and
Fort McDowell is expected to ask for financial assistant that could
enhance the proposal and make it more attractive for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to work with both parties to try to get something
done,'' said Chris Baier, director of sports development at the
Arizona department of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Fort McDowell representatives said they would begin discussions
with other clubs in hopes of luring another team but said they
didn't rule out a deal with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers continue to talk with Vero Beach and Indian River
County (Fla.) officials in hopes of landing a long-term deal.
Parties from each side spoke during a Tuesday conference call.
</P>
<P>
   The local Florida community has $12.5 million in funding. That's
enough to purchase the land from the Dodgers and lease it back to
the club, but it leaves no money for renovations to the antiquated
complex. The stumbling block continues to more money, but that
could be changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some opportunities (for more funding),'' Dodgertown
managing director Craig Callan said. ``It's something we're working
on.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Osuna cancels surgery: Injured reliever Antonio Osuna
continues to frustrate and infuriate Dodgers management. The
right-hander, who was scheduled to undergo Tommy John surgery
today, told the club Wednesday he's decided to wait and seek
another opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to be empathetic,'' general manager Kevin Malone
said. ``He wants to do the right thing. That's his decision. It's
his arm. He has to make it. He knows the position of the Los
Angeles Dodgers. We can strongly recommend (to have the surgery),
but what he feels is best is his option.''
</P>
<P>
   Some folks in the Dodgers organization believe Osuna's balking
at the surgery because he wants to prove he can pitch and collect
his $1.5 million option. But Dodgers officials said it's unlikely
such an option would be picked up.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time this season Osuna's balked at surgery.
He had bone spurs removed in May, but that came after he canceled
one surgical procedure. Renowned Dodgers physician Dr. Frank Jobe,
who pioneered the tactics now used in elbow and shoulder surgery,
recommended the Tommy John surgery. Osuna agreed to it last week,
only to stun the Dodgers with his change of mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
