<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6288 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFL-TEAM-2ndTAKE-LADN     08-05 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-TEAM-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: for the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   David Carter of the Sports Management Group said the message
being sent by Los Angeles officials was important.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in this community are beginning to ask how much is too
much,'' Carter said. ``Gov. Davis, Chadwick and the ownership
groups are saying we are not going to acquiesce to all your
demands. There is a changing of the dynamics and the local
officials are drawing a new line in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important symbolic step to say we are not going to
take it anymore,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Several officials also questioned why the owners were seeking a
short-term gain of a one-time payment of perhaps $3 million, when
it could be looking at much more on an annual basis from television
revenue by putting the team in the nation's second-largest media
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the end this will be media-driven,'' Sloan said.
``I think the networks that televise football will have to put
pressure on the league to say whether they want to be in the
second-largest media market or in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaroslavsky said the league also had to recognize the different
public attitude in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, this is a city that put on the Olympics with no public
money, and it was the most successful in history,'' he said. ``This
is not Charlottesville or somewhere else where they need football.
We already have football here with UCLA and USC, and several other
professional sports teams. I think the NFL needs Los Angeles more
than we need them.''
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, plans to try to develop other sources
of state revenue began to firm up.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than return to an earlier proposal that would have
diverted all money generated within Exposition Park to be allowed
to raise additional funds, the plan being developed now would
involve tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   The credits would amount to $50 million over 20 years and would
be given for special events held at the Coliseum, such as Super
Bowls or Pro Bowls, that are directly related to having a football
team in the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is to be made to the state Senate's president pro
tem, John Burton, D-San Francisco, and Assembly Speaker Antonio
Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles, within the next few weeks. Aides to
both officials said they had not been presented with any such
proposal and would not comment. &QL; 
!hair!
</P>
