<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BREWERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS DEFEAT BREWERS, 9-5 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ The level of opposition has been suspect for three
weeks, but that doesn't matter to the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   What is important is the National League East standing. The Mets
are two games in front of Atlanta after Wednesday night's 9-5
victory over the Milwaukee Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the first-place Mets (66-43) were more than a game
ahead in the standing was the final day of the 1988 season. The
last time the Mets were 23 games over .500? 1988 again. That was
the last time the Mets qualified for the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have the best record in the National League and trail
Cleveland and Texas by percentage points for the best record in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   So what if Kenny Rogers allowed five runs in six innings in his
second start as a Met? Led by three hits from Edgardo Alfonzo, the
Mets pounded out 17 hits at County Stadium, most of them after the
Braves had lost swiftly, 3-2, in Pittsburgh in 1 hour 48 minutes.
Robin Ventura and Alfonzo each hit a home run to offset the three
that Rogers allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who deserved to win in his first start with the Mets
last Wednesday, is 1-0 since being acquired from Oakland on July
23.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who won five of six games on this road trip, zoomed
past the Braves this week by sweeping a three-game set from the
Brewers. Since the All-Star Game break, the Mets are playing .800
baseball: 16-4. They have played seven series and have won them
all.
</P>
<P>
   None of their opponents, however, were over .500. (The Pirates
reached .500 by beating the Braves.) Their critics will say the
Mets have not beaten anybody, but last season the Mets were
criticized for not being able to beat the teams under .500, which
cost them a wild-card berth.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have been able to beat those teams this year. Still,
the remaining schedule looks challenging: three West Coast trips,
which will include three games each against the Giants and the
Diamondbacks. In September the Mets will play six games each
against the Braves and the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the Mets' No. 4 and 5 hitters did the most
damage. Mike Piazza and Ventura have combined for 5 homers and 14
runs batted in over the last three nights. Ventura homered in all
three games, Piazza in the first two.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's two-run homer in the second inning, off the rookie
right-hander Kyle Peterson, erased the 1-0 lead Jeff Cirillo had
given the Brewers with a one-out homer off Rogers. It was Ventura's
team-leading 25th home run of the season and seventh in his last
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets added another run on Rogers' first regular-season major
league hit, a one-out single to left with runners on first and
third to give himself a 3-1 lead. (He had an infield single for the
Yankees in Game 4 of the 1996 World Series.)
</P>
<P>
   But Rogers, who was not as sharp as he was in his Met debut, hit
Geoff Jenkins with a 2-2 pitch to open the bottom of the second,
then served up a two-run homer to Marquis Grissom, which sailed
over the center-field fence and tied the score, 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   Not for long. The Brewers' defense is as bad as the Mets' is
good. Piazza singled with one out in the third, took second one out
later when Darryl Hamilton walked, and was being stopped at third
on Benny Agbayani's single to left. The ball bounced off Jenkins's
glove in left, however, and Piazza easily scored the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets left the bases loaded in the inning when Rogers flied
to left. But they scored four runs in the fourth to go up by 8-3.
Piazza singled in two with the bases loaded and nobody out. Rey
Ordonez singled in two more with the bases loaded and two out.
</P>
<P>
   And Rogers had a comfortable lead.
</P>
<P>
   Not for long, again. Before the game, Manager Bobby Valentine
had said Rogers' right hamstring, which had bothered him throughout
his last start, was fine. But Rogers' pitches were up on Wednesday
night. And when Jenkins blasted his 18th home run, with one on and
nobody out in the fourth, it was an 8-5 game.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who was denied the victory last Wednesday when Dennis
Cook allowed a tying home run, needed to go another inning this
evening to qualify for his first N.L. victory, and for a moment in
the fifth, it looked as though he might not make it. But Rogers
induced Jenkins to hit into an inning-ending fielder's choice with
runners on first and second to complete the fifth. And then Rogers
tossed a perfect sixth to complete his night on a high note.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
