<HEADLINE>
METH BUSTS ``KILLING'' AZ TAXPAYERS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINA LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hundreds of times last year, police carrying submachine guns
stormed a building in Arizona, set up a blue tent and cleaned up a
methamphetamine lab.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to taxpayers: $2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The busts have more than doubled every year for the past four
years, and as they continue to explode, so will their price tags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meth is poisoning the community,'' said Detective Mike
McCullough of the Phoenix Police Department, ``but killing the
taxpayer.''
</P>
<P>
   While most people know that meth production in Arizona is on the
rise, they may not realize how much they're paying to fight it. It
costs $8,600 for an average-size lab.
</P>
<P>
   And the cost doesn't even include all the officers necessary for
a bust, officer training, equipment and prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, more than 300 meth labs were dismantled in Arizona by
a federally funded task force.
</P>
<P>
   The meth war is not going to end any time soon, said Jim Molesa,
Phoenix spokesman for the Drug Enforcement Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Once known as a ``West Coast biker drug,'' experts now say meth
is cropping up in every pocket of society.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's literally at an epidemic level,'' Molesa said. ``It's the
drug of choice in the metro Phoenix area, but in other in rural
counties as well, from Springerville to Show Low to Sierra Vista.''
</P>
<P>
   Methamphetamine is a drug that produces feelings of mental
alertness and well-being. It can be smoked, snorted, orally
ingested or injected.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty two different chemicals can be cooked together to make
methamphetamine, including anything from brake fluid to drain
cleaner to red phosphorous &UR; _ a highly flammable chemical that can
easily combust when mixed with water or air and a nearby flame.
</P>
<P>
   Once mixed together, the chemicals create toxic fumes that can
lead to liver and kidney failure, severe lung damage and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest threat to residents living near meth labs is an
explosion &UR; caused by the mixture of such volatile chemicals. But
neighbors can also inhale toxic fumes by walking by, or fumes can
travel through air-conditioning units.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biohazard problem is very real. It's misunderstood,'' said
Don Schneidmiller, a Maricopa County Sheriff's Office lieutenant
who works for the task force. ``What's even more scary is the
thought that what if my kids are going down the street and eating
crackers over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the danger meth labs leave behind, law-enforcement
officials try to remove all chemical traces, which raises the cost
of a bust significantly. Some recent high-dollar examples:
</P>
<P>
   In May, officials dismantled a trailer lab in Kingman that had
been producing about three to five pounds of meth every three days
for the past five years. The trailer was destroyed, and the dirt
had to be removed. Cleanup cost was $70,000. Investigators were at
the site for five days, costing an additional $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   Officers raided a meth lab in a Tempe condominium near Broadway
Road and Cairo Drive in April. Because the lab had been cooking for
at least six months, much of the building was contaminated.
Officers had to take out the sinks, carpeting, flooring and parts
of the closets and bathrooms. The cost was $23,000.
</P>
<P>
   A lab was found in an attic near 40th Street and Vineyard Road
last winter. Because the lab had been cooking for about three
years, officials had to tear out walls and wood in the attic. It
cost $12,000.
</P>
<P>
   Because the federal government realized that most local
departments can't handle this cost, it started the &UR; Maricopa County
Clandestine Lab Task Force &UR; in 1995. The task force includes &UR; 112 law
officers from 35 state and local agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception, its work has exploded.
</P>
<P>
   The task force usually busts three to five meth labs in Maricopa
County every week, spending about seven hours at each site.
</P>
<P>
   An average raid has at least 20 primary officers. Those include
special-tactics officers, a safety inspector, chemists, air-quality
and hazardous-materials experts, investigators and those needed for
transportation and cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   A paramedic usually is on standby in a helicopter above.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``This isn't overkill, this is necessary,'' Molesa said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers have to take such precautions because of the nature of
meth users.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a higher degree of violence with meth use,'' said Lt.
Al Thiele of the Phoenix Police Department, who works with the task
force. ``People become extremely paranoid and violent things occur.
They don't sleep for a great deal of time and tend to get a little
testy.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers at the scene are equipped with heavy-duty gear,
including breathing masks, to protect them from hazardous air.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still unclear how meth fumes will affect officers at
scenes. Some have developed tuberculosis, respiratory problems,''
said Steve Werner, former project coordinator of the meth task
force.
</P>
<P>
   Werner said officers have collapsed at lab sites. As a result,
the government must pay for officers' physicals every year to make
sure there's no poison in their systems.
</P>
<P>
   The task force recently arrested three people cooking meth in a
west-central Phoenix home.
</P>
<P>
   It was an average-size lab, yet it will likely cost taxpayers
about $11,500 for personnel and initial cleanup, Molesa said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors watched as workers in biohazard suits pulled out
glassware, bottles of drain opener and gallons of yellow acid. A
box was filled with jars of iodine crystals, ph strips and bottle
stoppers.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators will take samples of the materials for
evidence; the rest must be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The DEA contracts with a waste-management company that
incinerates or neutralizes some of the materials. Much of it is
boxed up and shipped to Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   An average labs costs from $2,000 to $4,000 just to clean up,
Molesa said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors of such labs said they didn't mind the expense.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey Rowswell, a neighbor of a recent meth-lab bust, said he
could smell the stench from his house a block away, and he wouldn't
let his son near the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would take a loan out and spend $30,000 to get it the hell
out of here,'' he said. ``It doesn't scare me. It's a relief it's
taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the federal government pays for most of the primary
investigators and cleanup, local taxpayers must pay for the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Fire departments are often called in case of an explosion, local
police supply officers to protect the scene and bomb squads are on
call for booby-trapped sites.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers may also end up paying for the aftermath of a raid.
</P>
<P>
   Children are at a higher risk of child abuse and neglect in a
meth house, and may become exposed to dangerous chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   When there's nowhere else to go, Child Protective Services steps
in to care for them.
</P>
<P>
   It happens all the time, Werner said, ``Kids. They're the
casualty of the meth war.''
</P>
<P>
   And for every pound of meth produced, five to six pounds of
chemical waste are left behind, according to the Center for
Substance Abuse Treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institute of Justice recently found that meth
cookers have little regard for the environment, saying in a study
that ``most take little care when disposing of the residue from
meth cooking and tend to pour it down the drain or dump it in the
dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Those toxins can contaminate groundwater.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1998, a lab in a shed caught fire near Interstate 17
and Deer Valley Road.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix firefighters unknowingly sprayed water on the fire,
creating a reaction with red phosphorous. The shed exploded,
causing toxic liquid to seep into the ground. Dirt 2 feet deep in a
30-foot perimeter was hauled away, costing taxpayers $63,000 in
cleanup alone.
</P>
<P>
   The task force is kicking off an advertising campaign this month
to educate people about the chemicals bought for meth production,
and what's left behind after a lab has been dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   Officers say it's a necessary effort, but a needless fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already the doormat for illicit drugs into the United
States, now we're known for clandestine labs,'' Molesa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly an expense we can afford to do without.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
