<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6300 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-TITANS-MCNAIR-HNS     08-05 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-MCNAIR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ When a team finishes 8-8 for three
consecutive seasons, fingers have to be pointed in some direction.
Among the players, it is usually the quarterback who is singled
out. But in the case of the Tennessee Titans, it would be unfair to
blame Steve McNair.
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who enters his fifth season with a franchise recognized
more for moving than for winning, threw for 3,228 yards and 15
touchdowns last season, not bad but not overly impressive. However,
he threw only 10 interceptions, five fewer than in 1997 and the
fewest ever by an Oilers starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   What began to set McNair apart last season wasn't yards passing,
touchdowns or interceptions. What got the attention of defensive
coordinators around the NFL was the way he established himself as a
dangerous two-minute quarterback who excels near the end of games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the game's on the line, I want the ball in my hands,''
McNair said between two-a-day practices at training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Against AFC Central rivals Pittsburgh and Jacksonville, McNair
engineered scoring drives in the last two minutes to pull out
victories. At Tampa Bay, McNair scored on a 71-yard run to secure a
win over the Bucs.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't McNair's fault when the then-Oilers blew games against
Seattle and Chicago. He led them to a late field goal that should
have been enough to beat the Seahawks, but the defense collapsed in
the final seconds. Against Chicago, McNair guided the Oilers to a
tying touchdown, but the special teams fell apart in the last
minute to cost them a win.
</P>
<P>
   Why has McNair been so successful in the last two minutes? There
are different theories, and all make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's successful because he knows what to do in the two-minute
drill,'' Titans coach Jeff Fisher says. ``It's something we work on
a lot. Steve makes very few mistakes in the two-minute drill. He
understands clock management. He doesn't throw interceptions in
pressure situations like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our two-minute offense (before halftime and the end of
regulation), Steve put us into position to score on 10 of 17
drives. Of those 10 drives, we scored eight times (five field
goals, three touchdowns) and missed two field goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive coordinator Les Steckel watches every play of practice
and games over and over. He sees things in McNair that others might
overlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, Steve's fearless, confident and courageous,''
Steckel says. ``Then, you have to realize how mobile he is. There's
no doubt that he's the best running quarterback in the league. In
those situations, not only can he make plays by running, but he can
use his mobility to buy some time while a receiver gets open.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair's mobility and power as a runner get almost as much
attention as his right arm. He has rushed for 1,233 yards over the
past two seasons, more than any other NFL quarterback. Many of his
best runs came on third down or in the last two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a matter of me using my instincts and mobility to
make plays,'' McNair says. ``I feel like I can get a lot more done
if I don't have a lot on my mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those situations, they (coaches) let the players play. We
don't go to the line of scrimmage and have to think. We have our
plays that we run in the two-minute offense. We work on them in
practice. Everybody knows them. Everybody knows what the
adjustments are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm competitive, and I don't like to lose, and I can do extra
things in the two-minute offense. I can do things you won't see in
the first and second quarters. And I think my teammates have
confidence in me in those situations.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Titans are trying to become more consistent on
offense and are working hard to find ways to avoid blowing games in
the end, a habit that has been difficult to quit over the past 12
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little things make a big difference,'' McNair says. ``If we do
things right in the first three quarters, maybe it won't come down
to the last two minutes of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair has been a regular starter for the past two seasons. One
thing the coaches have ingrained in him is to not force the ball
into coverage. Over his team's past 11 games, McNair suffered only
five interceptions. During one six-game stretch, he threw only two
touchdown passes but the team was 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of last season, the coaches have been working hard
to find a way to throw the ball down the field with more
effectiveness. McNair had only two pass completions of more than 40
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We attempted to throw the deep ball as much as anyone, but we
didn't complete as many as we wanted to for one reason or
another,'' Fisher says. ``Steve's not going to pass up an open
receiver to try to force the ball deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve doesn't throw the ball into coverage, but he wants to
make things happen down the field. We have to take advantage of our
one-on-one situations. We have to give our receivers a chance to
make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   If receiver Yancey Thigpen stays healthy and Kevin Dyson
develops, McNair will have a better chance of completing longer
passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried it a lot last year but didn't take advantage of it
the way we should have,'' McNair says. ``I didn't throw long as
much as I wanted, but I think that's going to change. If we can
throw it deep, it'll open up a lot of things underneath and take
some pressure off (Eddie George).''
</P>
<P>
   One NFL personnel director said the Titans should line up McNair
in the shotgun with running back George next to him and four
receivers in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine what it would be like to try to stop McNair
and George in the two-minute offense for the entire game?'' the
personnel director said. ``Thank God it's too much like the
run-and-shoot for them to actually do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
