<HEADER>
A6301 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     08-05 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CYNTHIA Cooper sports almost matching large, blotchy bruises on
both her upper arms, the result of what she calls the WNBA's latest
``let anybody but Coop beat us'' defensive conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   What we don't see is the contusion on Cooper's heart, and the
pain it causes her daily. The Comets' ``old pro,'' as coach Van
Chancellor calls her, may still be the centerpiece of the best team
in the brief history of women's professional basketball in the
United States, but this season is beating her down. Big-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough _ physically, mentally and emotionally,''
Cooper says of a year that, outwardly, wears a familiar happy face.
The naysaying notwithstanding, another Comets end-of-summer
coronation appears likely with the WNBA's twice champs hellbent on
lapping the league.
</P>
<P>
   And Coop, 36 years young, remains a leading candidate to
three-peat as Most Valuable Player despite the double- and
triple-teaming roughhouse tactics everyone has begun to employ
against her.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper is a marked woman, just as the Comets are a marked team.
However, blessed with an inordinate reserve of talent, confidence
and resilience, they're 20-4 and Coop has found a way to score just
a shade under 22 points per game, again tops in the WNBA and only a
hair off her pace of the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento game Monday was typical. Hogtied by the Monarchs
in the first half, she set her jaw, ratcheted up her resolve
several notches and knocked down 18 points in the second 20 minutes
as the Comets escaped the clutches of a troublesome opponent that's
on the short list of teams presumed capable of bringing their reign
to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, it has become popular to disrespect the Comets these
days. Women's basketball has arrived to the point that the talking
heads have taken notice, and lots of them apparently believe the
Comets are ripe for a fall. Of late, Los Angeles is the trendy pick
to go the distance. Sacramento and New York get votes, too. It's
difficult to find an ``expert'' who believes the Comets will go
3-for-3.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Comets' 71 victories (vs. 18 losses) since
the WNBA's inception are almost 50 percent more than any other
franchise has posted.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor, nonetheless, remains a true believer. His faith in
the Comets will be unwavering until it's proven to be unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `C' teams always save their `A' games for us,'' he said,
his voice rising like a TV evangelist's. ``Everyone wants to blow
us off our perch. But this team flat knows how to win. Most teams
are good at finding ways to lose. Our team is good at finding ways
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances, what the Comets are doing would
amount to a resounding second encore, for both the team and Cooper.
Given that Kim Perrot, the scrappy little point guard who, against
rather long odds, willed herself to a front-and-center spot during
the consecutive championship runs, hasn't been part of the
proceedings, it's all the more amazing.
</P>
<P>
   Were Perrot simply injured, she would provide a measure of
ancillary inspiration to her teammates and especially to Coop,
Kim's best friend and basketball soul mate. But Perrot isn't down
in Mexico seeking a cure for a sprained ankle or a wrenched knee.
She has a virulent cancer in her body, and even a third title will
hardly make everything all right in the Comets' orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Armstrong got his miracle, which certainly inspires hope
for Perrot's recovery. But as sick as he was, he wasn't as sick as
Kim.
</P>
<P>
   Ask either Chancellor or Cooper about Perrot, and their eyes
reflexively water up. Whatever great things the Comets accomplish
over the next month, the result will have a melancholy backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's still very much a part of us,'' Chancellor said. ``You
bet we miss her. Man, do we ever. She was my coach on the floor
and, more important, she was the heart of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper has been speaking to Perrot every day, and she was
excused from practice Wednesday to travel to Mexico to see her.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper tries to sound optimistic, although it's not a subject
she is overly comfortable addressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim's doing OK,'' she said softly. ``She has good days and bad
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was asked if Perrot might see the Comets' gaudy 20-4
record and feel irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' Coop said. ``Kim knows better than that. She
knows what she means to this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Note: Cooper said ``means,'' not ``meant.'' While the Comets,
collectively, may not have dedicated their every droplet of sweat
to winning for Kim, she remains a huge spiritual presence in the
locker room. You suspect another title, should it come to pass,
will be celebrated with equal parts satisfaction and sadness.
</P>
<P>
   There figures to be a tear for every cheer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
