<SLUG> BC-PERU-RIGHT-COURT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERU TAKES NEW STEP TO DIMINISH AUTHORITY OF HUMAN RIGHTS COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ President Alberto Fujimori on Wednesday withdrew a
team of lawyers who were to represent the government before an
international court in a suit filed by an Israeli-born television
station owner charging he was stripped of his Peruvian citizenship
solely because of his channel's reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's action comes three weeks after he persuaded Congress
to enact a resolution partially disavowing the court, the
Inter-American Commission on Human Rights, which is affiliated with
the Organization of American States.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Fujimori said he could not accept a decision made
by the court in June calling on Peru to retry four Chileans now
serving life sentences for treason and terrorism committed as
members of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement. The Peruvian
president said any retrial would open the door to the freeing of
hundreds of terrorists and would endanger security.
</P>
<P>
   But Fujimori's new decision, announced in the official
government gazette tersely and without explanation, extends Peru's
disavowal of the court's jurisdiction from matters of terrorism to
a civil case that has drawn international attention to the
president's human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves Baruch Ivcher, the owner of the Peruvian
television station Frecuencia Latina, which broadcast several
reports in 1996 and 1997 critical of the Fujimori government. One
stinging report said the government was spying on journalists and
opposition figures. Another gave details on tax forms filed by
Vladimiro Montesinos, the chief of the government intelligence
services, showing a rise in income from $8,500 to $600,000 in only
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after, the government announced that Ivcher had never
been naturalized and therefore had no legal right to own his
station.
</P>
<P>
   Frecuencia Latina was handed over to minority owners known to be
friendlier to the government. Ivcher has lived in exile in Israel
for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, Ivcher was tried in absentia and convicted of
customs fraud. He faces a sentence of 12 years in jail. Ivcher's
former station manager, Jose Arrieta, has fled the country after
his taxes were audited and he and his family received death
threats.
</P>
<P>
   The human rights court, which is based in Costa Rica, decided in
June that the four Chileans did not receive a fair trial because
they were tried in a courtroom in which the judge wore a mask and
his lawyers did not have the right to cross examine witnesses. The
court is also scheduled to hear a case brought by three judges who
were removed from office last year by Fujimori after they ruled
that the constitution prohibited him from running for a third
consecutive term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
