<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA-ISRAEL (Quneitra, Syria) _ From here, only a few coils of
barbed wire lie between Syria and its land, occupied by Israel for
32 years. To Syrians, the high-tech observation posts on
surrounding hilltops seem to laugh down at them, a boast about who
still controls the Golan Heights. The streets are all but deserted,
off-limits to most Syrians. The buildings are rubble, sacked by
Israeli forces years ago. But such is the mood in Syria today that
when visitors look into the middle distance, they say they see
prospects for an Israeli-Syrian peace that may be nearer than ever
before. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map
has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Zitinje, Yugoslavia) _ Despite the presence of
U.S. troops and armor, ethnic Albanians from this village and
surrounding ones intimidated the Serbs as the Serbs had intimidated
them a few months before. On Sunday, despite U.S. promises of
protection, all the 350 or so Serbs of Zitinje demanded and
received an armed U.S. escort to travel the 35 miles east toward
the border with Serbia. ``Yes, it felt like a defeat, and it was
perceived as a defeat by all the higher command,'' said 1st Lt.
Ryan Leigh, who commands the U.S. platoon here. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Washington) _ A news analysis looking at
differences between current China-Taiwan crisis and the last one.
By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ After months of often hostile
bickering, leaders of Mexico's two main opposition parties are
reporting surprising progress in negotiations to join forces in an
alliance against President Ernesto Zedillo's governing party in
next year's general elections. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOGGING (Seattle) _ Five years after the Clinton administration
hammered out a landmark plan to settle legal and environmental
disputes over logging across the Pacific Northwest, the region's
timber wars are flaring up again, as the same federal judge who
once issued rulings to protect the northern spotted owl has now
blocked nine major logging deals and imperiled dozens of others by
declaring that federal officials have failed to take proper steps
to ensure that other species are being protected as well. By Sam
Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE-TREASURYBONDS (Undated) _ For more than a decade,
Uncle Sam has financed the rising national debt by selling an
ever-increasing amount of Treasury bonds. But looking ahead, the
financial markets are heading for strange territory, a landscape in
which Treasury securities _ a mainstay of professional hedging
strategies, an influence on consumer and corporate borrowing costs
and a safe-haven investment for those with no appetite for risk,
become increasingly scarce. By Diana B. Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-AUTOS (Cordoba, Argentina) _ Fiat's Cordoba plant,
like much of Argentina's auto industry, is operating at less than a
quarter of its capacity. Part of the problem is the recession that
has been shaking Argentina since last September. But of more
lasting importance, auto executives fear, is the fallout from
Brazil's decision in January to devalue its currency, the real, by
nearly 40 percent. As a result, Argentina has lost competitiveness
in world trade and has only a limited capacity to export its way
out of its slump. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MONSANTO-SEEDS (Chicago) _ After spending more than $8 billion
in the past two years to acquire some of the world's largest seed
companies and millions more to pioneer in the development of
genetically engineered foods, Monsanto Co. is facing growing
skepticism about its debt management and mounting resistance to
some of its bio-engineered crops. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Commerce Department is scheduled to
make a decision Monday in a trade dispute that a number of
economists say could take the country's fair-trade laws to new
heights of absurdity. Twelve independent oil producers accuse Saudi
Arabia, Mexico, Iraq and Venezuela of selling oil in the United
States for less than it costs them to produce it. That is a
violation of trade rules known as ``dumping.'' The plaintiffs are
calling for the United States to impose taxes up to about 200
percent on oil imports from these four countries. By Michael M.
Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
