<HEADLINE>
TOLEDO TRIES TO PUT SCANDAL BEHIND HIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Like a comic who had thoroughly rehearsed his
routine, UCLA coach Bob Toledo stepped up to the microphone to
address reporters Wednesday and calmly delivered his punch line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry I'm late. I had to valet-park the car,'' Toledo joked, a
reference to the parking scandal that engulfed his program in
recent weeks and culminated with nine players pleading no contest
to illegally acquiring handicapped placards.
</P>
<P>
   Since these were Toledo's first public remarks over the
controversy, he started off with a disarming comment. But later, he
seriously addressed the issue at the Pacific-10 Conference's annual
media day in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't condone it. I was disappointed. I'm embarrassed,''
Toledo said. ``They got punished greatly.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the protesters at last week's court hearing might
dispute that last statement, but Toledo is trying to focus on
football now, along with the other nine coaches who attended the
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I think is important is you've got to continue to
educate the kids, scold them when they're wrong, but continue to
love them,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo is trying to get ready for training camp, knowing that
nine players will be suspended from the first two games because of
the handicapped-parking scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we've only got 68 scholarship players and 18 of them
are true freshman,'' Toledo said. ``If you don't know the reason,
you've been in a cave.''
</P>
<P>
   The other news of the day concerned USC, and in a sense, it was
old news.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett was unhappy that wide receiver R. Jay
Soward has made only a handful of appearances at summer workouts.
Big shock there, since Soward missed most of the winter workouts
earlier this year and was briefly AWOL from the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It affects me with great disappointment,'' Hackett said.
``After he decided to come back for his senior season, you would
think his attitude would be, `Let's prepare to have a great senior
year.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   USC tailback Chad Morton said he has seen Soward twice all
summer, although Soward has appeared for some media interviews and
photo sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he's not in trouble, that's fine. He's hanging out,
doing little things on the side,'' Morton said. ``He can still be a
kid for a year. There's no bad feelings toward him.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward's eligibility, which always gives cause for pause around
USC, should be better known in the next few days when he completes
USC summer school. He is expected to pass, but nothing is
official.But as even a ``disappointed'' Hackett pointed out
Wednesday, ``once we get to (training camp in) Irvine, it doesn't
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: If Soward is in shape, he will be expected to
return punts, kickoffs and be the Trojans' most explosive offensive
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   USC was picked second in a media preseason conference poll; UCLA
was a close third. But both schools were far behind Arizona, which
was easily chosen to win the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   Former Taft player DaShon Polk, now a Wildcats linebacker, was
cautious about the poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to look at that as nothing,'' Polk said. ``If we
take it seriously, that's the worst thing that can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona coach Dick Tomey was equally reserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing guaranteed you (just) because you've won a few
games last year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Bygones? Oregon coach Mike Bellotti and Washington coach Rick
Neuheisel had a brief conversation that apparently was intended to
bury any impression of hard feelings. The two have feuded since
Oregon and Colorado played in the 1995 Cotton Bowl, and it
escalated when Neuheisel's staff illegally contacted Oregon
recruits during an NCAA dead period after Neuheisel was hired by
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a bitter relationship with anyone,'' Bellotti
said. ``I see it as having a lack of tolerance for breaking the
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Hackett said USC running back Malaefou MacKenzie is
also playing receiver occasionally during his summer workouts and
could be used at that position this season. . . . Toledo said all
four UCLA quarterbacks (Drew Bennett, Scott McEwan, Cory Paus, Ryan
McCann) will get an opportunity to win the starting position.
``Bennett, I think, is the most athletic,'' wide receiver Danny
Farmer said. ``I think whoever it is will fit in nice.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAC-10 PRESEASON POLL &QL; 
Here's how the media voted in this year's Pac-10 football poll,
with first-place votes in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   Rank Team Points &QL; 
1. Arizona (29) 343 &QL; 
2. USC (2) 283 &QL; 
3. UCLA (2) 281 &QL; 
4. Arizona State (2) 242 &QL; 
5. Oregon 192 &QL; 
6. Washington 178 &QL; 
7. California 166 &QL; 
8. Stanford 107 &QL; 
9. Oregon State 79 &QL; 
10. Washington State 54
</P>
