u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-1STLD-     08-05 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMERGENCY SPENDING MEASURES WOULD EAT UP MOST OF NEXT YEAR'S
SURPLUS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 7th graf for updating on passage of House emergency measure)  (See also TAX-CONGRESS and DEBT-BUYBACK) 
(sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress on Wednesday night moved closer to
spending most of the projected surplus in next year's budget with
two ``emergency'' measures to aid farmers and conduct the 2000
census.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, preparing to pass a $61 billion agriculture spending
bill for fiscal 2000, approved a separate $7.4 billion emergency
measure for farmers. The House, debating a $36 billion spending
bill to finance the Commerce, State and Justice Departments next
year, included a $4.5 billion emergency measure to pay for the
census.
</P>
<P>
   Next year was supposed to bring a federal budget surplus of
about $14 billion, the first in 30 years. Wednesday's emergency
measures, which total nearly $12 billion and are likely to pass in
some form, are a strong sign that the surplus may be largely spent
before it materializes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is already gone,'' said Rep. David R. Obey of Wisconsin,
the ranking Democrat on the House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency spending, intended to address unexpected problems, is
a device that allows Congress to spend money beyond its budget. The
money can come from two places: cutting other programs or spending
out of surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   But most domestic programs, except for the military, already
have been cut or frozen. There are surplus Social Security funds,
but Congress has deemed them untouchable, for now. That leaves one
alternative: tapping into next year's projected black ink.
</P>
<P>
   The House also passed yet another emergency spending measure on
Wednesday night. On a 246-to-176 vote, it approved $270 million to
cover $1.5 billion in loan guarantees for steel, ol and gas
companies. The bill, already approved by the Senate, now goes to
the president. The money would come from across-the-board cuts in
domestic programs in the current fiscal 1999 budget.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Obey called the Republicans' designation of the census
funds as an emergency a crime against common sense and ``a
prescription for chaos.'' The law says emergency spending is
supposed to finance unforseeable crises. The Constitution says the
government must carry out the census every 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``A wholesale breach of the emergency designation would not be
too smart,'' said Rep. C.W. Bill Young, R-Fla., and the chairman of
the Appropriations Committee. But the creative accounting for
census funds was commanded by the House Republican leadership as a
way of appearing to hew to the strict limits on spending created by
Congress and signed into law by President Clinton in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has not declared financing the census an emergency.
Nor has the House matched the Senate's emergency measure for
farmers. The issues, like most of this year's spending bills, will
be resolved in a House-Senate conference in September.
</P>
<P>
   The House is scheduled to complete debate on the $36 billion
Commerce, State and Justice Department spending bill on Thursday.
The bill is more than likely to be vetoed by Clinton, according to
White House officials and House Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   It cut the president's spending request by nearly $3 billion. It
withheld $1 billion from the Commerce Department and another $1
billion from Clinton's program to help pay for local police forces.
It denied $506 million sought by the State Department and cut $329
million requested for the Department of Justice, including $182
million from the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also bars the FBI from spending money on a program
called Fidnet, a new initiative to create a computer monitoring
system with the stated intent of combating ``cyberterrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill places legislative roadblocks against paying part of
the $1 billion in back dues the United States owes the United
Nations and also cuts back programs for civil rights and
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, as written, slashed the budget for the Legal Services
Corp., which defends poor people in court, from $300 million to
$141 million. But on Wednesday the House voted, 242 to 178, to
restore most of that money, leaving the legal-aid group with a $250
million budget, a $50 million cut.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate earlier approved by voice vote a $7.4 billion
emergency aid package for American farmers. Republicans blocked two
attempts by Democrats to pass larger emergency aid packages, just
as they stymied an even bigger $10.8 billion plan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency aid package contains $5.6 billion in direct
payments to farmers, $400 million in crop insurance, and hundreds
of millions of dollars in various subsidies for livestock, cattle,
sugar beets, soybeans and other crops.
</P>
<P>
   In other votes, the Senate set aside an amendment, by a vote of
66 to 33, that would have ended price supports and loans for
American sugar growers. Senators also failed to break a filibuster
on a bill that would extend the Northeast Dairy Compact, which lets
farmers set milk prices, by another year.
</P>
</TEXT>
