<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN FOCUSES HIS ENERGY ON 4TH TITLE, NOT NFL LEGACY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS _ With the 1999 Pro Football Hall of Fame Game
days away now, Troy Aikman said that he gives no thought to his
place in NFL history and that winning a fourth Super Bowl with the
Cowboys is what burns inside his belly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've surpassed my wildest expectations in the National
Football League, and it's still not enough,'' Aikman said during a
one-hour, small-group interview session at the team's Midwestern
State University training-camp site Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman's first visit to the Canton, Ohio, pro football shrine
will be to play in Monday night's NFL preseason opener between the
Cowboys and the new Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman said this is a better team than last year's team that
finished 10-6 after completing an unprecedented sweep of NFC East
teams to win the division, only to lose in the first round of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he and others continue to adapt better and better
to Chan Gailey's Offense, The Sequel. He added that it will be
important for tight end David LaFleur, who missed three games
because of injuries last season, to keep himself on the field.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Michael Irvin remains his ``go-to guy,'' and that
the rest of the receiving corps _ Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail, Ernie
Mills, James McKnight, Jeff Ogden and rookie standout Wane McGarity
_ need Aikman to be ``not too tough and more supportive'' with a
group that leads the way in unfamiliarity among teammates.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the return of center Mark Stepnoski will improve
the team's blocking schemes and running game, adding, ``The only
guy who wanted Step back here more than I did might have been (left
guard) Larry Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear of losing, the fear of embarrassment, is what
motivates me each and every year,'' Aikman said. ``At times, I may
be too much of a perfectionist on the field. I don't know if that's
always a good thing. It has helped me be the player that I am, but
I wish I could harness it a little better. I expect a lot. I'm very
demanding, maybe sometimes unrealistically.''
</P>
<P>
   As for thinking of himself as a future Hall of Famer, Aikman
said, ``I've never counted on being in the Hall of Fame. If someday
it happens, I would be as honored as anybody ... but I've never
given it any thought. ''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman turns 33 years old when the Cowboys play at Arizona on
Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, I feel good,'' Aikman said. ``Of course,
(ex-QB-turned-TV sports anchor) Babe Laufenberg told me awhile back
that when you start saying you're in the best shape of your life,
it means only you're getting older, and I refuse to say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Aikman has never played in a pass-oriented offense in
his NFL 10 seasons, he would need to keep playing another 10 or 11
seasons after Dan Marino retired to even make a run at any of
Marino's NFL all-time passing records.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who is signed through 2007, did say Wednesday that he
plans to play ``another three to five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who came into the league in 1989, or six years after
Marino, has thrown for 30,000 fewer yards and 267 fewer touchdowns
than the NFL's all-time passing leader. But what Aikman has that
Marino doesn't are three Super Bowl rings. Marino lost his only
Super Bowl appearance _ 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't throw the ball 30 or 40 times a game,'' Aikman said.
``I've never played in a system where the offense has been based
around the passing game. But if I can leave the game with the
respect of my teammates, my peers and the coaches around the
league, then I would have had a successful career.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman has a .610 career winning percentage (94-60) despite a
1-14 record in his first 15 starts. In postseason play, he's 11-3,
including 3-0 in Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win the Super Bowl as bad today as when I won the
first one,'' Aikman said. ``I don't concern myself with my place in
history. I think winning is what I'm paid to do. I don't think
Jerry (Jones) pays me to go out and throw for 400 yards a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a season that statistically could have been his best
if he hadn't missed five games with a fractured collarbone, Aikman
seems to have arrived at a place in his NFL life where he should be
able to feel good about what he has done. But he won't let himself,
not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as intense about the game, as driven, as impassionate, as
I've ever been,'' he said. ``Sometimes I wish I wasn't as intense
about it. Maybe some of the push that I have, sometimes I wish it
wasn't quite as strong as it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is what it is, and that hasn't changed. I don't ever
think it will.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
