<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN'S HAPPY, HE'S SNAPPY, AND HE WANTS TO WIN AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ In his line of work, Troy Aikman can
never perform the miracle of pleasing all the people all the time.
But it might just be possible to appease some of the people some of
the time if Aikman would do the following three things in 1999:
</P>
<P>
   (1) Win another Super Bowl, therefore allowing Dallas Cowboys
fans worldwide to regain their rightful title of the most spoiled
and obnoxious in football.
</P>
<P>
   (2) Get married at the Texas Stadium 50-yard line at halftime of
the Thanksgiving Day game, therefore peeling back the cover on a
private life that is an obsession with a segment of nosy fans and
media.
</P>
<P>
   (3) Smile more for the network sideline cameras. And this last
item is very important, particularly if it would finally shut up
those sports talk-show callers who have agonized for years over
whether Aikman is enjoying his work.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, of course, the odds are very long on any of the three
actually happening. Start off by completely eliminating No. 2, but
as far as No. 3, Aikman did mention here Wednesday how he wished at
times he wasn't so intense. Could a sideline smile actually be
coming this season?
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the football part. In a wide-ranging interview
Wednesday, Aikman talked openly on many subjects, including the
Cowboys' chance of returning this season to a Super Bowl. No
surprise here: He's very optimistic,
</P>
<P>
   meaning his public stance is the same as it has been for the
past seven or eight summers.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, however, haven't been within smelling distance of
the Super Bowl in the past three seasons. And by most national and
local estimates, they couldn't locate Atlanta, site of this
season's ultimate game, with a map-reading bloodhound.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman did want to stress, however, that this summer he even
believes his own football words. ``Maybe there was a time a few
years back where that wasn't the case,'' he added, smiling. ``I
would come into camp trying to be optimistic, but...''
</P>
<P>
   Well, you get that picture.
</P>
<P>
   What hasn't changed is that Aikman still has a great belief in
team owner Jerry Jones. But now he also adds head coach Chan Gailey
to his list of most admired. He looks at the team's restocked
talent level, and he bounces that off what went wrong offensively
at the end of last season. And so he talks confidently of ample
room for legitimate personal optimism.
</P>
<P>
   And then he also judged the quarterback, while also defending
last season's sudden offensive slump in December and January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel my best years are ahead of me,'' he said, and spoke of
adding five more seasons, or at least three, to what has already
been a 10-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think my game has slipped,'' Aikman added. ``I think
I'm at the same level. I'm not saying I'm the same as when I was
25, but physically, I feel well.''
</P>
<P>
   Happiness is not something Aikman has ever worn on his sleeve,
trying to trick people. What you saw, you saw. But now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy where I am,'' he said. ``This is a good time
professionally and a good time personally. I'm as intense as I've
ever been, and sometimes I wish I wasn't. But I want to win a Super
Bowl today as much as I did the first one.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the people who are close to Aikman, and that's only a
few, say they've never seen him with a brighter outlook. Part of
that is the football thing. Part of that is his recent engagement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm engaged and very happy,'' he said, cutting if off at that.
This might be a result of his privacy surfacing, or it might be a
intense displeasure with the tabloid-like journalism that followed
when he became engaged in early July.
</P>
<P>
   When you are Troy Aikman, life can be good even though normal
life is impossible. Such is the territory.
</P>
<P>
   What won't change is the intensity on the football field. He
spoke freely of being driven by the fear of being embarrassed, and
how he was embarrassed by the lack of offensive performance in the
Arizona playoff loss.
</P>
<P>
   But in the good games, when the network cameras seek a sideline
smile, well...
</P>
<P>
   ``See there, I'm smiling just talking about it,'' he said. ``If
that's always going to be the No. 1 complaint about me, I'm
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, is what all those talk-show callers want to
know. Is he happy?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bizarre thing,'' said Aikman, meaning the question.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, with the Cowboys on Super Bowl rolls, Aikman
talked of not playing long into his 30s. He's now 32, and
retirement is way off on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want our football team to get back the respectability it
once had,'' said Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   Only then would some of the people be happy some of the time.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
