<HEADLINE>
THIS DOGFIGHT PITS BLUE ANGELS VS. MICROSOFT CODE JOCKEYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A dozen bullet holes in the windshield, no rudder and
a few howling dives into the ground would normally be serious
concerns to Blue Angels pilot Lt. Doug Verissimo.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, the lead solo pilot for the Navy's crack
formation-flying squadron laughed off those problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the heck. It's only a game,'' Verissimo, 34, said.
</P>
<P>
   And he was right.
</P>
<P>
   In town for Seafair, where they'll perform Saturday and Sunday,
Verissimo and fellow pilot Lt. Cmdr. Kiron O'Connor, 35, spent part
of their only day off here playing Microsoft's Combat Flight
Simulator.
</P>
<P>
   The squadron arrived earlier this week to plan and practice
their performances, which will take place from noon to 12:45 p.m.
Saturday and Sunday along south Lake Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the pilots took this game seriously. They had to, because itpitted flyboys against code jockeys: the very programmers who had
created Microsoft's World War II dogfight simulator.
</P>
<P>
   In a public relations brainstorm, Microsoft invited the pilots
and 18 support staff out to the Redmond, Wash., campus across Lake
Washington to take on Tucker Hatfield, the game's program manager,
and developer Matt Ployhar.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots had the advantage of experience _ but in their
Boeing/McDonnell Douglas FA-18 Hornets, not the P-51
propeller-powered fighters used in Microsoft's consumer-oriented
game.
</P>
<P>
   So a half-hour passed before Verissimo realized his Microsoft
feedback-enhanced joystick works as a rudder when twisted. He is
used to conventional rudder pedals (which a Microsoftie hinted are
on the way).
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the P-51s, whose guns fire 300 yards, the FA-18s
aren't armed, carrying only smoke pods.
</P>
<P>
   The developers had the advantage of insiders' knowledge and
hours of practice. Still, they were nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is scary,'' Hatfield admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Who won? The ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ground always has all the advantages,'' Verissimo said,
crashing yet again.
</P>
<P>
   All four participants managed to down each other repeatedly
during the one-hour session. No one kept score.
</P>
<P>
   Verissimo is one of the Angels' two solo pilots, who cut loose
when the other four fly in the Diamond formation. O'Connor flies in
position No. 3 within the formations.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots praised the game's realistic imaging and scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's fun, they said, it can't match the G forces, the
Mach 1.8 speed or the sheer exhilaration of the FA-18s.
</P>
<P>
   For anything close to that, they had to go down the hall, to the
bank of stereo-enhanced Midtown Madness driving simulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now those are some great games!'' said support staffer Petty
Officer Stephen Jason.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
