<SLUG> BC-GORE-VISIT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, SON TAKE SECRET GETAWAY TO NEW HEIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vice President Al Gore and his son are vacationing on
Mount Rainier as part of a private, unpublicized family visit, an
official at the White House said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the visit, a senior member of Gore's staff said
Wednesday night, ``The vice president is on vacation in the West
with his son,'' Albert Gore III. ``Beyond that, I cannot comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, an avid jogger and hiker, told the Post-Intelligencer last
September that he was eager to climb the 14,411-foot-high volcano
at some point in 1999, if he could spare the time.
</P>
<P>
   The White House official who acknowledged that Gore was on
Rainier would not comment for attribution. He said the trip has
been kept so secret that even many senior staff and presidential
campaign aides were not informed of it. A Democratic Party adviser
confirmed that account of the visit.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's presidential campaign chairman, Tony Coelho, told a
meeting in Washington, D.C., Wednesday that Gore was enjoying
``private time'' and would be back in the capital on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   John Krambrink, chief ranger at Mount Rainier National Park,
said Wednesday night: ``We just can't confirm that the vice
president is on the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard rumblings even from my own staff that the vice
president may be climbing the mountain,'' Krambrink added. ``We
have had the Secret Service contact us, and we've had the
communications people contact us. We did invite him to the Aug. 12
celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   A week from Thursday, the 238,000-acre national park will
celebrate its centennial with a ceremony at Paradise on the south
side of Mount Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   Krambrink said the vice president's name was not on lists of
clients supplied by guide services now leading climbs of the
mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's son, now 16 years old, was hit by a car, thrown 30 feet
and severely injured as the family was leaving a baseball game at
Baltimore's Memorial Stadium 10 years ago. The episode in part
galvanized Gore to write his best-selling book ``Earth in the
Balance.''
</P>
<P>
   A runner who has completed the Marine Corps Marathon in
Washington, D.C., and competed in Seattle's 1998 Race for the Cure,
Gore has talked extensively about the Mount Rainier climb with Rep.
Norm Dicks, D-Wash. Dicks is a close Gore friend and fellow
basketball player in the House gym.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Dicks had planned to spend time at the mountain late
last summer. But the plan was thwarted by security complications
involving an official visit, and because Sen. Patty Murray,
D-Wash., wanted Gore in Seattle for what one Dicks aide described
as ``a blue suit event.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said, during the September visit, that he was ``looking
forward'' to the climb but voiced surprise at the amount of time
required to learn such mountaineering safety techniques as
self-arrest on steep snow, and the two-day climb of the mountain
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoa! In other words, we need to block four days for this?''
Gore asked.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's athletic plans have also been influenced by
political considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years ago, Gore was persuaded by his daughters
Karenna and Kristin to run in the Marine Corps Marathon, which ends
with a climb up to the Iwo Jima Memorial at Arlington National
Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president later joked in a Runner's World magazine
interview that he could see the newspaper heading, ``Gore drops
out,'' if he did not complete the race. ``In my business, there are
good metaphors and bad metaphors,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Gore paddled into some controversy during an outing
in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   He was maneuvering a canoe along the Connecticut River for a
photo opportunity, but he had some help staying afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Utility officials, saying they were acting on a request by the
Connecticut River Joint Commission, opened a dam and released about
4 billion gallons to raise the level of the river so Gore's canoe
wouldn't get stuck in low water during the campaign visit.
</P>
<P>
   A Gore spokesman said no one on Gore's campaign staff had asked
for the water to be released.
</P>
<P>
   As vice president, Gore has still been able to enjoy a pleasure
that he will probably have to relinquish if he wins the White House
next year _ the ability to take private vacations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went off to the Caribbean one year, and we couldn't reach
him at all,'' said a former aide who now lives in Seattle. ``He
learned to scuba dive, and we knew magazines would be interested.
But what we heard was nothing doing. He was gone. He was out of the
loop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
