<HEADLINE>
ISMAIL FALLS ON LEFT SHOULDER, BUT INJURY IS ONLY A SPRAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys survived a scare of
sorts Wednesday when prized free-agent signee Raghib Ismail fell on
his left shoulder after catching a deep pass from quarterback Troy
Aikman during the morning practice.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail got up and threw his helmet in disgust before being taken
off the field by the Cowboys' training staff. Cowboys owner Jerry
Jones ran down from the observation deck.
</P>
<P>
   Good news of sorts came when Ismail's injury was diagnosed as a
sprained shoulder. He is listed as day-to-day by team trainers.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said Ismail will likely be
out for at least a week _ sidelining him for today's Blue-White
scrimmage and Monday's preseason opener against the Cleveland
Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, who brought in Ismail to juice up the Cowboys' offense,
knows it could have been worse. Ismail should be ready for the
Cowboys' second preseason game against the Oakland Raiders on Aug.
15.
</P>
<P>
   ``After years of watching (players) fall down, you can tell when
it might be bad...,'' Gailey said. ``It wasn't one of those type
deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Mills will replace Ismail in the starting lineup opposite
receiver Michael Irvin.
LIVE ACTION IN SCRIMMAGE
</P>
<P>
   Chan Gailey said the two things the Cowboys hope to accomplish
in tonight's Blue-White scrimmage, set for 8 at Wichita Falls'
Memorial Stadium, is to get some live action for his first-team
units and see some of the younger players perform under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the offensive and defensive starters) really have not
been able to go 100 percent out there in practice,'' Gailey said.
``You want to see that happen. The next thing you want to see is
the young guys who have to play on the first team like (rookie
guard Solomon Page) and the backups who are vying for positions.
You want to see them live and find out if they can make plays when
it counts under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the first part of the scrimmage will be more like a
practice, as the Cowboys need to install some things in the
red-zone offense. Once the scrimmage starts, it will consist of
roughly 36 to 40 plays.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive and defensive starters will go for 10 plays. The
reserves will go for about 12 plays of team scrimmaging, followed
by some goal-line and red-zone work before finishing with more team
scrimmaging from the reserves. TUCKER CATCHING ON
</P>
<P>
   Former TCU receiver Jason Tucker's play in training camp has
been noticed by Chan Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason has been a pleasant surprise for me,'' Gailey said. ``I
like what I've seen from the guy. He's dropped a couple of passes,
but he's made a couple of fantastic catches. Over the course of the
next two or three weeks, we'll be able to determine which is true _
the drops or the catches.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Gailey, who said Tucker has got a little natural talent
and a feel for the game, said the wide-out has already made enough
of an impression to be a viable candidate for a roster spot.
LIGHTNING STRIKES
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' second workout Wednesday was cut short by about an
hour because of lightning at around 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The onslaught of wind and rain that followed reminded
training-camp visitors of a scene from last year when the winds
from torrential thunderstorms were so bad that the inflated Pepsi
Ball blew across town.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' marketing staff was on the ball, so to speak, this
time.
</P>
<P>
   They had the Pepsi advertisement deflated just before the storm
hit. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
