<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD'S NEW ATTITUDE BALANCES TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So you've grown weary of Raul Mondesi's act.
You've had enough of his partying, his petulance, his prima
donna-like disregard for basic team rules.
</P>
<P>
   Before you give up on the right fielder, there's something you
should know.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield once sported a chip on his shoulder as big as the
gaudiest piece of jewelry in his Cartier's starter set.
</P>
<P>
   At times in Milwaukee and Florida and even last year in L.A.,
Sheffield said and did things that made his exasperated bosses want
to string him up by his 24-carat gold ropes.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the left fielder has gone on to become the Los Angeles
Dodgers' most consistent, most communicative, most commanding
leader, a veritable diamond in this salt mine of a season.
</P>
<P>
   If Sheffield weren't adding a little luster to the Dodgers'
prosaic lineup, he'd fit just fine under glass in some museum, a
paradigm of how brilliantly a gem can shine when given a little
polish.
</P>
<P>
   When Mondesi is ready to mature, he has a ready model in the
outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield's worth to the Dodgers goes beyond the 11-game hitting
streak that was snapped over the weekend, his 58 RBI and his .304
batting average.
</P>
<P>
   At various times, Sheffield has counseled Craig Counsell and
chided Eric Young and cradled Mondesi's fragile psyche.
</P>
<P>
   He has quietly become the de facto judge and jury of the
clubhouse's kangaroo court. So respected is his record _ it
includes an NL batting title and a World Series championship _ that
when he talks, his teammates listen.
</P>
<P>
   It's a strange and scary and sappy story, how Sheffield came to
be so valuable to the Dodgers. He had hired an image consultant
when he was with the Florida Marlins, after a single gunshot nearly
struck him down on a street in his hometown and some sinister
saboteur started distributing handouts saying he was HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until he found his soulmate that the Gary
underneath all the glitter started to shine through. Sheffield
bumped into Deleon Richards at the 1998 NBA All-Star Game in New
York and was instantly smitten.
</P>
<P>
   Richards, a gospel singer with a voice as sweet as Sheffield's
swing, has challenged the baseball player to become as familiar
with the Scriptures as he is the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Richards, whom Sheffield wed in the Bahamas in February, ``has
really helped Gary find out who he is,'' Dodgers general manager
Kevin Malone says. It was something Malone also set out to discover
after he replaced interim GM Tom Lasorda last December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had heard all the various stories about him in the past,''
Malone says.
</P>
<P>
   He gave Sheffield a clean slate anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield's image had suffered long before he held up the deal
that sent disgruntled catcher Mike Piazza packing to the Marlins
until he was able to negotiate for more money (the better to offset
the bigger chunk of change he was going to have to pay in
California taxes).
</P>
<P>
   His image had been scuffed up long before he expressed
ambivalence about playing in the 1998 All-Star Game in Denver (he
preferred to spend the time with his three children).
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield already had alienated a lot of fans _ including many
holding front-office positions throughout the league _ before he
squawked about retiring at spring training this year because of
custody complications involving his kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary's always been somewhat misunderstood,'' Malone says.
``Maybe because he says what's in his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield has worn his emotions outside since Milwaukee, the
first stop on his baseball odyssey. He was 19 _ a child, really,
but already with a child of his own _ when he was called up to the
Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being seen and not heard, as all good rookies should,
Sheffield gave players such as Paul Molitor the same sort of
needling Young and Devon White have been hearing lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't know how to communicate with people,'' Sheffield
says now.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield lost his way in a sea of acrimony and considered
quitting baseball before the Brewers shipped him to San Diego for
little more than postage and handling in 1992. That season he won
the batting title at the tender age of 23, batting .330 with 33
home runs and 100 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield was traded to the Marlins as part of the Padres' fire
sale in 1993. A series of misadventures in Florida fanned his
smoldering reputation. Sheffield was charged with driving under the
influence. Another time he narrowly escaped a bullet fired at his
car from close range as he tooled around his old neighborhood in
Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the speech he delivered during spring training in
1998, the one in which he declared, ``(The Marlins) didn't give me
$61 million as a leader. . . I don't think anybody can say you have
to . . . be a leader just because they gave you something.''
</P>
<P>
   In South Florida, Sheffield's words went over about as well as
modest bathing suits. So much for basking in the afterglow of the
Marlins' 1997 World Series title. Two months later, Sheffield was
traded to L.A. He appeared in 130 games with the Dodgers and batted
.302, with 22 home runs and 85 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   When Malone trekked to Florida this past winter to get a read on
his enigmatic outfielder, he returned to L.A. convinced Sheffield
was serious about succeeding in L.A. Nothing he has seen from
Sheffield the past few months has made Malone change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's committed to winning,'' Malone says. ``I think he
recognizes there's a need for him to do what it takes to get people
in line and get everyone focused on the goal of winning. He's got a
tough battle in there. But his teammates know his only agenda is
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone mentions this to other general managers and they curse
the awful telephone connection. ``Sorry, pardner, but I don't think
I heard you right. It sounded like you said Sheffield is a positive
influence in the room.''.
</P>
<P>
   They better believe it. Now a league turns its leery eyes to
you, Raul. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
