<HEADLINE>
MAVS TAKE 2ND IN SUMMER LEAGUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dallas Mavericks assistant coach Donnie Nelson returned from
Salt Lake City early this week a happy camper after the Mavericks
finished second in the Los Angeles Summer League and Rocky Mountain
Revue with a 10-4 record.
</P>
<P>
   In the final game, the Mavericks defeated Utah, 95-75, in Salt
Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the chemistry on our team, from the first guy to the
last guy, really got us through some tough stretches,'' Nelson
said. ``There was a period when we played eight games in nine
days'' and went 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Dirk Nowitzki averaged nearly 30 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, he was doing everything,'' Nelson said. ``We
posted him, he was shooting 3s and tearing it up on the fast break.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were only a couple of games where we had to challenge
him with his rebounding and on defense. But he got rave reviews
from everybody in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Leon Smith also shined before he left for Chicago. In one
game, Smith had 16 points and 16 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Smith and Shawn Bradley are scheduled to attend Pete
Newell's Big Man Camp, which is designed to help big players polish
their games. CEBALLOS PUZZLED Free-agent forward Cedric Ceballos
wonders why Mavericks coach/general manager
</P>
<P>
   Don Nelson didn't offer him a more lucrative contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to get $15 to $16 million,'' Ceballos said. ``I
want to be compensated for what I can do. I don't want to be taken
advantage of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Dallas would be a good situation for me to come back
to, being that they've got my full (Larry) Bird Rights. But they're
just offering the minimum.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson called the two-year, $2 million offer ``fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos said he is entertaining offers from Seattle, San
Antonio, Houston, Miami, New York, Atlanta and the Los Angeles
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nellie's a good guy, but I just can't read Nellie,'' he said.
``I never know what he's thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, he told me to wait until he gets a point guard, and
then they got Steve Nash. All I've done is waited. I don't know
what else I've got to do.'' TRENT HAS COMPETITION
</P>
<P>
   Forward Gary Trent, the Mavericks' top free-agent priority, is
competing with forward Shandon Anderson for an offer from Seattle,
a source close to the situation said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who played for Utah last season, is seeking a $6
million-a-year contract from the Jazz, but Utah is offering $3
million to $4 million, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the three-year, $11.28 million contract the Sonics
are contemplating offering Trent might wind up in Anderson's lap.
</P>
<P>
   Also, free-agent guard Mitch Richmond, who is tops on Seattle's
wish list, is leaning toward re-signing with Washington, the source
said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6337 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-ASTROS-HN     08-05 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
As the beneficiary of baseball's richest contract, Kevin Brown will
be able to buy a team by the time the Los Angeles Dodgers are
finished paying him the $105 million he is due over the next seven
years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No need to consider the Astros; he already owns them.
</P>
<P>
   Brown outdueled Chris Holt in a classic pitchers' showdown and
hung a 2-1 loss on the Astros in the process Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was oustanding and then some, outdueling Holt and the
Astros before 31,771 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   On almost any other night, Holt would have picked up his third
win; instead he lost No. 11 in the most painful of ways. The
hard-luck righthander held the Dodgers to four hits and two runs
(one earned) in eight innings, the unearned run coming as a result
of his own throwing error.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, talk of Brown's dominance was the buzz
following Wednesday's game _ and rightfully so _ but Holt might
have replaced him in the spotlight with a break here or there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brown was as good as usual,'' Astros shortstop Tim Bogar said.
``When he made mistakes, we didn't hit them, and after that he just
put you away. It's amazing how he can throw that hard and get the
ball to move as much as it does.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad part about this game is that Holtie pitched just as
well, if not better than Brown, but we just came up short.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' loss allowed Cincinnati to move within 1{ games of
first place in the National League Central Division. The Reds
defeated Colorado 6-3 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown fired a four-hitter and improved his record to 3-2 with a
1.50 ERA in seven career starts against the Astros. How can such
dominance be explained? Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell didn't
have to search long for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got 28 different arm angles, he's throwing sliders,
sinkers, cutters, forkballs, he's throwing 95 mph, and when he
keeps the ball down, it's sayonara,'' Bagwell said. ``I've never
seen the guy struggle. He's always dominated us.''
</P>
<P>
   Including his 1998 postseason mastery as a member of the San
Diego Padres, Brown has held the Astros to three runs on 13 hits in
his last 31 innings against them. He has struck out 36 batters
during that stretch, including seven Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell, Bill Spiers and Richard Hidalgo were the only Astros
to get a hit against Brown, who tossed his second complete game of
the season. Bell was 2-for-4 and drove home the Astros' run with a
two-out double in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Wednesday, Bell had seven strikeouts and just one hit
in 15 career at-bats against Brown. But lately, it seems Bell can
hit just about anyone. He is batting .380 in his last 13 games to
raise his batting average to .255 _ the highest it has been since
June 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just been trying to have quality at-bats, and I've been
putting some flex in my legs,'' Bell said. ``If I had known putting
flex in my legs would get me going, I would have done it earlier in
the season.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Brown, Bell said: ``It was the same old nasty Brown with
that nasty slider. The bottom just falls out of that thing. Chris
did a great job of keeping the game close; they just got the
breaks, and we didn't. Chris has had a lot of hard luck this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   While Holt didn't exhibit Brown's flair, he was every bit as
effective, and in some ways identical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the same approach as he does, and that is to go after
guys and try to induce ground balls,'' said Holt, who has watched
the Astros average just 3.1 runs in his losses. ``I knew it was
going to be this kind of low-scoring game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a 2-11 pitcher. I know I keep saying that, but there's
nothing I can do about it except keep trying to keep the team in
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   What clearly bothered Holt more than anything else was that he
committed his first error of the season _ and it led to the
decisive run in the game.
</P>
<P>
   With the Astros trailing 1-0 in the seventh inning, Holt fielded
a leadoff bunt by Dodgers center fielder Devon White and his errant
throw on the bunt single allowed White to advance to second.
</P>
<P>
   White ultimately scored from third on Craig Counsell's
fielder's-choice grounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shouldn't have thrown that ball away,'' said Holt, who has
allowed only three earned runs in his last 22 innings in the
Astrodome. ``If I make that throw, it's an out. If I make a good
throw, it's a whole different inning and a whole different game.
That's a play I should make.''
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Beltre's RBI single in the second accounted for the
Dodgers' other run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
