<SLUG> BC-SANDWICH-TRUCKS-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: public health as a responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The owner was cited with three violations, including the broken
blower, hot food kept at an improper temperature and food kept in
unprotected conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the truck, Tony Moufarrege, said a blown fuse
caused the refrigerator's blower to stop working. He said he
strives to keep his fleet of 15 trucks up to code but that the
streets take a toll and can break machinery.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes it is unfair to hold trucks to the same
health standards as restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to obey the rules but sometimes the rules are too
much,'' Moufarrege said. ``The restaurant sits there 100 years,
this truck moves every 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   By stopping at upward of 15 different locations each day, the
truck serves about 150 meals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Imbrenda's second inspection of the day led to another closure.
The refrigerator in the Eagle Foods truck parked outside a San
Fernando business read 66 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Vendor Sarah Jaimes said she assumed the refrigerator was
working because she could hear the fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to do the best for my customers so when the health
department comes they don't get us. Plus, you feel a lot better
working in a clean truck,'' Jaimes said. ``We try to do everything
but it's very hard. If something breaks you fix it and the next day
something else breaks and you have to fix that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaimes said she gets inspected about twice a month.
</P>
<P>
   Imbrenda gave the refrigerator time to cool but after about 15
minutes it was still not cold enough. Two violations were recorded
_ cold food stored at improper temperatures and an improperly
working fridge.
</P>
<P>
   As Imbrenda ordered the sausage links, burritos and chicken be
thrown away, he noted, ``Food-borne illness can be very violent and
severe.''
</P>
