<SLUG> BC-SANDWICH-TRUCKS-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH INSPECTORS FIND FAULT WITH FOOD TRUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Staff writer Douglas Haberman contributed to this story 
BY JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Even in the shade of a tree, the temperature
outside the Los Pastores sandwich truck crept toward 100 degrees as
county health inspector Tony Imbrenda examined the refrigerator
stocked with pork and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Gasping and struggling at 52 degrees, the refrigerator was more
than 10 degrees above the minimum level set by the state.
</P>
<P>
   The chance of the food spoiling in those conditions was too
great, so Imbrenda said he had no choice but to shut down the truck
and destroy the food.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hot today that it's just not cutting it,'' Imbrenda
said Wednesday of the refrigerator in the Los Pastores truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conditions are a lot more difficult to control in these trucks
in the summer. So the idea is to catch them early and make sure
everything is working properly before they head out.''
</P>
<P>
   As the summer sizzles, the county's 25 health inspectors are
waging war against bacteria and other food-borne threats to people
who eat at the 2,500 permitted hot trucks or 4,500 hot dog carts
and other mobile food stands.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows for sure how many operate without permits.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials said they act quickly to close trucks and
pursue legal action because the trucks move around so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can close them one day but there's little outside a boot to
prevent these guys from stocking up and heading out again the next
day,'' said Kenneth L. Marks, the county's chief environmental
health specialist who oversees the vehicle inspection program.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike restaurants, these trucks are not required to carry
letter grades that clearly signify whether they have passed
inspections. That could change, however. The Board of Supervisors
will receive a recommendation to include the trucks in the rating
system within the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're clearly looking at this,'' said John Schunhoff, chief of
operations for the county Department of Health Services' public
health programs.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwich trucks were left out of the original ordinance so the
county could focus on the 20,000 restaurants and 10,000 food
markets it monitors, Schunhoff said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the heat soared to 97 in the Northridge community
of Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley and a strong high pressure
ridge over the area meant temperatures will stay hot through the
weekend, weather officials said.
</P>
<P>
   That made Imbrenda's job all the more important.
</P>
<P>
   The refrigerator is the first place he looks, because that is
all that keeps the sandwich meat, chicken patties, sausage links,
cheese and other staples at the state-mandated 41 degrees or
cooler.
</P>
<P>
   And in each of three routine inspections done before noon
Wednesday, that piece of equipment was either broken or not up to
standards.
</P>
<P>
   All three trucks were shut down, and the operator's public
health permit was suspended. The owner must make the repairs and
pass a reinspection before the trucks can go back on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Those owners with prior violations likely will be prosecuted in
Municipal Court and face fines, inspection fees and restitution
that can top $2,000, Imbrenda said. First-time offenders usually
get a warning during a hearing with health inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   In his first inspection of the day, Imbrenda pulled up to a hot
truck in the parking lot of an industrial park in the Pacoima
community in the San Fernando Valley and immediately saw a problem
_ wastewater pouring out of tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Imbrenda checked the refrigerator and found the blower was not
working. That alone is enough to shut down the truck, but Imbrenda
found other violations of state and county health codes.
</P>
<P>
   A container of meat mixed with carrots and other vegetables was
sitting out, improperly cooling at room temperature, he said. Fried
chicken patties sat stacked next to the grill but should have been
in the refrigerator, Imbrenda said.
</P>
<P>
   The hot sandwiches in a warming oven accessible to customers
were uncovered, also posing a risk of contamination, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Imbrenda began to gather evidence like a detective.
</P>
<P>
   He took a photo of the thermometer as it read the refrigerator
temperature and took a sample of the fried chicken and cheese from
the refrigerator. Both samples were sealed in plastic evidence bags
and will be stored in a walk-in evidence freezer at the health
department's headquarters in Monterey Park.
</P>
<P>
   The chicken, sausage and grated cheese in the broken
refrigerator were removed and later destroyed by being chopped up,
covered with soap and thrown away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being closed down is not a fun thing for them _ it's a
hardship,'' Imbrenda said. ``But we don't care because it's a
public health issue. The people who do this have a very idealistic
approach and look at public health as a responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
