<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-SPEED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOT SPEED CARRIES RANGERS PAST TWINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Texas Rangers' high-octane offense runs
on wood. The bats, driving balls to the outer reaches of ballparks,
are why the team is second in the American League in runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   They won four of the first five games of the current homestand
by hitting .358 and scoring 43 runs. They scored at least nine
times in three of those games.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, though, the Rangers were forced to seek an
alternate source of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The bats were comparatively silent against Minnesota Twins ace
Brad Radke and four relievers, managing only nine singles and one
double. So, the Rangers used shoe leather to beat the Twins, 3-1,
manufacturing all three runs with good base running.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finding different ways to win,'' said shortstop Royce
Clayton, who stole a base and scored the final run in the seventh
inning. ``Radke was tough. We really had to manufacture runs.''
</P>
<P>
   After being shut out for the first five innings by Radke, the
Rangers broke through in the sixth because of Rusty Greer's hustle.
</P>
<P>
   Greer singled with one out, and Juan Gonzalez followed with a
sharp single to center. Twins outfielder Jacque Jones charged the
ball, but Greer didn't hesitate at second. He put his head down and
sprinted toward third, sliding in headfirst just in front of Jones'
throw.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed Greer to score when Rafael Palmeiro sent a deep
drive to center field that Jones caught with a leap at the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that won the game for us, Rusty going from first to
third,'' third base coach Jerry Narron said. ``A lot of players
don't make that play. They shut it down at second.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored twice more in the seventh, thanks to speed
and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, rookie outfielder Ruben Mateo hit a ground ball to
third and hustled down the line. Twins infielder Corey Koskie had
to hurry his throw, and Mateo was safe with an infield single when
the ball eluded first baseman Doug Mientkiewicz.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo stole second, and remained there when Twins shortstop
Cristian Guzman and second baseman Denny Hocking tried to fool him
with a decoy play, pretending the ball got past them and went into
the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton followed with a sharp grounder to first. If Mateo had
still been at first, it might have been a double play. Instead,
Clayton beat it out _ thanks to a favorable call by umpire Joe
Brinkman _ while Mateo went to third.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton also stole second, and again the Twins tried to fool the
rookie. Catcher Terry Steinbach threw to Guzman instead of Hocking,
who was covering the bag, hoping to catch Mateo straying. Mateo,
though, didn't move.
</P>
<P>
   With runners at second and third and one out, the Twins played
the infield in. Mark McLemore slapped a single to right field, and
both runners scored. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
