<SLUG> BC-NAVY-WOMEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN SAILORS FIND THE USS DECATUR AN ESPECIALLY GOOD FIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE USS DECATUR _ On her first ship, Petty Officer Pamela
Munsey went head-to-head with the Old School Navy Guys and hated
every minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   Now the gunner's mate 2nd class is on the Decatur, and she
couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a woman in the Navy _ on this ship _ is just like being
a man in the Navy,'' Munsey said Wednesday as the ship headed for
Seattle's Elliott Bay and its Seafair celebration, along with a
handful of other Navy and Coast Guard ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``On my first ship, they had only been integrated a year when I
got there, and they set me up to fail in my job. My job includes
having to lift 65-pound projectiles. The guys would tell me `Why
don't you step back and let me do that for you?' They weren't
letting me do what I was trained for,'' Munsey said.
</P>
<P>
   In a vocation where gender didn't matter for 200 years _ because
everyone was male _ now it doesn't seem to matter all that much.
About 13 percent of the Navy's enlisted force is made up of women;
about 14 percent of its officer corps is female.
</P>
<P>
   Munsey is one of 56 women on the Decatur, one of only a handful
of Navy combat ships built from the keel up to accommodate women
sailors.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year old, the Decatur is another step in the Navy's
goal of integration _ the Navy's word for mixing some of the 51,251
women in the Navy into the combat fleet.
</P>
<P>
   There are 155 ships in the fleet with women crew members; 104 of
those are combat ships.
</P>
<P>
   Most are older than the Decatur, and need extensive modification
before enlisted women are allowed to serve on them; women officers
are able to serve on any ship because they have semi-private
staterooms.
</P>
<P>
   The Decatur was built from scratch with women in mind. That
means bathrooms that can turn them from a men's room to a woman's
room with the flip of a sign, depending on demand, as well separate
bunking, shower areas and bathrooms _ sans urinals..
</P>
<P>
   But that's about it, aside from the 1950s-college-dorm-way of
calling out ``Man on the deck,'' when a man needs to enter the
women's quarters, or ``Woman on the deck,'' when the situation is
reversed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Integration here is transparent,'' said Lt. J.T. Garry, the
destroyer's combat-systems officer. He started sailing 10 years
ago, before the 1991 Tailhook scandal sparked a massive culture
change in the Navy . ``From a leadership or management perspective,
no one notices if a sailor's a man or a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Woman work on deck crews _ sweating and swearing the air purple
as do male sailors when they haul in mooring lines. They steer the
ship, work in supply and can fire missiles, torpedoes and guns, if
assigned to do so. ``You have your ups and your downs,'' said Lt.
j.g. Kathy Sandoz, the Decatur's first lieutenant, one of six
female officers on the destroyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ups are we don't have many problems on this ship, everyone
works together pretty well. The downs is that my former commanding
officer told me that women have a different way of looking at
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought about this until he told me. If I'm standing
watch and a contact comes up (on the ship's radar or sonar), I'll
ask my partner (another female officer) what she thinks. We'll
confer on it. If it happens when the watch team after us is on _
they're both men _ they'd just say `Here's the contact,' and act on
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that's from being a woman or just being me.
But it was something I had to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all women have had a good experience as sailors. There
have been stories about shipboard sexual relationships, unwanted
pregnancies and female sailors being passed over for duty.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Decatur, sailors said it's much smoother because from
the time the ship was launched, there were women on its crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problems are logistical,'' Sandoz said. ``We have 60 racks
for women to sleep in. When we have visitors, we have to be very,
very specific about what kind we get.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each summer we get midshipmen here to train. We have
</P>
<P>
   to look at our berthing and say `OK, we can only handle four
women and six men', or whatever it is.''
</P>
<P>
   All the sailors who report to Ensign Faith Tabatsko, the
destroyer's strike officer, are male. And, she said, no one has a
problem with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at the Naval Academy, I heard the stories about how
women were treated there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the only time we ever had a problem with it was when the
alumni would come back to the campus and these guys who graduated
in the '20s or '30s would get offended at women there.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that is because the Navy began its major culture change
in the wake of the 1991 Tailhook scandal, now almost a decade past.
The average crew member on the Decatur has been in the Navy four
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ship, the guys I work with, have all been to schools with
women before,'' Munsey said. ``They're used to us, to having us
around.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Decatur came into Elliott Bay, the ship's crew was sent
to ``man the rails'' _ standing along the deck for show. Jeannette
Perez, a boatswain's mate 3rd class was with them, hands clasped
behind her back looking at the Seattle skyline, patiently waiting
for the destroyer to dock so she could help with the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I feel like I can't complain about something,
because the guys aren't complaining,'' Perez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the chain of command here is very good about supporting
you. I think they've got a good balance. I don't feel like I'm a
female here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm a sailor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
