<HEADLINE>
THIS DOGFIGHT PITS BLUE ANGELS VS. MICROSOFT CODE JOCKEYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A dozen bullet holes in the windshield, no rudder and
a few howling dives into the ground would normally be serious
concerns to Blue Angels pilot Lt. Doug Verissimo.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, the lead solo pilot for the Navy's crack
formation-flying squadron laughed off those problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the heck. It's only a game,'' Verissimo, 34, said.
</P>
<P>
   And he was right.
</P>
<P>
   In town for Seafair, where they'll perform Saturday and Sunday,
Verissimo and fellow pilot Lt. Cmdr. Kiron O'Connor, 35, spent part
of their only day off here playing Microsoft's Combat Flight
Simulator.
</P>
<P>
   The squadron arrived earlier this week to plan and practice
their performances, which will take place from noon to 12:45 p.m.
Saturday and Sunday along south Lake Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the pilots took this game seriously. They had to, because it
pitted flyboys against code jockeys: the very programmers who had
created Microsoft's World War II dogfight simulator.
</P>
<P>
   In a public relations brainstorm, Microsoft invited the pilots
and 18 support staff out to the Redmond, Wash., campus across Lake
Washington to take on Tucker Hatfield, the game's program manager,
and developer Matt Ployhar.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots had the advantage of experience _ but in their
Boeing/McDonnell Douglas FA-18 Hornets, not the P-51
propeller-powered fighters used in Microsoft's consumer-oriented
game.
</P>
<P>
   So a half-hour passed before Verissimo realized his Microsoft
feedback-enhanced joystick works as a rudder when twisted. He is
used to conventional rudder pedals (which a Microsoftie hinted are
on the way).
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the P-51s, whose guns fire 300 yards, the FA-18s
aren't armed, carrying only smoke pods.
</P>
<P>
   The developers had the advantage of insiders' knowledge and
hours of practice. Still, they were nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is scary,'' Hatfield admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Who won? The ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ground always has all the advantages,'' Verissimo said,
crashing yet again.
</P>
<P>
   All four participants managed to down each other repeatedly
during the one-hour session. No one kept score.
</P>
<P>
   Verissimo is one of the Angels' two solo pilots, who cut loose
when the other four fly in the Diamond formation. O'Connor flies in
position No. 3 within the formations.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots praised the game's realistic imaging and scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's fun, they said, it can't match the G forces, the
Mach 1.8 speed or the sheer exhilaration of the FA-18s.
</P>
<P>
   For anything close to that, they had to go down the hall, to the
bank of stereo-enhanced Midtown Madness driving simulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now those are some great games!'' said support staffer Petty
Officer Stephen Jason.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6347 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN     08-05 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGE CAN'T HOLD BACK CUPID'S ARROWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DENNIS MCCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- There are a lot of ways a guy can break the ice
when he wants to talk to a woman he finds particularly attractive.
</P>
<P>
   The weather. What's wrong with the Dodgers? The wacky Clintons.
Things like that.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Jaye decided to go for the direct approach. When you're 89,
you don't have a lot of time to waste on small talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, how's your love life?'' he asked Edith Fishman the first
time he laid eyes on her this June over at the Jewish Home for the
Aging in the Reseda community of Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not bad,'' the 78-year-old widow said, without batting an eye.
``How's yours?''
</P>
<P>
   They smiled at each other and bells went off.
</P>
<P>
   It was love at first quip.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday, in front of four generations of their families,
Edith and Joe are tying the knot after four years of widowhood for
each.
</P>
<P>
   Joe wants it known up front there's absolutely no truth to the
rumors flying around the home that he's after Edith's money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although she does have a lot,'' he told me Wednesday. ``I
checked _ $61. Net.''
</P>
<P>
   Edith shakes her head and laughs. She's been doing a lot of
laughing the past couple of months since Joe walked into her life,
she says.
</P>
<P>
   It's like Burns and Allen are back, people around the home say.
You'd better be quick, or you'll miss the best lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe, tell me again why I'm marrying you?'' Edith says. ``I
forgot.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe's eyes light up. What a great straight woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at her,'' he says, proudly. ``She's got all the negatives
a man could want.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I gave all the women around here a chance at me, but
there were no takers,'' Joe says. ``Then Edith showed up, and I
swept her off her feet with my charm.''
</P>
<P>
   Edith shoots him a look that says, ``Yeah, right, pal. In your
dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   All the laughs and one liners are great, their friends say, but
they tend to overshadow the real story here.
</P>
<P>
   The love story.
</P>
<P>
   You don't marry someone just because they make you laugh. You
marry them because they touch something deep inside you that's been
missing after years of living alone. Something you want back.
</P>
<P>
   The tenderness of another person, Joe and Edith call it, turning
serious for a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both have missed not having someone to hold in our arms, or
just hold hands with,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter whether you're young or old, Edith says.
Romance is romance, and it's a wonderful feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Joe smiles and nods. ``It was the right time, the right
chemistry,'' he says, taking Edith's hand as they walk down the
hallway to the dining room for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Enough of this sappy stuff, the look in their eyes says. It's
time for Burns and Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere has changed in this place since we told
everybody we're getting married,'' Joe says with a big smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can feel the hormones stirring in them again, even though
they've been dead for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come by congratulating us, eyeing us,'' he says,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, after the wedding ceremony Sunday, the bride and
groom plan to honeymoon at home because that's where they get all
their meals and medication, they say.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect them for breakfast, Edith says.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
