A6348 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     08-05 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 MEDIA DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They staged the annual PAC-10 football media
session Wednesday at the Gateway Sheraton near LAX, and all the
conference's coaches except one got up and spoke about their teams'
strengths and weaknesses for the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   There was USC's Paul Hackett telling about how the rebuilding
Trojans are now on a path destined to land the team back in its
ancestral roots, the Rose Bowl, in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   There was Washington's Rick Neuheisel discussing his decision to
leave one pressurized job at Colorado for another one in Seattle
where the shadow of Don James still stalks whoever is in charge of
the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   There was Arizona's Dick Tomey relating how difficult it will be
for his heralded team to match last season's 12-1 record and how he
plans once again to alternate his two extraordinary quarterbacks,
Kevin Smith and Ortege Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   And there was UCLA's Bob Toledo talking about, oh, parking
violations instead of the departure of Cade McNown, or the running
skills of DeShaun Foster, or the incredible athletic ability of
Freddie Mitchell, or anything other than where his players parked
their cars last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry I'm late, but I had to valet park my car,'' joked Toledo
in his opening comments to the reporters as he stood at the podium
with his All American candidate receiver, Danny Farmer, seated next
to him. ``I didn't want to get Danny in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   As you might know, there were 11 UCLA football players recently
nabbed for illegally obtaining handicap parking permits, a
development that has resulted in widespread condemnation of the
Bruin players and cast a negative light on the school's football
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a list drawn up on a piece of paper of things I don't
want any of my players to do,'' said Toledo. And one of them is not
to park in handicap parking spaces. That's something I've
emphasized a lot, but I guess I should have told them not to get a
handicap parking placard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect these kind of things to happen at UCLA. I
don't condone it. I'm very embarrassed by it. The kids made a big,
big mistake, and they've been punished for it. We'd like to put
things behind us, but I realize it's also something that still has
to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, as he sat and had lunch with a few journalists, Bob
Toledo, starting his fourth season in Westwood with a 25-10 record
that included a 20-game winning streak, confided this has not been
his most enjoyable summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting ready for my daughter Alissa's wedding when I
got the call about the parking,'' said Toledo. ``I wanted to
address the issue immediately, but the lawyers kept us from saying
anything until the case was settled. That was very frustrating. You
want to speak up and say what you feel, but you can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``This definitely has been the worst vacation I've ever had. My
wife and I were planning to go on a few short trips around the
area, but we were told to stay close to home to deal with this
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked Toledo if he felt his stature had been diminished
by an incident in which nine of the Bruin players---two no longer
are in school---have been suspended for the team's opening two
games against Boise State and Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly hope not,'' he said. ``You don't have total
control over everyone on the team. What could I have done
differently? I tried to do the right thing. I had warned the
players constantly about not parking in the handicap spaces. I warn
the players constantly that they're student-athletes, and are
judged differently. I have what amounts to 105 sons on the team.
It's like a large family, and sometimes your children make
mistakes. You just have to punish them, and go on.''
</P>
<P>
   With McNown now a multi-millionaire drawing a paycheck from the
Chicago Bears, Toledo will start this season without a proven
commodity at quarterback, an ominous sign for the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't have a starting quarterback yet,'' he said. ``We
have four guys, Drew Bennett, Cory Paus, Scott McEwan and Ryan
McCann, competing for the starting job, but none has stood out to
the point he has won it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Bruins figure to be dangerous offensively as they
possess a trio of top running backs in Jermaine Lewis, Keith Brown
and Foster and a trio of talented receivers in Brian Poli-Dixon,
Farmer and Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Although eight starters return from last year's much-ridiculed
defensive unit that reached the dark depths in the regular-season
finale against Miami and then dipped even lower against Wisconsin
in the Rose Bowl, Toledo isn't sure that's a positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, we weren't very good on defense,'' said Toledo,
in a classic understatement.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins are able to remain as poised as their coach, then
they should be a formidable team again.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Toledo was interrogated constantly about the Bruin players'
parking indiscretions throughout the get-together, but he never
betrayed a hint of anger, answering the questions candidly and
openly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me when I tell you I'm embarrassed by it,'' he said.
``I wish it had never happened. I wish the kids would have listened
to me. But I've seen a lot worst things over the years. Remember,
I've coached at a lot of places.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
