<SLUG> BC-AMGEN-TESTING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMGEN, PARTNER TEST NERVE DRUG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Amgen Inc. and biotech partner Guilford
Pharmaceuticals Inc. have started the first clinical tests of a new
nerve regenerating drug they hope will aid in treating illnesses
like Parkinson's disease, the companies announced.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, a class of compounds known as neuroimmunophilins, will
be given to healthy volunteers in Europe to determine whether they
cause any side effects. This phase should last for about a year.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the next step will be giving the drug, which is
administered orally, to volunteers who have the disease. Absent any
major problems it could be seven or eight years before the drug is
ready for market, said Amgen spokesman David Kaye on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Since the drug is taken orally, the compounds are easily
absorbed into the blood and then the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers hope to eventually use these kinds of drugs to treat
a variety of brain-related illnesses such as Alzheimer's disease
and strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Neuroimmunophilins were discovered several years ago by two
scientific teams, one led by Guilford founder Solomon Snyder, a
researcher at Johns Hopkins University, and the other by Bruce Gold
at Oregon Health Sciences University.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reached an important milestone in the development of
the neuroimmunophilins. We will undoubtedly learn a great deal
about neuroimmunophilins over the next few months,'' Craig R.
Smith, Guilford's president and chief executive officer, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen licensed worldwide rights for the neuroimmunophilins from
Guilford in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Amgen's stock closed Wednesday at $77.0625, up 43.75cents.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
