<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TWINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOAIZA LEADS RANGERS TO SERIES SWEEP OF TWINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Texas Rangers' rampage has brought about
two surprises totally unforeseen at the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   The club's record is tied for the best in the major leagues, and
revitalized starting pitcher Esteban Loaiza has a four-game winning
streak. Each occurrence seemed three weeks ago about as unlikely as
Jeff Zimmerman giving up a run in two consecutive appearances.
</P>
<P>
   But the wonders keep coming at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza pitched six scoreless innings despite five walks, and the
Rangers completed a three-game sweep of the Minnesota Twins with a
3-1 victory Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman retired six of seven batters in two innings but
allowed the only run, a home run to Denny Hocking in the eighth
inning. He has now allowed a run in his past two appearances,
driving his earned-run average up to 0.99 and seriously damaging
his chances of being selected to Major League Baseball's
All-Century team.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger concern for an otherwise happy bunch is center
fielder Ruben Mateo, who injured his left wrist swinging the bat in
the seventh inning. X-rays after the game appeared to be negative,
but Mateo's hand was put in a splint. He will be examined by hand
specialist Dr. Bobby Wroten today.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are 17-3 since the All-Star break, giving them an
overall record of 65-42 that is tied with the Cleveland Indians for
the best in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a vote I'd say they're the best team in baseball,''
Hocking said. ``You can tell these guys are playing for a purpose.
They're more focused than anything. You can see it in their eyes. I
think they've got the team to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza has suddenly become a part of that after spending the
first half either in the bullpen or on the disabled list. Given a
second chance, Loaiza is 3-0 with a 2.65 ERA in three starts. Add a
victory in relief, and he has matched the longest winning streak of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy where I'm at right now,'' said Loaiza, who was never
happy serving in long relief. ``I'm throwing the ball great, and
I've come back strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Said manager Johnny Oates, ``If anything is different, he kept
his off-speed pitches and his slider down. He threw a lot of good
sliders and changeups down, especially against left-handed hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is he got three wins, however he does it. The
only thing is I know he can throw more strikes. Walking five in six
innings, he has better control than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza outpitched Twins ace Brad Radke, who had a 3.57 ERA
entering the game, third lowest in the American League. They
matched each other through five scoreless innings before the
Rangers broke through in the sixth on Rafael Palmeiro's sacrifice
fly. The Twins also had a chance for a breakthrough in the sixth,
but the Rangers' defense saved Loaiza.
</P>
<P>
   He got himself into trouble by walking Jacques Jones to start
the inning. Cristian Guzman bunted him to second and Todd Walker
was intentionally passed.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Cordova followed with a sharp grounder down the third-base
line, where Todd Zeile made a terrific backhand diving stop. Zeile
lost the race to the bag, but he did take away a run-scoring
double.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed the Rangers to escape because first baseman Lee
Stevens turned Corey Koskie's grounder into an inning-ending double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Defense has been a part of the Rangers' rampage; they've
committed just eight errors in their last 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always had confidence in our defense,'' shortstop Royce
Clayton said. ``We worked extremely hard on it in spring training
and sometimes when you stress something too much, you try to be too
perfect. I think everybody is settling down.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
