<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-STORAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON 
</HEADLINE>
 
20 percent gain expected for Public Storage 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE _ Public Storage Inc., the nation's largest
self-storage company, is expected to report strong second quarter
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Profits of 66 cents per share, a 20 percent increase from a year
ago, are expected by Wall Street analysts surveyed by First Call.
</P>
<P>
   The estimates ranged from a low of 62 cents to a high of 68
cents. With 1 representing a strong recommendation to buy and 5 a
strong one to sell, the analysts gave Public Storage an average
rating of 1.8. They pegged the company's growth rate at 11 percent,
compared with the industry's 10 percent, First Call also reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing very well,'' said Mark Benson, an analyst at
Jefferies &AMP; Co. in West Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Benson cites three reasons for his optimistic outlook: The real
estate investment trust's core business is growing about 7 percent;
the company's pickup and delivery operation is likely to break even
by the end of the year as losses continue to shrink; and the
purchase of Storage Trust Realty strengthens its position in the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Public Storage recently closed its acquisition of Storage Trust
for $600 million in stock and assumption of debt. The deal expanded
Public Storage's holdings to 1,300 facilities in 37 states, further
widening the gap between the company and Amerco, the second largest
provider of self-storage facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Benson believes company shares are a good value. Public Storage
closed at $25.375 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
