r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     08-05 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN MAKES A PROBLEM FOR HOUSTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ How long are the next two months going to feel for the
Los Angeles Dodgers? Just take Kevin Brown's 2-1 domination of the
NL's top club, the Houston Astros, on Wednesday as the latest
example of this fragmented club.
</P>
<P>
   After getting Houston's Daryle Ward to fly out to right to end
Brown's four-hitter and give him his first nine-inning complete
game of the season, Brown stood behind the mound while infielders
congratulated each other before they finally turned toward the
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was paid $105 million not just to make 35 starts but to
elevate the Dodgers' performance for 162 games.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he's made them immeasurably better for nearly all of
his 24 starts, but the intangibles he was supposed to bring haven't
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (12-6) is 8-3 after Dodgers losses, but the Dodgers are
3-8 following a Brown win. And the winning streaks don't
materialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope for that every night,'' Brown said of starting a
winning streak. ``Not just because I'm throwing. (I'd) just like to
start playing well and reeling off some wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has pitched well, but he hasn't had the profound effect on
the rest of the club, particularly the pitching staff, that the
Dodgers hoped for. Maybe it's unfair pressure, but his acquisition
was supposed to thrust the Dodgers into the playoffs. Instead, the
Dodgers (47-60) are drowning at the bottom of the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   But who's to blame? Dodgers manager Davey Johnson and the club's
management say Brown's been everything they hoped for, which shifts
the burden to the others to feed off his success and work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   Chan Ho Park, who spoke wonderfully of Brown during spring
training, stating he studied video of Brown, has been miserable and
Carlos Perez even worse. Dodgers starters have a 4.87 ERA, which
would qualify as one of the worst numbers in Dodgers' history.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Brown, he seems to be the guy who stops the losing
streaks, and we're riding him,'' said center fielder Devon White,
who scored the Dodgers' second run. ``Other teams want to know,
they're asking when he's pitching. They know how tough it's going
to be. It doesn't carry over.''
</P>
<P>
   But has Brown been allowed to do what he was brought to Los
Angeles to do? In his last start, Brown was pulled after 72/3
innings with a four-run lead. The bullpen blew it.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't going to happen against the Astros because Johnson
wasn't about to give the bullpen an opportunity. When asked how
long Brown was going to stay in the game, Johnson replied, ``Till
his arm fell off.''
</P>
<P>
   Or until Johnson could pry the ball out of Brown's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Brown threw 121 pitches, and not even Derek Bell's RBI double
with two outs in the ninth could cause Johnson to stir from his
seat on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to let that one get away from him like the one
before,'' Johnson said. ``With any luck he should have 18 wins, but
we lost a couple for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Management and players have sensed Brown's frustration for the
last two months, which might have peaked after his last outing. But
Brown, who hadn't thrown a pitch in the ninth inning as a Dodger,
remained stoic after coming within an out of shutting out the
first-place Astros (65-43).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important to finish but more important to win,'' Brown
said. ``I would have liked to get that third out a little easier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
