<SLUG> BC-GUITAR-CENTER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER EXPECTED TO LOWER GUITAR CENTER'S EARNINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Analysts expect Guitar Center Inc.'s second
quarter earnings to fall about 29 percent compared to the like
year-ago period, largely due to its merger with a catalog and
Internet retailer.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey of industry analysts by First Call, when
the Agoura Hills company reports its quarterly results today, it
should post earnings of 10 cents per share during the three-month
period ended June 30, compared with 14 cents that Guitar Center
actually earned last year.
</P>
<P>
   Guitar Center had warned in June that dilution related to its
merger with Medford, Ore.-based Musicians Friend, which also
operated nine retail stores, would cause earnings to fall. The
company also said that a slowdown in some business categories would
contribute to lower earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Nelson, a retail analyst with Stephens Inc. in Chicago,
said that changes in Guitar Center's direct mail program didn't
produce the anticipated benefits. In addition, sales slowed in the
high tech end of the business due to a lack of new merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   That business, Nelson said, had done particularly well in second
quarter 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had been growing at a very rapid rate and they were bumping
up against tough numbers this year versus a year ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson also said that the opening of stores in markets such as
Dallas, Houston, Detroit and Southern California where the company
already had outlets created a situation where Guitar Center was in
effect competing against itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're cannibalizing their existing store sales,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, Nelson thinks Guitar Center's place in the
industry is still secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the strongest format in the industry,'' he said.
``Their stores are still very profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
