r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN-(SLAN     08-05 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOOLRIDGE SAW AGEM IN THIS YUGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ All it took was one game and Orlando
Woolridge knew Yugoslavian point guard Gordana Grubin would fit
perfectly in the Los Angeles Sparks' plan.
</P>
<P>
   Woolridge, coach of L.A.'s WNBA team, was right.
</P>
<P>
   Grubin has found her niche in the team's lineup and doesn't
appear as if she's going to give it up any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   At first, however, it was hard to tell how Grubin would pan out.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) Only Woolridge, and players DeLisha Milton and Lisa
Leslie had ever seen her play.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) Because of a commitment to the Yugoslavian national
team's schedule in the European Championships, Grubin and
Yugoslavian teammate Nina Bjedov, wouldn't join the Sparks until
this season's opening day.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) And, the United States-led NATO armed forces had just
ceased airstrikes on their country.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 23 games into a season in which the Sparks are in position
for their first WNBA playoff appearance, every team in the league
knows about Grubin and her capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Woolridge knew all along and boasted about her every
day until she arrived.
</P>
<P>
   As an assistant coach on the USA Basketball team last February,
Woolridge first saw Grubin when Yugoslavia played the U.S. in a
European Tour. He says he was a believer from Day 1 and wasted no
time in finding out how to make her a member of the Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see right there if Gordana came to the WNBA she'd be
one of the best point guards in the league,'' Woolridge said. ``The
question was whether or not the league was going to draft her.
That's not my job. Even if the league would have signed her, I was
going to find a way, by way of the draft, to get her.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Woolridge the league concentrated solely on
players from the defunct American Basketball League. Because Grubin
and Bjedov were left unsigned, thus ineligible for the draft, the
Sparks were able to pursue them independently. L.A. beat out
Houston and Cleveland for Grubin.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I do know about professional basketball is
that those who wait miss out,'' Woolride said. ``When I saw Gordana
play that very first game, I talked to her coach after that game. I
asked her coach if she had any interest, she told her coach, `Yes.'
I immediately asked the coach who the agent was and I was on the
phone with the agent that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Van Chancellor realizes he missed out on a great
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a heckuva player,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Grubin knew that Houston was a ``good team,'' but she said her
agent, Italian Paolo Ronci, told her that the Sparks ``think they
can be champions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he told me who the people are (on the team), I thought
maybe it would be good to come here,'' said Grubin, who has started
the last seven games. ``I knew from the national team, DeLisha
Milton and Lisa Leslie, who everybody knows she's a great player.
She plays very well. I like how she played against us in Europe.
She played a very good game. So I saw what she can do. When you
have centers like two of them and some good perimeter players, I
think you can be the champions.''
</P>
<P>
   Grubin, who turns 27 next month, wanted to play in the WNBA last
year. She played professionally in Yugoslavia for two years, but
because of the embargo in her country, the team was not allowed to
play internationally. She left Yugoslavia to play for a Hungarian
team in the Euroleague last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every competition I had I saw that I could play on every
level in Europe,'' she said. ``I had a wish to play here (in the
WNBA), because this is the highest level in the world and finally,
you know, I'm here. I'm glad I came. I'm glad I fit in (with) the
Sparks so well. I think I do
</P>
<P>
   , from the beginning 'till this moment, I do a better job. Maybe
I can do more good, but it's OK, we're winning. It's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   She won't get any complaints from Woolridge. Once Grubin found
her comfort zone with the team and Woolridge told her to play her
normal style, which meant the green light was on, Grubin has become
another offensive threat for the Sparks. She's averaging 8.2
points, 2.4 assists and shooting 44 percent from the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's playing exactly the way I envisioned her playing,''
Woolridge said. ``The thing that I'm the most pleased with is she's
really adapted to that point guard position. She's pushing the ball
up the court, she's hitting the open shot, she's penetrating, her
defense is a lot better than she gets credit for, she's going to
the glass. She's playing a complete game. Right now she's playing
as good as any point guard in the league.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
