<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMESTORE-IPO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMESTORE.COM IPO EXPECTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- HomeStore.com is expected to go public as early
as Wednesday amid heavy interest from investors.
</P>
<P>
   The Thousand Oaks parent of real estate Web sites will be
selling its shares at $20 each, up from the $8 to $10 it originally
planned, according to Tom Taulli, an IPO analyst and author of
``Investing in IPOs.''
</P>
<P>
   The company _ owner of the Realtor.com, HomeBuilder.com,
SpringStreet.com and CommercialSource.com Web sites _ has an
exclusive arrangement with the National Association of Realtors.
The relationship enables HomeStore.com to provide one of the
nation's largest listings of homes online.
</P>
<P>
   Realtor.com provides general home listings, HomeBuilder.com is a
site for new homes, SpringStreet.com lists apartments, and
CommercialSource.com serves the commercial real estate industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to have as many homes listed as possible and by not
being a threat to agents and brokers,'' Taulli said. In most cases,
consumers still will have to call the local real estate agent to
look at the homes.
</P>
<P>
   Taulli expects the HomeStore.com initial public offering to
attract healthy interest from investors, despite the choppy IPO
market. In recent weeks, market turbulence has knocked down many
Internet stocks and put a damper on the IPOs of Internet companies
as well. However, selected IPOs have done well.
</P>
<P>
   HomeStore.com's lead underwriter is Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
for the 7 million-share offering.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to receive about $121.7 million in proceeds,
up from $56.6 million at the IPO's initial price range, according
to IPO Monitor, a Calabasas company that tracks the initial public
offering market.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds will be used for general corporate purposes, capital
expenditures, working capital and accelerated payments of $6.3
million under a distribution agreement with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   HomeStore.com has attracted the prominent Silicon Valley venture
capitalist firm of Kleiner Perkins, which had backed Netscape,
Excite, Intuit and Sun Microsystems in their infancies.
</P>
<P>
   After the offering, Kleiner will hold 14.4 percent of the
company and GE Capital will own 5.3 percent, according to IPO
Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   True to the Internet company stereotype, HomeStore.com is
unprofitable. In the first six months of the year, the company lost
more money than it made: $50 million in losses on revenues of $21.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 0149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
