<HEADER>
A6366 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GWYNN-LADN-(SLANG     08-05 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GWYNN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALICIA GWYNN HAPPY FOR HUSBAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS __ Fifth inning on a pleasant evening at Busch
Stadium. Small groans from Cardinal fans gain momentum as the
Padres load the bases. Up walks Tony Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   Someone behind Tony's wife Alicia, sitting just off the Padres'
third-base dugout, says the Cardinal fans aren't cheering as loud
for Tony now, with the bases loaded, as they did in the fourth
inning, when he stroked hit No. 2,996 of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Alicia pauses in her conversation with a reporter to watch her
husband. On the first pitch, that pause is broken by the crack of
Gwynn's bat and the sight of the ball soaring into the right field
bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   Hit number 2,997 is a grand slam, and most of those in the Gwynn
entourage stand and cheer as Tony makes his way around the bases
and then taps fists with his teammates. At the lip of the dugout,
he taps a high fist with his son, 17-year-old Anthony, and then
gives him a fatherly push on the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Gwynn did not get up when Tony hit his grand slam. She
didn't even clap. Like her husband, she is a humble person at
heart. And sometimes, it is much more meaningful to let a moment
wash over you. And this moment was a tidal wave.
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Gwynn's face reflected a thousand emotions during those
seconds, her eyes going to Tony, and to her son, and to others in
her family. Eventually, she looked at the several thousand Cardinal
fans, most everyone in the lower level located between the dugouts,
who stood and gave her husband a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a crowd like this to stand up and clap for you,''
said Alicia, ``when you can make them cheer for you when they are
here to see their team, that's respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited. But I mostly am happy for Tony. Because he earned
this. He deserves this.''
</P>
<P>
   The night would end with Tony getting a third hit, a slashing
single to left field, leaving him two hits shy of 3,000, and with
Mark McGwire hitting the 499th home run of his career, a 436-foot
blast that tied the game a Cardinals would eventually win, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Gwynn has been along for every hit of Tony's career, and
much more. They met when they were kids growing up in the same Long
Beach neighborhood, started dating when they were at Long Beach
Poly, got engaged while they were at San Diego State, and married
soon after she graduated and Tony went off to play professional
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   You can get Tony Gwynn to talk about baseball and his
experiences for a fortnight, and he can breakdown his swing the way
a biologist can breakdown a cell. But Alicia has played a large
role the last half-decade in making her husband more accessible to
the everyday fan, and not just because she was the first one to
videotape his at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Personal hubbub and huzzah are not Tony Gwynn's thing, to the
degree that he can't wait for his 3,000th hit ``just so things can
get back to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony has always been a little shy,'' she said between hits
2,996 and 2,997. ``I don't know if I exactly told him to get out of
his shell. He'll talk baseball all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's blessed to be a good ballplayer. And a lot of the
people who wanted access to him are those who helped him get here,
whether he knows it or not. He has his talents, but the fans played
a big part in him getting recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Alicia hears from those fans all the time people in the
neighborhood, people she meets at the store, old friends from Long
Beach, 20-year Padre season ticket holders. They tell her they've
been fans since the beginning and love her husband because he's
such a good guy.
</P>
<P>
   Alicia talked Tony into creating their foundation, The Tony and
Alicia Gwynn Foundation, in 1993 as a way to organize and better
direct their charity work. Prior to that, Gwynn gave of himself
through golf tournaments and special appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foundation allows us to direct exactly where the benefits
go,'' she said. The YMCA, Police Athletic League and several youth
programs are among the charities. Baseball honored Gwynn with the
Branch Rickey Award (for community service) in 1995 for his
foundation work, and he's a two-time winner of the Roberto Clemente
Award, which goes to one player on every team.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has since grown to include an annual golf
tournament, a benefit dinner, silent auctions and Gwynn's novel
mobile museum. A friend who owned a big rig asked if the Gwynns had
any use for one, and Alicia came up with the idea of a museum that
includes artifacts from Gwynn's career. The $1 admission fee goes
to foundation charities.
</P>
<P>
   Other contributions are more direct. There are several dozen
kids in the Gwynn neighborhood in Poway, friends of Anthony and his
sister Anisha, who have turned the Gwynn household into their
second home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come to the house to play, and I love to cook for them,''
she said. ``It's not uncommon for 15 kids to be over at the
house.'' And when Tony is home, there is undoubtedly a lot of
baseball talk.
</P>
<P>
   But, ``he will talk a lot about their lives, and what they're
going to do with it. There can be quite the little roundtable of
Tony and kids talking baseball and life.''
</P>
<P>
   Like his dad, Charles, did with Tony, older brother Charles and
younger brother Chris? ``Absolutely,'' said Alicia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony is a genuine person. He's just ... Tony. He gets his
(humility) from his parents. It was something his parents and my
parents reiterated to us. He may be wiser now, but he's basically
the same person he was when we met.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony's attitude is he loves what he does and he doesn't have
to tell everybody about it. And he does (charity) things because
they make him feel good, and it's not necessary to tell everyone
when he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that. I just want him to get his due. There's
something to be said for being consistent. Maybe that's what people
were cheering about tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
