<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6368 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GWYNN2-LADN-(SLAN     08-05 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GWYNN2-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GWYNN TWO SHY OF MILESTONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Wednesday night may have been the most electric
night of the 1999 baseball season. At least until tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Before 43,546 at Busch Stadium, Tony Gwynn got three hits,
leaving him two shy of 3,000 in his career, and Mark McGwire hit
the 499th home run of his career. The convergence of two players
nearing two baseball milestones in the same game was more than
enough to render the Cardinals' 7-6 win as
</P>
<P>
   meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Never in baseball history have two players reached 500 home runs
and 3,000 hits in the same game. A 500-to-3,000 parlay has happened
in the same season only three times, what with there being only 22
members of the 3K club and only 15 players with 500 home runs.
Needless to say, tonight's game here is a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn singled sharply to left in the fourth inning, slammed the
third grand slam home run in his 18-year career in the fifth, and
singled to left again in the seventh. He was waiting on deck when
the game ended.
</P>
<P>
   The slam was a stunning moment in Gwynn's march to 3,000. The
Cards led 3-2 when Gwynn drove Kent Mercker's first pitch over the
fence, putting the Padres up 6-3. Despite that, a large portion of
the crowd gave him a standing ovation, including most everyone in
the expensive field seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was unbelievable,'' said Gwynn afterwards. ``I can't
explain it. Their team is up by a run and suddenly down by three,
and people got on their feet. To be a visiting player and get that
kind of response is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's St. Louis,'' said McGwire. ``But I think people
appreciate milestones everywhere. I know they're special. I was
fortunate to see Dave Winfield get his 3,000th, and I'd like to see
Tony get it here. If he gets a single, I'll shake his hand and give
him a hug before he gets mobbed by his teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn's three hits came after going 1-for-10 in the first two
games and three innings of this four-game series. He has been
struggling with his mechanics since coming off the disabled list
July 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty happy to get a hit and finally do something
right,'' he said of his fourth-inning single. ``He (Mercker) got me
on a changeup my first at-bat. I stayed back on my second at-bat
and got the hit. My third at-bat, I thought he might try to get
ahead with the bases loaded and went looking for a fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn said he felt a little embarrassed to get such a response
from the fans. `It's great because it's not at home,'' he said.
``It would be historic if we both reached our milestones in the
same game, but I feel guilty because it's Mark's town. They may see
my 3,000th, but they're coming to see Mark.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's blast with two out in the seventh off Carlos Reyes
tied the game at six, and an unearned run in the eighth gave the
Cards the win.
</P>
<P>
   A pitching change in the seventh after Gwynn's third hit allowed
McGwire and Gwynn the chance to talk. They discussed what bat
McGwire has been using this season a Davey Lopes-model bat and how
difficult it is dealing with the media demands during moments like
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``For both of us, it's just a matter of time. What game, what
inning, what pitch,'' said McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you can do is play,'' said Gwynn. I can't preview it any
more. I'm numb. I really want to get it done with so I can get back
to being just one of 25 guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn's previous grand slams were also on the road. one at
Philadelphia in 1995 and one against the Dodgers, an
inside-the-parker in 1997 when Brett Butler dove for slicing drive
and injured himself
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 0159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
