<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6374 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      08-05 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINEMEN SEE LIFE ON THE LIGHTER SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ This just in: Cortez Kennedy and Sam Adams are
big.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXL big. Larger-than-life big. Big even by NFL standards.
Their weight has been a constant source for conversation,
consternation and even fines for as long as each has worn an
overmatched Seahawks uniform _ Kennedy coming aboard in 1990 as the
club's first-round draft choice and Adams joining him as a
first-round pick in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, both of the rotund defensive tackles checked into
training camp last week lighter and in better shape than they have
been in years.
</P>
<P>
   Also, with the arrival of new coach Mike Holmgren, weight has
become relative. In Green Bay, Holmgren had Gilbert Brown, who is
listed at 350 pounds but has played as heavy as 365 and taped
segments for NFL pregame shows flaunting the eating habits that
stoke his girth.
</P>
<P>
   Put Kennedy and Adams next to Brown and they would become a
diminutive duo.
</P>
<P>
   ``How big is too big to play?'' Holmgren said Wednesday. ``Each
guy is different. He can be big, but if he can play, that's the
standard.''
</P>
<P>
   While there have been a ton of questions about Kennedy's and
Adams' weight, no one has ever questioned that they can play.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was NFL defensive player of the year in 1992 on a 2-14
team and has played in the Pro Bowl seven times in his nine-year
career.
</P>
<P>
   Adams was a first alternate to the Pro Bowl two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Holmgren asked each to report at a reduced weight
because he will ask them to do different things than the previous
coaching staff, who used their massive bodies as disruptive
battering rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real pleased; Cortez and Sam worked real hard to get their
weight down,'' Holmgren said. ``If a player realizes why you're
asking them to do (something), it makes it easier for everyone.
It's stamina. It's longevity for their career. It's for their
health. It's for their quality of life. There are a lot of reasons
to try and get down; it's just hard for those big guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy got the message. He weighs 308 pounds, the lightest he
has been at training camp in four years. So did Adams, who played
at 320 last year but now weighs 314 and plans to get down to at
least 300 by the Sept. 12 regular-season opener against the Detroit
Lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like being lighter,'' Adams said. ``It's just easier on
your joints. With all the turf we play on (10 of 16 games this
season), toward the end of the season you slow down, your joints
are tired, you're in pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his reduced weight, Kennedy delivers a playful scowl
before offering, ``You know I don't talk about my weight. Let's
just say I'm underweight.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is the type who prefers to let his actions speak for
him, even if he will be doing it with a little less body language.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I respect about Holmgren's coaching is that he wants
you to be disciplined, play football and everything else will take
care of itself,'' Kennedy said. ``My weight has never been an issue
with me. People have made it an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we get to the regular season, I'm always at my weight, so
I don't care what they say or don't say. I'm just going to do my
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren doesn't want Kennedy and Adams to lose the explosive
burst that regularly launches them past would-be blockers and into
opposing backfields. But he also wants them to remain more under
control, so they can make more plays once they arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see Sam penetrate, then the quarterback or running back
will run right by him,'' Holmgren said. ``I saw that on film a
number of times. The same thing with Cortez. We don't want to take
away what has made them so successful, but we want them to
penetrate and, boom, make the play.''
</P>
<P>
   And at times, hold their own on the line and make the play as it
comes to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We term it a square-shouldered defense,'' said defensive line
coach Larry Brooks, who was a 260-pound Pro Bowl defensive end
during his career with the Los Angeles Rams in the mid-70s before
the influx of 300-plus-pound offensive linemen forced a similar
evolution in defensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to run up the field and create gaps the
linebackers can't fill. We like the linemen to use their hands and
play with leverage. For these guys, it's new.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kennedy and Adams, so is reporting to camp at less than 315
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   HAWK TALK: The team got a scare during the morning practice when
CB Fred Thomas crumpled to the ground while in pass coverage and
grabbed his right knee. The injury appeared serious, but Thomas was
able to walk off the field. ... DE Phillip Daniels sat out the end
of the workout after bruising his left knee. ... After seven very
physical practices, Wednesday's second session lasted only an hour
and focused on the punting game, which meant the offensive and
defensive linemen got the afternoon off. The lone exception was C
Greg Bloedorn, who handled the deep-snapping. ... Play du jour: FS
Jay Bellamy's stunning hit on RB Reggie Brown. Stunning? Brown was
stunned momentarily and remained on the ground for several minutes
after Bellamy arrived at almost the same instant as a short pass
from QB Jon Kitna.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
