<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6378 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     08-05 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLMGREN GIVES UNDRAFTED ROOKIE A RARE SECOND CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY _ Sunday morning when he walked out of Seahawks training
camp, Jonathon Nance kissed his cleats goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kissed `em, stuck `em on top of my locker and called my
buddies to come get me,'' Nance said.
</P>
<P>
   Forget that the shoes were covered in sweat, grass and medical
tape. Nance needed to perform some kind of symbolic final act to
end his blip of an NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   So Nance pressed his lips to the leather of his Nikes and blew
it all away.
</P>
<P>
   Or so he thought at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Nance, the 24-year-old rookie free agent defensive end out of
Washington State, had participated in exactly one practice session
before deciding he had seen enough.
</P>
<P>
   It did not matter that he was making the NFL-mandated $675 a
week just to be in Cheney or that his Seahawk contract would pay
him six figures if he made the team. At a slightly undersized 257
pounds, Nance felt he'd be better off running into brick walls than
hitting the 300-plus-pound offensive linemen now staring into his
face mask. And after spending too little time developing his
aerobic conditioning, Nance said he was too winded, too out of
shape to compete in Mike Holmgren's camp.
</P>
<P>
   Or so he thought at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Dreams die hard. Ever since he was 10 years old, growing up with
his six brothers and two sisters in football-mad Miami, Nance
dreamed of playing in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   But even more surprising than Nance walking out of Seahawk camp
after one practice is that he was back Wednesday. And he was back
because Holmgren called him and told him he had made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't thank him enough,'' Nance said of his return, thanks
to a coach who refused to let the rookie buckle to doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he saw that I made a bad decision. He said he wished I
had come talked to him man-to-man, told him what was going on, that
I was out of shape. I think what it shows is that coach cares about
his players,'' Nance said.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren did not want to discuss at length the details of their
conversation, only that he felt he should reach out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is hard. It's very competitive and hot, and I wanted to
make sure that if he was leaving, he was doing it for the right
reason. We just had a little chat and he's back here now,''
Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren's action has made a big impression on a lot of
Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other coach would have taken the time with a guy who has
all that stacked against him,'' said veteran defensive end Phillip
Daniels, who has now taken Nance under his wing, telling him about
all the free agents who have made it in the NFL and about how he,
too, weighed only 250 his first training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Against all odds. That's how some of the game's most
professional players make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another coach would have said `Let him go. We'll bring
somebody else in here,''' Daniels said, ``but coach took the time
to say to tell Jonathon, `You're young. You're making a dumb
mistake.' He said come back in. He gave him a second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   With some difficulty, Nance was tracked down in Pullman at the
home of former WSU teammates Joey Hollenbeck and Ryan Tujague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do much of anything except sit around the house for a
couple of days, eating and thinking. I was pretty down,'' Nance
said.
</P>
<P>
   Only 12 credits shy of his degree in criminal justice, Nance
said his plan was to save up some money and head back to school in
the spring. He said he wants to be a juvenile parole officer back
home in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Only now he realizes he can pursue that avenue later _
especially with veterans like Daniels keeping on him to stay
focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're young, you come in to camp, it's unfamiliar
territory. You come in and feel the odds are stacked against you.
You get to thinking that and thinking that you can't make it when
actually you can,'' Daniels said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted to tell him was never think negative. Always
think positive because you can get a spot on this team or somewhere
else. This is an opportunity. He would have regretted that the rest
of his life,'' Daniels said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the veterans didn't rib Nance. When they saw him come
walking through the training room Wednesday, Daniels looked over at
Cortez Kennedy, who started singing ``Welcome Back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Michael) Sinclair was on the table saying, `Leave him alone.
He's OK.' And Tez said, `I'm just playing with him. He knows I'm
joking with him.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Tez shook his hand and said, `Let's go. Welcome back,
Dog.' All us vets knew Jonathon made a bad decision. And we all
said we wished he had come talked to us. But I'm glad he's back,''
Daniels said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys dream of being in the NFL. I mean, you always
dream about this one shot. You just don't want to pass it up.
That's the one thing I told him.''
</P>
<P>
   So Wednesday, Nance took his cleats down from the top of the
locker, put them back on and went back out to try again.
</P>
<P>
   Word is he had a great practice.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
