<HEADLINE>
ON-THE-JOB TRAINING FOR BUHNER AT FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For those wondering, Jay Buhner's previous first-base
experience can be measured like the hairs on his head.
</P>
<P>
   Zippo.
</P>
<P>
   When Buhner starts at the first base Saturday against the New
York Yankees, it will be a career first _ at any level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish I would have played a little bit (at first base)
in spring training ... so I wouldn't be so nervous,'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   Since trading David Segui to Toronto last week, the Mariners
have used John Mabry and Raul Ibanez, both left-handed hitters, at
first.
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Edgar Martinez has played first in the past,
but the Mariners say they are more inclined to let him concentrate
on his hitting. That leaves a need for a right-handed batter at the
position.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Buhner.
</P>
<P>
   Normally a right fielder, Buhner had considered playing first
base during spring training, uncertain how his surgically repaired
right elbow might hold up on long throws from the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   But he proved to be a fast healer, the plans were scrapped and
he assumed his normal spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners turn to him now because of his athleticism and
their obvious need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks you get old and get put at first base, but
there's a lot to it,'' said Lee Pelekoudas, vice president of
baseball administration. ``He's athletic enough to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mariners manager Lou Piniella, ``He's got nice hands. I
think he'll do a real good job.''
</P>
<P>
   For Buhner, the move could be a career enhancer, an alternative
once his outfield skills diminish. He's looking forward to his new
duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it'll work out,'' Buhner said. ``I'm sure it won't
hurt me. Actually, it'll be nice to try something new, to break up
the monotony.''
</P>
<P>
   DON'T FORGET TO WRITE: He won't admit to helping Segui pack his
bags or high-fiving guys in the clubhouse, but the person who
benefited the most from the Segui trade was Mabry. A part-time
player since coming to the Mariners in the offseason, Mabry has
started seven of eight games at first base, including Wednesday
night, since the vacancy was created.
</P>
<P>
   A lifetime .286 hitter and full-time player entering the season,
Mabry was hitting .242 and playing sporadically when Segui left.
With regular at-bats, he had raised his average to .250 entering
Wednesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what's going to happen,'' Mabry said
cautiously. ``Baseball is a crazy game. You treat the game with
respect and it respects you. You never expect anything.''
</P>
<P>
   BLACK HOLE: If it seems there have been a large number of balls
skipping past the catchers at Safeco Field _ seven wild pitches and
two passed balls so far _ there is a reason.
</P>
<P>
   Catchers have had trouble picking up high pitches early in the
game against the center-field backdrop, combating both the
reflective glare from the sun and white lettering that rotates on
an advertising board.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners catchers Dan Wilson and Tom Lampkin met with club
officials on the field before last night's contest to try to
resolve the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``From 5 to 8:30, it's brutal,'' Lampkin said. ``Sometimes you
can't even see the spin on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   An obvious solution discussed was to change or darken the
lettering on the reader board.
</P>
<P>
   TICKET WINDOW: The four-game series that starts tonight against
the Yankees is virtually sold out. As of Wednesday, there were just
a handful of single tickets available for each game, though
season-ticket holders have the option of turning in seats and
making them available at any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the series that started selling immediately,''
Mariners spokesman Tim Hevly said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
