<HEADLINE>
SONICS LOOKING AT MAVS' TRENT AS RICHMOND DEALING COOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Sonics were close to signing a free agent
Wednesday, and an announcement could come as early Thursday,
according to a source.
</P>
<P>
   But the chances of that player being veteran shooting guard
Mitch Richmond are fading barring a sudden, multiple-team deal. The
source said one of five different deals could materialize for the
Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Among those on team president Wally Walker's ``prioritized list
that's reasonably short'' is Dallas free agent forward Gary Trent,
who has emerged as perhaps the most intriguing prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Walker rationalized his interest in Trent in Wednesday's
editions of the Forth Worth Star-Telegram, which reported the
Sonics are offering the 6-foot-8 forward a three-year deal worth
$11.28 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty well loaded at power forward and center, but you
can have a lot of guys who are versatile at the positions and go to
the best matchups and punish some folks,'' Walker told the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   If Trent signs, the Sonics plan to use him at small forward.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics Wednesday still had not ruled out quicker, more
athletic small forwards: Cleveland's Cedric Henderson, Dallas'
Cedric Ceballos and Utah's Shandon Anderson. But each of those
players can earn more by re-signing with their respective teams.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson originally wanted $9 million from the Jazz, which
offered $4 million a season. Now, Utah is presenting Anderson with
a four-year package worth $24 million and a spot in the starting
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos will simply go to the highest bidder, and the Sonics'
interest in Henderson is believed to have turned lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they'd know something by the afternoon,'' said
Dwight Manley, who represents Vernon Maxwell, another player the
Sonics are interested in signing. ``I don't know if they're still
trying to get Mitch or what. But we'll be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker has tirelessly pursued a sign-and-trade deal with the
Washington Wizards for Richmond. A source said Walker had not
completely given up late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are no takers for Hersey Hawkins and the
remaining two years/$8.6 million on his contract. So Walker's chore
has been to find a team with enough salary cap room to trade for
Hawkins or engineer a three-team transaction to complete a
sign-and-trade deal with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say the Sonics are out of (the Richmond
sweepstakes),'' the source said. ``Washington just doesn't want
Hawk. They're not going to give Richmond away. They've got someone
specific in mind and they want the Sonics to go get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Unloading Hawkins' $4.1 million salary for this season plus the
team's $3.3 million under the salary cap would allow the Sonics to
absorb roughly $7.5 million in salary for Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Walker will not talk about prospects until deals are announced.
Richmond's agent, Mike Sharpe, did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``With every day that goes by, it's getting tougher to do,'' the
source said of a Richmond deal.
</P>
<P>
   That is because of a few developments.
</P>
<P>
   Washington raised it's three-year offer to Richmond. It is a
deal that would start the six-time All-Star at $12 million. Also,
Miami was reportedly trying to find a third team with salary-cap
space to facilitate a three-way trade that would bring Richmond to
the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   Losing out on Richmond would be a big blow to the Sonics,
considering the size of shooting guards in the Western Conference.
Portland added 6-foot-8 Steve Smith, Sacramento traded for 6-6 Nick
Anderson, the Los Angeles Lakers have 6-7 Kobe Bryant, San
Antonio's Mario Elie is 6-5 and the 6-6 Anderson could be in a Utah
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Barring any changes in the Sonics lineup, any of those players
could post up Hawkins, who stands 6-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
