<HEADLINE>
MECHE HIT HARD AS DEVIL RAYS END MARINERS' WIN STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Mariners might have had Yankees on the mind.
</P>
<P>
   What they got instead was a former Yankee on the mound, a big
deficit before the first train rumbled past and a painful learning
experience for rookie Gil Meche.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to extend a six-game win streak and move to the plus side
of .500, the Mariners (53-54) went the other direction. After a
week of good feelings at Safeco Field, the home club turned
listless Wednesday night, losing 7-1 to Tampa Bay before a crowd of
42,336.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly a momentum-builder for a visit from New York,
which shows up Thursday for the first of four games _ and its only
tour of Seattle this season. On the mound, Roger Clemens will
oppose the Mariners' Jamie Moyer, a considerable step up in marquee
value from Wednesday night's Meche-Dave Eiland pairing.
</P>
<P>
   Against Tampa Bay, Meche (2-2), making his sixth big-league
appearance and fifth start, lasted just 11 batters. He retired the
first two. Easily. Strikeout and groundout to the catcher. The next
nine batters, however, roughed him up good.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't sharp tonight,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``He
couldn't get his breaking ball over and they were sitting on his
fastball. He threw 15 curveballs and only two for strikes. That's
not a very good percentage. He had the flu earlier in the week, but
he said he was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Included in the damage was Wade Boggs' 2,997th hit, an infield
safety in the second inning, leaving him three shy of a cherished
milestone. The Devil Rays star, however, didn't play that much more
than Meche, leaving with right knee inflammation in the fifth
inning and taking just three at-bats. Boggs' exit was described as
a precautionary move.
</P>
<P>
   Meche served up two runs in the first, Fred McGriff's homer to
right-center following up Tony Graffanino's triple to left-center.
That was the first long ball off the Mariners' pitching staff in
six games.
</P>
<P>
   The young Mariners starter was touched for two more runs in the
second, his wild pitch sending one across and Terrell Lowrey's
double bringing in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Meche finally sat down after Boggs got aboard, leaving runners
at first and third with two outs. Boggs slapped a ball to a diving
John Mabry at first and beat the throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's all right,'' said Mariners reliever Frankie Rodriguez of
Meche. ``He's got a good head on his shoulders. He knows what he
needs to do, and that's get it done the next time out.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Mike Defelice had four hits for the Devil Rays,
including a two-run homer off Rodriguez in the ninth. McGriff had
three hits.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the Mariners in check was Eiland, one of the big
league's ultimate journeyman pitchers and an unlikely nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   Eiland was 1-6 entering the contest, 7-22 for his
undistinguished career. He had been up and down and shuffled around
so much, he spent two separate tours of duty with New York, four
years apart. He spent the first two months of this season in the
minors. In fact, his job security had been so shaky, Eiland got
work last winter as a double for actor Kevin Costner in the
unreleased movie ``For The Love Of The Game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He broke in with me in New York,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Eiland doesn't have to keep his day job any longer.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the 33-year-old Floridian mixed his pitches and
threw six shutout innings at the Mariners before turning the game
over to his bullpen. He was in trouble only once, loading the bases
in the second inning, but got a double-play grounder from Russ
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Eiland scattered five hits, walked just one and picked up his
first road victory in the big leagues since 1990 _ when he pitched
the Yankees to a 7-2 win over Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Albie Lopez and Roberto Hernandez finished up, retiring nine of
10 batters, the only interruption a leadoff walk to Ken Griffey Jr.
in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   This one was over so quickly, the Mariners emptied their
bullpen. Newly acquired Tom Davey made his first appearance,
becoming the 25th player and 13th rookie to step on the mound for
Seattle this season. He threw 21/3 innings, giving up an unearned
run as the defense turned sloppy behind him, committing a pair of
errors.
</P>
<P>
   The home side was so quiet, the biggest stir from the crowd came
in the top of the ninth when a fan in a black T-shirt and shorts
sprinted across the field, only to be sent crashing hard into the
left field fence by security guards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
