<HEADLINE>
ONE BAT ENOUGH FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 WRITETHROUGH (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ A cynic might question why the Anaheim Angels
even bother to bring a bat to the plate at all, considering their
lack of offense this season.
</P>
<P>
   But they tried something a little different Wednesday night and
it worked in their 4-3 win over the Kansas City Royals before
18,216 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The first time through the order, all nine Angels batters used
the same bat, which belonged to outfielder Jim Edmonds. They went 4
for 8 with a walk, including an RBI double by catcher Ben Molina
that drove in the first run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   It was hitting coach Rod Carew's idea to lighten things up a
little. Picking Edmonds' bat had no real significance; they also
had Gary DiSarcina's bat ready, but they didn't need it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It broke the tension a little bit,'' Angels manager Terry
Collins said. ``We're just trying to have a little fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sitting in the dugout before the game and I hear someone
say, `Let's use one with tape on it because I need a grip on it.' I
said `What is going on?' They said, `We're using one bat,' so I
said, `There better be some (expletive) hits in that bat.'''
</P>
<P>
   But it also caused a little confusion. Orlando Palmeiro led off
the first inning and struck out looking. He dropped the bat on the
plate, leaving it for DiSarcina, who was up next.
</P>
<P>
   But home-plate umpire Tim Tschida thought Palmeiro was showing
him up and threw Palmeiro out of the game. Collins came out of the
dugout to explain, and Palmeiro was allowed to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was confusing, because I didn't say anything,'' Palmeiro
said. ``I didn't do anything in disgust and didn't say anything to
him. I was in shock. He said, `Come back and pick up your bat,' and
I said, `The next guy's using it.' It was just a
misunderstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels will try just about anything these days to change
their fortunes. Going into Wednesday's game, they had scored one
run or fewer in nine of the 19 games since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, they were hitting .231 as a team and averaging 3.0 runs
per game since the break.
</P>
<P>
   Molina's double off Royals starter Jay Witasick (4-9) in the
second inning not only drove in Darin Erstad (single) to give the
Angels a 1-0 lead, but it was Molina's first major-league hit. He
added an RBI single in the fourth inning and an infield single in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Molina, who got into two games last season and had one at-bat,
finished 3 for 4. He also got to keep Edmonds' bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have it right here, and the ball,'' Molina said, pointing
inside his locker. ``It's kind of awesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he's got the hottest bat in the American League
right now,'' Collins said. ``He handles the bat all right and he
throws all right. But before we put him in the Hall of Fame, let's
see him play a few more games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
