<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MO HAS INFECTED SHIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Mo Vaughn was not at Edison Field for
Wednesday's Anaheim Angels game against the Kansas City Royals.
Instead, he was resting at home in Newport Beach, fighting a staph
infection in his right shin.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn came out of Monday's game after five innings because he
felt ill, but he played Tuesday night. After Tuesday's game, Vaughn
had a 104-degree temperature and was instructed to go to the
hospital, but never did.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn finally went to the hospital Wednesday morning and now is
taking antibiotics. He'll be re-examined today, but isn't expected
to play tonight against his former team, the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   -- It wasn't working for him, so Angels manager Terry Collins
pawned it off on Todd Greene. Collins has had in his office all
season a decorative wheel, designed by a Native American witch
doctor. It is supposed to ward off evil spirits.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a wood carving of a bear, which is recognized as
the strongest symbol on a Native American Totem Pole. Both were
given to Collins by a woman who says Edison Field is cursed because
it sits on Native American burial ground.
</P>
<P>
   Both artifacts are now in Greene's locker.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's locker sits in the darkest corner of the clubhouse and,
in the past few seasons, it has been occupied by Eddie Murray and
Cecil Fielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, yeah, it's cursed,'' Greene said of his locker. ``Look
at all the people who have been there. They've been released or
sent down or hit .230. Or all of the above.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Going into Wednesday's game, pitchers starting against the
Angels had thrown four complete games in five days.
</P>
<P>
   The only pitcher who didn't go the distance was Royals pitcher
Jose Rosado, who pitched seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   -- Pitcher Mike James threw four scoreless innings at Class-A
Lake Elsinore Tuesday. He allowed three hits, struck out two and
didn't walk a batter in his second rehab appearance.
</P>
<P>
   James, recovering from elbow surgery, is expected to continue
his rehab at Triple-A Edmonton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
