<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 03:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6417 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAVIS-FUNDRAISING-SFC     08-05 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-FUNDRAISING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GOV. DAVIS HAS RAKED IN $6.1 MILLION SINCE JAN. 1  &HT;     By GREG LUCAS and LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Tapping traditional sources of GOP campaign money
such as agribusiness and utilities, Gov. Gray Davis pulled in a
record-setting $6.1 million in contributions since January 1 _ more
than $2.8 million in June alone, according to statement released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Davis received at least $360,700 from unions, the
Democratic governor garnered at least $328,000 from farming, dairy
and ranching interests and an additional $437,000 from utilities,
including $110,000 from Pacific Telesis.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Pete Wilson set the previous fund-raising record for
his first six months in 1991 with $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's press office referred calls to his political
operation, which did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, Davis told The Chronicle's editorial board
``everybody, when you are governor, wants to give you money.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics say Davis' fund-raising zeal _ for which he has been
legendary throughout his political career _ creates an appearance
that hefty contributors may get special treatment from Davis'
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are going to be giving to an incumbent are
very-special interest groups that have issues pending,'' said Craig
Holman, project director of the Center for Governmental Studies, a
Los Angeles nonprofit organization that studies campaign financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it isn't quid pro quo corruption, which it may be, it
certainly has the appearance of corruption,'' said Holman, who is
also a co-author of Proposition 208, an initiative which restricted
campaign contributions but was declared unconstitutional by a
federal judge last year.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also told The Chronicle's editorial board that he ``wanted
to be judged by the results that come from the regulatory and
legislative policies, not by the fact that somebody decided to have
a fund-raiser.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' first two nominees for the University of California Board
of Regents both contributed $100,000 to the governor this year.
</P>
<P>
   One is John Moores, chairman of the San Diego Padres baseball
club. The other is Judith Hopkinson, who heads Ameriquest Capital
Corp. in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' biggest individual contributor was Jerry Perenchio, the
billionaire owner of Univision _ the nation's largest Spanish
language television network. He gave $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   At No. 2 was Fox Group, owned by media mogul Rupert Murdoch,
which gave $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   In previous interviews, Garry South, Davis' top political
adviser, said the governor does not go after industries for
contributions. Davis' fund-raising is ``broad based,'' South said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the spring, Davis set his sights on agriculture. Sources
said two of the governor's confidants _ Rep. Gary Condit, D-Ceres,
and Keith Brackpool, head of Cadiz Land Co. _ organized a Davis
fund-raiser for agriculture interests at the Sutter Club in
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   On May 10, the Davis campaign committee received $5,000 from the
California Association of Wine Growers, $3,000 from the California
Citrus Mutual and $5,000 from the California Farm Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   In all, agricultural interests donated at least $328,000 to
Davis, including $20,000 from Brackpool's company.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Davis angered environmentalists by siding with
farmers and urban water districts in a long-standing court battle
over the distribution of California's water.
</P>
<P>
   Health care groups, including hospitals and HMOs, gave Davis at
least $109,000. The report does not include a fund-raiser sponsored
by HMOs in early July for Davis in Los Angeles. That event raised
at least another $110,000.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was criticized when, three days later, he called key state
legislators and asked them to slow down the progress of bills
increasing state regulation of health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   A small fraction of Davis' contributions were $500 or less. Most
came in chunks of $5,000 to $10,000, sometimes $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the contributions to Davis by industry:
</P>
<P>
   -- Oil _ $125,000. Occidental Petroleum gave $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   -- Gambling _ $125,000 including $75,000 from Hollywood Park
racetrack and $25,000 from the California Commerce Club, the
state's largest card club.
</P>
<P>
   -- Developers _ $226,000. Sacramento developer Angelo
Tsakopoulos gave Davis $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   -- Insurance Companies _ $136,000, including $75,000 from Zenith
Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   -- Timber Companies _ $46,500.
</P>
<P>
   Davis spent $34.8 million last year during his gubernatorial
campaign. Between the election and the new year, he had raised $3.1
million more.
</P>
<P>
   With less than $1 million in expenses, Davis is sitting on $8.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   He is up for re-election in 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
