r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-HARDAWAY-AZR     08-05 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-HARDAWAY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORLANDO MAKES SUNS WAIT  
 HARDAWAY DEAL LIKELY TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Thinking they had a deal completed for Orlando's
Anfernee ``Penny'' Hardaway, the Suns were still standing alone at
the altar Wednesday evening while Magic officials hesitated to walk
down the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   But a league source told ``The Arizona Republic'' that the deal
is likely to be consummated today.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Penny) has told us he wants to be here,'' Suns President
Jerry Colangelo said. ``We've finalized the contract, and now we're
waiting for Orlando to pull the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources told ``The Republic'' that the Suns believed the trigger
already had been pulled.
</P>
<P>
   The club had a commitment from Orlando General Manager John
Gabriel to make the deal, reportedly for Phoenix forwards Danny
Manning and Pat Garrity along with two first-round draft picks, if
the Suns could reach terms with Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway told Colangelo on Tuesday that he had decided to play
for the Suns, and Phoenix agreed to his contract terms _ seven
years for about $86 million, the maximum allowed for a player with
six years of experience in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Then the deal hit a snag.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic wouldn't complete the transaction as Coach Doc Rivers
apparently tried to derail the sign-and-trade arrangement either to
convince Hardaway to remain with Orlando or to sign for less money
and accept a different trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a deal until it's signed by us,'' Gabriel told
the ``Orlando Sentinel.'' ``We're not trying to undercut the Suns.
We just want to make sure everything has been discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make sure on a decision of this magnitude that we
have thoroughly discussed it and thought it through to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said the Suns were in contact Wednesday with Hardaway,
who assured the Suns that his position had not changed. Hardaway
told Colangelo again that he wants to play in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   With that, all the Suns could do was wait to find out whether
Gabriel would honor his commitment to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Manning's agent, Mark Bartelstein, said he expects the deal to
happen and Manning is ``OK either way it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrity worked out Wednesday at America West Arena and said he
also expects a deal, although the Suns had not told him he would be
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has told me anything,'' he said. ``But everything I've
heard is that it's me, Danny and a couple of picks.''
</P>
<P>
   While there was speculation that the Magic might be asking the
Suns to sweeten the deal, sources indicated the Magic has known
what the Suns were willing to give _ and already had agreed to take
it.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel said Tuesday that it was the only deal left on the table
for the Magic, which must work a sign-and-trade, re-sign Hardaway
and keep him, or lose him via free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Before the June draft, the Magic sent the Suns a list of players
it would consider attractive in a trade. The Magic wanted Duke's
Corey Maggette, but the Suns drafted Nevada-Las Vegas' Shawn Marion
_ who wasn't on the Orlando list _ because no trade was guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic later traded Horace Grant to Seattle in a deal that
included Maggette.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns, meanwhile, held fast to their offer of Manning,
Garrity and draft picks _ despite continuing inaccurate reports
that forward Tom Gugliotta would be included.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns were so insistent that Gugliotta would not be part of a
deal that General Manager Bryan Colangelo asked Gabriel to contact
Gugliotta's agent and assure him that Gugliotta was not being
discussed. Gabriel made that call.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway was a first-team All-NBA selection in 1995 and 1996 and
was voted by fans into the Eastern Conference starting lineup for
the 1995, '96, '97 and '98 All-Star Games.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hardaway reportedly clashed with former Orlando Coach
Chuck Daly, Rivers has lobbied to keep him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to wind down what we know the landscape of the
league to be, what Penny's value is and what his intentions are,''
Gabriel told ``Florida Today.'' ``Those things are becoming much
clearer to us now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's challenging and difficult to get everything you want in a
deal. But I don't know really what else we can do. We're going back
now and re-examining the work that was done 10 times and asking
whether we missed anything. All we can do is our best. We've put in
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And all the Suns could do was wait. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 0340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
