<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 03:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6420 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOSEMITE-CRIME-SFCHRO     08-05 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-CRIME-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 YOSEMITE KILLINGS CALLED HATE CRIMES  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Eureka woman who lost her daughter, granddaughter
and a family friend in a brutal Yosemite triple murder testified to
Congress Wednesday that the killings were a hate crime against
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else could they be?'' asked Carole Carrington, whose
daughter Carole Sund was killed in February, along with her
granddaughter Julie and Julie's visiting Argentine friend Silvina
Pelosso. ``A person who doesn't know the people at all, and murders
them only because they are women? It has to be that.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have said handyman Cary Stayner confessed to the
killings, along with the decapitation of 26-year-old Yosemite
naturalist Joie Armstrong in July, claiming he had fantasized about
killing women for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Carrington was called to testify at a House Judiciary Committee
hearing by ranking Democrat John Conyers of Michigan, who wants to
expand federal discrimination law to cover crimes motivated by
gender, sexual orientation and disability as hate crimes, along
with race, religion and national origin.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would give federal authorities jurisdiction to
investigate and prosecute such crimes and to aid local law
enforcement. Although Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder said most
hate crimes are investigated and prosecuted at the state level,
``in rare circumstances where state or local officials are unable
or unwilling to bring appropriate criminal charges ... the United
States must be able to bring federal civil rights charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder said the Clinton administration strongly supports the
legislation. Holder said that all murders and assaults should be
taken seriously but that crimes motivated by hatred of certain
groups of people ``I consider, quite frankly, more serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder said such attacks are ``not just on the individual
victim, but on the victim's community, and their impact is broader
because they send a message of hate.'' He said broader federal
jurisdiction to prosecute these crimes is essential.
</P>
<P>
   But several legal scholars called by the committee said labeling
certain crimes as motivated by hate punishes thought, in violation
of the First Amendment right to free speech. John Yoo, a professor
at the University of California at Berkeley's Boalt Hall School of
Law, said such legislation could be struck down by the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``All crimes are hate crimes,'' added Daniel Troy, a
constitutional lawyer at the conservative American Enterprise
Institute. Troy said the bill ``wrongly suggests that one person's
life is worth more than another's. ... If someone were to kill me
for being a yuppie swine or a ... Jew, I would be dead
regardless.''
</P>
<P>
   Heidi Hurd, a professor of law and philosophy at the University
of Pennsylvania who described herself as a liberal Democrat, said
all rapes would probably have to be classified as hate crimes. Hurd
said the bill is an ``extremely worrisome'' attempt to ``legislate
virtue'' by ``political perfectionists who believe the power of the
state should be used to improve people's thoughts and beliefs.''
Hurd said modern criminal law has always prohibited acts, not
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Carrington flew from her home in Eureka the night before the
hearing, and she also appeared Wednesday on ``Good Morning
America,'' ``Today'' and CNN. She said that although the FBI was
called in to investigate the murders in her family in part because
Yosemite is federal property, she had met many families of crime
victims whose cases remain unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   The hate crimes bill tops the agenda of the Human Rights
Campaign, a gay rights lobby. It died in the last Congress, but has
found stronger support this year (40 co-sponsors in the Senate and
182 in the House) after the beating death of openly gay Matthew
Shepard in Laramie, Wyo., and the murder of James Byrd, Jr., an
African American who was dragged to death behind a pickup truck in
Jasper County, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the bill passed the Senate on a voice vote as an
amendment to an appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde of Illinois said
he was undecided on the legislation and called Wednesday's hearings
to explore the effect of existing hate-crime laws and the potential
for overlap with other criminal statutes, as well as potential
conflicts with the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   A committee spokesman said Hyde may hold more hearings but has
not yet decided whether to proceed with legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Carrington, the panel heard from Tony Orr, a gay
man who was beaten with his partner, Tim Beauchamp, in Tulsa,
Okla., while getting money at an automated teller machine. Orr
testified that three young men approached the pair, referred to
them with a crude epithet and then proceeded to beat them severely,
only stopping when passers-by called police from a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Orr said the attackers told police they were ``only rolling a
couple of fags'' and that the local district attorney accepted a
plea bargain for 40 hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
   Reuben Greenberg, an African American who worked for the San
Francisco city government and now is chief of police in Charleston,
S.C., said that during the civil rights movement in the 1960s,
``federal legislation was seen as our only hope,'' but now local
law enforcement is adequate to prosecute such crimes.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in both the Byrd and Shepard cases, local and state
authorities ``acted quickly and decisively to arrest, prosecute and
convict those local persons who were responsible. ... There was no
delay, no hesitation and no reluctance,'' adding that Wyoming has
no hate crimes laws.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 21 states have hate crimes laws covering sexual
orientation and disability as well as race, while 22 cover gender,
and the rest states have no hate crime laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
