<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TERROR KING WITCH PROJECT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Absolutely no animals were harmed in the
production of this column. Unless you count the fly that drowned in
my coffee. Wish I'd noticed sooner.
<P>
   CONGRATULATIONS to all of us for surviving July, at least those
of us who didn't die trying. One month down, two to go.
Nostradamus, Daryl Glen reminds us, prophesied that ``in either
July, August or September of 1999 there will appear in the sky a
Great King of Terror.''
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion: When the King appears, let's throw him a curve.
Everyone look up and laugh like crazy.
</P>
<P>
   IF MR. TERROR KING does appear, won't the people who have been
in a panic over the Y2K crisis feel like a bunch of ninnies?
</P>
<P>
   CRIME RIPPLE: From the Marin Independent Journal police log,
spotted by Serena Lee: ``Tiburon theft: A Neds Way resident told
police someone took his Wall Street Journal.''
</P>
<P>
   Police are searching for the perp but are bearish on their
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``AIN'T TOO PROUD TO BEG,'' sings a Powell Street panhandler.
When the faux Temptation tunehandled Tom Sweeney, doorman at the
Sir Francis Drake, Sweeney said, ``I'll give you a buck if you zip
up your pants.''
</P>
<P>
   HOW DO YOU KNOW when you're old? Warning sign No. 734: Judi
Basolo was trying out a Walkman at Circuit City, tuned to an oldies
station, grooved to ``White Rabbit,'' blurted to the sales clerk,
``I just love Jefferson Airplane.'' Clerk said: ``Man, I thought he
was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   TRIHACK the well-read cabbie says: ``Thanks to the Macy's ads in
The Chronicle, I've been able to let my subscription to Playboy
lapse.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Macy's ads have good cartoons and stories?
</P>
<P>
   NOT A BAD RUMOR, just an outdated one: Reported here that John
Travolta is trying to buy the Spreckels Mansion. He was, but that
was way back when Travolta had Saturday night fever. Now he's got
Monday morning aches and pains.
</P>
<P>
   THE VULTURES of the tabloids, not to be confused with we
vultures of the legit media, are circling the Bay, sniffing out the
recent last-minute cancellation of a big-time diva's East Bay
concert. It was her fifth cancellation on her current tour due to
``exhaustion.''
</P>
<P>
   Like I've been trying to explain to my boss: Calling in sick
repeatedly can be very exhausting.
</P>
<P>
   AND THEY GET the bases dry-cleaned: Ray Birch wasn't surprised
to see, at a baseball game at Tamalpais High in Mill Valley, the
dirt-smoother screen being pulled around the infield by a BMW.
</P>
<P>
   LOCAL ANGLE: ``The Haunting,'' at a theater near you, is based
on ``The Haunting of Hill House,'' by the late Shirley Jackson
(died '65), who was born and raised in Burlingame, Calif., and
placed many of her spooky books and stories on the Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   MIXED REVIEWS for that film. It sux, says a Chronicle critic.
</P>
<P>
   I'm shopping a proposal for a horror movie about a horror movie
that is viciously hacked and slashed to death by a sadistically
clueless director and screenwriter.
</P>
<P>
   THOSE UCLA football players caught using bogus
handicapped-parking placards on campus got community service. Tina
Hirt says they should be assigned to help disabled students park
and get to their destinations. Would be an educational experience
for the lads.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE doesn't know the American people, scoffs Bill Bradley,
who adds, `'I know the American people.'' So Lee Houskeeper issues
Bradley the challenge: ``Name 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   APPROACHING the Golden Gate Bridge from the North, Ken Delpit
passed an electronic sign alerting drivers that they are entering a
``Double Fine Zone.'' Says Ken, ``With the bridge's magnificent
architecture and the spectacular view, I had to agree.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S UP, MOMA gallery guards wonder, with the woman who
``secretly'' videotapes herself standing on the same spot for hours
at a time?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she's a part-time installation. Maybe we all are.
</P>
</TEXT>
