<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ANEMIC FOOD STAMP PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government says food stamps are ``the first line of defense
against hunger.'' Unfortunately, years of bureaucratic delay are
punching holes in that defense, according to a report from the
General Accounting Office. The US Department of Agriculture, which
runs the food stamp program, must fix the holes.
</P>
<P>
   The report describes a sharp drop in food stamp use _ a 27
percent decline in participation over the past 3 1/2 years. The
main reason for the drop is a strong economy; other factors are
welfare reform and tighter food eligibility rules.
</P>
<P>
   But the report also voices concern that state efforts to reduce
welfare caseloads ``may have diminished eligible children's
participation'' in the food stamp program. The statistics concur.
The number of children helped by food stamps has dropped more
sharply than the number of children living in poverty. This
suggests that the program isn't meeting the need. Proof turned up
in New York City and Milwaukee, both of which have violated federal
law with unduly strict food stamp policies, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   The larger problem is that states are in a federal policy
vacuum. Three years ago the federal welfare reform law changed the
rules on food stamps, giving states more leeway in setting up
procedures. But the USDA's Food and Nutrition Service still hasn't
published the rules. The department attributes the delay to a
reorganization. In addition, required yearly examinations on how
states are running their food stamp programs do not always occur
because of a lack of resources.
</P>
<P>
   Welfare is no longer an entitlement program, but food stamps
are. And they are essential to low-income families as well as to
welfare recipients who are expected to find and keep jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Watkins, The USDA's undersecretary of food, nutrition,
and consumer services, is expected to testify in a congressional
hearing. The best thing she could do is announce a major overhaul
that will cut through the bureaucratic barbed wire that keeps
eligible citizens from getting this crucial aid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 0904EDT &QL; 
