A6495 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-HALLE-BERRY-IS-D     08-05 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-HALLE-BERRY-IS-DOROTHY-DANDRIDGE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALLE BERRY'S ROAD TO `DOROTHY DANDRIDGE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Halle Berry in
``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    They are from different generations _ indeed, from different
worlds _ but Halle Berry says she has no difficulty identifying
with the trials and tribulations of the late star Dorothy
Dandridge.
 &HT;    Both actresses have the faces of angels, and both embody a
smoldering sexiness that captivated Hollywood in their respective
eras.
 &HT;    Dandridge made film history in 1954, when her performance in
``Carmen Jones'' led her to become the first black ever nominated
for an Oscar as Best Actress. Her career soon went downhill,
however, and in 1965 she died at 42 from an overdose of
antidepressant pills.
 &HT;    Dandridge was beautiful and talented, but because she was black
she never had a chance to compete with the top Hollywood leading
ladies of her day. Berry has enjoyed a promising start _ including
memorable roles in ``Jungle Fever'' (l991), ``Losing Isaiah''
(l995) and ``Bulworth'' (l998), as well as the television
miniseries ``Alex Haley's Queen'' (l993) and the cable movie
``Solomon and Sheba'' (l995) _ and is hoping that she may be able
to make the leap that Dandridge was denied.
 &HT;    Times have changed, she says, but not as much as you might
think. Pencil-slim in a blue halter top with matching slacks and
sandals, the actress sits in the Ritz-Carlton Hotel in Pasadena,
Calif. She's talking about her own performance in ``Introducing
Dorothy Dandridge,'' which airs on HBO on Aug. 2l, but she's
thinking about Dandridge.
 &HT;    ``I feel we had a lot in common,'' she says. ``There was
something that Dorothy and I uniquely shared, and that was being in
Hollywood, wanting to be a leading lady and feeling like a leading
lady _ but being in an industry that has no place for us.''
 &HT;    Berry isn't so unrealistic as to compare end-of-millennium
America to the segregated world of the 1940s and 1950s. But she
says that Hollywood still has miles to go before she'll feel she's
playing on a level field.
 &HT;    ``Of course I realize how far we've come,'' she says. ``I can
walk into any club on any day of the week, speak to anybody I want
to and walk out the front door. But I still face barriers ... I
still don't feel like there's a space for a leading lady in
Hollywood who's black.''
 &HT;    Directed by Martha Coolidge, the movie co-stars Klaus Maria
Brandauer as director Otto Preminger, Dandridge's one-time lover,
and Brent Spiner _ best known from television's ``Star Trek: The
Next Generation'' _ as Earl Mills, the devoted manager who loved
her until the end.
 &HT;    It does not make excuses for Dandridge's often-foolish choices,
but it attempts to understand why, given the circumstances of her
life, the end was almost inevitable.
 &HT;    Sexually assaulted as a teen-ager by her mother's often-violent
female lover, Dandridge was uncomfortable with intimacy for the
rest of her life. Both of her marriages _ to dancer Harold Nicholas
of the famous Nicholas Brothers, and then to a minor-league con man
who left her bankrupt _ failed, and her only child was a retarded
daughter.
 &HT;    Her death was never officially ruled a suicide, but Berry
believes the actress killed herself.
 &HT;    ``I'm not saying I believe the night she died she took the pills
and said, `OK, I'm doing to lie down on the floor and die right
now,''' she says. ``I think it was a slow process. She was taking
the pills and mixing the alcohol and slowly killing herself for
years before she died.
 &HT;    ``At 42 she was back at the bottom of the heap,'' she says.
``When she was young and fresh and at her prime at 32, she was at
the top _ and still she was denied the brass ring. I think she was
tired and didn't want to fight that fight to get back on top
again.''
 &HT;    Born in Cleveland _ as Dandridge also was _ Berry grew up in
Ohio with a white, British mother who, she says, kept her on the
straight and narrow after her black father, Jerome Berry, deserted
the family when she was only 4 years old.
 &HT;    Berry never had to endure the everyday humiliations of
segregation _ even as a headliner, Dandridge often had to go
onstage via the service kitchen and was sometimes denied access to
bathrooms.
 &HT;    But growing up biracial wasn't easy. She remembers being called
``Zebra'' and ``Oreo,'' especially after her mother moved the
family to a predominantly white suburb.
 &HT;    It helped her understand Dorothy Dandridge, she says.
 &HT;    ``When I was 18 I first saw `Carmen Jones,''' she recalls. ``I
had no idea who she was. But I was moved and inspired by her _ I'd
never seen a black lady who was so beautiful and charismatic. I
didn't find out at that time that she was from Cleveland, too.''
 &HT;    As a young actress benefiting from Hollywood's improved racial
climate, Berry says she feels an obligation to those who went
before, particularly Dandridge, to get their story told. That sense
of obligation sustained her through the six years it took to get
the film made.
 &HT;    ``What really inspired me was the fact that Dorothy had been so
forgotten,'' she says, ``and that her contribution was so great and
so meaningful, not only to me but to an entire community of people.
 &HT;    ``I'm still almost in the exact same position she was, trying to
carve out that niche,'' Berry says. ``But because she lived and
ultimately died, I'm able to tell her story. And I have a chance to
carve my own big niche.''
 &HT;    Berry, who is also the film's executive producer, had to fight
to get the rights to Dandridge's story. Whitney Houston and Janet
Jackson both wanted to portray Dandridge, and for a while they
seemed to have the inside track.
 &HT;    ``How did I get it?'' Berry asks. ``I'm still asking myself that
question. I was relentless in my efforts. The other ladies are also
singing superstars, so they had other careers that demanded much of
their attention.''
 &HT;    To prepare for the role, Berry watched hours of tapes of
Dandridge and rehearsed lip-syncing to the voice of Wendy Williams,
who sings Dandridge's music. She also spent four months studying
dance with the film's choreographer, Kim Blank, in an effort to
duplicate Dandridge's sexy moves.
 &HT;    The biggest problem with the role, she says, is that it's raised
her expectations unrealistically high.
 &HT;    ``Now that I've done this amazing role of a lifetime,'' she
says, ``I have not been able to find a project that can even
compare to the role that I've just played.''
 &HT;    That would presumably include her next role, as the weather
goddess Storm in the big-screen movie adaptation of the hit comic
book ``The X-Men.''
 &HT;    Storm may be no Dorothy Dandridge, Berry says, but she takes
heart from the fact that she was able to play Dandridge at all.
 &HT;    ``In terms of black women in the entertainment industry,'' she
says, ``we've come a long way, because in l999 I had the power to
dare to dream a dream of producing a movie for myself about a woman
that I adored. Somehow I managed to make that happen.
 &HT;    ``Dorothy would never have been able to produce a movie back in
l953,'' she adds. ``It was a racist and sexist industry. But I do
think it's changing.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Introducing Dorothy
Dandridge,'' consult the HBO Website at www.hbo.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
