</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Flighty lawsuits challenge boundaries of tort
 &HT;    (For release Aug. 8, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There seems to be no end to creative lawsuits, giving support to
consumer advocate Ralph Nader's recurring contention that a museum
be built to acclaim our wackiest litigations.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, two cases arose on either side of the continent
that, if they reach the courtroom, likely will rival the case of
the New Mexico woman who spilled hot coffee in her lap at the
McDonald's drive-through.
</P>
<P>
   (The jury awarded the 81-year-old woman $2.9 million in punitive
and compensatory damages for a scalded crotch. Afterward, the judge
reduced the award to closer to a half-million dollars, which still
can buy a lot of lukewarm hamburgers and coffee down at the Golden
Arches.)
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Ana Margarita Martinez of Miami. She has filed a
personal injury claim against the entire island of Cuba. She's
claiming rape.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, she found out too late, was a double-agent, with
his prime allegiance to Fidel Castro's regime. He fled Miami for
Havana in 1996, deserting his wife, and Martinez says she was an
unwitting cover for him. She claims no knowledge of her husband's
covert activity.
</P>
<P>
   What she does have knowledge of, however, is that she and her
husband maintained a normal sexual relationship and that, in fact,
he was working for Castro and not intending to stay with her or in
this country. Therefore, she maintains, she actually was being
raped each time they had sex _ and it was the Cuban government that
was raping her.
</P>
<P>
   OK, we'll come back to that later.
</P>
<P>
   Now, out of Los Angeles, a man has filed a civil rights lawsuit
against the L.A. police department and city government, accusing
police officers of assault, battery and wrongful death in a case in
which his mother was shot to death by one of the officers.
</P>
<P>
   What intrigues me is that Margaret Mitchell, 54, was a homeless
woman who wandered the streets of Los Angeles pushing a shopping
cart. The police contend she threatened one of them with a
screwdriver, which resulted in the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly, there is a good case against the police. A 54-year-old
woman with a screwdriver shouldn't rate a bullet in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   But this son, the one who's suing; what do we know about him?
Well, we know that he allowed his mother to be homeless. We also
are told that the woman was mentally ill _ and, apparently, her son
did not provide help for that either.
</P>
<P>
   Why should this guy get rich over her death? If anything, I
think someone ought to sue him, maybe arrest him _ for neglecting
his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Cuba-raped-me lawsuit will get quite an airing in
Miami, which is heavy into Cubans. A precedent was set in 1996 when
families of four private-plane pilots shot down and killed by
Castro's MiGs in the Straits of Florida were awarded more than
$187.6 million in damages from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Fidel did not pull out his checkbook. Instead, the
victors are trying to pry loose the money from frozen Cuban assets
in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The two most recent cases could wind up as key exhibits in
Nader's fantasized museum of unconventional tort. As this first
surfaced a year ago, and I have heard nothing of it since, I would
assume that Ralph hasn't yet the funding for it.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he could sue somebody for something.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
