A6497 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN08-COX     08-05 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The red flag of racism
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a notion being hustled around naively _ or is it slyly?
_ that we've become a colorblind nation and that after 350 years of
severe racial oppression and 30 of indifferent relief, the books
are squared and broad efforts at racial catch-up such as
affirmative action abuse the downtrodden white folk.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this scenario is that reality keeps rudely
intruding. It is easy enough to pass off the continuing racist
murders _ de facto lynchings _ as random acts by the aberrant. But
how do you explain away the whole state of South Carolina?
</P>
<P>
   Fed up that the state's politicians can't summon the small
gumption to stop flying the Confederate battle flag over the
Capitol, the state's NAACP and the National Council of Negro Women
want African Americans to shun South Carolina's vacation sites, and
the Southern Christian Leadership Conference and even the staid
Urban League have canceled conventions there.
</P>
<P>
   This has moved the governor only to promise he will poll state
legislators on the issue _ legislators who savaged the previous
governor for proposing to take down the flag. Expect nothing better
than the same rebel yells from that quarter again.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one state senator, the deliciously named Arthur Ravenel
_ ``Gone With the Wind'' isn't gone! _ has said of a black tourist
boycott, in effect, good riddance. Ah, Southern hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina can't just be shrugged off as eccentric. Alabama
struck the Confederate ensign from its capitol in 1993 only because
a state judge ruled its display there illegal. Mississippi and
Georgia stick by state flags that incorporate the design.
</P>
<P>
   The resurgent and noisome Sons of Confederate Veterans recently
hoisted a huge Georgia flag near I-75, you may be sure only because
of that incorporation. One rhapsodized, ``With everyone who passes
by here every day, it should make everyone feel really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. (To boot, Georgia recently named a bridge on I-75 for
the state's last race-baiting governor, Lester Maddox, helping the
sons-of to make that interstate a racist sluice for traffic.)
</P>
<P>
   All of this is not said to pick on the South. It uniquely
suffers from having a handy and universally recognized symbol with
which literally to wave its racial irreconciliation and defiance.
</P>
<P>
   Those same attitudes occur in other regions, if less overtly
often even more destructively. One way: predatory attacks in the
courts on racial progress by tax-exempt law firms richly funded by
the sugar daddy families and foundations of the hard right.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, we've made huge racial progress in the last
generation. The gaps between black and white income, education and
health, and in most other social indices, have narrowed.
</P>
<P>
   But don't make the contrary mistake either. The gaps remain and
there are no few folks among us who, in ways both theatrical and
meanly real, are busy about the business of leaving to African
Americans alone the task of closing them.
</P>
<P>
   A colorblind nation wouldn't even think of flying the
Confederate battle flag, in fact or in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 0941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6524 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV08-C     08-05 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: JUMPING INTO THE FLIMSY INTERNET
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial queues for release
Sunday, Aug. 8.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wall Street's wedded bliss with the Internet now
seems in need of a marriage counselor. When the market capital of
an online firm that sells discounted airline tickets exceeds the
combined stock value of several major airlines, there well may be a
reason to seek a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Internet's glamour has faded among many
investors just as cheaper computers and powerful software have made
the Internet at long last into a true mass medium.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in years to come, the threat to the continued rapid
growth of the Internet will not be a lack of investment capital,
but rather a glut of computer code crackers, scam artists, thieves,
foreign spy rings and other forms of low life that appear to thrive
in cyberspace. High technology hasn't altered the human condition.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who have been paying our bills on line for years,
with the aid of virtual banks, know how nice it is to remotely
access current reports on the status of our accounts, without ever
writing checks or licking stamps.
</P>
<P>
   The Gartner Group, an Internet research company, estimates that
less than 5 percent of U.S. households now pay their bills on line.
In another decade, however, the firm predicts that this figure will
climb to 70 percent _ roughly following the trajectory that has
seen VCRs become standard items in most American homes.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with any such projection is that computer networks
aren't safe. The bigger they get, the greater the risk. The only
sure way to protect yourself on the Internet, a vast network of
networks, is to pull the plug. Even then, it's best to set up shop
in a double-walled, lead-lined chamber, where your keystrokes can't
be read by outside snooping devices.
</P>
<P>
   Editors love to play up stories revealing hardware or software
security holes that let hidden intruders gain access to the
computers of millions of customers, in order to steal or destroy
their data or shut down their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed industry executives duly come clean. They announce
that programs to patch the flaws are in the works. Things then
simmer down for a while until, inevitably, the same sad cycle
repeats itself.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the White House has cooked up a its own ``patch,''
which calls for sensors to detect intrusions into government
computers and report suspicious activity to the FBI. Critics charge
that an exaggerated threat of terrorism is being manipulated to
erode civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides, however, miss the point. By their nature, all
networks can be hacked and passwords broken. The same federal
government that frets about internal intrusions has spent billions
of dollars to penetrate external targets.
</P>
<P>
   So what to do?
</P>
<P>
   First, put a halt to the culture of admiration among some
computer gurus for bold cyber-safecrackers.
</P>
<P>
   Second, learn to ``hide in the open'' by keeping those elements
of your life that you truly need to keep private where no network
can ever find them.
</P>
<P>
   Third, read newspapers, magazines and books. They remain immune
one-way mirrors into an increasingly networked world.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
