<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6526 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV08-C     08-05 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: JUMPING INTO THE FLIMSY INTERNET
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial queues for release
Sunday, Aug. 8.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wall Street's wedded bliss with the Internet now
seems in need of a marriage counselor. When the market capital of
an online firm that sells discounted airline tickets exceeds the
combined stock value of several major airlines, there well may be a
reason to seek a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Internet's glamour has faded among many
investors just as cheaper computers and powerful software have made
the Internet at long last into a true mass medium.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in years to come, the threat to the continued rapid
growth of the Internet will not be a lack of investment capital,
but rather a glut of computer code crackers, scam artists, thieves,
foreign spy rings and other forms of low life that appear to thrive
in cyberspace. High technology hasn't altered the human condition.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who have been paying our bills on line for years,
with the aid of virtual banks, know how nice it is to remotely
access current reports on the status of our accounts, without ever
writing checks or licking stamps.
</P>
<P>
   The Gartner Group, an Internet research company, estimates that
less than 5 percent of U.S. households now pay their bills on line.
In another decade, however, the firm predicts that this figure will
climb to 70 percent _ roughly following the trajectory that has
seen VCRs become standard items in most American homes.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with any such projection is that computer networks
aren't safe. The bigger they get, the greater the risk. The only
sure way to protect yourself on the Internet, a vast network of
networks, is to pull the plug. Even then, it's best to set up shop
in a double-walled, lead-lined chamber, where your keystrokes can't
be read by outside snooping devices.
</P>
<P>
   Editors love to play up stories revealing hardware or software
security holes that let hidden intruders gain access to the
computers of millions of customers, in order to steal or destroy
their data or shut down their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed industry executives duly come clean. They announce
that programs to patch the flaws are in the works. Things then
simmer down for a while until, inevitably, the same sad cycle
repeats itself.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the White House has cooked up a its own ``patch,''
which calls for sensors to detect intrusions into government
computers and report suspicious activity to the FBI. Critics charge
that an exaggerated threat of terrorism is being manipulated to
erode civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides, however, miss the point. By their nature, all
networks can be hacked and passwords broken. The same federal
government that frets about internal intrusions has spent billions
of dollars to penetrate external targets.
</P>
<P>
   So what to do?
</P>
<P>
   First, put a halt to the culture of admiration among some
computer gurus for bold cyber-safecrackers.
</P>
<P>
   Second, learn to ``hide in the open'' by keeping those elements
of your life that you truly need to keep private where no network
can ever find them.
</P>
<P>
   Third, read newspapers, magazines and books. They remain immune
one-way mirrors into an increasingly networked world.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
