<HEADER>
A6575 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-DOGS-$ADV07-CO     08-05 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DOGS-$ADV07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO CITY URGES RESIDENTS TO SCOOP DOG POOP, A HEALTH THREAT
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Aug. 7 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Whenever a scruffy vagabond known as ``Bones''
relieves himself in a public park here, he's not engaged in an
isolated act.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1 million other stray dogs that roam this vast
metropolis have no choice but to use the city's streets and squares
as their toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the pack in this unfortunate slice of urban life are as
many as 2 million additional dogs lucky enough to have homes, but
whose masters habitually neglect to clean up their pets' solid
waste.
</P>
<P>
   The result is more than 350 tons of fecal matter deposited in
public areas here each day(CQ). It's a phenomenon that's not only
an assault on the eyes and feet, but a significant threat to
respiratory health, according to Mexico City health officials.
</P>
<P>
   Unchecked dog feces contributes to Mexico City's notoriously bad
air, along with automobile emissions, officials say. A transmitter
of bacteria and parasites, particles of dried dog waste also
contaminate food served in the city's ubiquitous outside taco
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It dries and then it flies into the air. Then I breath it and
you breath it,'' said an exasperated Laura Elena Herrejon,
president of the Pro-Neighbors Movement, a Mexico City residents'
group working with city officials to clean up dog excrement.
</P>
<P>
   For Herrejon, reducing dog waste is a matter of political will.
</P>
<P>
   Tackling the long-festering problem of street dogs is very
tough, she said. But laws exist requiring pet owners' to clean up
pet crud. They just haven't been enforced -- until now.
</P>
<P>
   In response to public outcry, officials in this capital city's
biggest and busiest district-- the Cuauhtemoc Borough -- have
initiated a campaign to clean the parks and raise pet owners'
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Last year special maintenance teams were created to scoop poop
in prominent public areas, while officials began sending out fliers
warning residents of the health risks of ``fecalism,'' or
``fecalismo,'' as officials call the abundance of dog doo in
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   By its own count, during one 85-day period last year the
district picked up 13 1/2 tons of excrement left by pets and
strays.
</P>
<P>
   In June the district teamed up with Pro-Neighbors Movement and
started a pilot program to impose penalties on negligent pet
owners.
</P>
<P>
   The Pro-Neighbors Movement provides plastic bags and officials
make sure that containers to throw the bags are available in a park
that's been chosen as the site of the pilot program.
</P>
<P>
   Police and volunteers are dispatched periodically to the Santa
Maria de la Ribera Park to remind pet owners of their obligations.
Officers have the power to give violators a ticket requiring them
to appear before a judge.
</P>
<P>
   A banner in the park warns: ``Neighbor! As of June 16 you could
be fined up to 344 pesos and 50 cents ($35) or jailed for between
six and 12 hours if you fail to pick up your pets' feces. We ask
that you cooperate in this action for the good and the health of
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Wire baskets are attached to a fence and signs instruct pet
owners on how to dispose of droppings and explain laws requiring
the clean up.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been cited yet for violating the regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to take someone before a judge to make an example,''
said Jose Carner, the district's chief of urban services.
</P>
<P>
   But officials would be happy, he said, if people comply with the
law because they understand their health is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc, Carner added, is a massive district chock full of
Mexico City's oldest buildings, monuments and squares, including
the city's historic downtown area. More than 600,000 people live in
the district and between 4 million and 4.5 million people work,
shop, eat or simply visit there every day.
</P>
<P>
   The excrement-extermination program fits into the district's
plans to reclaim the borough's decaying public areas, Carner said.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the result of a push for greater ``civic involvement''
in government, he said, a cornerstone of the 1997 election campaign
of Mexico City Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas -- the city's first
democratically elected mayor.
</P>
<P>
   At least one other district is following Cuauhtemoc's example
and has signed an agreement with the Pro-Neighbors Movement to also
start cracking down on dog waste, said Herrejon.
</P>
<P>
   At the Santa Maria de la Ribera Park, people on an early morning
stroll with pets said they're in full support of reducing errant
dog feces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always pick up the poo poo. I can't pick up the pee pee, of
course,'' said an elderly woman walking her Bassett hound.
</P>
<P>
   Fabiola Perez, mistress of two dogs, pulled out a plastic bag
from her pocket as evidence that she was cooperating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good program,'' she said. ``We've become way to used to
just letting our dogs run around and letting them do their thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez said some pet owners continue to ignore the regulations
and scoff at police -- probably because they don't respect them,
and associate police with corruption and bribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only real vigilance,'' she said, ``is going to be between
neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond pets, Perez said, the city and federal health officials
need to start better managing the capital's street dogs.
Periodically, dogs are rounded up and vaccinated or even
sterilized, but they're often released back on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Two such dogs live in Santa Maria de la Ribera Park. Perez and
other residents offer the animals affection -- they say they are
gentle -- and have named them Bones and Buford. On a recent
morning, one young man even was walking Bones with a rope tied
around the dog's neck.
</P>
<P>
   The strays, which appear to have been pets at one time, eat
scraps residents give them or hang around restaurants. But they
sleep, play -- and defecate -- in the park.
</P>
<P>
   Street dogs are ``a delicate subject,'' according to Carner.
</P>
<P>
   People often get upset when officials try to round the dogs up
because they fear they will be killed. Yet few people are willing
to give the animals a home. And it's common for people in Mexico to
dump pets they can no longer manage on the street to let them fend
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they killed all the strays in Mexico City, the next
day there would be more back on the streets,'' Perez said, petting
Bones and Buford, who looked at her lovingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lack of culture when it comes to taking care
of dogs,'' Perez said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
