<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6576 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-BOX-$ADV08-COX     08-05 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOX-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA'S DEPRESSING ECONOMIC PICTURE
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-CRISIS-$ADV08; RUSSIA-ECONOMY-$ADV08.
 &HT;    EDs: Aug. 17 marks the one-year anniversary of Russia's ruble
crash.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 8 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After an economic boom in 1996 and 1997, Russia fell on
hard times last summer. Its stock market collapsed, the ruble
declined in value, many banks closed and foreign investment dried
up. The sharp economic downturn caps a decade since the fall of the
Soviet Union that has seen Russia's standard of living decline.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at some aspects of Russia's life today:
</P>
<P>
   MORE POOR: The number of Russians living in poverty has
increased from 33 million last year to 55 million today, according
to official statistics released in July. Nearly four of every 10
Russians live below the official subsistence level, defined as an
income below 829 rubles a month, the equivalent of about US$34.
</P>
<P>
   LESS MONEY: The average monthly wage is 1,225 rubles, or about
US$51. Before the Aug. 17 crash, the average wage was the
equivalent of about US$200. Millions of workers go months or even
years without getting paid at all. The average pension is 403
rubles -- U$17 -- a month.
</P>
<P>
   MORE WORK: With the price of imported goods from the West out of
reach of most Russians, many sectors in Russian industry are
reporting an upturn, producing affordable, Russian-made consumer
goods. Industrial output is expected to rise 1.5 percent in 1999,
but still not rebounding from the loss in 1998 of 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   LESS TRADE: Imports fell 46 percent in the first six months of
1999, while exports dropped 11 percent compared to the same period
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   MORE TAX COLLECTIONS: In the first six months of this year,
Russia's tax police nabbed 6,000 tax cheats and added $200 million
to the government treasury, almost totaling the number for all of
1998. But the chief of the tax police, Vlacheslav Soltaganov, said
the figure ``is in my opinion a drop in the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   LESS COMPETITIVE: In an annual survey of business
competitiveness in 59 countries released last month by the
Swiss-based World Economic Forum, Russia finished dead last, ranked
below countries such as Bolivia (ranked 55) and Zimbabwe (57).
</P>
<P>
   MORE CRIME: Russia's murder rate is one of the world's highest,
triple that of the United States and seven times higher than in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   FEWER PEOPLE: Russia's population stands at 146 million,
dropping by 401,000 people last year, and about 2 million over the
past seven years. Alcoholism and the decline in health care have
contributed to a rising death rate and people are having fewer
children. Life expectancy is now estimated at 60.8 years for men,
up considerably from a low of 57.6 years in 1994, but still low for
an industrial nation.
</P>
<P>
   PESSIMISM ABOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   In May of this year, and last September, the Public Opinion
Foundation polled 1,500 Russians assessing their attitudes about
life and the economy. Here's what it found:
</P>
<P>
   ....................................................................
...........................September 1998..............May 1999
</P>
<P>
   Those that believe the worst is 
over?..............................2%...............................
......5%
</P>
<P>
   Those that believe the worst is 
now?.............................26%................................
..32%
</P>
<P>
   Those that believe the worst yet to
come?..................60%..................................53%
</P>
<P>
   Those that have no 
opinion...................................................12%.......
.............................9%
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Poll results have a accuracy of plus or minus 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
