<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6577 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-CRISIS-$ADV08-     08-05 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CRISIS-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ONE YEAR LATER: COPING IN AN EVEN POORER RUSSIA
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-ECONOMY-$ADV08; RUSSIA-BOX-$ADV08.
 &HT;    EDs: Aug. 17 marks the one-year anniversary of Russia's ruble
crash.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 8 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ How's this for spin? Russian officials recently
delivered the good news that the country's economy will not expand
this year.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the times, the government issued the promising
forecast that the economy would remain flat in 1999, compared to
earlier estimates that predicted the downward spiral that commenced
last summer would continue.
</P>
<P>
   One year into its deepest economic crisis since the Soviet Union
collapsed, Russia's outlook is assessed not so much by what's going
right, as by the horrible things that could have -- but haven't --
gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation is down. Industrial production is up. The value of the
ruble has remained relatively steady. To call it the start of an
economic recovery is premature; but neither is Russia the unbridled
disaster some thought it would be by this time.
</P>
<P>
   On August 17, 1998, the value of Russia's national currency
plummeted as the country of 146 million slid headlong into an
economic abyss -- and the world held its collective breath and
watched to see how the globe's second-largest nuclear power coped.
</P>
<P>
   Russians did not riot. With stoic resignation to their plight,
they made do. Though Russia today is a considerably poorer place
than it was last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Russians living in poverty has increased from 33
million to 55 million, according to official statistics released in
July. Today, nearly four of every 10 Russians live below the
official subsistence level, defined as an income below 829 rubles a
month, the equivalent of about US$34.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can we do? `` asked Sergei Kastanov, an out-of-work
Moscow laborer who collects empty bottles and offers rides in his
dilapidated compact car to earn a meager living. ``We're cursed
with bad leaders, bad factories and bad fate.''
</P>
<P>
   The predictions were dire. In the weeks after the ruble crash,
major banks closed and hundreds of thousands of workers lost their
savings and their jobs. Food shortages were reported, including one
Arctic town where residents were said to be killing and cooking
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   As winter set in, some areas of Russia were without heat. Even
an official United Nations report speculated that the cold and
scarcity of food could incite social unrest. After all, an economic
crash in Indonesia earlier in 1998 provoked rioting in the streets
and the fall of the government in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   Amid it all, the sickly President Boris Yeltsin seemed out of
touch, changing his prime ministers with nearly the same frequency
as his hospital visits. Four overhauls in the government were
ordered in the 14 months between March 1998 and May of this year,
when current Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin was appointed.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia has managed to confound the Western experts who last
fall were predicting calamity. Accustomed to coping with Soviet-era
scarcities and previous economic crises since communism fell in
1991, Russians hardly protested when their currency dropped
fourfold, from 6 rubles to the dollar to the current rate of 24
rubles to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   But if the worst predictions have not come true, neither has
real progress.
</P>
<P>
   Russian government and businesses are still plagued by
corruption and inefficiency. Wealth remains in the hands of the
relative few. The stock market is edging up, but nowhere near its
boom levels of two years ago. Foreign investors fled last summer
and for the most part have stayed away. Tax collections are up, but
far from levels needed to fulfill the state's needs.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin continues to remain largely secluded, leaving the
country's affairs to be run by a close circle of insiders. No one
expects real improvement until Russia struggles through its
election season and the post-Yeltsin era takes shape. Parliamentary
elections are scheduled for December and Russia is set to elect a
new president next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're stuck somewhere between feudalism and capitalism,''
laments Olga Pushkina, a financial consultant whose company seeks
to turn around failing Russian firms.
</P>
<P>
   The larger, looming unknown element now is not economics, but
politics: Will the elections for parliament and president be fair?
Who will prevail -- market reformers, old-style communists or
something in between? And what of the fate of Russia's experiment
with democracy?
</P>
<P>
   ``We approach the elections in a state when nothing is known for
sure. Absolute uncertainty,'' said Yevgeny Yasin, a former
economics minister. ``What will happen after the elections? Nobody
knows.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Russians are getting by as best they can. In some
instances, the ruble collapse worked to Russia's benefit,
invigorating domestic industries that can produce goods cheaper
than foreign imports.
</P>
<P>
   At the Spirovski bottle factory, near Tver, production has
tripled as Russian vodka-makers have turned from importing more
expensive glass bottles from European suppliers to the factory's
cheaper bottles. Likewise, the Russian carmaker Autovaz has this
year hit a five-year high on its production lines.
</P>
<P>
   Such sporadic good news was bolstered further in July when two
of the world's financial institutions gave Moscow some breathing
room.
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund agreed in July to resume lending
to Russia with a $4.5 billion assistance package to be delivered
over the next 18 months. And foreign debtors of the so-called Paris
Club in last week(CQ) eased the payment schedule on $8.1 billion of
arrears dating back to Soviet times.
</P>
<P>
   Yet billions more dollars in debt has piled up in the years
since 1991. (The Soviet-era debt deal settled in Paris represents
only about half of Russia's' external debt.). It is a crushing
burden that unless deferred or forgiven threatens to consume
Russia's entire government budget, currently at $25 billion in
1999. ``Any economic growth in the next 10 years is absolutely out
of the question,'' Deputy Prime Minister Mikhail Zadornov warned
recently, referring to the debt problem.
</P>
<P>
   And the upbeat anecdotes and financial tidings cannot mask the
fact that Russians are vastly poorer today, and largely soured on
Western-style economic reforms that they equate with economic
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standard of living for Russian citizens has noticeably
dropped and is currently only 60 percent of 1997 levels. A new
economic decline has taken place in Russia,'' said Vladimir
Kuzmichev, who writes about economics for the daily Nezavisimaya
Gazeta.
</P>
<P>
   They survive largely by taking advantage of Soviet-era subsidies
that keeps the cost of housing and health care low. They also grow
their own food on small plots of land in the country. Russians also
operate in an underground economy based on cash -- mainly U.S.
dollars -- not recorded by government statisticians.
</P>
<P>
   The news is not all bad. Russia continues to develop an
entrepreneurial class of younger people accustomed to their
post-Soviet freedoms and commercial opportunities. According to
polls, few Russians are satisfied with the messy transition from
communism to Russia's current system of half-done capitalism. But
the majority does not want to go back to the USSR, either.
</P>
<P>
   Yevgeny Primakov, the former foreign minister who led the
government from last September until this May, gave Russia ``no
progress and no steps back,'' according to Yasin.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's cautious approach seemed to be the correct one for
the time being.
</P>
<P>
   Russia could not return to drastic Soviet-era economics --
printing rubles and nationalizing industries -- without alienating
the IMF and donor countries like the United States and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But with its hamstrung economy and political gridlock
(communists and nationalists control the opposition parliament),
neither could it dig itself out of its hole and make gains toward
real democratic and market reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The worst predictions have not come true. But neither have the
greatest hopes. Russia reckons the good news is somewhere in
between, where things may be uncertain, but stable for now.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
