<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6585 &Cx1f; tad-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-$ADV08     08-05 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOVIET STEEL TOWN STRUGGLES WITH CRISIS AND CAPITALISM
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-CRISIS-$ADV08; RUSSIA-BOX-$ADV08.
 &HT;    EDs: Aug. 17 marks the one-year anniversary of Russia's ruble
crash.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 8 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAGNITOGORSK, Russia _ In its heyday, the giant steel mill on
the Ural River was one of the world's largest, a smoke-belching
symbol of Soviet industrial might.
</P>
<P>
   Success was measured by the steady volume of raw steel rolling
from its production lines. The fallout from the open blast furnaces
turned the snow black throughout this city of 430,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the snow is white,'' but times are hard, complains Yelena
Sherbakova, a retired mill worker struggling to live on a monthly
pension of just $20. ``It is difficult for everybody. Prices are
very high. You can see signs of improvement, but our lives are
still horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   The output from Magnitogorsk Metal Works is less than half of
what it was a decade ago. The quality of what it manages to churn
out is low. Even Russia's automakers choose to import steel rather
than buy locally because the surfaces of the inferior Russian
product can't hold a paint job.
</P>
<P>
   The promise and problems of Magnitogorsk illustrate the deep
troubles of the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   Magnitogorsk has the natural resources, the technical know-how
and the labor force to compete in the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   But it is lacking the modern facilities to do the job, a stable
Russian economy in which to operate, and an efficient management
and workforce honed for a free-market economy.
</P>
<P>
   It is a Soviet town that with privatization in this decade
became a company town, buffeted by the country's stormy transition
since the Soviet Union collapsed in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The factory survives on barter deals, pays its bloated workforce
in part with credits to be used at the company store and largely
still measures success the old-fashioned Soviet way -- not so much
by profits as by its capacity to produce.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is an industrial town trying its best to modernize and
compete. In the good times, before Russia's economy crashed last
August, the plant sunk its profits back into the company to replace
several antiquated open furnaces with two modern and cleaner
furnaces.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it has plans to borrow by issuing ruble-denominated bonds
to raise money to further modernize the mill. Meanwhile, the
factory and the city are seeking investors to develop other
companies -- construction, manufacturing and light industry -- and
become less reliant on steel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're adapting the economics and politics to the real
conditions that exist in the country. In socialist times,
Magnitogorsk was an industrial center. Now, there are other
directions,'' said Faik Mukhametzianov, chairman of the local Duma,
or city council.
</P>
<P>
   Situated in the southern Urals about 800 miles southeast of
Moscow, Magnitogorsk was founded in 1929 on ``magnetic mountain''
-- a ridge of solid iron ore that was central to the first Soviet
five-year industrialization plan.
</P>
<P>
   Magnitka, the nickname bestowed on both the city and the
factory, stretches for seven miles along the river it pollutes.
Smokestacks still spew columns of orange, gray, brown and black
exhaust that forms an almost permanent haze over the city.
</P>
<P>
   The factory operates in a uniquely Russian mixture of
capitalism, socialism and shadowy financing. Company officials
declined to be interviewed for this article and sought to prevent
city officials from speaking to Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The company maintains a payroll of some 55,000 employees, down
only slightly from Soviet days and unrealistically high in a market
economy, according to industry experts. About 40 percent of
Magnitogorsk's transactions are done in barter; a system that keeps
the business running but injects no new cash into the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Russia's domestic demand for steel is less than 30
percent of its levels a decade ago, and Russian producers have
confronted trade barriers in seeking to sell their product in the
United States and Europe. Asia offers good customers, but the
economic downturn of 1997-98 has hurt that market, too.
</P>
<P>
   Landlocked and remote, Magnitogorsk pays heavy costs to
transport its goods, making it tough to compete with Russian
companies closer to seaports.
</P>
<P>
   Young people, too, feel a bit trapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no where to go. There's nothing else to do. No new
businesses. No new jobs,'' said Slava Masla, 24, a factory
machinist.
</P>
<P>
   But in relative terms, the mill is prospering amid Russia's
economic crisis. Steel sold abroad -- mainly to Asian markets --
brings hard currency, while the factory's operating costs, fixed in
rubles, have fallen over the past year as the ruble plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   Workers earn about 4,000 rubles a month -- about US$167, well
above the national average. But half of it is paid in cash and half
in credits redeemable at the company store.
</P>
<P>
   In Soviet times Magnitogorsk was a ``closed'' city, off limits
to foreign travelers and many Russians, a testament to its
importance. The city still has main streets named for Lenin and
Marx.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgi Tikhonov, editor of the local newspaper, the
Magnitogorsk Worker, says pragmatism, not politics, guides the city
and its people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a workers' town,'' he said. ``Magnitogorsk works no
matter what the system is in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
