<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forget bipartisanship as parties vie for House
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ All his Texas Democratic siblings have been
killed in political battle. He's the only elected Democratic
official left with statewide clout.
</P>
<P>
   A movie about his political mission for 2000 might be called
``Saving Speaker Laney.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's no movie _ just Texas politics. And like former U.S.
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen used to say, Texans consider politics a contact
sport.
</P>
<P>
   In the one-party Democratic days in the Texas Legislature,
personal loyalty and personal organizations were more important
than party affiliations. The late Democratic Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock
eventually made bipartisanship a mantra, and Republican Gov. George
W. Bush picked up on it.
</P>
<P>
   But as Republicans near a majority in the Texas House of
Representatives, amicable dealing across the aisles might be in
greater danger than the whooping crane. The GOP has 72 seats to the
Democrats' 78.
</P>
<P>
   Laney, a cotton farmer and used-car dealer from Hale Center,
northeast of Lubbock, was elected speaker in 1993 after two decades
in the House. Though a Democrat, he's always had Republicans on his
leadership team, as they were for his predecessor for a decade, Gib
Lewis of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   But particularly since the legislators elected next year will
redraw legislative and congressional districts in 2001, overt
bipartisanship might be ending. As Republican numbers have steadily
grown, so have demands from the more strident Republicans _ known
as ``Shiites'' _ that Republicans vote for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican Caucus has asked its members not to sign
pledge cards to any speaker candidate until after the 2000 election
_ obviously to pressure Republicans who might want to pledge
support for Laney to stay neutral.
</P>
<P>
   Laney on paper remains bipartisan, and indeed has a cadre of
Republicans _ several from his area of the state _ who might vote
for him even if the Republicans gained a slight edge. But given the
hardened attitude of Republicans, Laney's team obviously has a
vested interest in holding or adding to Democratic seats.
</P>
<P>
   That team includes five freshman Democrats who won open seats
last year targeted by Republicans (Dan Ellis, Livingston; David
Farabee, Wichita Falls; Mark Homer, Paris; David Lengefeld,
Hamilton; and Allan Ritter, Nederland).
</P>
<P>
   It also includes veteran Democrats from districts whose voters
often choose Republicans at the top of the ballot (David Counts,
Knox City; Craig Eiland, Galveston; Bob Glaze, Gilmer; Patricia
Gray, Galveston; Tom Ramsay, Mount Vernon; Bob Turner, Voss; Tom
Uher, Bay City; Ken Yarbrough, Houston; and Zeb Zbranek, Winnie).
</P>
<P>
   Though Laney caters to incumbents, his supporters' tears would
dry quickly if some marginal seats now held by Republicans (Wayne
Christian, Center; Rick Green, Dripping Springs; Rick Hardcastle,
Vernon; Charles Jones, College Station; and Todd Staples,
Palestine, if he runs for Drew Nixon's Senate seat) were captured
by respectable mainstream Democrats. Recruiting posters are already
up.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans think Bush for president atop the Republican ticket
will help them. They're using that argument to try to get some of
their Democratic colleagues to switch parties. But word so far is
that Democrats aren't defecting. They think they can hold their
own, and maybe even gain a seat or two because:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bush's coattails will be shorter in 2000, because he won't
spend much time or money on Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Polling indicates Democratic issues, such as regulating health
maintenance organizations and protecting Social Security, resonate
with voters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Laney's running a full-out speaker's race that includes noting
the repercussions to members who vote for the loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be out actively working,'' he said. ``I'll try to
be everywhere every member wants me to.''
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, for those Republicans who want him out.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
