<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School initiatives are a bit heavy on the starch
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ With the 2000 census near, it was instructive to
do a nose count at a recent photo op touting education reforms by
the majority party in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   For this photo, children were assembled. A school bus was rolled
into place before the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The scene shared by The Associated Press shows House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, surrounded by suits, and by 30-plus kids in
T-shirts. My eye finds every nose in the picture to be white except
for two.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there were more black and brown children at the event.
Maybe they were just cropped out.
</P>
<P>
   It's unfair to read too much into a picture. But he who lives by
the photo op shall die by it as well.
</P>
<P>
   The June 22 event touted a Republican budget initiative that
would diddle with President Clinton's plan to hire 100,000 teachers
to reduce class size in grades 1 through 3. The initiative instead
would convert $13 billion in education aid to block grants to be
spent as governors wish.
</P>
<P>
   This is a curious turn, since the last Congress approved an
initiative to hire 30,000 teachers. Now the House GOP line is that
states are handcuffed by the class-size initiative and should be
freed to spend the money on teacher training or something else. But
in fact, the current program already allows school districts to
apply for waivers of federal regulations. A case of oafish federal
government with its heel on the necks of local school boards?
Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers worry about what this initiative would mean to
Title 1, the federal program aimed at helping school districts with
the most poverty. It could mean in some states the siphoning of
some federal dollars to the suburbs already rich from siphoning off
urban dollars as they cherry-pick families and students.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it might mean nothing of substance. In that case at
least you've got a photo op.
</P>
<P>
   It's a challenge for some lawmakers who really don't buy into
the concept of public schools to show they care about those
schools.
</P>
<P>
   That's a good reason why vouchers often get trotted out as God's
gift to education reform. It is a perfect match _ policy-makers
whose children wouldn't be caught dead intermingling with all that
social diversity and its baggage suggesting that government make it
possible for others to opt out of the system, just like they did.
</P>
<P>
   Some earnestly believe that vouchers would improve public
schools. But even if that doesn't happen, they can find comfort in
an ideological constituency that is anti-government, quick to blame
public schools for all that ails our world, and is historically
rooted in the quest to keep schools segregated in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Some wrinkles in Texas have served the purpose of getting people
back to bunching in racial groups. Charter schools so serve in some
instances. The George Bush-signed 1995 reform that would allow
``breakaway'' school districts spawned an aborted effort to create
an all-black district in Waco. Four years under that law, no such
breakaway has occurred in all of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other GOP policy positions seek to rub the necks of
those who purchase sanctuary in private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) has made so-called education savings
accounts _ tax-free sums for private education _ his signature
issue. It's portrayed as a way for the starving masses to save up
and achieve private-school nirvana. But you can't save what you
don't have.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, some struggling families would benefit greatly by being
able to tax-shelter accounts to pay for private schooling. But
Coverdell's plan, costing $1.6 billion over 10 years, isn't
means-tested.
</P>
<P>
   A Treasury analysis found that 70 percent of the benefits would
go to the top 20 percent of income earners.
</P>
<P>
   Is that so wrong? Your call. Just don't sell this brand of
education reform as one that helps those children cropped out.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
