<HEADER>
A6613 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-WALTRIP06-COX     08-05 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-WALTRIP06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jaws: The finale
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They were two of stock-car racing's dominant figures
in the early 1970s when Darrell Waltrip first burst on the NASCAR
scene.
</P>
<P>
   But in Indianapolis, where NASCAR prepares for Saturday's
Brickyard 400 and Waltrip announces his yearlong farewell tour
before next year's retirement, Bobby Allison and Cale Yarborough
remember the rivalry with Ol' D.W. in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Yarborough can chuckle about the loudmouthed kid he nicknamed
``Jaws'' some 26 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a great career, and I think he realizes that it's
time that he do something else,'' said Yarborough, who won his last
NASCAR championship in 1978, when Allison finished second, Waltrip
third. ``He's been a great asset to the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison and Waltrip, however, do not speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darrell Waltrip has had friends and fans along the way. I
don't want to take any of that away from him,'' said Allison, who
lost championships to Waltrip by 53 points (1981) and 72 points
(1982) and beat him by 47 points for the 1983 title.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel like he's hung around way, way too long, because
he's had the advantage of things like provisional starts, which he
had 24 last year. He's had really good sponsors, and he's been able
to be in really, really good cars but hasn't been able to do well
in recent years. Maybe it's time that he should step aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarborough and Waltrip had a different relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came into the sport kind of like nobody else that I've seen
lately, doing a lot of talking,'' Yarborough said. In return,
Waltrip came up with the Cale Scale, measuring the difficulty of a
win.
</P>
<P>
   Their skirmishes apparently didn't produce any lingering hard
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had one race in Michigan several years ago where Darrell
and I battled it out most of the day,'' Yarborough said. ``On the
last lap going down the backstretch, we had a battle to the
checkered (flag), and I beat him.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we passed the start-finish line, he made a dive for me
to try to spin me out or try to hit me after the race was over. I
saw him coming, and I avoided him. He went on down and spun out in
the infield. It had been raining the night before, and he got
bogged down in the infield; they had to send a wrecker to get him
out of the mud. I think he was a little embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry with Allison was more intense.
</P>
<P>
   Allison's career ended in 1988 with a crash at Pocono, in Long
Pond, Pa., a wreck that erased a big chunk of memory. He said he
can't remember winning the Daytona 500 that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first racing event that I remembered when I woke up at
Lakeshore Hospital after my Pocono situation, was a race in
Nashville in 1981,'' Allison said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remembered I was driving the Hardee's car, and I was leading
the race. We had a caution flag and on the restart, he just drove
right by me, which convinced me that he had left side tires put on
the right side of the car. So I radioed by crew and told my crew
chief to put left side tires on my right side. The crew chief
informed me that if we got caught, I had to pay the fine. I said,
OK, I'll pay the fine, right now we've got to win the race. So they
put the tires on my car the next pit stop and that let me race him,
but he beat me by a fender.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days, the first five cars had to go to the gas pumps
and the scales, then the winner went to victory lane. He pulled up
to the gas pump and climbed out of his car and called for Joe
Gassaway, the assistant chief inspector. I climbed out of my car to
see what the situation was. As Joe got there, Darrell said `Joe,
Bobby's got left side tires on the right.' Now, he was first and I
was second, so it wasn't going to move him ahead any that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days, the fine was $100 a tire. Ol' Joe stuck his
finger in my face and said, `I'm gonna fine you $1,000 a tire.' I
said, `Joe, he's got 'em on the right, too. With that, Joe turns
his back toward Darrell's car and said, `We ain't looking at him;
we're looking at you.'''
</P>
<P>
   It galls Allison that he is tied for third with Waltrip on the
all-time victory list with 84 wins. Allison said he has never been
given credit for a win in a Mustang in 1971. Waltrip's last victory
came in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But driver Jeremy Mayfield said Waltrip inspired his career.
Mayfield and Waltrip both are natives of Owensboro, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in high school, Darrell came and talked to an
assembly at our school,'' Mayfield said. ``My shop teacher knew how
important racing was to me and how I felt about Darrell, and he
made sure I got the chance to meet him. We didn't talk three
minutes, I bet, but it was probably the biggest three minutes of my
life right then.''
</P>
<P>
   The new generation of Winston Cup drivers might not know the
Waltrip that Allison remembers. To the new kids, he's the witty
one-time champion who needed provisionals to make races the last
several years and usually finished near the rear. But they respect
him for the history he made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of the reason Darrell had a little trouble with
the fans at the beginning of his career wasn't because he talked a
lot,'' Sterling Marlin said. ``The thing is, he'd say he was going
to beat all those boys, (Richard) Petty, Allison, (David) Pearson,
Cale, and then he'd go out and do it. And then he'd say he was
going to do it again. In my neck of the woods we have a saying, `It
ain't bragging if you can do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
