   COXNET ENTERTAIN PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout is available today after 2 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 0807: TELEVISION AND RACE _ The television
landscape has been turning a whiter shade of pale for several
seasons, and come fall, America's real-life diversity will be
reflected more in commercials than in prime-time entertainment on
the four major networks. (Holloway, Austin American-Statesman) Art
includes 3-column color photo illustration showing ``The Cosby
Show,'' an 18-pica color photo from ``The Hughleys,'' an 18-pica
color photo from ``Third Watch,'' a 1-column color photo of comic
Steve Harvey.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MINORITY CHARACTERS LIST _ Here are returning shows and new
shows with prominent minority characters. (Holloway, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS -- The last 15 minutes of ``Message in a Bottle''
are a lunkheaded embarrassment and star Kevin Costner is to blame.
Also, reviews of ``Blast from the Past,'' ``Cruel Intentions'' and
``20 Dates.'' (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes
18-pica color photo from ``Message in a Bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS _ ``This Time,'' doesn't so much advance Los Lobos'
agenda as consolidate it. It's not a breakthrough, instead, it
reveals how the group has reached a point where even seemingly
casual gestures take on a rich sonic complexity. Also reviews of
the new releases from Allison Kraus and The Verve Pipe. (Staff,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Books page for the current week. This
layout is now available.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0803 -- Elva Trevino Hart was working for IBM,
making six figures and driving a Mercedes, when she decided to take
a writing course at a YWCA. She felt a need to write about her
migrant worker childhood. The result is a touching memoir of a
fascinating life. (Morris, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SMUTTY NOVEL -- Amy Sohn's ``Run Catch Kiss,'' a
collection of fleshed-out Penthouse letters masquerading as modern
literature. (Wizda, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GATES PLOT -- Author Gary Rivlin has written an intimate
history of the do-or-die competition that reigns in the lucrative,
high-stakes world of computer technology.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SUMMER READING -- Short takes on latest mystery releases
of note. (Warmbold, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BOOK NEWS -- Nothing sells books like the tragic death of
a much-loved celebrity. Expect the same with John F. Kennedy Jr.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Peter Matthiessen (``Bone by Bone'') and Peter
Garalnick (``Careless Love: The Unmaking of Elvis Presley'' ) are
this year's winners of the Southern Book Awards. Eudora Welty also
will receive a lifetime achievement award at the Southern Festival
of Books in Nashville in October. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 21.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MILNER _ Jay Milner's review of a recently released book.
(Milner, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-LEFTBEHIND _ Jerry Jenkins and his ``Left Behind'' series
of Christian novels based on the book of Revelation has left behind
all other religious books in sales. The original has sold nearly 2
million and is averaging 100,000 sales per months. The five sequels
are each averaging 70,000 a month. And, the newest one, released
Thursday, had advance sales of 800,000. We talk to Jenkins about
the appeal and about how his life has changed with this
best-selling series. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
MY-LAI _ WASHINGTON _ Hugh Thompson, the former Army helicopter
pilot in Vietnam credited for cutting short the My Lai massacre of
civilians, appears at a news conference Thursday to promote a newly
published biography. (Dart, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
</P>
