   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316, rickd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334, andya(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ WARSAW _ Under communism, the people of
Poland had their problems. Out from under communism, the people
still have problems. The difference is ... well, everything's
different. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ This column will not move today. (Ernest
Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Since I acquired the habit
every few months of relaying a few puns in this space that were
sent to me by friends and readers, the number of submissions has
mushroomed. So it's time to clean out the closet and torture you
once again with a few of my favorite groaners. (Gary Borders is
editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel.) MOVED.
EMBARGOED for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   GARCIA-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Today's reserve components are
50 percent of the country's military forces. You don't have to be
Gen. George C. Marshall to figure out that these days Guard and
Reserve troops are a safety valve for politicians and the public.
Using Guard and Reserve personnel to fill in the ranks of the
active duty is relatively cheap and holds at bay discussion of
reviving a draft. Ironic, no? (Arnold Garcia is editorial page
editor of the Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ AUSTIN, Texas _ All his Texas
Democratic siblings have been killed in political battle. He's the
only elected Democratic official left with statewide clout. A movie
about his political mission for 2000 might be called ``Saving
Speaker Laney.'' But it's no movie _ just Texas politics. And like
former U.S. Sen. Lloyd Bentsen used to say, Texans consider
politics a contact sport. (McNeely, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ WACO, Texas _ With the 2000 census
near, it was instructive to do a nose count at a recent photo op
touting education reforms by the majority party in Congress. For
this photo, children were assembled. The scene shows House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, surrounded by suits, and by 30-plus kids in
T-shirts. My eye finds every nose in the picture to be white except
for two. Maybe there were more black and brown children at the
event. Maybe they were just cropped out. It's unfair to read too
much into a picture. But he who lives by the photo op shall die by
it as well. (John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
