<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, August 6,
1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week. This
layout is now available.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 0803 _ A visit to the misty Ilse of Skye in the
Scottish herbribes, where the scene of Surf-pounded skerries (off
shore rocks), tiny fishing villages and mountian-locked lochs has
barely changed since Robert Louis Stevenson's time. (Hulbert,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 4-column color photo of
Scottish castle, a 2-column color photo of mountains by the sea,
2-column color photo of a cluster of mountains on a peninsula,
2-column color map illustration.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PRACTICAL TRAVELER -- When allergic children travel,
adults who are aware of the child's situation need to be sure they
have packed a special pillow or protective case, any medicines
taken regularly, inhalers and whatever else the child may need in a
medical emergency. (Wade, N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- Delta Airlines took the top spot for
leaving ticketed passengers behind in the first three months of
1999. The line bumped 8,144 of its ticketed passengers, while the
nine other major airlines together bumped a total of 9,167. (N.Y.
Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-JAPAN _ TOKYO _ This was my third trip to Japan, where I
go periodically to satisfy my decades-long curiosity about a
culture so different from ours. In fact, I had timed my visit to
coincide with Tokyo's Sanja Festival, intending to watch at least
one day of the three-day event. But participating in the festival's
parade? That was completely unexpected. I found myself in full
traditional costume, hoisting a huge shrine on my sholder, after
signing up for a Japan National Tourist Organzation program in
which more than 1,000 English-speaking families in 14 cities around
Japan open their homes to foreigners. (Gordon, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 8.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TOKYO-GO _ IF YOU GO. . . to Tokyo sedebar, listing info
on food, lodgings, attractions. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 8.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SAWGRASS _ PONTE VERDRA BEACH, Fla. _ A visit to Sawgrass
Marriott Resort _ an inviting family vacation spot on Florida's
Northeastern-most coast. Here, among the dunes and sands of Ponte
Vedra Beach, Marriott has engineered a perfect marriage of natural
beauty and upscale resort amenities that makes the whole crew fell
right at home. In that regard, it's a fine alternative to the
better-known coastal resorts of Hilton Hea, Seaside and Destin _
which are only mirginally closer to Atlanta. (Tate, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 8.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SAWGRASS-TIPS _ PONTE VERDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Even the
toughest choices we had to make all weekend at the Sawgrass
Marriott Resort _ beach or pool, tennis or golf, daiquiri or pina
colada _ were blissfully easy to resolve. That allowed us to focus
on more important things, like becoming that most elusive of family
creatures: Happy vacationers. We tip readers on what they need to
know to enjoy an escape of their own. (Tate, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 8.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AUSTRALIA _ ELBOW VALLEY, Australia _ It's a good thing
we're not serious golfers, because the kangaoos think they own the
links at Cherrabah Homestead Resort in Queensland. Kangaroos by the
hundreds live wild at the Australian outback resort, and some will
even hop up to you and eat out of your hand. A visit to this dude
ranch that's similar to ones in the American West-- except for
those jumpy golfers. (Holzer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 8.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ Officials in Mobile, Ala., are hoping that the nearly
600,000 people toured ``Nicholas &AMP; Alexandra: The Last Imperial
Family of Tsarist Russia'' in the six months it was on display in
Wilmington, Del., will pass through its Civic Center by Nov. 14
when the elaborate presentation closes. The show is is not merely a
display of possessions and architectural recreations. It is a
fascinating story of Russia's last royal family told in their own
words against a background of turbulent history that changed the
modern world forever. (Saunders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The Atlanta Journal-Constitution Style page will not be
available this week.
</P>
<P>
