<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6621 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-LANDMINES-$ADV08     08-05 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-LANDMINES-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'VILLAGE DE-MINERS' LOSING DESPERATE BATTLE AGAINST THE ODDS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Erbil is a large city in
northeastern Iraq.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 8 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ERBIL, Iraq _ Rather than forfeit the land of his ancestral to
land mines, Hassan Hussein Darwish decided to fight the odds and
remove them.
</P>
<P>
   The odds caught up to him. Now, a 29-year-old missing his hands
and eyes, Darwish tells the story of those who landmine experts
call ``village de-miners.''
</P>
<P>
   They risk their lives for land their families need to make a
living.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come to the mines. The mines came to us,'' says
Darwish, an Iraqi Kurd. ``Of course, you are face-to-face with
death at any moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Northern Iraq, a semi-independent region also called Iraqi
Kurdistan, is one of the most heavily mined regions in the world.
</P>
<P>
   United Nations officials estimate that more than 20 percent of
the land, in fertile valleys and steep mountainsides, is laden with
up to 10 million landmines. It may take 35 to 70 years to clear
them all.
</P>
<P>
   The mines were laid in complex layers. The Iraqi and Iranian
armies planted the most, during their eight-year war in the 1980s.
Turkish forces have also laid some mines, as have the three main
Kurdish forces, often warring against each other.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas, multiple forces laid mines on the same land,
making it especially difficult to find accurate maps of the
explosives beneath the ground.
</P>
<P>
   More than 7,000 people have been injured, including about 2,400
killed.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations de-mining program in Iraqi Kurdistan, which
began in 1997, has more than 900 staff to remove mines and train
locals to remove them. They do it the right way -- with body armor,
mine-sniffing dogs, metal detectors and, above all, with great
care.
</P>
<P>
   That's not how Darwish did the job.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a year and a half after his injury, he has moved from his
mountain village to a squalid block house on the shanty-town edges
of urban Erbil where he tells his story.
</P>
<P>
   He is a man who writes poetry -- he calls himself a ``friend of
the pen'' though he now dictates his poems. He confidently slices
the air with the two pointed stumps of his forearms to make his
point.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting cross-legged on a metal frame bed, he describes life in
the village of Balula, near the Iranian border.
</P>
<P>
   His family planted rice, and other vegetables and fruit on the
land. They lived in mud brick houses without electricity. Due to
wars and uprisings, they spent years as refugees before returning
to the village in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of residents have since been killed by the mines, which
they think were laid by the Iraqi army in order to deter an Iranian
invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Darwish starting clearing mines in 1992, picking up the skill
with other villagers from a neighbor who had trained with a
mine-clearing agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were imitating each other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Darwish worked full-time at the job and said every family in the
village of 120 homes had a son clearing mines.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, Darwish had mine maps to help him. Otherwise, he
just used metal prods to probe the ground. Sometimes, he burned the
brush to make mines easier to spot.
</P>
<P>
   He says he removed more than 2,000 mines over five years,
gingerly lifting them from the ground and disarming them. He
cleared about 20 on the morning he came across a small mine he did
not recognize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had it in my hands and was inspecting it, then it
exploded,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, professional mine removers leave the mines in the
ground and explode them there, rather than risk moving them. It's
one technique they use to make the job safe.
</P>
<P>
   David Edwards, project coordinator for the U.N. mine program in
Iraqi Kurdistan, said no U.N. de-miners in Iraq have been hurt
clearing mines yet. He shakes his head at the village de-miners
like Darwish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire what they do,'' Edwards said. ``It's just bloody
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
