<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6634 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-05 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR HOUSES, OURSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've never said these words in this particular order:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do that because I've got to clean the house.''
</P>
<P>
   I've always been proud of that achievement. Since my goal has
been to participate in life at the highest level, I've jumped
aboard the merry-go-round and ridden every horse until I was dizzy.
I have chosen ``yes'' rather than ``no'' at every opportunity and
never let mundane responsibilities stand in my way.
</P>
<P>
   I think that may have been a big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   My days have come to resemble a video on MTV; I cut from one
scene to another with no breathing space in between. The result is
that I often arrive exhausted at the end of the day, thinking, Oh,
my God, I didn't get a chance to clear off my desk, straighten out
our bedroom, sort through my piles of paper, or clean off the
counters.
</P>
<P>
   Again!
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, every morning, I wake up with the resolve to get
organized. Every evening I'm puzzled anew by my failure to do so. I
may have planned on using my every free moment to get this house in
some semblance of order, but for another day _ like so many others
_ I somehow didn't manage to find one free moment for housekeeping.
This can go on for weeks. All right, for months. It's got to stop.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the house looks bad. I have a cleaning lady who
keeps the public spaces neat enough so that anyone who drops by has
a place to sit down. It's more that disorganization frazzles my
mind. I'm always looking for things I can't find, starting a new
task on the ruins of an old one, harboring the uneasy feeling that
things are slipping out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The muddles in this house are mirrored in my psychic unease.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor suggests that tension in my neck and shoulders plays
a part in causing my headaches. Some of that tension, I know,
springs from my feeling that there's so much unfinished business at
home that I can never truly relax here. All the hot spots in this
house sink into my brain like little fishhooks as I rush past them
on the way to somewhere else. They tug at my consciousness, they
disturb my rest, they distract me whenever I take time to watch a
video or read a book. They jiggle in my head while I'm trying to
fall asleep, fraying my nerves.
</P>
<P>
   I know if I only had one day, one afternoon, even one hour to
create a more restful environment, I'd feel a lot more peaceful.
I've been waiting for that time to show up on its own for months,
to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   It makes me wonder how I ever managed to write my latest book,
``Family Puzzles.'' I recall a similar struggle to find time to
work on it, until I put it on my calendar. I didn't go out for
lunch, or baby-sit my grandkids, or answer my e-mail on those days
``work on book'' was down in black and white, carrying just as much
weight as any of my other commitments. Perhaps I can solve this
dilemma by taking a pen and writing ``clean house'' here and there
in my schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Oh-oh, it's not that simple. How can I do that when I vowed that
when I got married I'd never become a ``housewife''? When my mother
cleaned up because company was coming, I promised myself I'd never
worry about what other people thought, or be that desperate for
approval. Add to that the Sisyphus factor, the feeling that it's
senseless to commit oneself to a task that can never be completed.
One part of me is convinced that the way to deal with a job that
never ends is to never begin.
</P>
<P>
   I've replaced clearing the decks with wringing my hands.
</P>
<P>
   My house, it seems, has become an extension of myself. As such,
it is worthy of more careful tending. It helps to think of it this
way: My failure to act is cluttering my inner world with a
traumatic accumulation of stuff from my past, preventing me from
being present in the moment. In the end, running away from the
problem isn't an escape; it only makes the problem chronic rather
than acute.
</P>
<P>
   If I commit time to the task of organizing, simplifying, and
paring down, I can change the flow of energy in this house and in
my body. With the help of Jeff Campbell's wonderful book ``Clutter
Control: Putting Your Home on a Diet,'' I know I can soothe myself
by reducing the complexity of everyday living. What better gift
could I give myself?
</P>
<P>
   Here goes. I'm writing down ``C-l-e-a-n h-o-u-s-e.''
</P>
<P>
   Intention and result.
</P>
<P>
   I hope.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's website is at www.shore.net(tilde)weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
