<HEADER>
A6644 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDDLEMAN-COLLEGES-2T     08-05 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDDLEMAN-COLLEGES-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT LOANS ENRICHED MIDDLEMAN AT FOUR COLLEGES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALICE DEMBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- To four small private colleges in Greater Boston, it
was an enticing prospect: Boost enrollment by helping recent
Russian immigrants learn English and keep costs low by contracting
with a local entrepreneur to provide classrooms, deliver students
by the hundreds, and help secure federal and state scholarships to
pay their fees.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last eight years, Fisher, Newbury, Aquinas, and Curry
colleges have established special programs that enrolled nearly
3,000 students. The government paid millions of dollars in
financial aid to the colleges, which funneled a substantial portion
to the middleman, a nonprofit agency called Nefesh.
</P>
<P>
   Now, federal and state authorities, including the FBI, are
investigating Nefesh and the programs amid allegations that many of
the students had too much prior education to be eligible for
scholarships, that some students or program officials falsified aid
applications, that the programs may not have been eligible for aid,
and that Nefesh received head-hunting bonuses in violation of
federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Nefesh, the go-between, appears to have collected fees of at
least $2.5 million from just two of the colleges, Newbury and
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, based in the Back Bay, has already agreed to repay the
US Department of Education $2.6 million in Pell grants,
scholarships earmarked for needy students, most of which went to
Russian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Newbury, located in Brookline, has voluntarily returned about
$500,000 in state scholarships, and records show that another $2
million in federal money may be at issue there.
</P>
<P>
   An additional $4 million in state grants to Newbury and Fisher
are being reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher acknowledged in a written statement that ``honest errors
may have been made,'' but said the college ``at all times made a
good-faith effort to comply with the letter and the spirit'' of
student aid rules. Officials at Newbury declined comment because of
the pending investigation.
</P>
<P>
   At Aquinas and Curry colleges, officials said they had strictly
adhered to financial aid rules, denying aid to students if there
was any question, despite Nefesh's assurance that nearly all the
students would be eligible. To date, there have been no allegations
of financial aid problems at Curry or Aquinas.
</P>
<P>
   Nefesh officials denied any wrongdoing and said the colleges are
responsible for any problems.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Nefesh, the creation of two rabbis and an
urban planner, prospered until the government moved in.
</P>
<P>
   As Nefesh, a Hebrew word for soul, developed contracts with
colleges, its budget soared from $194,000 to $1.2 million over four
years; so, too, did the salary of its founding executive director,
James Lebowitz. According to records filed with the state, his
salary jumped from $1,890 to $148,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher and Newbury officials declined to discuss the program.
But records show Newbury paid Nefesh nearly $1.5 million in an
18-month period in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Nefesh received payments from Fisher of as much as $490 per
student each semester, as well as a bonus of $80 per student when
enrollment topped 400, according to a federal review. The report
suggests that Fisher paid Nefesh more than $1 million in all, most
of it drawn from state and federal scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got revenue, but we provided a lot of services,'' said
Lebowitz. ``No one was trying to grab a quick buck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't people getting together to try to engage in any
criminal or fraudulent behavior,'' he said. ``The arrangements were
all fashioned by the . . . colleges and the colleges' lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   But the first approach to the colleges was made in 1991 by
Nefesh's other two founding directors, Rabbi Chaim Zalman Gurkow
and his brother-in-law, Rabbi Avraham Asher Bronstein, two years
before Nefesh was incorporated and Lebowitz took charge.
</P>
<P>
   At Curry College in Milton, academic dean David Fedo said the
rabbis and two New York educators approached the school in 1991
about ``making a buck by Americanizing Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   Fedo said they offered references from a similar program at
Molloy College in Rockville Centre, N.Y. ``They said we would be
doing community service and could make some money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Molloy College _ with the help of Jewish community
organizations, including one run by Bronstein's father, Rabbi Zvi
Bronshtein _ was enrolling hundreds of Russian immigrants and
collecting $16 million in federal and state scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview, Bronstein said, ``We thought maybe we
could start such a thing in Boston.'' But he added that his own
role was minimal, and he referred all other questions to Lebowitz
and Gurkow.
</P>
<P>
   Gurkow said that early on they hired a New York agency with
connections to Molloy to run the program here. He said that he
mainly provided outreach to immigrants and that he had no knowledge
of or involvement in the funding or operations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, investigators for New York state and the federal
government found that some students had been recruited to the
Molloy programs with posters advertising a stipend for studying
English. Students allegedly received up to $500 a term as a stipend
while Molloy and the agencies split the rest of the scholarship
money.
</P>
<P>
   In a settlement in 1996, Molloy agreed to repay $2.5 million,
while denying any wrongdoing. None of the organizations that
recruited students or hosted the courses were prosecuted. The
details of the Molloy scheme were reported by New York newspapers
beginning in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fall of 1991, Molloy was effusive about the program,
and Curry decided to set up a small English-language program, in
partnership with the rabbis and the New Yorkers. The college,
however, ended the venture in June 1992 over financial concerns.
Only half the 50 students produced academic records the college
needed to determine if they were eligible for financial aid, Fedo
said, and the college was losing money.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Nefesh's leaders reached out to other colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk University rebuffed the group. ``We felt that there were
some questions as to giving these people Pell grants,'' said
Suffolk vice president Marguerite Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   The Pell grant program is reserved for poor students who do not
have bachelor's degrees. To be eligible, students taking English as
a Second Language, or ESL, classes must be enrolled in a
degree-granting academic program or in a one-year ESL program that
helps them use existing skills to get jobs. Many of the Russians
that Nefesh recruited, part of a wave of immigrants to Boston, were
highly educated, and many were elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Retreating from Suffolk, Nefesh approached Aquinas, a two-year
Catholic women's college in Newton, again citing the agency's
experience with Molloy, another Catholic institution, according to
Sister Marian Batho, who was then president of Aquinas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6646 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDDLEMAN-COLLEGES-2N     08-05 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDDLEMAN-COLLEGES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... of Aquinas.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aquinas enrolled about 220 Nefesh students in 1993-94 and paid
Nefesh between $100,000 and $200,000 before deciding the program
``wasn't a good match,'' Sister Batho said.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Batho, who was interviewed by the FBI in January, says
the college rejected about half of student requests for aid,
despite Nefesh's urging ``to push the envelope.''
</P>
<P>
   For Nefesh, the rejection by Aquinas had an up side. It pushed
them into a much more lucrative alliance with Fisher College, a
two-year college on Beacon Street in Boston. Fisher eventually
enrolled about 1,500 Nefesh-recruited students before ending the
program abruptly in fall 1996, as federal officials began raising
questions.
</P>
<P>
   At Fisher, as at most of the other colleges, Nefesh supplied the
students and the off-site classrooms and support services, while
Fisher hired faculty. Nefesh's revenues and payroll ballooned.
</P>
<P>
   But the program ran afoul of federal laws and regulations,
according to a review by the US Education Department.
</P>
<P>
   The federal report says Fisher accepted all Nefesh students, but
only charged tuition if they received financial aid. Nefesh's pay
from Fisher was contingent on the amount of financial aid a student
received, the report asserted. For example, if a student got a Pell
award of $1,170 per semester, Fisher got $680 and Nefesh got $490.
If a student got less, Nefesh got less.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, students also appear to have received as much as
$880 a semester for living expenses, while in others they got no
stipend beyond tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Federal reviewers determined that at least $3 million in federal
funds was misspent. After inquiries by the Globe, the state
commissioned a separate audit, still under way, of a $2.5 million
increase in state grants to Fisher during this period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The college's financial arrangement with Nefesh was
specifically prohibited'' because it was tied to financial aid,
according to the federal report.
</P>
<P>
   In written responses to the government, Fisher College has
asserted that its students and programs qualified for aid and that
the payments to Nefesh were reimbursements for Nefesh's costs.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher officials declined to respond to questions from the
Globe, but said they were cooperating fully with authorities. On
July 14, they agreed to repay $2.6 million to the federal
government, while denying any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Newbury College also refused to discuss its involvement, but
released a statement saying that Newbury ran a program for Russian
immigrants, in conjunction with Nefesh, from January 1996 through
December 1997, but halted the program before learning of the
federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Nefesh's Lebowitz said Newbury approached his organization to
set up the program and eventually enrolled about 1,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   Records show that Newbury College collected $2 million more in
federal scholarship money than in previous years. State records
indicate a $1.6 million jump in Newbury's state scholarship funds,
of which the school has already refunded $512,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lebowitz said Nefesh's second contract with Newbury specifically
absolved Nefesh of any responsibility for financial aid. Lebowitz
also said the government's rules did not apply to Nefesh because it
isn't an educational institution.
</P>
<P>
   However, the FBI has been focusing on Nefesh, and Lebowitz said
the agency last fall subpoenaed Nefesh's files. But, he added,
``I'm 100 percent sure that . . . we're going to be 100 percent
vindicated. No one pocketed that money.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Gurkow wasn't so sure. ``When Nefesh was running . . .
pockets were filling up,'' he said. ``Jamie was drawing quite a
salary.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurkow, who said Lebowitz shut him out of the organization's
decision-making, added that he wasn't aware that Lebowitz's salary
had jumped to nearly $150,000 until the FBI informed him recently.
``I was quite taken aback,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gurkow said he received ``close to $20,000 a year'' to counsel
students until he resigned from the organization in 1996. His name,
however, has continued to appear on official documents. ``If I had
known or had any suspicion of something wrong, I would have pulled
out immediately,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lebowitz defended his salary as payment, approved by Gurkow and
Bronstein, for 60-hour work weeks. He also said Nefesh's intentions
were good and the program results were impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lebowitz acknowledged that he had no way to document
it, he said that ``these Russian immigrants have gotten more bang
for their buck from entitlement programs than most.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Plenty of students,'' he said, ``went to the program and got
jobs based on their knowledge or pursued education at other
institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Stephen Kurkjian of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
