<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6648 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      08-05 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALLER PATIO MEANS LESS MAINTENANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I would like to make a little patio, about 4 by 6 feet, near
my back door. There is simply no more space than 4 by 6 feet. A
basement window is nearby, with a pressure-treated frame on a
concrete sill, within inches of the ground. Do I need to put in a
window well? Rainwater drips from the roof onto the patio 18 to 20
inches from the house.
</P>
<P>
   SHERRIE WEINSTEIN, Needham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The patio will provide a real tete-a-tete situation for you;
two chairs and a tiny table, with room for a couple of espressos
(espressi?). But that is cool, and even cooler is that you do not
need a window well. You might get a bit of splashing on the window
during rain or from the drip line, but it will be minor. Besides, a
window well will take away some of that vast patio area. Lay down a
bed of brick or any other kind of paver in sand, squeeze in the
furniture and call up a friend for that espresso and tete-a-tete.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about the size of the patio is that there is
almost no maintenance. You wil be the envy of your neighbors and
friends with their 24-by-48-foot decks and patios.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. One of the glass panes in my French door broke. How can I
take out the old glass and put in the new?
</P>
<P>
   DAVID CHIN, Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It should not be a problem. Most French doors with divided
lights (several individual panes of glass in the door) are glazed
with a wood bead, a flat, plain strip of wood that is inserted
against the glass on one side of door. Simply pry off this wood
bead (there are four, one on each side of the opening), wear heavy
gloves to remove and dispose of the broken glass, clean out the
edges of any dirt or glazing compound, and set in new glass. Before
putting in the glass, line the opening with a thin bead of glazing
compound; this is called bedding putty, and acts as a seal for the
glass as well as a cushion to guard against jarring.
</P>
<P>
   With new glass inserted, nail on the old wood beads. With luck,
you may only have to touch up paint or stain/varnish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have two sets of pocket doors in the 100-year-old house I
just bought. They have been painted, and I would like to strip and
refinish them, but I would like to do that work outdoors. How can I
remove them?
</P>
<P>
   JIM FRECHETTE, Braintree, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You should be able to lift them off their tracks. Pull one
out of its pocket so it is completely exposed. You will probably
have to remove some of the trim along the top of the opening, where
the top jamb normally would be, to allow lifting and moving the
door sideways in order for the wheels to clear the track when you
lower it. Do this with a helper; those doors are heavy.
</P>
<P>
   They are also valuable. How valuable is a good question, but
back in 1946, when there was a fire in my parents' house in
Michigan, and one set of oak pocket doors was burned, my mother got
$100 from the insurance company, just for the doors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our new central air conditioning is not cooling quite enough.
I was told to add insulation to the attic floor. There is now one
inch there with old, broken paper. My husband wants to take it out
and start all over again _ put in a separate vapor barrier between
the joists, then add suitable insulation. Would that help keep the
house cooler than it is now? It was also suggested to put more
vents in the attic; there is one vent at each end of the attic now.
</P>
<P>
   CLAUDETTE COTCHIAN, Peabody, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Your husband has good instincts and is proposing to do the
right thing, and what he proposes will indeed, make the house
cooler. That old broken paper, full of holes, tears, and cuts, is
no longer a vapor barrier. A vapor barrier is best set directly on
the ceiling below. Then add 12 inches of unbacked fiberglass. If
possible, bring the insulation to the tops of the joists, then add
another 6 inches cross-wise to the joists. The vapor barrier in
conjunction with the insulation will do much better than insulation
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Adding vents to the attic, such as a ridge vent and soffit (the
underpart of the roof overhang) vents, will keep the attic cooler,
further reducing the burden on the a/c.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a full-sized swinging door between my kitchen and
dining room. It swings in both directions, and I can lock it in an
open position. The door swings on pivot hinges, one at the top jamb
and one on the floor. The top bracket is loose and I can't get to
the screws that hold it on. How can I get to the screws? The door
does not easily lift off those pivot hinges.
</P>
<P>
   BOB CLARK, Duxbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The ony way you can get to the bracket is to take the door
off, and the ony way to take the door off is to lift it. It may be
hard to lift because the opening for the bottom pivot rod is gunked
up with dirt and oil. Spray a little WD-40 in that section, and
also pry the door up rather than lift it. Put a pry bar under the
door and pry carefully and slowly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
