<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
  
 FOR-PROFIT HOSPITALS TIED TO HIGHER HEALTH COSTS
 &HT;    STATISTICS COME UP SHORT ON CHILD-ABUSE DEATHS
 &HT;    HIGH DOSES OF VITAMIN E SHOW HOPE FOR DIABETICS
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX.  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   &UR; For-profit hospitals tied to higher health costs
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When for-profit hospitals dominate a region, total health costs
are higher, researchers at Dartmouth College and the White River
(Vt.) Junction Veteran Affairs Medical Center are reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at total Medicare expenditures around the nation over a
six-year period, the researchers found a clear pattern of higher
total costs in regions with only for-profit hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Total Medicare spending in 1995, for instance, averaged $5,172
per capita in the 208 areas where all hospitals were for-profit. In
the 2,860 regions with only nonprofit institutions, total per
capita spending was $4,440. Mixed areas fell in between. Total
Medicare costs also grew fastest in areas with only for-profit
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   An American Hospital Association official criticized the study
for failing to account for some factors known to drive Medicare
spending, such as regional differences in doctors' practice styles.
But the researchers said they took into account differences in age,
race, geography, HMO enrollment, number of physicians, and other
factors besides for-profit ownership that might have affected
costs. There is no evidence, they said, that for-profit hospitals
provide better care.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all Medicare enrollees had lived in areas served by
not-for-profit hospitals, we estimate that Medicare would have
saved over $5 billion in 1995 alone,'' said Dr. Elaine Silverman,
an author of the study, which appears in the current New England
Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Why might areas with for-profit hospitals have higher spending
for all care, not just hospitalization? ``For outpatient hospital
services and home health care, there are clear financial incentives
to increase utilization, since both types of care have been
reimbursed on a fee-for-service basis with few restrictions,'' the
authors wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Most for-profit hospitals currently are concentrated in
California and the southeastern states. But Dr. Steffie
Wooldhandler of Cambridge Hospital said for-profit chains may make
inroads into New England. ``It's definitely on the radar screen for
us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Statistics come up short on child-abuse deaths
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Official statistics on child-abuse deaths vastly understate the
problem, according to a North Carolina study.
</P>
<P>
   By combing 10 years of records, the North Carolina researchers
discovered that official statistics missed 152 deaths due to child
abuse and correctly identified only 68 _ an underreporting of
almost 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Child abuse accounted for 85 percent of all child homicides in
the state between 1985 and 1994, a period when the rate of
child-abuse fatalities increased 12.3 percent a year. In North
Carolina, homicide among children under 11 years is not attributed
to child abuse unless there is a pattern of battering or other
injury preceding the death.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published Wednesday in the Journal of the American
Medical Association, found that black children were killed at three
times the rate of whites, most of the probable batterers were men,
and biological parents were to blame for 63 percent of the
child-abuse deaths.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; High doses of vitamin E show hope for diabetics
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vitamin E supplements reduced damage to eyes and kidneys caused
by Type I diabetes in a Joslin Clinic study that appears in the
journal Diabetes Care.
</P>
<P>
   After four months on high daily doses of vitamin E _ 1,800
units, or 60 times the recommended daily allowance _ 36 diabetic
patients had significantly increased blood flow to the retina, the
delicate tissue at the back of the eye that registers images.
Kidney function also improved.
</P>
<P>
   The study, led by Dr. George L. King and Sven-Erik Bursell, is
the first to demonstrate that vitamin E can normalize blood flow in
the eyes and kidneys of diabetic patients, said Sushil K. Jain in
an accompanying commentary.
</P>
<P>
   The results could have major implications for millions of
diabetics, but Jain said it would be premature to recommend
high-dose vitamin E. Larger and longer trials are needed, involving
both Type I and adult-onset Type II diabetes patients, to see if
vitamin supplements can prevent blindness and kidney failure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
