<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Friday,
August 6. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE _ It has not been an especially good few weeks for
Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan's fledgling bid for U.S. Senate. Reports
out this week show his campaign fund is about $765,000 smaller than
that of his opponent, incumbent Sen. John Ashcroft. And three weeks
ago, the governor was two months late filing his personal financial
disclosure form with the Senate, which may result in a $200
penalty. 15. Kevin Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   BROUSE: The file on William Brouse case, which police were
indicating might be closed with his death, might have a bizarre
footnote to it. Brouse might have been hiding in Plano with help
from Cheryl Stein, wife of the Leawood sports memorabilia shop
owner who was killed last August in his Grandview home. Brouse may
have been a suspect in that case. Trying to sort the validity of
that, and see if we have a suspect from an unrelated slaying now in
play. Oscar Avila, Kim Kozlowski, other staff. 20. File mug.
</P>
<P>
   ARMA. World War II was very personal for this tiny southeast
Kansas mining town, even though the fighting was in places many
residents knew little about. The veterans' memorial at the edge of
the city park displays a plaque with the names of 629 young men
from the Arma area who went off to war. For the Varsolona, Kmetz
and Kovacic families, the contribution was extraordinary. Each of
the families sent five sons to the Pacific or Europe. Miraculously,
all 15 men returned safely. Twenty-six young men from Arma weren't
so lucky, and they are being remembered this weekend, Aug. 6-8,
during what Arma residents believe is the nation's oldest annual
celebration of V-J Day (even though V-J Day isn't really until next
weekend). It's a tradition that began in 1946. John Petterson. 27.
Map. Photo.
</P>
