<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUREAUCRAT' NOT ALWAYS A FOUR-LETTER WORD 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIEDMONT, Calif. _ Think ``bureaucrat'' and the image that pops
up is that of a robotic motor vehicles minion wrapped tight with
red tape.
</P>
<P>
   Let me introduce you to the antithesis of the stereotypical
bureaucrat, Neil Thomsen, an archives technician at the National
Archives and Records Administration's regional office in San Bruno,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   July 30 was Thomsen's last day in the windowless ``lower bay''
of the federal facility. He retired, at age 56, after 12 years of
work that was, to many Chinese-Americans, heroic. In those dozen
years he helped preserve a significant part of Chinese-American and
Asian-American history.
</P>
<P>
   When Thomsen joined the agency in 1987, the lower bay storeroom
was piled high with cardboard boxes filled with all sorts of
records _ Bureau of Land Management, Navy, Coast Guard, Merchant
Marines, Army Corps of Engineers, National Park Service _ and the
Chinese immigration files from the so-called exclusion era (1882
through the 1940s), files once held by the Immigration and
Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   Records turned over to the Archives have been judged
historically significant and are to be kept for posterity.
</P>
<P>
   His boss told Thomsen and several other workers to start
sorting.
</P>
<P>
   ``From 8 in the morning to 2 in the afternoon, we moved boxes,''
Thomsen said, sitting at his government-issued metal desk the day
before his last. ``It was total chaos down here.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Thomsen and his colleagues began organizing the files.
</P>
<P>
   Thomsen tackled the Benicia Arsenal records, then the Chinese
immigration files. They had been made permanent after years of
campaigning by the late Paul Chow.
</P>
<P>
   Reading the files was an epiphany for Thomsen, a man who had
known nothing of the Chinese exclusion era despite his master's
degree in history with a specialty in modern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were life stories here. Anyone with feelings has to be
affected by what those stories told,'' he said. ``There was so much
anti-Chinese feelings. There was so much hypocrisy on the part of
government officials toward the Chinese. It was so obvious this was
wrong. Government officials were trying to trick Chinese
immigrants. It was so clear they (officials) felt superior
interviewing inferiors.''
</P>
<P>
   Many files contain detailed interrogations of immigrants by
federal immigration inspectors, whose job it was to enforce the
Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882. In his 12 years, Thomsen figures he
has read 150,000 of the 250,000 Chinese files in San Bruno. It
wasn't just laborious paperwork. Chinese-Americans began visiting
the archives, seeking a paper trail to the tangled, secretive, and
frequently fraudulent immigration history of their forbears.
Thomsen went to extraordinary lengths to find a family's file,
something an ordinary bureaucrat would not do.
</P>
<P>
   In his typically modest way, Thomsen said, ``I don't think what
I did was extraordinary. I feel I have had a little bit of a
similar experience as those Chinese immigrants. I've seen things in
my lifetime; I've been beaten down so many times that I have
developed an empathy for victims of the system.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``I admire dignity in human beings. I admire the
dignity of the people in those (Chinese) files. They conducted
themselves with dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   So when their family members went to the San Bruno archives with
barely a clue, Thomsen helped them connect with their murky past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very conscious to treat them properly,'' he said. It is
good to know that a bureaucrat earning $30,000 a year can be as
caring as Neil Thomsen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is wongink(at)earthlink.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
