<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6659 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-     08-05 1467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WITCH' CRAFT BREWS ON THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mayor of Burkittsville, Md., is having trouble sleeping
these days _ and she hasn't even seen ``The Blair Witch Project,''
the horror film allegedly set in her quiet, one-street town,
population 200. Strangers are converging on the cemetery; the town
sign disappeared; and county police have increased security. It's
all Mayor Joyce Brown can do to keep up with the constant queries:
Is it true? Is the movie true?
</P>
<P>
   For the record, it's not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with it day by day,'' says Brown. ``This is a
Christian community, and we're praying that it all goes away.''
</P>
<P>
   That's hardly likely. The hype surrounding ``Blair Witch,'' a
film made for $30,000 with a couple of hand-held cameras, has been
building on the Internet for more than a year, long before Mayor
Brown became a celebrity and long before the film shattered box
office records when it opened on 27 screens two weeks ago. The mock
documentary about three film students who disappear in the woods
outside Burkittsville doesn't have any stars, special effects, sex,
or stupid bathroom tricks. But the story itself does have all the
elements that create a sensation on line: a carefully crafted
mythology, a conspiracy theory, and an interactive Web site. There
are more than 30 fan sites, and the official Web site receives 2
million hits a day, with a total of 40 million hits to date.
</P>
<P>
   And now that the film has opened on 1,000 screens nationwide,
the story behind the phenomenon has become the stuff of legend in
its own right, generating its own mythology and its own set of
nagging questions. The film is a landmark in movie marketing, the
first sensation created almost exclusively on line. But how much of
the word of mouth was spread by genuine fans and how much was
fabricated by pals of the filmmakers? And what are the long-term
implications for the movie-industry marketing machinery?
</P>
<P>
   ``People are scrutinizing our movie not on the merits of the
film, but on whether we are moral dudes or not,'' says Dan Myrick,
the Florida filmmaker who codirected ``Blair Witch'' with partner
Eduardo Sanchez. ``It's not like we said, `Hey man, put up a fan
site, and we'll put you on the payroll; you'll be fan number 532.'
We had no money. We encourage the fans, and we love it when it
happens, but even now, we know the hype is out of control. It's
scary.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's no doubt that it's becoming a common practice in
Hollywood for studio flacks to ``leak'' gushing advance reviews to
amateur on-line film forums or to create fake fan sites. ``Plants
are all over the Internet,'' says one studio executive. ``Paramount
did it for `Titanic.' I can't tell you how many times I went into a
chat room and saw `Oh my God, I love Leo DiCaprio,' and it smacked
of a publicist.''
</P>
<P>
   But to this day, the ``Blair Witch'' creators and their
distributors at Artisan swear they didn't fabricate the hype. Yes,
they walked the fine line between fiction and reality, but that's
the whole point of the film, which is designed to be so realistic
it makes the muscles on the back of your neck constrict. And while
the Artisan marketing campaign (which cost under $2 million
initially for print, Internet, and on-campus efforts, and didn't
include television or radio advertising until this week) is
ingenious and offbeat, the filmmakers themselves didn't even know
the basics of marketing when they set out to film the scariest
campfire story of all time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But ever since its early days, the film has created a furious
debate, with some folks questioning the integrity of the makers and
suggesting that their production company, Haxan Films, ought to be
called ``hacks-in-films.'' It all began in the summer of 1997, when
preliminary footage aired on Split Screen, a show produced by John
Pierson on the Independent Film Channel. A second tape was aired in
April 1998, and Pierson played along with the game, telling viewers
he wasn't sure whether the story was fact or fiction.
</P>
<P>
   The Split Screen bulletin board (www.grainypictures.com) was
flooded with queries, some accusing Pierson of being unethical.
``There were so many obvious clues that it was fiction, and maybe
we were just encouraging people to indulge their most paranoid,
wanna-believe inclinations,'' Pierson says.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, the filmmakers set up their own Web site,
www.haxan.com. In the first few days, friends of the filmmakers
traded barbs: Sanchez's sister wrote, ``My brother is scary!!!''
But then outsiders found their way to the site. One of them was
Jeff Johnson, an aquatics merchandiser in Northern California. He
says he scoured the Net for information about the Blair witch
legend, checking out crime sites and government records.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most startling thing I had ever seen, and I wanted
more information,'' says Johnson. He became a regular site visitor,
particularly when the filmmakers posted segments from the alleged
diary of one of the ``missing'' students. Johnson didn't care when
the filmmakers finally fessed up and admitted the story wasn't
true. ``I thought the concept was brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were less than thrilled, especially when phony messages
from the nonexistent Blair County Historical Society started
appearing on the site. (Myrick says he doesn't know who posted
those messages, even though some fans suspect Haxan staffers.) The
loyal fans conducted flame wars with the furious skeptics, and
Johnson became such a champion he might as well have been on the
Haxan payroll, even if they didn't have any money at the time. Last
October, he initiated a discussion of the film on the ``Mark and
Brian Show,'' a syndicated radio show in Los Angeles that is
listened to by industry insiders.
</P>
<P>
   After that, there was no stopping the on-line buzz.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the story plays like a film industry fairy tale: The
unknown filmmakers got accepted to the prestigious Sundance Film
Festival, where ``Blair Witch'' was purchased by Artisan for $1
million. Artisan launched a nontraditional marketing campaign,
sending teams of paid interns to college campuses to generate buzz.
``We wanted to create a cult event,'' says Paul Campbell, Artisan's
director of field operations.
</P>
<P>
   Artisan also targeted the youth market on the Internet. The
official Web site, www.blairwitch.com, doesn't offer a shred of
evidence that the film isn't true.
</P>
<P>
   And Artisan released the trailer to Ain't-It-Cool-News, the
controversial fan site that many in the industry say is rampant
with studio plants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many of the original fans aren't thrilled with Artisan's
``guerrilla marketing'' tactics; they criticize the distributor for
continuing the myth on its Web site without a disclaimer and for
refusing to let the actors be interviewed when the movie was first
released. ``It's not right to hamper the careers of your stars,''
says fan Eric Alan Ivins.
</P>
<P>
   Ivins himself was recently accused of being a shill for the film
in the on-line magazine Salon. He and his fiancee, Abbie Marceluk,
met on the Haxan bulletin board; they later appeared in the
television documentary ``The Curse of the Blair Witch,'' leaving
the impression that they were in cahoots with the directors. ``It
cracks me up that people think we're studio shills,'' says Ivins.
``Our Web site goes against Artisan's marketing and says the film
isn't true.''
</P>
<P>
   But the real-life controversy only adds to the film's mystique.
``Just dangle a conspiracy theory on the Net, and people will gnaw
on it like a dog on a bone,'' says Gordon Paddison, director of
on-line marketing for New Line Cinema. ``That plays well to an
on-line demographic.''
</P>
<P>
   What doesn't play well is deliberate on-line meddling by
studios. The line between promotion and genuine buzz is getting
blurrier and blurrier. But the ``Blair Witch'' case is unique: You
can't fake the kind of enthusiasm that gets people standing in line
to see a film that's going to scare them to death and, in some
cases, make them sick to their stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   And the directors now realize that hype can be a mixed blessing.
``Ed and I are nervous about too many people talking about it and
expecting too much,'' Myrick says. ``Just chill out. It's a small
movie. It's not going to change your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, you're the mayor of Burkittsville. ``We're
waiting to see what the impact really is after it goes out to more
theaters,'' says Brown. She, however, is one of the few people who
won't be checking out the Web site or lining up at the local cinema
this weekend. The mayor of Burkittsville, it turns out, doesn't
have Internet access, and she doesn't like horror films.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
