<HEADER>
A6667 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-05 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAS IMUS LOST HIS EDGE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don Imus is trying to make fun of Monday's Talk magazine party,
a gathering of Hollywood and New York swells to celebrate the
launch of Tina Brown's chronicle of contemporary culture.
</P>
<P>
   A bastion of the elitist establishment, Talk magazine is
everything talk radio is supposed to hate. But Imus _ who is
leaving his longtime Boston base at WEEI-AM -- can't feign much
distaste. Even as he groans, ``Geez . . . 30 years in New York, and
I've never been to one of those things,'' he chats up a Talk
reveler, White House aide turned kiss-and-tell pundit George
Stephanopoulos. Here, even the veneer of disdain for Tina's big
bash vanishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens when you get the invitation?'' Imus asks
Stephanopoulous earnestly. ``What's the process?''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Imus is the prototypical Talk partygoer. The
one-time wild-man-turned-syndicated-radio-talkmaster now hosts an
endless salon for political and media bigfeet from Arizona's
Senator John McCain to CNN's Jeff Greenfield. Whether appearing on
``Larry King Live'' or the cover of Newsweek, he is a mainstream
media darling. In the past year, he has shown up 162 times in the
Hotline political newsletter, a repository of Beltway bloviation
designed for an audience that is ``90 percent Washington power
elites,'' according to Hotline editor Craig Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   At 59, and syndicated on 92 stations, Imus may finally be a
victim of his own success. Not only is his insider shmoozefest at
odds with the mood of a country turning away from Washington, it is
out of touch with talk radio _ an angry, populist, anti-mainstream
medium. Add in his preoccupation with his young son, his brother's
business ventures and even his charitable efforts on behalf of sick
children, and some believe Imus has evolved from unpredictable
shockjock into a self-obsessed member of the media elite. (Calls to
the Imus program were not returned.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not outrageous. He's the establishment,'' says cultural
critic Steven Stark, who characterizes Imus's show as `` `This Week
with David Brinkley' with a different host. It's antithetical to
what he was originally about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just totally lost his edge, he's very passive on the
air,'' says Jason Wolfe, program director at WEEI, who points to
Imus's sagging ratings. (According to an industry source, later
this month Imus will move to Greater Boston Radio's smooth jazz
station WSJZ, not its WBOS-FM outlet.)
</P>
<P>
   Depending on whom you believe, Imus was either dumped from his
morning drive slot at WEEI or he jumped ship for a better deal.
``The person who said he lost his fastball is the person that lost
the negotiation,'' responds Joel Hollander, president and CEO of
Westwood One, which syndicates Imus's show. ``He has been doing the
same show for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollander is not alone in being bullish on the I-man. ``He is
bigger than he's ever been,'' insists Michael Harrison, publisher
of Talkers Magazine. ``Imus has always proven to be smart enough to
stay on the cutting edge.'' More common, however, is the reaction
from this radio executive when asked about Imus's ratings: ``I
guess what's really important is the quality of the audience and
Imus reaches far and away the most upscale audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Imus does bring a high-end listener to advertisers, but he does
not bring a lot of listeners to advertisers. At WEEI, his ratings
in the crucial 25-54-year-old male demographic put him in fifth
place among morning shows in the market. But he hosted the
station's lowest-ranked show and Howard Stern's WBCN-FM morning
program is clobbering him.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Imus's pull among men 25-54 puts him in the bottom
third of that market. Brian Wilson, the program director at Imus's
outlet in Kansas City says, ``from a sales standpoint, they've been
pretty content with it. From a ratings standpoint, we wish it was
doing better.'' At KHTK-AM in Sacramento, Imus is seventh among men
25-54. ``Compared to the rest of the day, he is our lowest-rated
day part,'' says program director Mike Remy.
</P>
<P>
   A recent story in The Washington Post, noting that Imus was tied
for 15th place among men 25-54 in that market, said those numbers
``suggest that his Washington audience consists essentially of the
people who appear on his show and the people they bump into on the
Hill or at Georgetown parties.''
</P>
<P>
   And at WISN-AM in Milwaukee, which dropped Imus last year,
program director Jerry Bott says, ``the true problem is this show
massively underperformed the rest of the radio station. The show
can be brilliant. Unfortunately, in my opinion, it is massively
undisciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   In radio-speak, ``undisicplined'' means the Imus show is too
much about Imus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks about what he wants to talk about,'' says Wolfe. ``He
talks about what makes him comfortable. He talks about his ranch
all the time and his family all the time.'' And though eminently
laudable, the New Mexico ranch that Imus is building for sick
children is a symbol of his growing willingness to foist his own
interests on the public _ whether it be his brother Fred selling
salsa or his favorite charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ranch was such a dominant topic in the program that I
began to get calls from faithful Imus listeners (saying) `just get
him to talk about anything else,' '' says Bott.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are two problems with his program,'' says
longtime WBZ-AM talkhost David Brudnoy in Boston. ``The endless
nonsense with Fred and the salsa crap (and) the interviews with a
very select cast of characters.''
</P>
<P>
   That select cast of characters has made Imus very popular with
Hotline editor Crawford. ``The guests he has on tend to be what we
call `Hotline' people,'' he says. But too much hobnobbing with
``Hotline people'' may make Imus a duller boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the basic difference,'' acknowledges Crawford. ``He's
not as dangerous as he once was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
