<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6670 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-AUSTRALIA08-CO     08-05 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AUSTRALIA08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wildlife, starry nights keep Down Under dudes hopping
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 8.
 &HT;    By Helen Holzer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELBOW VALLEY, Australia _ It's a good thing we're not serious
golfers, because the kangaroos think they own the links at
Cherrabah Homestead Resort in Queensland. Kangaroos by the hundreds
live at the Australian outback resort, and some will even hop up to
you and eat out of your hand.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the kangaroos and the brightly plumed wild parrots,
Cherrabah could be any dude ranch in the Western United States.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled in the great dividing ranges of central eastern
Australia, and about a three-hour drive from Brisbane, Cherrabah's
seclusion and mountain views provide a welcome respite.
</P>
<P>
   Its lodge sits at an elevation of 2,832 feet, and its 52 cabins
boast seasonal rates of $57 to $70 daily per person, quite a
savings off pricey American dude ranches.
</P>
<P>
   Horseback riding, tennis, golf and three hearty meals a day are
included in that price. Liquor and soft drinks are extra, however.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the 5,000-acre resort fans out into lushly forested
bush country and into higher elevations overlooking a broad valley.
</P>
<P>
   At night, the ranch, far from city lights, provides magnificent
stargazing. Within minutes, we saw a shooting star and caught our
first sight of the Southern Cross.
</P>
<P>
   A naturalist's dream, Cherrabah is home to two types of
eucalyptus. However, three types are necessary for a koala's diet,
so we didn't get to see any of them in their natural habitat. We
did see some wonderfully shady coolabah trees and fig trees, and
there's even supposed to be something called a ``bush lawyer
tree,'' but no one could point one out to us. We could only imagine
what a bush lawyer would look like.
</P>
<P>
   Animal life abounds with kangaroos and wallabies, rabbits and
tropical birds of all colors, and at least one red-bellied black
snake, known to be poisonous but shy _ and also a vigilant guard
over the gate we needed to pass on our trail rides.
</P>
<P>
   Cherrabah's stables cater to all ages and equestrian levels. A
snapshot in the horse barn pictures a spry 93-year-old who mounted
her first horse here in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   One of our horseback rides took us past Balancing Rock, two
heavy boulders perched precariously on a hill overlooking the
ranch. A photo in Cherrabah's lodge of the same boulders in the
1930s shows a couple standing next to a small tree growing between
the two rocks. Today that tree dwarfs the boulders and stands about
50 feet tall, while the rocks do not appear to have moved an inch.
</P>
<P>
   We also rode to the base of a black granite overlook, where we
had to ``park'' our horses and walk. Near the top, mounted into the
rock, is a bronze plaque dedicated to a climber who loved the view
so much he had his ashes strewn over the spot.
</P>
<P>
   For those not adventurous enough to ride one of the ranch's 40
horses, Cherrabah provides motorized tractor train rides around its
property.
</P>
<P>
   Cherrabah's lodge houses a stage and dance floor, two dining
rooms, a game room with ping-pong and billiards, a video room
loaded with movies and a mechanical bull. There are also a
children's program, dance lessons and entertainment. Outside are a
swimming pool, tennis courts, a petting zoo and a pond for
canoeing.
</P>
<P>
   A big difference between Cherrabah and many American dude
ranches is the made-to-order food.
</P>
<P>
   For lunch and dinner we had our choice of fish, beefsteak, pork,
veal or chicken, either grilled or prepared in French or Asian
style, plus salads, soups, vegetable specials and desserts.
</P>
<P>
   Hearty breakfasts consist of eggs, sausage, bacon, baked beans,
cereals, yogurt and toast with jelly or Vegemite toppings. For the
uninitiated, beware of Vegemite, Australia's answer to peanut
butter, because its strong flavor packs a punch.
</P>
<P>
   The wine list offers such local favorites as Seppelts Muroomba
Moselle and Wynnes Coonawarra Riesling, or you can try Australia's
own beers, Fosters, Tooheys and XXXX Gold.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 minutes from the ranch, near the town of Killarney, is
the most famous local attraction, Queen Mary Falls. After driving a
winding mountain road, visitors park and walk through a rain forest
overgrown with orchids and huge ferns. Suddenly you hear chattering
parrots and the gush of water ahead. A wide gorge unexpectedly
appears, and the falls tumble dramatically 130 feet between black
granite cliffs to lookout areas below.
</P>
<P>
   Another local attraction is the lodge's nightly entertainment,
provided by singer (and golf course maintenance expert) Russell
Vitnell, who says he once sang backup for Roy Orbison on an
Australian tour. Vitnell encouraged the audience to close its eyes
and imagine Orbison's voice. Then he revved up his backup tape and
tore into an amazingly accurate rendition of ``Pretty Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Stable manager Sharon Lowthian said the ranch is so large that
she's ridden for hours at a time on horseback and never cleared its
5,000 acres. Cherrabah was a sheep ranch before becoming a guest
ranch in the 1970s, and Lowthian has heard of one old-time shepherd
who spent much of his life trying to find buried treasure hidden
somewhere at the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that in the late 1800s a bushman (highwayman)
named Thunderbolt stole a fortune in Ipswitch, near Brisbane, and
escaped as far as Cherrabah, where he buried the loot before he was
captured and hanged.
</P>
<P>
   As for how Cherrabah got its name, Lowthian suggested that
besides being a sheep ranch, Cherrabah was also once a cherry
orchard. If you combine cherry with a sheep's ``bah'' in an
Australian accent, you get Cherrabah.
</P>
<P>
   Merv Yeoland, Cherrabah's resident manager, laughed at that,
allowing that no one knows where the name originated.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he said with a twinkle in his eye, ``it's as good a
story as any, ain't it?''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: For departures through Aug. 31, United, Qantas
and Air New Zealand fly to Brisbane (via Los Angeles and Sydney)
for $1,378 round trip, with a 21-day advance purchase (seven-day
minimum stay required; visits one month maximum). The fare rises to
$1,648 for departures Sept. 1-Dec. 8. From Brisbane, drive or take
a bus ($32 round trip) three hours southwest to Warwick. Follow
signs to Cherrabah in Elbow Valley.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cherrabah information: Cherrabah Guest Ranch, Elbow Valley,
Via Warwick Mail Service 162, Warwick, Queensland 4370.
61-7-4667-9177.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.qttc.com.au
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
