<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6672 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-JAPAN08-COX     08-05 2004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-JAPAN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How a festival, weo costumes and animated visits with a Japanese
family forged a new friendship
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 8.
 &HT;    By Betty Gordon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Every few seconds, wood met bone.
</P>
<P>
   Three thin layers of cotton were all that was separating my
shoulder _ and most of the shoulders of those tightly sandwiched
around me _ from a heavy wooden Japanese shrine that we were
carrying on the second day of the annual Sanja Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Not much padding, considering that the multi-
</P>
<P>
   tiered, multicolored, house-shaped shrine weighed hundreds of
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I was having a spectacularly good time trying to move
compatibly with the 30 or so similarly costumed porters of this
mikoshi as we paraded slowly around the Asakusa district, chanting
all the way.
</P>
<P>
   The light rain had stopped, and night had fallen. Spectators
lined the narrow steets, some chanting and following the shrine,
others watching from balconies.
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiastic parade, full of history and culture, seemed
like something out of a film, and it made me marvel even more that
I was here.
</P>
<P>
   Not in Tokyo _ I had planned that meticulously. This was my
third trip to Japan, where I've traveled since the late '70s to
satisfy my decades-long curiosity about a culture so different from
ours. In fact, I had selected mid-May for my trip to coincide with
the festival, intending to watch at least one day of the three-day
event. But participating in this procession? That was completely
unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 minutes earlier on an overcast Saturday afternoon, I
had met the Sakurai family, a meeting I'd ``applied'' for the day
before at the Japan National Tourist Organization. Any tourist can
participate in the Home Visit System, in which more than 1,000
English-speaking families in 14 cities around Japan open their
homes to foreigners. You just fill out a simple form at the JNTO
office and the office staff makes the arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour of my application, two visits (a single visit is
the norm) with the Sakurai family had been organized. My hope was
that meeting a family one-on-one would give me a better
understanding of their everyday lives.
</P>
<P>
   I had no idea it would turn into so much more.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I arrived at the family's multipurpose three-room
apartment with a galley kitchen (shoes off at the lower landing, of
course), a party was going on. That was pretty clear in any
language.
</P>
<P>
   I was introduced to a roomful of their Japanese and Western
friends and family, many dressed in traditional costume for the
festival. On the table were plates of food, including a large pot
of fish stew, a curry dish, vegetables and three types of rice. I
was encouraged to eat and immediately felt welcome, with other
guests bringing me into the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   It was getting close to 6 p.m., the appointed time for us to
watch the festival, in which up to 100 portable shrines are paraded
through the working-class neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   At least I thought we were going to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Mieko Sakurai, our hostess, said it was time for me to change my
clothes, indicating that I wasn't going to be standing on the
sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not serious,'' I said to her, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   But she was.
</P>
<P>
   Mieko and one of her guests helped me put on a blue-and-white
patterned blouse, on top of which went a denim work vest with front
pocket that I was tied into, on top of which went a matsuri-hanten,
a special short coat for festivals with a symbol or crest on the
back that indicates the community group. I pulled on form-fitting
three-quarter-length denim pants, which I was also tied into. After
the addition of a hachimaki (headband) and dark blue tabi (foot
coverings), I was pronounced ready.
</P>
<P>
   And that is how I came to find myself a part of the shrine team
in the festival that celebrates nature and includes prayers for a
good harvest.
</P>
<P>
   For two hours, we carried or followed ``our'' intricately gilded
shrine around the streets. I lasted less than a half-hour with the
shrine on my right shoulder. And I confess that I hadn't quite
gotten the bouncy, rhythmic movement down correctly. So I stepped
out of line and another porter quickly took my place. My shoulder
was sore for a week.
</P>
<P>
   When a new group of carriers stepped in en masse, a patterned
clap (three sets of three and a single clap) signaled the change.
The same pattern, called ippon-jime, was done when we passed a
permanent shrine and when the portable mikoshi arrived at its
resting place for the night. (The clap's purpose is to summon the
gods and focus one's mind.)
</P>
<P>
   When we finished, soft drinks, beer and a sealed pouch of cold
fish stew were given to each person in costume. The Sakurai
family's group reassembled in its house for another go at the food
still piled on the table (the sweets were brought out, too) and a
discussion of Sunday's events.
</P>
<P>
   The festival's final day is the most crowded and most important.
It draws almost a million people, all crammed together close to the
Asakusa Shrine. The three largest portable shrines are brought out
for this celebration, each requiring at least 60 men to carry them.
Because of the crowd density, it takes hours to advance the shrines
any distance. And people have been known to lose their lives in the
crush of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It was getting late, and knowing that some of my new friends
would be getting up at 3 a.m. to get to the Asakusa Shrine, I left
for the subway back to my hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, I was back at the Sakurais. The JNTO instructs
visitors to arrive at 7 p.m., expect a sweet and tea, and to leave
within two hours. But we had hit it off Saturday, and I had been
invited for dinner. Amid the festival excitement, there wasn't time
for in-depth talk, and the dinner invitation gave us a better
opportunity to get to know each other.
</P>
<P>
   Mieko, in her 50s, had been a dental assistant for 25 years. She
prepared chicken pieces in teriyaki sauce, tempura onions and
carrots and two types of tangy green vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Our conversation centered mostly on lifestyle. The family was
interested in hearing about Atlanta, my neighborhood and
particularly how much space I had. They wanted to know how
frequently I cleaned my house, especially how often I vacuumed. I
think these questions were prompted by their mental pictures of my
suburban home while we sat in their small living room, which is
also used as a dining room and a bedroom. They also asked where
other members of my family lived, about my other trips to Japan and
what sights I had seen on this visit.
</P>
<P>
   I had brought them postcards, including one of Bulloch Hall in
Roswell, (Ga.), and boxes of chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone With the Wind,'' Mieko said immediately when she saw
Bulloch Hall's columns.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese generally are guarded about their privacy, and not
wanting to make any faux pas, I kept my questions simple. I found
the Sakurais open, friendly and interested in Americans and other
Westerners.
</P>
<P>
   Hatsumi, an aerobics instructor and model in her 30s, spoke the
best English. She travels to Los Angeles at least once a year and
she and her mother have visited a pen-pal friend and his family in
Louisville, Ky. Mieko showed me an album of photos from this trip,
which included a jaunt to New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Eiji, the father who is in his 60s, is a distributor for a large
Japanese cosmetics company. He didn't say much the entire evening,
but I could tell he understood almost everything that was said. He
and Mieko were readying for a trip to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Daughter Ami, in her late 20s, is taking English lessons. She
used to work for a computer supply company but had quit so she
could travel to India. She was considering a trip to Seoul, South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Tsune, the grandmother, listened to everything but didn't utter
a word. Mieko explained that Tsune's knees were bothering her and
that's why we were not sitting on the floor to eat.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Mammie, their 2-year-old Yorkshire terrier, a
lovingly spoiled bundle of energy. Mammie and her Yorkie friend
Boku attended the festival with us _ in their own appropriate
costumes (Mammie has at least 30).
</P>
<P>
   After dinner, Mieko had another surprise for me: a tea ceremony.
She told Ami to take me upstairs, where Ami and her husband live,
and to dress me in a kimono.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has read ``Memoirs of a Geisha,'' the best seller by
Arthur Golden, knows that getting in a kimono is a complicated,
layered process. Ami rummaged through her drawers, pulling out the
necessary underclothing, acting almost as if I were an old friend
over to spend the night.
</P>
<P>
   And then at last, the gorgeous kimono. It had a white
background, and flowers and butterflies in several shades of
orange, red and blue. There are no buttons, zippers or snaps
involved, but a few clasps secure the undergarments. Mieko came up
to help Ami dress me, and about 20 minutes later I had been wrapped
into the kimono, complete with wide obi (sash) tied into a square
in the back.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, I felt no awkwardness as they fussed over me like a
lifesize doll. Though these were women I knew only slightly, I was
totally at ease, and I was fascinated at how expertly they brought
about my transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in this exquisite finery, it wasn't hard to see why
Japanese women in kimonos have beautiful posture: The tightness and
restrictiveness of the costume demands that one stand up straight
and move slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you wear your kimonos often?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only for New Year's and special occasions,'' Mieko said, a
special occasion being defined as a wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Back downstairs at the dinner table, Mieko began to heat the
water for the tea ceremony. She had donned an informal yukata, a
cotton robe that Japanese often wear around the house.
</P>
<P>
   And by this time, Mammie was also in a kimono, the same print as
the one I had on.
</P>
<P>
   Using a digital camera, Eiji took my picture with Mammie, and
minutes later I had a souvenir of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Mieko took out the small red lacquered jar in which she stores
her best powdered green tea. She poured the water into a small
bowl, swirled it around to heat it and poured the water out. She
then began to mix the tea and water with a whisklike implement
called a chasen.
</P>
<P>
   When the tea was frothy, she instructed me in tea etiquette.
First the hostess bows to the guest, a gesture the guest returns.
The guest then accepts the bowl with the right hand and places it
in the left. Then the bowl is turned clockwise twice to avoid
drinking from the area that has the most elaborate design. The tea,
slightly bitter, is then supposed to be finished in three long
swallows, and the bowl passed back to the hostess along with
another bow.
</P>
<P>
   The entire ceremony is performed with the utmost grace,
contemplation and serenity. Mieko said she does the ceremony every
Friday, but this was only Tuesday, and I felt particularly honored.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists can pay to attend tea ceremonies at some Tokyo hotels,
but I'll bet they don't wear kimonos or get such personal
attention. And there are three major schools of chanoyu (tea
ceremony), so tourists' experiences might be a bit different.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lot quicker getting out of the kimono, and back into my
clothes. Shortly before I left, the family presented me with a
homemade paper plaque in English that commemorated my visit to
their home. On the back, Tsune had rendered with colored pieces of
paper a scene of a boy with a net in a fenced field trying to catch
flying objects. I couldn't decide if they were birds or
dragonflies.
</P>
<P>
   Long before this, I suspected we had forged a friendship. I was
certain when Mieko invited me to stay with her family on my next
trip to Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know when that will be, but I can hardly wait to see
what costume the Sakurais will have ready for me.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Gordon writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
