<HEADER>
A6673 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SAWGRASS-TIPS0     08-05 1474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SAWGRASS-TIPS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kids out of sight, not out of mind at Sawgrass
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 8.
 &HT;    By Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ On a recent weekend visit, we knew
we'd made a good choice before we'd even checked in to the Sawgrass
Marriott Resort.
</P>
<P>
   On the way in, the concierge took one look at my son Josh, 5,
and his 8-year-old brother, Danny, and handed my wife, Jodi, a
``family fun pack'' offering discount coupons on everything from
dinner at the Marriott's in-house restaurants to admission to the
Adventure Landing family fun center in nearby Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it got better.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for our room to be readied, we headed to the cavernous
lobby atrium _ a leafy high-ceilinged jewel box, lush with palm
fronds and goldfish ponds, and fronted by two-story windows
overlooking the Marriott's grounds. While watching the Wimbledon
finals on a big-screen TV, Jodi and I sipped cocktails while our
sons guzzled freshly made tumblers of chocolate milk _ artfully
topped with real whipped cream and cherries.
</P>
<P>
   Refills came unbidden _ along with the first soothing twinges of
vacation-mode release.
</P>
<P>
   The days that followed were a running series of poolside games
with the boys, tennis matches on the Marriott's lighted clay courts
and wave-hopping at the resort's private beach. And even the
toughest choices we had to make all weekend _ beach or pool, tennis
or golf, daiquiri or pina colada _ were blissfully easy to resolve.
That allowed us to focus on more important things, like becoming
that most elusive of family creatures: happy vacationers.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you need to know to enjoy your own escape ...
</P>
<P>
   Essentials: Spaciousness is a given at the Sawgrass. The
resort's 324 guest rooms ($120 per night) are spotless and large
enough to accommodate a king-size bed (or two doubles) and two free
roll-away cots. The large open rooms also include a desk, coffee
maker, refrigerator and TV, offering children's films among the
pay-per-view movies. In addition, the Marriott has more than 100
one- and two-bedroom suites and villas (for an additional $25),
with separate sitting areas, bedrooms, kitchenettes and room to
sleep eight.
</P>
<P>
   Guests have five resort eateries to choose from _ ranging from
the casually romantic Ocean View Restaurant at the Marriott's
private beach to the casually elegant Augustine Grille. For
families, the midpriced Cafe on the Green is the most comfortable
place to grab a bite. Here, children's menus double as activity
booklets and offer inexpensive favorites like pancakes, pizza,
burgers and chicken fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Golf: With the PGA Tour headquarters located in Ponte Vedra,
golf may be the city's most popular pastime. The Marriott offers 99
holes, including two 18-hole courses that are part of The Players
Club (TPC) Stadium Course, for which the Sawgrass is the official
hotel. For a $110 greens fee (June to September), plus $25 cart
rental, guests can play the same par-72 course _ including the
famed island green on the 17th hole _ that has challenged Tiger
Woods, Fred Couples and Greg Norman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the few truly famous holes in golf that is open
to the public,'' said visitor Bill Richer of Alpharetta (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Marriott guests can play four other courses, with greens fees
ranging from $35 to $100, all within three miles of the resort.
Younger duffers also can be carted along to the Sawgrass driving
range.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis: Ponte Vedra is also home to the U.S. Association of
Tennis Professionals (ATP), rivaling Atlanta as a regional tennis
center and featuring a variety of public and private courts.
Marriott guests can play the resort's six lighted clay courts for a
daily charge of $12 per player. And parents don't need to book a
baby sitter; a fenced-in miniature golf course adjoins the courts,
allowing kids to work on their short game while parents take
lessons or volley for bragging rights. That $12 fee grants Marriott
guests access to the nearby ATP Tour international headquarters
(200 ATP Tour Blvd.), which features 11 grass, red-clay and hard
courts _ and frequently hosts pros like MaliVai Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Water sports: The resort itself boasts two large
waterfall-framed pools _ one designated for kids and families, the
other for adults. Poolside, the 100th Hole bar and grill offers
snacks and drinks; and dockside tables overlook the lagoons and
water traps most likely to harbor turtles, duck, small fish and the
occasional gator. Complimentary shuttles also run every 30 minutes
to the resort's Cabana Beach Club, less than a mile away and
straddling a pristine 2.5-mile stretch of private white-sand
Atlantic beach. An Olympic-size pool, Jacuzzi, and bar and grill
are here; a guest credit card, provided at check-in, covers food,
drinks, beach-umbrella rentals and other incidentals.
</P>
<P>
   The great outdoors: Capitalizing on its pristine location, the
Marriott has created several miles of trails for jogging, hiking,
biking and horseback riding (for ages 12 and older). Guests can
also book sailing and fishing day trips for a fee. Still not tired?
Try the resort's full-service health club or, alternatively, pamper
yourself at the spa with a massage ($70-$90), facial ($50-$65) or
makeover ($50 and up).
</P>
<P>
   Kids' stuff: Coloring contests and tie-dye shirt-making on the
pool deck. Pingpong matches by the lagoon. Races, relays and
charades at the pool. They're all part of the Marriott's
``Grasshopper Gang'' day-camp program. It's open 10 a.m.-2 p.m.
daily for kids ages 3-12 ($40 per child, includes lunch). The
nighttime equivalent _ ``Kids' Night Out'' _ keeps kids entertained
with movies, games and dinner in one of the resort's large
conference rooms ($40 per child, 5-9 p.m.). Baby sitters are also
available, by appointment, for $10 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Delta and AirTran offer round-trip flights as
low as $104 to Jacksonville International Airport, on a 14-day
advance purchase. From there, it's a 37-mile drive to the Sawgrass
Marriott Resort. From Atlanta, it's a 370-mile drive. Take I-75
south to I-10 east to I-95 south to Fla. 202 east to Fla. A1A
south. Follow the signs to Sawgrass.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Augustine: Just 30 miles south of Ponte Vedra Beach, St.
Augustine _ America's oldest city _ is worth a quick side trip. The
awe-inspiring Castillo de San Marcos National Monument _ a large
star-shaped limestone fort built by the Spanish in the 17th century
_ should be the focus of any family visit. The fort, at 1 Castillo
Drive (904-829-6506), is open 8:45 a.m.-4:45 p.m. daily. Admission
is free for seniors and children under 16; $4 adults.
</P>
<P>
   Also, make sure to walk St. Georges Street, a narrow pedestrian
way flanked by preserved or re-created 16th and 17th century
buildings _ as well as coffee bars, candy stores, souvenir shops
and more than a few taverns.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Beaching it: The beaches around Sawgrass offer two distinct
experiences. The Jacksonville beaches, just north of Ponte Vedra,
are a funky Floridian take on Coney Island _ built up with surf
shacks, sidewalk vendors and boutiques and flavored with a
bohemian/surfer-dude atmosphere. The sedate Ponte Vedra beaches,
farther south, are more private and naturally beautiful _ well
known for 40-foot dunes that roll into thickets of oak trees and
palmettos. Miles of marshes, lagoons and creeks can also be found
here.
</P>
<P>
   Nature lovers will want to take in the nearby Guana River State
Park, featuring five miles of beach and bordering a 9,600-acre
wildlife management area, just north of St. Augustine.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to eat: There's no shortage of world-class restaurants
or cheap-eats family places from Jacksonville to Ponte Vedra to St.
Augustine. Good mid-priced family restaurants include the Aqua
Grille (950 Sawgrass Village Drive, Ponte Vedra Beach,
904-285-3017) and Barnacle Bill's (14 Castillo Drive, St.
Augustine, 904-824-3663). Both provide terrific seafood specialties
_ fried, grilled and broiled _ and are clued in to the needs of
kids and families.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Downtown Jacksonville: At the mouth of the St. Johns River,
Jacksonville is a 45-minute drive north of Ponte Vedra Beach. The
waterfront city features upscale shopping at Jacksonville Landing
and a 1.25-mile Riverwalk, the well-regarded Jacksonville
Zoological Gardens (8605 Zoo Road, 904-757-4462) and the Museum of
Science and History (1025 Museum Circle Drive, 904-396-7062), which
features well-built dioramas exploring Florida's natural and
cultural history.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Sawgrass Marriott Resort, 904-285-7777 or
www.marriott.com/marriott/JAXSW/. Ponte Vedra Beach Chamber of
Commerce: 904-285-0666.
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
