<HEADER>
A6674 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SAWGRASS08-COX     08-05 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SAWGRASS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vacation easily becomes family affair at Sawgrass Marriott
Resort
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 8.
 &HT;    By Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ Still as stone, the gator's eyes
barely broke the dark water's surface _ the only clue to its
advancing position on the morning's meal.
</P>
<P>
   In a sudden splash of water and feathers, he snapped his jaws,
scattering two startled ducks and a half-dozen turtles. The crust
of bread vanished without a fight into the gator's jagged maw, as
the ducks and turtles took up safer positions along the water's
edge.
</P>
<P>
   Not 10 feet away, my 5-year-old son, Josh, broke off another
bread crust and cocked his arm like Tom Glavine. ``Did you see
that?'' he asked, tossing another morsel to the gator from the
relative dockside safety of his father's arms. ``He took it right
out of that turtle's mouth!''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing for the turtle _ and my son _ that this gator prefers
fresh bread to fresh meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wally,'' as we nicknamed him, is something of a mascot at the
Sawgrass Marriott Resort _ an inviting family vacation spot on
Florida's northeasternmost coast. Here, among the dunes and sands
of Ponte Vedra Beach, the Marriott has engineered a perfect
marriage of natural beauty and upscale resort amenities that makes
the whole crew feel right at home. In that regard, it's a fine
alternative to the better-known coastal resorts of Hilton Head,
Seaside and Destin, which are only marginally closer to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Blue heron and white egret perform elegant water ballet in and
around the water traps of the Marriott's highly rated golf courses.
Osprey, with their majestic 5-foot wingspans, soar overhead,
lending a grandeur to the resort's manicured gardens and hiking
trails. Red-tailed foxes roam the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Every detail of the 4,800-acre resort seems designed with
families in mind _ from the spacious one- and two-bedroom
efficiency villas and rooms (all of which feature balconies with
high safety walls) to the kid-friendly restaurants, sports
facilities and day-camp activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place has terrific kids' programs,'' notes Bill Richer,
39, an Alpharetta (Ga.) software consultant who visited on business
and was so taken with the Marriott children's day camp and night
programs that he plans to return with his family Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   While Sawgrass has no direct beach access, complimentary
shuttles run every 30 minutes to the resort's private Cabana Beach
Club, less than a mile away, on the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Tate writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
