<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6675 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-TOKYOGO08-COX     08-05 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TOKYOGO08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If you go
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 8.
 &HT;    By Betty Gordon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  GETTING STARTED
</P>
<P>
   Write the Japan National Tourist Organization
</P>
<P>
   (1 Rockefeller Plaza, Suite 1250, New York, NY 10020, or call
212-757-5640) and request publications such as ``Your Guide to
Japan'' and a map of Tokyo. On the Web _ at www.jnto.go.jp. _
you'll find a list of free publications and general information.
</P>
<P>
   Also, get a good guidebook. I used ``Tokyo'' ($14.95) from the
Lonely Planet series.
</P>
<P>
   Delta offers one daily, 13 1/2-hour nonstop to Tokyo. With a
seven-day advance purchase, round-trip fares are $1,100 for midweek
departures Nov. 1-Dec. 16 and Jan. 3-March 23; $1,200, Aug. 30-Oct.
31; and from $1,400, through Aug. 29 or Dec. 17-Dec. 26. American,
United, Continental, Northwest, JAL, Korean and Singapore airlines
fly to Tokyo, but with a stop (and typically a plane change) in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   I had a travel agent buy my ticket from a consolidator, Pacifico
Creative Service (www.jalpak.com,
</P>
<P>
   1-888-352-5725), and paid $556 round trip for my Delta flight.
</P>
<P>
   Home Visit System: A JNTO office in the lower level of the Tokyo
International Forum (a 10-minute walk from the Ginza shopping area)
is where I ``applied'' for a visit. The form asks name, age,
address, nationality, occupation, hobbies and where you are
staying.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour, an official had set up my visit with my hosts,
given me written directions and an identification badge.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Tokyo, families in Kyoto, Osaka and Kobe, among other
cities, also participate.
</P>
<P>
   Festivals: They are plentiful throughout the year all over the
country. Almost all involve colorful costumes and processions. The
JNTO guide has a list and your guidebook should, too. Participation
is welcome in most.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  GETTING AROUND
</P>
<P>
   Your guidebook or the materials from JNTO will probably have
routes for the subway and trains. If not, they're available at the
stations and some hotels. The subway and trains run frequently, are
safe and clean (no grafitti anywhere), inexpensive and easy to
navigate. And they were not as crowded, even at rush hour, as I
expected.
</P>
<P>
   The trickiest thing about the subways is that in the larger
stations, there can be many exits. Look for the big yellow signs on
the walls after you exit the turnstiles. They will list the main
streets and attractions. Taking the wrong exit will result in an
indirect route to your destination. I found that only the major
streets were marked on my Tokyo map, and only the major street
signs were in English. Plus, there were some streets that curve and
change names.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  LANGUAGE
</P>
<P>
   It would be misleading to say that English is widely spoken, but
in the places you need it, it's there. All subway and train
stations have their names in English, and at Narita International
Airport there are enough signs in English and enough
English-speaking employees to help you on your way. Most hotels
that cater to tourists also have English-speaking front-desk help.
</P>
<P>
   Several times I had stopped to consult my map or subway routes
and was asked if I needed help. So there is no need to be afraid of
setting off by yourself in this metro area of almost 12 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FOOD
</P>
<P>
   I don't like most fish or seafood, which is very popular in
Japan, but there are so many other choices that it wasn't a
problem. And there is no need to spend large amounts of money in a
restaurant for every meal.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants: You are never very far from an American fast-food
chain or the Japanese equivalent, and small Japanese restaurants
serving dishes heavy on noodles are inexpensive and abundant. Many
restaurants have plastic renditions of their dishes in the front
window, so if worse comes to worse, you can take your waiter
outside and point.
</P>
<P>
   Vending machines are on almost every street. Soft drinks and
bottled water cost 120 yen, which during my trip was about $1. The
machines also sell sports drinks, beer and wine, among other
things.
</P>
<P>
   Stores: All the big department stores have a huge selection of
food, usually at basement level and below. You can buy everything
from sushi to deli meats and salads to French pastries and
chocolate. So most of my meals were picnics in a park. And what
you've heard about prices for fruit is true. Two cantaloupes: about
$140.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  MUSEUMS, ATTRACTIONS, MARKETS
</P>
<P>
   Fish market: On the edge of Tokyo Bay and south of the Ginza
shopping area, the sprawling, wholesale Tsukiji Central Fish Market
was built in 1923. It covers 56 acres and features 1,600
wholesalers. Get there early, say around 7 a.m. There will have
been a daily auction before you arrive to which visitors generally
aren't welcome. The market sells 2,500 tons of fish a day.
</P>
<P>
   The bluefin tuna were easily 6 or 7 feet long and several
hundred pounds. There were octopuses, squid, crabs, oysters, clams,
sea urchins and some things I couldn't identify as I walked up and
down the narrow, bustling aisles.
</P>
<P>
   And the smell wasn't bad. The fish and seafood are expertly and
quickly cut down to size (the length and heft of the knives will
impress you) and iced. Some fish await their fate in tubs of water.
</P>
<P>
   A word of caution: Wear old shoes and watch where you step. The
floor is wet everywhere (and in some places bloody) and motorized
carts dart quickly down the rows. There is also a produce market
that's worth a look and an external market where you can pick up
souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   Open-air museum of Japanese folk houses: The collection of 24
buildings of traditional architecture that constitute Nihon
Minka-en has been brought from all over Honshu (the main island,
home to Tokyo) and reassembled in Kawasaki, about an hour west of
downtown. Some buildings date to the 1600s. The project began in
1965 and the upkeep is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings range from an inn for horse traders to a village
chief's house to a merchant's. Some of the houses that were moved
from western Japan have roofs that are sharply inclined to keep the
snow from accumulating and collapsing the house.
</P>
<P>
   You can walk on the ground floor of some buildings, but as in
all Japanese residences, take off your shoes first.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo National Museum: If you're interested in antique kimonos,
samurai swords and armor, sculpture, pottery and calligraphy,
Japan's oldest and largest museum is the place. It's set in the
northern end of Ueno Park and is really three buildings: one for
Japanese arts, another for Oriental antiquities and the third
housing Japanese archaeological objects.
</P>
<P>
   Edo-Tokyo Museum: This building, opened in 1993, traces the
history of Tokyo from the days of the Tokugawa shoguns (1603-1867)
to postwar reconstruction. There are life-size replicas of a kabuki
theater, split-row houses and other buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Gordon writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
