<HEADER>
A6676 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SHOEMAKER-BOS &LR;      08-05 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SHOEMAKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIAN OFFERS INVITING ACCOUNT OF TEA PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE SHOEMAKER AND THE TEA PARTY 
Memory and the American Revolution 
By Alfred F. Young 
Beacon, 262 pp., illustrated, $24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Tea Party may be the most easily apprehended of all
the events in Boston that led up to the Revolution. An easily told
story, it also makes for easy reenactment. No need to trot out a
squad of musket-toting Redcoats (as for the Boston Massacre or the
skirmishes at Lexington and Concord); just some face paint, some
old clothes, and a styrofoam box or two to toss off the Tea Party
ship into the Fort Point Channel.
</P>
<P>
   But as historian Alfred F. Young details in this fine account of
one of the participants and of how the event was remembered, it did
not become the ``Tea Party'' _ with that ``faintly comic and
irreverent'' connotation _ until close to a half century later.
When it was remembered at all during that half century (which was
rarely), it was as ``the destruction of the tea,'' the more
``serious and reverential'' term that appears on Charles Bulfinch's
1790 monument to the Revolution standing (in an 1898
reconstruction) behind the State House.
</P>
<P>
   Young's shoemaker is George Robert Twelves Hewes (the curious
``Twelves'' was apparently a family name) who was born in Boston in
1742. His cobbler's shop was on the waterfront, near Griffin's
Wharf, where the Tea Party occurred. He moved to New York State
after serving in the Revolution and ``remained a poor man'' until
his death in 1840.
</P>
<P>
   Hewes was one of the young artisans and mechanics who dumped tea
from three British merchant ships on the night of December 16,
1773; he was given a leadership position because of his well-known
talent for whistling, which was useful in summoning his team. He
was a witness to the Boston Massacre in 1770 and a witness or
participant in other ``mobbish'' actions. He was one of the
veterans of the Revolution whose ``discovery'' in the 1830s
coincided with the restoration of the Tea Party and other radical
events into the Revolutionary canon.
</P>
<P>
   Two biographies of Hewes appeared in 1834 and 1835, about the
time he returned to Boston _ and had his portrait (now in the
Bostonian Society) painted as a ``Centenarian.'' They were the
first books to use the term ``tea party'' in the title, the first
to focus on the event itself, and the first biographies of any
participant. As Young notes, ``Hewes and the term `tea party'
emerge in print culture at the same time _ or so it seems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Shoemaker and the Tea Party'' is actually two separate
essays. The first, a masterful bringing to life of an obscure
participant in a historic and iconic event, was originally
published in 1981 in the William and Mary Quarterly. Young, a
senior research fellow at the Newberry Library in Chicago, explains
that in the succeeding two decades ``there has been a revolution in
the study of personal memory . . . along with an explosion in
scholarship about public memory'' among historians.
</P>
<P>
   In the second essay, Young addresses the intriguing question of
why the Tea Party was virtually forgotten for close to a half
century _ and why it was then ``rediscovered.''
</P>
<P>
   In the decades after the Revolution, Young writes, Boston was
``an overwhelmingly Federalist town'' and focused its celebrations
on the ``safe, conservative'' Fourth of July. And in those
``orderly and hierarchical'' celebrations, there was no room for
remembrances of events that might reignite the fires of public
protest.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the Tea Party stood as ``the most revolutionary
act'' of the decade preceeding 1775, Young writes, a
``quasi-military action'' organized during a series of ``palpably
illegal'' meetings and involving the most radical in its planning
and execution. In addition, its ``carnivalesque'' atmosphere was
``a wild reversal of the traditional order.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the 1830s, several things had changed. There were
Lafayette's visits to Boston in 1824 and 1825 (the latter one
included laying the cornerstone of the Bunker Hill Monument),
which, writes Young, ``watered the Liberty Tree.'' At the same
time, veterans were being ``discovered,'' often as petitioners for
public welfare, but calling forth ``a sense of loss of the last
links to the Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   In weaving together the stories of Hewes and the Tea Party,
Young has made a major contribution to an understanding of the role
of ordinary people in important events, and of the way in which
even seemingly well-known events can be forgotten and remembered,
interpreted and reinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, though, this is a book for Boston. As Young notes,
``Boston has to be the most bestatued city in the country'' _ and
while he correctly notes that ``the sway of past conservative
public memory is strong,'' the more radical and ``mobbish'' events
are now also commemorated. But the restored and venerated ``sites
are quiet,'' he writes, while ``the Revolution was noisy.''
</P>
<P>
   His question of ``how, amid the skyscraper caverns of a bustling
downtown, could you convey the picketing boys, the massive funeral
processions of men and women, the hanging of effigies, the tarring
and feathering _ the stuff of the popular revolution'' is a
challenge to consider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
