<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIBLE-FLOWERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADD FLOWER POWER TO YOUR REPAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ ``I don't know what I expected a sunflower to
taste like,'' said a colleague, ``but that wasn't it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a zinger.
</P>
<P>
   Edible flowers actually taste like something. They are
ingredients. And just because they're pretty doesn't mean you can
go sprinkling them over everything willy nilly like a flower girl
at a wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Kelly, the award-winning chef at the Old Chatham
Sheepherding Co. Inn, uses flowers on almost every dish that leaves
the kitchen. But she does it carefully. ``They each have individual
flavors and I try to match the flowers with the dish,'' Kelly says.
``Some marigolds are savory. Pansies tend to be more fragrant. I
usually try and balance a dish. For instance, I wouldn't put a
sweet floral flower on a sweet entree. But I would use one on
dessert because that's sweet all around and that's what you're
looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   The grounds at Old Chatham include extensive gardens and a
greenhouse where the flowers are grown. But those not blessed with
a full-time gardener can serve flowers, too. Chances are, you may
be growing a few edible varieties already.
</P>
<P>
   Nasturtiums, geraniums, day lilies, sunflowers, Johnny-jump-ups
and roses are all edible, providing they haven't been exposed to
harmful chemicals. If you have a lawn service, spray your plants
for pests or have a neighbor who does, skip grazing in your garden
and buy edible flowers from stores. Boxes of them are frequently
stocked with the herbs in larger grocery stores and gourmet
markets. Also avoid picking edible flowers from roadsides where
exhaust fumes, road salt and other contaminants tend to accumulate.
</P>
<P>
   And don't limit your edible flowers to garden beauties. Kelly
says she uses blossoms from herbs as well as flowers from sweet
pea, squash and other vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Squash blossoms go well battered and fried and served atop a
squash salad. It's a little of the flower and a little of the
fruit,'' Kelly says.
</P>
<P>
   But Kelly has one caution for those new to serving flowers:
``Don't just pick, you have to know what you're putting in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep a copy of `Peterson's Field Guide for Edible Foods'
just so I know that what I'm picking really is edible,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Kelly, executive chef at the Old Chatham Sheepherding
Co. Inn, uses this recipe with lobster dishes. ``The peppery flavor
of the nasturtiums counterbalances the sweetness of the lobster,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NASTURTIUM BUTTER
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 1/2 cup)
</P>
<P>
   Nasturtium leaves and flowers
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Remove stamens and pistils from flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Puree nasturtiums, butter, lemon juice and salt in a food
processor until the flowers form flecks of color in the butter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOD TIP: When serving edible flowers, it's best to remove the
stamens and pistils (the male and female parts in the center of the
blossom) before serving, advises a Web site from the University of
Illinois Cooperative Extension Service and Cathy Barash, editor of
Edible Flowers. Of course with daisies and sunflowers that have
more pistils than petals, it's easier to remove the petals and
discard the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The site also notes that wild roses taste better than cultivated
ones, but it is best to remove the lower part of the rose petals to
reduce bitterness. No mention of what color roses are the most
flavorful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
