<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEAMING UP MOUNT WASHINGTON TO CELEBRATE A CENTENNIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have been atop Mt. Washington in the glistening splendor that
any of the four seasons can bring to its summit. I've also been
there in the midst of lightning storms that sent me scampering to
get below treeline and in the middle of several fierce and howling
winter moments that ended in tragedy for others.
</P>
<P>
   This is, after all, a mountain that has killed more than 200
people in the past century. So it has always seemed an irony to me
that for all the skilled climbing that has gone on there and all
the tragedies that have struck, you can drive a car to its peak, or
take a train there.
</P>
<P>
   You've seen the contrapuntal T-shirts: ``This Car Climbed Mt.
Washington'' and ``This Body Climbed Mt. Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   This year marks the 138th anniversay of the carriage road up the
mountain _ a carriage road now known as the Mt. Washington Auto
Road _ a twisting, undulating path up the mountain with steep drops
along its edges and a propensity to overheat engines on the way up
and cook brakes on the way down.
</P>
<P>
   This month is also the 100th anniversary of the first ascent of
the mountain by automobile and beginning steam autos will flock to
the mountain and the White Mountain and Great North Woods regions
of New Hampshire to commemorate that first auto climb.
</P>
<P>
   Steam is the auto of choice because it was a steam auto that
wheezed up the mountain on Aug. 31, 1899. And given the nature of
the mountain and what had to have been a far more treacherous road
than what exists today, it is perhaps appropriate that the first
climb was in a rig called a Locomobile.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard the Locomobile were Freelan Oscar Stanley and his wife,
Flora, and in wonderful weather they picked their way up the Auto
Road and into history. It is a drive that will be recreated by many
of the more than 80 steam automobiles expected to assemble at the
base of the Auto Road beginning next weekend (Aug. 7-8).
</P>
<P>
   The weekend kicks off seven days of activities, including time
trials on the Auto Road, cookouts, exhibits and steam auto tours
through northern New Hampshire, are sponsored by Maine's Stanley
Museum and the Mt. Washington Summit Road Co.
</P>
<P>
   Cars are coming from Europe, California, and other parts of the
United States, and they include Stanleys, Whites, Locomobiles, a
Doble, a Waltham, and other steamers.
</P>
<P>
   The cars will be on exhibit to the public from 12-4 Sunday and
some may go up the Auto Road that day. On Monday, time trials on
the Auto Road go from 6-9 a.m. and beginning at 10 the road reopens
to the public, whose drivers may find themselves on the road with
steam autos.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the steam celebration, of course, is the Stanley
Steamer, developed by identical twin brothers _ Francis Edgar and
Freelan Oscar Stanley (F. E. and F. O. as they were known) from
Newton. The inventive brothers' steam car had raised a stir at an
1898 exhibition in Cambridge and caught the eye of macadam tycoon
Amzi Lorenzo Barber. The following spring, he bought the Stanley
company and by the summer of 1899 Stanleys had become Locomobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Barber, wanting to prove his cars to be tough and reliable,
looked for a test that would impress the public. He chose the road
up Mt. Washington, 8 miles of what was then among the most
challenging roads in America.
</P>
<P>
   Flora Stanley's account of their climb in Locomobile (NU)93 is
wonderful for its dated writing style, its sometimes understated
tone, and its prescient view of how New Hampshire natives and
Massachusetts tourists would eye each other down the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the twenty-sixth of August, 1899, an unusual expedition
started from Hunnewell Avenue, Newton. . . .'' she wrote. ``Our aim
was a high one since it was Mt. Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   They crossed the Charles River Bridge into Watertown and went
north to Newburyport and then into New Hampshire where, apparently,
little has changed since then. The first obstacle they came to in
the Granite State was a toll booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a toll bridge between Portsmouth and Dover,'' Flora
Stanley wrote, and then explained how the posted tolls included 5
cents for foot passengers and 15 cents for horse and wagon. Two
``rosy-cheeked maidens'' who tended the toll were baffled as to
what to charge for an automobile so they consulted ``Marm,'' who
told the Stanleys that 10 cents was the proper price.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanleys eyed the locals with some sense of superiority and
the locals eyed the rich tourists from Massachusetts with some
suspicion _ as I said, little has changed in New Hampshire since
then.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were a wonder and surprise to the rustic population,
they were a source of amusement to us,'' Flora Stanely wrote.
</P>
<P>
   It took them five days to make the trip from Newton to Mt.
Washington, and the trip up the mountain, after a good night's
rest, was remarkably smooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went on and up, up, still up,'' she wrote. ``The continuous
climbing being varied only by a steepness so excessive that as we
looked ahead to it, we felt a sickening anxiety lest each brilliant
dash should be our last . . . our engine, panting and quivering,
never failied us, but pushed us bravely over seemingly impassible
heights.''
</P>
<P>
   The 8-mile climb took 2 hours and 10 minutes, including a stop
for water three-quarters of the way up the mountain. This on a road
that took eight years to build and which horse-drawn stages took
six hours to ascend.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, purists, who wish the road had never been
built, but it was and the Locomobile climbed it and so here we are
today, ready to celebrate that ascent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford covers the automotive world for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
