<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION STILL NOT FULL STRENGTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- They'll get Joe-Max Moore and John Harkes back in time
for Friday night's road game against the Colorado Rapids, and
that's the good news for the New England Revolution as they try to
break a three-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   But then there's the reality that defender Dan Calichman is
still hobbling a bit with hip and groin problems and may have to
sit this one out, coupled with the continued absence of forward
Giovanni Savarese, who practiced Wednesday but will not make the
trip because his knee is not 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the return of one of their best scorers in Moore and
midfield catalyst Harkes from the US Confederations Cup team, the
Revolution will have their work cut out after being outscored,
11-3, during their slump, and will be facing the cream of the
Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've still got a sore groin,'' said Calichman, who played just
the first half of last Saturday's 4-1 loss at Tampa Bay. ``I'd like
to be able to go 90 (minutes), but maybe I need to rest it a little
to be able to do it . . . so we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Calichman said ending the losing streak is pressure enough, but
the big picture is even more important. The team is still in the
playoff hunt in fourth place in the Eastern Conference, ``and so
there's even more pressure on to get that `W' and three points.
Right now, we're in a dogfight. It's simple. We need to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Calichman said the team's problems have boiled down to ``a few
little things. We seem to lose our concentration, we've given up
easy goals early, and that has put us in a hole right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, said Calichman, the Revolution would be in better
shape with all of their top players on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we have the players who can get the job done, but we've
played poorly over the last three weeks and we have no one to blame
but ourselves,'' added captain Mike Burns. ``From a coaching
standpoint, for Walter (Zenga) and Bepe (Galderisi), it would be
nice to get the same lineup to play some consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're a better team than what we showed, but there's a
long way to go. Even a month ago, when everyone was saying we were
so much better _ which I think we are _ we still hadn't proven
anything. We've run into a bad spell, but we'll get out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's last win was July 4, a 3-2 decision in
Foxborough over the MetroStars. Injuries and the loss of Moore and
Harkes to the third-place US team in Mexico have kept the roster in
a state of flux.
</P>
<P>
   ``A month seems like a year when you haven't won and when you're
playing every game in 100-degree weather. This summer has been
brutal across the country,'' said Burns. ``I can't wait for
September. It's been tough physically to play in this kind of
weather _ but it's the same for every team. I've talked to some of
the guys from teams in Florida and the Midwest and West and they've
had to practice at 9 in the morning because it's been so hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soccer players, we're in good shape, but still, you've
heard the news when they tell you to stay inside, and we're out
there running around.''
</P>
<P>
   The altitude in Denver may also pose a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are different theories about that. It affects some
players more than others,'' said Burns. ``Regardless, Colorado is a
solid team. They're not giving up a lot of goals and they're
scoring goals on the chances they're creating. They're playing with
a lot of confidence right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Savarese, meanwhile, expressed disappointment about not being
able to return, but said that by staying home and taking more
treatment, he hopes to be ready for next Thursday's home game
against San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling much better. I was able to train today and it was
my first day back,'' he said. ``I felt good, but I'm not 100
percent and I don't want to come back until I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating. I want to be a part of helping us. It's
difficult just to watch. But when all of us are back and healthy, I
think we can be a very good team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
