<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOORSTOPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOORSTOPS PROVIDE FUNCTION, DECORATIVE FLAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Don't be frustrated by doors that keep swinging
shut when you're trying to keep more than one door open for
cross-ventilation. Sit down, relax and keep unruly doors open with
a doorstop.
</P>
<P>
   These old-fashioned functional stops, also known as door
porters, are about 6 to 12 inches high. They are made of cast iron
to keep them from toppling over.
</P>
<P>
   They are also decorative and whimsical in nature. The designs
and shapes are endless, from fauna to flora and famous people, from
early presidents to other historical figures.
</P>
<P>
   Early doorstops were mostly likely a rock, stick of wood, brick
or chair propped up against the door to keep it open. The first
doorstops were manufactured in England in the second half of the
18th century. They were cast in molds in earthenware, and later
made of marble, bronze, wood, brass and glass.
</P>
<P>
   Early doorstops came outfitted with a handle or straight rod,
which allowed the user to place or remove them without bending
down. Since 1810, the molded shapes provided easy grips, doing away
with handles.
</P>
<P>
   Victorian doorstops looked like baskets of flowers or fruit,
scenic images, buildings and allegorical and biblical images. Many
are colorfully painted on only the three-dimensional side. Designs
varied between manufacturers, who often competed with each other.
</P>
<P>
   According to an article in Country Living, cast-iron doorstops
were manufactured in America between 1910 and 1940, with the Albany
Foundry in Albany being one of the most prolific producers. The
company, which also produced a catalog, discontinued its line in
1948.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their weight and size, doorstops can also double as
bookends or as a simple piece of sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Although many fine examples of antique doorstops from the 19th
and 20th centuries can be found in antiques shops, new versions and
reproductions are easy to find. Costs can range from approximately
$40 to hundreds of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Like any antique, the value of a historic doorstop is based on
its untouched original paint finish. Antique doorstops also weigh
more. Later doorstops are made with less iron, to cut down on
production costs.
</P>
<P>
   Doorstops, which fell out of favor when rooms were
air-conditioned in the later part of the 20th century, can be
researched in Jeanne Bertoia's 1985 book ``Doorstops:
Identification and Values'' ($9.95 Collector Books).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
