<SLUG> BC-US-ECONOMY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL ECONOMIC EYES ON THE US 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A &UR;  &LR; year ago, Asia's currencies seemed to be sliding into the
sea. Russia's cobbled economic system was breaking apart, and
Brazil began to quake. The world's troubles brushed even Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the United States powered ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The US economy expanded by almost 3.5 percent in the first half
of 1999 and has been a singular and dominant force in stabilizing _
even repairing _ a fragile global economy in the months since the
fallout last year, international economists say. Although financial
and currency crises also jeopardized the US financial system last
year, bold moves by the Federal Reserve to drop interest rates
saved the day.
</P>
<P>
   Now, amid expectations the central bank may raise rates to cool
an overheated economy or, worse, fears the nation could flip from
boom to bust, the fate of the United States, the globe's biggest
economy, has become more important than ever to a world still on
the mend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, of course, how long this can go on,'' said
Flemming Larsen, deputy director of economic research for the
International Monetary Fund. ``A relatively soft landing would be
much better for the world. If we see an abrupt (US) slowdown, that
would be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   According to IMF estimates, the global growth rate slowed in
1998 to 2.5 percent, after expanding in 1997 at a 4 percent clip
amid the first outbreak of financial contagion that raged through
southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But 1999 looks brighter. Due to a combination of US strength and
unexpected improvement abroad, the IMF in May raised its projection
of 1999 growth from 2.2 percent to 2.3 percent. Many emerging
countries _ including Thailand, Indonesia and Brazil _ were among
those with better prospects this year, according to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US economy has been critically important in allowing the
world economy to avoid a much broader and deeper recession,'' said
Larsen. ``The relationship is a mutually beneficial one.''
</P>
<P>
   America's most obvious contribution overseas is its importing of
goods. Insatiable consumers, their pockets stuffed with strong US
dollars, have soaked up bargains all over the world, pushing the US
trade deficit to a record $21 billion in May.
</P>
<P>
   Low-cost imports have also helped keep US inflation in check and
continue the US expansion. But American buying has risen most in
countries where currencies plummeted most _ it is the natural
recalibration that helps those economies hit hardest, such as
Malaysia and South Korea. Should US spending slow, countries
relying on those exports to America would suffer.
</P>
<P>
   In South Korea, government officials moved decisively to stem
fallout from their sliding currency, the won, and stanched the
damage to their banks and economy. Today, economists say South
Korea is farthest on the road to recovery; it is expected to grow
4.5 percent this year after shrinking nearly 6 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Recovery has been helped by a 19 percent increase in South
Korea's exports to the United States, which purchased $11.24
billion of its goods in the first five months of 1999. Export
growth in Korea far outpaces growth for the region overall.
</P>
<P>
   Southeast Asia's stability has helped Japan, which relies
heavily on its Pacific Rim trading partners, said Akinari Horii, a
general manager for the Bank of Japan in its New York office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the demand from the West, Asian economies would be in
deeper trouble, which would've posed a bigger problem on Japan's
economy,'' Horii said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan faces a long road out of its economic abyss. The world's
second-biggest industrial country has been mired in recession or
stalled since the early 1990s and contracted 2.8 percent last year.
Its deterioration accelerated amid turmoil in the region, as banks
were closed or sold.
</P>
<P>
   But Japan had a surprising spike in first-quarter growth this
year. Though that pace is not expected to continue, Japan's economy
has clearly ``stopped declining,'' Horii said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has taken center stage at a time when Japan is
struggling and European nations are frustrated that they have been
unable to achieve the kind of expansion witnessed here.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, policy makers are running out of tools with which to
create growth. With interest rates scraping near 0 percent, Bank of
Japan is unable to fuel growth through monetary policy. Tax cuts
boosted the economy, but economists said the key to the country's
recovery is in fixing its financial system.
</P>
<P>
   In an ideal world, the United States would keep growing at a
sustainable pace, said Alan Sinai, chief economist for Primark
Decision Economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is _ I think it probably will happen this way _ that
the damaged and devastated parts of the world economy will reverse
and pick up and move into a self-sustaining recovery before the US
has to slow down its economy,'' Sinai said.
</P>
<P>
   That would also help Europe, where Italy and Germany are trying
to shake off negative growth at the end of last year. Europe's
growth is expected to slow to 1.9 percent for 1999, from 2.6
percent last year, according to Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe has not been the other engine of growth in the global
economy,'' said Nariman Behravesh, international economist at
Standard &AMP; Poor's/DRI, a Lexington economics consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   With Europe's economy weak, the Continent is unable to play its
traditional role as an engine of world growth and is trying to jump
on the US locomotive, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   US strength also benefits overseas economies through direct
investment and acquisitions by US corporations. The bulk of US
direct investment goes to industrial regions, such as Europe,
Canada, and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the foreign economies are going up,'' said Ray Mataloni,
economist for the federal Bureau of Economic Analysis, ``US
corporations tend to reinvest that money.''
</P>
<P>
   US-based companies, putting their record profits to work,
invested $121.64 billion last year in plants, offices, equipment,
and other goods necessary to operate abroad, according to the BEA.
That's a 44 percent increase from just two years ago. This year is
on target to surpass that. (BEA data exclude investments in
overseas stocks and bonds.)
</P>
<P>
   Kem Stokes, an economist for the International Trade
Administration under the US Department of Commerce, said exports
are Europe's best route to faster growth. A plunge in the unified
currency, the euro, has boosted US imports from the European Union
by 10 percent in 1999, compared with a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to grow a bit more rapidly than they have been,''
said Stokes, who said European nations are constrained by the
Maastricht Treaty from using government spending to boost their
economies. Trade, he said, ``is their only option.''
</P>
<P>
   While the US economy shows no signs of weakness yet, there are
risks on the horizon. The current account deficit _ a measure of
money flowing into and out of the country _ ballooned to $233
billion in 1998 and is expected to exceed $310 billion this year.
The effect is that the United States has become a vacuum sucking in
borrowed money from investors around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a limit,'' Stokes said, ``to how much support you can
give'' the world economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
