<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-AUGUST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUGUST GIVES FLIGHT TO FLOWERY THOUGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH S. FOSTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   August is the lazy season in the backyard garden, a time to
muse, to dream, to sit with a cool drink and a fan, and just
vegetate. The famous philosopher Rene Descartes said, ``I think,
therefore I am.'' But in summer I just am, therefore I think.
</P>
<P>
   So some thoughts born of the August heat follow. A few may be
useful, a few informative, but most are just the rambling
cogitations of our all too human self-consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever wondered why the best balcony gardens belong to
little old ladies who live in apartment buildings in southern
Italy? The reason is that they watch their plants every day. They
water just so. They pick spent blooms. They fertilize. They tend.
And the Italian sun shines and shines on their works.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies the secret of great gardens. A garden only
thrives as long as there is a gardener in the sun. Mother Nature
doesn't garden. She just sits, waits, and watches as the fittest
survive, and cares not who they be.
</P>
<P>
   For in gardens there is a never-ending war among the plants for
space. What we human gardeners do is decide who fills it. Will it
be flowers? Vegetables? Trees? A perfect green lawn? Whatever
strikes our fancy we can plant, for every garden is the creation of
a human mind in search of beauty and a space of one's own desires.
</P>
<P>
   Forget what the garden magazines and TV shows, Scott's grass
seed, and especially Disneyland, tout as today's style. Design is
infinite, and your idea of beauty is as good as any one's.
</P>
<P>
   So how about eating some of that beauty? Well, it's very
possible, and in these days of gourmet competition in the kitchen,
you can wow your picky friends and family with flower-embellished
food.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers are easiest used as garnish on salads or as you would
use fresh herbs on hot dishes. Some blossoms have a mild taste,
some are spicy, some mimic herbs. Most people are adventurous
enough to taste at least one blossom.
</P>
<P>
   Squash blossoms, rose petals, pansy, borage, violets, and
hollyhock have a mild taste. For a more spicy flavor consider
marigold, stock, nasturtium (a bit like horseradish), geranium (all
different, nibble one first), dianthus (peppery-cloves), daisy,
calendula, and chrysanthemum.
</P>
<P>
   The flowers of commonly used herbs, chives, thyme, sage, and
rosemary, work well, too, if you catch them young. Lavender
blossoms are another possibility, maybe sprinkled on vanilla ice
cream, for fragrance is an important part of taste perception.
</P>
<P>
   I must confess I have not tasted all of these, but for the
adventurous palate, they are safe to eat as long as they have not
been sprayed with any pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   The August garden always looks bare unless one had the spring
foresight to plant lots of annuals in full sun. Some perennial
gardens may be blessed with asters and chrysanthemums (which are
hard to overwinter well). Easier late-season blooming perennials
are Sedum spectabilis, old-fashioned late phlox, or Hosta
plantaginea `Grandiflora.'
</P>
<P>
   You can add any or all of these to the bare spots now. But for
quick color until frost, consider that old standby impatiens, the
soft-leafed variety for shade, the New Guinea for sun. Hydrangeas
can help, too, though the blue and pink ones are not winter hardy.
</P>
<P>
   Going on vacation and worried about how to keep flower pots and
hanging plants watered? Try a variation on ``pillow planting'' (for
unglazed clay pots only). Get a bag of moist peat moss. Cut some
X-shaped holes in the top. Fill the peat with water until it is
thoroughly and completely soaked, which takes about two days of
filling it up with water, waiting until it is absorbed, then
filling it up again. Then punch a couple of small drain holes in
the bottom. This will stay moist for about a week.
</P>
<P>
   Finally sink clay flower pots into the holes in the top of the
wet peat moss bag, covering the rims but not the plants. Works for
sphagnum-lined baskets, too. Water is absorbed from the peat right
through the clay or moss.
</P>
<P>
   Or one can try this variation on a commercial tree-planting
system. Start with a large plastic bag, such as a garbage bag. Fill
it with water and tie the top. Make one tiny, tiny pin hole in the
bottom so it will take several days to drip out. It's tricky to
calibrate correctly. The bag can be stabilized in a flowerpot or
box and placed just next to the plant that needs vacation watering.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to water while away is to use a thick cotton wick
(often braided). One end is buried in the soil, the other in a big
jar of water, which is usually at the same height or higher than
the flower pot. When properly set up, the water wicks out of the
jar by capillary action and into the soil. Test it first because it
doesn't always work as planned.
</P>
<P>
   But let's be honest, a neighbor boy with a bucket is the easiest
thing, assuming he won't forget in the heat of this sultry summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Ruth S. Foster has been a landscape consultant in the Boston area
for many years.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
