<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE ISLAND, UNDER GOD, INDIVISIBLE . . . 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My heart went out to the people of Nantucket when I read a story
in Monday's Globe about Joyce and Michel Berruet, proprietors of
the island's L'Isle de France, subtitled The French General Store.
Perhaps you read the story too, on the front of the Metro section.
It was difficult to miss, illustrated as it was with a photograph
of the Berruets looking as though they had barely survived some
unspeakable tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   It was a complicated story, but the bottom line for Nantucket is
simple and stark. Because of continuing trade disputes between the
European Union and the United States, the World Trade Organization
has approved 100 percent tariffs on some European goods. These
include certain French products that are mainstays at the French
General Store, items such as duck mousse pate and bread baked in
Paris one afternoon by ``famous French artisan baker Lionel
Poilane'' and delivered to Nantucket the following morning.
</P>
<P>
   The shipments from Poilane have stopped. There is no authentic
French bread to be had on the entire island. To make matters worse,
the French pate company's permission to export has been
provisonally suspended. When will the madness end?
</P>
<P>
   Of course Nantucketers are not the only people who suffer. In
country clubs and exclusive watering places across the continent
the cry has gone up, ``What, no pate?'' Somehow, though, the
situation seems more poignant on Nantucket, so beautiful, so
remote, so rich.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Nantucket should secede from the United States and
become a sovereign nation. Then it could negotiate its own trade
agreements with foreign powers and remove the prohibitive tariffs
on imported French bread and pate and other necessities of island
life.
</P>
<P>
   I make this suggestion to atone for a column I wrote a couple of
years ago in which I made some rash generalizations about rising
prices and declining civility on the island. A number of Nantucket
residents responded to that column, and soon made me see the error
of my ways. They explained that the island isn't for ordinary
tourists who want to spend a day or a week or two soaking up
Nantucket charm. It's a kind of preserve, where people with plenty
of money are able to band together for mutual protection from
people who don't understand their way of life. People like me, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   The last few years have seen the level of consumption on
Nantucket escalate sharply. In June, Joe Kahn reported on this page
about the startling changes wrought on the island by ``new money,''
people who throw up multimillion-dollar ``cottages'' and fly in on
their private jets. A story in Sunday's New York Times reported on
the escalating pace of building and development that, some
Nantucket old-timers believe, threatens the island's integrity.
</P>
<P>
   From these and other reports it seems clear that Nantucket is
well on the way to becoming a community strictly of and for the
very rich. Why not make the most of it? If the island declared its
independence it could become a tax haven, like Monaco. A sovereign
Nantucket could restrict the flow of the hoi polloi, all those
day-trippers and short-term visitors. It could put import tariffs
where they belong, on the sorts of things the nonrich consume. Taco
chips. Wonder Bread. Budweiser. In the unlikely event someone on
the island wanted a jug of Gallo, he'd have to pay big time.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, perhaps mainland sympathizers should organize a food
drive to aid the beleaguered citizens of Nantucket. Let them eat
cake? Forget it. Let them eat Velveeta and Triscuits. If we hurry,
we can organize a mercy flight before the weekend parties get under
way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1301EDT &QL; 
