<HEADER>
A6688 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY06-COX     08-05 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mobile hosts treasures of Russia's last czar and his family
 &HT;    By Tinah Saunders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOBILE, Ala. _ There's nothing like a tale of star-crossed
lovers, incredible wealth, ultimate power, intrigue, treachery and
murder to draw a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 600,000 people toured ``Nicholas &AMP; Alexandra: The Last
Imperial Family of Tsarist Russia'' during the six months it was on
display in Wilmington, Del. And Mobile officials are counting on at
least that number to pass through its Civic Center by Nov. 14, when
the elaborate presentation closes there. But crowds were sparse
during our visit over the July Fourth weekend, three weeks after
the exhibit opened June 12.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Arnold, spokeswoman for the Mobile Convention &AMP; Visitors
Corp., attributed the lack of visitors to the last-minute timing of
the exhibit. In two weeks, Mobile raised $1 million in donations
from individuals and local businesses to stage the traveling
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't have the time to publicize it properly before
it opened,'' Arnold said. She expects numbers to increase as word
of the quality of the show gets out.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit organizer Broughton International is headed by James E.
Broughton, who initiated the successful ``WONDERS: The Memphis
International Cultural Series,'' which opened in 1987 with
``Ramesses the Great.'' ``Nicholas &AMP; Alexandra'' is the ninth such
presentation that Broughton has produced.
</P>
<P>
   This one is certainly crowdworthy. More personal than the 1996
``Palaces of the Czars'' show in Jackson, Miss., ``Nicholas &AMP;
Alexandra'' is not merely a display of possessions and
architectural re-creations, but a fascinating story of Russia's
last royal family told in their own words.
</P>
<P>
   Many people once thought that all traces of the Russian royal
family were obliterated after the Bolshevik Revolution. But a
surprising number of royal treasures, personal mementos and
official documents survived 80 years of Communist rule. There are
700 objects on display in the 14 galleries carved out of Mobile's
cavernous civic center, many of them never seen in public before
this exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   There's something for everyone: elegant ball gowns worn by the
czarina and her court; the gilded coach that carried Alexandra to
her coronation; jeweled bibelots crafted by some of Europe's finest
artisans, including a miniature, diamond-encrusted set of the
imperial regalia created by Karl Faberge for the 1900 World
Exhibition in Paris. There are love letters from ``Alix'' to her
``Darling Niki,'' diaries and old photographs of the family, which
was connected by birth or marriage to almost every European monarch
of the time.
</P>
<P>
   And there are grim reminders of the family's fate, such as the
bayonet that finished what a squad of gunmen could not in the
basement of a house in isolated Ekaterinburg. Also on display:
fragments of blood-spattered wallpaper and stoneware jugs that
contained the acid used to disfigure the bodies after death.
</P>
<P>
   Catching eyes is a 190-foot-long watercolor painting, a panorama
of Moscow at the coronation of Nicholas and Alexandra in 1896, that
was unrolled for the first time in this century especially for this
exhibition. The painting depicts a sophisticated city, made festive
with millions of electric lights at a time when electric light was
still rare in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most poignant display is the series of drawings done
by the royal children for their mother _ the kind that mothers
everywhere display proudly on refrigerator doors today. The
drawings point out better than anything else in the exhibition the
incredible ordinariness of the last of the Romanovs. It was an
admirable characteristic, but one that did not endear them to their
people and helped isolate them from those who might have rallied to
their aid.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas and Alexandra had been born to rule. Nicholas' family
had reigned over Russia for 300 years, and Alexandra was the
favorite granddaughter of Britain's Queen Victoria, who took the
child under her wing when her mother died. But Nicholas' father,
Czar Alexander, had refused to teach him about affairs of state,
and when Alexander died unexpectedly, Nicholas was thrust into a
position he was not prepared to assume.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra was shy and reclusive. She did not approve of Russia's
sophisticated court society, over which Nicholas' mother reigned.
Not long after her wedding, Alexandra had a falling out with her
mother-in-law and retreated into a private world that revolved
around her husband and children. Although the couple were devoted
to each other and to their children, the exclusive nature of their
relationship helped create an enmity in the court and with the
Russian people. They were, in their naivete, their own worst
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Such a personal look at one of the century's most tragic
families takes time. There are 25,000 square feet of exhibit space,
as well as an extensive gift shop and bookstore. Visitors are
advised to allow at least two hours to tour the exhibit, but we
were surprised to find, when we checked our watches as we left,
that we had spent four hours there. Tickets are sold by reservation
for specific times, the latest being 6 p.m. The exhibit closes at 8
p.m. Don't rush yourself.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Mobile is a five-hour drive from Atlanta. Take
I-85 South to Montgomery, then I-65 South. Follow the signs to
downtown Mobile and watch for signs to the exhibit. The Civic
Center is at 401 Civic Center Drive, in the historic district.
Parking is $3 in the lot behind the facility.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tickets: Adults, $14.95; seniors (62 and over), $13.45;
college students, $8.95; youth (grades K-12), $4; children under 5,
free. Family package (two adults, four youths), $34.95. Add tax to
all prices. There is a $2 per ticket charge for tickets ordered by
telephone or mail. Toll-free ticket line: 1-888-395-0005.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to stay: A Holiday Inn (334-694-0100), a Holiday Inn
Express (334-433-6923) and the Malaga Inn (1-800-235-1586) are
within walking distance of the Civic Center. The Adams Mark hotel
(334-438-4000), overlooking Mobile Bay, is offering special room
and ticket packages.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to eat: Mobile is famous for its seafood restaurants.
One of the oldest and best-known is Wintzell's Oyster House
(334-432-4605) on Dauphin Street, where you can enjoy some of the
area's freshest catches or even try your luck at breaking the
oyster-eating record. A branch of the famous Dreamland Bar-B-Que
restaurant (334-479-9898) is located on Old Shell Road just off
I-65. Justine's Courtyard and Carriageway (334-438-4535), in the
historic district, offers a champagne brunch on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mobile tourism information: 1-800-566-2453.
</P>
<P>
   Tinah Saunders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
