<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Hiawassee, Ga. _ The 49th annual Georgia Mountain Fair today
through Aug. 15 features a pioneer mountain village, one-room
schoolhouse, old-time crafts demonstrations, concerts and carnival
midway on the banks of Lake Chatuge. 706-896-4191 or
www.georgia-mountain-fair.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Young Harris, Ga. _ The 11th season of the state's official
historical drama, ``The Reach of Song,'' continues through Aug. 22
in a tribute to mountain poet Byron Herbert Reece. 1-800-262-7664.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jekyll Island, Ga. _ The 16th Annual Beach Music Festival on
the Beach Deck on Aug. 14 is one of the biggest beach parties in
the Southeast. 912-635-3636.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ The 72nd annual Mountain Dance and Folk
Festival on the stage of the Diana Wortham Theater at Pack Place
downtown is Thursday through Saturday. Tickets: 828-257-4530.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ The 17th Annual Asheville Quilt Competition
and Exhibit will be Friday through Sunday at the North Carolina
Arboretum at Blue Ridge Parkway Milepost 393. 828-285-0318.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Burnsville, N.C. _ The 43rd Annual Mount Mitchell Crafts Fair
is Friday and Saturday on the Square. More than 200 crafts people
showing works including quilts, pottery, woven baskets, blown glass
and woodwork. Entertainment and a food mall. 1-800-948-1632.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brevard, N.C. _ Dr. John and Joshua Redman are headliners for
JAZZ Brevard 12, celebrating a century of jazz Aug. 13-14. The core
of the festival is 12 hours of nonstop music on the grounds of the
Brevard Music Center. Clinics with many of the artists on tap.
Tickets: 1-888-283-4878.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ Biltmore Estate's Summer Evenings Concerts
on the South Terrace overlooking the Blue Ridge Mountains continue
through Aug. 28. The lineup: jazz trumpeter Chuck Mangione
(Saturday); country singer Kathy Mattea and the legendary Doc
Watson (Aug. 14); jazz artists Spyro Gyra and guitarist Earl Klugh
(Aug. 21); and the big band sounds of the Tommy Dorsey Orchestra
(Aug. 28). By reservation only; $35. 1-800-323-6804.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Florence, Ala. _ The W.C. Handy Music Festival through
Saturday celebrates the music of the Florence native known as the
father of the blues. Entertainers include Bill Anschell, Gary
Motley and Roberta Flack. 256-766-7642 or www.wchandyfest.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Anniston, Ala. _ The Anniston Museum of Natural History will
celebrate its 69th birthday Saturday with performances by David
Holt, who has recorded traditional mountain music and Southern folk
tales and won a 1996 Grammy for his recording of ``Stellaluna.''
Animal programs, face painting and tie-dying T-shirts. 256-237-6766
or www.annistonmuseum.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Montgomery _ The Alabama Shakespeare Festival presents ``Lost
Highway: The Music and Legend of Hank Williams'' Aug. 13-Sept. 19.
The play by Mark Harelik and Randal Myler tells the story of one of
country music's most tragic stars through his music. 1-800-841-4273
or www.asf.net.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
