<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Aug. 6:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOKE-CONFIRM (Washington) _ The Senate, 81-16, confirms
Richard Holbrooke as the U.N. ambassador. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ A Senate committee report rebukes the
government's handling of the Chinese espionage investigation,
finding mistakes and missteps ``at all levels of government.''
Sens. Thompson and Lieberman, chair and ranking member of the
panel, release the most detailed report yet on FBI/DOE/DOJ
investigation of Wen Ho Lee, the Los Alamos scientist fired for
security violations. By Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   WARCRIMES-TRIBUNAL (United Nations) _ The U.N. is expected today
to name Carla del Ponte, the Swiss attorney general, to replace
Louise Arbour as chief prosecutor of war crimes tribunal. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   ARMS-SALES (Washington) _ Hurt by Asian economic woes and Saudi
Arabia's weak finances, arms sales around the world fell sharply
last year, but the United States firmed up its role as the world's
leading arms supplier, especially to the developing world, the
Congressional Research Service says. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SECT (Beijing) _ The crackdown on the Falun Gong sect is
turning out to be far less severe than it first looked, with more
propaganda than action. The fierce rhetoric of the official
campaign versus the soft reality points to the resilience of the
Communist Party's political apparatus and, paradoxically, to the
reluctance of the authorities to use it to its fullest extent. By
Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO (Abidjan, Ivory Coast) _ The rebel leader who signed the
cease-fire now rejects it because, he says, a pro-government
bombing raid (by a Sudanese plane) killed 500 people on Wednesday.
By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-CONGRESS (Washington) _ House Democrats and moderate
Republicans are expected to reach an agreement on their own managed
care bill, including a right to sue HMOs, and will challenge the
leadership to bring it to the floor in the fall, saying they have
the votes to pass it. President Clinton goes to the Hill to urge
cooperation this and other issues. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House is set to pass the tax
bill, and we may get a vote in the Senate, late, where the outcome
is less certain, with several Republican moderates on the fence. By
David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   TAX-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on why Republicans
believe deep tax cuts are a political winner and why the Democrats
believe the public doesn't yearn for these tax cuts and fighting
them is good politics. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate may get back to the
Interior spending bill with its riders and amendments favoring
mining, oil, gas and other drilling interests. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ House and Senate conferees meet for
the first time, but decide to postpone their heavy lifting until
September; statements on both sides make clear, however, that they
will carry the issue home and to various bully pulpits; and that
the NRA, which has spent $1.5 million on lobbying since the
Littleton school shootings, will spend that much again through
October. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MORRIS-MISS (Jackson, Miss.) _ Willie Morris is lying in state
in the Capitol today. He was a Southern writer who showed that you
could come home, who wrote about the South with empathy and
understanding, who was accessible to those who would follow the
tradition, if that is even possible today in the New South. By Rick
Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   GRAND-CANYON (Denver) _ After years of analysis and public
debate, officials are announcing a plans to develop the national
forest land south of the Grand Canyon. They have two final choices:
a conservative plan that would cut out only 50 acres for federal
housing and community facilities, and a proposal by a Scottsdale,
Ariz., developer to clear a section four times as big so that
hotels and retail space can be added. Both would also provide 60
acres for a transit center where a new light rail will pick up
canyon-bound visitors. (Summary from wires) By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPACE-STATION (Washington) _ Something on board the
International Space Station seems to have made astronauts feel ill
_ a fact the last crew to visit the station delayed reporting for
weeks. By Warren E. Leary. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BEAR-FRAUD (New York) _ The Securities and Exchange Commission,
the Manhattan District Attorney and Bear Stearns Securities reach a
settlement in the nearly three-year-long investigation into the
firm's role in the 1996 failure of A.R. Baron, a small brokerage
firm that defrauded investors out of $75 million. By Gretchen
Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks fell sharply this morning after the
Labor Department reported that labor costs rose in the second
quarter at their fastest pace since the fourth quarter of 1997.
Productivity growth rose at a 1.3 percent annual rate, a sharper
slowdown than expected. By early afternoon stocks had recovered,
with the Dow up 46 points, the S&AMP;P 500 and NASDAQ little changed.
The 30-year Treasury bond was yielding 6.08 percent. European
markets were lower, with London down 2.22 percent and Frankfurt
down 2.78 percent. Tokyo stocks closed down 1.85 percent, and in
Hong Kong, the Hang Seng was down 2.48 percent. (Story will
elaborate on the economic reports as well as the trading day.) By
Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   TV-STATION-OWNERSHIP (Undated) _ The Federal Communications
Commission is expected to ease today existing restrictions that
prohibit a single company from owning more than one local TV
station in a given market or from owning a TV station and a radio
station in the same market. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   DATA-STARTUPS (Eatontown, N.J.) _ Spurred on by the voracious
global appetite for advanced data services, dozens, perhaps
hundreds, of start-up companies like Tachion Networks are seeking
to supply the new technologies underlying the communications
revolution. What's unusual about the emergence of companies like
Tachion is that unlike Web companies, which have drawn its
management strength from established financial and commercial
enterprises, communications start-ups have had a harder time
drawing from the industry's behemoths. That lack of industry
pollination has been particularly striking in New Jersey, home to
Bell Labs, AT&AMP;T and the Science Applications International
Corporation's Telcordia unit. Should Tachion, based in Eatontown
and with a core of former Bell Labs engineers, be successful, all
that might change. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   SOCGEN-BNP (Rome) _ The takeover battle between Societe Generale
and Banque Nationale de Paris comes to an end on Friday night. It
now appears that BNP will not win a majority of Societe Generale,
while SocGen may not get Paribas, leaving the outcome very much in
doubt. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-EMPOWERMENT (Johannesburg) _ New Africa Investments
Ltd., South Africa's oldest and largest ``black empowerment
company,'' announces a major restructuring plan that will grant
more equitable rights to all shareholders but means the company
will no longer be controlled by blacks. The restructuring may be
the final nail in the coffin of the black empowerment trend here.
By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-TELECOM (Toronto) _ AT&AMP;T and British Telecommunications
will jointly buy a 33 percent in Rogers Cantel Mobile
Communications, Canada's second-biggest wireless company, for about
$900 million (United States), while BT will also buy part of AT&AMP;T's
31 percent stake in AT&AMP;T Canada for about $402 million. By Timothy
Pritchard.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
