<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK-99-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY INTERNET IS HELPING IN WOODSTOCK PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME, N.Y. _ Woodstock '99 concertgoers, outraged at the
behavior of the few hundred who burned and destroyed the venue last
week, are now getting back at them.
</P>
<P>
   As the New York State Police continues to investigate the
crimes, hundreds of people have called or e-mailed tips to the
police about the identity of some of the perpetrators. The police
now have so many leads they've doubled the number of investigators
to 10, are questioning suspects in Virginia and Maryland, and are
considering trips to Pennsylvania, Vermont and parts of New York
state as well.
</P>
<P>
   The police had received 155 tips by e-mail as of Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten many possible leads,'' said State Police Capt.
John Wood. ``We're going to do what we can to make an arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood also said a third person died Sunday from medical problems
that occurred during Woodstock, the musical festival that took
place at a former Air Force base in upstate New York the weekend of
July 23-25. Frank Cooper, 31, of St. Petersburg, Fla., was
hospitalized July 24, and died from complications of both diabetes
and heat-related hyperthermia.
</P>
<P>
   Rioters caused several million dollars in damage at the end of
the three-day Woodstock festival in Rome by tearing down speakers,
setting fire to 12 tractor-trailer rigs and looting vendor booths.
Authorities say less than 500 of the 250,000 concertgoers actually
took part in the mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   Explanations for their behavior have ranged from the heavy music
to the heat, from the high prices of food and water to the three
days worth of garbage that filled the venue.
</P>
<P>
   Since the riot, the police posted 14 photographs on their
Website. More than 4,200 people have logged on to the site,
``www.troopers.state.ny.us.''
</P>
<P>
   The pictures that have generated the most responses are the
clearest _ those that show people breaking into Ace Hardware Store
tractor-trailers, two people smashing and reaching into an ATM
machine and a man trying to break into a pay telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Perpetrators could face charges from misdemeanor larceny charges
to felonies like arson. How serious the charges are would depend on
whether authorities would decide to try to extradite the suspect
from another state, Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have somebody in California who committed an arson that
caused $1.5 million in damage,'' he said, ``I'm quite sure we'll go
out to get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Many concertgoers were angered by the riots. On an Internet
site, discussion of the riot has generated hundreds of responses,
with many of them criticizing the few hundred who took part in the
destruction. When one woman wrote to take credit for setting one of
the fires, another responded that he had forwarded her letter to
the police _ a response applauded by others.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the State Police Internal Affairs is still
investigating allegations that state troopers posed with nude
female concertgoers during the riots. So far, one supervisor has
been suspended. No other officers have so far been implicated, said
Lt. Jamie Mills, a spokeswoman for the police.
</P>
<P>
   Also, cleanup of the Woodstock site continues, with help from
some 20 refugees from the Mohawk Valley Resource Center for
Refugees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
