A6738 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-INVESTORS-HN     08-05 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-INVESTORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS PUMP MONEY INTO NEW INTERNET VENTURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The recent Internet stock woes do not seem to be
slowing down private investors, who are pouring an unprecedented
amount of cash into new Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   According to VentureOne, a venture capital research company in
San Francisco, 565 Internet startups raked in $6.3 billion in
venture capital during the first six months of this year. Venture
capital firms raise and invest money in budding companies in
exchange for stock or other ownership interests. They've been the
major supporters of the burgeoning Internet economy.
</P>
<P>
   The six-month amount exceeded the $5.7 billion invested in
on-line companies during all of 1998. It also topped the amount
that venture capital firms pumped into Internet startups in 1997
and 1996 combined.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of investment continues despite the shaky performance
of stocks of Internet companies, highlighted by this week's
lackluster market debut of four on-line ventures:
1-800-Flowers.com, BigStar Entertainment, Splitrock Services and
Quotesmith.com. All finished their first trading days below their
offering prices.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the stock sag, ``it's full steam ahead on the Internet
as far as venture capitalists are concerned,'' said Rolf Selvig,
director of Business Development at VentureOne.
</P>
<P>
   Selvig said that Internet companies specializing in
business-to-business services were ``very hot'' with venture
capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   According to the VentureOne survey, new on-line companies
accounted for $2.2 billion of the $6.3 billion raised during the
first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists, Selvig added, are unfazed by the current
Internet stock market slouch because they are focusing on the
future, not on an individual company's historical performance.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Golden, a partner in the Palo Alto-based Accel Partners
venture capital firm, said the astounding rate of investment
indicates that, despite a market downturn, the Internet still has a
very bright future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bet is over the long term,'' Golden said. ``We look at
on-line opportunities independent of market cycles. We don't take
one-dimensional snapshots. We look out over the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   The flow of venture capital money into Internet startups was
especially heavy in the second quarter, totally $3.8 billion. That
represented a 170 percent increase over the second quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The VentureOne survey also pointed out how the Internet was
gobbling up private investor dollars. During 1995, $6.3 billion in
venture capital was invested into all U.S. startups. At that time,
Internet companies accounted for only 15 percent of that total.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, startup funding had increased to $13 billion,
and 44 percent went to Internet companies. During the first half of
this year, Internet startups grabbed 55 percent of the $11.4
billion invested in newly public companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
