<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6741 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MY-LAI06-COX     08-05 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MY-LAI06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESSMEN TRIED TO SCUTTLE MY LAI TRIALS, PROSECUTOR SAYS
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democratic leaders of the House Armed Services
Committee tried to scuttle military trials so no American soldiers
would be tried for war crimes in the 1968 My Lai massacre during
the Vietnam War, a former Army prosecutor said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The late Reps. F. Edward Hebert of Louisiana and L. Mendel
Rivers of South Carolina ``decided these trials were detrimental to
the interests of the United States'' and ``calculatingly'' sought
``to sabotage them,'' said William Eckhardt, a retired Army colonel
who served as a prosecutor in several cases stemming from My Lai.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhardt spoke at a publication press conference for ``The
Forgotten Hero of My Lai,'' a biography of Hugh Thompson, the Army
helicopter pilot who, with his crew, has belatedly been credited
with stopping the infamous military operation that killed 504
Vietnamese civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The book details how Hebert and Rivers called virtually everyone
involved in the My Lai incident before their investigating
subcommittee and then classified the testimony. By refusing to
release the accounts of over 100 witnesses to defense attorneys,
the congressmen provided potential grounds for dismissal of charges
against the five soldiers who were court-martialed, Eckhardt
explained.
</P>
<P>
   The legal maneuver failed, but only First Lt. William Calley, a
platoon leader, was convicted. Many Americans considered Calley a
scapegoat and his sentence was eventually reduced to about three
years under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   In their efforts to thwart a trial, the two congressmen also
tried to discredit Thompson, who landed his helicopter between
American soldiers and Vietnamese civilians to stop the killing, the
book says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another key to sabotaging the prosecution was to get Hugh
Thompson,'' Eckhardt recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal case became intertwined with ``a cultural civil
war'' being waged over the Vietnam War, said Eckhardt. The antiwar
movement believed massacres such as My Lai were everyday
occurrences _ which Eckhardt called ``malarkey'' _ and
conservatives such as Rivers and Hebert wrongly assumed American
soldiers would not commit such atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   The 248-page biography, written by Trent Angers, a veteran
Louisiana journalist, traces Thompson's life from his birth in
Atlanta in 1943 through his adolescence in Stone Mountain, Ga., and
his 20-year Army career.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades after the massacre, Thompson and his gunner, Larry
Colburn, received the Soldier's Medal for heroism at a ceremony at
the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington. The other gunner on
the helicopter, Glenn Andreotta, was honored posthumously. He was
killed in Vietnam three weeks after the My Lai incident.
</P>
<P>
   The book concludes that the My Lai killings were only the first
stage of a chilling operation that would have left many more
civilians dead had not Thompson raised a ruckus upon his return to
headquarters that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game plan of Task Force Barker was to permanently get rid
of the Viet Cong from a large area of Quang Ngai Province. My Lai-4
was only the starting point. It was but one subhamlet of one hamlet
in one village in the target area,'' Anger wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were going from village to village to village to clear it
out. There were no provisions for prisoners of war,'' the author
said at the press conference. ``The orders were to kill
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is an authorized biography.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the story of my life,'' said Thompson, who joked that
``it even tells some things I didn't want brought out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Forgotten Hero of My Lai: The Hugh Thompson Story'' is
published by Acadian House Publishing of Lafayette, La.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
