<HEADER>
A6759 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TREK-STAR-WARS-CASTIN     08-05 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-STAR-WARS-CASTING-DIRECTOR-ROBIN-GURLAND-ART-ADV16-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV16 
 INSIDE TREK &AMP; SCI-FI 
 WANTED: ANAKIN SKYWALKER _ AND OTHER PROBLEMS CASTING `STAR WARS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., AUG. 16, 1999) 
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Jake Lloyd
with Liam Neeson and Ewan McGregor in ``Star Wars: The Phantom
Menace.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    So, how did Anakin Skywalker end up on that godforsaken planet,
Tatooine?
 &HT;    Beats us. But how Jake Lloyd wound up there, playing Anakin ...
well, that would be on account of Robin Gurland.
 &HT;    ``It was my job to find all the cast, from the principals down
to the smallest speaking role,'' casting director Gurland says by
telephone from her northern-California office. ``I generally work
with the writer, producer and director _ and in this case they were
one person, George Lucas, which made it very pleasant.
 &HT;    ``My task was to creatively come up with who I felt would be
appropriate for each role,'' she continues. ``After that, it
flipped to the business side of casting, which was dealing with
contract negotiations, scheduling and finalizing the cast.''
 &HT;    Gurland, a veteran casting director, came aboard ``Star Wars:
The Phantom Menace'' as an independent contractor in July 1995. She
remained with the project until April 1999, collaborating with
Lucas through principal photography and the looping process.
 &HT;    Watching the finished film in a theater, Gurland recalls, was a
surreal experience.
 &HT;    ``I usually don't watch films I cast,'' she says, ``because I
come with such a history that it's hard to have an objective eye
when the actors are on screen. Because this film was so
all-encompassing and took a couple of years, I felt like a mother
hen, very protective of my cast and proud of them.''
 &HT;    In casting Qui-Gon, Gurland originally contemplated selecting an
American actor to play a role that needed ``someone like Liam
Neeson.'' But she and Lucas started to focus on Neeson himself,
coincidentally, just as he mentioned in an interview that he was
interested in the project.
 &HT;    Natalie Portman was the first and only choice as Queen Amidala,
Gurland reports, but choosing an Obi-Wan Kenobi was far trickier.
 &HT;    ``Alec Guinness put his imprint on the character,'' Gurland
says. ``We didn't want a spot-on mimic of Guinness. The actor
needed to play Obi-Wan as a young man who will have 30 years of
experience under his belt by the time the films match up.
 &HT;    ``I'd been watching Ewan for a while, and met him even before
`Trainspotting,''' she says. ``He's an amazing actor. He had to
create someone who'd grow into Obi-Wan, and I think Ewan did that
beautifully.''
 &HT;    The most controversial choices were Ahmed Best as Jar Jar Binks
and Lloyd as Anakin. Many fans and most critics detested the Jar
Jar character and were underwhelmed by Lloyd's performance.
 &HT;    ``I think Ahmed brought such life to Jar Jar,'' Gurland says.
``Initially, I was ... not defensive, but I was quite astounded by
the reaction and how people put their own perceptions onto the
film. And how wrong they were.
 &HT;    ``After a couple of months I realized that it was ridiculous,''
she adds, ``that people have to take the film for what it is, and
that I can't worry about what everybody reads into it.
 &HT;    ``I had to let it go and realize what good work was done by
Ahmed within the context of the film,'' she concludes. ``Jar Jar is
a comic-relief character geared to kids, and both in movement and
nuance Ahmed gave him life.''
 &HT;    Gurland discovered Lloyd when he was 5 years old.
 &HT;    ``Jake is breathtakingly beautiful and has an impish, whimsical
quality,'' she says. ``You'd believe he had mechanical skills. He
was just spot-on the character.''
 &HT;    She naturally disagrees with the critics of Lloyd, whom one wag
dubbed ``Mannequin Skywalker.''
 &HT;    ``You're asking the wrong person,'' Gurland replies. ``I'd, of
course, say they're unfair because I brought him into the fold. I
just don't understand what people were looking for and what, beyond
Jake's performance, there could be.
 &HT;    ``To me, with the criticism of the film, I see it as a bigger
issue of how we tend to bring things up just to knock them down,''
she says. ``That sounds cliche and trite, but this film has again
proved that theory.''
 &HT;    Lucas obviously appreciated Gurland's efforts, as she's already
signed to handle the casting for the next two episodes. She expects
to begin sometime in September, after Lucas finishes the next
script.
 &HT;    Lloyd will not be back as Anakin, because the second episode
picks up 10 years after ``Phantom Menace,'' setting up the most
controversial casting search since Scarlett O'Hara.
 &HT;    ``I get about 20 calls a day now,'' Gurland says, laughing.
``I've got people saying, `I've never acted before, and I want to
be your new Anakin.'
 &HT;    ``I'm just now starting to get some agent calls, but I'm telling
everybody that nothing is being done until at least September.''
 &HT;    So those pesky rumors about James Van Der Beek or Leonardo
DiCaprio aren't true?
 &HT;    ``I just shake my head at them,'' Gurland says. ``At first it
would bother me, and I'd want to set the record straight. Now I
just think, `Whatever ... ''' 
 -0- 
 NEXT WEEK  
 &HT;    Charlize Theron talks about ``The Astronaut's Wife.'' 
 -0- 
 SIDEBAR: CONVENTION CALENDAR  
 August 27-29: Canadian Sci-Fi Expo at the Metro Toronto Convention
Center in Toronto, featuring Ray Park, Jeri Ryan and Kenny Baker.
For information, call (416) 761-1760.
 -0- 
