<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6761 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TINA-BROWN-TALK-NYTSF     08-05 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TINA-BROWN-TALK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 TINA'S TALK-ing ... IS ANYBODY LISTENING?  
 &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1999 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   With the exception of the late John Kennedy Jr., Tina Brown is
the most famous magazine editor the world has known in the last few
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is such a pop icon that she was the partial inspiration
for the Kristin Scott-Thomas character in ``The Horse Whisperer,''
the sun-dappled, nine-hour classic in which Robert Redford,
Scott-Thomas and the troubled horse all had the same tasteful
blonde highlights in their respective manes.
</P>
<P>
   She's British. She's fabulous. She's famous. From the New Yorker
to Vanity Fair to the mega-hyped Talk magazine, Brown has displayed
an uncanny genius for promoting herself and her product.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent buzz is, for the most part, warranted. When you
debut your publication with an interview in which a delusional
Hillary Clinton traces her husband's serial philandering to
shouting matches between his mom and grandmama more than four
decades ago, you've got yourself one heckuva ``get.'' (I mean, who
gave Hillary that strategy, Eleanor Roosevelt?)
</P>
<P>
   So everybody is talking about Talk magazine. Dozens of columns,
hundreds of stories, thousands of sound bites.
</P>
<P>
   However, I'm not sure that most of the people who have been
talking about Talk magazine have actually read Talk magazine _ even
though reading, I believe, is still the basic point of a print
publication, even in this age of multimedia symmetry.
</P>
<P>
   The reason most people haven't read it is because it's not
available in 95 percent of the country. In fact it won't be on
newsstands in Chicago until the middle of next week.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but why wait. I'll be glad to share my copy with you.
</P>
<P>
   No need to dwell on the interview with Mrs. Clinton, other than
to suggest that she stop invoking ``vast right-wing conspiracies''
and kitchen table screaming fights from 1952 when rationalizing her
husband's tendency to drop his trousers at the slightest hint of
possible action. How about saying, ``He screwed around but I still
love him, and beyond that it's nobody's business and I'm never
talking about it again''? Real-world voters would appreciate
something like that.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the Clinton feature is only the second-most fascinating
article in the premiere issue. The most insanely intriguing piece
is the profile of the grief-stricken and apparently bonkers
Mohammed Al Fayed, who has become obsessed with solving the
``murder'' of his son Dodi and Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
   According to Al Fayed, the car accident was no accident at all _
it was a carefully orchestrated assassination masterminded by the
``Nazi sympathizer'' Prince Philip and carried out by M16, the
British international intelligence agency, with the help of the
CIA, who provided a built-to-order Fiat that played a key role in
the deadly mission.
</P>
<P>
   Right. Either that, or a drunken limo driver crashed in a tunnel
while trying to avoid a pack of reckless paparazzi.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights of Talk's debut include a chilling report about
the murders of several young girls in a Mexican border town; yet
another profile of the overexposed George W. Bush; several funny
essays; a collection of photos of the young JFK Jr., taken by
renowned photographer Peter Beard in the early 1970s; and lots of
pictures of movie stars, including a two-page color shot of
America's sweetheart, Academy Award winner Gwyneth Paltrow,
fondling a riding crop while wearing a skimpy leather bikini, her
hair swept up in some sort of bizarre
David-Bowie-circa-Ziggy-Stardust deal. (Paltrow's ``Shakespeare in
Love'' was a Miramax film; Miramax is part-owner of Talk. So there
you go.)
</P>
<P>
   Big-name veterans and sharp young talents abound. Tom Stoppard,
Peter Maass, Michael Korda, Christopher Buckley, Martin Amis.
</P>
<P>
   But patience and tenacity are required just to reach the
articles. I waded through nearly 50 pages of advertisements and
mastheads before finally reaching the first feature _ a nearly
incomprehensible photo essay about what to wear ringside at a
championship boxing match. It was another 10 pages of gunk before
``the conversation,'' an opening collection of snippets ``exploring
news and investigating pleasure,'' as the magazine puts it.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the editorial content of Talk is well worth the $2.95
cover price _ even if the supposed European texture and style is
also reminiscent of an old issue of Look _ that is, if Look had
been plagued by overzealous layout artists.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the biggest problem for the debut issue may be too
much Talk too soon. Why blast the world with news of your big scoop
nearly two weeks before most people can buy the thing? By the time
Talk is available worldwide to the very people who will have to buy
it on a regular basis in order for it to survive, we might all be
talking about something else.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times, a commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has
appeared on programs such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News
with Dan Rather,'' ``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1426EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
