<HEADLINE>
`SIXTH SENSE' IS CHILLING, CAPTIVATING, AND BEST SEEN WITHOUT
EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's getting harder and harder to be surprised by a movie these
days. By the time it gets in the theaters, we tend to know
everything about it _ from the millions spent on advertising,
underground word-of-mouth and previews that insist on telling us
every beat of the story.
</P>
<P>
   One of the great things about being a critic, however, is that
you often see movies weeks or even months in advance, and can
actually be surprised by a film, often pleasantly. This definitely
happened to me with the Bruce Willis occult thriller, ``The Sixth
Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be that by the time you see it, all its surprises and its
punch line will be common knowledge, and it simply won't grab you
the way it did me. But, coming in cold, I haven't been so
captivated, chilled and surprised by a movie in years. It strikes
me as the best movie so far in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   So my advice (which I tend to give for only one or two movies a
year) is don't read anything about it or have any expectations one
way or the other. Just go see it, and experience it with as fresh a
perspective as possible under the impossible circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   But, if you must know, it's the story of an acclaimed
Philadelphia child psychologist (Willis) who, in the presence of
his wife (Olivia Williams), is accosted by a now-grown, former
patient he barely remembers, and shot in the stomach just before
the attacker commits suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to the next fall and the doctor, who has not psychologically
recovered from the experience, is now taking on the case of an
eight-year-old boy (Haley Joel Osment) whose symptoms and
alienation are striking similar to that of his attacker _ the
patient he so obviously failed.
</P>
<P>
   So the film is about the doctor seizing a second change, and
trying to find personal redemption by helping a terrified child who
believes he's being visited by ``dead people'' _ ghosts of the
recently deceased who just won't leave him alone.
</P>
<P>
   It's a somber, non-exploitative drama that plays it perfectly
straight, never goes for a cheap thrill, and uncannily creates its
own world _ both the disjointed, impotent world of the doctor, and
the horror-filled, interior world of the traumatized little boy.
</P>
<P>
   Without trying to be, it manages to be an extraordinary chilling
movie. The skill with which it communicates the child's terror and
vulnerability at the hands of his ``ghosts'' is truly eerie. There
are moments in which the hair stood up on the back of my neck, that
actually gave me goosebumps.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of 11-year-old Haley Joel Osment could well be
the most convincingly tortured by a child actor since Patty Duke in
``The Miracle Worker;'' and Willis is almost as good, devoid of his
usual mannerisms, his body slumped in defeat, heartbreakingly
believable.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is so original, and so effective that I was shocked to
find it was directed by M. Night Shyamalan, the young director
whose first Hollywood film, ``Wide Awake,'' struck me as completely
phony, one of the worst films of 1998. It only proves that
directors, like child psychologists, deserve a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixth Sense. Directed and written by M. Night Shyamalan.
Cast: Bruce Willis, Haley Joel Osment, Toni Collette, Olivia
Williams. Hollywood Pictures. 107 minutes. Rated PG-13 for
emotionally intense scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1452EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
