<SLUG> BC-FILM-CROWN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THOMAS CROWN AFFAIR' MAY BE RENE RUSSO'S BEST WORK EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Die-hard fans of the 1969 caper-romance, ``The Thomas Crown
Affair,'' will probably have little use with this 1999 remake,
which lacks the movie-star presence of Steve McQueen as its spark
plug and the original's distinctive blend of voluptuous charm and
'60s cool.
</P>
<P>
   But non-cultists should enjoy what is an engaging and well-acted
retread _ a film that develops its own charm as it goes along, and
ends up being a surprisingly strong star vehicle for Rene Russo,
perhaps even her career best.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 version of Thomas Crown (Pierce Brosnan) is a Wall
Street billionaire so bored by his big success that he embarks on a
secret life of crime _ specifically, the theft of an Impressionist
painting in a caper so complicated it takes up the first 25 minutes
of screen time.
</P>
<P>
   His nemesis is a sexy insurance investigator (Russo) who figures
out straight away that Crown is the mastermind behind the theft,
and spends the movie getting close to him, trying to psyche him
out, lifting the keys to his apartment, looking for evidence, and
so forth.
</P>
<P>
   So the plot is essentially a cat-and-mouse game between this
pair of attractive, perfectly matched opponents, which, of course,
gradually turns into a steamy sexual attraction which inevitably
presents them with a big moral dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   As it does, the weakest link is Brosnan (who also co-produced).
He's a good actor, and he has his own distinctive charm that works
well in the neo-James Bond series. But he's almost too good at
communicating the stiff, suffocating smugness of this arrogant
tycoon character.
</P>
<P>
   Director John McTiernan (``Die Hard'') also lacks any real flair
for the romantic, the appearance of original star Faye Dunaway in
an extended cameo (as Crown's shrink) is clumsy, and the use of the
original's Oscar-winning song, ``Windmills of Your Mind,'' as
background music just makes us want more of it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the film essentially works, and it's the kind of movie
that's become virtually extinct in the '90s: a thriller that tries
to be less a nail-biting action piece as a more leisurely, sexy,
movie-star romance with exotic locations and glamorous settings.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Thomas Crown Affair'' also manages to be a striking
vehicle for Russo. Constantly employed in movies of the last
decade, the ex-supermodel tends to be competent but lackluster.
Here, as the film's confident, single-minded power woman, she
finally comes into her charismatic own.
</P>
<P>
   The Thomas Crown Affair. Directed by John McTiernan. Screenplay
by Leslie Dixon &AMP; Kurt Wimmer. Cast: Pierce Brosnan, Rene Russo,
Denis Leary, Ben Gazarra, Faye Dunaway. Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer. 114
minutes. Rated R for sexual situations and some nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1452EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6800 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-FESTIVAL-HNS &LR;      08-05 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-FESTIVAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL WORK, LITTLE PAY, BUT STAGE CELEBRITIES LOVE WILLIAMSTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL ECK  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. _ Gwyneth Paltrow isn't the only big star
strutting across the lawn of the Adams Memorial Theatre this season
_ not by a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   Ethan Hawke opened the summer in ``Camino Real,'' which also
boasted Blair Brown, Jeffrey Jones and rising star Hope Davis. Bebe
Neuwirth followed suit, lighting up ``The Taming of the Shrew''
along with old ``Cheers'' co-star Roger Rees. And ``Friends'' hunk
David Schwimmer left Ross at home for a chance to put Warren
Leight's latest play, ``The Glimmer Brothers,'' on the boards.
</P>
<P>
   Williamstown, a bucolic college town in western Massachusetts,
has long been a celebrity hang-out, but this summer things feel a
bit different. It feels, perhaps for the first time, as if
Hollywood might be encroaching just a little bit on this quiet gem.
</P>
<P>
   The Festival feels it too, and producer Michael Ritchie says
that he's had to turn down more than a few media requests from
glitzy outfits like ``Entertainment Tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This year,'' Ritchie says, ``quite simply because of having
Gwyneth here and her having won the Oscar, there was a lot of
attention that was thrown at us. All of those people did in fact
call and ask to cover the show and do interviews, and we turned
down all those requests because we don't want to send that kind of
image out. For us it's about the quality of the work and not the
notoriety of the talent we have here.''
</P>
<P>
   The work is what draws actors _ established stars and unknown
hopefuls _ to the festival. Broadway star Karen Ziemba loves the
fact that she can even catch a show in the morning at Williamstown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much going on here,'' Ziemba says, ``from
rehearsals to readings of new plays, from the Mainstage productions
to the cabaret evenings. It's a theatrical oasis.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie says that each performer finds his or her own reason for
heading to the festival. For Paltrow, Williamstown feels like a
second home. Her parents, actress Blythe Danner and director Bruce
Paltrow, have been associated with the festival for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gwyneth grew up here,'' Ritchie says. ``She has an automatic
attachment to the place. This is where she first started acting, so
it's not a big surprise that she would choose to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwimmer, like many, was enchanted by the idea of doing good
work, but getting it done quickly. ``David,'' Ritchie says, ``is a
perfect example of someone who has a limited window of opportunity
to do something that's not on his TV series. Now he could do a
movie, but there are few places that he could do a play where he'd
be able to do the caliber of work that he does and have only a
five-week commitment. Broadway is six months, Off-Broadway is six
months. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Hawke was simply pleased to find a venue so willing to take on a
production as big as ``Camino,'' which required 45 actors and a
running crew of the same size. ``Here you can do something that's
very expensive, has a huge cast and which isn't very commercial,''
Hawke says. ``In New York, `Camino' would cost so much money that
they'd never do it. They couldn't make their money back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At Williamstown we've got all the creative freedom we want
without the hassle of New York,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hot director Scott Ellis (who is helming ``Glimmer Brothers''
and ``The Waverly Gallery'' this season) said in an interview last
year that he likes to get away to the ``beautiful'' Berkshire
Mountains and appreciates the chance to get out of New York during
the dog days.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't hurt,'' Ritchie says. ``It's one of the reasons I
started coming here as a stage manager with my family. ... My wife
(actress and Festival regular Kate Burton) and I literally started
turning down Broadway jobs so that we could take Williamstown jobs
because of what it meant to us as a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, though, the work at Williamstown comes cheap. All
performers sign a stock contract, and Ritchie assures that just
about anyone of note takes a pay cut to appear on the illustrious
Adams Memorial stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesssss,'' he elongates, ``I can guarantee that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the art that gets made every summer is enough of an
attraction in itself _ for everyone from the biggest marquee names
to those in the festival's many training programs (which Ritchie
stresses are a large part of what Williamstown is all about).
</P>
<P>
   Eric Stoltz, who was interviewed when he opened the 1998 season
as Tom in Tennessee Williams' ``The Glass Menagerie,'' waxed
rhapsodic about the festival. ``I love this place,'' Stoltz said.
``If I didn't, I wouldn't be here, and I could be out actually
earning a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Viola Davis, who played Ruth in the just-finished ``A Raisin In
The Sun,'' came for the attitude instead of the paycheck. ``It's a
place where artists can take risks,'' Davis says, ``and still be
supported and nurtured, which is what the creative environment
should be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie brought a pretty impressive Rolodex with him to the
producer's desk, but he's not the only one knocking on doors. Many
of the performers knock on his first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Kind (of television's `Spin City') is a perfect
example'' Ritchie says. ``He picked up the phone last year and
called me and said, `Look, we've never met, but I want you to know
I want to be involved with Williamstown; I've always wanted to be
there.' It was easy for me to say, `Yes, I want you here,' and
luckily I had parts for him. The same thing happened with David
Schwimmer.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Williamstown's best talents _ Paltrow among them _ are
found right within the festival's own ranks. Sam Breslin Wright, a
bright comic actor who nearly stole ``Shrew'' from Neuwirth and
Rees with a bravo-winning monologue, worked his way up through the
training programs, eventually getting his Actor's Equity card from
the company just this season. Ritchie says that even the biggest
names get a kick out of helping upstarts like Wright.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones that are new to the festival, I think, find it
surprising. You get a great a sense of responsibility to the young
actors, a sense of passing on the knowledge of the craft. ``It's
surprising how little ego is shown here when there could be a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie firmly believes that the festival could get by on that
new talent alone if it had to, but luckily it doesn't. He says the
smaller Nikos Stage sells out on its own power. The Mainstage stays
close to capacity on strength of reputation and choice of material
as well. Star power, he figures, is like the beautiful Berkshire
ambience _ it doesn't hurt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1453EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
