<SLUG> BC-FILM-MYSTERY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MYSTERY MEN' INCORRIGIBLY JUVENILE AND WAY TOO LONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many movies derived from comic books and aiming for a state
of inspired silliness, ``Mystery Men'' must have seemed magically
goofy on storyboards, but has somehow turned into an unappealing
mush by the time it made it to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a Dark Horse comic series, it's a farce about a band of
incompetent, wannabe superheroes who finally get their chance at
the big time when Champion City's ace crime fighter, Captain
Amazing (Greg Kinnear), is kidnapped by the arch villain, Casanova
Frankenstein (Geoffrey Rush).
</P>
<P>
   The would-be rescuers includes The Shoveler (William H. Macy),
who dispatches baddies with dirt shovels; The Blue Raja (Hank
Azaria), who wears a turban and hurls forks through the air; and
The Furious (Ben Stiller), whose seething rage is his empowering
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting more personnel for the big fight, they add The Bowler
(Janeane Garofalo), who wields a deadly bowling ball; The Spleen
(Paul Reubens), a master of debilitating flatulence; and Invisible
Boy (Kel Mitchell), who is only invisible if no one looks at him.
</P>
<P>
   And when they find a guru in advanced crime-fighting techniques
in the form of The Sphinx (Wes Studi), and take on an arsenal of
secret weapons given them by eccentric inventor Dr. Heller (Tom
Waits), they become the Magnificent Seven of superheroes.
</P>
<P>
   As directed by first-time filmmaker Kinka Usher, the proceedings
are filled with special effects, over-the-top performances,
future-noirish visuals and one campy situation after another that
combine to take the themed-crimefighter idea to its ultimate absurd
extreme.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes a special flair to make a souffle like this rise _
the kind of touch Tim Burton gave the first ``Batman,'' for
instance _ and Usher (whose background is in TV commercials)
apparently doesn't have the gift: His movie just seems incorrigibly
juvenile and way, way too long.
</P>
<P>
   Mystery Men. Directed by Kinka Usher. Written by Neil Cuthbert.
Cast: Ben Stiller, Hank Azaria, William H. Macy, Geoffrey Rush,
Greg Kinnear, Paul Reubens, Janeane Garofalo, Tom Waits, Kel
Mitchell. Universal. 120 minutes. Rated PG-13 for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1453EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
