<SLUG> BC-FILM-TRICK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRICK' BELONGS ON NEXT TIER OF GAY-THEMED MOVIES THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally _ a trick that's an infectiously engaging treat.
</P>
<P>
   We've been privvy to some good, gay-themed coming-of-age movies
this year. ``Edge Of 17'' and ``Get Real'' provided a positive
platform for gentle, non-threatening but edgy comedies that don't
shirk responsibility to their protagonists' personal voyages of
self-discovery because of sexual preference. But they don't push
too many safety buttons either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trick'' belongs on the next tier. Its sweet, idealistic hero
is already ``out.'' He's a reluctant musician living in one of
those nasty, scum-crusted studio flats in downtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is, his gayness isn't a problem for anybody but him.
For Gabriel (Christian Campbell, the sweet-faced look-alike brother
of ``Scream'' queen Neve Campbell), being gay seems to mean being
doomed to live life alone. He's tired of sleeping in the hall when
his shallow heterosexual roommate gets lucky. One night, after Gabe
auditions some of his Andrew Lloyd Webber-type songs with his best
friend, aspiring actress and ex-girlfriend Katherine (Tori
Spelling), his previously dismal luck suddenly shifts.
</P>
<P>
   In a moment of loneliness, Gabe hits a local gay bar. Dancing on
the counter is gorgeous go-go boy, Mark (J.P. Pitoc). The spark is
instantaneous. And in the next eight hours, Gabe will suffer from
inadequacy, anger, jealousy, fear, happiness and peace in Mark's
presence.
</P>
<P>
   Director Jim Fall, who has worked primarily on the New York
stage, ingeniously weaves his panorama of gay and straight
characters, resulting in the running joke that no matter where Gabe
and Mark turn in a city as huge as Manhattan, they can't find a
place where they can be alone. Will they or won't they? Who cares
... the spark they strike incites everyone around them to reunite,
break up, sleep, wake up and tell the truth for a change.
</P>
<P>
   Trick. Directed by Jim Fall. Written by Jason Schafer. Cast:
Christian Campbell, John Paul Pitoc, Tori Spelling. Fine Line
Features. 90 minutes. Rated R for language, nudity, sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6808 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-OZAWA-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     08-05 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-OZAWA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  
 LENOX, Mass.: ... ``Peter Grimes.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The BSO ``Elektra'' and ``Pique-Dame'' were released on CDs, and
Ozawa has conducted recorded performances with other orchestras of
``Salome'' and ``Carmen'' with Jessye Norman and Offenbach's ``Les
Contes d'Hoffmann.'' Some of these works have also been seen at the
Saito Kinen Festival, where Ozawa led Poulenc's ``Les Dialogues des
Carmelites'' and a famous televised production of Stravinsky's
``Oedipus Rex'' that was designed by Julie Taymor.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, Ozawa has also conducted other works not associated
with him in Europe or America, in an annual series of operas with
the New Japan Philharmonic sponsored by Hennessey cognac _ there he
has led such works as ``The Barber of Seville,'' ``Manon Lescaut,''
``The Magic Flute,'' and ``Der fliegende Hollaender.''
</P>
<P>
   What has eluded Ozawa are some of the major works of Mozart,
Verdi, and Wagner; conductors these days are often typecast _ no
one would think of asking Ozawa to conduct ``Peter Grimes,'' a work
he led more convincingly than some of the British conductors who
specialize in Britten. None of the Vienna repertory has been set
for Ozawa yet, but there are definitely things he wants to do. ``I
have never conducted Berg's `Wozzeck' in the theater, but we did it
in Boston, and Hildegard Behrens, who sang Marie, says it was the
best `Wozzeck' she was ever in. I have learned Berg's `Lulu' and
never conducted it, and I once spent five months learning
Schoenberg's `Moses und Aron' for a production that was canceled.
My car was broken into then, and the only thing that was taken was
my score to `Moses und Aron'! I was once offered Wagner's `Ring'
Cycle, but I couldn't make that commitment of time over a period of
three years, but now I want very much to do it. ''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the subject of his departure from Boston in 2002,
Ozawa says, ``I didn't want to go down; everything in Boston must
always be going up. Until my very last day I want to be the music
director here, and I must be very strong; the first thing I am
asking of myself and of the orchestra is that these next three
years must be the very best of our time together. We are also
behind in commissioning new works, so I must give that a kick.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa says the decision to leave was ``difficult and sad. Both
for my family and for me Boston and Tanglewood have been a major
part of our lives. I know my feelings about this orchestra will
never change. I used to say that the relationship between a music
director and an orchestra was like a marriage, and forever, but now
I think the relationship is more like that of a family, which is
permanent and important in a different way. I think the orchestra
and I understand each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa bridles at the suggestion by some out-of-town critics that
the orchestra is currently in a state of disarray. ``We have some
wonderful new players now, a new first viola, a new first horn, a
new first flute, and they have changed the whole situation. There
are so many young strong players in the orchestra now, and I think
the orchestra is wonderful. I do not conduct so many orchestras
now, but I do conduct the Berlin Philharmonic and the Vienna
Philharmonic, and I think the Boston standard holds up _ this
orchestra has character, the way those do, and the character of the
Boston Symphony is something that I love. Boston has its own color,
and it never pushes; the musicians never become rough _ they hear
well and they blend well. Of course, like every orchestra we are
sometimes up, sometimes down, but it never comes down below Boston
Symphony standard. Only the greatest orchestras can do what the
Boston Symphony does at its best, as it did in our big tour
performances of Mahler's Third and Sixth symphonies. We can't do
that every day, but that's impossible. If people do not agree,
that's OK, but I don't understand what they are talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also surprised by the amount of covert and even overt
anti-Asian condescension that surfaced in some of the commentary
greeting the announcement of his departure. ``In the beginning,
yes, I was very aware of this problem, but it is something I have
not felt for many years, especially when I conduct in Berlin or
Vienna. But I know it will not stop until I die; I know I am a test
case. Everyone wonders how much I can learn, how much I can
understand. But the problems I have had have always ended in a
positive way. I have always enjoyed learning, and I still do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Changes at Tanglewood
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa has few regrets about the major controversy that has
dominated the last few years, the changes he has implemented at the
Tanglewood Music Center. ``It was my responsibility to do this.
There was some hot stuff to take, but I'm glad I did it, and now I
still have time, three years more, to drive the Music Center along
toward new levels. The school has started a whole new era, and
needs all the energy I can give to it. I hope I can continue a
relationship with the school, but I cannot invite myself, and I
don't want to be a Tanglewood ghost. If the music director invites
me, I will happy to do anything he asks me to.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of gratitude to his own mentors, Ozawa has become profoundly
committed to teaching. ``Conducting is not so easy, you know. You
have to be a good musician to begin with, and then you need the
tools to become a conductor _ and that's not something you can
learn in a room by yourself. When I was studying with Hideo Saito,
I was his only student, and I conducted every single week from the
time I was 16 or 17, starting with a string quartet playing
symphonies by Haydn and Mozart and later pieces like the
Tchaikovsky `Serenade for Strings.' I was so lucky. These days
there is not much chance for a young conductor to have the kind of
training I did, anywhere in the world. To be fair to the next
generation, I want to create this kind of chance for young people.
Today they all find the CD and listen to it, but to be a conductor
you have to understand things inside of you; you have to find the
next level within yourself. Music is this really big thing, and you
have to come up to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1456EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6811 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-OZAWA-2TAKES-AR     08-05 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-OZAWA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OZAWA, ON THE RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENOX, Mass. _ While the city of Boston was joining its symphony
orchestra in celebrating Seiji Ozawa's 25 seasons as music director
last fall, Ozawa himself was holding quiet conversations with his
wife, Vera, about when the right time to leave would come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking with my wife about how I wanted to teach,''
Ozawa said in an interview in his home near Tanglewood a week ago.
``I want to help the Saito Kinen Orchestra and Festival grow in
Japan, and I want to guest-conduct instead of attending all the
meetings a music director has to go to. Every year in Boston, my
contract is renewed for another three years; I thought maybe this
September, or a year from this September, would be a good time to
say I would plan to leave in three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa's decision to accept the music directorship of the Vienna
State Opera came as a surprise to everyone in Symphony Hall, and it
came as a surprise to him _ Ozawa was not looking for another
full-time job. ``I went to Vienna to conduct Tchaikovsky's
`Pique-Dame' right after the Boston Symphony Orchestra tour last
spring. I went on to China, but the orchestra didn't, because the
end of the tour was canceled because of the bombing of the Chinese
embassy in Belgrade. While I was in Vienna, I was approached about
the job, and my first reaction was to say no. But then they changed
many things in order to suit me. As I said, I would never think of
going to another orchestra after the Boston OZAWA, Page N13 &QL; 
Symphony. But before I die, I want to taste more opera, so this
seemed like a not so bad idea after all. It all happened within two
or three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa's unpretentious home in the Berkshires was the scene of
many family-oriented activities during his tenure as music
director; his children grew up alongside the Boston Symphony, and
Tanglewood was one of the family's favorite parts of the job. Son
Yukyoshi, 24, was born after Ozawa became music director; he is now
a popular actor in Japan, where he's busy promoting his first
movie, which has just been released.
</P>
<P>
   Yukyoshi's basketball court at the end of the driveway here was
looking a little folorn, but the nearby gardens were flourishing.
Ozawa's daughter Seira, 26, did pop downstairs for a moment;
working toward a career as a stage director in opera, she is also a
writer and journalist whose current assignment is to write a story
for a leading Japanese magazine _ the subject is Tanglewood. Ozawa
settled down on a corner of the white living room couch and poured
tea, avoiding the fresh lemon-rind cookies until his interviewer
had seriously diminished the supply.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa was thoroughly well trained in music before he left Japan
for the first time to participate in the Besancon conducting
competition in France in 1959 _ the event that brought him into the
orbit of the Boston Symphony Orchestra, because one of the judges
was BSO music director Charles Munch, who invited him to enter the
conducting program at Tanglewood.
</P>
<P>
   Opera, however, represented a whole new world to Ozawa when he
arrived in Europe. ``Opera is something we did not have in Japan.
The first opera I ever saw was in Vienna in 1959, `The Marriage of
Figaro,' conducted by Maestro von Karajan. I remember he also
played the recitatives at the keyboard. I was the guest of a very
distinguisehd Japanese lady who had been a friend of my teacher,
Hideo Saito, and she also took me to the Opera Ball. I had to rent
everything I wore, including the white gloves, which I hated. I
didn't even have shoes _ I was riding around Europe on my
motorscooter.''
</P>
<P>
   The first opera Ozawa conducted was Verdi's ``Rigoletto'' in a
concert performance by the Toronto Symphony, during the early years
of his first music directorship (1965-69); he remembers that Reri
Grist and George Shirley were in the cast. His first staged opera
was Mozart's ``Cosi fan tutte'' at the Salzburg Festival a little
later.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Sleepy Seiji'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I did that because Herbert von Karajan asked me to, but I was
crazy to try it. The previous summer I had been his assistant on a
production of `Don Giovanni' in Salzburg _ Mirella Freni and
Nicolai Ghiaurov were both in it, and that was when they met; later
they got married. I played the piano for the singers and even
conducted in rehearsals because Maestro von Karajan was staging the
opera and couldn't stop directing and working on the lighting. I
did not know how the opera house worked at all. I couldn't see
anything at all because I would spend the morning playing tennis in
the sun and then go into the production, which was so dark. One day
I must have drunk some beer at lunchtime, and everyone was talking
in German and it was dark and cool, so I just feel asleep and
missed a cue. My nickname that summer became `Sleepy Seiji' _
Mirella still remembers that and teases me about it. Maestro von
Karajan was furious with me, but he did ask me to conduct `Cosi fan
tutte' the next summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa remembers that the cast included Walter Berry and that
Teresa Stratas sang Despina; Jean-Pierre Ponnelle directed. ``This
was the beginning of my life in the opera, and at the first
performance I made a terrible mistake _ I forgot to give the
orchestra a bow, and the orchestra committee came and paid a formal
call on me to complain. I am surprised that they did not fire me.
Some of the players from that time are still in the orchestra.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Ozawa made another important debut, at La Scala,
conducting his first ``Tosca.'' Karajan, who had encouraged him
with ``Cosi,'' knew the pitfalls of Puccini's opera, and thought
Ozawa was crazy _ he even called Ozawa's manager and said, ``What
are you thinking of?'' The manager replied, ``Where do you want him
to learn Italian opera _ in Germany?'' ``I did this,'' Ozawa
recalls, ``because Luciano Pavarotti said to me, `Seiji, you do.'
But Maestro von Karajan said, `Seiji, you are going to be cooked.'
Raina Kabaivanska, who was a very prima donna then, was supposed to
be Tosca, and she was going to wear Maria Callas's costume at the
opening performance, which was on television. But she got sick
during rehearsals, so Eva Marton sang. Kabaivanska showed up for
the telecast, saying `This performance is mine,' only nobody told
me _ I found out when I heard a new voice singing `Mario, Mario'
offstage. Everything in the performance was different from what I
had rehearsed with the other soprano. At the end, I was booed for
the first time in my life. My mother, who had come to cook for me,
thought it was another Italian way of saying `Bravo.' But the
orchestra played fantastic for me, and by the third performance we
had a triumph.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa has conducted opera since then in Paris, Vienna, and in
Japan, and in 1980 he inaugurated a regular series of semistaged
opera productions at Tanglewood and in Symphony Hall _ among the
works he has conducted with the Boston Symphony are Gluck's
``Orfeo,'' Beethoven's ``Fidelio,'' Puccini's ``Tosca'' and
``Madama Butterfly,'' Mozart's ``Idomeneo,'' Berg's ``Wozzeck,''
Strauss's ``Salome'' and ``Elektra,'' Stravinsky's ``The Rake's
Progress,'' Tchaikovsky's ``Eugen Onegin'' and ``Pique-Dame,''
Honegger's ``Jeanne d'Arc au Bucher,'' and Verdi's ``Falstaff.'' At
the Tanglewood Music Center he conducted Poulenc's ``Les Mamelles
de Tiresias'' and great performances of Britten's ``Peter Grimes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
