<HEADER>
A6816 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-NOTES06-COX     08-05 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pioneer, Presley the winning touch
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter Matthiessen's novel about infamous Florida pioneer Edgar
J. Watson and Peter Guralnick's biography of Elvis Presley are this
year's winners of the Southern Book Awards presented by the
Southern Book Critics Circle.
</P>
<P>
   The fiction winner, ``Bone by Bone'' (Random House, $26.95), is
the final volume in a trilogy about a real-life desperado that
began with ``Killing Mr. Watson'' and continued with ``Lost Man's
River.'' Drawing on a few sketchy facts about the real Watson, a
back-country South Carolina farmer who became a legend on the
lawless frontier of turn-of-the-century Florida, Matthiessen
created a compelling and at times horrifying portrait of a
cold-blooded killer.
</P>
<P>
   Matthiessen, who lives on Long Island, is the author of more
than two dozen works of fiction and nonfiction, including ``At Play
in the Fields of the Lord'' and ``The Snow Leopard,'' which won the
National Book Award.
</P>
<P>
   Guralnick's ``Careless Love: The Unmaking of Elvis Presley''
(Little, Brown &AMP; Co., $27.95), a sequel to the 1994 biography
``Last Train to Memphis,'' chronicles the last half of the singer's
career. The Boston writer and music historian is the author of
``Lost Highway'' and ``Sweet Soul Music.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Book Critics Circle, a group of book editors and
reviewers at newspapers and magazines in the South, also will honor
writer Eudora Welty with its Distinguished Achievement Award.
Awards will be presented Oct. 8 at the Southern Festival of Books
in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Film rights: The big book-to-film deal this year is Dino De
Laurentiis' $10 million purchase of Thomas Harris' novel
``Hannibal,'' but other literary works are headed for the big
screen as well. Robert Altman is at work on the film version of
musician Artie Shaw's autobiography; Oprah Winfrey is ready to
begin filming Janet Fitch's ``White Oleander''; John Boorman, who
brought ``Deliverance'' to the screen, is planning a new version of
Jack London's ``The Sea Wolf''; and ``Fargo'' directors Joel and
Ethan Coen are exploring the possibility of a dialogue-free
adaptation of James Dickey's novel ``To the White Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In the works: ``Les Miserables'' producer Cameron Mackintosh
plans to make a musical from John Updike's novel ``The Witches of
Eastwick.'' The debut would be in London next spring, according to
Publishers Weekly. ... Cary Stayner confessed to the Yosemite
murders on July 26, and already there's a true crime book scheduled
for September. Author Carlton Smith signed the deal with St.
Martin's Press. ... Hyperion Books has bought two more celebrity
books: Country singer Loretta Lynn will do a sequel to
``Coalminer's Daughter'' and comedian Bill Cosby will give his
views on the changing nature of families in ``Now What?'' ... With
``'Tis,'' Frank McCourt's sequel to ``Angela's Ashes,'' hitting the
stores in September, brother Malachy McCourt has sold ``Singing Him
His Song,'' his sequel to ``A Monk Swimming,'' to HarperCollins for
a mid-six figures.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the Web: Atlanta native Mark Pendergrast will be featured
at 1 p.m. Tuesday on CNN's recently launched interactive Web site,
CNN.com/chat. Pendergrast, the author of ``For God, Country and
Coca-Cola'' (1993), tackles another favorite beverage in his latest
book, ``Uncommon Grounds: The History of Coffee and How It
Transformed the World'' (Basic Books, $27.50). In addition to
Pendergrast, a dozen other authors in five different genres are
available to answer questions on an ongoing basis at
CNN.com/Asktheauthor. Among those are horror novelist Lois Duncan
(``I Know What You Did Last Summer'') and mystery novelists Walter
Sorrells (``Cry for Justice'') and Ridley Pearson (``Pied Piper'').
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
