<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIANT-BIRD06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As the nation copes with gun violence, Brad Bird's `The Iron
Giant' examines the struggle of good and evil
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he started work on his film in late 1996, director Brad
Bird couldn't know that ``The Iron Giant'' would have such
unexpected resonance by the time it hit screens today.
</P>
<P>
   Adapting the tale of a huge robot from outer space, Bird changed
the story line of Ted Hughes' children's book to ask a question
that's both childlike and adult: What if a gun had a soul?
</P>
<P>
   That's a climactic struggle in Bird's stylish, PG-rated film, as
the big metal man struggles between his pre-programmed warfare
impulses and his wish to be a peace-loving hero like Superman.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's anti-gun stance arrives in the shellshocked days
following spree shootings in Colorado, Conyers and, only a week
ago, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think no one anticipates these kinds of horrifying specific
things,'' Bird says during a visit here only a day after the
shootings in Buckhead. He adds that his movie is less about gun
control than a consideration of the human struggle between good and
evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of whether or not to act upon your darker
instincts goes back to the beginning of time,'' he says. ``People
lock onto the gun aspect of the movie, but I think really what
you're dealing with is whether to use your own power to destroy
things or to heal them. We all have tremendous potential to affect
things in a negative way. That's a curse of having a brain.''
</P>
<P>
   In case ``Iron Giant'' sounds like a heavy, moralizing movie,
don't worry, it's not. Deviating from the familiar Disney formula
(``five songs and a story we've heard 5,000 times,'' in Bird's
words), the stylish, witty Warner Bros. movie takes place in 1950s
Maine, where Cold War fears and ``duck and cover'' nuclear attack
drills are in full swing.
</P>
<P>
   In creating the jazzy visual of the picture, Bird and his
animators looked at Norman Rockwell's Saturday Evening Post covers,
Thomas Hart Benton paintings and 1950s magazine illustrations and
comic books. ``I wish I could say it was a superintellectual
process,'' he says. ``It wasn't. We had to move very quickly. We
had about half the time and about a third of the money that our
friends at DreamWorks and Disney have.''
</P>
<P>
   The upside of those limitations was a freedom to take creative
risks, while at the same time trying to make the movie look as good
as possible. ``We didn't want our limited resources to be an excuse
for not doing a big film,'' he says. ``We killed ourselves to get
every last dime up on the screen and make it work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing to go from our budget was sleep. If you cut
sleep, you can be quite efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   While still a high schooler, Bird was mentored by Milt Kahl, one
of Disney's famous band of animators known as the Nine Old Men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Disney deserves every ounce of success they've had,''
he says. ``They worked hard to develop their (animation) teams
through successes and failures, and their commitment to animation
is deep. But I don't think Disney films are the only way to make
them, and a lot of bad animated films have been made trying to
chase Disney's tail.''
</P>
<P>
   With ``Iron Giant,'' Bird says he hopes to show that there's
more than one formula for animation. ``I'm anxious not only to
widen the notion that every animated feature has to be fine for
your 5-year-old, but I'm also hoping we can do quality films that
go in new directions.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in his career, he came up with the idea that turned into
the ``Family Dog'' animated segments on Steven Spielberg's
``Amazing Stories,'' and went on to be creative consultant on ``The
Simpsons'' and ``King of the Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 42, the filmmaker takes time to acknowledge the executives
at Warner Bros., who didn't try to pull the plug on ``Iron Giant''
when they saw that it didn't have Disney-style songs and comic
sidekicks. ``Usually with a studio, every time you try to do
something different they flinch,'' he says. ``They always say
they're looking for something new, but when you give it to them
they start whining, `You didn't tell me you were gonna do something
new.'''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
