<HEADER>
A6848 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-GIANT06-COX     08-05 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-GIANT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With smart story and a distinctive look, animated `Iron Giant'
stands tall
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Family films have been looking up of late. ``October Sky'' had a
soaring script about young rocketeers, and Disney's ``Tarzan''
portrayed the tree-swinging ape-man with the greatest of glee. Now
comes the animated, early-space-age flick ``The Iron Giant.'' It's
another swell kids' movie with enough smarts to keep parents fixed
in their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Appealingly filmed by animator Brad Bird, whose resume runs the
gamut from Disney to ``The Simpsons,'' ``Iron Giant'' is an unusual
yet eye-filling mix of 1950s Disney, '60s Astro-Boy and a dash of
'90s Japanimation. It works.
</P>
<P>
   The time is 1957. Sputnik is puttering around in space while,
back on Earth, children are being told that, in the case of a
nuclear attack, they should ``duck and cover.'' One starry night, a
UFO crashes in rural Maine. It turns out to be a gigantic iron
robot that eats metal. Almost electrocuted when he stumbles into
some power lines, the giant is saved by _ and subsequently
befriended by _ 9-year-old Hogarth Hughes (voiced by Eli
Marienthal).
</P>
<P>
   But his trail of munched-on tractors, trucks and grain silos
hasn't gone unnoticed. A paranoid government agent _ the kind of
false-hearted guy who insists on calling Hogarth ``champ'' or
``chief'' or ``slugger'' _ is soon snooping around and causing
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iron Giant,'' based on a book by the late Ted Hughes
(named Britain's poet laureate in 1984 and husband of poet Sylvia
Plath), has many things going for it besides its distinctive
animation style.
</P>
<P>
   For one, it achieves what last year's mega-hyped ``Godzilla''
got across only in its trailers: namely, an awe-inspiring sense of
size. Using perspective and a bright palette of autumn colors, Bird
shows us his giant towering over the surrounding countryside. This
thing isn't just big; it's humongous.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Bird's humor, especially his lighthearted depiction of
the era's ``duck and cover'' instructions, is laugh-out-loud funny.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the vocal talent is well-cast. Along with Marienthal
(who has a distinctive ``Babe''-like crack in his voice), we hear
Jennifer Aniston as Hogarth's beleaguered single mother, Vin Diesel
as the Iron Giant and Harry Connick Jr. as a beatnik with seductive
Elvis eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It's a heartwarming trip far, far away from the embarrassingly
funny escapades of those potty-mouthed ``South Park'' tykes.
</P>
<P>
   One tip for '90s parents: There's a kind of
``Bambi''/``Starman'' moment, but kids can probably handle it. Just
be aware.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iron Giant''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of Jennifer Aniston and Harry Connick Jr.
Directed by Brad Bird. Rated PG for mild violence. At metro
theaters. 1 hour, 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Nice story for kids, nifty look for adults.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
