<HEADER>
A6851 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-THOSCROWN06-CO     08-05 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-THOSCROWN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Russo steals the spotlight in sexy `Thomas Crown'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Windmills of Your Mind'' is still on the soundtrack, in
subdued jazz mode. But the big hats, the seductive chess game, and
even the bank are gone from the remake of ``The Thomas Crown
Affair.'' Good riddance.
</P>
<P>
   The revamp from director John McTiernan (``Die Hard'') appraises
the 1968 Steve McQueen-Faye Dunaway caper flick for what it was: a
lively, sexy piece of junk whose main purpose was to give
moviegoers a taste of livin' large. Thirty-one years later,
McTiernan and his screenwriters know it's the same thing. Sure, we
want to find out if billionaire Thomas Crown (Pierce Brosnan) will
get away with his part-time hobby of stealing priceless
impressionist paintings, or if solo investigator Catherine Banning
(Rene Russo) will pin the theft on him, before, during or after
their extended sex scene in his lavish townhouse.
</P>
<P>
   But really, that townhouse is the real reason for the movie. Oh,
yeah, and the tropical island getaway he whisks Catherine to. And
that sheer, no-underwear dress Catherine wears to the black-tie
ball. (Likewise, last year's ``A Perfect Murder'' gave equal
attention to the villain's motives and to his Fifth Avenue bathroom
fixtures and collection of modern art.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Crown'' is a guilt-free pleasure, a way to waste a couple of
hours happily at the theater without encountering
computer-generated monsters or teenagers losing their virginity.
The movie's most brazen notion is its faith that anyone over 30
goes to the movies. And that anyone over 40 can still be a sex
symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes almost too discreet for the movie's sense of big-label
fun, Brosnan still makes an appealing gentleman rogue. But the
movie really belongs to Russo, whose pleasure is almost palpable as
she prowls around the screen savoring a smart, sexed-up character
who's not above sunbathing nude for the audience's prurient
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Only purists of 1960s melancholy chic will mind that the remake
noodles with the original's ending. But there's campy compensation
in a supporting role by Dunaway as Crown's therapist, chortling her
way through the film (and through a very thick filter on the lens).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thomas Crown Affair''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Pierce
</P>
<P>
   Brosnan and Rene
</P>
<P>
   Russo. Rated R for sexuality and language. 1 hour, 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A guilt-free summer diversion.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
