<HEADER>
A6886 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-E-COMMERCE-FRAUD-HNS &LR;      08-05 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-FRAUD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERVICES EMERGE TO PROTECT ON-LINE COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBY McGILL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mirroring the explosion of electronic commerce
nationwide, there has been a growth of organizations specializing
in on-line consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Washington-based Internet Fraud Watch, the
number of fraud complaints about Internet commerce jumped from
1,280 in 1997 to 7,752 last year. While the Federal Trade
Commission has acknowledged the problem, the agency says Internet
fraud is not among its top complaints. This makes on-line consumer
groups an important alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Bojana Fazarinc heads the San Francisco chapter of the Better
Business Bureau Online (www.bbb.org). BBBO, based in Arlington,
Va., follows the same model established by its parent, the
87-year-old Better Business Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The BBBO says its mission is to ``promote trust and confidence
on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Fazarinc says the primary challenge facing the BBBO is the
relative anonymity of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (on-line businesses) can put up their shingle without any
ability for the customer to confirm that they really exist and that
they will be there when there is a problem with a product or a
service,'' Fazarinc said.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Communications, a New York-based research group,
estimates that e-commerce sales will approach $12 billion for all
of 1999 compared with $7.1 billion in 1998. Jupiter predicts that
e-commerce sales will mushroom to $41.1 million by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   According to Russ Bodoff, senior vice president and chief
operating officer of the BBBO, businesses eager to get a slice of
the huge market can gain credibility among consumers by joining his
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Members must adhere to a code of business practices set forth by
the BBBO, such as truth in advertising and full disclosure of
privacy policies. If a company disregards its policies as stated to
the customer, it forfeits the right to display the BBBO seal of
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Member companies have to pay BBBO to be listed. Bodoff said that
annual memberships range from ``a few hundred dollars'' for small
businesses, to as high as $5,000 for larger corporate members.
</P>
<P>
   Bodoff said the organization has about 3,600 member businesses,
including industry giants Microsoft, AT&AMP;T and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   BBBO is not the only cop on the e-commerce beat. Others include:
</P>
<P>
   _ FlimFlam.com (www.flimflam.com), a nonprofit Web site that
monitors on-line scams and distributes the information to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   _ ICAB (www.isitsafe.com) allows consumers to submit a company's
URL for approval. If the URL is not listed, ICAB will research the
company and post the result.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
