<HEADER>
A6894 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-COOLTREATS-COX     08-05 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COOLTREATS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fresh fruit . a little imagination needed to create splendid
summer desserts.
 &HT;    By Jan Norris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mangoes drop like red-orange bombs in the back yard.
Passionfruits and lychees are ripe for the picking.
</P>
<P>
   Along comes a chef with a cool dessert in mind. In this case,
it's Mike Perrin, chef-owner of 11 Maple Street in Jensen Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Add his organic herb garden and intuitive creativity, and you
have a sweet, tropical ending for a meal.
</P>
<P>
   Take his coconut sorbet, set among the petals of a sliced
medjool date. He scents it with lemon balm, and perches it atop a
macadamia nut crumble. A few strawberry-infused tuiles add crunch
and color, while a drizzle of maple syrup tops off this tower of
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you have a backyard Eden in full fruit, or you buy your
fruits from a roadside stand, you can follow Perrin's lead and turn
them into cool, refreshing desserts that make you forget the heat.
(Save those heavy chocolate concoctions for cooler weather.) Many
of the summer fruits or berries will work; they don't have to be
tropical.
</P>
<P>
   The chef's one lament about the seasonal fruits is having no
fresh figs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't be in for a few weeks,'' Perrin said. ``I'd prefer
those instead of the dates, but the dates are nice and have a good
texture contrast for the sorbet.''
</P>
<P>
   But substituting figs for dates is just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   You can lose the strawberry and add lemon to the tuiles _ or use
lemon instead of coconut in the sorbet. Or make a passionfruit
coulis instead
</P>
<P>
   In Perrin's tropical pancakes and passionfruit with mango
mousse, the coconut is used in the crepe-like pancakes.
Passionfruits perch atop them, and are filled with the creamy mango
mousse. Passionfruit is in the coulis here for color, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fruits really are versatile,'' Perrin said. ``They have a
lot of distinctive flavors.''
</P>
<P>
   Home cooks can use all or only a few of his ideas. For instance,
you can make the coconut sorbet, and use it to fill a sponge
jellyroll. Serve the pinwheel-like slices with a mango sauce or
chutney.
</P>
<P>
   Take the coconut pancakes and roll them around a fresh fruit
medley of mangoes (use peaches or even apples if you don't have
mangoes). Top with dollops of icy sorbet _ lemon would be good here
_ and drizzle a flaming rum sauce over all for an elegant
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Cheesecake is another natural cool base for the fruits. Judy
Pertnoy at Sweet Endings commercial bakery in West Palm Beach uses
several fruits in her popular tropical passion cheesecake. It's
full of mangoes and passionfruit, and studded with mandarin
oranges.
</P>
<P>
   Her desserts are sold to chefs around the state and throughout
the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a couple of tropical things. The reason is that we
do a lot with the islands and Key West. People come down to Florida
and expect something tropical besides Key lime pie,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She adapted the recipe for her popular cheesecake for our home
cooks. A mango cheesecake has a coconut crumb crust. She suggests a
passionfruit sauce for color. ``You could toast more coconut and
sprinkle it on top of the coulis; that would be really pretty,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Leave yourself open to ideas and mix and match from the
following recipes for a cool, tropical end to a meal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1526EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
