<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6895 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K06-COX     08-05 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K WON'T BRING 'NATIONAL CATASTROPHE,' ADMINISTRATION SAYS
 &HT;    With Y2K-COLLEGES. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While Jan. 1 will not bring widespread power
outages or bank failures, the day may be difficult for thousands of
local governments, small hospitals, school districts and small
businesses, the Clinton administration said Thursday in its latest
overview of the year 2000 software problem.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Y2K bug'' is a programming flaw that can cause some older
computers and electronic equipment to misread the date 2000 as
1900, potentially causing malfunctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic infrastructure of the country will hold,'' said John
Koskinen, chairman of the President's Council on Year 2000
Conversion. He said enough work has been done at banks, utilities,
stock exchanges and federal agencies to ensure ``we're not going to
have a national catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the administration is worried about the many local
governments, small businesses, school districts and colleges that
have been taking a ``wait-and-see'' approach.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular concern is the lack of preparation being done by
the 911 call centers operated by local governments. Koskinen said
that as of June, only 37 percent of emergency call centers had
cleared their systems of computer bugs.
</P>
<P>
   He urged cities, counties, hospitals and businesses to develop
contingency plans for coping with possible system failures _ for
example, assigning police officers to major intersections at
midnight in case computer-controlled traffic lights malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Contingency plans also are needed for school districts, most of
which are woefully unprepared for computer problems. Only 28
percent of more than 3,500 school systems reported being ready for
the date change, he said. Possible problems for schools include the
loss of computer systems that control bus schedules, report cards,
transcripts and payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K report, which was the third quarterly assessment issued
by the president's council, forecast no significant problems with
the nation's grocery stores, banks, electrical and water utilities
and phone companies, except for international calls.
</P>
<P>
   While Koskinen was generally upbeat about the United States'
ability to handle Y2K disruptions, the White House was less
optimistic about other countries. The report noted that while
foreign preparations have increased in recent months, many
governments lack information about the readiness of their
industries.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen also said the outlook for computers that regulate
international maritime traffic were mixed, noting that many
questions still surround the preparedness of many ports and
foreign-flagged ships.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
