<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6921 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MYSTERY-MEN-LADN     08-05 1604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYSTERY-MEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERHERO SATIRE FLESHES OUT COMIC BOOK CHARACTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tired of overdesigned, underimagined and utterly
soulless superhero movies?
</P>
<P>
   So were the makers of ``Mystery Men.'' Though based on a
long-running set of supporting characters in Dark Horse Comics'
``Flaming Carrot'' series that satirized the absurdities of that
sturdiest of comic book genres, the $70 million movie production
had to do more than just take obvious shots at broad targets.
</P>
<P>
   After all, wasn't the last ``Batman'' sequel such an
unintentional self-parody that it probably couldn't be topped?
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than the original `Batman' movie, which Tim Burton did
and I thought was great, superhero films became too overly
produced, too gadget-oriented, and you started to lose the
characters,'' says Kinka Usher, an award-winning commercials
director (Miller Lite, Taco Bell, ``Got Milk?'') who makes his
feature debut with ``Mystery Men.'' ``Something we tried very hard
to do with this was preserve the characters as the most important
element of the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing ``Mystery Men'' does have going for it is characters.
Boy, are they characters.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Burden, the cartoonist who created this kind of
bargain-basement Justice League, saw them as the guys who really
want to be crimefighters but just don't have the powers to get the
job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a world with Batman in it, in that world there's
got to be guys who sit in a diner somewhere and complain that, if
they only had the right break, they'd get the attention he does,''
notes Mike Richardson, the founder of Dark Horse Comics who has
produced ``The Mask,'' ``Barb Wire'' and several other movies based
on his company's publications. ``I liken it to playing basketball
on playgrounds with the guy who's always there that says, `I'd be
playing in the NBA if I'd gotten a break.' Of course, everybody
knows there's not a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's our guys. They're not superheroes but they want
to be in the worst way. That's their dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of some 40 costumed wanna-bes who have popped up over the
years in the ``Mystery Men'' strips, a core of seven deemed, um,
most relatable to the average guy were chosen for screen
immortality.
</P>
<P>
   The three principal pretenders are Mr. Furious, a junkyard
worker with no particular power but who can get very, very mad,
played by ``There's Something About Mary's'' Ben Stiller; the
Shoveler (William H. Macy), a working-class family man who truly
believes that his incredible dexterity with, well, a shovel has to
be used for the public good; And the Blue Raja _ played with a fake
English accent by ``Simpsons'' voice wiz Hank Azaria _ who still
lives with his mom and has mastered the art of hurling silverware _
though he refuses to fling knives.
</P>
<P>
   These likable losers have been overshadowed their whole
non-careers by Champion City's star, corporate-sponsored superhero,
Capt. Amazing (Greg Kinnear). But when he's captured by evil genius
Casanova Frankenstein (``Shine's'' Geoffrey Rush), our guys are
forced to beef up their ranks with even more pathetic specimens to
save the day.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new recruits are the Bowler (Janeane Garofalo),
daughter of the original Bowler, whose still-powerful skull has
been preserved inside a deadly accurate round hunk of lucite; the
Invisible Boy (Nickelodeon's Kel Mitchell), a kid so accustomed to
being overlooked that he's actually developed the power to turn
invisible _ as long as nobody's watching; the Spleen (erstwhile
Pee-wee Herman Paul Reubens), master of incapacitating body odors;
and the mysterious Sphinx (Wes Studi), who actually has some neat
powers but bores everybody stiff with his Yoda-like platitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Funny stuff. But pitching it right was tricky. Satire, as the
show-biz truism goes, is what closes on Saturday night, and in
order to properly parody the gigantism the genre's grown into, more
money had to be spent on ``Mystery Men'' than on your average,
catchall spoof film of the ``Airplane!''/``Hot Shots!'' variety.
But to try to earn that investment back, it was decided, audiences
needed something more to latch onto than scattershot snide jokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge of this movie was walking a fine line between
satire and being pretty sincere at the same time, sort of having it
both ways,'' says Lloyd Levin, who produced the film with partner
Lawrence Gordon (``Die Hard,'' ``Predator'') and Dark Horse's
Richardson. ``To me, some of the funniest stuff is when it's at its
most sincere as well.''
</P>
<P>
   To pull this off, the producers knew they needed funny actors,
but ones who were capable of bringing some humanity back to the
genre as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ideal was to cast people who would never be cast in some
of the more constipated versions of superhero stories,'' Levin
says, not joking.
</P>
<P>
   And the players took their assignment to heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid, I loved reading Marvel comics at camp,''
Blue Raja Azaria recalls. ``My idea was, what if you actually tried
to live out your childhood fantasy of being a superhero. So, I
viewed him as a guy who just did not grow up. I felt, why not carry
it far enough that a guy actually changes his voice and his persona
to be a superhero character, playing with the idea of an alter ego
a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my original ideas was to actually play the character
like an 8-year-old,'' Azaria adds. ``That seemed like going a
little too far, but I always felt kind of like an 8-year-old
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo, whose sophisticated, dry wit has been praised in such
films as ``Clay Pigeons'' and ``The Truth About Cats and Dogs,''
never read superhero comics. But she has opinions about the general
state of costumed crimefighter movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's a big franchise with Batman, and there's talk
about making a Spider-Man movie and all of those things, but they
tend to take themselves too seriously,'' she observes. ``Even when
they claim to be poking fun and winking at the audience, to me they
still seem very overblown, overbudgeted, A-list actored.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this one, I'd say the only thing we've got is the giant
budget,'' she adds with a chuckle. ``But what hopefully has been
accomplished is the spectacle-type film with attention to dialogue,
which tend not to go hand-in-hand. The hope was that these
characters were invested with actual personalities and not
one-dimensional, flashy figures.''
</P>
<P>
   While most of the Mystery Men came from an improvisational
comedy background, the shovel-slinging William H. Macy is a veteran
of playwright David Mamet's crack dramatic ensemble. He struggled
to bring a convincing earnestness to his performance, which proved
a somewhat quixotic mission among this group of cutups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't lie to you; the relationship that Hank, Ben and I had
on screen, we had off screen,'' Macy, who earned an Oscar
nomination for his work in ``Fargo,'' reveals. ``I was constantly
bickering with them, saying, `Yeah, enough with the jokes, but
isn't this a scene where...' But working with all of these people
who were so improvisatory was good for me, because I either had to
duke it out or lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Macy shares most of the ``Mystery'' crew's disappointment with
what superhero films have mutated into.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all became about the special effects, the explosions, and
I'm just bored with that stuff,'' he says. ``All an explosion can
be now is a little bigger than the last one. It doesn't appeal to
me. What appeals to me is a story that has something to do with my
life. Even if it takes place on Mars or in the Old West or in a
comic book, there's got to be a dilemma that I can relate to.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why this script appealed to me,'' Macy adds, waxing
Shoveleric. ``It's about everyday people with everyday foibles we
can all identify with, who are not prepared to fight the villain.
They don't have the tools they need, they're the last guys in the
world who should be given this job, but there ain't nobody else,
and it's gotta be us.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the stories that just make me weep, the everyday
schmo who must rise to the occasion. It strikes me as a singularly
American story, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Very American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we all want Capt. Amazing's endorsements and
fame,'' Macy notes. And indeed, the film's take on superheroes also
serves as a not-so-disguised joshing of show biz and celebrity in
general.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally an actor's story,'' Azaria notes. ``Or like guys
forming a rock band, very similar vibe. My character's adoration of
Capt. Amazing would be like the way you'd bother Mel Gibson or
somebody like that if you saw them.''
</P>
<P>
   But from the little guy's perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the great Jenifer Lewis, who plays my wife in the movie,
says, `Honey, you've been doing this for 15 years, isn't it time to
give it up'... Well, we all know that speech, don't we?'' Macy
adds.
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, ``Mystery Men,'' the movie, will become a notch
of bankability in the utility belts of everyone who was involved
with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're exactly `Austin Powers' or `Big Daddy' or
`American Pie' kind of comedy, and I don't think that we're the
traditional superhero movie,'' producer Levin acknowledges. ``I
just hope that it's refreshing enough that people like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a gigantic audience that finds the superhero genre
appealing and has been kind of disappointed in what they've been
seeing in those movies recently,'' Levin adds. ``They might
appreciate a movie in which the characters are as intelligent as
they are.'' &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
