<HEADLINE>
`LOCK, STOCK' AND BARRELS OF SHADY CHARACTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Along with the razzle-dazzle that British
writer-director Guy Ritchie brought to his first feature, the crime
comedy ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels'' was some true grit
in the form of real-life criminals. Ritchie says he estimates that
about half the cast has criminal records while another 25 percent
probably hasn't been caught yet.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, despite critical raves here and big box-office
numbers in England, the film did little business in America when it
was released in March. This may have been because U.S. audiences
were put off by the thick cockney accents. Too bad, because it's
one of the best films so far this year, especially when you
consider many of the dismal efforts that have come out this summer.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, ``Lock'' hits video stores, and, thanks to the
rewind button, you won't miss the film's wacky dialogue that gives
the caper story such a fun, offbeat flavor. It's basically the
story of four lads who live on the edge of the criminal world and
spot a chance to make a big score by ripping off a drug dealer. But
they are a gang that couldn't shoot straight _ or actually, at all;
so, things quickly and hilariously go awry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're armed,'' says Eddie (Nick Moran), when the gang
unexpectedly runs into its foes. ``Armed? Armed with what?'' asks
Soap (Dexter Fletcher). ``Feather dusters, colorful language. What
do you think? Guns, you twit!''
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie, who got his start directing commercials and music
videos, keeps the action-and-laugh quota high while giving the
modestly budgeted film (it cost $1.6 million) a pop visual style
without being gratuitous in an MTV sort of way, which is an
irritating fault of many recent first-time directors.
</P>
<P>
   Though you might not recognize the faces _ rock star Sting, who
plays a small role, is the biggest name _ ``Lock'' is rollicking
good fun, and Ritchie is a director to watch.
</P>
<P>
   LOVE THAT BARD: ``Shakespeare in Love,'' which also comes out on
Tuesday, doesn't have as many guns as ``Lock,'' but it has lots of
swordplay _ in both senses of the way the Bard of Avon used it in
his plays. The Oscar-winning film is overrated in cinematic terms
but nevertheless is quite charming and highly entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   It also boasts some wonderful performances. While Gwyneth
Paltrow and Judi Dench picked up Academy Awards for best actress
and best supporting actress, respectively, the men shouldn't be
overlooked. Joseph Fiennes as Shakespeare imbues his Bard with the
strong will he needs to pull off his dual pursuit of Viola
(Paltrow) and theatrical success, while Geoffrey Rush is
delightfully daffy as in-debt theater impresario Philip Henslowe.
</P>
<P>
   Like Shakespeare's own plays, ``Shakespeare'' is filled with
mistaken or hidden identities, pratfalls, raucous puns, tragedy
and, of course, love's labors lost.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay by Marc Normand and Tom Stoppard is quite clever
in interweaving historical events and Shakespearean themes into a
story that feels as up to date as it is Elizabethan.
</P>
<P>
   Deftly directed by John Madden, ``Shakespeare'' is an appealing
souffle, even for guys who like smoking guns.
</P>
<P>
   SOMETHING MORE ABOUT `MARY': Flipping radio dials recently, I
landed on ``Build Me Up Buttercup,'' a song I hated until last
year's hit film ``There's Something About Mary.'' It's funny how a
good movie can change you. Now, despite my critical tastes, I find
myself singing along. Earlier this week, Fox released a ``Special
Edition'' DVD that features an extra video that is a sort of
sing-along of the song plus about seven minutes of outtakes. This
may not make the DVD really special, but the film _ which is
destined to be a comedy classic _ alone is worth it, and the
additional material is a bonus. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
