<HEADLINE>
98 DEGREES MOVING BEYOND POP IDOL STATUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The heat is still on for Ohio-born pop foursome 98
Degrees.
</P>
<P>
   But the Grammy-nominated boy band, which scored smash singles
(``The Hardest Thing,'' ``Because of You'') along with its album
(``98 Degrees and Rising''), is targeting a wider audience than
just the teen-age girls who screamed during the quartet's
performance at the KIIS-FM (102.7) fest at Dodger Stadium in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're musicians who sing,'' said Jeff Timmons, 25, of the
harmony-driven group, which also includes Justin Jeffre and
brothers Nick and Drew Lachey. ``Hopefully, we offer a variety of
things for people. We're not just going for the pop phenomenon
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   With lyrics that go beyond the usual teen-magnet interests and a
live show that focuses on singing rather than flashy choreography,
98 Degrees seem less tailored than Five, C-Note and 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   ``We model ourselves after Boyz II Men, and that's what we're
known for,'' said the New York-based Timmons. ``Expect uptempo
material from us. We don't mind being compared to the Backstreet
Boys, but once you see our show and hear our records, you'll see
we're not the best dancers in the world but we do care about
singing. That's our main thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is, 98 Degrees' audience ranges from teens to
middle-aged women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ballads are definitely our thing,'' Timmons said. ``It's
something that comes naturally to us.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ON THE SCENE:
</P>
<P>
   Still-sealed vinyl jazz on the Blue Note label will be among the
attractions at the Universal Record Show on Sunday at the Beverly
Garland Hotel (4222 Vineland Ave., North Hollywood). In addition,
Viper Room DJ Mike Vague will join more than 40 other music vendors
at the event, which runs from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m. ... Dixie Chicks'
new album, ``Fly,'' is due Aug. 31. ... John Hiatt has been named
the new host of public TV's music series ``Sessions at West 54th.''
Guests for the new season include Los Lobos, Mandy Barnett, Ruben
Blades, Diana Krall, Sheryl Crow and Macy Gray. ... Paul McCartney
has two albums out in October. ``Run Devil Run'' is a collection of
rock 'n' roll covers and ``Working Classical'' features chamber
music versions of Beatles and Wings songs along with orchestral
readings of McCartney's classical pieces.
</P>
<P>
   (To reach music writer Fred Shuster with tips or comments,
e-mail him at dnlalalife(at)aol.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
