<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-05 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FREE ENTERPRISE': CAPTAIN KIRK AND FRIENDS GROUNDED IN NEVERLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prolonged adolescence of the sort built on inextinguishable
obsession with ``Star Trek,'' ``Star Wars,'' ``The Brady Bunch,''
Stephen King novels, mini-series like ``The Winds of War,'' comic
books, movie posters and action figures finds its justification in
the slight, bright, clever romantic comedy ``Free Enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Written by Mark A. Altman and Robert Meyer Burnett and directed
and edited by Burnett, this film tells the tale of two friends
named Robert and Mark. Shaped in childhood by ``Star Trek,'' they
are working in Los Angeles and coming up fast on 30, which, as
aficionados of the futuristic 1976 thriller ``Logan's Run,'' they
know to be the end of life. They are also hoping to find lasting
love and thrilled to become friends with their idol, William
Shatner, playing Bill, who proves to be a far cry from their idol,
Captain Kirk, commander of the Starship Enterprise in ``Star
Trek.''
</P>
<P>
   The fun of ``Free Enterprise,'' which occasionally runs a bit
thin but is mostly sustained by the filmmakers' verve and wit, lies
in its many visual and verbal references to popular culture trivia,
its knowing, gleeful sendups of movies and the movie business and
the good humor and willing feet of clay that Shatner brings to his
role.
</P>
<P>
   Like the high-spirited, irresponsible Robert (Rafer Weigel) and
the serious, Spock-like Mark (Eric McCormack), the hard-drinking,
stogie-smoking Bill is without a steady woman in his life. Like
Mark, who when first met is pitching a proposal for a horror film
called ``Bradykiller,'' Bill has his own dream movie project: a
musical version of ``Julius Caesar'' in which he will play all the
roles except Calpurnia. He is saving that for Sharon Stone or
Heather Locklear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free Enterprise'' brims with jokes of that sort. When Robert
finally meets the woman of his dreams, Claire (Audie England), over
a graphic novel in Golden Apple Comics, his friends don't employ
ordinary language to lament his ensuing absence from their life.
They compare him to Claude Rains in ``The Invisible Man.'' Action
across a pool table becomes a ``Color of Money'' moment. A great
idea for a birthday celebration would be to get together with
friends and go out to a theater playing ``Star Trek: The Wrath of
Khan.''
</P>
<P>
   So it comes as no surprise that ``Free Enterprise'' has a
Hollywood ending, with love ascendant, Shatner delivering a rap
rendition of Shakespeare, and final credits peppered with
references fit for a trivia contest.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   FREE ENTERPRISE
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Free Enterprise'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes partial nudity,
simulated sexual acts and coarse language.
</P>
<P>
   Directed and edited by Robert Meyer Burnett; written by Mark A.
Altman and Burnett; director of photography, Charles L. Barbee;
music by Scott Spock; production designer, Cynthia Halligan;
produced by Dan Bates, Altman and Allan Kaufman; released by Regent
Entertainment. Running time: 113 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Rafer Weigel (Robert), Eric McCormack (Mark), Audie
England (Claire), Patrick Van Horn (Sean), Jonathan Slavin (Dan
Vebber), Phil LaMarr (Eric Wallace) and William Shatner (Bill).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
