<HEADER>
A6943 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISASTER-INSURANCE06-     08-05 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISASTER-INSURANCE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BILL WOULD ALLOW INSURANCE RESERVE FOR MAJOR DISASTERS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JONATHAN HALL
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Worried that a major natural disaster could
bankrupt insurers and leave thousands of consumers without
coverage, a bipartisan group of lawmakers Thursday unveiled a bill
to let the insurance industry insure itself.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, sponsored by Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., insurers would
direct some of their policy holders' premiums into a tax-deferred
reserve fund devoted only to covering claims associated with
natural disasters. Federal law now prohibits such a fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we cannot predict nor prevent natural disasters from
occurring, we can prepare for them,'' Foley said at a Capitol Hill
news conference. ``This is a common-sense measure ensuring that
home and business owners who suffer one tragedy don't suffer
another'' if an overexposed insurer went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   After Hurricane Andrew hit Florida in 1992, 10 insurance
companies were unable to pay all of their affected policy holders.
It's believed that if Andrew had come closer to Miami, roughly
one-third of the insurance companies in Florida would have become
insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, the disaster fund would be phased in gradually
over 20 years and held in a special tax-deferred account until
needed to pay claims to policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated $16 billion reserve fund would be built within the
first 10 years, costing the government about $500 million per year
in deferred taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Current federal tax law allows insurers to make reserves only
against losses that have already occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed bill ``will directly address and solve this problem
in the tax law,'' said the National Taxpayers Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The taxpayers will be much better served. The insurance
companies can remedy the claims, remain solvent, remain in business
and not come up with the constant government solutions for the
(disaster) problems,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated efforts to adopt similar bills over several years have
failed to win congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
