<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-COLLEGES06-COX     08-05 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLLEGES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RILEY, COLLEGES SQUABBLE OVER Y2K-BUGS IN STUDENT LOANS
 &HT;    With Y2K.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Education Secretary Richard Riley irritated top
officials of the nation's colleges and universities Thursday by
scolding them for their delays in conducting Y2K-bug tests of the
data systems that funnel more than $40 billion a year in federal
loans and grants to their students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the (Education) Department's systems and data
exchanges have been tested internally, we all need the reassurance
that can only be provided by live testing of the data exchanges''
with the schools, Riley said. ``So far, only 22 of the over 5,800
U.S. institutions in the student aid programs have successfully
tested.''
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K bug is a software flaw that can cause some older
computers and electronic equipment to misread the date 2000 as
1900, potentially causing them to malfunction. If federal computers
don't mesh correctly with school computers, student aid could be
lost, delayed or incorrectly provided.
</P>
<P>
   The department's test period, originally set for July 8 to Aug.
20, will be extended to the end of August in hopes that more
schools will test their federal-aid links.
</P>
<P>
   Riley included two thinly veiled threats in a letter he sent to
each president or chancellor of an American public, private or
for-profit post-secondary school:
</P>
<P>
   _ Hinting at a bureaucratic crackdown, he said he is
``considering'' a proposal by his department's inspector general
that the government require, rather than merely encourage, data
exchange testing by schools whose students obtain federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hinting at bad publicity for schools, he said that ``negative
assumptions are likely'' for presidents and chancellors who fail to
spell out details of their progress in the Y2K conversion process
to the public through the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Leftwich, vice president of the Career College
Association, which consists of privately owned vocational schools,
said the Education Department's data must be inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would confidently say that the (federal aid software) in 85
to 90 percent of our more than 700 members is Y2K-compliant,''
Leftwich said. ``Our members know that student aid is is their
lifeblood, and they're not in business if that gets cut off.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Elmendorf, vice president for government policy at the
American Association of State Colleges and Universities, criticized
the ``exaggeration'' in Riley's letter, and noted that the data
exchanges are optional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the 426 members we had at our most recent board meeting in
July, every single president had a committee or other effort under
way, not only to make their own institution Y2K-ready, but also
their their vendors,'' Elmendorf said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Education Department is only one of our vendors, and I'm
sure our members will eventually test data exchanges with it when
they are ready,'' Elmendorf said. Meantime, he said, many are
giving a higher priority to tests of their links with vendors who
handle faculty payrolls and with foundations and other large
funders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
