<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MYSTERY-FILM-REVIEW-N     08-05 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYSTERY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MYSTERY MEN': SUPERMEN, CARTOON CHARACTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes at end)  
(jt) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like Austin Powers, the self-styled superheroes of ``Mystery
Men'' have only the dimmest suspicions that they are anything short
of cool. The way they see it, the world was running out of
superheroes, and, well, it was a dirty job but somebody had to do
it. Even somebody armed with forks, a shovel, a bad temper or a
bowling ball. The kind of paragon who might solemnly intone, as
William H. Macy's Shoveler does: ``We've got a blind date with
Destiny _ and it looks like she's ordered the lobster.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, these aspiring supermen (and one superwoman, played by
Janeane Garofalo armed with one weird bowling ball) have been
reading too many comic books. And this crafty tongue-in-cheek
satire hopes that its audience has, too. This witty if eventually
overblown movie is based on the Dark Horse series created by Bob
Burden, and it plays off the conventions of the genre at their most
absurd. When the Shoveler is told that the stellar Captain Amazing
(Greg Kinnear with one hilariously quizzical raised eyebrow) is
actually mild-mannered Lance Hunt, he notes in bewilderment that
Lance wears glasses but the Captain does not. ``That's
ridiculous,'' surmises the Shoveler, in a fine display of logic a
la Spinal Tap. ``He wouldn't be able to see!''
</P>
<P>
   With a terrific offbeat cast operating on one shared, loony
wavelength, ``Mystery Men'' introduces Hank Azaria as the Blue
Raja, who actually wears green, fakes an effete English accent and
tosses dinner forks as his special skill. (Yes, there's a bold cry
of ``May the forks be with you!'' heard here.) Ben Stiller plays
the self-proclaimed powder keg whose weapon would be his temper if
it actually scared anyone, and Macy totes his shovel with great
deadpan aplomb. They are late joined by Paul Reubens, whose
exaggerated pimples and carefully deployed flatulence do wear out
their welcome, and Wes Studi of ``Dances With Wolves'' as The
Sphinx, the compleat know-nothing sage. The Sphinx is just about
unstoppable when he starts delivering such pearls as ``To learn my
teachings, I must first teach you how to learn.'' And: ``You must
lash out with every limb, like the octopus who plays the drums.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, directed by Kinka Usher with a little too much of the
same special-effects silliness that it mocks, locks its hapless
good guys in battle with Casanova Frankenstein, played by Geoffrey
Rush in another sneakily funny turn. Casanova is abetted by the
Disco Boys, who lurk in their lair to the accompaniment of the Bee
Gees and manage to mimic John Travolta's famous ``Saturday Night
Fever'' pose when they go into the fray. Also cropping up in small
roles are Tom Waits as a weapons designer, in a movie where talk of
things like ``a heat-seeking anthrax projection dart'' comes cheap;
Louise Lasser as the mom who wonders if her Blue Raja isn't ``on
the marijuana''; Claire Forlani and Lena Olin in small but sharp
roles, and Jenifer Lewis as the exasperated Mrs. Shoveler.
</P>
<P>
   The jokes are smart in the screenplay by Neil Cuthbert, but they
are allowed to wear thin despite the brief running time. And the
look of ``Mystery Men,'' in which businesses like wholesale fish
and tire shops are well represented, is droll yet overly cluttered.
The requisite air of futuristic grunge and global reach is conveyed
by what look like signs for Chinese restaurants in the film's
nighttime street scenes.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY MEN
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Mystery Men'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It includes occasional strong language and a mild
gross-out from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kinka Usher; written by Neil Cuthbert, based on the
Dark Horse comic book series created by Bob Burden; director of
photography, Stephen H. Burum; edited by Conrad Buff; music by
Stephen Warbeck; production designer, Kirk M. Petruccelli; produced
by Lawrence Gordon, Mike Richardson and Lloyd Levin; released by
Universal Pictures. Running time: 100 minutes. This film is rated
PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Hank Azaria (The Blue Raja), Claire Forlani (Monica),
Janeane Garofalo (The Bowler), Greg Kinnear (Captain Amazing),
William H. Macy (The Shoveler), Kel Mitchell (Invisible Boy), Lena
Olin (Dr. Annabel Leek), Paul Reubens (The Spleen), Geoffrey Rush
(Casanova Frankenstein), Ben Stiller (The Furious), Wes Studi (The
Sphinx), Tom Waits (Dr. Heller) and Jenifer Lewis as Mrs. Shoveler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1611EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
