<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6948 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-05 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE ADVENTURES OF SEBASTIAN COLE': GROWING PAINS OF A SUBURBAN
YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who has endured the frustration and growing pains of a
suburban adolescence should identify with the angst and uncertainty
besetting the 17-year-old title character of Tod Williams' film
``The Adventures of Sebastian Cole.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1983 in Dutchess County, New York, the movie gets deeply
under the skin of Sebastian (Adrian Grenier), a bright, attractive,
energetic high school student reacting badly to the seismic jolts
when his family unexpectedly comes apart.
</P>
<P>
   The opening scene finds Sebastian squirming during one of those
excruciating family dinners at which various branches sprung from
divorce put on a painfully uncomfortable show of solidarity for the
sake of children on whom nothing is lost. Among those present are
Sebastian's biological father, Hartley (John Shea), a smug yuppie
architect, and his new trophy wife; Sebastian's sister, Jessica
(Marni Lustig), who is bound for Stanford; his high- strung mother,
Joan (Margaret Colin), and his shaggy-haired stepfather, Hank
(Clark Gregg).
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, it is obvious that Hank, who exhibits a
stern but loving attitude toward his stepson, is much more caring
toward Sebastian than Hartley ever was. Therefore it comes as an
awful shock, not long after the dinner, when Hank gathers his wife
and stepchildren together for a meeting at which he bluntly
announces that he has decided to go through the process of sexual
reassignment and become a woman.
</P>
<P>
   The family's initial shock is followed by fury. Although Hank
insists that he would like to stay married to Joan, she is
devastated. The family flies apart, with Joan returning to her
native England and Jessica fleeing to California with her
boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Sebastian briefly joins his mother abroad, but is miserable, and
returns to upstate New York to live with Hank, who now calls
himself Henrietta and has begun wearing dresses, makeup and
jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   At this critical turning point, ``The Adventures of Sebastian
Cole'' admirably steers away from becoming a transgendered update
of ``The Odd Couple.'' Instead of dwelling on the obvious social
and sexual tensions inherent in the living arrangement, the movie
becomes an richly detailed, episodic study of Sebastian's troubled
adolescence, with a performance by Grenier that beautifully
captures his character's precarious balance of naivete and bravado,
self-destructiveness and self-invention.
</P>
<P>
   Churning with an inchoate anger, Sebastian, who dreams of
becoming a writer, does poorly in high school and bungles his first
serious relationship with a girl (Aleksa Palladino). One evening he
nearly poisons himself to death in a show-off drinking binge.
</P>
<P>
   On a trip to New York he narrowly escapes being beaten up by the
pimp of a teen-age prostitute he foolishly tries to rescue. He
rides a motorcycle down his high school hallways. In the funniest
scene, Sebastian, threatened with nongraduation for having cut
physical education, fools his teachers into giving him credit for
the missed classes by putting on a bogus but flashy karate
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   In in its handling of Hank's sexual change the movie is so
matter-of-fact that it seems evasive. The movie never delves into
Hank's psyche and only cursorily deals with the effects of his
decision on his stepson and the reaction of the community. One
scene, in which he punches out a man who calls him ``faggot,'' is
just not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Once Hank has become Henrietta, there is no visible change, from
hormone therapy or electrolysis, between the two except for the
character's donning of frumpy dresses, makeup and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg's Henrietta never looks or acts like anything less
masculine than a big hairy lug comically lumbering around in an
ill-fitting frock. And although Gregg's performance has plenty of
heart, his character seems too saintly to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Through all his changes, he remains an ideal, caring parent to
Sebastian, setting boundaries and offering just the right amounts
of tough love when the situation demands. That's why the movie, for
all its audacity and attention to rituals and moods of teen-age
life, finally feels incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE ADVENTURES OF SEBASTIAN COLE' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has sexual situations
and some strong language.
</P>
<P>
   `THE ADVENTURES OF SEBASTIAN COLE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Tod Williams; director of photography,
John Foster; edited by Affonso Goncalves; music by Lynn Geller;
produced by Karen Barber and Jasmine Kosovic; released by Paramount
Classics. Running time: 99 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Adrian Grenier (Sebastian), Clark Gregg (Hank/Henrietta),
Aleksa Palladino (Mary), Margaret Colin (Joan), Marni Lustig
(Jessica) and John Shea (Hartley).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1612EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
