<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-05 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A LITTLE BIT OF SOUL': DEVILISH CHICKENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're going to make a movie about upper-class Australian
Satan worshipers, it is pretty daring not to reveal or even mention
Satanism until half an hour before the end. It is also pretty
self-defeating.
</P>
<P>
   Moviegoers who happen onto ``A Little Bit of Soul'' without
advance research can be forgiven for thinking that the movie is a
comedy about a nerdy scientist who lives with chickens. That would
be Dr. Richard Shorkinghorn (David Wenham), seen reading ``A Brief
History of Time'' on the train and arriving for a country weekend
with a lot of luggage and two cages of live poultry. To his horror,
his nubile former assistant, Kate Haslett (Frances O'Connor), has
been invited on the same weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Their hosts are Godfrey Usher, the federal treasurer, played by
Geoffrey Rush, who looks extremely uncomfortable trying to rise
above this film, and his wife, Grace Michael (Heather Mitchell).
Grace joins Kate in laughing hysterically at Richard but soon
throws herself into his arms. ``It's so long since I've been held
by a real man,'' she sighs. Meanwhile, the soundtrack is booming
with all-too-specific folksy American numbers like ``Open the Door,
Richard'' and ``Nobody Here but Us Chickens.''
</P>
<P>
   It's only after another weekend guest has died (killed herself,
say the hosts, explaining the blood-drenched bathroom) that Kate
and Richard _ and the audience _ learn about the hosts' demonic
hobby. ``Why the Devil, Grace?'' Kate asks gently. Kate shrugs and
says, ``Oh, it's a family thing.'' Then she explains her real
motivation: ``I'm going to be 39 next birthday.'' Seems the movie
is also about the search for eternal youth. Who knew? Richard and
Kate have both been doing research on ``the key to the body clock''
and are making lots of progress. So is Godfrey, who soon becomes
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Making a completely boring film about the Devil, the fountain of
youth and government figures making fools of themselves is quite an
accomplishment, especially from a filmmaker with promise. Peter
Duncan, the writer and director, made his feature film debut two
years ago with ``Children of the Revolution,'' an offbeat but
well-received comedy about Stalin's love child. Sometimes the risks
pay off; sometimes they don't.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   A LITTLE BIT OF SOUL
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``A Little Bit of Soul'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes fairly strong
profanity, sexual situations and a lot of blood.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Peter Duncan; director of photography,
Martin McGrath; edited by Simon Martin; music by Nigel Westlake;
production designer, Tony Campbell; produced by Duncan, Martin,
McGrath and Peter J. Voeten; released by Phaedra Cinema. Running
time: 84 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   Cast; Geoffrey Rush (Godfrey Usher), David Wenham (Richard
Shorkinghorn), Frances O'Connor (Kate Haslett), Heather Mitchell
(Grace Michael) and John Gaden (Dr. Sommerville).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1613EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6951 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISC-REVIEWS-LADN     08-05 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISC-REVIEWS-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS LOBOS/``THIS TIME'' (Hollywood)
</P>
<P>
   Los Lobos' second album of new songs since 1992's acclaimed
``Kiko'' finds the band again collaborating with avant-garde
alchemists Mitchell Froom and Tchad Blake. This time around,
though, Lobos return to less experimental, familiar ground with the
Colombian soundscape of ``Cumbia Raza,'' along with r&AMP;b-fueled
winners like the easygoing New Orleans groove of the War tribute,
``Oh, Yeah,'' a swampy ``Viking'' and the sweetly soulful title
track. With its enjoyable mix of blues, rock, soul and rootsy folk,
``This Time'' offers a multicultural musical road map for a new
era. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster
</P>
<P>
   SOUNDTRACK/``SOUTH PARK: BIGGER, LONGER &AMP; UNCUT'' (Atlantic)
</P>
<P>
   The musical companion to the outrageous animated comedy deserves
to win an Oscar for best movie score of the year, even if we can't
spell out all the song titles in a family newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Arranged and partially penned by Academy Award-nominated
composer Marc Shaiman, the soundtrack features such memorably fully
realized show-tune parodies as ``Blame Canada,'' ``What Would Brian
Boitano Do?'' ``Eyes of a Child'' (performed by Michael McDonald)
and ``I Can Change,'' hilariously sung by a cartoon Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   To stretch out the disc's dozen film tracks, there are eight
less successful interpretations by an eclectic lineup, notably Kid
Rock, RuPaul and the Violent Femmes. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster
</P>
<P>
   TIN HAT TRIO/``MEMORY IS AN ELEPHANT'' (Angel)
</P>
<P>
   The playfully inverted title here hints at the scrambled yet
sophisticated sensibility within. Suavely compressing Cajun,
klezmer, tango, bluegrass and bossa nova into soulfully cerebral
chamber jazz, this Bay Area trio sounds like what you might get if
David Grisman, Bill Frisell, Astor Piazzolla and Samuel Barber were
somehow to form a Left Bank busker group.
</P>
<P>
   Never lapsing into mere pastiche, Tin Hat Trio fuses the
structural incisiveness of classical with the sensual fluidity of
jazz, offset by probing, avant-garde atonalities. Rob Burger
establishes the almost-cinematic !ital!mis-en-scene with richly
melancholic overlays of accordion, piano and pump organ, while
Carla Kihlstedt's elegantly austere violin and viola playing
jostles dramatically with Mark Orton's earthy guitar, mandolin and
banjo rumblings. This is cosmopolitan ``roots'' music of a very
rare order. 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Reed Johnson
</P>
<P>
   PACO DE LUCIA/``LUZIA'' (Blue Thumb)
</P>
<P>
   After collaborating with jazzers such as Chick Corea, John
McLaughlin and Al DiMeola, innovative flamenco guitar icon de Lucia
offers an engaging solo work that recalls ``Siroco,'' his serene
1989 tribute to traditional flamenco forms. The difference here are
the eight original pieces focusing on unusual harmonies and
tempered by an intimate backing of mandolin, bass and percussion.
As always, the spotlight is on de Lucia's dazzling fretwork, even
when taking the lead vocals on the title track and ``Camaron,''
dedicated to the late flamenco singer Camaron de la Isla. 3 1/2
stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster
</P>
<P>
   ETTA JAMES/``HEART OF A WOMAN'' (Private Music)
</P>
<P>
   On her new album, James tackles a set of popular standards,
including songs by immortals like Duke Ellington, Sammy Cahn and
Irving Berlin. The disc kicks off with a swinging rendition of the
melancholy ``You Don't Know What Love Is,'' followed by the bluesy
``Good Morning Heartache.'' James' bossa nova spin on the classic
``My Old Flame'' works well, while the Stevie Wonder-inspired horns
on Berlin's ``Say It Isn't So'' is an instant highlight. Also worth
checking out is a reworked version of James' 1961 smash, ``At
Last,'' bolstered by a snazzy Hammond organ solo. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster
</P>
<P>
   BETH HART/``SCREAMIN' FOR MY SUPPER'' (143/Lava/Atlantic)
</P>
<P>
   After her surprisingly fully formed debut several years ago,
singer-songwriter Hart's jinxed sophomore effort veers up a
driveway called mediocrity. Problem is, the seething Hart has
apparently lost her identity and isn't sure whether she's Janis
Joplin or Sheryl Crow. On an album that could easily be filed under
metal-lite, she screeches her way through much of the proceedings,
stopping briefly to ape Crow on the painfully obvious ballad ``L.A.
Song.'' 1 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster
</P>
<P>
   FREEDY JOHNSTON/``BLUE DAYS, BLACK NIGHTS'' (Elektra)
</P>
<P>
   It was the idiosyncratic Johnston's 1994 major label debut,
``This Perfect World,'' that garnered a streak of critical praise
and a bona fide radio hit with ``Bad Reputation.'' On his latest
nicely unpolished T-Bone Burnett-produced disc, the Kansas-bred
singer-songwriter turns down the volume for a biting set of
delicately arranged songs cut almost entirely live in the studio.
Johnston's songs look into life's dark little corners and his usual
theme, as evidenced by such standouts as ``While I Wait for You''
and ``The Farthest Lights,'' is loneliness. Feeling bad has never
felt so good. 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster
</P>
<P>
   G. LOVE &AMP; SPECIAL SAUCE/``PHILADELPHONIC'' (OKeh/550 Music)
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop bluesman Love's fourth platter finds the Philly native
running out of steam _ and ideas. Where his previous disc, ``Yeah,
It's That Easy,'' used four different lineups to lend the mostly
wonderful tracks a variety of sound and energy to spare,
``Philadelphonic'' unfortunately features the return of Love's
usual lo-fi backing crew. The slurred and lazy results, even with
the hip-hop-oriented use of loops and samples, is uninspired and
often self-indulgent. 2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1613EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
