<HEADER>
A6966 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-THOMASCROWN-TEX     08-05 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-THOMASCROWN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STYLISH, SHALLOW REMAKE REMINDS AUDIENCE THERE WASN'T MUCH TO
STEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new version of ``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' directed with
steely aplomb by John McTiernan (''Die Hard,'' ``The Hunt for Red
October'') provides the filmmaker with a chance to show off
dazzling men-at-work-on-high-tech-scenarios during a museum
robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody stages no-nonsense setups better than McTiernan; he has a
feel for labor-and-machinery-intense prologue unmatched by any
working director. And his love for the retro genre known as the
caper film, a mainstay of the 1960s, gives the new ``Crown'' a
sheen like one found an antique owner's proudly polished vintage
car. He's smart enough to avoid the missteps made earlier this year
by ``Entrapment.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the effort expended here provokes a question. Is there a
reason to remake 1968's ``The Thomas Crown Affair''? So many of the
elements that made the original work _ such as the young woman
(Faye Dunaway) working as a stylish and lethally amoral insurance
investigator, and the rough-hewn Method School bad-boy Steve
McQueen shedding his denim and leather to play a bored Boston
Brahmin who resorts to bank heists to keep himself interested in
life _ were a fresh air of counterculture back in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Crown,'' however, is swank and anonymous. The cast _
Pierce Brosnan, Rene Russo and Denis Leary _ probably could have
been assembled for a Lifetime version of this picture about five
years ago. In the update, Brosnan's Crown is a self-made
billionaire who steals a Monet _ which he folds, that can't be good
for a masterpiece _ from a well-guarded museum, not because he's
bored, but because he has something to prove. (He reveals this to
Faye Dunaway, who has a cameo as a psychiatrist whose makeup job
makes her look like a museum piece.)
</P>
<P>
   The super-smart Russo takes on Crown to rouse herself from
routine investigations; she's been given the McQueen excuse for
motivation. This time around, hunter and hunted eye each other with
serious intent, and seriously manipulate each other, too. This is
unlike the original ``Crown'' in which the two protagonists toyed
with each other and took nothing seriously, a pair of indulgent
opportunists playing a game of chess. (Yes, they actually sat down
at a chessboard.)
</P>
<P>
   Much of this current ``Crown'' is built on Brosnan's turning his
image on its ear. (He produced the project.) He's doing some
Bond-trading, playing against type, against the perception of him
as effete, landed gentry. The protagonists being roughly the same
age this time _ in their mid-40s _ gives the remake an earthiness
that makes the proceedings slightly more realistic.
</P>
<P>
   That's ever so slightly: no man _ unless he were participating
in a Duran Duran reunion tour _ would sport sarongs on white sand
beaches as often as Brosnan. And Russo, who looks fabulous, is
given to laughing and throwing her head back a little too
desperately to show that she has a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, this remake of ``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' with
the stars slipping out of their beautiful clothes _ and Russo has a
reason to be proud of her body _ is as much about appearances as
the original, which was a shallow classic. Only nowadays everything
is boastful about its insignificance, which makes the new ``Crown''
even more meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Thomas Crown Affair''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: John McTiernan
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Pierce Brosnan, Rene Russo
</P>
<P>
   Length: 114 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language and sexuality, and nudity
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
