<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6970 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NARCOLEPSY06-COX     08-05 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NARCOLEPSY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MUTATED GENE MAY PLAY ROLE IN NARCOLEPSY
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Narcolepsy, a strange disorder that plagues an
estimated 125,000 Americans with brief but uncontrollable episodes
of sleep, is apparently the work of a mutated gene _ at least when
it occurs in dogs and mice.
</P>
<P>
   In separate studies made public Thursday, scientists at Stanford
University's Center for Narcolepsy and the University of Texas
Southwestern Medical Center reported tracing narcolepsy to faulty
communications between brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   A genetic study of the Stanford center's population of
narcoleptic dogs shows the brain cells fail to make proper
connections because of a defect in the gene that carries the
genetic building plans for the ``hypocretin2 receptor.''
</P>
<P>
   The mutated receptor is like a lock with a flaw that keeps the
key that is made for it _ in this case, the hormone hypocretin2 _
from fitting properly, said Stanford narcolepsy researcher and
Emmanuel Mignot, who also treats patients with the disorder.
</P>
<P>
   The proper binding of the hormone and the receptor appear to
promote wakefulness.
</P>
<P>
   However, Dr. Mignot said in a telephone interview Thursday that
the condition in humans may not result from genetically induced
flaws in the receptors.
</P>
<P>
   Some research suggests that in humans narcolepsy is actually an
autoimmune disorder that could have disrupted the production of the
hormone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think trying to give people small amounts of the hormones
themselves is something that should be tried, whether I do that or
someone else,'' Dr. Mignot said. Officials of the National
Institutes of Health, which funded the research, hailed the
findings as a possible opening to eventual treatment of the
sometimes disabling condition.
</P>
<P>
   Besides falling abruptly into deep dream sleep, people and other
creatures with narcolepsy experience weird episodes of
``cataplexy,'' in which they remain conscious but become limp and
cannot move for several seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The results of a search by Mignot and his fellow researchers for
the gene responsible for what was already viewed as an inherited
condition were startling because hypocretin2 and its receptor were
thought to control only eating behavior. The hormone was discovered
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the data that we have on food needs to be reconsidered
in light of these findings,'' Dr. Mignot said, ``because what were
seen as food effects may be an indirect result of the sleep
effects. Obviously, you don't eat when you sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the journal Cell, Mignot and fellow researchers said
either of two different flaws in the gene for the hypocretin2
receptor can cause narcolepsy in dogs. One, in which a piece of the
protein is missing, causes the condition in Doberman pinschers and
another, in which the protein has an extra piece, causes it in
Labrador retrievers.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued jointly by the directors of the the National
Heart, Lung and Blood Institute and the National Institute of
Neurological Disorders and Stroke, said the Stanford group's
discovery ``opens the door to identification of the narcolepsy gene
in humans and to development of new treatment approaches and
possibly a cure for this disabling sleep disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   In a second article, scheduled to appear in the same scientific
journal on Aug. 20, researchers at the Texas Southwestern Medical
Center in Dallas reported accidentally creating narcolepsy in mice
by removing the gene for hypocretin2 _ the key, rather than the
lock.
</P>
<P>
   Masashi Yanagisawa, professor of molecular genetics, said he and
other researchers at the Texas center were studying ways
hypocretin2 and hypocretin1, also known as orexin-A and orexin-B,
fit their respective receptors to stimulate food consumption.
</P>
<P>
   However, they soon found that mice that do not have the two
brain hormones were unexpectedly falling asleep in the middle of
high activity.
</P>
<P>
   Analysis of brain wave patterns produced readings that matched
those of humans experiencing narcoleptic sleep, Yanagisawa said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
