<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6971 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOCA-EXHIBIT-LADN     08-05 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOCA-EXHIBIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTISTIC METHOD GIVES EXHIBIT DIFFERENT DIMENSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Jackson Pollock first dribbled paint onto a
bare canvas, he unleashed the idea that art could be as much about
means as about ends.
</P>
<P>
   Pollock's methods dramatized how the artist's choice of
materials, and the way he or she manipulated them, could either
liberate or stifle the innate potential of an artwork. Even today,
Pollock's abstract expressionist masterpieces suggest a dynamic
interplay between randomness and precision, anarchic impulse and
painstaking process.
</P>
<P>
   Pollock's unusual procedures _ to say nothing of his prodigious
talents _ influenced a whole generation of young American artists
who came of age in the 1960s and '70s. While these artists later
splintered into many genres _ performance art, conceptual art,
earth art, feminist art _ they continued to share an interest in
artistic process for its own sake.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler and more intellectualized than the abstract
expressionists, or even the pop artists, these art school-trained
20- and 30-somethings began making art the subject of which was the
making of art itself.
</P>
<P>
   Subjective feelings and personal obsessions were purged from
this new equation. This was art as a branch of mathematics, art as
science (or pseudo-science), art as a kind of visual architecture
that could be mapped out if you just followed the blueprint.
Drawings, when combined with other materials and carefully labeled
and explained to the viewer, were transformed into a new kind of
sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   In some of these works, art became a virtual instruction manual,
a how-to list of steps that documented and deconstructed how the
work was made. So much for the Romantic ideal of art as an
inscrutable, semi-religious undertaking and the artist as a
mystical visionary.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Contemporary Art in downtown Los Angeles
investigates this period and the artists who contributed to it in
the exhibition ``Afterimage: Drawing Through Process.'' Consisting
of more than 160 works on paper by 24 American artists, the show
focuses on the years 1966 through 1974.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fascinating, if highly cerebral show, impossible to rush
through and perhaps best appreciated upon reflection several hours
later. But you'll have to hurry: ``Afterimage'' closes Aug. 22
before moving on to Houston, Seattle and other national venues.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by MOCA associate curator Cornelia H. Butler, the
exhibition moves forward by grouping together similar uses of
materials and overlapping artistic strategies.
</P>
<P>
   The first group of galleries are dominated by Richard Tuttle's
series of ``Wire Pieces'' from 1972-99. In these dramatic
compositions, pieces of wire pop loose from the outlines of wall
pencil drawings like busted guitar strings. It's as if they'd
broken free from the ghostly outlines of their former selves.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite wall, Joel Shapiro's series of finger prints
ironically combines the ultimate symbol of human individuality with
the same process of machinelike reproduction that Andy Warhol used
in his serial prints of Mao and Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Hesse's ink washes on cardboard challenge Renaissance ideas
about visual perception and the way the eye organizes and
subdivides space.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, several samples of Sol LeWitt's ``Folded
Drawings'' of the early 1970s derive their patterns not from actual
``drawings'' but from the lines of the paper folds.
</P>
<P>
   The title of one of these origami-like works has the same ring
of scientific objectivity as a Dutch still life: ``Folded Drawing
(From midpoint of the top side to a point halfway between the
midpoint of the bottom side and the lower right corner, March 23,
1975).'' Only LeWitt isn't representing life; he's documenting
intent.
</P>
<P>
   The middle galleries deal more directly with the idea that
artistic manipulation itself can be the true art object.
Particularly noteworthy are the avant-garde/feminist filmmaker
Yvonne Rainer's ``Dance Scores'' and other documentation of her
performance pieces from the early 1960s. There's a wry, vaguely
subversive humor in this annotated choreography, which demonstrates
how arabesques, plies and other dance movements can be mapped out
and diagrammed to form designs.
</P>
<P>
   The Pomona-born artist Marcia Hafif gives a similar concept
surprisingly visceral form in ``One Hour Twenty Minutes,'' in which
hundreds of tiny pencil marks represent the seconds ticking off
Hafif's life on Nov. 20, 1972. Despite its seemingly detached
measuring of a random block of time, the work inevitably inspires
thoughts of how we mete out our existence.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, by the time you reach the final galleries, pent-up
emotion has begun to bleed back into the exhibition, or sneak in at
the margins. From a distance, Nancy Grossman's ``Tough Life Diary''
(1973) looks as densely threaded as a computer circuit board. On
closer inspection, it reveals doodlings and marginalia about the
artist's hectic routines, with squiggles and blotted-out writing
forming a swirling maze of highly personal symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   With Grossman's diary, the exhibition comes full circle: No
matter how much you try to control art, it seems, chaos always
breaks out in the end. Pollock, who plunged in and created, would
approve. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
What: &LR;  ``Afterimage: Drawing Through Process.'' &UR;  &QL; 
Where: &LR;  Museum of Contemporary Art, 250 S. Grand Ave. &UR;  &QL; 
When: &LR;  Through Aug. 22. Museum hours are 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tuesdays
through Sundays and 11 a.m. to 8 p.m. Thursdays. &UR;  &QL; 
Admission: &LR;  $6 adults; $4 students and senior citizens; free to
MOCA members and children under 12. Admission is free to all from 5
to 8 p.m. every Thursday. Call (213) 626-6222. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
