<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6972 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SIXTHSENSE-TEX     08-05 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SIXTHSENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOW-MOVING PSYCHOLOGICAL DRAMA HAS SURPRISINGLY SATISFYING ENDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may be the season of the witch, the ``Blair Witch'' that is,
but Hollywood still has a few spooky tricks up its sleeve. Take
``The Sixth Sense.'' On the surface, it's a bloated, plodding
psychological drama that doesn't get warmed up until it's almost
halfway over. But for the patient viewer, there are some genuine
chills, intense performances and one of the best
rug-yanked-from-under-you endings of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Willis is devoted child psychologist Malcolm Crowe, maybe
too devoted for his wife's (Olivia Williams') tastes. Haunted by
his failure to save a former patient from suicide, Willis becomes
obsessed with a quiet youngster named Cole (Haley Joel Osment, in a
grippingly convincing performance) who appears to have a similar
affliction.
</P>
<P>
   After an excruciatingly tedious getting-to-know-you period, we
finally learn that the boy has a ``gift'' for communicating with
the dead. The unhappy, restless souls he encounters daily are
hardly of the Casper variety, and Cole's spirit-inflicted scratches
and bruises cast aspersions on his fiercely devoted mother (Toni
Collette). As the boy struggles to discover what the dead want from
him, Willis learns how to resolve his own marital problems at home,
and together they uncover more secrets than either of them had
bargained for.
</P>
<P>
   Director M. Night Shyamalan (whose previous picture ``Wide
Awake'' didn't bode well for this project) shows a firm grasp of
mood. Once the spooky business finally gets rolling, the chills
come fast and furious, aided by Osment's compelling depiction of
terror. Osment, remembered as the young ``Forrest Gump,'' has the
precocious, haunting speaking style of a channeling medium, and he
alone brings home some of the movie's most powerful moments.
</P>
<P>
   Willis isn't bad either, proving that his more soft-spoken,
introspective moments do more for his credibility as an actor than
dodging gunfire or blowing up buildings.
</P>
<P>
   But the film is ultimately done in by its frighteningly sluggish
pacing. It's loaded with great ideas, but crams most of them after
the halfway mark where most viewers will have either dozed off or
sneaked into the house next door to catch the last half of
``Mystery Men.''
</P>
<P>
   And missing the ending would be tragic, because ``Sixth Sense''
has one of the most surprisingly satisfying payoffs this year. It's
the perfect antidote for those put off by ``Blair Witch's''
deliberate vaguery. A little patience pays off. I promise.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Sixth Sense''
</P>
<P>
   Director: M. Night Shyamalan
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Bruce Willis, Haley Joel Osment
</P>
<P>
   Length: 115 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ violence, adult subject matter, spooky business
and disturbing imagery
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
