 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
 (gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are considering
for Page 1, Friday, Aug. 6. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOKE-CONFRIM (Washington) _ The Senate voted today to
confirm Richard C. Holbrooke as chief American diplomat to the
United Nations, ending a 14-month nomination battle that left the
Clinton administraton without a high-profile representative to the
United Nations during military conflicts in the Balkans and the
Persian Gulf. The Senate approved Holbrooke, the former American
ambassador to Germany and the architect of the 1995 peace agreement
in Bosnia, on a vote of 81 to 16. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ The government's investigation into
China's acquisition of U.S. nuclear weapons secrets was plagued by
widespread mistakes and misjudgements but no political
interference, according to the two ranking members of a Senate
committee that held closed hearings into the investigation. By Jeff
Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SECT (Beijing) _ China's fierce-looking crackdown on Falun
Gong, the spiritual movement that claims tens of millions of
followers, is turning out to be far less severe than it first
looked, with more propaganda than action. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congress gave its final approval
today to a Republican plan that would lower the income taxes of all
Americans who pay them, but the bill stands no chance of becoming
law. The House approved the bill on a party-line vote, 221 to 206;
the Senate is scheduled to vote about 7 p.m. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   TAX-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis: Are the Republicans,
or perhaps the Democrats, driving off a political cliff on tax
cuts? Almost all Republicans in Congress favor one, and almost all
Democrats are against it. Rarely have both parties sounded equally
confident about the political benefits they think their policies,
decided on principle alone, of course, will bring. With each side
sated with polling data and focus group results, the conflict
suggests that at least one side is taking a big chance on the
voters. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-CONGRESS (Washington) _ House Democrats and a group of
dissident Republicans were expected to reach agreement today on a
comprehensive bill to regulate the managed health care industry and
they challenged the Republican leadership to bring their measure to
a House vote in the fall. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MORRIS-MISS (Jackson, Miss.) _ The mourners said the same thing,
over and over. Willie Morris should have been here, to write about
this. Morris, one of the most loved writers of the modern South,
lay in state in the rotunda of the Old Capitol as hundreds of
people circled round and round, gazing at the dark-wood coffin
covered in white flowers before moving on to hug his wife, JoAnne
Prichard, her tired face drifting somewhere between a smile and a
sob. ``Willie,'' she said, ``would have loved this.'' ``Oh,'' said
his son, David Rae Morris, ``he does.'' By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   GRAND-CANYON (Denver) _ After years of analysis and pitched
debate, federal officials are planning to announce on Friday an
ambitious plan to develop national forest land beside Grand Canyon
National Park in Arizona that environmentalists are hailing as a
model for the future. The proposed Canyon Forest Village, 272 acres
at the south entrance of the park in the town of Tusayan,
represents a compromise that appears to have something for
everyone, making it a rare example of cooperation between two
forces _ environmentalists and developers _ who rarely agree on
anything in the West. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BEAR-FRAUD (New York) _ The Securities and Exchange Commission,
the Manhattan district attorney and Bear Stearns Securities Corp.
reached a settlement on Thursday in the nearly three-year-long
investigation into the brokerage firm's role in the 1996 failure of
A.R. Baron, a small, New York brokerage firm that defrauded
investors out of $75 million. Bear Stearns Securities Corp., the
giant trade-processing subsidiary of the Bear Stearns Companies,
was a cause of the securities fraud perpetrated on the investing
public by A.R. Baron, the SEC said. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   TV-STATION-OWNERSHIP (Undated) _ The FCC on Thursday voted to
liberalize rules limiting television station ownership, allowing a
single company or network to own two separate stations in the
largest cities. One immediate result of the decision may be a rush
by big television companies like the broadcast networks to sweep up
any available television stations in cities where they already own
a station. As put in one memo to the top corporate officers at one
of the four big broadcast networks, ``The race is on.'' By Bill
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CARDIO-DEATHS (Undated) _ The death rates from
cardiovascular diseases have plummeted by 60 percent since 1950,
the government announced today, making the conquest of this leading
killer of Americans one of the major public health achievements of
the twentieth century. The CDC report notes that stroke deaths have
declined almost linearly since the beginning of the century but
those from heart disease peaked in the 1960s and have been on a
downhill course ever since. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
