<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: ANCIENT ART FASHIONED OF FEATHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Try to imagine Ellsworth Kelly, Josef Albers and Mark Rothko
working 2,500 years ago in Peru. They would be using the same
lexicon of abstract art _ concentric circles, stripes, squares and
triangles _ but working entirely with exotic feathers instead of
paint.
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine that their finest creations had been placed in
burial tombs, only to be discovered in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   You now understand the impact that ancient Peruvian feather art
has had on today's sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, an exhibition opens in Bonn that features some feather
work. The show, at KAH, the Art and Exhibition Hall of the Federal
Republic of Germany, is called ``Orinoco-Parima, Indian Societies
in Venezuela: The Cisneros Collection'' and runs through Feb. 27,
2000. It includes weapons, baskets, musical instruments, ceremonial
artifacts and feather art collected by Gustavo and Patricia
Cisneros of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Feather art was used in many ancient societies in South America,
but most of what has survived comes from pre-Columbian Peru.
Several spectacular antique feather wall hangings from Peru are on
view in New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art, most of them
donations by Nelson A. Rockefeller. The colors are dramatic, and
the workmanship is exquisite. One has a large checkerboard
composition of four rectangular color-field panels, two of
brilliant blue feathers and two of bright yellow.
</P>
<P>
   They are testimony to the truth of Jean Renoir's comment that
masterpieces are made by artisans, not artists.
</P>
<P>
   These anonymous, magical works were made long before 1532, when
Francisco Pizarro and the Spanish conquistadors began their
conquest of Peru.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, by 1550, the Spanish religious authorities were so
worried about the shamanistic powers of feather textiles that they
ordered them destroyed; luckily they were not always obeyed.
</P>
<P>
   Feather textiles from Peru, Chile and Bolivia can go back 2,500
years. Most examples show the feathers arranged in dense,
overlapping rows. They were stitched onto horizontal threads called
hileras, which were then affixed to a natural or dyed woven cloth
ground. They are found on tunics, shirts, loincloths, belts,
headdresses and saddlebags, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   The cloth is either cotton or wool taken from South American
alpacas, llamas and vicunas.
</P>
<P>
   Why were these pieces made?
</P>
<P>
   James Reid, whose book ``Magic Feathers'' (Textile and Art
Publications, London) will be published in mid-2000, offered an
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the great fashion style for the elite: the hereditary
nobility, the military, the priests and local governors and
chiefs,'' he said. ``You can see these pieces from 100 yards; my
theory is that feather work was a kind of propaganda for the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid said that feathered clothing was ``a way in which
authorities could disseminate messages.'' For a people who had no
written language, the textiles would be as readable as the
stained-glass windows in a Gothic cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feather textiles were also clearly a religious form of tribute
to the deities,'' Reid continued. ``They paid homage to the gods up
above, to the sun, the rain, storms and snow, to the gods of this
earth, and to the gods of the underworld.''
</P>
<P>
   Ancient Peruvians were buried with feather works, which ``were
found in underground burial sites, in caves, in pyramids and in
above- ground burial areas,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   He gave this explanation for why Peruvian feather textiles have
survived more often than those from other cultures: ``That they
have survived so often in pristine condition is the consequence of
an elaborate burial and storage tradition, and of the felicitous
climatic condition of the dry, desert Pacific coast. It's one of
the driest areas in the world. It is particularly conducive to the
preservation of cloth and feather objects.''
</P>
<P>
   Feathers can retain their brilliant color for thousands of
years, and indeed, feather works are remarkable for their vivid
hues. Those who know tropical birds can identify the plumage of the
scarlet macaw, the flamingo, the Paradise tanager, the multicolored
mealy parrot, the parakeet, the pink roseate spoonbill, the white
hawk, the great egret and the Muscovy duck, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Some feathers were imported into Peru; others came from pet
birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feathers came from a variety of coastal, highland and jungle
birds,'' Reid said. ``There was a trade in feathers.''
</P>
<P>
   Those of brilliant red, chartreuse green, chrome yellow and
iridescent blue were prized. Gail Martin, a New York dealer who
specializes in textiles, has a pectoral from the Nazca people of
Peru that depicts what she calls her ``Keith Haring man.''
</P>
<P>
   It is covered in black, white, orange, green and blue feathers
and was made between A.D. 200 and 600. The price is $24,000.
</P>
<P>
   Feather designs can be as striking as their colors. The
iconography includes many figurative motifs: stylized
representations of humans, animals real and mythological and
deities.
</P>
<P>
   Some look like pictographs or geometrized humans like Ms.
Martin's ``Keith Haring man.'' Some animals, like the cameloids and
the monkeys, are easily identifiable. Others, like two-headed
snakes, represent deities.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the nonfigurative motifs: the square, the circle,
the zigzag and the triangle. Reid said the triangle might represent
a pyramid, and the zigzag might stand for a mountain peak in the
soaring Andes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mountain peaks were revered both for being sacred places as
well as for being associated with the source of water,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other pre-Columbian motifs include a curvilinear wave, a Grecian
fret and a cross, all prevalent long before contact with Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ancient people of Peru arrived, through a universal
subconscious, at an esthetic beauty,'' Reid said. ``These feather
pieces have an aura to them that other textiles do not.''
</P>
<P>
   The Peruvians knew how to use abstraction for esthetic effect,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reid added: ``The textile museums have missed the boat on
feather art because all they focus on is warp and weft. The modern
art museums shy away because they call it artisan craftwork. I want
to do a show displaying feather works next to paintings by Morris
Louis, Brice Marden and Kenneth Noland.''
</P>
<P>
   Three New York galleries that carry some feather art are Merrin,
at 724 Fifth Ave., at 56th Street; Throckmorton Fine Art, at 153 E.
61st St., and Gail Martin, 310 Riverside Drive, at 103rd Street
(open by appointment).
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from a few thousand dollars to occasionally more
than $100,000 for a single feather work.
</P>
</TEXT>
