<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-IRONGIANT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `GIANT' STEP FOR WARNER BROS. ANIMATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Iron Giant'' is an animated film of such charm that it's a
shame that it cops out on itself with an overdone gunbattle in the
final act. Not that the little boys it's aimed at will mind,
although their parents might raise an eyebrow or two over a cartoon
with a few instances of mild swearing (which is probably no worse
than what you'd hear in an average schoolyard).
</P>
<P>
   Based very loosely on poet Ted Hughes' 1968 children's book
``The Iron Man'' (renamed ``The Iron Giant'' in the United States),
``Giant'' is yet another variation on ``E.T.,'' but at least it's
one of the better variations. In this boy-meets-alien story, set in
1957, the boy is Hogarth (voice of Eli Marienthal), a precocious
lad with a tendency toward junk food and past-his-bedtime horror
movies. One night, while investigating a problem with his TV
reception, he runs into the Iron Giant, an alien robot with an
insatiable appetite for metal.
</P>
<P>
   You know what happens next. Boy and robot bond. Boy tries to
keep robot hidden from adults, especially attractive single mom
(Jennifer Aniston). Government loon (Christopher McDonald) begins
suspecting that something fishy is going on, and becomes film's
villain. Boy enlists aid of older, cooler friend (Harry Connick
Jr.), an artist who, conveniently enough, runs a scrap-metal yard _
or, as it's known to the Iron Giant, a buffet.
</P>
<P>
   None of the story is particularly original, and it varies so
widely from Hughes' book _ although the poet acted as a consultant
before his death last year _ that it's a wonder the filmmakers
actually call it an adaptation. But director Brad Bird, making his
feature debut here after his TV work with such shows as ``The
Simpsons'' and ``King of the Hill,'' makes up for a lot with his
obvious affection for the material.
</P>
<P>
   Bird's animation won't make anybody over at Disney lose any
sleep, but anyone who complains about the occasional static
qualities of the images in missing the point. The drawing has a
pleasant retro feel, as if Bird were trying to replicate what a
1957 animator would have done with modern-day tools; he focuses on
expressive faces while supplying more impressionistic backgrounds.
He also has a great feel for period flavor _ check out the scene in
which bored elementary-school pupils sit through a choppy ``duck
and cover'' nuclear-paranoia film.
</P>
<P>
   Bird and screenwriter Tim McCanlies (who wrote and directed
``Dancer, TX'') aren't above playing to the baser interests of
young kids, and they throw in a bit of benign (and quite funny)
toilet humor. But they seem in conflict with themselves; one of the
messages of the movie is that guns are bad _ a pretty radical
statement for Hollywood product, when you think about it _ but then
they deflate the message with the movie's over-the-top climax,
which involves a lot of cool-looking gun stuff. In these scenes
McDonald, a specialist in smarmy villainy, really overdoes it as
the wacky federal agent, but since he's saddled with an overwritten
character, he's not really to blame.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is Warner Bros.' third major entry in the animation
war, after the likable but forgettable ``Quest for Camelot'' and
the what-were-they-thinking pickup of Rankin/Bass' ``The King and
I.'' ``Giant'' is an indication that there may be hope, after all,
for Warner Bros.; it looks unique, and it doesn't bow to
traditional animation formulas (i.e., there are no talking-animal
sidekicks). It's diverting, and it held the attention of the kids
at a fairly crowded screening. But it comes up short of being the
truly special film it could have been.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Iron Giant''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Brad Bird
</P>
<P>
   Voices: Harry Connick Jr., Jennifer Aniston, Christopher
McDonald
</P>
<P>
   Length: 84 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ adult language and subject matter and violence
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
