<HEADER>
A6982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      08-05 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Renzo Piano Revisits Texas
</P>
<P>
   More than two years after the collector and developer Raymond D.
Nasher announced plans to establish a sculpture garden on two acres
next to the Dallas Museum of Art, he has chosen the Italian
architect Renzo Piano to design it.
</P>
<P>
   Piano, who won the Pritzker Prize in 1998, has designed several
museums, among them the Beyeler Foundation in Basel, Switzerland;
the Menil Collection in Houston, and, with the British architect
Richard Rogers, the Georges Pompidou Center in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to a number of architects and felt that Renzo's ideas
were poetic and very exciting,'' Nasher said. ``He best understood
the nature of the project, that the garden needs to be flexible
since we are contemplating doing a different exhibition every
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Piano said he had explored the relationship between art and
nature in several museum designs. ``I think of this more as an
open-air museum than a sculpture garden,'' he added. ``To my
knowledge there is no other truly urban sculpture garden of this
size in the world. I hope it will be a model for others.''
</P>
<P>
   Completion of the Nasher Sculpture Center is scheduled for 2001
and the preliminary design drawings and models will be developed by
the fall. So far, Piano's plans call for a large protected space
where small, more fragile sculptures can be shown. The plans would
also put the garden below street level to make it seem like an
archeological find.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great attractions to the space is that it is
sitting in the middle of the mess of the city, not paradise,''
Piano said. ``I've always been intrigued by the relationship
between the sacred _ the art _ and the profane _ the street. I like
that idea.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Getty as Muse &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While most of its permanent collection dates from before 1900,
the J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles is beginning to organize
exhibitions that feature the work of contemporary artists.
</P>
<P>
   Its first large-scale group show, which will run from Feb. 29
through May 7, is ``Departures: 11 Artists at the Getty.'' It will
consist of commissioned pieces produced by 11 Los Angeles artists
in response to works in the Getty collection.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the artists are internationally known while others are
not familiar names.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was interested in seeing a broad response to the Getty's
collection from people at different points in their careers,'' said
Lisa Lyons, the show's guest curator. ``I thought it would be
particularly interesting to see many unexpected connections these
artists make between their work and pieces from the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The artists are John Baldessari, Uta Barth, Sharon Ellis, Judy
Fiskin, Martin Kersels, John M. Miller, Ruben Ortiz-Torres, Lari
Pittman, Stephen Prina, Alison Saar and Adrian Saxe. Using the
Getty's collection as inspiration, they will create new works in
media that include painting, sculpture, photography and film.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to helping the Getty organize a schedule of
contemporary art exhibitions, Ms. Lyons, formerly the director of
art programs at the Lannan Foundation in Los Angeles, has also been
involved in commissioning public art for areas on the Getty
Center's sprawling campus.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Edward Ruscha's ``Picture Without Words,'' which was
designed for the lobby of the Harold M. Williams Auditorium in the
center, and a multimedia installation made by Alexis Smith for the
Getty's restaurant, will soon be a 45-foot-tall sculpture by Martin
Puryear, which was commissioned for the museum's entry plaza.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture, made of welded, sandblasted stainless-steel tubes
bound at the joints by strands of bronze, will rise from a
travertine pavement, its form suggesting a delicate fish net and a
human head. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cultural Exchange &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the latest exchange of art between museums, the Pitti Gallery
in Florence, Italy, will lend the Art Institute of Chicago two of
the greatest portraits of the Italian Renaissance _ one by Titian
and one by Raphael _ and the Art Institute will lend the Pitti
seven landscapes by Monet.
</P>
<P>
   Both loans are firsts of a sort. The Raphael will be shown
outside Europe for the first time. (The Titian has been exhibited
once before in the United States, in the ``Titian, Prince of
Painters'' exhibition in 1990 at the National Gallery in
Washington.) And the Pitti's show will be the first in Italy
devoted solely to Monet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to fill gaps in each other's collections,'' said
Larry J. Feinberg, a curator in the department of European painting
at the Art Institute. ``The Pitti owns no Monets and while we do
have some Italian Renaissance portraits, they are not as good.''
</P>
<P>
   The portraits coming to Chicago are among the Pitti's
masterpieces. The Raphael, ``The Veiled Lady'' (circa 1516), is
considered the artist's greatest portrait and was inspired partly
by Leonardo da Vinci's ``Mona Lisa.'' Titian's ``Young Englishman''
(circa 1540-45) dates to the artist's early maturity.
</P>
<P>
   The portraits will be hung with a small group of Renaissance
portraits from the Art Institute's collection. The show, which runs
from Dec. 15 through March 19, will trace how these masters changed
portraiture in 16th-century Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will also explore issues of gender, as well as the
Florentine School versus the Venetian School,'' Feinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The Art Institute's Monets are on view at the Pitti until Sept.
1.
</P>
<P>
   Portraits on Tour
</P>
<P>
   The National Museum of American Art isn't the only part of the
Smithsonian Institution that has established a traveling-exhibition
program while its home is being renovated. The National Portrait
Gallery, which shares the Old Patent Office Building on F Street
with the museum, must also close for about three years and will
also send several exhibitions drawn from its collection to museums
here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   But an affiliated institution, the Renwick Gallery, on
Pennsylvania Avenue at 17th Street, will remain open and offer its
full program of crafts exhibitions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
