<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHOPTALK: SEPHORA
 &HT;    Wall-to-wall beauty, fragrance with French accent
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 8.
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Name: Sephora, a huge cosmetics and beauty store. Opened June
18 in Lenox Square and July 23 in Gwinnett Place Mall. In 1993, the
first Sephora store debuted in Paris; today there are more than 100
of them in Europe and 28 in the United States, with 22 more set to
open by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The pitch: Think of it as a self-service shopping emporium for
cosmetics aficionados. ``It's total freedom,'' says Libby Carroll,
store director at the Lenox location. ``You can touch, feel and
smell. And you won't be sprayed with perfume when you enter the
store. Nor will a consultant (salesperson) ask you if you need any
help. You can sample products on your own, make selections, then
take them to a cashier _ without ever speaking to anyone. If,
however, you prefer to shop with a consultant, we also offer that
service.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The merchandise mix: As you enter a Sephora store, you are
blown away by the number of products, ranging from fragrances and
foundations to skin treatments and shampoos. Up front are Sephora's
private-label items, which include bath products (average price
$20) in yummy colors and fragrances; nail polishes (a 0.1-ounce
bottle for $3.50); potpourri ($8); professional tools such as
makeup brushes (a set is $15); and clear wax candles ($18-$22) done
especially for the store by Perfumes Isabell. What's lots of fun is
the massive lipstick bar, holding 365 tubes of lipstick ($9 each)
ranging from white to black and every color in between, including
green, yellow and blue along with the obvious shades.
</P>
<P>
   In the World of Color (blushes, eye shadows and liners,
foundations and lipsticks), the store offers some of the biggest
names in classic makeup: Christian Dior, Shu Uemura, Givenchy and
Shiseido. Cutting-edge lines include Anna Sui, Comfort Zone, Hard
Candy, Urban Decay, Tony &AMP; Tina, Club Monaco (an exclusive), Bloom
and Two Faced. One of the most popular is Stila, known for high
quality and low prices.
</P>
<P>
   At the back of the store, treatment products, including such
prestigious lines as Juvena, Decleor, Cellex C, Peter Thomas Roth
and Naturopathica, are showcased in the Library and arranged by
categories of need: dry skin, oily skin, sun, body, hair and face.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Making scents: Fragrances are organized alphabetically _ men's
on the left, women's on the right _ along the walls. And best
sellers are displayed in a special nook.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The decor: Contemporary tones of red, black and white
dominate. Consultants wear French-made black tunics and trousers.
Women wear only red lipstick and red or natural-color nail polish _
and no jewelry except a watch. Each consultant wears one black
glove so that he or she can show off a product in the best light,
as a jeweler uses a black velvet pad to display gems to a client.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Great gift idea: The store offers empty boxes so that you can
create a personalized gift filled with combinations of soaps,
bubble bath, room sprays, bath oils and potpourri. Complimentary
wraps include black or red paper and textured ribbons. Average
price is $30.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thoughtful gestures: Baskets are available to hold goodies
while you shop. Also, you can freely test makeup throughout the
store. And candy is at the cashier stand, free for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vital statistics: Open 10 a.m.-9 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays;
noon-6 p.m. Sundays. All major credit cards accepted. At Lenox
Square, 404-816-0123; at Gwinnett Place Mall, 678-473-4711.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
