<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLARIWITCH06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spooky storyteller scared even actors in `Blair Witch'
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The script isn't the only thing spooky about ``The
Blair Witch Project.''
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who has seen the film will remember near the beginning
the woman holding a toddler. She's interviewed by the on-screen
actors as they start to make their documentary of the harrowing
witch tale.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the woman says, she's heard of the Blair Witch.
Immediately she starts spouting off eerie details. And her toddler
protests, shouting out ``No!''
</P>
<P>
   Surely the woman is an actress just like almost everyone else in
the fictional ``Blair Witch,'' the box office phenomenon, which on
Friday expands to about 2,150 theaters nationwide. But she isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really know who or where she is,'' says ``Blair
Witch'' producer Robin Cowie, formerly of Marietta. ``We've tried
for two years to find her, but to no avail.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the film's improvisational setup, ``Blair Witch's''
main actors _ Heather Donahue, Joshua Leonard and Michael Williams
_ were sent to Burkittsville, Md., and told to search for people to
talk about the made-up ``Blair Witch'' tale. Other actors had been
planted in the town to give the details needed to move the story
along.
</P>
<P>
   ``They found this woman in a restaurant,'' says ``Blair Witch''
co-director/writer Eduardo Sanchez. ``She made that stuff up. We
could not have scripted what she did any better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It sent chills up my spine,'' says Donahue, who talked with
the woman while filming the scene. ``When I got that I knew I had
struck gold. That moment had to be the scariest moment in the movie
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, all that the film's creators know about the woman is the
name she gave Donahue in a release before the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've asked all around Burkittsville and no one knows her,''
Cowie says. ``Apparently she was visiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Could she be the Blair Witch?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oooh,'' Cowie says.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few other little-known facts and news updates about
``The Blair Witch Project,'' which Artisan Entertainment, the
movie's distributor, estimates will ultimately top $100 million at
the box office:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Last weekend, moviegoers in Cobb County stoked the film's box
office more than any other area of metro Atlanta. The movie made
$65,349 at AMC's Barrett Commons 24 in Kennesaw, far outpacing the
take at other local movie cineplexes, according to Artisan. The box
office at some other theaters: $39,187 at AMC's Southlake Pavilion
24 in Morrow; $35,839 at United Artists' Tara Cinema in Atlanta;
$35,831 at AMC's Colonial 18 in Lawrenceville; $32,241 at AMC's
Mansell Crossing 14 in Alpharetta; and $30,032 at Regal's Hollywood
24 in DeKalb County.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Artisan and the ``Blair Witch'' creative team are expected to
meet on Monday to discuss sequel options. Steve Rothenberg,
Artisan's executive vice president of domestic sales, says his firm
``hopes'' to have a sequel in theaters for summer 2000. ``We'd sure
like to make it with the original team,'' Rothenberg says.
</P>
<P>
   Cowie, however, says the ``Blair Witch'' team's view is that
``you're not going to see it next summer _ not from us at least.''
He says his group will be concentrating on making a comedy called
``Heart of Love.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Blair Witch'' team has developed ideas for what the group
is calling a ``sequel/prequel.'' Speculation is that it might
involve the original 1785 witch tale and/or the 1940s serial killer
case, both mentioned in the film.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Blair Witch's'' frightening final moments were actually shot
over three nights (the filmmakers had to return in part because the
light on Donahue's camera went out). The last of the filming
happened on Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Throughout filming, the cast's food supply dwindled. Donahue
says that in the final days she ate nothing but bananas and power
bars. Williams took a different tact. ``I got so tired of power
bars I decided not to eat,'' he says. On screen you see him slowly
munching on a big tree leaf. Yes, he ate it. Williams says his
character ``was so gone he doesn't even realize what he's doing and
he doesn't care. He's kind of in la-la land at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The spooky rundown house exists in Seneca Creek State Park in
Maryland. ``We had to add support to some of the flooring, but
that's about it,'' Cowie says. The creepy kid-size handprints on
the walls were made by the three young nephews of the movie's art
director, Ricardo R. Moreno.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The movie was made in Maryland for one simple reason.
Co-director Sanchez was living there. ``I grew up in Maryland,'' he
says. And it's where he was driving a delivery truck and suffering
from depression after the failure of another full-length film
``Gabriel's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when the creators of ``Blair Witch'' decided to give
filmmaking one more try.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
