<HEADER>
A6985 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAZZ-LALAH06-COX     08-05 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-LALAH06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pop vocalist Lalah Hathaway finally makes commercial waves in
jazz pairing with pianist Joe Sample
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Having an R&AMP;B career on hold for five years hasn't
been a bad thing for Lalah Hathaway. Particularly since she thinks
R&AMP;B is pretty bad of late.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like this music has forsaken the whole art of A&AMP;R,
watching an artist develop, and having a story to tell with a
beginning, middle and end,'' says the 30-year-old daughter of one
of the genre's most revered talents, the late Donny Hathaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially for black girls who want to do something other than
shake (their) butts,'' she quips.
</P>
<P>
   And she should know. Even with a famous last name, Hathaway had
it hard when her self-titled debut came out in 1990. Around that
time, another young woman with an even more familiar name _ Jackson
_ was welcoming listeners into her multimillion-selling ``Rhythm
Nation.'' And, frankly, few seemed to have a problem with Janet
Jackson's ``hip-centered'' choreography.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lalah Hathaway'' came from a completely different direction
than the heavily produced albums that peers such as Jackson, Jody
Watley and Paula Abdul were releasing. The focus was on vocal
quality, not being videogenic. Commercially, it flopped.
</P>
<P>
   Unbowed, Hathaway followed it in 1994 with ``A Moment,'' which
was also a sales disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   In jazz circles, however, many were taking notice of Hathaway's
silken, husky alto. Bassist-producer Marcus Miller asked her to
record and tour with him. Then she joined keyboardist-producer
Herbie Hancock on the road overseas. And, as early as 1992, pianist
Joe Sample asked her to accompany him stateside on a tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working so closely with Lalah has helped me to better
appreciate her ability to convey powerful emotions in subtle
ways,'' Sample says, ``which is not typical of so many of today's
pop singers.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet their first album together, Billboard's Top 5
contemporary jazz effort ``The Song Lives On,'' may finally be
elevating Hathaway to pop success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's found her niche,'' says Jay McLaughlin, morning
announcer on jazz station WCLK-FM (91.9). ``My listeners actually
listen, and obviously aren't driven by MTV and what have you. And
it's quite clear she's a talented young lady. I don't know a lot of
R&AMP;B singers that can just come over and start singing jazz. And be
received like she has been.''
</P>
<P>
   Hathaway's contemporary jazz work has kept her busy during the
half-decade she hasn't had her own album.
</P>
<P>
   Content is another matter altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't always want to be singing smooth jazz either,'' says
Hathaway, who is far more pleasant than her feelings for certain
kinds of music.
</P>
<P>
   `` A lot of my friends do smooth jazz, and I support them,'' she
continues on the phone from her Los Angeles home. ``But it's not
really my cup of tea.''
</P>
<P>
   So, believe it or not, despite what she thinks of it now,
Hathaway still wants a career in rhythm and blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's at my core,'' she says. ``I can't let the business
dissuade me. I want to record again.''
</P>
<P>
   But she's not going after a record contract the easy way; she's
recording a tribute album to her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it's something I'm interested in,'' she says. ``I could
walk into a deal now and do that. But I really think that would be
the most anticlimactic thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm young and I have time to, need to, re-establish myself
with the audience,'' Hathaway says. ``Doing that would kind of be
like getting over. People say, `Well, Natalie Cole did it.' But
Natalie had been around and recording for like 18 years, been
through counseling, been through rehab, and been through a lot that
emotionally I'm not prepared to do either. I have a legacy, and I'm
not prepared to squander it away by doing the okie doke.''
</P>
<P>
   Or the shakey-shake, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Sample,
</P>
<P>
   Lalah Hathaway
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight. $25 and $37.50. Atlanta Symphony Hall, Woodruff Arts
Center, 1280 Peachtree St. N.E. 404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
