<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6986 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACING-EXHIBIT06-COX     08-05 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACING-EXHIBIT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South's passion for racing gets artistic salute
 &HT;    By Tom Patterson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Since its advent in the years after World War
II, stock car racing has enjoyed a wide following in the South, and
North Carolina has been one of the hotbeds of this daredevil motor
sport.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of capitalizing on its mass appeal, the Green Hill
Center for North Carolina Art is presenting a show of contemporary
works inspired by stock car racing. Titled ``Just Racin': Art on
Wheels,'' it is curated by Roger Halligan, a sculptor from Randolph
County, N.C. Most of the works were created for this show, and few
of the 29 artists had demonstrated any particular interest in stock
car racing before they were invited to participate.
</P>
<P>
   The show's theme isn't likely to inspire work of great depth or
profundity, and, indeed, it hasn't. Several artists have
contributed relatively straightforward images of cars and races
that do nothing more than illustrate the most obvious aspects of
the sport, and the selection could have been improved by weeding
out such mediocre pieces. Nonetheless, a predominance of works that
are as brash, loud and garish as stock car racing itself _ and a
prevalent cartoon aesthetic that's entirely appropriate to the
theme _ make this a generally lively and often amusing exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   The more effective pieces celebrate well-known stock car
drivers. The cleverest of several that pay lighthearted homage to
the South's most famous driver, Richard Petty, is Rob Kowski's
``Life Is Good.'' This plastic pink flamingo lawn ornament, an icon
of white-trash culture, has been transformed into a caricature of
Petty, wearing miniature versions of his trademark cowboy hat,
wraparound sunglasses and cowboy boots. To complete the portrayal,
its hooked beak has been painted with a cartoon rendition of
Petty's familiar grin. Wendell Scott (1921-1990), the first
African-American champion racer in NASCAR, is depicted by Roy
Nydorf. ``Homage to Wendell Scott'' juxtaposes a realistic portrait
of a fiercely heroic-looking Scott attired in a racing helmet with
background images of his No. 34 cars. With its flamboyantly
scripted caption texts, this painting recalls the bold style of old
movie posters.
</P>
<P>
   Scott is memorialized in more symbolic fashion in Mark Brown's
``Shrine for the Short Track (for Wendell).'' This mock trophy cup
and its wheel-mounted pedestal is covered in a multicolored
patchwork of nailed-on metal scraps salvaged from the exteriors of
several stock cars. In its formal and material aspects, it alludes
to Scott's cultural heritage by referencing traditions of African
ritual sculpture and black folk recycling.
</P>
<P>
   In an exhibit that emphasizes cars more than it does drivers,
the most imaginative depictions of stock cars are sculptures by
Luis Jimenez and Robbie Barber, which highlight the implications of
sex and violence within the stock car subculture. Jimenez, a New
Mexico sculptor who is the show's most widely known artist, is
represented by ``Demo Derby,'' a fiberglass model car whose
parenthetical subtitle, ``(Pure Sex),'' underlines the association
between fast cars and sex that is an essential component of
American capitalist mythology. This curvaceous caricature of a
stock car has a red-accented metal-flake blue exterior emblazoned
with numbers and slogans in a lurid shade of Day-Glo orange, and
it's equipped with electronically illuminated head and tail lights.
</P>
<P>
   Barber's realistically detailed painted-wood replica of a Ford
Fairlane emblazoned with a large No. 11 and a series of decals
bearing the logos of well-known auto racing sponsors is titled
``Good Ole Boys,'' in honor of the kind of men who form the core of
the car-racing audience in the South. Under its hood is a
velvet-lined case that holds a snub-nosed .38-caliber revolver and
six bullets, and its open trunk reveals a pint bottle of Southern
Comfort whiskey. The gun is an emblem of the Southern obsession
with firearms, and the trunk full of liquor is an allusion to the
illicit transportation of bootleg whiskey _ a job at which more
than one Southern stock car racer learned the art of high-speed
driving.
</P>
<P>
   Other noteworthy pieces include Dan Millspaugh's monumental
cast-aluminum effigy of a robotlike ``Gas Man''; Ginger Spangler's
text-augmented collages about the rural origins of Southern stock
car racing; John Rosenthal's trackside photograph of a huge balloon
in the shape of a cigarette pack; Stacy Lambert's clever ceramic
treatments of stock car drivers, pit crew members and racing
sponsors; and Mark Kingsley's small paintings of cars racing up and
down a mountain that resembles the biblical Tower of Babel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just Racin':
</P>
<P>
   Art on Wheels''
</P>
<P>
   Through Aug. 27. 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays; 10 a.m.-7
p.m. Wednesdays; 2-5 p.m. Sundays. Green Hill Center for North
Carolina Art, Greensboro Cultural Center, 200 N. Davie St.,
Greensboro, N.C. 336-333-7460.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A lively show.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Patterson is a free-lance writer based in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
