<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clothing blocks sun
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 8.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Got sunscreen?
</P>
<P>
   Men, women and children all need some form of protection from
the sun's harmful ultraviolet rays, and summer is the time of
highest risk. But people often forget or neglect to apply
protective creams and lotions to the skin laid bare by short-sleeve
shirts, swimsuits, short pants and the like. For them, there's an
innovative solution: sun-blocking apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Florida-based Solarveil America has introduced a wide-ranging
collection of beach wear, sportswear and hats in a revolutionary
fabric rendered in 10 colors. Its patented Solarveil fabric is a
breathable, open-weave knit that blocks up to 80 percent of UVA and
UVB rays; a double layer blocks up to 95 percent of the rays. The
collection includes golf caps, sarongs, polo shirts and drawstring
pants. They range in price from $25 to $85 and come in men's,
women's and children's sizes.
</P>
<P>
   The collection is available by calling 1-800-400-3377 or by
visiting www.solarveil.com. A list of retail locations is posted on
the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   _ A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
