<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6989 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-05 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET THE SUNSHINE IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chief Justice William Rehnquist sits atop one of
our three equal branches of government. He is a powerful figure who
exercises immeasurable influence over all our lives.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when he appeared in the Senate chamber to preside over the
impeachment trial of President Clinton, it was the first time that
most Americans had ever seen him in motion or heard him speak.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist was a novice to television. We live in an age
dominated by visual images _ but not at the Supreme Court and the
lower federal court system.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist and several other Supreme Court justices adamantly
oppose allowing television cameras to record the court's public
proceedings; not a single justice actively favors allowing cameras
in the curt. The result: The justices, unlike officials of the
other two branches, operate virtually in secret.
</P>
<P>
   The justices do not want their personal comments spread about
and they do not want to assist journalists trying to report on the
brief public hearings they conduct before making major decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David Souter, considered a centrist on most other
issues, has plenty of company when he vows that there will be no
cameras as long as he is on the bench. He told me he believes that
television has a distorting influence on a courtroom, artificially
affecting the way judges, witnesses and lawyers behave and
distracting everyone from the legal issues involved.
</P>
<P>
   The single concession from the high bench was a ruling in 1981
that, as a matter of principle, cameras in the courtroom are now so
unobtrusive they do not disrupt sober legal thought and are
therefore not unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Only two federal appellate circuits permit television coverage
of civil appeals cases and only 14 of 89 federal districts courts
permit judges to allow TV or radio coverage. None of the federal
courts permit television in criminal proceedings at either the
trial or appellate level.
</P>
<P>
   State courts have been far more receptive to expanding access to
public trials; 47 states allow some form of audio-visual coverage
of court proceedings, at the judge's discretion.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans are not aware of the television blackout by the
federal courts because they have followed saturation TV coverage of
notorious cases that occurred in state courts. The O.J. Simpson
murder trial and the William Kennedy Smith rape trial, for
instance, became such media carnivals for posturing celebrities
that justice seemed like an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   The Simpson case was particularly outrageous. But television was
not at the root of it. The event itself was the problem. In our
entertainment-driven, race-influenced culture, that trial was
destined to spin out of control whether cameras were inside the
courtroom or poised for self-serving interviews outside it.
</P>
<P>
   If we weren't fascinated, of course, we didn't have to watch.
But we did watch, by the millions. Television is a fact of modern
life and federal judges cannot defy the public interest forever.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee gave the issue a push recently by
passing a measure that would allow federal judges to permit
television cameras in their courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would merely authorize the right to include cameras,
not require them. A similar measure is pending in the Senate and
both appear to have a good chance of passage.
</P>
<P>
   The issue here is how much it weakens our democratic system to
pretend we are still a rural, slow-paced nation in which locals
wander down to the courthouse to catch up on the legal news. These
days we mostly get our information from television and the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Through modern technology millions of people instantly have
access to gobs of information about what is going on in the world.
Sometimes it overwhelms us with too much of a good thing. But if we
are to understand how our judicial system works, that is how we
will learn about it in the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
   And this is a good thing. Cameras can provide the whole story of
a trial, not just an edited version filtered through a reporter's
eyes or the pen of a court artist. The machine is a more objective
observer than the human.
</P>
<P>
   Experiments with cameras in a few federal courthouses between
1991 and 1993 were generally viewed as successful by the judges.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that if you believe in open government,
judicial credibility and mass public participation, the federal
courts cannot be excluded from modern means of communication.
Justice will not be respected if it takes place in an antiquated
context.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the judicial reform measure has bipartisan support.
It is sponsored in the House by Reps. Steve Chabot, R-Ohio, and
William Delahunt, D-Mass., and in the Senate by Sens. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y., and Chuck Grassley, R-Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Chabot noted that ``open trials will help ensure the fair
administration of justice.'' He added pointedly that because
federal judges are political appointees who serve for life, their
roles should be constantly observed, discussed and evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine. If President Clinton had been indicted and tried
for perjury or obstruction of justice rather than impeached by
Congress, he would have been in the dock in a federal courtroom
that could accommodate only a select few to observe whether he got
a fair trial or not. The lack of internal cameras would have
exacerbated the inevitable media circus outside and raised
suspicions that all was not right within.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLIAMSTOWN-TRAVEL-A     08-05 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMSTOWN-TRAVEL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER IS JUST THE FIRST ACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. _ When summer comes and the golden yarrow is
blooming, this impossibly tidy New England town revels in its
nickname, ``The Village Beautiful,'' and in the usual tension of
dramas that divide twins, trap lost souls, rile shrews and inspire
neutrons to burst into song.
</P>
<P>
   Benedict Arnold and Henry David Thoreau may have retreated for a
respite to this village in the Berkshires of northern
Massachusetts, but the theater tourists drawn here are seeking
something more dynamic at the annual Williamstown Theater Festival.
For three months each summer, festival organizers mount an
ambitious schedule of new plays and classics that tap the talent of
Broadway and Hollywood. (The actor Ethan Hawke recently played the
doomed boxer in Tennessee Williams' ``Camino Real'' and Gwyneth
Paltrow is performing in Shakespeare's ``As You Like It'' this
month.) This year, from June to Aug. 29, 11 plays are being
performed.
</P>
<P>
   The tranquil setting does not influence the selection, said
Michael Ritchie, the producer of the festival, but it does help
lure actors, many of whom live during performances at the
dormitories of Williams College, a small, 206-year-old liberal arts
institution at the foot of Mount Greylock, the highest peak in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier time, the benefits of a retreat to the area duly
impressed Thoreau, who remarked that ``it would be no small
advantage if every small college were thus located at the base of a
mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``some will remember, no doubt, not only that they
went to college, but that they went to the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   The same advantage holds for the festival, said Ritchie, who
noted that the New England setting was ``a great hook in terms of
making an appeal to actors. It's an idyllic town of brick walls
surrounded by these beautiful mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   For the uncelebrated tourist without a script for a long
weekend, Williamstown is not only a draw for its theater but also a
convenient staging area for a leisurely drive along the 63 miles of
the Mohawk Trail, the only motor road of the pre-World War I era
still in use in the United States. Opened in 1914, the Mohawk Trail
(Route 2) is a two-lane road that follows the old footpath of trade
through northern Massachusetts. It was once used by five nations of
American Indians, including the Mohawk of New York and the Pocumtuc
of the Connecticut River Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Roaming with a 2-year-old, the road beckoned for its hypnotic
effect on my passenger on a day when I didn't have a ticket to a
matinee. The air was cool and scented with wildflowers. The
sweeping view from Western Summit, or Spirit Mountain, as it was
known by Indians, takes in Mount Prospect, Mount Williams and Mount
Greylock, where Herman Melville and Nathaniel Hawthorne once met,
and the site this October for a ``ramble hike'' for an expected
crowd of 3,000 hikers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mohawk Trail's twists, dips and landmark hairpin turn
conjured up the epigraph for the script for the dreamy ``Camino
Real,'' which I had seen a day earlier: ``In the middle of the
journey of our life I came to myself in a dark wood where the
straight way was lost.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a road that can lead a traveler to quirky landmarks, odd
adventures or serious institutions. For example, the newly
renovated 19th-century brick mill complex that houses the
Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art in North Adams. This
community bills itself the city of spires for its abundance of
churches; in autumn, it is host to one of New England's oldest
celebrations, the foliage parade. In Williamstown itself, the
Sterling &AMP; Francine Clark Art Institute draws busloads of tourists
for its expansive collection of Impressionist art, including more
than 30 Renoirs, and a current exhibition devoted to the work of
the 19th-century artist Jean-Francois Millet.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mohawk Trail is also a path to the unexpected, a place
where the local guidebooks suggest short detours off the trail for
llama treks to sunset picnics or touring a climate-controlled
shiitake mushroom farm or glacial potholes. In a deserted clearing
looms the ``Hail to the Sunrise'' monument of a lone Indian in a
loincloth with outstretched arms. A short detour south leads to an
arched trolley bridge built in 1908 and now transformed into a
vivid garden of carefully labeled day lilies, primroses and
petunias.
</P>
<P>
   The Shelburne Falls ``Bridge of Flowers'' is described as
internationally famous in local guidebooks, but I was unfamiliar
with this 400-foot bridge, spanning the Deerfield River. It is
blooming with some 500 varieties that are tended by volunteers from
the Shelburne Falls Women's Club, which created the garden in 1929.
On Aug. 14, the village of Victorian homes and shops will be host
to the Bridge of Flowers Classic Road Race with a 10-kilometer and
two-mile run.
</P>
<P>
   Shelburne Falls is also home to a trolley museum that displays
the last surviving trolley car from the Shelburne-Colrain trolley
line, which used to rattle along the Bridge of Flowers. For years
the No. 10 sat idle after roads were improved and trucking drove
out the trolley business that hauled freight from the rail yard in
Shelburne Falls to mills in Colrain, Mass. In retirement the
trolley car doubled as a chicken coop in a farmer's field, but now
it is restored, and the museum and its volunteers are preparing to
operate it for passenger runs perhaps by October, when autumn-leaf
tourists head for the Berkshires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping it's going to run, but we're not promising it,''
said the museum's president, Tony Jewell.
</P>
<P>
   From the Bridge of Flowers, a two-lane road leads to little
galleries and a glass-blowing shop and candle-making factory, Mole
Hollow Candles, with a wide window on the workers dipping rows of
hundreds of sleek white tapers. Candles with imperfections are sold
at a discount footsteps away in a seconds store.
</P>
<P>
   And just beyond the candle factory is a lookout spot for viewing
glacial potholes, a tumble of ancient granite rocks smoothed and
scupltured by whirlpools just below Salmon Falls, which was a run
for salmon on their way to spawning grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Our trip along the Mohawk Trail was limited by a deadline to
return to Williamstown for the theater, but I made mental notes of
little detours that I planned to make in the future. One would be
to the apple orchards just north of the trail off Route 112 in
Colrain, where the West County Winery offers tastings of its hard
cider wines. Nearby is one of four covered bridges in the area, the
1886 Arthur Smith Bridge across the North River.
</P>
<P>
   I was curious about watching the salmon on a spawning journey
upstream between May and mid-June at a fish ladder along Turners
Falls, where there is a grotto that is a Roman Catholic shrine to
the Blessed Kateri Tekakwitha, the Lily of the Mohawks.
</P>
<P>
   The return to Williamstown was placid. The road was marked with
bear-crossing signs, but none of the animals shared the trail with
us. We were somewhat disappointed that the restaurant at the fabled
hairpin turn was closed for renovations, but Thoreau was right
about the comforting qualities of Williamstown, which at twilight
was a peaceful place for a walk along the village's own little
bridge blooming with flowers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The main road in Williamstown leads toward the Williams campus,
the dominant white clock tower of the First Congregational Church
and a bustling little road of commerce, where a few students
gathered around a bakery.
</P>
<P>
   On Spring Street we found Robin's Restaurant and Catering, a
place where the chef and owner comes out of the kitchen to inquire
whether diners liked the lobster ravioli, and brochures are offered
testifying that the meals are made with Massachusetts produce.
</P>
<P>
   We also took a 20-minute tour across the Massachusetts border to
stay at the Sedgewick Inn, an airy old tavern stop with a
wraparound porch off Route 22 in Berlin, N.Y., a more isolated and
rural area with hay drying in the fields. Visitors seeking dinner
in its candlelit restaurant were turned away, but the inn makes
room for its overnight guests. Children are not allowed to stay
overnight in the historic portion of the inn but are welcome in a
small motel behind its carriage house. However, the nicer rooms,
furnished with antique beds and thick quilts, are in the main
house.
</P>
<P>
   But I preferred lodging closer to Williamstown, where we were
within milling distance of the summer theater crowd, which,
Ritchie, the festival producer, said tended to be made up of three
types of visitors _ local ones, those from around Albany and a
large contingent from New York City. Most of the actors and
playwrights are also from New York.
</P>
<P>
   During the last few years, the festival has made alliances with
the local museums so that the theater experience extends beyond the
stage to the Clark Art Institute, where on Monday afternoons
seminars take place that bring together festival directors and
designers to discuss topics like the creation of ``Camino Real.''
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art in nearby North
Adams has also formed an association with the theater festival.
This month it is staging an animation exhibition, and in July it
was the site of ``Quark Victory,'' the festival's production of a
science-fiction musical comedy featuring singing electrons and
neutrons.
</P>
<P>
   The festival draws on a New York talent pool, but Ritchie
insisted that Williamstown plays its own quiet role in the
performances. ``The people that come here are inspired,'' he said.
``They're away from the normal pressures and they're surrounded by
these wonderful mountains. That's got to have an effect.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Williamstown, Mass., is about 175 miles from New York City.
Here is a sampling of attractions and places to stay and eat in the
area, along with travel information.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIELD FARM GUEST HOUSE,  &LR; 554 Sloan Road, Williamstown, (413)
458-3135. A 1948 country estate on 296 acres with pond, trails and
tennis courts. A double room is $100 for one person, $125 for two
(includes breakfast); reservations are difficult to come by in the
high summer season, but cancellations occur.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SEDGEWICK INN,  &LR; Route 22, Berlin, N.Y., (800) 845-4886. A
peaceful retreat across the border from Massachusetts. The
18th-century building includes a library and five bedrooms
decorated with antiques. There is also a small motel where children
are welcome. Prices range from $75 and $85 for the motel, to $105
to $145 for rooms at the inn; all include a full breakfast. The old
tavern also has a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WILLOWS MOTEL, &LR;  480 Main Street, Williamstown, Mass., (413)
458-5768. A comfortable motel with country decor and a heated pool
that is within walking distance of the Williamstown campus. Double
rooms are $79 and $95 and include a continental breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROBIN'S RESTAURANT AND CATERING,  &LR;  Spring and Latham Street,
Williamstown, (413) 458-4489. At the end of a small commercial
strip near the Williamstown campus, Robin's features casual dining
and a menu of French and Italian food.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STERLING &AMP; FRANCINE CLARK ART INSTITUTE,  &LR;  225 South Street,
Williamstown. (413) 458-9545. The institute is known for its
collection of French Impressionist paintings, which includes more
than 30 by Renoir. ``Drawn Into the Light,'' an exhibition of works
by Jean-Francois Millet, remains on display through Sept. 6. Hours:
daily, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. (until 8 p.m. on Tuesdays). Admission: $5;
free for those 18 and younger and students (free on Tuesdays for
all).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WILLIAMSTOWN THEATER FESTIVAL,  &LR;  1000 Main Street,
Williamstown. Through Aug. 29. This weekend: On the main stage,
``As You Like It,'' tonight at 8; tomorrow at 4 and 8:30 p.m. and
Sunday at 2 p.m.; tickets, $27 and $37. On the Nikos stage,
``Chaucer in Rome,'' also tonight at 8, tomorrow at 4 and 8:30 p.m.
and Sunday at 2 p.m. All performances are sold out, but any
returned tickets would be available one hour before the
performance; tickets, $19. Box office: (413) 597-3400. 24-hour
information line: (413) 597-3399; Web site: www.wtfestival.org.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRIDGE OF FLOWERS, &LR;  off Route 2A, Shelburne Falls, Mass., (413)
625-2143. Trolley bridge from 1908 that was converted in 1928 into
a 400-foot flowered pathway. May through Nov. 1. Contributions
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LLAMA HIKES. &LR;  Berkshire Mountain Llama Treks, Lee, Mass., (413)
243-2224. Half-day, hourly and sunset hikes. A group rate of $40 an
hour for the first hour for up to 10 people. The llama farm is a
31-mile drive south of Williamstown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MASSACHUSETTS MUSEUM OF CONTEMPORARY ART, &LR;  87 Marshall Street,
North Adams, Mass., (413) 662-2111. Housed in a 19th-century mill,
the museum focuses on works that blur the line between visual and
performing arts. Through August it is featuring an animation
festival that includes an evening with Barry Purves, a puppet
animator, tomorrow night at 8. Tickets: $15 and $20. Museum hours:
Fridays and Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 7 p.m.; Sundays through
Thursdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Museum admission, $8; $3 for children
under 16.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOHAWK TRAIL.  &LR; Marked on maps as Route 2 through Massachusetts,
the Mohawk Trail opened in 1914 and runs from Williamstown to
Greenfield.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHELBURNE FALLS TROLLEY MUSEUM,  &LR; 14 Depot Street, Shelburne
Falls, (413) 625-9443. This museum, created by volunteers in 1991,
is open on Saturdays and Sundays from 11 a.m. to 4 p.m.; weekdays
by reservation. Its restoration of the Shelburne Falls No. 10
trolley is expected to be finished, and the trolley running, by
October. Donations accepted. How to Get There
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BY CAR: &LR;  Take Interstate 95 to the Cross Westchester Expressway
(Interstate 287) and continue on I-287 to Interstate 684; go north
on Interstate 684 to Interstate 84 East and continue on I-84 East
to Connecticut and U.S. 7; continue north on U.S. 7 to
Massachusetts, passing Pittsfield.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BY BUS:  &LR; Bonanza Bus Lines runs three buses daily to
Williamstown from the Port Authority bus terminal, Ninth Avenue and
42d Street, Manhattan. Round-trip fare for the ride, about five
hours, is $66 ($33 for children under 11). Information: (212)
947-1766.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
