<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     08-05 0232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHTING AN ALBUM OF THE WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACY GRAY; ``On How Life Is'' (Epic).
</P>
<P>
   Macy Gray has a degree of talent, originality and vision wrapped
in a familiar package. The problem with having this, as anyone from
well-knowns like Bruce Springsteen to unknowns like Mary Cutrofello
can tell you, is that the music business is so hungry for this type
of performer that it's hard to live up to the fanfare and
expectations on a first album.
</P>
<P>
   So if ``On How Life Is'' doesn't meet its impossible criteria as
the introduction of a seminal new voice that rhythm-and-blues fans
will be listening to for decades, it at the very least is a musical
success in its time, 1999, as something new delivered in a classic
mold.
</P>
<P>
   With the rasp of Rod Stewart when he had a glimmer of soul, Ms.
Gray reaches to grasp the intangible beauty of love, rainbows, and
self-awareness; though she knows her goal is unattainable, she
keeps on reaching, and therein lies the instantly likable depth of
these 10 songs. (The limited number of songs is in itself a
self-conscious throwback to the LP era.)
</P>
<P>
   Her singing is hard to forget, her music evokes Sly and the
Family Stone with turntables and samplers and her album is just
what rhythm-and-blues needs: another authentic, unfiltered,
immediate voice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1648EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
