<HEADER>
A6993 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT &LR;      08-05 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Race Relations Taught on Tape  
 New Releases of Video Cassettes: Reviews by New York Times
Critics  
 Past Releases 
 (yn) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RACE RELATIONS TAUGHT ON TAPE: Applied to race relations, video
can be as good a teacher as it is an entertainer and, given the
average treatment of race in feature films or on television,
probably a lot better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Video is a way to provide empathy and understanding at a
distance because it's not in your face in a setting that can cause
high tension,'' said Timothy Gunn, executive director of National
Video Resources, a nonprofit organization in New York that supports
varied uses of independently produced films and videos.
</P>
<P>
   The group's current project promotes documentaries about race
made by those with firsthand experience. ``The tellers, unlike
those on network television, are often persons of color who have
lived the situation,'' Gunn said.
</P>
<P>
   With the idea that such films would be of value to organizations
and individuals working with race problems, National Video
Resources has put together a multifaceted publication called
``Viewing Race: A Videography and Resource Guide.'' In the
introduction, people with direct experience at using video to
explore race explain how to set up community programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who do not usually discuss this subject find it less
difficult to come together to talk to and learn from each other as
a part of a workshop,'' write Lauren Kucera and Milton Reynolds,
contributors to the guide.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 titles are included, and it is a diverse selection.
Jennifer Fox's ``An American Love Story,'' for example, is about
the ups and downs in the 30-year marriage of a black man and a
white woman. Stephen C. Ning's ``Freckled Rice'' is the story of a
Chinese-American boy in Boston and Jay Rosenstein's ``In Whose
Honor? American Indian Mascots in Sports'' focuses on a Spokane
Indian named Charlene Teeters, who battles the University of
Illinois over its stereotypical Chief Illiniwek.
</P>
<P>
   Headings in the titles index are similarly diverse:
African-American Identity (and Asian-American Identity and
Arab-American Identity and Biracial and Multiracial Identity);
Immigration; Indigenous Peoples; Chinese Americans (and Korean and
Laotian and Mexican Americans); Labor and Race, Political
Correctness (for example, Michael Pack's ``Campus Culture Wars,
Five Stories About P.C.''), and War and Race.
</P>
<P>
   Gunn said the guide was aimed at community groups, libraries and
colleges and universities. Since few of these videos are in
mainstream distribution, prices sometimes run to several hundred
dollars, but discounts are offered to nonprofit organizations. For
example, the price of ``In Whose Honor?'' drops from $195 for an
individual to $99 for a nonprofit group.
</P>
<P>
   A free copy of ``Viewing Race'' can be obtained by faxing
National Video Resources at (212) 274-0284 or e-mailing
ViewingRace(AT)nvr.org.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES OF VIDEO CASSETTES: REVIEWS BY NEW YORK TIMES
CRITICS
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE
</P>
<P>
   1998. Miramax. $107.37. 122 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to produce a money-maker for the strapped Rose Theater,
the young Will Shakespeare (Joseph Fiennes) is stymied by writer's
block, which in turn has shut him down sexually. But just when his
latest project, ``Romeo and Ethel, the Pirate's Daughter'' is about
to disintegrate altogether, along comes the high-born Viola de
Lesseps (Gwyneth Paltrow) to inspire the project and bring Will's
libido to a boil. An aspiring actor, which was forbidden for a
woman of the day, Viola poses as Romeo in a film that, Janet Maslin
wrote in The New York Times, ``soars freely into the realm of
invention, wittily weaving Shakespearean language and emotion into
an intoxicatingly glamorous romance.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRUE CRIME
</P>
<P>
   1999. Warner. $104.16. 127 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Now a codgerly 60-something, the burnt-out and alcoholic
newspaperman Steve Everett (Clint Eastwood) still hits on
23-year-olds, not to mention his editor's wife (at least she's
older). And there's still enough gas in the tank to jump into the
case of Frank Beachum, a black man sentenced to death for killing a
pregnant white college student. Believing the man innocent, Everett
battles the case right through to the moment of execution in a film
directed ``with righteous indignation and increasingly strong
momentum'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRITY
</P>
<P>
   1998. Miramax. $104.16. 113 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen's film wonders whether getting Knicks season tickets
and hot restaurant reservations are the supreme achievements of a
``culture that took a wrong turn somewhere.'' As Lee Simon, a
depressingly callow and thoroughly ordinary magazine ``journalist''
panting along the celebrity trail, Kenneth Branagh is in the
accustomed Allen role of the womanizing loser kvetching about his
career and chasing what he can't have and eventually wouldn't be
satisfied with anyway. In the end, though, Allen, not Branagh, ``is
the only man who can save these tics from whiny obsequiousness''
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   THE DEEP END OF THE OCEAN
</P>
<P>
   1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. 108 minutes. Closed captioned.
PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a crowded hotel lobby, Beth Cappadora (Michelle Pfeiffer)
takes her eyes off her 3-year-old son, Ben, for a couple of minutes
and he's gone, presumably never to be seen again. But after living
for years obsessed with the loss, to the detriment of her
relationships with her husband (Treat Williams) and other children,
Beth answers the door one day and there stands Ben. At this point,
Ulu Grosbard's film, based on Jacquelyn Mitchard's book, shows an
interesting ``awareness of how wrenchingly, in any family, real and
idealized relationships can diverge'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   PAST RELEASES:
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNIN' WILD: THE FILMS OF CLARA BOW. Hollywood's ``It'' girl of
the roaring '20s stars in three films, and gets her own
documentary, narrated by Courtney Love. In ``The Plastic Age''
(1925, 73 minutes), the nubile Cynthia (Bow) has to decide whether
to cut herself loose from a college boy (Donald Keith) before he
does himself and his career some permanent damage running after her
and a life in the Jazz Age fast lane. ``Parisian Love'' (1925, 62
minutes) finds Bow in Paris, where she sets out to seduce and get
revenge on the man who shot her lover. As a lingerie salesgirl in
``It'' (1927, 72 minutes), Bow chases and snares the owner of the
department store where she works, only to lose him when she's
mistaken for an unwed mother. The fourth tape, the documentary
``Clara Bow: The It Girl'' (1999, 65 minutes), has interviews and
scenes from 25 films. Kino. Four cassettes, $24.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   OUT OF THE BLUE. In Dennis Hopper's film, he stars as a longtime
former convict whose return from prison only adds to the emotional
burdens of his teen-age daughter, played by Linda Manz, an outsider
from the punk rock generation who's about to lose control. 1980.
Anchor Bay. $29.98. 93 minutes. R.
</P>
<P>
   SOMEWHERE OVER THE RAINBOW: HAROLD ARLEN. In Don McGlynn's film,
Barbra Streisand, Frank Sinatra, Mel Torme, Lena Horne, Tony
Bennett, Johnny Mercer, Bing Crosby, Judy Garland and others
perform a raft of hits by the creator of ``Stormy Weather.'' 1999.
Winstar. $19.98. 70 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
