<HEADER>
A7012 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARTHA-STEWART-WEDDIN     08-05 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTHA-STEWART-WEDDINGS-ADV07-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV07 
 (FOR RELEASE SAT., AUG. 7, 1999 OR THEREAFTER)
</HEADLINE>
  askMartha Weddings: CAN YOU RECOMMEND SOME INEXPENSIVE DECORATING
IDEAS FOR A PATIO RECEPTION? 
  
 (This is the debut of Martha Stewart's 'askMartha Weddings,' a
weekly Q&AMP;A all about weddings, from the engagement to the
honeymoon. Art is available. FOR PURCHASE INFORMATION: Contact New
York Times Syndicate sales director BOB FARNELL at (800)
535-4425(AP), fax (212) 499-3382 or farnell(at)nytimes.com.) 
  
 By MARTHA STEWART  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUESTION: Do you have any inexpensive decorating ideas for our
reception, which will be held on a patio? _ Katie via e-mail
</P>
<P>
   MARTHA STEWART: A pretty outdoors venue doesn't require a lot of
embellishment. There are no bare walls or ceilings to transform,
and you may even have a lovely view.
</P>
<P>
   But if you need to mask a less than attractive area, consider
renting potted trees from a nursery or florist. For a daytime
wedding, tie the pots with wide ribbon or fabric, string ribbons
through the branches or drape the trees in tulle.
</P>
<P>
   At night, decorate the trees with white lights, or line up tiki
torches or luminaria (paper bags with a little sand for weight and
a candle inside) around the perimeter of your space.
</P>
<P>
   Next, you'll want to concentrate your efforts _ and the largest
portion of your decorating budget _ on the guest tables. Cut flower
arrangements make lovely centerpieces, but why not consider using
pots of planted flowers or fragrant herbs? Terra-cotta pots are at
home in a garden setting, but you can spray-paint them to
complement your color scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Add candles _ in hurricane lanterns or even jelly jars _ to
illuminate your table. Platters, bowls and cake stands can be
rented or borrowed and used for centerpieces. Pile them with fresh
fruit and tuck in a few flowers or leaves. For a rustic lunch or
dinner, assemble a basket with assorted country breads, bowls of
olives and olive oil, a pitcher of water and jugs of wine.
</P>
<P>
   While white or ivory linens and china are traditional, consider
adding a bit of color. Colored napkins, a sheer overlay on the
table, unique china or unusual glasses enhance any setting.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: Who is usually invited to the rehearsal dinner? _ Dana
M. Tieman, Oxford, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   MARTHA STEWART: The rehearsal dinner is traditionally hosted by
the groom's family and held the evening before the wedding. It can
be an intimate gathering or a big party.
</P>
<P>
   The guest list always includes the members of the wedding party,
their spouses and members of the bride's and groom's immediate
family. The officiant and his or her spouse are often invited, if
they are close to the family. Beyond that, the list can include
extended family and close friends, especially those who have a role
in the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   It is customary _ not obligatory _ to invite out-of-town guests,
who would not otherwise be able to spend much time with the bride
and groom. For a destination wedding, in which everyone travels to
a special spot for a weekend or longer, all of the wedding guests
are usually included in rehearsal dinner.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: When should we leave for our honeymoon? The day of the
reception or the day after? _ Oct99bride, via e-mail
</P>
<P>
   MARTHA STEWART: There is absolutely no right or wrong time to
depart on a honeymoon. Make your travel plans according to what
will be most comfortable, enjoyable and exciting for you.
</P>
<P>
   Some couples relish the idea of making a dramatic exit from the
reception and going straight to the airport. This isn't always
possible, especially if the party lasts well into the evening. Keep
in mind that you may feel exhilarated after the reception, but you
are also likely to be exhausted, and embarking on a long journey
may prove stressful.
</P>
<P>
   Many newlyweds stay overnight in a local hotel or inn, where
they can relax before departing the next morning. And still others
leave later that afternoon or even the following day so they can
enjoy the company of the relatives and friends who have come from
afar. It is not uncommon for couples to postpone the honeymoon
because of work or financial situations. Sometimes this can't be
helped, but I cannot stress enough the importance of taking a
honeymoon, whether for a few weeks or just a few days. Newlyweds
deserve to spend this special time together, celebrating their new
status as husband and wife.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Questions should be addressed to askMartha Weddings, care of The
New York Times Syndication Sales Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York,
N.Y. 10168. Questions may also be sent to Stewart by electronic
mail. Her address is: mstewart(at)marthastewart.com. The (at)
represents the symbol on your keyboard. Please include your name
and daytime telephone number. And indicate that your question
concerns Weddings. Questions of general interest will be answered
in this column; Martha Stewart regrets that unpublished letters
cannot be answered individually. &QL; 
