<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-JARRETT-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT RETURNS TO BRICKYARD 400 A YEAR WISER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It is over, but not forgotten. A lesson learned,
Dale Jarrett says now.
</P>
<P>
   It was just a year ago that Jarrett came here with a car that
blew everybody's doors off.
</P>
<P>
   As the 1998 Brickyard 400 approached the halfway point, Jarrett
was far out in front and getting faster. Some 59 laps into the
race, Jarrett led Jeff Gordon by 1.242 seconds. By lap 66, he was
2.692 seconds ahead. By the 70th lap, he was 4.123 seconds up. By
76, it was 4.232 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, though, Jarrett was not only outrunning
Gordon, he was outrunning himself, gobbling up more gas than
planned.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's fuel use had been carefully calculated by Todd
Parrott, Jarrett's crew chief. It would be tight, Parrott knew, but
the thinking was Jarrett could lead the 80th lap and collect the
$10,000 bonus that goes to the car in front at the race's halfway
point.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't.
</P>
<P>
   An ominous warning came on lap 79, when Ward Burton's Pontiac
sputtered and slowed on the track.
</P>
<P>
   One lap later, after winning the $10,000, Jarrett's car coughed
and died on the backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   As he coasted around to the pits, his team had put $10,000 in
one pocket and taken nearly $1.5 million out of the other.
</P>
<P>
   Refueled, Jarrett would mount a furious, almost unbelievable
charge, making up the four laps he lost but running out of time
before he could regain the lead. When the race was finished, so was
he, in 16th place.
</P>
<P>
   But Jarrett, who had plenty of gas in 1996 when he won here, is
back, looking to run up front and determined to stay there if he
has the competition covered. His car was the fastest of the 57 that
ran here in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have the best car you'd like to take advantage of
that, especially in a race as big as Indy,'' Jarrett said. ``But I
think it gave us a heads-up on this year because we're gonna be
bringing the same race car back.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's loss was made even more frustrating because NASCAR
officials seemed slow to throw the caution when Burton's car
finally died.
</P>
<P>
   With an earlier caution, Jarrett might not have lost as many
laps, which could have changed the outcome of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's over and done, too,'' Jarrett said. ``Those are things
that are in the past, and hopefully, everybody learned from what
went on there and we know better than to sit and wait on something
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Which doesn't mean Jarrett's team has stopped taking risks.
</P>
<P>
   In Daytona's Pepsi 400 this year, Jarrett once more stayed on
the track when it was uncertain how much fuel he had left.
</P>
<P>
   This time the race was winding down, and he was going for the
win.
</P>
<P>
   With the aid of a late caution, he made it to the end and won
the race before he ran out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   During the caution, Jarrett came down off Daytona's high banks
and ran on the apron, the flat part of the track.
</P>
<P>
   But he insisted he would have made it even if the race had
stayed green.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett said he stayed low under caution because ``riding on the
bank that slow gives the fuel plenty of time to go away from the
pickup, and we just didn't want to take any chances.''
</P>
<P>
   The fuel pickup is on the right side of the car, which tilts to
the left on the banking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had enough fuel, especially under caution, to make it,''
Jarrett insisted. ``But there's no sense in taking a chance in
having the thing burping and running out of something for a split
second and then being hard to crank up.''
</P>
<P>
   So the gamble that failed at Indy worked at Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to take chances on fuel and tires sometimes,''
Jarrett said. ``Those are the type things you have to do if you're
going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Zier writes for The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla., which is a
member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This article
was distributed by The New York Times News Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
