<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL CARDS ARE A WHOLE NEW GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's surprising nobody thought of it before:
Baseball Tarot Cards.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lerner and Laura Phillips have produced 78 tarot cards
wrapped around a baseball theme (Workman Publishing, $20), with
handsome, hand-done images of everything from the Ace of Bases to
the Twelve of Mitts, from The Goat to The Umpire to a Whole New
Ball Game. The set comes complete with a 324-page book explaining
the way baseball tarot complements traditional tarot.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting Roger Angell (``Baseball seems to have been invented
solely for the purpose of explaining all other things in life''),
the book talks about the Majors, a group of 21 cards that
corresponds to the Major Aracana or Trumps in traditional tarot _
``the universal, underlying principles of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 57 cards fall into four suits _ Mitts, Balls, Bats
and Bases _ to make up the Minors. Mitts, including the Three of
Mitts (Triple Play), refer to matters of the heart or Cups in
traditional tarot. Balls (Swords in traditional tarot) deal with
analytical thought and include the Ace of Balls and the Eleven of
Balls (No-hitter). Bats, corresponding to Wands, offer Four of Bats
(Grand Slam) and Ten of Bats (Bases Loaded). Bases (Pentacles) has
cards labeled Pickoff, Rundown and Winning Streak.
</P>
<P>
   Players can refer to Baseball Tarot one card at a time for
everyday guidance, for a regular weekly or monthly reading, or only
when a pressing question is raised.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner and Philips offer a breakdown of different reading
layouts, starting with two- and three-card readings (Hit, Ball,
Strike), a 10-card layout, and the more traditional 12-card layout,
set in the shape of a baseball diamond _ each player at his
position, with a batter, umpire and on-deck hitter bringing the
total to 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Diamond is Baseball Tarot's answer to the traditional
Celtic Cross layout,'' the book explains, providing ``a fuller,
more detailed view of a situation's meaning and potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Lerner and Philips also offer a ``Who's on First?'' layout,
which include ``Who,'' ``What'' and ``I Dunno'' for ``when you're
completely confused, like the characters in the famous Abbott and
Costello comedy routine.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors are serious about their baseball. In her
acknowledgments, Philips thanks ``Dem Bums and the Amazing Mets for
providing my family with a religion.'' Lerner thanks ``my camp
friends with whom I played ball and traded and flipped cards for
seven summers in upstate New York'' and ``the guy from Dallas who
didn't show up to meet his friends at Yankee Stadium, allowing me
to take his place and go to the third game of the 1964 World
Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Philips and Lerner, who came up with Baseball Tarot at
Peralandra Books in Eugene, also are serious about their Tarot,
warning readers not to tempt the cards by asking the same question
over and over: ``You will likely find that the Tarot has an uncanny
way of unmasking attempts to get a `better' answer. A second-guess
reading will often include many of the same cards as the original
reading, underscoring the reader's reluctance to consider what's
already been offered.''
</P>
<P>
   The book breaks down the meaning of each card in a given order _
from the Ten of Bats (``acceptance of responsibility'') to the
Catcher (who ``shows up to remind you of an old adage: sometimes
you just know''). Along the line are philosophies, large and small,
from Ted Turner's ``People have the most fun when they're busting
their ass'' to Wes Westrum's ``Baseball is like church. Many attend
but few understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
