<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-IN-WASHINGTON-ART     08-05 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-IN-WASHINGTON-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONUMENTAL PLEASURE IN A CAPITAL OF ART 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For out-of-town visitors, summer in Washington can
mean many things: monuments and documents, a Babel of regional
accents, First Family photo ops (though these are rare), and the
sight of local office workers jogging at lunchtime on the National
Mall _ up and down, up and down _ no matter how hot the weather.
</P>
<P>
   But summer also means art, and plenty of it. Washington is a
serious museum city. There's the National Gallery of Art, of
course. And the Smithsonian Institution covers a wealth of cultural
bases. The nation's collections of African, African-American and
Asian art are under its auspices, as is the Hirshhorn Museum, a
showcase for contemporary work. That's just a partial list. Throw
in privately financed outfits like the Corcoran Gallery and the
table is set for a feast.
</P>
<P>
   All these venues have worthy-to-outstanding fare on view at
present, including retrospectives of Roy Lichtenstein, Brice Marden
and Alma Thomas; a survey of recent work from South Africa, and a
truly celestial gathering of South Indian goddesses. None of the
shows will travel to New York, which may make a Washington trip
(with a stop in Baltimore on the way) something more than a
should-we-or-shouldn't-we proposition.
</P>
<P>
   One attraction that certainly won't be going anywhere is the
National Gallery's new Sculpture Garden, which opened in May.
Covering a 6.1-acre square plot next to the museum, it has curvy
paths, shady plantings and a circular fountain about the size of
Lake Lucerne. This sends out mighty fire-hose-style jets of water
in summer; in the winter it will be a skating rink.
</P>
<P>
   Installed throughout the grounds are 17 examples of postwar
sculpture from the museum's collection. Some, like Ellsworth
Kelly's oval-shaped steel ``Stele II'' and Isamu Noguchi's ``Great
Rock of Inner Seeking,'' are poised and circumspect, the way we
wish politicians were. Others, like Louise Bourgeois' bronze
``Spider'' and Joan Miro's ``Gothic Personage, Bird-Flash,''
browse, wary and shy, among the the trees.
</P>
<P>
   To be frank, inner-city sculpture gardens are an iffy idea. They
corral together large-scale occupants who have basically nothing to
say to each other, then force them to show off competitively, a
situation in which nobody wins. Still, this one is good of its
kind. Most of the work gets to claim some personal space, and some
pieces are outgoing and user-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can lounge around, for example, on Scott Burton's
granite seats and feel relieved that they don't have to negotiate
Lucas Samaras' vertiginous stack of turquoise chairs. And they can
fantasize a home away from home in Roy Lichtenstein's aluminum
``House I,'' with its cartoon lines, Pop colors and eye-tickling
play with perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Corcoran Gallery of Art
</P>
<P>
   Lichtenstein, who died two years ago and is best known as a
painter, has a full-scale survey of sculpture at the Corcoran
Gallery. It encompasses some 40 years of work, and although the
artist was involved in the planning stages, the final selection was
made by Jack Cowart, deputy director and chief curator at the
Corcoran.
</P>
<P>
   The show has much to offer, though it gets off to a shaky start.
The polychrome sculptures installed on the museum's grand interior
staircase are swamped by the heavy 19th-century architecture. They
look flimsy, almost like clutter. Lichtenstein's painstakingly
breezy art was made for cleaned-out modernist spaces. It often
depends on them, in fact, which is both a weakness and a strength.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside the white-cube environment of the galleries,
everything perks up. The show begins at the beginning. From the
1940s comes a carved stone head influenced by pre-Columbian
sculpture, from the '50s a slender assemblage of painted wood in
which the artist's eye for whittled-down forms and his deadpan wit
are already in evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lichtenstein had a brief Deco-ish phase in the late
1960s, his renowned Pop art style was firmly in place by 1964, as
seen here in sculptures of women's heads, soulful and Ben
Day-dotted steaming coffee cups and ``explosions.'' These images
were transferred straight from paintings, with in some cases the
Ben Day dots replicated in perforated steel.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture became more abstract as time went on and folded in
a range of art historical references, Picasso, Matisse and Abstract
Expressionism among them. Lichtenstein's famous images of frozen
brush strokes, which gently mock the psychic imperatives of Action
Painting, proved especially amenable to the sculpture medium, and
several variations splash and drip in mid-air here.
</P>
<P>
   If the show feels more and more absorbing as it goes on, it's
not because the work gets better exactly, but because one gets
attuned, even faintly addicted to, its character: self-amused,
good-natured, always preferring the eloquent turn of phrase to the
Big Statement. It all looks effortless, though the preliminary
studies and working collages in the show _ scuffed up, rethought,
drawn over _ tell a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Lichtenstein's art is cool, in the sense of ``Wow, that's
cool.'' He had oodles of style, enough to sustain a whole career.
It was a career very much of a piece. His sculptures, paintings and
prints are, visually speaking, all cut from the same bright, sheer,
wash-and-wear modern cloth. As a body of work, they give
lightweight a good name.
</P>
<P>
   Hirshhorn Museum
</P>
<P>
   If the Lichtenstein show offers a lesson in carefully honed
consistency, ``Brice Marden, Works of the '90s: Paintings, Drawings
and Prints'' at the Hirshhorn is the record of an artist taking a
big mid-career leap.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s and '80s, Marden was known for his multipart
monochrome paintings. With their panels often arranged in
post-and-lintel format and their reverberant colors and skin-taut
encaustic surfaces, they seemed to infuse Minimalism with a muted
subjectivity.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '80s Marden was steeping himself in Chinese
literature and calligraphy, and his work changed. He began to trace
lines on monochrome grounds. Then, as if to physically break the
grip of geometry and the habit of control, he started to paint with
a stick held at a distance from the canvas.
</P>
<P>
   The linear webs and tangles that resulted both did and did not
amount to a personal signature. They were generated by the arm, and
to some degree by the eye, but they weren't hands-on. Physical
distance produced accident. Accident puts a drag on ego.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what one imagines was going on. A small painting
at the Hirshhorn, ``Prayer Flags,'' seems to encapsulate the
before-and-after effects of the process. The hard, dark lines in
the background (they seem to tilt and bend resistantly rather than
curve) were executed in 1989. The marigold color cords of paint
that twist over and around them were added in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In between came the monumental ``Cold Mountain'' paintings
(1989-91), probably the artist's best-known works. In them the
skeins of paint have the fluctuating tonal weight and uneven,
scratchy fibrous edges of ink-and-brush strokes, with underlying
webs that suggest erasures and pictorial depth.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually the line fattened up and color returned, and with it a
different kind of energy. The painting ``Progression'' (1993-95),
with its ropey swirls of hot orange and yellow on a blushing
ground, is as warm as an arterial system and has the adamant,
sensuous charge of Tantric deities locked in an embrace.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But by no means are all of Marden's sources Asian. A love of
Greek culture has infused his work all along; the patterns in
``Study for the Muses'' (1991-97) bring to mind the wind-whipped,
body-caressing drapery of classical sculpture. And natural forms or
forces, which are at the foundation of classical Greek and Chinese
art, underlie everything he does.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of ``classical'' has different implications in those
two cultures. Broadly speaking, in Greece it was associated with
stability and centeredness; in China, with flux and dispersal.
Marden's paintings in the Hirshhorn show, which was organized by
Charles Wylie for the Dallas Museum of Art, adroitly join the two.
</P>
<P>
   Anacostia Museum Gallery
</P>
<P>
   The abstract painter Alma W. Thomas (1891-1977) also drew
inspiration from nature, and often from specific forms: the flower
beds and cherry trees in Washington's parks, the light-catching
leaves of the holly tree outside the house in which she spent most
of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas studied art at Howard University, where she was the first
graduate of its fine arts program, and she was a junior high school
art teacher for 35 years. It was only after her retirement in 1960
that she turned to painting full time. And most of the work in the
Anacostia show, which comes from the Fort Wayne Museum of Art in
Indiana, dates from the last two decades of her life.
</P>
<P>
   She knew artists of the so-called Washington Color School, like
Kenneth Noland, Sam Gilliam and Gene Davis, and she studied with
Jacob Kainen. But she evolved a chromatic style of her own. Her
paintings from the 1960s are made up of multicolored bands,
mosaiclike streaks and dabs. In the early '70s, the strokes were
one color over a dark ground, as in ``Cherry Blossom Symphony,''
with its porous pink curtain floating over a field of hummingbird
emerald and blue.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later the strokes became puzzle-piece shards, as in
``Scarlet Sage Dancing a Whirling Dervish'' and the fantastic,
wall-filling ``Red Azaleas Singing and Dancing Rock-and-Roll
Music.'' Finally, in ``Oriental Garden,'' they mutated into
calligraphic commas, check marks and zigzags, which typically bunch
together on the left side of a painting and thin out as they move
to the right, like leaves scattered by a whoosh of wind.
</P>
<P>
   The links between Thomas' work and Marden's _ a passion for
nature and for abstract art's peculiar exhilarations _ are oblique
but real. It's great that they are showing in the same city at the
same time. Unfortunately, the likelihood of visitors chancing on
the Anacostia are slim. The museum, one of two sites for the
Smithsonian's Center for African-Amrican History and Culture, is in
a residential neighborhood and not near a Metro stop. But it's a
quick ride by cab from the Mall and worth the extra effort.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the Anacostia is a show of contemporary work, ``Locating
the Spirit: Religion and Spirituality in African-American Art.''
Many pieces _ a ``Crucifixion'' by Allan Rohan Crite is one _
depict biblical narratives. Others, like Ben Jones' heart-shaped
``Shango Fan'' and an altarlike installation by Leslie
King-Hammond, refer to Caribbean religions. Still other references
are to Islam. Such is the case with Yahya Muhammad's ``Victory,''
with its wild sci-fi landscape and Koranic inscription written in
traditional calligraphic scripts that also evoke graffiti art.
</P>
<P>
   It's a populous show, and not everything is on the same level,
though a selection of photographs in a separate gallery _ by Carl
Clark, Linda Day Clark, Adger Cowans, Michael Cunningham, Sheila
Pree, Ken Royster and Jeffrey Scales _ is a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Arts and Industries Building
</P>
<P>
   For another photography show _ huge, unwieldy, deeply engrossing
_ head to the Arts and Industries Building, the Anacostia's in-town
headquarters on the Mall. The exhibition ``Revue Noire: Africa by
Africans, a Photographic View'' was organized by Deborah Willis and
has already traveled to Europe and South America in a much larger
form. But with more than 200 images by dozens of photographers from
across Africa, the Washington edition still feels compendious.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the names _ Seydou Keita, Peter Magubane, Rotimi
Fani-Kayode, Malik Sidibe _ are familiar in the United States. Most
are not but certainly deserve to be. To take random examples, one
would like to have an expanded look at the work of the wonderful
Samuel Fasso and the Congolese photographer Depara, who died in
1997, or the output of the Boyadjian family, once portraitists to
the Ethiopian court. (Don't miss the portrait of Haile Selassie.)
And the vividly colored South African interiors by Zwelethu
Mlthethwa make one hungry to see more.
</P>
<P>
   Documentary pictures, including those sponsored, for better or
worse, by government agencies, and others published in magazines
like the South African Drum give a textured sense of African life
at all social levels. They also raise endless questions about the
very idea of ``Africanness'' and about who controls the Africa seen
in the West (Politicians? Photographers? Curators? The art
market?). Big and scattershot as this exhibition is, it is the tip
of a many-faceted diamond of an iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   National Museum of African Art
</P>
<P>
   Photography plays a crucial, if incidental, role in ``Claiming
Art/Reclaiming Space: Post-Apartheid Art From South Africa,''
organized by Lidia Pucinelli at the National Museum of African Art,
where it is just one of several media _ painting, sculpture,
printwork _ mixed together in a peppery, simmering stew of a show.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the work still carries the sting of political emergency.
Willie Bester's tight assemblage of car parts and metal fencing
refers to drive-by police shootings. David Koloane's expressionist
painting of stray dogs is a thinly disguised symbol for a military
state. Kay Hassan's terrific mural-scale collage of torn-up
billboard posters is a shout-out-loud celebration of the country's
free elections.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of artists follow a less confrontational, more
metaphorical path, William Kentridge, Georgie Papageorge and
Rudzani Nemasetoni (who was an artist-in-residence at the Studio
Museum in Harlem a few years ago) among them. So does Gavin
Jantjes, who now lives in London. His series of astrological
paintings are dreamy to look at but pose questions about what's in
the stars for the still-vulnerable South African nation.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's special exhibitions gallery is not an optimum place
for seeing art. Long and narrow, and fitted with a choppy series of
partition walls, it tends to make shows look scrappy and
disorganized. And the selection in this case, drawn entirely from
the museum's collection, is fairly familiar. The next step will be
to bring fresh material from South Africa, which one hopes the
Museum for African Art in Manhattan will do in an exhibition
scheduled to open this fall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Arthur M. Sackler Gallery
</P>
<P>
   Directly across a pretty garden courtyard is the African
museum's architectural twin, the Arthur M. Sackler Gallery, with
the Freer Gallery beyond. The Freer and Sackler are among the
city's jewels. The curatorial lineup is top-notch, the exhibition
quality high, the combined collections spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   The Sackler's stellar draw at the moment is ``Devi: The Great
Goddess,'' a gorgeous, soul-stirring gathering of sculptures and
paintings, ancient and modern, devoted to the female divinities of
India. The objects range from cast-bronze temple icons to rural
figures carved in wood to action-packed manuscript pages. And the
aura they are collectively generating is as wide as a city block.
Organized by the art historian Vidya Dehejia, this show rates a
Washington visit all by itself.
</P>
<P>
   National Museum of American Art
</P>
<P>
   For a change of pace, carve out time for ``Picturing Old New
England: Image and Memory'' at the National Museum of American Art.
The show brings together roughly a century's worth of objects, from
paintings (Winslow Homer, John Singer Sargent) to dust-gathering
bric-a-brac (a stationery box in the form of Henry Wadsworth
Longfellow's Cambridge, Mass., home, with pictures of Grave Alice
and Laughing Allegra and Edith With Golden Hair on the inside lid.)
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to examine how New England became a national symbol
(of moral rectitude, among other things), and a tourist lure. Art
had everything to do with it, according to this
exhibition-as-critical-essay, and the case it presents is on the
whole craftily wrought.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Museum of Art
</P>
<P>
   If you're heading north from Washington and have an extra hour
and energy to spare, consider a quick stopover in Baltimore to see
``Chokwe! Art and Initiation Among Chokwe and Related Peoples'' at
the Baltimore Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Manuel A. Jordan for the Birmingham Museum of Art
in Alabama, the show measures out art and anthropology in judicious
doses. It suggests how the Chokwe people of Africa, who now live in
Angola, Congo and Zambia, have traditionally passed the realities
of the present through the clarifying filter of the remembered past
to assure social harmony and spiritual continuity.
</P>
<P>
   Sculptures, masks and ceremonial paraphernalia of all kinds are
instrumental in this exchange, and some of the examples here bring
their extraordinary charisma intact into the museum setting. A
wooden chief's figure with a swept-back Superdome coiffure, a chair
bristling with minute human figures and a mask of a glamorous
female ancestor with high cheekbones and paint-rimmed eyes are a
few of the high points.
</P>
<P>
   The show requires some reading of wall texts to pick up its
thematic logic. But the installation, with its biscuit-colored
walls, is clean and straightforward, the material deeply absorbing.
And with full-dress, thought-through scholarly shows of African art
still absurdly rare in American museums, kudos to Baltimore (and to
Birmingham, of course) not only for being host of the show, but for
giving it main-stage attention as well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Here are the addresses and hours of the Washington and
Baltimore museums whose shows are reviewed by Holland Cotter.
Admission is free unless indicated.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CORCORAN GALLERY OF ART, &LR;  500 17th St. N.W., Washington, (202)
639-1700. ``Roy Lichtenstein: Sculpture and Drawings.'' Through
Sept. 30. Hours: Wednesdays through Mondays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.;
Thursdays to 9 p.m. Admission: $6; $3 for students and the elderly;
$10 a family.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GALLERY OF ART, &LR;  Fourth Street at Constitution Avenue
N.W., Washington, (202) 842-2403. The new sculpture garden is on
the National Mall, at Seventh Street and Constitution Avenue, N.W.
Hours: Mondays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, 11
a.m. to 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIRSHHORN MUSEUM AND SCULPTURE GARDEN, &LR;  Smithsonian
Institution, Independence Avenue at Seventh Street S.W.,
Washington, (202) 357-3091. ``Brice Marden, Works of the '90s:
Paintings, Drawings and Prints,'' through Sept. 6. Hours: daily, 10
a.m. to 5:30 p.m.; Thursdays through Sept. 4, to 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANACOSTIA MUSEUM AND CENTER FOR AFRICAN-AMERICAN HISTORY AND
CULTURE, &LR;  Smithsonian Institution, Anacostia Museum Gallery, 1901
Fort Place S.E., Washington, (202) 287-2061. ``Alma W. Thomas: A
Retrospective,'' through Sept. 12. ``Locating the Spirit: Religion
and Spirituality in African-American Art,'' through Dec. 1. Hours:
daily, 10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANACOSTIA MUSEUM AND CENTER FOR AFRICAN-AMERICAN HISTORY AND
CULTURE, &LR;  Smithsonian Institution, Arts and Industries Building,
900 Jefferson Dr. S.W., Washington, (202) 357-4500 ``Revue Noire:
Africa by Africans, a Photographic View'' through Dec. 31. Hours:
daily, 10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL MUSEUM OF AFRICAN ART, &LR;  Smithsonian Institution, 950
Independence Ave. S.W., Washington, (202) 357-4600. ``Claiming
Art/Reclaiming Space: Post-Apartheid Art from South Africa.''
Through Sept. 26. Hours: 10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m.; Thursdays through
Sept. 2, to 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARTHUR M. SACKLER GALLERY, &LR;  Smithsonian Institution, 1050
Independence Avenue S.W., Washington, (202) 357-4880. ``Devi: The
Great Goddess,'' through Sept. 6. Hours: 10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m.;
Thursdays through Sept. 2, to 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL MUSEUM OF AMERICAN ART, &LR;  Smithsonian Institution,
Eighth and G Streets N.W., Washington, (202) 357-2247. ``Picturing
Old New England: Image and Memory.'' Through Aug. 22. Hours: 10
a.m. to 5:30 p.m.; Thursdays through Sept. 2, to 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BALTIMORE MUSEUM OF ART, &LR;  10 Art Museum Dr., Baltimore,
Md., (410) 396-7100. ``Chokwe! Art and Initiation among Chokwe and
Related Peoples.'' Through Sept. 5. Hours: Wednesdays through
