<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-KIDS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL JORDAN IS WORKING ON HIS BELLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.) (rk) 
 By NICK MASUDA and LEAH ETLING   
 Santa Barbara (Calif.) News-Press   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA BARBARA, Calif. _ Michael Jordan has surfaced once again
in Santa Barbara, conducting his Flight School basketball camp for
the fourth straight summer at the University of California at Santa
Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan continued his custom of declining media interviews, but
he allowed his campers to ask questions. On Tuesday night, Jordan
opened up the floor to queries from the campers during a half-hour
``Talk Back'' session.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of some of the questions:
</P>
<P>
   So, how is the pot belly coming?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is coming along,'' said Jordan, who had announced that a
big belly would be a part of his life after retiring in 1998. `It
is a slow, gradual process.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you have an interest in coaching?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not right now,'' he said, confidently. ``I can't say I
won't down the road, but right now I am enjoying coaching my kids.
That is all I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Are you ever going to come back to the NBA?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I am done,'' Jordan said to a sea of disappointed
whimpers.
</P>
<P>
   Did you push off Bryon Russell (for the game-winning shot) in
the 1998 NBA finals?
</P>
<P>
   ``No I did not, did they call a foul?,'' said Jordan with a big
smile. ``I was simply getting my balance. Now, what Reggie Miller
did to me in Game 6 (of the 1998 Eastern Conference finals) was a
foul. But, I am not whining.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was the hardest championship to win?
</P>
<P>
   ``The last one,'' said Jordan. ``We had a lot more
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you think you can guard Sacramento Kings' guard Jason
Williams?
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is, can he guard me?'' said Jordan. ``He has
a killer crossover, but he has to play at the other end too.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you really like Wheaties?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said, after a second of thought. ``Do you really
expect me to say no?''
</P>
<P>
   Do you wear Hanes?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said. ``I told you kids ask the best questions. Only
a kid would ask that question.''
</P>
<P>
   What kind of gum do you chew during games?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it depends on the opponent,'' said Jordan. ``If we play
the Lakers, Wrigley's Doublemint. If we play the Clippers,
Bubblicious.''
</P>
<P>
   If you had a chance to play golf with anyone, who would it be?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be Ben Hogan,'' said Jordan, who now
considers golf to be his favorite sport.
</P>
<P>
   Do you ever watch Dennis Rodman wrestle?
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that what Dennis is doing now?'' said Jordan with a smirk.
``I haven't talked to him in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the question-and-answer session, Jordan put on a show
with the help of some of his basketball friends. The camp
directors, stars at the high school and collegiate level, split up
into teams for two 20-minute halves.
</P>
<P>
   While Jordan made about 90 percent of his shots, East St. Louis
High School star Gary Smiles stole the show. Smiles, a 7-foot
senior, converted on five spectacular dunks, including his own
version of Jordan's patented flight from the free-throw line to jam
the ball home.
</P>
<P>
   With retirement a permanent part of Jordan's life, he'll have to
get used to passing the baton onto younger players like Smiles.
</P>
<P>
   But judging by the sea of black-and-red No. 23 jerseys at UCSB's
Thunderdome, the kids will always live in a Jordan world.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Barbara News-Press in Santa Barbara, Calif., is part
of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
