<HEADLINE>
THE `REAL' THING: ANOTHER BRITISH COMING-OUT STORY RINGS TRUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's getting to where director John Hughes' name is getting
batted around as an allusive source almost as much as Hitchcock's.
</P>
<P>
   He's been credited as the inspiration of audience-pleasing
comedies such as ``Can't Hardly Wait,'' ``She's All That'' and the
smash hit ``American Pie,'' as well as two new gay indie pictures,
``Edge of Seventeen'' and this weekend's ``Get Real.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite ``Get Real's'' upper-class British setting and gay
main characters, the trials and tribulations of its high school
heroes has never seemed more Hughes-ian. Call it ``The Brunch
Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Silverstone is Steven Carter, a 16-year-old walking hormone
who has comfortably come to grips with his own homosexuality _
though not enough to tell anyone other than his gal pal, Linda
(Charlotte Brittain).
</P>
<P>
   Carter endures the ruthless taunts of the school jocks while
mooning over track superstar John Dixon (Brad Gorton). Linda,
meanwhile, purposefully continues to flunk her driver's ed test in
order to woo her instructor.
</P>
<P>
   Neither experiences much success, until a chance encounter at a
public restroom accidentally outs Steven and John to each other.
What follows is all the delightful awkwardness of first love _
Steven dealing with his giddy excitement at learning that the man
of his dreams has eyes for him as well, and John dealing with how
his affection forces him to face his own painful closetedness.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of running secondary story lines _ Steven must
fend off an amorous female classmate while John has to keep his
life secret from his catalog-model girlfriend and his homophobic
jock friends, but director Simon Shore has found such a terrific
cast of talented unknowns that they make you almost forget the
film's Afterschool Special approach.
</P>
<P>
   Silverstone, especially, is an amazing find. His Steven is among
a refreshing new breed of gay teen heroes _ confident in his own
sexuality, brave enough to take the difficult steps toward coming
out, and in touch with his own emotional turmoil without being
crippled by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Real'' makes a great companion piece to the lower-class
Brit coming-out film ``Beautiful Thing,'' offering an interesting
comparison of class structure's influence on gay youth. And the
good news is that ``Get Real's'' upper-class dialect is a lot
easier to digest than the thick wish-it-had-subtitles slang of
``Beautiful Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Get Real''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Simon Shore
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Ben Silverstone, Brad Gorton, Charlotte Brittain
</P>
<P>
   Length: 110 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ rated rather harshly as an R, though its mild
profanity, adult subject matter and violence are really suited more
to a PG-13
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
