<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7097 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOOR-THEATER-REVIE     08-05 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOOR-THEATER-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE LOOK AT OUTDOOR PLAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Monday night, like generations of actors before me, I played
a fairy.
</P>
<P>
   Not just any fairy, mind you, but Fairy No. 6, one of the
midnight sprites, a bit player in the sultriest Shakespeare comedy,
``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, I joined the members of the city's acting fraternity
who spill out of theaters and into the great outdoors every summer,
tossing aside their fine-tuned elocution and 10-step relaxation
exercises in exchange for the big gestures and shouting over
traffic noise, which are the hallmarks of open-air theater.
</P>
<P>
   They are everywhere, from the Joseph Papp Public Theater's sleek
showcases at the Delacorte Theater in Central Park, where
``Tartuffe'' begins on Tuesday, to a gritty production of ``Romeo
and Juliet'' being staged this weekend in an outdoor garage next to
the Theatorium on the Lower East Side.
</P>
<P>
   The Shakespeare Project takes its outdoor stage to public spaces
all across the city, while the Fringe Festival, beginning on Aug.
18, will invite troupes from across the city to perform downtown.
Farther afield, outdoor performance rules in bucolic locales like
Lenox, Mass., in the Berkshires, where Shakespeare and Co &UR; . &LR; 
resides on the Mount, and a production of ``Love's Labour Lost''
romps through Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   But for a true acting challenge, urban actors have their country
brethren beat. The complications are Ozian in scope: winos and
hecklers and teenagers, Oh my!
</P>
<P>
   War stories are rampant. Actors tell of being upstaged by ice
cream trucks _ ``children are fickle'' _ chased by dogs and ignored
by audience members who feel no compunction about leaving in the
middle of a soliloquy. Sometimes it rains.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are moments when actors get the better of
these elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year there was this drunk dude, heckling us through the
entire second scene, who finally yells out, `Yeah, but can you do
it like a Viking?''' recalled Matt Daniels, who appeared last year
as Nick Bottom and has performed outdoors for three summers. ``So I
went immediately into a Swedish accent. I think he gained a new
respect for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But considering the potential indignities, why would actors put
themselves through this?
</P>
<P>
   I decided to try it firsthand, donned my acting persona (taller,
more confident) and headed for the park. The plan was simple: to
join, for one night only, the annual production of ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream,'' staged for the last 10 years by the Gorilla
Repertory Theater Company &UR;  &LR; and its director in the southwest corner
of Washington Square Park in Greenwich Village. It wasn't a
tremendous stretch; in college I performed in the same play and I
flirted with the profession for several years after that.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of the Delacorte, which has big budgets and
fixed seating, most of the outdoor troupes have to create their own
playing space; audience members sit on the grass or take chairs.
Gorilla Rep's production is played on a small wedge of grass
between the park's dog run and its chess tables, with the audience
following the actors as they move about the space from scene to
scene. Three bike hills dominate the landscape. Still, on a good
night a performance can draw hundreds of spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans of the company's open-air campaigns speak in awed tones
about the feeling when the audience is that big and that close.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no fourth wall,'' said Lynda Kennedy, who has been
acting in Gorilla Rep shows since 1991. ``They are right there.
You're walking on them.''
</P>
<P>
   While the outdoor life may mean anxiety for actors, directors
seem to thrive on having the city as a backdrop, a setting that
allows for effects that simply can't go on in a normal theater.
``We'd be rehearsing and as Richard would be giving a particularly
demonic speech, sirens would start going off,'' said David Levine,
who directed ``Richard III.'' ``It was three times as good as
anything you could plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in watching some of this summer's open-air shows, all
sorts of unexpected gems emerge. The clanging of the bells at
Riverside Church as two ``Midsummer'' lovers kiss. A pair of
tattooed punks hugging and peeking through a gate to watch Juliet
fall by her Romeo.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, what separates these productions, most of them
free, from their indoor counterparts is their ability to draw
audiences that aren't usually found in Broadway theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare's audience had the groundlings and the elitists,''
said Jennifer Spahr, the artistic director of Expanded Arts. ``What
we've got is the same thing. We've got the scholars, people who
read along with the play. And then we've got the locals, walking
through and saying, `What are you doing?' And often times they sit
down and watch.''
</P>
<P>
   With limited rehearsal time and an infinite capacity for
embarrassment, it was agreed that I would play the sixth fairy in
the gang of the fairy king, Oberon, as well as the plum role of Tom
Snout, the tinker, a part made famous by absolutely nobody.
</P>
<P>
   But playing Snout had an added advantage over my fairy role; the
role had lines. Three of them, to be exact, plus a 10-line speech
in the play's climactic play-within-a-play, wherein Tom Snout plays
a wall that divides two lovers, Pyramus and Thisbe. It was a small
part but staggeringly vital.
</P>
<P>
   Like most companies, Gorilla Rep rehearses inside for weeks
before releasing its actors into the wild. The goal, said
Christopher Carter Sanderson, Gorilla Rep's artistic director, is
to school actors in the art of performing in public spaces (speak
up) and school them out of habits bred indoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dramatic pause is my greatest enemy,'' Sanderson said.
``You've got to be the most interesting thing happening in that
moment, and it's not easy to be more interesting than a drug deal
or a drag queen or a car alarm going off.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanderson also said he emphasized a quick to blistering pace for
performances.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Scott Cargle, an actor and the artistic director of the
Shakespeare Project, summed up a typical approach: ``Subtlety you
can forget about. You have to tell the story in broad character
strokes and engage the audience as much as possible by talking
directly to the audience as much as possible. You see someone
fidgeting, you talk to them.''
</P>
<P>
   To recap: Be big, loud and fast.
</P>
<P>
   My only full rehearsal was far from the teeming city, at a
company member's family house in Connecticut. The estate spread
over five acres adjacent to a forest. In the afternoon, I watched a
run-through as the 13-member cast clambered over rocks, through the
woods and across the tennis court, playing scenes wherever they
chose. The exercise is called a para-theatric; I was exhausted just
watching.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the cast began to run my scenes, comforting me as I
tripped over them and my lines _ all three of them and that big
speech. The assistant director, Andre-Philippe Mistier, had only
one note for me: Don't hide my face as I speak.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hallmarks of outdoor performance is the immediate
rejection that actors can get from the audience. In a theater
intermission is usually the only time an unsatisfied crowd can
escape. Outdoors they come and go all the time, and if you're
onstage, you watch 'em go. A rule of thumb is that audiences
usually grow as the play progresses; but if their numbers are
getting smaller, something may be seriously wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Early on Monday before my performance I began to feel the
sensation known to every actor: nerves, sneaky twinges in the
belly.
</P>
<P>
   By midday I had worn dog-ears on my copy of the script, studying
my final lines:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus have I, Wall, my part discharged so,
</P>
<P>
   And being done, thus Wall away doth go.''
</P>
<P>
   I memorized them, stuck the script in my pocket, panicked a
moment later and repeated the process. Again. And again.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 p.m. I arrived in the park, where Sanderson and company
walked me through the blocking for the play. The first fairy scene
would be played in the grass, the second on the bike hills etc. All
I had to remember was to keep the audience moving from location to
location. While I was ``offstage,'' I was to use a flashlight to
help light the actors ``onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   The evening was perfect. It was cool and clear for the first
time in a week, and in the center of the park acrobats played to
circles of fans and the fountain provided instant water sports.
Several people lounged on the grass nearby, while a family of three
finished a picnic. All in all, I thought to myself, not a bad place
to work.
</P>
<P>
   By 10 minutes before the show about 20 people had gathered at
the playing space. On the periphery a homeless man slept beside a
grocery cart full of his possessions.
</P>
<P>
   The play began with Theseus, the Duke of Athens, striding up and
over a bike hill, as his bride, Hippolyta, the Queen of the
Amazons, approached from West Fourth Street. Just as Shakespeare
imagined it . . .
</P>
<P>
   It came off without a hitch. Theseus' voice echoed off the
nearby buildings as the rest of the players confidently strode into
the crowd, playing lines to them, with them and for them. And true
enough, the crowd began to build. By the time of my first entrance,
the crowd in the grass had doubled, and by my first exit, nobody
had left. I considered it a victory.
</P>
<P>
   The play moved along furiously, pulling the audience from the
grass to the bike hills and back again. There were a few
complications. A fight in the dog run (between dogs, not owners)
occurred during Act III, drowning out a lovers' quarrel in the
play. A bewildered group of tourists stumbled too near the playing
scene and fled of their own accord.
</P>
<P>
   Night, which ever is when day is not, fell. I played several
more scenes and much to my dismay, the crowd began to ebb. Was
something wrong? Daniels, who plays Nick Bottom, the play's
soft-hearted clown, put my mind at rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Monday night,'' he said. ``The feel of the park is
different.'' He talked about the energy of the weekends on a warm
evening compared with those nights when clouds threaten. Or the
Yankees play. Or there's a full moon. Each is different, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Act V, scene 1: Enter Snout as Wall''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd had rebounded by the play's finale. On the bike hills,
about 75 spectators hunched to watch Nick Bottom and company play
out, as Shakespeare quipped, the ``tedious brief scene of young
Pyramus and his love Thisbe'' for Theseus and his court.
</P>
<P>
   As Wall, I wore a giant foam glove etched with a brick wall
pattern, which was handy because I had an epic case of the cold
sweats. I dabbed my brow with my giant glove, entered and opened my
mouth for the big speech.
</P>
<P>
   My first line was half finished when I heard it. A snicker. Was
that a good snicker or a bad snicker? I stopped and looked in the
snickerer's direction, but was blinded by the light from a
flashlight. Then another snicker, from another direction. I shot a
glance in that direction, and my panicked look prompted a laugh. I
was in a snicker vortex. I spoke the second line of the speech;
there was a twitter and a throaty laugh. A warm feeling began to
replace the cold sweat.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I got to my final two lines, it was official: I was
hamming it up. My mood was so high that my final two lines, the
ones I'd suffered over all afternoon, came out like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus I, Wall, have finished my part so,
</P>
<P>
   Thus being done so, I in your absence go go.''
</P>
<P>
   Not really English, not really Shakespeare, but enough to exit
trippingly.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, the play was over. The audience stood to applaud;
to be fair, they had been sitting on concrete but they stood
nonetheless. Then they wandered off, and the park was the same as
before the play had begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweet are the uses of adversity,'' Shakespeare wrote in ``As
You Like It,'' and true to his words, the cast had used the barking
dogs, the limited light and the confused tourists to help create
the strange world of the play. The dogs became the hounds of
Athens, the tourists became woodland sprites. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   And as I took off my big foam hand, I came to see the payoff was
the same out of a theater as it is in one: the satisfaction of
transporting yourself and an audience somewhere else. It's just
where you start from _ in a park, in a plaza, in the cool night air
_ that's different.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
