NYT-08-05-99 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7101 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     08-05 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ In this era of intensive media nosiness, politics
and corporate life have been transformed by the routine exposure of
previously private matters, from sexual affairs to financial
malfeasance to mere incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   The world, in short, has been demystified by digging _ all the
world, that is, except at least one area: moviemaking.
</P>
<P>
   It's odd because Hollywood has been the focus of a profound
fascination in recent years in both the mainstream press and
specialty publications. And yet with all the attention lavished on
stars, the media tend to get little access to the unglamorous
day-to-day process of creating and distributing movies, save for
carefully managed set visits from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' for example, took more
than three years to make, involved scores of actors, technicians
and studio executives, and was the subject of heavy media
speculation. Yet the public learned almost nothing of substance
about the film _ other than what the studio and its publicity
agents doled out _ until it was released three weeks ago to mixed
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   All this underscores why Rob Nilsson is, by Hollywood standards,
so deeply subversive. His new movie, ``Scheme,'' would probably
just be one of the hundreds of small independent films made every
year if it did not breach the one taboo Hollywood rarely ignores:
the one against making the filmmaking process completely
transparent.
</P>
<P>
   And it is doing so thanks to the Internet, where Nilsson is
displaying his dailies, or scenes as they are shot, mistakes and
all, as well as a running commentary explaining what he is up to.
The Web address is: www.ifilm.net.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson, 59, is something of a guerrilla filmmaker. He has
tended to work with small budgets on offbeat subjects, and some of
his films have been well received critically. ``Northern Lights,''
about the struggles of some farmers in North Dakota, received an
award at Cannes in 1979, and ``Heat and Sunlight,'' about a
photographer whose affair with a dancer is falling apart, took a
prize at the Sundance Film Festival in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   For his last several movies he has enlisted the homeless,
through his Tenderloin Action Group in San Francisco, to make
pictures that are heavily improvised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scheme,'' he said, begins with some general scenarios focusing
on a thief named Bid who chooses to live outside the system on his
motorcycle. But the actors will then recreate the scenes much the
way they want. The story ``is about people who are going to do
something but never do,'' he said, adding, ``It is about people who
sustain a dream, or a scheme, but the seeds of its destruction are
in the characters or the culture around them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think of it as depressing,'' Nilsson said. ``It's as
true a fact as any in our lives that our schemes don't work out.
What's wrong with not getting the whole wave?''
</P>
<P>
   He said the movie would cost in the neighborhood of $150,000,
was being shot digitally on electronic cameras and was scheduled to
be completed around the end of the year, when it would be
distributed digitally on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a way of demystifying the whole filmmaking process,
and that's subversive,'' Nilsson said. ``Hollywood wants to keep it
a big secret and say there's this golden process. But that's just
the way they make money.''
</P>
<P>
   To help viewers understand what is happening in the movie,
Nilsson is even going so far as to film elements of the back
stories of the characters. In other words, the Internet shows
scenes depicting key events in the lives of his characters that
will not appear in the final cut of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of this guarantees that the movie will be good
or that many people will want to watch it. But at least lots of
people will know about it, another important aspect of this
pioneering project.
</P>
<P>
   Rodger Raderman, 30, the chief executive of iFilm Network, the
company behind the Internet screening, said: ``The whole idea is to
create this community of interest before it even comes out. My
feeling is people will come to like and appreciate the characters.
They'll want to see the finished project more, not less.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a subversive side to using the Internet to market
``Scheme.'' The tactic has reduced costs considerably and gotten
around the traditional and extremely expensive distribution system
controlled by the studios.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Normally each print of a movie costs as much as $4,000. So if a
film opens on 100 screens, it costs $400,000 right there. And
traditional marketing and promotion add about 25 percent to the
production costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scheme'' will incur none of those costs, yet an almost
limitless number of consumers will have the opportunity to watch
it. Raderman said he hoped to make money not by charging people to
watch the film on the Internet but by charging for advertising that
will run with it, much as a television network does.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that this process was best suited to smaller
projects that might not be viable by Hollywood's usual financial
standards. But he said it would provide a new generation of
filmmakers with a novel method of finding an audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts artists in direct contact with consumers,'' Raderman
said. ``You don't need the whole studio structure to find that
audience.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adam Rifkin is an example of an increasingly common Hollywood
type. At 32 he's a filmmaking veteran with a long and diverse
career in a business increasingly run by and catering to the youth
market.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote and directed the independent movie ``The Dark
Backward,'' for instance, a low-budget tale of a talentless garbage
man who, after failing in his efforts to become a comedian,
suddenly grows a third arm from his back and enjoys a peculiar kind
of celebrity. He has also written big-budget mainstream movies like
``Mouse Hunt'' and ``Small Soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Rifkin is in short a movie nut who did not sell a script until
his 30th effort and who now tries to use his extremely profitable
successes to finance the more personal, oddball projects he loves
to do _ and do and do.
</P>
<P>
   He is hoping his latest movie, ``Detroit Rock City,'' to be
released next Friday, will be a combination of the two, a quirky
movie about things he likes and a mainstream commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is Rifkin's first job as a director of a studio
feature; he did not write this one. He noted that its budget, about
$16 million, was more than all the other movies he has directed
combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit Rock City,'' which stars Edward Furlong, Giuseppe
Andrews, James DeBello and Sam Huntington, is essentially a
coming-of-age film for the new generation of filmmakers. It is
about four young people desperately in love with the clownish rock
act Kiss (the movie takes place in 1978, the group's heyday) and
desperate to get into one of the band's concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Simmons of Kiss is one of the movie's producers, and the
aging band members make cameo appearances. The journey of the four
young friends is a tale of misadventures and of growing up in a
twisted sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   It is a sort of '70s movie for the '90s, because the baby
boomers who really came of age at that time may not completely
recognize it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel so much nostalgia for the '70s,'' Rifkin said.
``It just seemed like such an innocent time.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was pointed out that he was just 11 years old in 1978,
Rifkin added: ``I wasn't these kids, but I idealized kids like
this. These were the big brothers of my friends. The movie's my
perception of what their world was like.''
</P>
<P>
   Rifkin said that while the film's intended audience was young
people, he hoped it would click with aging baby boomers nostalgic
for their misspent youth and still able to chuckle at these kinds
of antics.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, this band was every parent's worst nightmare,''
Rifkin said. ``Now, there's a Kiss Visa card. I hope all different
age levels will connect with that irony.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
