<HEADER>
A7106 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARGENTINA-PHOTOGRAPHY     08-05 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-PHOTOGRAPHY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHY REVIEW: WHIMSY AND HARSH REALITIES IN THE LAND OF THE
TANGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARGARETT LOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Argentina may commonly be associated in the American
popular imagination with Eva Peron, Nazi war criminals, polo,
tango, soccer and steak. But for the 11 photographers represented
in ``Myths, Dreams and Realities in Contemporary Argentine
Photography,'' now at the International Center of Photography
uptown, Argentina is quite another place.
</P>
<P>
   For them, it is a land of bewitching primordial forces and a
cruel plague known as AIDS, of children without homes and women
without freedom, of the grimly religious and the ill-fated
``desaparecidos'' (disappeared), of urban whimsies and urban
horrors, of simple hope and brash Warholian spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   The photographers in this show, which was organized by the Pan
American Cultural Exchange in Houston, and curated by Anne Wilkes
Tucker, curator of photography at the Museum of Fine Arts in
Houston, have varied backgrounds and highly individualistic visions
of Argentina. Yet the images, five from each artist, have an almost
organic cohesion.
</P>
<P>
   The common denominators are a gentle humanity, a sophisticated
eye, an uncommon intelligence and originality, and an expert
command of black-and-white tonal ranges. Only one artist works in
color.
</P>
<P>
   All but three of the photographers were born in Buenos Aires,
where most still live and work. The oldest was born in 1948, the
youngest in December 1968. Like Manuel Alvarez Bravo, the grand old
man of modernist photography in Latin America, all are clear-eyed
and unsentimental about what they capture on film.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the photographers have at least one or two strong images
in the show.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Southeasterly Winds, North Shoreline, Buenos Aires,''
Marcos Zimmermann juxtaposes the full misty fury of crashing waves
with the still black motifs on a waterfront balustrade. Among
Adriana Lestido's photographs of women in prison is a haunting one
of a woman, a dirty apron over her clothes and a big kitchen knife
in one hand, who looks with fierce mournfulness at the camera.
</P>
<P>
   The standouts in the show are Gabriel Valansi, Marcos Lopez,
Martin Weber, Eduardo Gil and Helen Zout.
</P>
<P>
   Valansi, a self-taught photographer, has produced some of the
show's most transcendent work. His ``Buenos Aires at Night''
series, all printed in gorgeous black-and-white tones, is dreamy
and mysterious. Valansi's nocturnal finds include a ghostly dress
in a cellophane bag; a popcorn machine that at first sight
resembles a fish tank, and a luminescent street banner against a
velvety black sky.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the only photographer who registers the
blatantly cosmopolitan side of the capital and its iconic masks is
not a native porteno, as a resident of Buenos Aires is known. Born
in Santa Fe Province in 1958, Lopez went to film school in Cuba,
and his Technicolor post-modern work is exuberantly irreverent,
with mad touches of Warhol, Cindy Sherman, David Levinthal and
Henri Rousseau.
</P>
<P>
   President Carlos Saul Menem has been praised for halting years
of hyperinflation. So in ``Buenos Aires, the City of Happiness''
(1993), Lopez gives him a kind of visual credit by making drawings
of Menem's smiling face the backdrop for an affluent-looking couple
_ she in white fur, he in wool coat and yellow muffler, both
wearing Chiclet smiles, bright red lipstick and 3-D paper glasses.
</P>
<P>
   The other strikingly post-modern work is by Weber. His series
``Dreams With Me'' is a combination of performance and conceptual
art. Weber asked his subjects to write down their wishes on a small
blackboard, then artfully posed his subjects with the blackboard.
In lesser hands, this would be a hokey enterprise. But Weber gives
his spare black-and-white pictures a lovely narrative spin.
</P>
<P>
   The best is the one in which the wish is for many horses.
Slightly evocative of Sally Mann's pictures of her wise-innocent
children, this photograph is a marvelous portrait of a seemingly
unspoiled young man leaning against a tree, a bamboo grove behind
him, horse reins in his hands, the horse standing nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Also nearby are two little girls, obviously oblivious to the
longed-for wish. One is crouched and looking wide-eyed at the
camera; the other looks away and stands with hands nonchalantly
holding onto bamboo stalks.
</P>
<P>
   Gil's surreal ``Buenos Aires 1984-1996'' series suggests that
the man behind the camera has seen his share of urban horrors but
remains fascinated by the mysteries in human drama. In a riveting
image, a man in white shorts sits at the foot of a tree, bandages
over his eyes, his mouth and one knee.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting beside him is an anguished blond woman in a halter and
sarong skirt, one hand on the man's chest, the other gesturing
desperately at someone or something out of the camera's range.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most powerful images were taken by Ms. Zout. She
began a series on children with AIDS in 1989, and, like Gil, she
has not let the grimness of what she has seen lessen the humanness
of her subjects.
</P>
<P>
   With no-nonsense tenderness, she shows a mother and daughter
with AIDS hidden under a lacy cloth. The cloth may hide their
identities but it is very likely a harbinger of the funeral shroud.
Cruelly highlighting their plight is a photograph above them of a
different mother and child: a healthy mother breastfeeding a
healthy baby.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zout's portrait of a child afflicted with AIDS playing in
his home, his face behind a fright mask, brings to mind the masked
subjects in Ralph Eugene Meatyard's photographs and the violently
distorted faces by Francis Bacon. Here the mask is not just a
kindness to the boy but also a not-so-subtle gibe at a society that
continues to react with horror to those struck by the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myths, Dreams and Realities in Contemporary Argentine
Photography'' remains at the International Center of Photography,
1130 Fifth Ave., at 94th Street, (212) 860-1777, through Sept. 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
