<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-MARTIN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURIES WON'T STOP MARTIN FROM RACING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Mark Martin isn't thinking about the Winston Cup
championship, although he's second in points to Dale Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   And he isn't thinking about his injuries or how much he hurts,
although he is driving with a cast on a broken wrist and a brace on
a fractured knee, which now has a pin in it. All he's thinking
about is the next race, which is Saturday's Brickyard 400.
</P>
<P>
   That the Brickyard is now arguably the second most important
event on the schedule, trailing only the Daytona 500 in many minds,
makes no difference to Martin. To Martin, a race is a race is a
race. You put the same effort into all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Lately though, that has been difficult for Martin, who went hard
into the wall at Daytona in the final practice for the July 3 Pepsi
400 and tore himself up. He put the pain aside to drive the very
next day, ending up 17th. And he drove at New Hampshire the next
week, finishing sixth despite arthroscopic surgery on his knee.
</P>
<P>
   After a week off, he was third at Pocono, where his crew still
had to lift him into and out of the car.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Indy. For many drivers _ especially those who grew up
in open wheel ranks like Jeff Gordon, John Andretti, Tony Stewart
and Kenny Irwin _ it is a huge event.
</P>
<P>
   To Martin, it is another race to do his best, another race to
try and win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to win every one of them, every race I run,''
Martin said. ``That's how I feel about them. I know that's a big
disappointment to a lot of people, but I don't pick one particular
race and say that's it and if I don't win I'm going to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not that way,'' Martin said. ``I try my hardest in
every race I run. It doesn't matter where it is or what's at
stake.''
</P>
<P>
   That he has been able to continue driving competitively,
considering the severity of his injuries, amazes many.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pain is pain,'' Martin said. ``The one thing I have found
about pain, especially in these particular injuries, it reminded me
that whatever hurts new, hurts,'' said Martin, who has been
bothered by a disc problem in his back for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you live with that for awhile, your body adapts to that
pain and you're able to go on and not notice that pain as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still there, but your body becomes adapted to it, and you
learn how to move and get around the pain the best way possible.''
</P>
<P>
   What has never become tolerable, for him, is being unable to
compete. And as long as he can get in a race car, or someone can
put him in, he'll drive, because for Martin, the real pain doesn't
start when he's in the car. It begins when he has to get out.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0247 </DOCNO>
