<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV09-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERY BOY NEEDS A BOX
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Monday Aug. 9)  
(rk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The watchword in father-son relations these days is ``quality
time,'' which in my household means doing a project that could
result in a messy power-saw accident and a panicked run to the
emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Call me old-fashioned, but to me nothing says ``bonding'' like
sitting slumped in the front seat, your severed thumb chilling in
the cooler between your feet, while your hysterical wife fishtails
the Oldsmobile through rush-hour traffic with one hand while
applying pressure to your bloody stump with the other.
</P>
<P>
   The project that Michael and I attempted the other day is called
a ``low box,'' a name that derives from the fact that it is nothing
more than a box, and a rather low one at that.
</P>
<P>
   If you cannot comprehend the purpose of a low box then it is
likely that you are not a 13-year-old boy who has been recently and
seriously bitten by the skateboarding bug.
</P>
<P>
   Florida skateboarders discovered some time ago that standing
motionless atop a skateboard, waiting for a geological event that
would result in something called a ``hill,'' was not only
time-consuming but also incredibly boring. So they built, possibly
with the help of their fathers, boxes and ramps and half-pipes and
other dangerous apparatuses on which they could injure themselves
more expeditiously.
</P>
<P>
   The low box that we built is, or at least should be, 8 feet
long, 4 feet wide and 10 inches high. We made it out of
three-quarter-inch-thick pressure-treated plywood that, in case you
haven't bought any recently, is alarmingly expensive, more
expensive, in fact, than several of the major furniture items in my
living room.
</P>
<P>
   It occurred to me that I might save a lot of money, not to
mention blood, by simply dragging the couch out into the driveway
for Michael and his skateboarding friends to jump onto and off of,
but I figured the years of accumulated dog hairs and Coke stains
might cause some traction problems not to mention complaints from
the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   We bought the blueprints for our low box from a company that
sells such things on the Internet. I did not think the $9.99 price
was horribly outrageous (compared to the price of the plywood, at
least) until I learned, at the end of my order, that the company
required a minimum purchase of $10, thereby requiring me to buy
another set of $9.99 blueprints to make up the penny difference.
And yet some people wonder why there were riots at the Woodstock
concert, where water was selling for $4 a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the blueprint was clear and easy to read, the kind
of blueprint an 8-year-old could follow without any difficulty.
Unfortunately, we didn't have any 8-year-olds handy, which meant
that I had to decipher the blueprints myself, resulting in a sawing
error that came within a half-inch of costing me a $38 piece of
plywood. (Michael has insisted that I report that it was he who
discovered my mistake in the nick of time, which I will be glad to
do if and when he cleans his room.)
</P>
<P>
   Before we began our low-box project, I never really understood
what this ``bonding'' business was all about. But looking back, it
seems to have something to do with squatting together for hours at
a time in the hot sun, driving in numberless screws with a cordless
drill that poops out and needs recharging about every 15 minutes,
drinking lots of Cokes and competing with each other to see who can
burp the loudest.
</P>
<P>
   The bloodletting was confined to a small cut on the back of my
hand (no emergency-room trip necessary) and the effects of the
squatting dissipated over the course of a few short weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The box itself looks a lot like, well, a box, only lower.
Michael and his friends spend hours on it, working on tricks that
have names like ollie and nose slide and half-cab and 50-50. White
with spray-painted green graffiti, it is a nice addition to the
driveway decor.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if it had cushions, I'd consider moving it to the
living room.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
