<HEADLINE>
AUTO SAFETY: A FATAL CRASH'S REPERCUSSIONS, 100 YEARS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a season of anniversaries _ 30 years since the first moon
landing, 25 since Nixon resigned _ Heward Grafftey is pitching one
more. He says that September is the centennial of the first
recorded auto fatality.
</P>
<P>
   If he is correct, the accident would seem to have begun a New
York City trend: The victim was a pedestrian.
</P>
<P>
   The death occurred in Manhattan on Sept. 13, 1899, at Central
Park West and 74th Street. According to an article on the front
page of The New York Times the next day, the victim was H.H. Bliss,
``a real estate dealer.'' He was ``alighting from a southbound
Eighth Avenue trolley car when he was knocked down and run over by
an automobile in charge of Arthur Smith of 153 West 62d Street.''
Smith told police that he had to pass close to the trolley because
a truck was in the way _ a situation that sounds quite plausible
today. The passenger in the car was a doctor returning from a house
call, which no longer seems so likely.
</P>
<P>
   The car, the article noted, was electric. The Times detailed
Bliss' injuries in somewhat greater detail than is now customary.
Smith was arrested, but a search of the following days' papers did
not turn up a disposition to the case. His passenger, Dr. David Orr
Edson, son of a former New York City mayor, provided medical
attention at the scene, but Bliss died later at Roosevelt Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Grafftey, a former member of the Canadian Parliament, said that
a daughter of his secretary, a neighbor and an executive assistant
while he served in the House of Commons had all died in traffic
crashes. He is now president of Safety Sense Institute, a nonprofit
organization Orleans, Ontario, that promotes traffic safety.
</P>
<P>
   Grafftey figures that Bliss was the first of about 30 million
auto fatalities worldwide. He came to New York in 1969 to
commemorate the death, and again in 1989, when two of Bliss' great
grand-daughters attended a ceremony at the site.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Grafftey has organized a ceremony that is to include
the unveiling of a plaque and a speech on auto safety by Rep.
Thomas Petri, R-Wis., chairman of the surface transportation
subcommittee of the House Transportation Committee. Six of Bliss'
descendants are expected at the ceremony, at 10:45 a.m. on Sept. 13
at the site of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   In a century, Grafftey said in a telephone interview, ``We have
doubled life span because of improved health care, but this
man-made epidemic has crept up on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bliss is not exactly a cult figure, but he does have a
following. In 1991, Ralph Nader presented an H.H. Bliss Award to 11
inventors who helped to develop the air bag.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Differing on Car-Truck Deaths  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trucking industry is promoting a new study by the Office of
Motor Carrier and Highway Safety, which regulates heavy trucks,
finding that in truck-car crashes in which someone died, the car
driver's behavior often contributed to the collision.
</P>
<P>
   Trucking opponents cite another recent study, by the General
Accounting Office, that found the Office of Motor Carriers was not
very good at gathering statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The OMC study looked at 8,300 crashes involving one large truck
and one passenger vehicle (a car, van, pickup or sport utility
vehicle) from 1994 through 1996. There are about 2,700 crashes a
year between a single truck and a single passenger vehicle in which
someone dies.
</P>
<P>
   In head-on crashes, the passenger vehicle crossed the double
yellow line 89 percent of the time, and the truck 11 percent, the
study found. In sideswipe crashes in which the truck and passenger
vehicle were moving in opposite directions, the passenger vehicle
hit the truck in 88 percent of the cases. When the two vehicles
were moving in the same direction, the passenger vehicle hit the
truck 72 percent of the time. And in rear-end crashes, 80 percent
of the time it was the passenger vehicle that rear-ended the truck.
</P>
<P>
   The study said that in 71 percent of the crashes, the police
found ``one or more errors or other factors related to the driver's
behavior'' for the passenger vehicle driver, but none for the truck
driver.
</P>
<P>
   This last statistic infuriates those who lobby for tighter
control of trucks. ``The trucking industry has been trying for
years to place most of the blame for accidents on car drivers, and
it's patently false,'' said Michael Scippa, a spokesman for
Citizens for Reliable and Safe Highways, or Crash. The reason for
the statistic, he said, is that in 98 percent of the cases in which
one driver dies, it is the person at the wheel of the car, not the
truck. ``The reports are written based on the truck driver's
recollections,'' Scippa said. ``Dead men tell no tales.''
</P>
<P>
   Another lobbyist for tighter restrictions on trucks, Dr. Gerald
Donaldson of Advocates for Highway and Auto Safety, said that
assignment of factors ``isn't adjudicated fault assignment, but
subjective work by police officers who may have only one live
driver to talk to, the one from the truck.''
</P>
<P>
   But the OMC found that in 15 percent of the crashes, both
drivers survived. And in those, investigators cited the car
driver's behavior 73 percent of the time, compared with 34 percent
for the truck drivers. Donaldson said that when analysts pared
their sample size, eliminating all but the biggest trucks, and
cases in which more than one truck or car was involved, the
remaining 500 cases were too few to allow meaningful conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   In the fatal crashes, the OMC said that physical evidence showed
that for sideswipes and head-on or rear-end crashes, physical
evidence, rather than recollections, established the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   But the GAO told Congress in March that the Office of Motor
Carriers had problems collecting data. One is that its analysis is
not based on thorough investigation at the crash scene. Another is
that the office itself estimates that it never gets reports on
about 38 percent of all crashes, and 30 percent of all fatal
crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The office uses the crash data in part to focus on trucking
companies that have more than their share of crashes. But the GAO
said that 10 states reported fewer than half the fatal crashes
occurring within their borders, and 4 states reported fewer than 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether the crashes that were not reported
differed systematically from those that were reported and analyzed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
