<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Aug. 6, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Another in a series of weak cold fronts will sweep southeast
from the Great Lakes into the Northeast. A few thundershowers will
dampen the hilly terrain of New England, but most coastal sections
should stay dry with ample sunshine and afternoon cumulus clouds.
The boundary between warm and somewhat humid air over the Ohio
Valley and a crisp air mass across the northern Great Lakes will
produce a few clouds but no rain across Michigan and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   A high-pressure system in Kentucky will circulate very warm and
moderately humid air across the Middle Atlantic region. The South
will stay sultry with morning sunshine, yielding to a patchwork of
afternoon cumulus clouds, a few of which will grow into
thunderstorms, especially over Florida and along the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   A disturbance over the Rockies, which produced an all-time
24-hour rainfall record of 4.21 inches in Colorado Springs on
Wednesday, will begin to move over the Plains. As a result, a
cluster of thunderstorms will migrate into Nebraska and Kansas.
Flash flooding is possible in a few sections. Thundershowers
associated with the monsoon circulation of tropical moisture over
New Mexico and Colorado will persist. More showers will dampen
eastern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The weather will turn dull and damp across much of the Pacific
Northwest as a disturbance moves onshore across Oregon.
Thunderstorms will erupt over the Sierra, but sunshine will return
to much of Nevada and Utah. Coastal clouds will linger in
California as onshore winds strengthen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Drizzle Storm
</P>
<P>
   A storm of tiny drizzle drops produced 0.07 inches of
precipitation at Eureka, Calif., on Wednesday, breaking the town's
record rainfall for the date. Actually, drizzle is not light rain.
The diameter of a drizzle drop ranges from about 0.01 inches to
approximately 0.02 inches. Any drop with larger diameter is
considered to be a raindrop, while any drop with a smaller diameter
qualifies as a cloud droplet. That drizzle broke a rainfall record
at Eureka in August is not meteorological heresy. Most August days
are dry, with the average monthly rainfall only about a quarter of
an inch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
