<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATES
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, Aug. 6, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds: Adds: OLY-REPORT, AIRLINES, SHOOTINGS_HAVASH;
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MY-LAI _ WASHINGTON _ Hugh Thompson, the former Army helicopter
pilot in Vietnam credited for cutting short the My Lai massacre of
civilians, appears at a news conference Thursday to promote a newly
published biography. (Dart, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
</P>
<P>
   NARCOLEPSY _ WASHINGTON _ Scientists at Stanford University 's
Center for Narcolepsy report in Thursday's edition of Cell that
they identified the gene responsible for the weird condition, which
causes some people to abruptly fall asleep or become temporarily
paralyzed, even though they remain conscious. A mutation in a brain
receptor responsible for managing a hormone called hypocretin2.
(Nesmith, Cox News Service). 17.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ WASHINGTON _ John Koskinen, head of the President's
Council on Year 2000 Conversion, releases the third quarterly
report on the country's readiness for the Year 2000 date change.
(Geewax, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-COLLEGESWASHINGTON - Education Secretary Richard Riley
scolded the vast majority of the nation's college presidents and
chancellors Thursday for their slow pace in Y2K preparations. ``So
far, only 22 (cq) of the over 5,800 institutitons participating in
the student aid programs have successfully tested'' their data
exchanges with his department, Riley said in a letter to every
president and chancellor. (Mollison, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   DISASTER-INSURANCE _ WASHINGTON _ Insurance companies would be
required to create a special reserve fund for natural disasters
under a bipartisan bill introduced Thursday in Congress. (Hall).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTINGS_HAVASH _ ATLANTA_ Traditional Moslem funeral services
for Jamshid Havash, 44. Delayed until today to allow time for his
wife, Roya, and daughter Tannaz, 7, to return from Tehran, Iran.
They only learned Havash was dead upon return to Atl. Wed. night.
Family believe the way he died was predetermined at birth. Friends
in Iran try to keep him alive with animal sacrifice, but didn't
know at the time that it could do no good. He was dead. Memorial
services planned for Sunday at Westin Hotel in Dunwoody. (Stepp,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ALA-SHOOTINGS _ PELHAM, Ala._Three people were shot to death
Thursday morning at two businesses in a suburb south of Birmingham
and a man who worked at one of the firms was arrested, police said.
We're there for react in wake of last week's Atlanta shootings.
(Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES _ Consumer complaints about airline travel are on the
rise again, according to a Transportation Department report
released Thursday. The complaints include one from one man who said
he was ``imprisioned in the airplane on the runway'' while trying
to fly from Philadelphia to Atlanta this spring. A professional
musician complained that after his saxophone was damaged, a baggage
agent quickly ruled ``claim denied'' and then told the passenger to
``shut up.'' (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ELVIS-TUPELO _ TUPELO , Miss. _ Elvis's birthplace has always
cowered in the shadows of Graceland and the almighty Elvis
foundation that guards the rights to all things The King with
Brinks-like care. But this weekend (starts friday evening), Tupelo
is in the spotlight, hosting its first-ever Elvis Festival. The
event is a street fair featuring a Vegas Elvis ''stylist,'' local
acts, Gospel, blues and even some old stars from the Sun Records
days. A Cadillac will be given away, just as Elvis used to give
away caddys to friends and waitresses. This north Mississippi town
has no idea if 600 or 6 zillion Elvis fans will show up this year.
(Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: (Elvis Week in Memphis begins Sunday through Aug. 16,
marking the Aug. 16 anniversary of The King's death in 1977 at his
Graceland Mansion.)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ King &AMP; Spalding has rescinded the earlier
comprehensive report to Congress on Atlanta Olympic gift-giving
practices, admitting it was incomplete and incorrect. (Turner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHPARTY _ The Southern Party, a fledgling organization whose
symbol incorporates the Confederate flag, says it seeks diverse
members who support its goals of limiting the federal government's
role in peoples' lives. Short of reversing what it calls the
country's slide toward federal tyranny, the party advocates
Southern independence from the United States. A curtain riser on
the party's inaugural rally Saturday in Flat Rock, N.C. (Burritt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-RACE _ CHICAGO_In their bids for the Democratic nomination,
Bill Bradley and Vice President Gore have been reaching out to
minority voters, a key voting block in the Democratic primary.
Despite Bradley's long record of speaking out on racial issues,
most analysts say that Gore holds the edge, benefiting in part from
the strong support black voters give President Clinton. They note
that Gore is strongest in the South, where most black voters live,
and that Bradley hasn't made a serious attempt to build grassroots
support in the region. Bradley attempts to make inroads among black
voters with a speech to the Rainbow Coalition's annual meeting
Thursday. Tipper Gore will speak later in the day and the vice
president will deliver a key note address Saturday. (Foskett,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ATOM _ First Atom bomb dropped on Japan. Eyewitness to History
accounts. Norman Ingram was among the first GIs to occupy Japan. He
has pix of him and a pal standing amid the atomic rubble. Also
Roger Farlow, co-pilot of a B-24, saw the Hiroshima bomb explode.
(Kalajian, Palm Beach Post). 43. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ATOMSIDE _ Three more eyewitness accounts. (Kalajian, Palm Beach
Post). 10.
</P>
