<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ASO appreciates Levi with Beethoven concerts
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Symphony Orchestra has announced a
seven-concert Beethoven Festival for June 2000, to be conducted by
music director Yoel Levi as the final programs of his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   The concerts, called by the ASO ``A Celebration and Appreciation
of Yoel Levi,'' are offered to ``underscore the gratitude felt by
the entire Atlanta Symphony family'' for Levi's 12-year
directorship, according to ASO board chairman A.D. Frazier Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the greatest musical challenges imaginable, and
I had been thinking about doing it for some time,'' Levi said
Wednesday. ``It is rarely done, to perform all of Beethoven's
symphonies and concertos in one shot, which makes it a truly
special cultural event for the community.''
</P>
<P>
   But Levi declined comment on the ASO's official gesture of
farewell, according to ASO spokesman Charlie Wade.
</P>
<P>
   Levi said in an interview Wednesday that he had been given a
printer's proof of the planned summer brochure during a rehearsal
break the previous day and had not had time to read it. Nor would
he discuss anything more about it until after this weekend's
performances of ``The Abduction From the Seraglio.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled for June 9-24 in Symphony Hall, the Beethoven concerts
will feature the nine symphonies, the five piano concertos with
Argentine pianist Bruno Leonardo Gelber, the triple concerto (for
violin, cello and piano) with the Eroica Trio and the violin
concerto with ASO concertmaster Cecylia Arzewski. All except the
trio are old friends and musical colleagues of Levi.
</P>
<P>
   The final concert will include the ``Choral Fantasy,'' with
Gelber playing the piano solo, and the ``Choral'' Symphony No. 9,
both to be sung by the ASO Chorus. Vocal soloists for this program
have yet to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   The ASO describes the Beethoven concerts as ``a tribute ... to
culminate (the ASO's) season-long salute to esteemed music director
Yoel Levi.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement incorporates a summation of his accomplishments
with the ASO, including:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The 1991 European tour, which received excellent critical
notices.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  28 recordings, including the first four increments of a Mahler
symphony cycle. Next season's performances of the Symphonies Nos. 1
and 2 will be recorded by Telarc International to continue the
cycle.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A Grammy Award nomination for ``The Planets,'' the first ASO
recording not conducted by the late Robert Shaw to be nominated.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The ASO's performance at the opening ceremonies of the 1996
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The ASO's nomination as ``Orchestra of the Year'' (1991-92)
for the first annual International Classical Music Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets to the Beethoven concerts are $25, on sale today through
the ASO season ticket office. Those who buy four tickets will
receive one free. Ticket information: 404-733-4800 or
www.atlantasymphony.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In other ASO news, soloists for the master season finale
program of Mahler's Symphony No. 2 (''Resurrection'') in May will
be Margaret Lloyd, soprano, and Mary Phillips, mezzo.
</P>
<P>
   The ASO's New Year's Eve concert will be led by guest conductor
Robert Spano instead of Levi. Tickets for the New Year's Eve
dinner/concert package are $40-$90.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
