<SLUG> BC-MOTORCYCLE-AUCTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOTHEBY'S HOPES TO SELL A $500,000 MOTORCYCLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(DW) 
 By JIM McCRAW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sotheby's, the auction house known for selling objets d'art,
plans a sale of high-performance and vintage motorcycles, its first
in North America, on Sept. 13 in Chicago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's Chicago showroom will feature about 100 motorcycles
from around the world, as well as 150 antique and vintage bicycles
and related memorabilia. The sale will be led by a number of
Italian-made Ducati motorcycles, including some famous racing
machines, street bikes, racing memorabilia, parts and champions'
racing leathers. Items will be exhibited on Monday through Thursday
the week of the auction.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sirolli, director of Sotheby's Chicago, said: ``You're no
longer dealing with the same crowd of people who for years traded
bikes at swap meets and bought them from garages. You now have Wall
Street execs and traders all of whom are very into motorcycles _
extraordinary toys for big boys, to some extent.'' Sirolli likens
Ducati design to Italian Futurist works by Giacomo Balla, Umberto
Boccioni and Gino Severini, for their movement and mechanical
flavor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The piece de resistance of the Sotheby's sale will be a
one-of-a-kind Ducati MH900e, a bike designed by Pierre Terblanche
to recall the 1978 Ducati F1 ridden to victory at the Isle of Man
TT races in 1978 by Mike Hailwood, the British world champion.
Sirolli says there is no precedent for the sale of such a
motorcycle; he expects a serious collector to bid at least
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Second only to the MH900e in collector interest and value will
be the Ducati 996 factory racer ridden to the 1998 Superbike world
championship by Carl Fogarty, the British three-time Superbike
champion. Sotheby's has estimated the selling price of this bike at
$180,000 to $200,000 because of its racing record and 200 mph
performance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fogarty's personal Ducati, a 1998 Monster 600 with a shark paint
job, is also offered, with an estimate or $15,000 to $22,000, along
with a Ducati 900 Super Sport Final Edition, at $12,000 to $15,000,
and a 1997 Ducati Senna 916, a special model dedicated to the late
Ayrton Senna, the Formula One world champion from Brazil, which is
expected to fetch $22,000-$28,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Ducatis, motorcycles from the collection of the
late Frederick G. Wacker will be offered. These include a 1922
Ricardo Triumph 550, a 1950 Vincent 1000 Custom and a 1924
Harley-Davidson JD. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
