A7184 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      08-05 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON SAYS RESCUING TROUBLED YOUTH HELPS THE NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 and DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TONAWANDA, N.Y. _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton urged
Americans Thursday to tune out violent television programs and join
a crusade to help troubled young people become productive,
taxpaying adults who can help underwrite the retirement of baby
boomers.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, after hearing nightmarish stories of inner-city
life in nearby Buffalo, appealed to the self-interest of the
American middle class in hopes of rescuing gang members or other
alienated young people.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing her exploration for a possible Senate campaign in New
York, the first lady issued an impassioned plea for parents to
protect their children from the ``overwhelming amount of violence
and mayhem'' in some television programming. She urged parents to
use the technical device called a ``V-chip'' to block violent
programing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot give our children their childhoods back if we throw
them into a situation that you would not let (come) into your
house,'' Clinton said, her voice rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody knocked on the door, and said, `Let me come in,
yell and scream and swear and carry on, and use an assault weapon
in front of your child,' you'd say, `You're crazy,' and you'd call
the police.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clinton said Americans ``invite those people into our living
rooms'' every day through the television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, be the bad guy on the block and maybe you'll set an
example for the rest of the parents,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady told an audience invited for a round-table
discussion at an elementary school in suburban Buffalo that the
nation cannot afford to lose a single potentially productive worker
in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Within 15 years there will be only two employed workers paying
into the Social Security system for ever one of the 76 million baby
boomers who begin to retire in 2011.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now every time I'm in a group of young people, I'm trying to
figure out which are my two because I want to make sure that my two
are going to be productive working citizens to support the whole
system as the rest of us get older,'' said Clinton, 51.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said her outlook is ``a way that all of us ought to be
thinking because there really isn't anybody else's kids that we can
waste, that we can walk away from.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady also expressed her ``great disappointment'' with
the Republican-led Congress for ``its lack of action'' on ``common
sense'' gun safety legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that guns play a very important role in the level of
violence and fear in our communities _ and unfortunately in our
schools,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton heard vivid accounts of inner city strife from teachers
and students with experience in the tough neighborhoods of Buffalo,
a city of 311,000 people less than 10 miles to the south of
Tonawanda.
</P>
<P>
   Although the discussion took place in a middle-class suburb,
Clinton spokesman Howard Wolfson said the first lady planned to
visit inner-city neighborhoods later in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Schuta, a curriculum specialist at an inner-city school
in West Buffalo, recounted a second-grade girl arriving at school
one morning to tell the authorities to call the police because her
father had broken both of her mother's arms and torn the phone from
the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Schuta also introduced the first lady to one of her students,
whose father is in prison for murder. Schuta drove the young
student home from school one afternoon to see gunplay under way in
the boy's neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a natural part of David's life,'' Schuta said.
</P>
<P>
   Tomeka Sanders, a high school senior in East Buffalo, told
Clinton how hard it is for teen-agers to turn aside the allure of
gangs or temptations to fight at an inner-city school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really easy to be bad. If I wanted to get a gun, I could
get a gun right now,'' she said. ``It's not considered cool to be
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady told her, ``If you can give young people a good
gang _ a theater group, a team, a band to be part of _ they'll join
a good gang 99 times out of 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Trooper Bill Conway, a 21-year veteran on the New York State
Police, recalled a 10-year-old girl approaching him in a Buffalo
school not long ago to alert him that her uncle had been molesting
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a police officer in the building that they know that
they could come to is an asset,'' Conway said. Clinton endorsed
setting up ways for students to tip the authorities, either through
suggestion boxes or secure telephone hot lines.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton referred to the killings at Columbine High School in
Colorado, where two students killed 12 classmates and a teacher
before committing suicide, and at two brokerage houses in Atlanta,
where a frustrated stock trader killed nine people and wounded 13
others before committing suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The two episodes underscore that ``no criminal deterrent can
stop someone who is both homicidal and suicidal,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke before she learned about the latest multiple killing
in Pelham, Ala., were the police said three people were shot dead
at two businesses. The suspected gunman was in police custody.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Washington, a prominent Republican defended the
first lady and her interview with Talk magazine in which she
discussed her husband's infidelity and attributed it to troubles in
his childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, a Republican presidential contender
until he dropped out of the race last month, said he didn't think
Hillary Clinton was making excuses for her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what she was saying is `I hate what the president did.
My take is he did it for these reasons. I don't think he did it
because he's a bad guy. I think he did it because he's got these
problems that he hasn't fixed.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a tragic thing for this woman,'' Kasich said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell and Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920.
Their e-mail addresses are stewart(at)hearstdc.com and
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
