A7185 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-MYSTERYMEN-TEX     08-05 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MYSTERYMEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEEBLE, LAUGHABLE SUPERHEROES COMPETE WITH FUTURISTIC SET IN
`MYSTERY MEN'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you followed the blueprints combining Joel Schumacher and Tim
Burton's Gotham City and employed the building materials used to
create Ridley Scott's ``Blade Runner,'' you'd probably come up with
the architecture of Champion City, the setting of the action-spoof
``Mystery Men.''
</P>
<P>
   The matte-blue towers stretch so high they appear to be a danger
to passenger plane traffic. The overambitious set design is a
winning joke. However, between the overly elaborate sets and the
wide-angle, deep-focus shots used by director Kinka Usher _ the guy
behind ``Got Milk'' and ``Yo quiero Taco Bell'' ads _ ``Mystery
Men'' eclipses ``Armageddon'' as the most determinedly busy visual
spectacle of the decade. Half the time, there's so much going on
that you're not sure where to look.
</P>
<P>
   An unfortunate situation, because ``Mystery Men'' is an idea
whose time has come, a parody of superheroes with a hard-working
group of actor-comedians as its stars. Ben Stiller is Mr. Furious,
a runt dressed in rough-trade leather motorcycle gear who can
become a ``ball of rage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shoveler (William H. Macy) is the calm yin to Mr. Furious'
yang, wearing his little boy's catcher's vest and wielding a
shovel. The Blue Raja (Hank Azaria), with his fruity fake British
accent and lack of blue in his costume, flings silverware, ``but no
knives.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the least lethal superheroes in memory _ and the least
powerful _ this core of the Mystery Men is a pathetic version of
the Justice League of America. They labor in the shadow of Champion
City superhero, and super sellout, Captain Amazing (Greg Kinnear),
whose jumpsuit sports more logos than the entire pack at the Indy
500. When the smirking Captain Amazing is dispatched by
superannuated disco villain Casanova Frankenstein (Geoffrey Rush),
Champion City has no choice but to turn to the jealous Mystery Men.
</P>
<P>
   Or rather, the Men force themselves on the city. They shore up
their numbers with the Bowler (Janeane Garofalo), the most
dangerous one of the bunch _ she hurls a bowling ball possessed
with the spirit of her father. At least, she talks to him through
it all the time, anyway. Invisible Boy (Kel Mitchell, of
Nickelodeon's ``Kenan and Kel,'' reprising the happy-go-lucky
earnestness of his ``Good Burger'' character without the surfer's
accent) can maybe turn invisible, but only if no one is looking.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there are those who think the Spleen (Paul Reubens) is the
most dangerous. It appears at first his power is his warty, pasty
bad skin. Until he lets loose his explosive flatulence, which sends
good and evil alike to their knees in tears. The Sphinx (Wes Studi)
has a moldy aphorism for every situation, when he isn't
mysteriously carving guns in half _ maybe his real power is to bore
men's minds.
</P>
<P>
   The director is so busy finding God in the details that the
actors are left on their own. Reubens noted that the cast was an
able collection of writers on their own, and Usher was smart enough
to stay out of their way. Which leaves the movie without a unifying
narrative. The funny moments dissipate because the movie's all over
the place.
</P>
<P>
   The actors, whose chic makes the movie look as if it were cast
out of an issue of Details magazine, are battling with the costumes
and set design. Tom Waits shows up as a weapons inventor who
cruises rest homes for dates. And there are turns by the Fugees'
Pras, British comedian Eddie Izzard (who maybe one day will not
have to wear a '70s retro wardrobe in a movie), and the Goodie Mob
(playing villains called the Not So Goodie Mob). The schism makes
``Mystery Men'' more facetious than funny.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the movie's central idea, squabbling second-raters who
have to get past their neuroses to do some good, is worthwhile.
Surprisingly, creator Burden's concept remains intact. (Don't
worry, ``Flaming Carrot'' fans. The rights to Burden's original
creation _ the Mystery Men were secondary characters in the
Carrot's book _ were secured by other producers, so don't think he
wasn't good enough for this movie.)
</P>
<P>
   The film lacks Burden's wormy, depressed surrealism. Burden's
heroes would be more at home in a trailer park eaten away by weeds,
not this steroided world of the future. Instead of being close to
Burden's world in that way _ he made an eccentric mess _ the movie
of ``Mystery Men'' is an ecstatic mess.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Mystery Men''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Kinka Usher
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Ben Stiller, Janeane Garofalo, William H. Macy
</P>
<P>
   Length: 113 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ violence, including humans melted by a ray gun,
and adult language
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
