<HEADLINE>
NEBRASKA IS GOVERNED DIFFERENTLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I understand that Nebraska has a different form of state
government. Can you explain this?
</P>
<P>
   _S.W., Granbury, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Nebraska is the only state that has a unicameral legislature.
Legislators are elected to a State Senate _ commonly known as ``the
Unicameral'' _ rather than a house and senate in bicameral
governments such as Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The state's unicameral system was approved in 1934, cutting the
number of elected legislators from 133 to 43 and reducing the cost
of funding a session of the legislature in half.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference unique to Nebraska is its nonpartisan
election. Legislative candidates are listed on the ballot without
identifying their party affiliation, and the top two vote-getters
in the primary face off in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   The Nebraska Unicameral Web site at www.unicam.state.ne.us
includes a complete history of the system.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to make a report on a tax charged by a Saginaw, Texas,
grocery store. What's the 800 number that used to be Bob Bullock's
office?
</P>
<P>
   _ U.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: To report a possible violation of the state's sales tax laws,
call the Comptroller of Public Accounts at (800) 252-5555.
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller monitors state sales tax collection, auditing
businesses at least once every four years. The basic sales tax rate
is 6.25 percent, though city, county and special districts can
increase the rate up to 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A sales tax holiday on most clothing and footwear priced under
$100 will be Aug. 6-8. The purchase of any qualifying item will not
include a state or local sales tax. The main items that are not
exempt from tax during the holiday are clothing and footwear used
primarily as protective wear or for athletic activities.
</P>
<P>
   The event, scheduled to occur the first Friday, Saturday and
Sunday of each August, is expected to reduce this year's sales tax
collections by $84.7 million, state Comptroller Carole Keeton
Rylander predicts.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm unable to find the TV show ``Judge Wapner's Animal
Court'' in my TV guide. When and where does it air?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.H., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Animal Court'' airs three times a day during the week on
the cable channel Animal Planet.
</P>
<P>
   The show premiered in September 1998 and features small-claims
cases involving animals. Rusty Burrell, Judge Joseph Wapner's
bailiff on ``People's Court,'' has the same position on the new
program.
</P>
<P>
   Wapner, 79, is a former Los Angeles Superior Court judge whose
TV jurisprudence career began with ``People's Court'' in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
