<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP EXAMINES POPULAR CULTURE TO DETERMINE WHAT PEOPLE WANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do people want?
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the burning question in business today. Never
before have companies been so eager to zero in on the products and
services that people need and desire.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many are beginning to realize that answering that
question correctly can lead to unparalleled success. Missing the
boat, or even worse, not paying attention to the customers, can
lead to disaster.
</P>
<P>
   All that makes companies such as Iconoculture even more
valuable.
</P>
<P>
   This interesting group of marketers lists its offices as
``somewhere between cyberspace and a Starbucks in Minneapolis.''
Their focus is popular culture, specifically American, and their
methodology involves traveling cross-country by car, browsing the
Web, reading everything in sight and ``relentless'' channel surfing
on television.
</P>
<P>
   Then the group members _ Mary Meehan, Larry Samuel and Vickie
Abrahamson _ get together to ``make sense out of the cultural
chaos, make key connections, and discuss the implications for
individuals and marketers.''
</P>
<P>
   Iconoculture's clients include the likes of General Mills,
Wendy's and Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't afford to hire this group, you certainly can afford
its book, which is out in paperback. It's called ``The Future Ain't
What It Used to Be: The 40 Cultural Trends Transforming Your Job,
Your Life, Your World'' (Burkley Publishing Group, 270 pages
$14.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``These forty cultural trends are literal signs of the times,
guideposts that point the way for you to proactively manage your
future,'' they write. ``Think of signs as territories to stake with
your career, business or brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider their take on ``zentrepreneurism,'' businesses out to
make a positive social change as well as some monetary change. The
Iconoculture group calls it ``the fusion of one's personal vision
with one's professional mission, grounded in activism and holistic
philosophy,'' adding that this trend will be the hallmark of the
next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The group provides numerous examples of zentrepreneurism from
New York City's ``Street News,'' a newspaper for homeless vendors
to sell so they can get back on their feet, to Aveda's lipstick,
which is made in cooperation with an Amazon Indian tribe that
benefits from sales of the makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Investing, trade, even transportation (Greyhound offers free
rides for runaways returning home) are cashing in on doing good.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows that ethnic is in, but did you know that in the
1980s, more immigrants came into this country than in any other
decade in American history _ about 10 million? Or that more than 80
percent of them were Latin American or Asian and that 75 percent of
them came to just six states, including Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Such a trend affects everything from food and beverages to
tourism to fitness to education. Diversity will be the name of the
game in virtually every product and service seeking success in the
next century.
</P>
<P>
   Along with all that diversity, however, is another strong trend
toward ``beehiving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where you look and with whom you share physical, emotional,
educational, and spiritual hallelujahs and high-fives will not
necessarily be the traditional venues of home, neighborhood, work
and Main Street,'' the group writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``New beehives of shared interests and value are buzzing on the
horizon, reshaping relationships inside and outside of the
honeycomb.''
</P>
<P>
   That trend is being adopted in branding (Saturn,
Harley-Davidson), housing (retirement communities) and technology
(chat sites, support groups). Iconoculture calls the American
Association of Retired Persons the biggest beehive of all. Watch
for it to get even more enormously powerful within the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian philosophy of chi, or tapping into your body's energy
flow for health and well-being, is taking this country by storm. So
is fingerprinting, in which each person has a personal consumer
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   The trends are there, spelled out in black and white, in a
fascinating look of where society is heading, and how to cater to
it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wall Street Journal Guide to Understanding Money &AMP;
Investing''
</P>
<P>
   By Kenneth M. Morris and Virginia B. Morris
</P>
<P>
   Lightbulb Press, $15.95
</P>
<P>
   This colorful, graphic-laden, easy-to-read guide takes the dull
gray out of most investment primers and makes it almost fun to
learn about. A popular book since it was first published in 1993,
it has sold more than a million copies and has even been translated
into Chinese. The revised edition includes many of the changes in
the financial world.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The 101 Toughest Interview Questions ... and Answers That Win
the Job''
</P>
<P>
   By Daniel Porot
</P>
<P>
   Ten Speed Press, $12.95
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you worth?'' ``How do you react when you realize you
made a mistake?'' ``Why are you looking for a new job?'' If
questions like this make your skin crawl, this book should keep
your mouth from freezing and your mind from going blank. Written in
a simple question and answer format, it provides four or five ways
to answer these tough questions. An excellent resource for a tricky
situation.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Your Y2K Personal Protection Plan''
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Hickman
</P>
<P>
   HarperResource Book, $15
</P>
<P>
   The ``electronic tidal wave'' is coming, and this author
recommends having the goods and wherewithal to sustain yourself for
at least two weeks after the new century dawns. The bad news, says
Jim Hackman, who guides workshops on Y2K readiness around the
country, is that there is a good chance the telephone and electric
systems will go down at least temporarily because of the software
problem. The good news is that the banks have worked through most
of their Y2K problems, and that our home appliances should be
unaffected.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
