<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7191 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SPYING-HNS &LR;      08-05 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SPYING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA SPYING REPORT EXAMINES RENO'S ROLE IN U.S. PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A string of ``baffling decisions'' by Attorney
General Janet Reno and Justice Department officials stifled the
FBI's investigation into possible Chinese espionage and may have
prevented the agency from catching a nuclear spy, a congressional
report charged Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., chairman of the Senate Governmental
Affairs Committee, who wrote the report with Sen. Joe Lieberman of
Connecticut, the committee's top Democrat, said much of the blame
for the ``shockingly poor'' investigation lies with Reno who
appeared ``out of the loop'' for many important decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very troubled by the Department of Justice in this case
because it had a string of baffling decisions,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also criticized Reno, saying she should have been more
involved in the investigation, which he called a ``tragedy of
errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she had not seen the report and had no comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the FBI's espionage case against the Los Alamos
National Laboratory weapons scientist, Wen-Ho Lee, was considered
``flawed from the outset'' because authorities failed to
investigate a number of other nuclear lab workers who had access to
the W-88 information and who appeared to be security risks because
of their close associations with Chinese scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, the investigation disregarded many people
who could be guilty,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional report detailed information gathered during
two closed-door hearings the committee held this spring on the
federal investigation into the possible theft of design information
on the W-88 nuclear warhead. The weapon is used in the Trident II
submarine-launched ballistic missile system carried aboard many
U.S. submarines.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's investigation eventually led to Lee, who was fired
from his top-secret job last March for minor security violations
after becoming the probe's primary suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a Taiwan-born naturalized U.S. citizen, has not been
charged with a crime.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional report said it has no evidence that the W-88
or other nuclear weapons information had been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview last Sunday, Lee categorically denied
providing nuclear secrets to China or anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   However, the congressional report disclosed that Lee failed a
polygraph test in February when asked if he had passed nuclear
secrets ``to any unauthorized person.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-page report focused much of its criticism on the FBI's
unsuccessful attempts to get Justice Department approval to search
Lee's office computer.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1997, the FBI urged the department to request the
Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court to issue a warrant allowing
the FBI to search Lee's office computer and to place him under
surveillance, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's told the department that Lee had ``extremely close''
contacts with Chinese scientists, had traveled often to China, had
given a Chinese scientist unclassified but weapons-related computer
codes and had contacted another U.S. scientist who was under
investigation at a separate nuclear lab.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Department officials refused to ask for a search
warrant on the ground that the FBI had ``not sufficiently
demonstrated a connection between Lee and the compromise of the
W-88 information.''
</P>
<P>
   In August 1997, Reno was alerted to the FBI's inability to get a
search warrant, the report said. She then asked the deputy attorney
general's office to look into it but never heard back, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said it was ``unfathomable'' that the Justice
Department refused the FBI's request on such an important matter.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said it was ``remarkable'' that FBI Director Louis
Freeh ``didn't just picked up the phone and say to Reno, `Stop
treating this like it's a burglary.'''
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that the dispute between the FBI and Justice
Department likely was unnecessary because Lee had signed a privacy
waiver allowing authorities to search his computer and that his
computer, in fact, carried a ``banner'' warning that such searches
could be made.
</P>
<P>
   That the FBI was unaware of Lee's signed waiver was the result
of a series of misunderstandings between an FBI field agent and Los
Alamos officials in 1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to provide accurate information to senior FBI and
Justice Department officials had ``significant implications for the
course of the Lee espionage investigation,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (entire probe) is a story of investigatory missteps,
miscommunications, misunderstandings and mistakes at all levels of
government,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators finally searched Lee's computer in March and found
he had transferred thousands of top-secret computer code files from
a highly secured computer system in Los Alamos to his unclassified
office computer that was linked to the Internet. It has not been
determined whether any of those files ever left the lab.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was fired on March 8 for minor security violations, such as
leaving his computer unattended and not protecting papers that were
unclassified but sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that while the scientist's activities were
suspicious and deserved to be investigated, the FBI should not have
limited its probe to Lee and his wife, Sylvia, also a Los Alamos
employee.
</P>
<P>
   The report said ``key technical information'' concerning the
W-88 warhead was available at a number of other government and
military sites where workers could have stolen the data, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the start, the government excluded a whole group of
people who could be responsible ... and who could still be
operating,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   These other suspects also had access to the secret information
at Los Alamos, traveled to China, had contacts with Chinese
scientists visiting the New Mexico lab, and fit the profile that
made Lee a prime suspect, the report said. Still, they were not
investigated in any detail, although the FBI questioned some of
them earlier this year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
