<HEADLINE>
BUSH APPEALS TO IOWANS WITH TAX CUTS, FARM POLICY  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST DES MOINES, Iowa _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush tried to lure
traditional Republican Iowans into his presidential camp for next
week's straw poll Thursday with talk on tax cuts, preserving Social
Security and farm policy.
</P>
<P>
   In just his third visit to Iowa, the Republican front-runner
said he is taking seriously the Aug. 14 Ames straw poll and
believes it will be a show of the strength of his grass-roots
organization in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're for me, I'm honored to have you on my team,'' Bush
told about 300 people in West Des Moines. ``If you haven't made up
your mind yet, thank you for giving me a chance to share some
thoughts with you. If you're for somebody else, that's OK. Just
don't work too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has not been campaigning as hard in Iowa as most of
his Republican rivals, his staff has organized buses to bring
people from almost 110 cities to Ames and give them $25 tickets so
they can participate in the straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has arranged for a slate of country and western
entertainers at his 65,000 square foot tent outside the coliseum
where the straw poll will be held, as well as appearances by former
Dallas Cowboys quarterback Roger Staubach and bass fishing
professional Johnny Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has been criticized for vagueness on the issues
discussed taxes and farm issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bush played to his Iowa audience in saying he backs the
controversial ethanol tax credit for turning grain into
alcohol-based fuel. He also said he supports ``emergency cash
payments'' to farmers and said he wants to open European markets up
to ``biogenetically grown corn.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush restated his support for the compromise tax cut package put
together by congressional Republicans, saying the tax bill that
President Clinton has threatened to veto contains many elements he
supports, including cutting marginal tax rates, eventually
eliminating estate taxes and the so-called ``marriage penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted, however, that he wants to use part of the nation's
budget surplus to shore up Social Security for people already
committed to the system. But Bush said he wants to expand Social
Security so that part of the payroll deduction for Social Security
could go to individual savings accounts for younger people.
</P>
<P>
   The governor did not go into details on what percentage of
Social Security money &UR;  &LR; could be diverted to such accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``However much is possibly affordable,'' Bush said. ``Personal
savings accounts will make it more likely that younger contributors
to Social Security will have money available when they retire.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to appealing to traditional Iowa Republicans, Bush
met Thursday with a group of about three dozen Hispanics, almost
half of whom were employees of the University Park Holiday Inn
where he was speaking. The meeting had been described on his
schedule as a meeting with Hispanic ``leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   He came under tough questioning from the group, whose views of
Republicans had obviously been forged by anti-immigration and
anti-affirmative action policies promoted by former California Gov.
Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Bush received hearty applause from the group when he said he
opposes ``English only'' programs.
</P>
<P>
   But others said Bush's stands on using ``affirmative access'' to
replace affirmative action, on immigration and how to treat
undocumented workers already in this country were ill-defined and
left them wondering about the depth of his plea to Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's interested in getting our votes, he needs to give us
some specifics. I didn't feel he gave any specifics,'' said Sandra
Sanchez, a naturalized citizen who directs Immigrants Rights
Project of the American Friends Service Committee, a non-profit
organization that helps local Hispanic immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in his heart he is very earnest. He in his heart
really believes it is important to reach out to Hispanics,''
Sanchez said. But she added that anti-immigrant policies in
California have soured many Hispanics to Republican candidates in
general.
</P>
<P>
   However, Mike Murillo of West Des Moines praised Bush for taking
a position that could force other Republicans to start addressing
Hispanics and Hispanic issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the new future and the new direction of the Republican
Party for Hispanics,'' Murillo said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
