<HEADLINE>
RESENDING TO CORRECT MOVIE TITLE  
 `THE DINNER GAME' ISN'T CINEMA MAGIC BUT IT STILL WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With his two Gerard Depardieu-Pierre Richard teamings, ``La
Chevre'' (1982) and ``Les Comperes'' (1983), French writer-director
Francis Veber found a near-perfect star chemistry and scored two of
the funniest mismatched buddy comedies of the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   In his new film, ``The Dinner Game,'' he tries to recreate some
of that same distinctive chemistry with two new actors, Thierry
Lhmerette and Jacques Villeret. Not surprisingly, lightning doesn't
strike twice in the same place, but the results are passably
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which opened the last Seattle International Film
Festival and moves into a regular run on Friday, is about Pierre
(Lhmeritte), a shallow Parisian publisher trying to find a guest to
bring to a dinner that's actually a secret contest by his friends
to see who can find the biggest ``idiot'' _ so they can laugh at
him.
</P>
<P>
   And the despicable yuppie seems to find the perfect fool in
Francois (Villeret), a sweet-spirited but impossibly naive and
clutzy tax accountant whose avocation is building scale models of
famous buildings and monuments with matchsticks.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner has Pierre snared this perfect dinner guest than
everything goes wrong. Not only does an injury keep him from the
dinner, he can't get rid of Francois, and his meddling steadily
creates havoc in Pierre's well-ordered life: alienating both his
wife and mistress, even triggering a tax audit.
</P>
<P>
   From the first scene, it's clear that Veber is out to recerate
his early-'80s successes by once again teaming a hunky, attractive
leading man (Lhhmeritte instead of Depardieu) with a knockabout
physical comedian (Villeret standing in for Richard), and letting
the sparks fly.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't completely work. Barely 78 minutes long, the film
seems incorrigibly slight for a feature, Lhmeritte never quite
works his way into the likable range, Villeret is almost too
bumbling to be believable, and the pair never really click as a
comedy team.
</P>
<P>
   But if not cinema magic, ``The Dinner Game'' is still a workable
screwball comedy of frustration. Veber builds and sustains an
enjoyably frantic pace, his physical gags are clever and
imaginative, and the formula works to the extent that it's always
fun to watch an arrogant smartie get his comeuppance at the hands
of the lovable fool.
</P>
<P>
   The Dinner Game. Directed and written by Francis Veber. Produced
by Alain Poire. Cast: Thierry Lhermitte, Jacques Villeret, Francis
Huster, Daniel Prevost, Catherine Frot. Lions Gate. 78 minutes. In
French with English subtitles. Rated PG-13 for sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
