<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNDAY-IN-BERLIN-925&AMP;     08-05 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-IN-BERLIN-925&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKING MERCHANDISE `SOUVENIRS,' A BERLIN STORE DEFIES SUNDAY
SHOPPING BAN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Called everything from Rambo to an apostle of German
freedom, his courage compared to that of the people who brought
down the Berlin wall, a middle-aged department store executive with
a very big mustache has emerged as the most talked-about man in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Guenter Biere and his much-discussed revolution has
consisted in opening the large Kaufhof department store on the
Alexanderplatz here on a Sunday. In so doing, he defied the
labyrinthine shop-closing law intended to insure that Sunday
remains a rest day for Europe's largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that his coup, which he has vowed to repeat every
Sunday, occurred as newspapers here pondered how to fill their
August columns. It is also true that most Germans are at the beach.
The chancellor is in Positano, an Italian resort, and the
substantial Toskana-Fraktion (Tuscany Set) in Parliament has
retired to its villas. Still, Germany is about as close to abuzz as
it ever gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about me,'' Biere, 55, said as he tugged a strand
of his mustache out toward his left ear. ``It is about changing an
absurd situation. Our law on Sunday shopping is as full of holes as
a Swiss cheese, and I decided to indulge in a little provocation
designed to bring Germany into the modern world.''
</P>
<P>
   Biere should know about Swiss cheeses _ he has been in retailing
at various Kaufhof branches for 41 years, rising from an apprentice
to store manager. Along the way, he learned how to market an idea.
</P>
<P>
   For there is now little doubt that his brazen challenge to the
law, applauded by the 50,000 people who shopped at Kaufhof last
Sunday, has touched a nerve in a country increasingly torn between
custom and innovation, control and deregulation, and between the
different desires of its eastern and western parts.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufhof occupies the building that was formerly the main
department store for state-produced goods in Communist East
Germany, and that neatly symbolizes the fact that challenges to a
stolid, complacent western German society are increasingly coming
from the brasher east.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the Sunday store opening in what was until 1989
the main square of East Berlin, the Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung
commented that the ``conventions of western Germany'' were being
challenged by a movement ``whose message was clear _ free at
last.''
</P>
<P>
   That may seem a lot for Germany's most serious newspaper to read
into buying sheets, shirts or sugar on a Sunday. But then shopping
is a lot more than shopping when done on German soil. It is a
legally intricate, culturally charged, emotional and sometimes
frustrating undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   Its rules are defined with the laborious detail of a tax code,
complete with exemptions, special conditions and rigorous
deadlines. Its significance is often charged with the weight of a
cultural conflict between America's frenzied materialism and the
gentler pace of European society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course the American drugstore has to be open at any time
when the cowboy swings by,'' said Ingo Schwoppe, an official at the
union representing about 200,000 store employees. ``But ours is a
different, less consumerist culture. Our members still think it is
important that Sunday be a day for the family and for children.''
</P>
<P>
   The current law bans shopping on Sundays in most of the country,
except in airports, gas stations and train stations. As a result,
some new shopping malls, like the 140-store complex in Leipzig
opened in 1997, have been built in train stations, making it very
convenient to buy bread when taking a Sunday train trip but less so
at other times.
</P>
<P>
   Stores can generally open until 8 p.m. on weekdays, and until 4
p.m. on Saturdays. But they can open for two hours longer on the
four Saturdays before Christmas, and on four Sundays a year,
provided they have closed by 2 p.m. on the preceding Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   One significant loophole permits Sunday shopping for a limited
number of articles _ including sun-cream, umbrellas and souvenirs _
in so-called ``tourist areas.'' When the Berlin city council
extended Berlin's ``tourist area'' to Alexanderplatz at the end of
July, Biere pounced.
</P>
<P>
   Having prepared his move by having 600,000 ``Berlin Souvenir''
stickers printed and by reaching an agreement with his 1,000
employees granting a 20 percent pay bonus for Sunday work, Biere
opened the Kaufhof from noon to 5 p.m. Every article sold was
labeled a ``souvenir.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales were 15 percent higher during a five-hour day than during
a normal 11-hour day, Biere said. Opinion polls quickly appeared
showing broad approval. But the Office for Workers' Protection,
which oversees shopping laws, was not amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Souvenirs must be specifically related to the area they are
from,'' said Robert Rath of the Berlin Workers' Protection office.
``Putting a little souvenir sticker on a washing machine does not
make it a souvenir. Perhaps an iron would qualify if its grip was
in the form of the Brandenburg Gate. But only then.''
</P>
<P>
   Rath said a fine of 50,000 marks ($27,500) imposed on Kaufhof
might be doubled if the store opened next Sunday, and the police
might be called in to force the store to close.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufhof has appealed the fine, and Biere said he was determined
to fight on. He has hired 20 new employees to work on Sunday, and
argues that Sunday opening could help create jobs in a society with
a 10.3 percent unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally I prefer American culture, and I go to America four
times a year to shop,'' Rath said. ``But the law is the law.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With unemployment over 20 percent in some eastern areas, with
Sunday religious observance lower than in the west, and with many
increasingly deserted eastern city centers desperately needing the
injection of life that Sunday shopping might bring, the east has
led the push for Sunday shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only stupid tradition of an old Germany is against this,''
said Gabriele Mueller, who works for a German subsidiary of the
United States Can Co. in the eastern town of Schwedt and came to
Kaufhof to shop. ``People work all week, and it only adds to their
stress if they cannot shop on Sunday. We should accept our
Americanization.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was regulation, not deregulation, that cemented the
postwar success of Germany's social-market economy, with its
emphasis on solidarity, consensus and order. Although the system is
now ailing, especially in its inability to create jobs, the
attachment to it remains strong, especially in labor unions and
churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The men and women who wrote our Constitution saw the need to
make Sunday a work-free day,'' said Manfred Kock, the president of
the Evangelical Church of Germany. ``We should respect them and
preserve a day of communal tranquillity for social as much as
religious reasons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
