</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-AFFAIR06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brosnan, Russo are remake's crown jewels
 &HT;    By Jim Luksic
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Analogies between this remake of ``The Thomas
Crown Affair'' and Norman Jewison's 1968 version can't be surmised
instantly. Alan Trustman's original narrative, though tweaked and
slightly glossed over, remains essentially intact here _ the
Hollywood-cliched finale notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Chunks of dialogue will ring a bell, and many of the
forerunner's principal figures are back in place. Director John
McTiernan also has enlisted one performer (Faye Dunaway) to return,
this time as Crown's shrink.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce Brosnan steps into the late Steve McQueen's shoes as our
suave billionaire, and it's hardly a stretch for the actor best
known as James Bond. Portraying the restless title character,
Brosnan oversees the heist of an invaluable Monet from New York's
Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Big Apple's finest _ namely detective Michael McCann
(Denis Leary) _ would even conceive of Crown being the culprit, but
that only makes investigator Catherine Banning (Rene Russo) more
determined. For reasons not made convincingly clear, she suspects
the affluent playboy immediately. (Her deductive logic: Because
Crown capsized a yacht just for kicks, he also must be bored enough
to steal paintings.)
</P>
<P>
   Banning is on his heels and under his covers as the pursuit,
much to McCann's jealousy, crosses the professional line. Brosnan
avoids tipping his player's hand by staying cool and letting us
mull over the identity of an enigmatic companion (supermodel Esther
Canadas).
</P>
<P>
   It's clear, despite Leary's fleshed-out effort, this stage
belongs to the capable Brosnan and Russo. The former is a sturdy
pillar of panache, a fine foil to his female counterpart, who
smoothly grabs the spotlight and doesn't let go. Ben Gazzara barely
warrants a glance as an attorney; the veteran, well utilized in
``Summer of Sam,'' is brutally underused. And Frankie Faison, as
Leary's sidekick, is asked to do little beyond make faces while
expressing resignation at Russo's antics.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, the filmmakers deserve kudos for remodeling and
resuscitating a caper that hasn't worn out its welcome. Jewison's
employment of hideous split-screen, screen-in-screen gimmickry has
been suitably replaced by McTiernan's straightforward gaze and
orthodox approach.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Conti's intrusive score simmers, yet it fails to transport
us back three decades, as it was obviously designed to do. And a
few action segments seem prolonged, in turn extending their
improbability.
</P>
<P>
   Co-writers Leslie Dixon and Kurt Wimmer have some trouble
keeping absurdity to a minimum, but golden moments can be seen: The
hero abandoning his ride to follow and console his distraught
lover; a cleverly tooled climax in which numerous bowler-hatted
gentlemen befuddle the police force; any shots inside the elegant
ballrooms and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   When all is done, this reworking of ``The Thomas Crown Affair''
proves to have a distinct style, personality and direction. It
stands, and occasionally falls, on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
