A7221 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SIXTHSENSE06-C     08-05 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SIXTHSENSE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plot twist, psychic sidekick help Willis redeem himself in
creepy `Sixth Sense'
 &HT;    BY Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The sight of Bruce Willis shepherding a young boy
raises the troubling specter of ``Mercury Rising,'' a ludicrous
1998 suspense thriller about a 9-year-old autistic child who
cracked a secret government code and needed washed-up FBI Agent
Willis to save him from evil Alec Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mercury Rising'' was Willis' attempt to show his soft side,
but it sank fast as he reverted to his usual action-hero mode. He
succeeds with ``The Sixth Sense,'' an eerie psychological thriller
in which he helps a frightened boy who is terrorized by ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   The film is effectively creepy, despite its muted tone and
tendency to drag. Stripped of his sidearm, Willis gives the kind of
weighty, measured performance that proved his abilities as an actor
in ``Pulp Fiction'' and ``12 Monkeys.'' However, he's outshined by
Haley Joel Osment, who is incredibly intense as the 8-year-old
clairvoyant, Cole Sear.
</P>
<P>
   Willis plays Malcolm Crowe, an award-winning Philadelphia child
psychologist. As the story opens, Crowe and his wife, Anna (Olivia
Williams), are confronted in their home by one of his former
patients, Vincent Gray (Donnie Wahlberg), now an adult. The
disturbed young man babbles something about knowing what makes
people afraid when they're alone before shooting Crowe and killing
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Having failed Gray, Crowe tries to ease his conscience by taking
the similar case of Cole, who is diagnosed as suffering from acute
anxiety. The pale, stricken-looking lad eventually confides that he
can see and hear dead people. He is a reluctant channel, plagued by
sometimes violent spirits with unresolved problems.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from some strange occurrences, such as Cole's mother (Toni
Collette) stepping out of the kitchen for a second and returning to
find every cupboard and drawer open and her son unmoved, we don't
witness many manifestations during the first 40 minutes. Much of
the plot also deals with Crowe's estrangement from his wife, who is
being romantically pursued by a co-worker, Sean (Glenn Fitzgerald).
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ``The Sixth Sense'' is often heavier on mundane
drama than chilling horror. The spine-tingling scenes in which
phantoms materialize are scary and disturbing, heightened by
writer-director M. Night Shyamalan's otherwise minimal use of mood
music and visual effects.
</P>
<P>
   The story builds to a well-handled whammy of a plot twist that
does much to redeem the film's shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Willis is poignant in an unusually sensitive role, but ``The
Sixth Sense'' belongs to 11-year-old Osment, who merited Emmy
consideration as a dying boy who wanted to sue God in an episode of
``Ally McBeal.'' His haunted performance is riveting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
