<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUFTWAFFE-FLIGHTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL BARS GERMAN AIR FORCE FROM FLYING OVER RANCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ American and German fighter pilots will not be
conducting low-level, high-speed flights over a course that
stretches 800 miles from New Mexico to the Big Bend region of
Texas, according to a settlement announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In settling a lawsuit filed by five West Texas ranchers over the
proposed exercises, the Air Force agreed this week to withdraw its
application with the Federal Aviation Administration to use the
route.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it means there won't be any airplanes flying on the
routes that were contested,'' Kaare Remme, a principal in the McCoy
Land and Cattle Co. and one of the plaintiffs, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its a great victory but sort of a left-handed one. They agreed
to stop it, but they said they might try to perpetrate it on our
neighbors,'' Remme said from his office in San Marcos, about 45
miles northeast of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   According to the settlement, the Air Force may try to find
another West Texas route for the German pilots who conduct training
mission in the United States. The Air Force agreed to do further
environmental studies before proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Air Force officers and government lawyers involved in
the settlement were not returned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome represents a clear, if narrow, victory in the
ongoing legal struggle between West Texas ranchers and the federal
government over military training flights above private property.
</P>
<P>
   The next battle brewing is over the Air Force's plan to begin
``realistic bomber training'' missions over a broad expanse of West
Texas. Widely resented, the bomber plan cannot be challenged in
court until it is formally adopted by the Air Force, a step that
may occur late this year.
</P>
<P>
   The five plaintiffs involved in the lawsuit over the training
flights by Germany's Luftwaffe own several hundred square miles of
ranchland in Reeves, Pecos and Davis counties.
</P>
<P>
   They sued last year, claiming the Air Force did not follow
procedures in the National Environmental Protection Act to evaluate
the impact of the flights on humans and animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Military Airspace Expansions will directly interfere with
the company's operations, including cattle management and
operations, tourism and hunting operations, employee quality of
life and safety ...'' the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the plaintiffs, the planes reach speeds of 600 mph
while flying within 100 feet of the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The Luftwaffe pilots are based at Holloman Air Force Base, near
Alamogordo, N.M., and train over West Texas and New Mexico because
such low-level flights are prohibited in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The route that sparked the lawsuit was once used to test cruise
missiles but has never been used for fighter pilot training.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for the plaintiffs, Murray Feldman, said the
settlement has limited significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not overstate it. It's just one instrument route. But if
you are someone like Mr. Remme and the route was right over your
ranch house, it's pretty darn significant,'' Feldman said from his
office in Boise, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Feldman said the Texas lawsuit was noteworthy
because, unlike most actions against the Air Force over training
flights, it involved private and not public land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Air Force faces too much pressure from citizen groups and
land management agencies when they try to expand flights over
public lands, so they were looking at private land,'' he said.
``But you almost have to wonder if they underestimated that people
who own their own property have the same, if not a greater, level
of concern.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
