<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Fri., Aug. 6. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
DOUGLAS (Douglas, Ariz.) - The mayor of Douglas is fed up. He's
sick of illegal immigrants dying in the desert as they try to cross
the border. He's sick of ranchers with rifles looking for a reason
to shoot immigrants camping on their property. He's sick of the
disease, the violence, the trash and the tragedy that surround the
flow of people into his city. But instead of going after the
immigrants, he's lashing out at those who entice them to come:
employers. He has launched a letter writing campaign to newspapers
across the country, slamming those who hire illegal immigrants. The
mayor takes us on a tour of his gripes, showing and telling us why
he's taken this unusual step. By GRACIELA SEVILLA. Story will move
in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GRAND CANYON (Grand Canyon, Ariz.) - After years of analysis and
public debate, forest officials will vote Friday on two final
choices for developing land south of the Grand Canyon: a
conservative plan that would cut out only 50 acres for federal
housing and community facilities, and a proposal by a Scottsdale
developer to clear a section four times as big so that hotels and
retail space can be added. Both would also provide 60 acres for a
transit center where a new light rail will pick up canyon-bound
visitors. By MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ODD LAWS (Phoenix) - We look at some of the odder laws that go into
effect today (Friday), from setting the legal temperature for
storing eggs to letting law-enforcement officers give you a
blood-alcohol test even if you're dead; from allowing almost any
organization get a custom-designed license plate to making it a
felony to tattoo anyone under 18 without parental consent. By JON
KAMMAN. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;  &QL; 
BADCOMPANY (Phoenix) _ Paul Rodgers, whose soulful voice fronted
the popular '70s rock act Bad Company, talks about his 15-year wait
to ``set the record straight'' on the group's current reunion tour.
By LARRY RODGERS. Story will move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) - They died in Kosovo two days after a
small plane disappeared off the coast of Martha's Vineyard, so
reports of their passing were buried inside most newspapers under
truckloads of JFK Jr. and ``the end of Camelot`` and ``the Kennedy
curse.'' Army Sgt. William ``Gunz'' Wright, 27, and Spc. Sherwood
B. Brim, 30, They were husbands. They were brothers. They were
sons. They were, in Wright's case, a father. They were overlooked.
By E.J. MONTINI Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - When the house I grew up in went up for
sale, I couldn't blame anybody.
</P>
<P>
   My sister Lisa and her husband had been living in that house
after my parents moved several years ago, and, quite frankly, the
neighborhood had changed. By LAURI NOTARO. Story will move in the
``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
