<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS HILLARY CLINTON GAINING WITH WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARA JAKES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton's approval rating among
New York women has surged since publicly addressing her husband's
infidelities, according to a poll released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a similar survey by Zogby International found that 42
percent of women voters across the state would vote against Clinton
should she run for the U.S. Senate against the Republican favorite,
New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Now that number is down to 37 percent, while 50.1 percent of New
York women say they would vote for Clinton, according to the new
poll, which also was conducted by Zogby.
</P>
<P>
   The poll was released in the wake of this week's inaugural issue
of Talk magazine, in which the first lady discusses, for the first
time publicly, President Clinton's extramarital affairs. Fifty-five
percent of the state's registered voters are women.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the survey shows Hillary Clinton and Giuliani in a
statistical dead heat, each with 44 percent of the vote. Eleven
percent of the 761 likely state voters surveyed were undecided. The
poll has a margin of error of plus or minus 3.7 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
