<P>
   TEKELEC-SHARES (Los Angeles) _ Shares of Tekelec shot up 23
percent in heavy trading Thursday, a day after the telecom
equipment company reported pro forma earnings that beat estimates
by a penny. Wall Street apparently thinks Tekelec has finally hit
rock bottom, six months after the company's shares fell 50 percent
in less than three weeks on surprisingly bad earnings. By Dave
McNary. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GM-BUGS (Los Angeles) _ Warner Bros. and General Motors Corp.,
two American corporate heavyweights, staged a love-in Thursday as
they unveiled a minivan bearing a Bugs Bunny logo to launch a
four-year marketing alliance. The automaker announced it will build
20,000 Chevy Venture Warner Bros. vans during the next year as the
first element of their partnership, which is expected to lead to
another 15 joint marketing programs. ``You'll not only see more
vehicles but lots of other tie-ins,'' said Phil Guarascio, GM vice
president for advertising and corporate marketing. By Dave McNary.
(Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HOMESTORE-IPO (Los Angeles) _ Shares of HomeStore.Com rose in
heavy trading Thursday, the first day of trading for the company
that runs Realtors.Com and other home-related web sites.
Apparently, investor enthusiasm for Net IPOs hasn't ebbed. By
Deborah Adamson. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
