<HEADLINE>
`IRON MAN' MORE INTELLIGENT, THOUGHT-PROVOKING THAN USUAL KIDS'
FARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally _ a terrific summer film for kids.
</P>
<P>
   One that mixes fine writing _ the book ``The Iron Man'' by the
late British Poet Laureate Ted Hughes _ with the animated film
world.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes won more notoriety as the husband of feminist icon and
poet Sylvia Plath, who committed suicide in 1970. But his
children's stories, which depict the brutal world of animals and
nature, are as powerful as his book of poems on life with Plath
called ``The Birthday Letters.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he seems an ironic choice for kid's movie material. Maybe
that's why ``The Iron Giant'' is more intelligent and
thought-provoking than the usual dumb and dull-witted fare for
children.
</P>
<P>
   It's essentially ``Frankenstein'' updated into the paranoid Cold
War of the 1950s, but this time out there is a young boy named
Hogarth (voice of Eli Marienthal) involved.
</P>
<P>
   Hogarth lives with his single mom, Annie Hughes (Jennifer
Aniston) in the small town of Rockwell, Maine. When Hogarth
overhears a wild sea-tale from a crusty old sailor who believes he
spied a giant monster in the midst of a gale, he opts to believe
it's true.
</P>
<P>
   One dark night Hogarth stumbles upon this iron giant and the
pair become friends. He teaches the metal man to speak and helps
the big guy discover his humanity. What Hogarth doesn't know is
that this robot is fully equipped to decimate the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns kill,'' Hogarth teaches him after the pair spy hunters
murdering a beautiful deer and Iron Giant sees red. But the old
tar's tale has reached the ears of a special government bureau and
soon word of the robot's existence spreads and the town becomes
paranoid and fearful of this ``symbolic'' intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   When the army invades, the giant is faced with a dilemma:
annihilate the weapons that have been ordered to blow him away or
heed Hogarth's reminder that ``You don't have to be a gun; you can
be what you want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Iron Giant's newfound will is surprisingly moving and shows
that even in a time of unreason and disorder, soul and heart come
from the most unexpected places.
</P>
<P>
   Director and animator Brad Bird lovingly illustrates the idyll
of American small-town life in the '50s while refusing to shirk
several unusual subplots _ single moms and the difficulty of life
as a bohemian artist in a time when ``men were men.'' And the
animation in ``The Iron Giant'' is beautiful and sometimes as
delicate, perfect and gorgeously lit as real life at sunrise or
dusk.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, there is quite a lot to chew on for adults and kids
alike. ``The Iron Giant'' is more truthfully scary and full of
humanity (and humor) than the run of children's movies that show
violence without remorse. This is a film that allows some
destruction but also gives us an aftermath _ the loss of loved ones
_ and includes a huge dollop of regret and responsibility once
terrible acts are committed that could have been avoided with just
a moment's patience and, most of all, tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   The Iron Giant. Directed by Brad Bird. Written by Tim McCanlies.
Voices of Jennifer Aniston, Harry Connick Jr., Vin Diesel,
Christopher McDonald. Warner Bros. 84 minutes. Rated PG for mild
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
