<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS PUZZLED ABOUT BARAK STALL ON WYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ By now, most Palestinians, and even some Israelis,
expected that Yasser Arafat would be president of an independent
Palestine comprising the West Bank and Gaza, with at least a token
piece of Jerusalem to call its capital.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Israel and the Palestinians are still fighting over
details of the peace agreement signed in 1993 _ and updated,
changed, and delayed countless times since. A final peace agreement
was supposed to have been completed by May.
</P>
<P>
   But Arafat, who turned 70 on Wednesday, seems to have decided he
no longer wants to debate already-signed agreements; instead, he
wants to see them implemented and is refusing to listen to Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's pleas for changes in the Wye accord signed
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's stance has befuddled many Palestinians, who do not know
whether the new prime minister is willing to give up territory but
just wants to do it his own way _ or whether this is an attempt to
thwart the Palestinians' takeover of land they were already
promised.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian Authority officials characterize Barak's latest
moves as disappointing, particularly efforts to change the
US-mediated Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
   Even some Israelis are unsure of Barak's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this just an irritating delay or a major breakdown?'' said
Barry Rubin, a Middle East specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complicated situation and we still don't know yet what
exactly Barak has in mind,'' said Rubin, who has written a book on
Palestinian politics that will be published in September by Harvard
University Press.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, who spent much of the past three years waiting for
former prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu to stop what critics
called stalling on the peace process, is not in the mood to give
Barak the benefit of the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   In a weeklong round of trips, meetings, and speeches, Arafat
made clear he will not agree to changes in the accord, under which
Israel is supposed to turn over another 13 percent of the West Bank
to partial or full Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   His refusal to consider anything else has already sparked angry
words between the two sides, reminiscent of the mistrust that
existed during Netanyahu's administration. Netanyahu carried out
the first redeployment under Wye and then suspended the accord,
claiming the Palestinians were not doing enough to stop armed
militants opposed to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who took office in July amid promises to make the
Palestinians real partners in the peace process, now says he is
worried about leaving Jewish settlements isolated by
Palestinian-controlled land, as will happen after the Israeli
redeployments.
</P>
<P>
   Barak proposed delaying the next withdrawal until October and
putting off the third Wye withdrawal until the two sides have
reached some agreements on the final peace accord, which will deal
with issues like what to do with the Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Israeli military source said the fear was that isolated
Jewish settlements would be vulnerable to attack. In the past,
attacks by Palestinian groups opposed to the peace process have
soured the atmosphere and often delayed the whole process.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Palestinians, the settlements are at the core of the
dispute over how much land the expected state will comprise.
Palestinians in the West Bank, whose farm-land is confiscated for
roads for the settlers or swallowed by settlement expansion, see no
reason to do something special for people who say they are opposed
to the land-for-peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians are also waiting for the start of free movement
between Palestinian-ruled Gaza and the West Bank _ Palestinians now
need permission, which Israel does not give easily _ something also
promised in the Wye accords.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Arafat is shoring up his support to make it
clear that when he speaks, he speaks for all Palestinians and that
Barak should not think the Palestinians are weak, divided, or can
be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat went to Egypt this week to meet opposition Palestinian
groups that reject the Oslo peace accords. While the sides are not
reconciled, conciliatory statements coming out of the meeting were
a sign that Arafat remains the one person who can gather support
for a final peace accord, observers said.
</P>
<P>
   At home, Arafat's position is assured. A new poll by a
Palestinian research group put support for Arafat at 44 percent _
but support for the nearest rival, the Islamist Hamas's Sheik Ahmet
Yassin, was only 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What's less assured are his options if Barak refuses to adhere
to the Wye accords. Arafat's tough statements cannot hide the fact
that he has few cards to play, specialists said.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat probably will look to US Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright to help him pressure Barak into carrying out the Wye
accord, which was signed in Washington after personal intervention
by President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   She is expected in Israel Aug. 14 for a four-day visit that will
include trips to Jordan and Syria. The United States is eager to
help restart peace talks between Syria and Israel, but Albright
could instead find herself trying to defuse a new
Israeli-Palestinian crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
