<HEADLINE>
ALTMAN TO MOVE TO MISSOURI REP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Mo.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Peter Altman, the producing director of the Huntington
Theatre, will be assuming the reins of the Missouri Repertory
Theatre in Kansas City a year from now. The theater is in the same
League of Resident Theatres category as the Huntington _ LORT B _
although it is not considered in the same league artistically.
</P>
<P>
   The move, then, comes as something of a surprise to those in the
Boston theater community who thought Altman would be moving to a
bigger theater than the Huntington. ``I really wanted a new
situation,'' said Altman by phone Thursday, reaffirming that he
didn't have another situation in mind when he announced his
decision to leave the Huntington last year. ``I thought there was
the potential to take an institution forward, and I like the
challenge of making the progress that needs to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Altman, 56, has been the only artistic director at the
Huntington since its inception and will be here through next
season, his and the Huntington's 18th. He has a strong-minded view
of theater, and he expects to carry that vision forward in Kansas
City, where his title will be producing artistic director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to be very responsive to the community you
serve,'' Altman said. ``You have to learn what it likes, what it's
had before. No doubt I'll try to find some Kansas City- or
Midwest-based plays, but I still believe in the diversity of
America and finding plays that reflect that diversity; I believe in
an international sector of programming and that will continue; I
believe in musical theater; and I'm certainly committed to classic
plays that are done with respect for the text.'' Among the artists
who've reflected those categories at the Huntington are August
Wilson, Tom Stoppard, Gilbert and Sullivan, and Friedrich von
Schiller, with this season's ``Mary Stuart.''
</P>
<P>
   As for plays that fit a community's life, the Huntington is
premiering an adaptation of ``The Last Hurrah'' this season. Altman
will continue to look for coproductions in Kansas City and thought
that the Huntington could be a future partner, depending on its
choice of a new artistic director, which should be made in the next
few months.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that an artistic director can be too far
ahead of his audience, he pledged that there wouldn't be any
condescension in his selections: ``There won't be any `Harveys,' ''
he laughed, referring to audience grabbers that theater companies
produce for box office enhancement. ``Or Mamet,'' he added,
referring to David Mamet, whom Altman has never particularly liked
and therefore has not produced.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Rep has a 733-seat theater and the use of smaller
theaters at the University of Missouri at Kansas City. As the
Huntington is associated with Boston University, the Missouri Rep
is aligned with UMKC, and Altman will also be in charge of the
school's theater program.
</P>
<P>
   Altman is certainly a coup for the Kansas City theater, which is
trying to increase its profile in the world of resident theaters,
and both the university and Altman are eager for him to continue
his work with playwrights, directors, and designers he championed
at the Huntington. The Missouri Rep currently has a $4 million
budget, which it will be increasing incrementally over the next few
years to a size that approaches the Huntington's $6 million budget.
The Kansas City Star reports Altman will be earning $144,000 in
salary and benefits, which is thought to be in the same ballpark of
what he was earning at the Huntington.
</P>
<P>
   The university affiliation is surprising to some, since there
have been longstanding rumors of friction between Altman and BU
that may even have contributed to his decision to leave. ``The
difference,'' said Altman, ``is that the training program is
primarily a graduate program. I must say that's attractive, a
program that emphasizes more advanced students. I would also become
the producing director of the university theaters and have the
opportunity of supervision and oversight; I don't have to be the
chairman myself. The structure is different in that at BU the
director of the theater program reports to a dean, and in this case
the director will be overseen by me.''
</P>
<P>
   Altman denied, though, that problems with BU or other
frustrations were the reason he's leaving. ``There are always going
to be some people who wonder about it, but the main thing is it's
good to leave at a time when things are successful and to find a
new opportunity that's invigorating. I certainly had a wonderful
time at the Huntington doing the work I've enjoyed doing.'' As for
Kansas City, ``I love learning about a new place, what's specific
to it. My impressions are positive, and I'm curious to learn more
and have the experience of discovering it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
