<HEADLINE>
BUSH TO TARGET HISPANIC VOTES IN IOWA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES _ Texas Governor George W. Bush, who has staked his
reputation as the clear GOP frontrunner on winning next week's
Republican straw poll in Ames, has unveiled what he hopes is his
secret weapon of support here: the state's small but active
Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this has ever been done in Iowa before,'' Bush
said at a meeting with a few dozen Hispanics here. ``I want your
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   While only about 53,000 out of Iowa's nearly 3 million people
are of Hispanic origin, Bush spent an hour Thursday in a Holiday
Inn conference room in Des Moines meeting with Hispanics, including
community leaders and more than a dozen workers from the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Hispanic population has been growing quickly,
largely because of the state's labor shortage, represented by a 2.5
percent unemployment rate. Many of the new arrivals come from Texas
and Florida, where Bush and his brother, Jeb, are governors of
those states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to make an active effort to reach out to the
Hispanic community,'' said Bush, who switched between English and
Spanish in his remarks. ``I did so in the state of Texas, and I am
going to do so in the state of Iowa and in other states. I am
trying to broaden the base of the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides dismissed suggestions that governor was trying to
make amends with the Hispanic community for failing to show up last
month at a Texas meeting of leading Latino organization called La
Raza, or a Corpus Christi meeting of the League of United Latin
American Citizens. In both cases, Bush said he had scheduling
conflicts. Bush's meeting was open to the press, highlighting an
effort by the campaign to publicize the candidate's relationship
with the Hispanic community. A Bush aide denied reports that the
meeting was opened only at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that Bush has strong support from Hispanics in
Texas. In his 1998 reelection, Bush received between 41 percent to
49 percent of the Hispanic vote, according to exit surveys, an
extraordinarily high number for a Republican. Bush's strategy for
winning the nomination and the general election rests significantly
on continuing to get strong support from Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to gauge the depth of Bush's support among
Hispanics in Iowa. At Thursday's event, perhaps 30 Hispanic leaders
and another dozen hotel workers listened to Bush as the candidate
stood under a sign that said ``Un Nuevo Dia'' _ A New Day.
</P>
<P>
   The Reverend Roberto Mendez, of the Rivers of Living Water
church in Des Moines, said Bush can count on significant support
from Hispanics. Mendez, a recent arrival from Florida, said many
people in the community are familiar with Bush and are pleased with
his immigration policies.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not break any new ground in his discussion with
Hispanics, but he promised to ``revisit'' the question of whether
undocumented immigrants should be given the right to become
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   When a woman in the audience asked Bush about his immigration
policy, the candidate offered only vague language about how ``the
dream is meant for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you give us some specifics?'' the woman asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Bush replied, using a favorite line, ``every child
ought to be educated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
