<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYWRIGHT-BANG-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTROSIMONE TACKLES SCHOOL VIOLENCE IN `BANG, BANG, YOU'RE DEAD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOE ADCOCK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Playwright/screen-writer William Mastrosimone insists: ```Bang,
Bang, You're Dead' is not part of my professional career.'' At the
same time, his play about high school homicide has provided him
with some of the most ``sensational, fulfilling moments'' he ever
expects to experience in his life as a writer.
</P>
<P>
   Mastrosimone, 51, lives in Enumclaw, Wash.. He writes in a
converted barn with a view of Mount Rainier. Deer, elk and even
bears and mountain lions are among the neighbors he sees around his
property from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   But even in this bucolic setting, fear of murder at school can
be a scary possibility. Mastrosimone and his wife, Sharon, have
four children, two boys and two girls. Last year they were startled
to learn that someone had written on a blackboard in the junior
high school attended by one of their sons, ``I'm going to kill
everyone in this class. And the teacher, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't sleep that night,'' Mastrosimone said in an
interview earlier this week. ``I'm a playwright. So what can I do?
That night I wrote a play, or at least the first draft of a play.''
</P>
<P>
   That draft turned into ``Bang, Bang, You're Dead,'' a fictional
drama that reminds audiences of recent school murder sprees in
Littleton, Colo., Jonesboro, Ark., Springfield, Ore., and Paducah,
Ky. Since its premiere early this year, ``Bang, Bang'' has been
produced by something like 4,000 groups of young people all over
the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Children's Theatre's youth acting program will stage
``Bang, Bang'' Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The play focuses on Josh, an angry high school freshman who has
killed five of his schoolmates. The dead literally come back to
haunt Josh in his jail cell. At first he blows them off with
smart-aleck zingers. But eventually he realizes his homicidal spree
was not a video game or a 3-D version of an action/adventure
revenge movie. Trivia and cheap thrills turn into real tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Mastrosimone achieved national recognition with his unusual
revenge drama, ``Extremities,'' which was first a play and then a
1986 movie starring Farrah Fawcett and James Russo. Like many
playwrights, Mastrosimone supports his interest in writing for the
stage with income from TV and film projects.
</P>
<P>
   Mastrosimone is not exactly sure how often ``Bang, Bang, You're
Dead'' has been produced. The play was published in a unique way.
The text can be downloaded, free, from a Web site
(bangbangyouredead.com). Anyone can produce it. Some 16,000
downloads have been recorded to date. The only stipulation
regarding use of the material is that productions must be
not-for-profit. Mastrosimone makes nothing from the show in the way
of fees and royalties, which is why ``Bang, Bang'' is not really a
milestone in his ``professional career.''
</P>
<P>
   Producers may not even sell refreshments in their theaters.
``This is entirely a way of focusing on a particular issue,''
Mastrosimone says. ``It's not a fund-raiser. It's not about
somebody's ego. I've turned down TV and film offers. This is by
kids, about kids, for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was developing ``Bang, Bang,'' Mastrosimone approached
the drama department of Thurston High School in Springfield. ``I
had the shell of the play,'' he says. ``I realized the kids at
Thurston could give it the emotional content.''
</P>
<P>
   At first there was resistance. The title was offensive. The
events were offensive. The timing was offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, the drama teacher, Mike Fisher, is a real regular
guy,'' Mastrosimone says. ``He's the teacher who tackled Kip Kinkel
when he was shooting in the school cafeteria. Mike had done my play
`Extremities' in college. I'm one of his favorite writers. So he
was willing to give it a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a community meeting. Lots of people spoke against
it. But by then the kids were really dedicated to the project. They
said that they'd do it in the streets or in the parks if they
couldn't do it in the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principal, Larry Benz, is one of my all-time heroes. He
said we'll take this real slow and see how things work out. I
thought he'd simply cancel the whole venture. But no.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher and his cast rehearsed in secret. ``The auditorium was
locked,'' Mastrosimone says. ``Not even the janitor was allowed to
see what they were doing. When they were ready, the cast brought in
an invited audience, about 100 community leaders, police chiefs,
fire chiefs, teachers, doctors, people who had been in the thick of
the massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   Mastrosimone was in the back of the auditorium. Like any
playwright watching a run-through of a new play, he had his laptop
computer open, ready for notes. ``About 30 seconds into it,'' he
says, ``I closed my computer. It was clear to me that something
very special was going on. I just watched in awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end no one applauded. What's wrong? I started down the
side aisle, so I could see people's faces. Everyone seemed to be
reaching for a Kleenex or a handkerchief or wiping their nose on a
sleeve. Then they were jumping up to hug the kids in the cast. I
mean cops and fireman and professional people _ not folks you'd
expect to be real emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Mastrosimone had touched a nerve. Subsequent responses
confirmed his satisfaction with ``Bang, Bang.'' ``As a writer for
non-profits or the commercial stage, I try to be economical, keep
the cast to six or less,'' Mastrosimone says. ``But high school
drama clubs are not concerned with actors' salaries. There are
none. The more roles the better. I popped into a production in
Southern California and, my lord, it looked like they had
Napoleon's army up there on the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   A member of the Writers Guild of America, Mastrosimone has been
rethinking his position on Hollywood aesthetics and ethics. He
wrote an article for the June/July issue of the association's
magazine, ``Confessions of a Violent Movie Writer.'' ``The essay
caused such a stir that it's being reprinted in the August issue,
something that publication just doesn't do, normally.''
</P>
<P>
   Mastrosimone's sons are 12 and 15. ``I am sometimes aghast at
the movies they see on television,'' he says. ``I try to watch with
them and talk to them about the violence. I find humor, making fun
of the material, sometimes works.''
</P>
<P>
   Mastrosimone recalls seeing the movies ``Natural Born Killers''
and ``Pulp Fiction'' with his wife. They were startled when the
audience cheered and laughed during scenes of grotesque violence.
And yet, Mastrosimone notes, mayhem-as-entertainment is even more
extreme in video games like Quake and Doom.
</P>
<P>
   A new play by Mastrosimone, ``Like Totally Weird,'' is a
satirical comedy drama about Hollywood's exploitation of the
malleable imaginations of young males. A Quentin Tarantino type
meets two of his rabid fans. The results are not fun for all.
Mastrosimone expects a Broadway production of ``Like Totally
Weird'' this fall and a movie within a year after the stage
premiere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of studies have shown the correlation between
fantasy violence and real violence,'' Mastrosimone says. ``We
create monsters. We poison the souls of kids. The Paducah killer
was definitely trying to act out `The Basketball Diaries.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Studies are ignored. Well, the pharmaceutical industry finally
got nailed. The tobacco industry got nailed. The car industry got
nailed. The entertainment industry may be next. Parents are
passionate about their children's safety. You ask them to chose
between their kids' safety and the First Amendment and it's no
contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Bang, Bang, You're Dead'' is not part of Mastrosimone's
``professional career,'' it has brought him a unique professional
satisfaction. ``Four kids got in touch with me through the
Internet,'' he says. ``Three had seen the play. One had read it.
They all confided that they had their hit lists. But the play made
them change their minds. Wow! And if four get in touch with me, how
many have had the same response but kept quiet about it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
