<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7272 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATOM06-COX-COX     08-05 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATOM06-COX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Veteran never saw action, but plenty of death at Nagasaki
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Somewhere in the Pacific, Motor
Machinist's Mate 3rd Class J. Norman Ingram read a mimeographed
news summary as it passed from hand to hand aboard the USS
Waukesha.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never heard the phrase, `atomic bomb,''' Ingram says,
recalling how he learned about the devastation of Hiroshima on Aug.
6, 1945. ``But it sounded like it was just what we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than four years after being jolted into World War II by
disaster at Pearl Harbor, America had Japan in a tight squeeze. By
late July, the 3rd Fleet had sailed straight into Tokyo Bay,
launching explosive shells onto shore. Waves of B-29s firebombed
city after city.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Japan refused to surrender, although it had nearly
stopped fighting back.
</P>
<P>
   ``By patiently biding our time,'' announced a Japanese broadcast
beamed toward America, ``we are taking the strategy of preserving
our aircraft for the coming decisive battle of the homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect was ominous: Japan still had 8,000 warplanes and 2
million soldiers. American ships were being attacked by torpedoes
and suicide dive-bombers. ``We were told they'd fight until they
had nothing to eat but rocks,'' Ingram says.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram believed it. He still does.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Navy in 1944, right after graduation from Palm
Beach High School, just in time to be trained for Operation
Downfall _ the invasion of Japan. He drew a perilous assignment,
ferrying troops ashore on an LCM (landing craft, mechanized).
</P>
<P>
   He got a firsthand preview of those perils as the Waukesha, a
cargo ship outfitted for attack, docked at Guam, Guadalcanal and
other battle sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw any action,'' says Ingram, now living in Palm
Beach Gardens. ``The fighting was over when we got to each of these
places. But we saw plenty of death. I saw the caves where the
Japanese had dug in and refused to come out. I saw their skulls.''
</P>
<P>
   Ingram, and everyone back home in America, thought the fight
might be over for good when the first A-bomb exploded over
Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
   (SET ITAL, BREAK)WASHINGTON, AP _ The most terrible destructive
force ever harnessed by man _ atomic energy _ is now being turned
on the islands of Japan by United States bomber. The Japanese face
a threat of utter desolation and their capitulation may be greatly
speeded up.(END ITAL, BREAK)
</P>
<P>
   Three days passed with no surrender. On Aug. 9, a B-29 loaded
with a second A-bomb headed for the steel-making center at Kokura.
Cloudy skies diverted the flight to the backup target, the shipyard
city of Nagasaki. Meanwhile, Russia declared war on Japan and
launched an attack.
</P>
<P>
   Another day passed after the second A-bomb blast before Japan
offered to surrender, but only if Emperor Hirohito could keep his
throne. President Truman repeated the Allied demand for
unconditional surrender and ordered conventional bombing to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese finally gave up on Aug. 14. They got to keep their
emperor with a couple of conditions they didn't ask for: He would
take orders from American Gen. Douglas MacArthur, and he would
insist that his subjects do the same.
</P>
<P>
   The invasion force became an occupation force. Ingram's ship
sailed into Tokyo Bay and docked at the battered Yokosuka Naval
Base on Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know what to expect,'' he says. Although Japan had
surrendered, no treaty had been signed. ``To be honest, I was
frightened,'' Ingram says. ``We wondered if they'd let the fleet
sail in and then try to trap us.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no tricks. The ship dropped off troops and equipment
and returned to sea.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram and the Waukesha came back to Japan with another load of
Marines on Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The port: Nagasaki.
</P>
<P>
   Only a small crew of sailors needed to unload cargo went ashore
with a Marine occupation force. They were ordered to take no
pictures, but Ingram pretended not to hear. He'd been carrying a
palm-size camera since he left home, sending back film of exotic
locales to his parents in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the pictures, and the way I described it, it was like a
pleasure cruise,'' he says. ``I didn't want to worry them.''
</P>
<P>
   There was supposed to be little time spent in Nagasaki, but a
choppy tide stranded the crew for most of a day. It was enough time
for Ingram and shipmates to wander from the southern port to the
north side of the city, where the bomb fell.
</P>
<P>
   No one warned them about radiation. They weren't given special
suits or helmets or breathing gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we were the first Americans in Nagasaki after the
bomb,'' Ingram says. ``I'd never seen anything like it. No one
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Flattened buildings. Shattered concrete. Seared grass.
</P>
<P>
   Bodies everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weeks after the bomb, and people were still dying,''
Ingram says. ``The stench was awful, unforgettable.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of death within days of the explosion are as high as
70,000; as many died in following years from radiation. Concern for
his parents caused Ingram to turn his camera away from the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Although more powerful than Hiroshima's bomb, Nagasaki's did
less damage because the hilly terrain shielded some of the
concussion. ``On one side of a hill, everything would be intact,
and the other side would be destroyed,'' Ingram says.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram photographed a number of survivors, but always in the
background. Some stared; some ran away. None showed anger.
``Mostly, they seemed to be afraid of us,'' Ingram says.
</P>
<P>
   The Waukesha was at sea again in less than a week. Ingram was at
home in two years, going to work at his father's grocery store.
He's found no ill effects from radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his mates weren't as lucky. Cancer is a big topic at
reunions. ``We've lost a lot of men from that ship because of that
bomb,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 years passed before the federal government
acknowledged the radiation hazards of such duty. The National
Association of Atomic Veterans says it has documented high cancer
rates among veterans of the atomic occupation zones and later
A-bomb test sites. The group has continued to lobby for more tests
and increased benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his concerns about radiation, Ingram isn't swayed by
revisionist historians who argue that the war could have been won
without using the atomic bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't hear that from veterans,'' he says. ``You don't hear
it from people who would have had to take part in an invasion. If
it weren't for the bomb, I don't think I'd be alive.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
