<SLUG> BC-ATOMSIDE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Troops weren't guarding Enola Gay but plane's cargo
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ On Tinian Island in the Pacific, late
July 1945: I'd just completed my 35th combat mission against the
Japanese and was being processed for my journey home.
</P>
<P>
   Something strange occurred that none of us could understand. One
area of the island was sealed and completely off limits to all
personnel. Being curious, we got as close as we could. All that was
visible were two B-29s with armed troops, probably 10 or 15 around
both planes.
</P>
<P>
   A few of us had been in the B-29 program from its inception.
What could be so secretive about two very familiar-looking B-29s?
</P>
<P>
   Long story short, I arrived home (Miami) around Aug. 1, 1945.
The news came over the radio Aug. 6 that a super bomb had been
dropped on Hiroshima and later on Nagasaki. Both of these attacks
came from Tinian Island.
</P>
<P>
   I knew then and there that one of the B-29s I saw from some
distance was the Enola Gay. The secret wasn't the planes; it was
the bomb. _ William Boyer, Palm Beach Gardens
</P>
<P>
   I was co-pilot on a B-24 flying a mission on the island of
Kyushu the day the first atomic bomb was dropped. We had orders not
to go within 15 miles of Hiroshima, with no explanation. Flying at
12,000 feet, we had an unobstructed view of the huge mushroom cloud
rising from the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   We decided it must be a huge raid on Hiroshima, but we did not
know the truth until we returned to our base on Okinawa and learned
it was one bomb. _ Roger R. Farlow, Fort Pierce
</P>
<P>
   Development of atomic weapons continued after the war with the
first peacetime test at Bikini Atoll in the Marshall Islands.
</P>
<P>
   I was the flight navigator on a crew assigned to fly observers
to the test during the last week of June 1946. We picked up our
passengers at Hamilton Field, Marin County, Calif. We then flew to
Hickam Field, Honolulu and on to Kwajelein Island in the Marshall
Islands. Our passengers included a general, an admiral and a
senator.
</P>
<P>
   Flying within 5 to 8 miles of the blast, we circled the area,
waiting.
</P>
<P>
   We were given special glasses and told not to look directly at
the blast. After the blast, we could observe the white mushroom
cloud. After circling for about a half-hour, we returned to
Kwajelein Island. _ Ralph Langley, West Palm Beach
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
