<SLUG> BC-FBI-CONNOLLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-FBI AGENT SAYS HE ACTED LEGALLY IN HANDLING MOB INFORMANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c. 1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Former FBI Agent John Connolly reiterated Thursday
that he did nothing to violate policies or laws in his handling of
James ``Whitey'' Bulger as an informant against the Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly was responding to remarks made by FBI Director Louis
Freeh during a visit to the Boston office of the FBI on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly has been under investigation by a special task force of
agents from the FBI and other federal agencies that is looking for
evidence of crimes by anyone who dealt with Bulger and Stephen
``The Rifleman'' Flemmi over the decades that they were FBI
informants.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no time during my entire career did I engage in any conduct
in violation of those policies or existing laws,'' Connolly said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony during lengthy hearings last year before US District
Judge Mark L. Wolf indicated that gifts, including wine, were
exchanged among Bulger and Connolly and his FBI supervisor John
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who testified under a grant of immunity from
prosecution, also acknowledged that he accepted as much as $7,000
in cash from Bulger that he never repaid. Morris also claimed that
Bulger and Flemmi had been tipped off to investigations, a charge
Connolly has steadfastly denied.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly maintains that everything he did with Bulger ``was done
with the full knowledge, approval, and direction of my superiors in
the Department of Justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many of the events involving Bulger date back to the
1970s and 1980s, Freeh said the task force is trying to determine
whether there is any evidence that falls within the statute of
limitations and could be used to prosecute agents who dealt with
the informants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
