   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   BEAR-FRAUD (New York) _ Bear Stearns Securities Corp. willfully
aided and abetted A.R. Baron, a small, New York brokerage firm that
defrauded investors out of $75 million, according to the SEC. The
regulators also said that Bear Stearns willfully violated
securities laws in its record-keeping practices by discarding
documents relating to A.R. Baron's operations and violated
regulations governing the credit it extended to its customer
clearing firm. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOKE-CONFIRM (Washington) _ The Senate voted Thursday to
confirm Richard Holbrooke as chief U.S. diplomat to the United
Nations, ending a 14-month nomination battle that left the Clinton
administration without a high-profile representative to the United
Nations during military conflicts in the Balkans and the Persian
Gulf. The Senate approved Holbrooke, the former U.S. ambassador to
Germany and the architect of the 1995 peace agreement in Bosnia, on
a vote of 81-16. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-CONGRESS (Washington) _ House Democrats and a group of
dissident Republicans were expected to reach agreement Thursday on
a comprehensive bill to regulate the managed health care industry
and they challenged the Republican leadership to bring their
measure to a House vote in the fall. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis: Are the Republicans,
or perhaps the Democrats, driving off a political cliff on tax
cuts? Almost all Republicans in Congress favor one, and almost all
Democrats are against it. Rarely have both parties sounded equally
confident about the political benefits they think their policies,
decided on principle alone, of course, will bring. With each side
sated with polling data and focus group results, the conflict
suggests that at least one side is taking a big chance on the
voters. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   VACATION-SMOG (Washington) _ People who flee the big cities for
the beach or the mountains this summer are finding as much smog on
vacation as they left at home, according to a survey of government
monitoring data by environmentalists. Sometimes, the sea breezes
are even more noxious than the urban fumes, because the air arrives
there after loading up with pollutants in the cities and baking for
hours in this summer's strong sun and relentless heat. By Matthew
L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   TV-STATION-OWNERSHIP (Undated) _ The FCC on Thursday voted to
liberalize rules limiting television station ownership, allowing a
single company or network to own two separate stations in the
largest cities. One immediate result of the decision may be a rush
by big television companies like the broadcast networks to sweep up
any available television stations in cities where they already own
a station. As put in one memo to the top corporate officers at one
of the four big broadcast networks, ``The race is on.'' By Bill
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FIELD-OF-DREAMS (Dyersville, Iowa) _ All that really happened
here is that someone decided to shoot a movie. But that is not how
people here see it. The place is an eastern Iowa cornfield where
Hollywood built the set of ``Field of Dreams.'' The stirring,
fanciful story of a farmer who hears a voice telling him to build a
baseball diamond in his cornfield was an instant sensation.
Suddenly, some 50,000 people a year started coming to the baseball
diamond in the cornfield. People still come, but now the object of
their sentimental pilgrimage is ensnared in a bitter disagreement
between the farm couple who owns most of the outfield and the farm
couple who owns most of the infield. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 7:45 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CARDIO-DEATHS (Undated) _ The death rates from
cardiovascular diseases have plummeted by 60 percent since 1950,
the government announced today, making the conquest of this leading
killer of Americans one of the major public health achievements of
the twentieth century. The CDC report notes that stroke deaths have
declined almost linearly since the beginning of the century but
those from heart disease peaked in the 1960s and have been on a
downhill course ever since. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ The government's investigation into
China's acquisition of U.S. nuclear weapons secrets was plagued by
widespread mistakes and misjudgments but no political interference,
according to the two ranking members of a Senate committee that
held closed hearings into the investigation. By Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES-LEGROOM (Undated) _ With airplanes growing more crowded
and passenger complaints soaring, the nation's biggest airline
announced day that it would offer its best customers more of what
has become an increasingly scarce commodity: leg room. By Laurence
Zuckerman.
</P>
