<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7276 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-CROWN06-COX     08-05 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-CROWN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Crown' remake is a well-polished gem
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Admit it. Old movies gave us our only
chance to learn how the other half lives. They taught many of us
which fork to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' is an old-fashioned movie featuring
sleek stars playing sophisticated characters. But the zillionaire
Mr. Crown of the title is not someone to emulate. He's a thief. For
the hell of it.
</P>
<P>
   This enjoyable romantic caper is a remake of the 1968 movie. It
has Pierce Brosnan in the Steve McQueen role of the bored
gentleman-thief and Rene Russo as the insurance investigator who
must decide whether to nab him or marry him, a role originally
played by Faye Dunaway.
</P>
<P>
   The flick has all the virtues of old-school filmmaking. Although
the plot has a few forgivable holes in it, the film is crisply
paced, with smart dialogue and stylish settings. Even the songs fit
perfectly, beginning with Bill Conti's bouncy jazz score and ending
with an upbeat ``Windmills Of Your Mind'' (also in the first
movie). And another virtue in this summer of dung-stirrers, the
film is free of gross twits.
</P>
<P>
   As Thomas Crown, Brosnan is a very cool customer _ a self-made
man who has earned millions in corporate acquisitions. He lives in
a beautiful New York penthouse and _ geez _ even has a man servant.
</P>
<P>
   He's a true sophisticate, a man who has everything, including a
case of ennui. ``A big day for him is taking off his tie,'' someone
observes. So, to amuse himself, Crown plans an elaborate heist of a
multimillion-dollar Monet from the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Russo as Catherine Banning, a hot-shot insurance
investigator not afraid to use her obvious charms to get her man.
She has some run-ins with a police detective on the case, played
nicely by Denis Leary with a minimum of smart-mouth.
</P>
<P>
   But the heart of the film is her confrontations with Thomas
Crown. The pair are well-matched, and after some amusing
intellectual fencing, and a bit of steamy rump-wiggling at a
charity ball, they fall in love. This presents a dilemma for the
lady when Crown sets out to return the painting to the museum in
another clever if improbable caper.
</P>
<P>
   Brosnan is a very likable mogul, exuding quiet confidence and a
good deal of bemusement. And like his other character _ James Bond
_ he looks good in a suit.
</P>
<P>
   Russo is delectable. Although a hard-core snoop, her Catherine
charms us with a bag of little tricks _ a cute smile here, a giggle
there. Faye Dunaway makes a welcome cameo appearance as Crown's
bemused therapist.
</P>
<P>
   The movie also charms through small, comedic touches, such as a
simple shot of two pairs of feet after a night of lovemaking. The
heists are exciting, and it's doubtful that people will guess how
Crown plans to return the Monet. But the film is basically
lighthearted, with perhaps a touch more emphasis placed on the
romance than the capers.
</P>
<P>
   The director is John McTiernan, known for action films such as
``Die Hard'' and ``The Hunt for Red October.'' He proves he can
also shoot romance. He's fond of close-ups and does some nifty
quick-cuts during the heist. And there's the must-do, revolving
overhead shot, lifted from the original film.
</P>
<P>
   Like the original, ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' is an affair to
remember _ classy, clever and thoroughly entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
