<SLUG> BC-EMC-SOFTWARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMC TO STEP UP SOFTWARE MARKETING EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EMC Corp. will boost its efforts to market software to other
companies, a move it hopes will increase sales of its information
storage hardware as well.
</P>
<P>
   EMC previously sold only a few outsiders portions of its code,
pieces known as software ``hooks.'' These are needed to write
programs around the big Symmetrix disk-drive systems EMC sells to
major banks, airlines, and other companies that store a lot of
data.
</P>
<P>
   But at a meeting with financial analysts at its new facility in
Franklin, Mass. Thursday, EMC executives said they will now sell
its hooks to almost any company wanting to develop new programs to
make use of EMC-stored data.
</P>
<P>
   The software secrets will cost $35,000. But EMC's chief goal is
to enable outsiders to customize Symmetrix to their own needs _ and
deepen clients' dependence on EMC, said chief executive Michael
Ruettgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge value, because as we get designed into new
systems, they (customers) will only want to work with EMC,''
Ruettgers said.
</P>
<P>
   EMC's move comes as the company is fighting off renewed
competition from rivals including IBM, which recently introduced a
low-priced storage system. Also, longtime partner Hewlett-Packard
Co. recently ceased buying EMC parts for resale, a relationship
that had accounted for as much as a fifth of EMC's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Still, EMC leads the market for big storage systems; despite
HP's move, EMC executives said they are sticking by their earlier
projection the company will have revenue of $10 billion in 2001, up
from $4 billion in 1998. New incentives for its own sales staff
will make up for lost orders from HP, EMC said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the code marketing tactic also should help EMC
achieve its targets. They compared EMC's strategy to one Microsoft
Corp. pursued to encourage outside software developers to write
programs around its Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes a lot of sense once you reach a certain size and
have the market power to get the leverage,'' said Justin Kelly,
analyst at Winslow Capital in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   EMC vice president Don Swatik said companies including Computer
Associates, Sterling Software, and HP have already developed new
application programs for Symmetrix, and that EMC is in talks with
Oracle Corp. to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's meeting, some wondered whether EMC might be
sharing too much of its code with outsiders, but Swatik said the
company would share only code needed to develop new interfaces.
``We're not disclosing the algorythms for what makes Symmetrix
tick,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in EMC, whose headquarters are in Hopkinton, Mass., rose
2 1/16 to close at 62 5/16 in New York Stock Exchange trading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
