<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUNG-CANCER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG THAT IDENTIFIES CANCER CELLS IN LUNGS OK'D 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KRISTIN VAUGHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new drug made by a New Hampshire company that lights up cancer
cells could help doctors determine if patients with suspicious
chest X-rays need a biopsy for lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   NeoTect, made by Londonderry-based Diatide Inc., was approved
Wednesday by the US Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't replace biopsy. It is supposed to be used as an
adjunct with an abnormal chest X-ray or CT scan,'' said Dr.
Florence Houn, director of the FDA's Office of Drug Evaluation III.
</P>
<P>
   Patients are injected with a teaspoon-size amount of the drug
which floats through the body searching for basket-shaped receptors
found atop proteins that are produced by many types of lung
cancers. A common nuclear-medicine camera then feeds the image to a
computer screen or an X-ray-like film where the image of the lung
lights up to show where cancer cells or located. If there are no
cancer cells, the drug flows through the body.
</P>
<P>
   Richard T. Dean, president and CEO of Diatide Inc., said that it
works with the X-rays and CT scans to if suspicious masses that
appear could be cancerous tumors or maybe just scar tissue.
</P>
<P>
   `This takes the technology to the next level. X-rays can tell if
there is an abnormal mass in the body, but it can't tell what it
is. It could be a tumor, a blood clot or a golf ball. With NeoTect,
if it is a cancer, it will light up and if it is not malignant the
patient doesn't have to go through invasive procedures like surgery
and biopsies.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean said that in addition to detecting cancer cells, NeoTect
can also help doctors determine if there are other areas that have
cancer cells and it can be used as a follow-up procedure with
cancer patients to see if treatments are working effectively or if
cancer has spread.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Dr. Bruce Johnson, Director of Lowe Center For
ThoracicOncology at Dana Farber Cancer Institute said that the drug
could potentially be the most helpful.
</P>
<P>
   The drug could help cut down on the amount of tests cancer
patients need to determine whether it has spread outside of the
lung, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We usually do a number of tests to make sure that it hasn't
spread outside of the lung by doing a CT scan to image the liver,
brain, bone scan...about three If you do the test and pick
something up, you could do it in one test,'' Johnsons said. Houn
said that ``We (FDA) think it's an important new diagnostic tool.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Diatide Inc. had its application put through a
``priority review'' by the FDA, a fast-tracking approval approach
done for only about 10 to 20 percent of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Houn said that it is commonly done with drugs that could be of
significant benefit to life threatening diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Lung cancer is the number one cancer in women and men in the
United States. More than 170,000 have been diagnosed with the
disease. Biopsies in which lung tissue is surgically removed allows
doctors to diagnose the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Houn said the help that it can help patients and doctors make
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are wondering, `Could this be cancer or something
benign, this test can help,'' ' Houn said. ``If you are not sure if
it is a scar, this can help when you are stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   In active NASDAQ trading Diatide stock fell 5/8, to 6 1/8 with
more than 253,000 shares _ more than three times its average daily
volume _ changing hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
