<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7286 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-TATYANA-ALI-SPI     08-05 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TATYANA-ALI-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC HAS ALWAYS BEEN SPECIAL TO TATYANA ALI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tatyana Ali, one of the stars of Nickelodeon's ``All That Music
and More'' festival, launched her singing career after an episode
of NBC-TV's ``The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Smith, Ali's co-star on the family comedy about a
streetwise Philadelphia teenager sent to live with rich relatives
in Bel-Air, suggested an episode in which Ali could show off her
singing talents.
</P>
<P>
   Ali, who played Ashley, Smith's closest pal in the Bel-Air
household, was skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will knew that I sang, but I kept saying, `No, no, no. I'm not
going to do it,''' Ali said in a phone interview this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him it was going to be corny, it was going to be
cheesy. I was afraid that if I sang on the show, I would end up
mocking the thing I loved. Music had always been really special to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, formerly of the rap duo D.J. Jazzy Jeff and the Fresh
Prince, finally talked her into singing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will promised me it'd be cool,'' she said. ``He said,
`Everyone will talk about this episode. Please just trust me, trust
me.' I finally said fine, but told him that I'd never speak to him
again if it came off cheesy.''
</P>
<P>
   When the episode aired about three years ago, about a year
before the show went off the air, rumors began circulating that Ali
was recording an album.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really amazed me,'' the 20-year-old Ali said with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Ali later signed a development deal with Smith's production
company, which in turn led to a recording contract with MJJ Music,
a label distributed by Epic Records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will and I have always had a really good relationship, like a
brother-sister relationship,'' Ali said. ``When I started the show,
I was like 11. And he was about 21, around my age right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always had a lot of faith in me, even when I didn't have
a lot of faith in myself. And because he's someone I respect, it
meant so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali _ her father is a native of Trinidad, her mother a native of
Panama _ is a lifelong overachiever who began performing for family
and friends at age 4 and appeared at age 7 on TV's ``Star Search.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard-bound teenager began work on her debut album, ``Kiss
the Sky,'' after graduating from high school on Long Island, N.Y.
It's a smooth collection of upbeat, semiautobiographical dance
tunes and ballads, among them ``Boy, You Knock Me Out,''
``Everytime'' and ``Yesterday'' (a duet with Chico DeBarge).
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was done, I played it for some of my friends and they
all laughed and said, `Oh, great. You just told everybody
everything that's gone on in your life for the last year.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ali worked at her own pace on the album, collaborating with a
team of songwriters and producers. Among them were Shawn Stockman
(of Boys II Men) and Narada Michael Walden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, no one's going to pay attention to the album, so
I'll take my time, enjoy myself and I'll see who wants to work with
me in the studio. And someday I'll tell my grandchildren, `Look
what grandma did when she was young.'''
</P>
<P>
   The album, released last August, was far more successful than
Ali ever imagined. It has produced two hits, ``Daydreamin''' and
``Boy, You Knock Me Out.'' Her latest single, ``Everytime,'' is
currently on Billboard's Top R&AMP;B Singles &AMP; Tracks chart.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Ali decided to tour with 'N Sync, deferring her second
semester at Harvard, where she is studying genetics and African
American culture and history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that I couldn't say that I had completed the whole
recording process for the album without actually performing the
songs on the road,'' she said. ``I couldn't call myself a singer
without going out and singing.''
</P>
<P>
   The 'N Sync tour gave Ali some much-needed experience as a
performer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt improvement everywhere, from my comfort level in front
of the audience to my stamina during the show,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the 'N Sync tour, Ali joined the Backstreet Boys on a
European tour. Her current trek with ``All That Music and More,'' a
kind of Lollapalooza for kids, is her third tour.
</P>
<P>
   The tour appears Sunday at 4 p.m. at The Gorge outdoor
amphitheatre in George, Wash.. It includes Monica, 98 Degrees, 3rd
Storee, BWitched, No Authority and Aaron Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of the kids, this is their first concert,'' Ali
said. ``They're just freaking out and dancing on the lawn to the
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like watching any other music festival _ but in
miniature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
