<HEADER>
A7306 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NARCOLEPSY-GENE-BOS &LR;      08-05 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NARCOLEPSY-GENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NARCOLEPSY-INDUCING GENE IN DOGS IDENTIFIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a decade of trying, scientists are beginning to discover
the genetics and chemistry of one of life's most basic functions _
sleep and wakefulness.
</P>
<P>
   As an added bonus, the nerve cells and neurohormones that
control sleep and wakefulness turn out to be closely related to
those that regulate another vital behavior _ eating.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new findings appear in two scientific reports in the
current edition of the journal Cell, published in Cambridge, Mass..
</P>
<P>
   In one, Stanford University researchers report the discovery of
a single gene that causes a dramatic disorder called narcolepsy in
dogs _ one of the few species other than humans to have the strange
and often disabling disease.
</P>
<P>
   A second paper, to be published in Cell later this month, will
report the unexpected discovery that mice who lack the ability to
produce a key protein thought to be involved in feeding behavior
also suffer from narcolepsy. That report is authored by researchers
at the University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center with
colleagues from Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center in Boston and
Miyazaki Medical College in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   People with narcolepsy, thought to number about 135,000 in this
country, suddenly suffer attacks of irresistible sleepiness that
can occur while talking, standing, walking, eating, or driving.
Attacks are often brought on by strong emotion.
</P>
<P>
   People and dogs with the most severe form can suddenly collapse
from muscle weakness that mimics a state called ``atonia'' that
normally occurs every night when humans or animals enter
rapid-eye-movement (REM) sleep after about an hour and a half of
non-REM sleep. REM sleep is characterized by dreaming, lack of
muscle tone, and involuntary muscle twitches.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Emmanuel Mignot and his Stanford colleagues found that the
gene for narcolepsy in Labrador retrievers and Doberman pinschers
is a mutant form of the blueprint for a receptor that sits on the
surface of nerve cells that are widely distributed in the brain.
The receptor permits these cells to respond to a chemical called
orexin discovered only last year.
</P>
<P>
   That's where eating comes in. Orexin, also called hypocretin,
got its name from the Greek word orexos, which means ``to eat,''
because scientists noticed that injecting orexin into rats
increased their appetite and feeding behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Orexin or hypocretin is a potent activator of nerve cells, so
scientists hypothesize that a faulty receptor for this chemical
messenger disrupts the body's normal mechanisms for maintaining
wakefulness or neurologic ``arousal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on brain anatomy, we predicted that orexin would be
related to arousal,'' said Dr. Joel K. Elmquist of Beth Israel
Deaconess, a coauthor of the report on the narcoleptic mice.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship of orexin to appetite and eating, Elmquist
said, is still not understood. It may involve a similar brain
chemical called melanin-concentrating hormone, a potent appetite
stimulator whose distribution in the brain closely overlaps with
orexin. This makes sense, Elmquist noted, because wakefulness and
feeding behavior are necessarily linked.
</P>
<P>
   Another intriguing piece of the mosaic is that the Boston
researchers have shown that a newly approved narcolepsy drug called
modafinil (brand name Provigil) works by stimulating
orexin-producing nerve cells.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford researchers note that the orexin receptor gene they
have discovered in dogs also exists in humans. But it appears that
the genetic mechanism of human narcolepsy is more complex, perhaps
involving several genes and an environment trigger. One hypothesis
is that some people's immune system mistakenly attacks the system
of orexin-producing neurons or orexin receptors.
</P>
<P>
   The new discoveries represent ``a giant step toward
understanding the molecular basis of sleep,'' said Dr. Gerald D.
Fischbach, director of the National Institute of Neurological
Disorders and Stroke, and Dr. Claude Lenfant, director of the
National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute, in a statement Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
