<HEADER>
A7309 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-PIRACY06-CO     08-05 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-PIRACY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Microsoft piracy suit cites 5 Atlanta firms
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Microsoft filed suit this week in federal court
against five Atlanta area companies, claiming the computer hardware
and software retailers are selling pirated products.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said the companies _ Microseconds in Duluth; Atlanta
Computer and CompuTime International, both in Norcross; Tierra
Computer of Doraville; and Net-Sol, in Hall County _ sold illegal
versions of its software products to undercover detectives working
for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The software included Windows 95, Windows 98 and Office
Professional 97. The civil suits, filed Tuesday, also claim the
companies loaded unauthorized versions of Microsoft software onto
hard disks of PCs they sold.
</P>
<P>
   The companies can face penalties of up to $100,000 for software
products sold, regardless of how many copies. CompuTime
International, accused of selling illegal copies of Windows 95,
Windows 98 and Office Professional 97, could face up to $1 million
in fines, $100,000 each for the Windows products and $100,000 for
the eight programs included in the Office Professional suite.
</P>
<P>
   People who bought the allegedly counterfeit software from the
companies would not be liable for any of the damages or eligible
for any award given to Microsoft. A Microsoft spokesman said the
company would give customers a letter to bolster their case for a
refund from the stores.
</P>
<P>
   The companies' owners, none of whom returned callsThursday, have
20 days to respond to the complaints. None of the companies is an
authorized distributor of Microsoft products. A ruling could take
up to a year.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Psyhogeos, a Microsoft corporate attorney based in
Washington, said Microsoft is stepping up its efforts to combat the
illegal use of its software. The company started a television and
billboard anti-piracy advertising campaign in Georgia in May.
</P>
<P>
   Piracy is widespread, the company claims. Microsoft estimates
that one of every five software programs being used in Georgia was
illegally obtained, most by small- to medium-sized businesses. In
1998, the Business Software Alliance, a lobbying group, collected
$10 million in fines from companies using software for which they
did not have licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that these companies knew what they were doing and
they willfully ignored our requests that they refrain from that
conduct,'' he said. Psyhogeos said half of any settlement will be
given to local charities focused on teaching kids technology and
toward technology training for displaced workers.
</P>
<P>
   Psyhogeos said Microsoft learns of companies selling pirated
software or businesses using counterfeit versions from people who
call its toll-free anti-piracy number, 1-800-RULEGIT. Then they
hire a private detective to conduct a ``test purchase'' at a
suspected business.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Microseconds, Microsoft claims that it twice
bought PCs with pirated copies of Windows 95 installed, in
September and in April. After the September purchase, Psyhogeos
said Microsoft sent Microseconds a letter asking it to stop selling
the counterfeit product. Then last month, Microsoft said it bought
components of the 1997 version of its Office Pro software that
proved to be counterfeit. Office Pro includes several components,
including a word processor and a spreadsheet.
</P>
<P>
   Microseconds owner Steven Brandt was among the owners who could
not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Psyhogeos said consumers sometimes can tell if they are buying
pirated software because the user manual, license agreement and
warranty card will be missing.
</P>
<P>
   He said Microsoft is most interested in finding out where the
retailers get their counterfeit product.
</P>
<P>
   One such source was shut down in June.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Southern California arrested an eight-person operation
using a $1.2 million machine to copy 15,000 Microsoft software
programs a month.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
