<HEADER>
A7311 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-05 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: KOSOVO'S THREE WARS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching the latest cycle of ethnic revenge being played out in
Kosovo, this time with Albanians murdering Serbs, is a graphic
reminder that there were actually three wars in Kosovo this year.
The first war we lost, the second war we won and the third war is
yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
   The first Kosovo war was the diplomatic fight that was supposed
to prevent an ethnic war in Kosovo. At the Rambouillet peace
conference the United States and its allies laid down a plan
calling for autonomy for Kosovo, but with the promise of some kind
of referendum on statehood three years down the road, which looked
like a tacit commitment to independence for Kosovo Albanians on the
three-year installment plan. Rambouillet also gave NATO the right
to operate inside Serbia. Using coercive diplomacy, the U.S.
declared that if the Albanians accepted Rambouillet, and the Serbs
rejected it, NATO would bomb the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Milosevic rejected this plan, and so did the Albanian
Kosovars, some of whom wanted firmer guarantees of independence.
But after intense arm-twisting by the United States, the Albanian
Kosovars said yes. This was a dishonest yes _ it was a yes that was
given not because the Kosovars truly embraced Rambouillet, but
because it was whispered in their ears that if they just said yes
and the Serbs said no, NATO would bomb the Serbs, and in a few days
Milosevic would cave. He didn't cave, NATO bombed, and Milosevic
began ruthlessly killing and evicting Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the first Kosovo war was lost. The U.S. and NATO,
having adopted a strategy of coercive diplomacy against Milosevic,
were totally unprepared with sufficient coercive power when he
called their bluff. As a result, the very people whom NATO had set
out to protect with its diplomacy were ravaged by Serbian forces
before NATO was able to get an effective military response
together.
</P>
<P>
   This led to the second Kosovo war, which was fought purely to
reverse the results of the first war. This war was fought with no
coherent view of what sort of Kosovo political settlement NATO
wanted. Rather it was fought to stop the ethnic cleansing, to
return the refugees so that all Southern Europe wouldn't be
destabilized and to save NATO's credibility. The whole debate
around this war was about the means _ air power or ground troops _
not the political ends, which were vague.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that the only way NATO could sustain this war in a
corner of Europe with little strategic significance was by not
asking too much of its own citizens and by relying on air power
alone. Given these constraints, it was a war fought skillfully by
the Clinton administration and NATO. Air power alone worked.
Milosevic's ethnic cleansing was not allowed to stand, and all the
world got to see that. NATO won Kosovo War No. 2, and that was
important.
</P>
<P>
   But air power worked not because NATO bombed all the Serbian
troops out of Kosovo but because it bombed all the jobs out of
Belgrade _ crushing its economic infrastructure, and creating
something of a vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Now we are in Kosovo War No. 3. We are back to fighting over
what sort of Kosovo would be best. The U.S. and NATO favor a
self-governing, multi-ethnic, democratic Kosovo _ fully autonomous
but still formally part of Yugoslavia. An autonomous Kosovo still
officially part of Yugoslavia is what the Serbs also want, though
they resist the notion of multi-ethnic democracy. The devastated
Kosovar Albanians, however, want full independence now more than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   This has led to an odd situation. As the Council on Foreign
Relations fellow Michael Mandelbaum points out in a provocative
article coming out in Foreign Affairs, the NATO alliance has
``intervened in a civil war and defeated one side, but embraced the
position of the party it had defeated on the issue over which the
war had been fought.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens next?
</P>
<P>
   Think of it this way: NATO says it wants three things in Kosovo
_ multi-ethnicity, democracy and a very small NATO/U.S. presence.
But when you have two intermingled populations that fear and loathe
each other, as you do in Kosovo, you can only have two out of
three. You can have multi-ethnicity and democracy, but only with a
large NATO presence that puts a policeman on every corner. This is
the Lebanon solution, where you have different communities
intermingled, but under the hard fist of Syria. NATO doesn't want
to play Syria, though, and it is shamefully trying to fob off the
job on the U.N. That won't work. How are 3,500 U.N. police going to
do what 35,000 NATO troops can't?
</P>
<P>
   The other option is that we can have democracy and a small NATO
presence, but only if we give up on multi-ethnicity and divide
Kosovo _ only if we partition it into a separate Serbian Kosovo and
a separate Albanian Kosovo (which would mean a second Albanian
state) and then just patrol the line between them.
</P>
<P>
   Those are our Kosovo choices: Either we create two Albanias or
one Lebanon. If we don't face that squarely, NATO will be presiding
over Kosovo War No. 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
