<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERACTIVE-TV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Interactive TV potential `massive'
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it comes to interactive TV, you'd better stop
laughing _ and some local companies can celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   A leading industry consultant now says that this technology will
rival the Internet within three years, generating $20 billion in
revenue by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the findings of a new report by Forrester, a
Boston-based company that studies the commercial and social impact
of technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interactive TV has gone from being a laughingstock to becoming
a potentially massive revenue generator,'' says Josh Bernoff,
principal analyst for television research at Forrester.
</P>
<P>
   If Bernoff and Forrester are right, interactive TV could become
a bonanza for some Atlanta-based companies such as Cox
Communications and Scientific-Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications has been rebuilding its cable systems to
eventually offer interactive services.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta, which sells cable TV operators a digital
cable system called Explorer 2000, has bet big on interactive
television. In the past six years, the company has invested $300
million in the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Scientific-Atlanta sees the Forrester study as
an affirmation of its digital gamble. It also says that the
Forrester study tracks what it is finding in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, the consumer response to our digital systems has been
outstanding,'' says Jim McDonald, Scientific-Atlanta's president
and chief executive. ``The response has surpassed everyone's
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Interactive television refers to the ability to use a TV set for
such things as electronic mail, buying merchandise online, playing
games against others and browsing the Internet. Perhaps one of the
most eagerly awaited promises of the technology is video on demand
_ the ability to structure television programming according to the
viewer's interests.
</P>
<P>
   It has long been promised with the advent of digital technology,
but no one yet has figured out how to cash in on interactive
television.
</P>
<P>
   The days of stumbling, however, may soon be over. At least
Forrester says so.
</P>
<P>
   The medium is on the cusp of generating billions of dollars for
the cable operators, broadcast networks and entrepreneurs who have
invested so much in it, Forrester's study finds.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester says, for example, that interactive TV will generate
$11 billion in advertising, $7 billion in commerce and $2 billion
in subscription revenue by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an advertising medium, it will rival the Internet within
three years,'' says Bernoff.
</P>
<P>
   Three hot uses of interactive technology will drive revenue,
says Bernoff. The first is electronic program guides, which let
viewers see and browse shows from one easy-to-use list on the
screen. Advertisers are expected to spend $3.2 billion buying ads
on electronic guides within the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The second is what Bernoff calls enhanced broadcasts. The term
refers to such things as playing games with someone across town _
or across the country _ on your television. Enhanced broadcast
services are expected to generate $3.8 billion in fees and $6.2
billion in ad revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The third is Internet access through the television, which
Forrester forecasts will generate $5 billion in revenue from
advertising, subscriptions and electronic commerce within five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Bernoff says the big beneficiaries of this bonanza will be the
cable operators and satellite companies, which have led investment
in interactive television.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, cable _ and especially satellite companies _ have
been lesser players in the media business compared with the big
four broadcast networks and the movie studios.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interactive television will turn the media industry inside
out,'' says Bernoff. ``As ITV (interactive TV) spreads across the
consumer landscape, it will pull advertising dollars away from
existing media, including television and the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
