<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-AMNESTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 GRANTED AMNESTY BY SOUTH AFRICA TRUTH COMMISSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ A former Cabinet official, a former
head of the national police force and the former head of the brutal
Vlakplaas police unit were granted amnesty Thursday for their roles
in blowing up a church headquarters in Johannesburg in 1988 and
falsely implicating an anti-apartheid activist in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the men, Adriaan Vlok, once the minister of law and
order, and Gen. Johann van der Merwe were the highest-ranking
officials of the former government to confess to illegal activities
and ask the Truth and Reconciliation Commission for amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   Vlok testified before the commission that when he ordered the
bombing he was acting under direct orders from P.W. Botha, the
president at the time, who told him the South African Council of
Churches headquarters, known as Khotso House, had become a ``house
of evil.''
</P>
<P>
   The former leader of the Vlakplaas Unit, Eugene de Kock, a man
nicknamed ``Prime Evil'' by his men, has confessed to more than 100
acts of sabotage, assault, torture and murder. This is the first
time he has been granted amnesty for any of his crimes. He is
serving a 212-year jail sentence for his crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The commission found that all three men had met the requirements
for amnesty: They had ``made a full disclosure of all relevant
facts'' and had ``a political objective'' when they organized the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The six-story Khotso House _ the name means house of peace in
the Sotho language _ was virtually demolished in June 1988 by an
explosion in the middle of the night. The bomb injured more than 20
people.
</P>
<P>
   After the bombing, the government then engaged in a smear
campaign, trying to blame a young anti-apartheid activist, Shirley
Gunn. Ms. Gunn, and her baby, were detained by police for 62 days.
Vlok has publicly apologized to her.
</P>
<P>
   When it was destroyed, Khotso House had become a symbol of
nonviolent resistance to apartheid. In his application for amnesty,
Vlok said Botha had asked him to render it unusable. He quoted
Botha as saying he had done ``everything possible to persuade''
those who worked at Khotso House to ``come to their senses, but
nothing helps.'' Botha, now 83, has steadfastly denied any
involvement in illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
   The Truth Commission also released its findings Thursday in
another notorious case, involving the killing of three white
right-wing activists who invaded the former black homeland of
Bophuthatswana on the eve of the country's first nonracial
elections five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The commission granted amnesty to the homeland police officer
who killed the members of the Afrikaner Weerstandsbeweging, known
as the AWB, two of whom were killed methodically after they had
already been injured.
</P>
<P>
   The right-wingers were among thousands of AWB members who had
invaded the homeland _ an area designated for blacks under the
apartheid government _ to try to quell a popular uprising against
the homeland leader, Lucas Mangope. Mangope was refusing to have
Bophuthatswana reintegrated into the new South Africa, and most of
his army and police officers turned against him. As the militant
whites invaded to help Mangope, chaos broke out and more than 20
people died.
</P>
<P>
   But the killing of the three white militants stood out amid the
carnage in part because it was captured by television cameras.
Journalists watched as the police officer, Ontlametse Menyatso,
approached the three men who lay in the dust around their Mercedes,
one dead and two bleeding badly but still answering questions.
</P>
<P>
   Menyatso then aimed his automatic rifle and shot them four
times. The killings were a defining moment in a day in which South
African right-wingers mounted their first armed challenge to the
new South Africa and went away disorganized and defeated. Mangope
acknowledged defeat the next day.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the commission, created to help South Africa put
its brutal past to rest, found that ``the events which led to the
general chaos and violence which reigned'' that day were clearly
politically motivated and it found that Menyatso had also made a
``full disclosure of all relevant facts.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
