<HEADLINE>
800 LIBERTY MUTUAL WORKERS MAY FACE JOB LOSS IN CUTBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HEATHER KAMINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Liberty Mutual Group, the nation's largest workers'
compensation insurer, is laying off employees as part of a national
effort to contain costs and consolidate its operations.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 800 workers may receive pink slips, according to
several former employees who asked to have their names withheld.
Layoffs began about six weeks ago, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees said the layoffs were undertaken after Liberty Mutual
acquired a number of smaller insurance firms in the United States
and overseas. ``They told us it was because of reorganization,''
one former company attorney said. ``They said they didn't have the
workload to support all of the people they had.''
</P>
<P>
   John Cusolito, a spokesman for Liberty Mutual, confirmed
Thursday that the company is laying off some of its 37,000
employees as part of a nationwide ``expense management'' program.
``It's in all parts of our organization,'' he said, and is being
carried out by managers in various departments and offices in order
``to align expenses with revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   However, reports of 800 layoffs are ``not accurate,'' Cusolito
said. ``It's really too premature,'' he said. ``We don't have an
overall number.''
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs came across the board, according to the former
employees. But substantial numbers of workers were cut from the
legal, computer support, research, and statistical analysis
departments, they said. It's unclear how many employees in
Massachusetts would be affected.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 workers in Liberty Mutual's information technology
division in Dover and Portsmouth, N.H., were let go at the
beginning of July. Those layoffs were attributed to a declining
need for technicians as the company completed its preparations for
dealing with the computer glitch known as the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Liberty Mutual reported a net income of $244.8
million. The Boston company manages more than $61 billion in
assets.
</P>
<P>
   Workers' compensation insurance, which provides benefits to
workers who are unble to perform due to injuries on the job, is
becoming an increasingly competitive industry with significant cost
pressures, Cusolito said.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two years Liberty Mutual has aggressively sought
to buy a number of insurance companies across the nation and in the
United Kingdom, notably Wausau Insurance Cos. of Wisconsin and
Guardian Royal Exchange PLC, to diversify business and become less
dependent on workers' compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Mutual has received strong credit ratings from both
Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. and Moody's Investors Service, but in
February Moody's added a ``negative'' outlook to its ``Aa3''
rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Aa3 rating means they are a fairly sound franchise,''
Moody's analyst Bill Wilt said, adding that increased competition,
medical cost inflation, and government reform efforts have made the
market less profitable. ``In general workers' compensation results
have been deteriorating,'' he said. ``It has been an increasingly
challenging way to make money.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kimberly Blanton and Steven Wilmsen of the Globe staff contributed
to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
