<HEADLINE>
RAPE OF 14-YEAR-OLD IN BALLET PROGRAM ALLEGED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY AND RYAN DAVIS AND  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Police are investigating allegations that two young
male dancers in the Boston Ballet's summer program committed
statutory rape when they had sex with a 14-year-old female dancer
in the program.
</P>
<P>
   The charges surface as the summer program draws to a close
Friday with concluding performances.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Police detective Sergeant Margot Hill confirmed that
there is an ongoing statutory rape investigation involving students
in the summer program, but declined to supply any details. The
Suffolk County District Attorney's office also is involved in the
probe, office spokesman James Borghesani said.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Ballet spokesman John Michael Kennedy said the ballet
company ``is cooperating fully with the appropriate authorities as
this matter is further investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boston Ballet acknowledges the seriousness of the
allegations involving students in its Summer Dance Program,''
Kennedy said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The ages of the male dancers were not available, but each would
have to be 22 or younger to participate in the summer program.
</P>
<P>
   Students said Boston Police detectives visited the ballet's
facility in the city's South End this week, where they interviewed
several members of the teaching staff and dancers.
</P>
<P>
   Two male students left with police officers for further
questioning, a witness said, but no one has been charged.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations of statutory rape _ meaning the alleged victim
is younger than 16 years old _ would make it unnecessary for
prosecutors to prove in court that sex was coerced. Even consensual
sex is barred by the statute, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The company recruits students for the summer program from
throughout the world. Landing one of the 300 coveted slots in the
program is a highly competitive venture.
</P>
<P>
   Auditions are conducted at about a dozen sites around the
country, including New York City and San Francisco, Kennedy said.
In addition, some candidates send in videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   Considered a ``pre-professional program,'' the program has
students ranging in ages from 13 to 22. Many hope the exposure and
concentrated study will help launch their professional careers.
</P>
<P>
   The ballet has had 332 students in its summer program this year,
including 294 females.
</P>
<P>
   The students stay in a dormitory at Emerson College, where 13
resident advisers are on hand to supervise, Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   The students are divided among 10 skill levels, not by age,
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which started in 1980, includes one group that
meets for the six-week span and two others that meet for three
weeks each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
