<HEADER>
A7339 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMS-RACE06-COX     08-05 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-RACE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rainbow/PUSH: Democrats court key voters
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Democratic presidential hopeful Bill Bradley and
Tipper Gore, his rival's wife, campaigned at the Rainbow/PUSH
Coalition's annual meeting Thursday, bringing messages of racial
unity to a key Democratic Party constituency.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president will speak to the gathering Saturday, and the
stakes for both men couldn't be higher. Rainbow Coalition founder
Jesse Jackson hasn't endorsed anyone, and many other influential
black leaders haven't, either.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and Gore both were warmly received by the hundreds of
delegates gathered in Chicago under the slogan, ``Building Bridges,
Building Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore was clearly given the VIP treatment. The keynote
speaker for a luncheon honoring women, she spoke to more than 1,200
delegates _ three times the breakfast audience Bradley had hours
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Gore referred to her husband repeatedly in her remarks and
promised that if he is elected president, he will reduce class
sizes, make schools ``drug free and gun free'' and ``remain fully
committed to affirmative action and civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has remained neutral in the Gore-Bradley presidential
sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great respect for both,'' said Jackson, who spoke
privately with Bradley after his remarks. ``Vice President Gore _
our relationship is good. It's personal, it's deep, but that's true
for Bill Bradley, too. Both are decent men, smart, both are
sensitive. Both have the stuff of which great presidents are
made.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said it was time for the candidates to ``stake out their
territory and be defined by what they are going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bradley's long record of speaking out against racial
prejudice, most analysts say that Gore holds a distinct edge among
the nation's black electorate, benefiting partly from the enormous
popularity President Clinton enjoys among black voters.
</P>
<P>
   They note that Gore is strongest in the South, where black
people make up a larger portion of the Democratic primary vote, and
that Bradley has yet to make much of an effort to organize
grass-roots support in that region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see Bradley as a candidate who has any Southern
appeal,'' said David Bositis, senior analyst at the Joint Center
for Political and Economic Studies.
</P>
<P>
   In a new poll to be released as early as today, Bositis said he
found that black voters view both Bradley and Gore favorably by a
four to one margin. But Bradley is still unknown to more than 40
percent of the black electorate, while Gore is ``universally''
known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore has been going out of his way since at least 1996 to
attract black voters,'' Bositis said. ``It isn't that Bill Bradley
is unpopular. His biggest problem is that he is unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to delegates here, Bradley spoke about his
life-long commitment to ending racial inequality, and declared that
``racial unity is not a project, it is not my position, it is my
core.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley challenged the vice president to convince President
Clinton to sign an executive order banning racial profiling in
federal law enforcement, something Gore has said he will do if
elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say why wait?'' said Bradley. ``Mr. Vice President, walk
down that hall where the president is seated, go up to him with the
executive order and say to him, 'Sign this now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also charged that the White House has not paid enough
attention to the plight of poor children.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first two-term Democratic president since Franklin
Roosevelt, the number of children in poverty in America has barely
blipped down,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Egondu Onyejekwe, an engineer from Columbus, Ohio, gave Bradley
middling marks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was OK,'' she said. ``Sometimes they offend you by saying
things you know they wouldn't do. It's a very good skill to talk in
generic terms, but I want something I can put my hands on and
feel.''
</P>
<P>
   During Clinton's impeachment ordeal, black voters were
consistently Clinton's biggest backers. In 1998, blacks voted in
sharply higher numbers and helped elect Democrats, especially in
the South.
</P>
<P>
   Much, though not all, of that support for Clinton will probably
transfer to Gore, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore starts out with a lot,'' said Emory University political
scientist Merle Black. ``He has certainly been the contact person
with the White House and with black elected officials across the
country. That pays off in political support.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Clinton is personally popular with black voters, some
of the administration's policies have upset black leaders. There is
still unhappiness that Clinton yielded on the welfare reform bill
and his initiative on race relations failed to deliver on many of
its promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with Gore is that he is trading on the record of
the Clinton administration,'' said Dr. Ron Walters, a scholar at
the James McGregor Burns Academy of Leadership. ``What people want
to see is what he will do differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same challenge has to be met by Bradley,'' said Walters.
``He gives you the feeling he has an understanding of (racial
inequalities), but that is far from a public policy agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   In her own speech to delegates, Tipper Gore noted that
unemployment figures for blacks and Latinos are at record lows, and
she pledged her husband would work to increase incomes for poorer
Americans, something Bradley has also promised to make a priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just magnificent,'' said Helen Anglin, a Chicago
restaurant owner. ``She did address our concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
