<HEADLINE>
ROLE OF ASSAD'S SON SAID TO BE UNDECIDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria _ Whether the 34-year-old son of President Hafez
al-Assad is his father's preferred choice as the next leader of
Syria is an open question, a high-ranking government official said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Information Minister Mohammed Salman, seemed to be
trying to inject a bit of doubt into the increasing presumption
that the son, Bashar, is being anointed as Assad's successor. There
has been speculation that the succession might be a factor in
Syria's renewed efforts toward peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Some prominent Syrians and foreign diplomats here have suggested
that a desire to smooth the way for the younger Assad might be
behind the 68-year-old president's declared eagerness to move
swiftly toward peace with Israel and its new leader, Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The question of succession is highly sensitive, one that Syrian
officials have almost always sidestepped. But Salman, who does not
often meet foreign journalists, raised the issue at the start of an
interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to now, officially there is nothing to indicate that he has
been appointed to any official position,'' Salman said of Bashar
Assad, a former ophthalmologist whose sole title is colonel. Under
the constitution, a president has to be a member of the command
council of the governing Baath Party and should be 40.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Salman did not try to close the door on the prospect that
Bashar Assad might be elevated, and he praised him at length. He
called the younger Assad a technocrat and a modernizer and noted
that as president of the country's computer society, he had been
the driving force behind Syria's gradual embrace of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people in this country see these new initiatives, they
are inclined to express their welcoming of such a man in a high
position,'' he said. ``As a person, I really want him to have a
high position, either in the party or the leadership of the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   The succession question is increasingly being discussed, as the
president has shown signs of uncertain health and as his son Assad
has been given additional responsibilities. In official Syrian
publications, the caption under portraits of Bashar Assad describes
him as ``the hope.''
</P>
<P>
   A persistent rumor reported by many well-connected Syrians is
that Bashar Assad will be elevated to a party post at a meeting
being planned for the late fall, a step that could put him in line
for future promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Many diplomats based in Damascus say there is little doubt that
Bashar Assad is his father's choice. But the fact that Assad is
young and untested and that Syria has no history of family
dynasties has persuaded some that if the father died soon, the son
might be made part of a collective leadership headed by Vice
President Abdel Halim Khaddam.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are hard-core elements in the Baath establishment and
the military leadership that might not see in Bashar the caliber of
leadership that they believe is required,'' said one well-connected
Syrian.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the interview Thursday, Salman also expressed a new hint of
dissatisfaction with Barak, whose post-election pledges of a
commitment to make peace with Syria have kindled a sense of
optimism. Salman said Syria was still waiting for Barak to
reiterate what Damascus says is a commitment that Israel made
before negotiations were suspended in 1996 _ to work toward a peace
that would include a full withdrawal from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope,'' Salman said, ``that such maneuvering by Barak will
not lead to a delay in the restarting of negotiations and, of
course, to a deadlock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
