<HEADLINE>
ROSENBLUTH INTERNATIONAL BUYS BUSINESS TRAVEL WEB SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.) (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the 2nd graf instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(rk) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rosenbluth International said Thursday that it had bought a
majority stake in Biztravel.com, a leading site for making business
travel arrangements over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Other investors, including Continental Airlines, Marriott
International, Sun Microsystems and Excite (AT)Home, also bought
stakes in the company, which promises to vault Rosenbluth, a travel
management company, into the forefront of online travel.
Rosenbluth, which is privately owned, declined to disclose the
purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity to get into e-commerce,'' said Hal
Rosenbluth, the chief executive of the company. ``We've been
studying it for some time, and we were embarked on building our own
site, but when this opportunity came along, we jumped on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many companies, Rosenbluth was aware of a forecast by
Jupiter Communications, a research group, that online sales of
travel services will grow to about $11.2 billion in 2002 from $911
million in 1997. Its opportunity to become a bigger player in that
market arose after Biztravel.com retained Paine Webber to sell it
at auction, Rosenbluth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that happened,'' he said, ``we were hellbent on ensuring
that we won, then we went out and brought in the other partners,
all of them class companies with good brands.'' The Blackstone
Group acted as Rosenbluth International's financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbluth, based in Philadelphia, is the nation's third-biggest
travel agency, with $3.74 billion in gross retail sales last year,
according to the Travel Weekly trade publication. Its revenue now
exceeds $4 billion a year, the company said. Only American Express,
with gross revenue of $11.9 billion, and Carlson Wagonlit, with
more than $11 billion, are bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, Rosenbluth International will establish
an affiliate company, Rosenbluth Interactive, It will comprise
Biztravel.com, which will focus on smaller businesses, including
the fast-growing home-based businesses, and a consumer site that
will be available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most notable features of the consumer site, to be
announced later, will be its posting of a wide range of discounted
fares that will be monitored up until the day of departure.
Rosenbluth said it would monitor those fares and would exchange
tickets already bought at a higher fare with cheaper tickets that
become available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our booking engine will continually pulse the airlines for low
fares,'' Rosenbluth said, ``and if we find a ticket lower than the
one somebody already bought from us, we'll exchange the cheaper
ticket for the more expensive one.'' Rosenbluth added that he was
``a firm believer that most of the public doesn't really think it
got the best air fare.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
