<HEADLINE>
TREASURY SECURITIES RISE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury securities rose for the second consecutive
session Thursday, as the pricing of a huge debt issue by Wal-Mart
Stores failed to hurt the sale of U.S. government paper.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond gained 23/32 to a price of 89 7/32; its yield,
which moves in the opposite direction of the price, fell to 6.04
percent, down from 6.09 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts noted the strong investor demand for the debt of
Wal-Mart, the world's largest retailer. The size of the issue
increased twice before pricing, to $5.75 billion. The debt
offering, handled through underwriters led by Lehman Brothers, is
the first AA-rated deal paper to be sold in about four months. It
drew buyers by the sheer visibility of its name, its credit quality
and the yield spread over Treasury securities with a similar
maturity.
</P>
<P>
   The debt was sold in three maturities, with $1.25 billion of
two-year global bonds priced to yield 6.179 percent, or about 65
basis points more than a similar Treasury security. A basis point
is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   The second maturity included $1.25 billion of a five-year
maturity, priced to yield 6.586 percent, or 85 basis points more
than a similar Treasury, with the longer maturity totaling $3.25
billion of 10-year debt priced to yield 6.93 percent, or 103 basis
points more than a comparable Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Traders expect that Treasuries could have a difficult time
pushing higher in the weeks ahead, with about $44 billion more in
debt sales scheduled to be sold.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's advance was likely tied to investors buying back
Treasuries that had been sold ahead of the Wal-Mart deal.
Securities firms tend to sell their most liquid government paper
before underwriting large issues as a hedge against a rise in
interest rates while investors absorb the new securities, then buy
back the Treasuries as the sale is completed.
</P>
<P>
   With investors worried that the Fed may raise interest rates
later this month, there is a chance that the appetite for more debt
is dwindling. Still, that was not apparent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rally, investors continue to watch the labor markets
for any hint that the economy is picking up and that inflation
might thus become a threat. Friday's July employment report should
give more clues about what to expect from the Federal Reserve
policy makers at the Aug. 24 meeting of the Fed's Open Market
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
