<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION HOPE TO SURVIVE RAPIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Revolution might be in the midst of another down
cycle, but John Harkes is taking the situation in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll be all right,'' Harkes said while preparing for
Friday night's game against the Colorado Rapids. ``You look around
the league and this happens to most teams. Even with D.C. United
there were times when we would lose two or three games in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, though, have taken losing to extremes, setting
MLS records with nine-game losing streaks in 1997 and '98. In 115
MLS games, the Revolution have earned 117 points, the lowest
per-match average in the Eastern Conference and tied with San Jose
for all-time lowest. Further, the Revolution's all-time goal
differential is worst in the league, though the problem appeared to
have been solved until the last three matches.
</P>
<P>
   But after losses of 5-2, 2-0, and 4-1 in the first three games
of the second half of the season, many questions have been raised
about the Revolution. Certainly, the Revolution have missed Harkes
and Joe-Max Moore, who returned from US national team duty this
week. But both were in the lineup when the Revolution losing streak
started against Los Angeles July 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the best situation when you are missing players,''
Harkes said. ``But we won games when I was out before and when Joey
missed a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think about what happened last year or before that.
This is a whole new team and we have a whole new attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkes's career has rebounded from a year ago, when he had been
dismissed from the United States national team by former US coach
Steve Sampson during preparations for the France '98 World Cup.
Last month, Harkes was chosen for the MLS All-Star Game, then
performed for the national team that finished third place in the
Confederations Cup in Mexico, where he was reunited with his former
D.C. United coach Bruce Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing is that Bruce has faith in the team's depth,''
Harkes said. ``From what I saw during training sessions, Bruce and
his coaching staff are on the right track. We had some good
success, beating Germany and we had a good chance to beat or tie
Brazil. We just didn't finish our chances the whole tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied with my performance, but who knows where Bruce
stands? I know him well but he is still juggling players, so we'll
see. I don't think I have to prove anything to anyone. One person
(Sampson) made a decision on me. But I've continued to play the way
I know how and I'll always play the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Revolution has lacked Harkes's competitive spirit,
especially in a 4-1 loss at Tampa Bay. But even with Harkes, Moore,
and newcomer Ariel Graziani, the Revolution have yet to address
their defensive shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a problem when I left,'' Harkes said. ``Maybe
we need to change things around, go back to a 4-4-2. We have enough
good players on this team to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Would Harkes consider moving into central defense, especially if
Dan Calichman continues to struggle with groin and hip injuries?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever I'm needed, I will play there,'' Harkes said. ``But
we have a lot of experience in defense. Mike Burns is our captain
and he can work out a lot of things back there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
