<SLUG> BC-LLBEAN-PHONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN WHO GOT L.L. BEAN CALLS TO GET GIFT CERTIFICATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She became Bean For A Day _ L.L. Bean, that is.
</P>
<P>
   But the Northern Virginia woman who suddenly found her phone
ringing off the hook with orders from customers wanting to outfit
their children in the latest outdoor Beanwear wasn't discomfited by
the experience, a company official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was extremely gracious and good &UR;  &LR; natured and wonderfully
helpful,'' said spokeswoman Mary Rose MacKinnon, describing the
still unidentified woman who found herself accidentally at the end
of L.L. Bean's toll-free line last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``She even took orders for us, so no sales were lost,''
MacKinnon said, happily.
</P>
<P>
   The mixup occurred last week when L.L. Bean's new children's
catalog, ``L.L. Kids,'' arrived in customers' homes. The toll-free
order number, which was supposed to read 877-LLB-KIDS, was changed
to 800-LLB-KIDS on some pages in the catalog.
</P>
<P>
   The outdoor gear company provided more details of the snafu
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 800 number was originally assigned to ``a kids' business
which had become inactive,'' MacKinnon said. But through what she
described as ``a technical phone-company glitch,'' the number
actually rang at the private residence of a woman who lived in
Virginia. Additional details about the glitch were not provided.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials declined to identify the woman, saying ``she
has been through enough'' as the recipient of an avalanche of
calls. ``We choose not to inconvenience her further,'' MacKinnon
said.
</P>
<P>
   L.L. Bean acquired the inactive toll-free number immediately at
no cost, MacKinnon added. She initially denied reports that the
company financially compensated the good samaritan who cheerfully
fielded all the calls.
</P>
<P>
   Later she said the company is ``sending her a very generous gift
certificate to express our regret for the inconvenience and to
thank her for being such a good sport.'' She declined to disclose
the amount.
</P>
<P>
   The children's catalog was one of about 50 published this year
by the Freeport, Maine mail-order giant, whose net sales in 1998
amounted to $1.03 billion. Nearly 90 percent of these sales came
from catalog customers, MacKinnon said.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives declined to say how many catalogs were mailed
out bearing the faulty phone numbers. But they said the company
distributed about 150 million catalogs of all kinds last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
