<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7349 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELVIS-TUPELO06-COX     08-05 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELVIS-TUPELO06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elvis' hometown spotlights famous son with music, film fest and
more
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUPELO, Miss. _ Before Elvis Presley wore sequined jumpsuits,
gave away Cadillacs and created a Jungle Room in a mansion in
Memphis, he lived in a shotgun shack in this Mississippi town.
</P>
<P>
   But Tupelo, 100 miles southeast of Memphis, tends to be in the
shadow of Graceland and Elvis Presley Enterprises, the family
corporation that zealously guards the rights to the use of the
King's name, likeness and image. His birthplace is a museum, but
the town is otherwise pretty quiet about its claim to fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always thought the birthplace was all we could do,'' said
Jim High, assistant manager of Tupelo's Main Street Association.
``Graceland guards his image pretty closely.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, the town that gave birth to the King will come out
of the shadows and spotlight its legacy with the first-ever Elvis
Presley Festival. Set downtown, the street fair and music fest come
just before ``Death Week,'' when thousands of Elvis fans journey to
Memphis for seven days leading up to the anniversary of his death
on Aug. 16, 1977. High and others are hoping the festival will
entice folks to spend a few days here before heading north to
Graceland.
</P>
<P>
   ``People going to Memphis for Death Week usually come here for a
few hours, but then they get back on the tour buses and leave,''
High said. ``We want them to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival kicks off tonight with a tribute to the jumpsuit
years: Trent Carlini, an Elvis ``stylist'' from Las Vegas, will
perform at the Tupelo Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the music will be true to the spirit of the young
Elvis Presley, who sang gospel and loved the blues. There will be a
gospel singing contest and a performance by a local group called
the Landmarks Gospel Quartet. Acts on outdoor stages include
bluesman Bobbie ``Blue'' Bland and several recording artists who
worked with Elvis at Sun Records in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   Besides music, there is a film festival featuring seven of his
33 movies and an exhibit of his movie posters. There's a classic
car show called Cruising With the King, a 5K run called Running
With the King, and a bicycle race, called _ what else? _ Riding
With the King. A Harley-Davidson motorcycle rally begins Saturday
morning at the birthplace. There's even an Elvis ballet performance
planned.
</P>
<P>
   One lucky festival attendee will receive a new Cadillac.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elvis gave away Cadillacs to his friends and it didn't matter
who it was, even if it was a waitress,'' High said.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing missing are the peanut butter and banana
sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   High, who is the festival's activities director, said the idea
for the event came from Linda Butler, Tupelo's new Convention and
Visitors Bureau director.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came last fall and asked us why we didn't promote Elvis
Presley, and we didn't have a very good answer,'' he said. ``She
suggested we go to Memphis and ask permission to have a festival.
We got the permission.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival, sponsored by the Main Street Association and
Downtown Tupelo, is free except for certain events, such as the
Carlini show, the poster exhibit and the movies. Ten percent of the
proceeds goes to a nonprofit foundation owned by Elvis Presley
Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis Aron Presley was born on Jan. 8, 1935, in a narrow shotgun
house in East Tupelo. About 100,000 fans visit the home annually.
The only other Elvis ``shrine'' in town is Tupelo Hardware, where
the King of Rock 'n' Roll got his first guitar. A classic Main
Street establishment with high tin ceilings, wood floors and red
wagons on display, the store doesn't bear a sign advertising its
part in history.
</P>
<P>
   The store is owned by the son and grandson of the man who owned
it when Gladys Presley brought her son to buy his 10th birthday
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elvis wanted a rifle but his mama wouldn't buy him the rifle,
so she said she'd buy him the guitar,'' said George Booth, who owns
the store with his father.
</P>
<P>
   The guitar cost $8.
</P>
<P>
   Booth sells T-shirts commemorating the sale, but since he can't
legally use the name Elvis Presley, they simply say, ``Where Gladys
bought her son his first guitar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Booth is excited about the festival, although he wonders how
many people will show up. He stocked up on T-shirts in case there's
extra demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've wanted to promote Elvis but we didn't know
how,'' he said. ``There's so much hype around Graceland, it's hard
to break into that.''
</P>
<P>
   Vernon Chadwick, who began an annual Elvis academic conference
some years back, said the birthplace always has been overshadowed
by the big home in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tupelo has been competing with Memphis ever since Elvis became
the celebrity that he is,'' said Chadwick, whose conference, now
more of a small gathering, also begins today. Called ``Elvis
Unplugged,'' it will be in a cafe in Memphis called the Map Room.
This year's theme is Elvis in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went to visit President Nixon in 1970, and ever since, his
spirit has been residing in the Oval Office,'' Chadwick said.
``Look at President Clinton: Elvis is alive and well in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick says he believes Mississippi has a history of mixed
feelings about her most famous native son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mississippians feel the stigma of the so-called redneck, and
Elvis represents that, and he reminds them of the whole history of
poor white families in Mississippi.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Elvis was controversial: He was overtly sexual, and he
sounded black when he sang on the radio, which upset segregated
1950s Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father thought he was terrible,'' High said. ``It was rock
'n' roll, you wiggled your hips. People like my father never
changed how they felt about him, and it was people his age in town
who could have jumped on the legacy and promoted it, but didn't.
They probably just hoped the legacy would die when Elvis died. But
he just keeps getting more famous.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
