<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATORS FOR HOUSE, SENATE AGREE ON PLAN FOR ENERGY DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., S.C., Texas) (rk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House and Senate negotiators reached agreement
Thursday on a significant revamping of the Department of Energy,
establishing a new agency within the department to oversee nuclear
weapons programs in response to accusations of Chinese espionage.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials said the proposal constrained the
energy secretary's authority. They indicated that Energy Secretary
Bill Richardson would recommend that President Clinton veto the
Pentagon's $289 billion budget bill that contains the provision
unless lawmakers modified this aspect.
</P>
<P>
   Vetoing the military budget bill would be politically risky for
the president, and many senior Republicans in the House and Senate
predicted he would not take that gamble. Lawmakers and
administration officials were scrambling Thursday night to work out
language acceptable to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting in marathon sessions all week, lawmakers hammered out
one of the most far-ranging legislative responses to the
allegations that China stole some of the country's most sensitive
nuclear secrets because of lax security at weapons laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement Thursday sets up a new agency with some autonomy
within the Energy Department _ the National Nuclear Security
Administration. It gives the agency's director, an under secretary
of energy, with broad authority over policy, budgeting, security
and counterintelligence for nuclear programs. The director would
report to the secretary of energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation will provide for cleaner lines of authority
and accountability to ensure that our nation's most vital nuclear
secrets are properly managed and secured,'' said Rep. Floyd Spence,
R-S.C., chairman of the House Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   If enacted, the measure would represent the most dramatic
restructuring of the department since it was formed in 1977.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The changes, House Republicans said, would eliminate tangles in
the lines of authority and replace what Rep. Mac Thornberry of
Texas called ``a dysfunctional bureaucracy'' with a military-style
chain of command from the secretary through the new agency's
director to the field directors of weapons laboratories like Los
Alamos and Sandia.
</P>
<P>
   Wen Ho Lee, a former scientist at Los Alamos, has been
questioned by the Federal Bureau of Investigation about the
possible theft of nuclear secrets by China. Lee has denied that he
divulged atomic secrets to China or ``any unauthorized person.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month the Senate overwhelmingly approved the Energy
Department reorganization as part of a bill authorizing the
government's intelligence programs. The bill won bipartisan support
only after Democrats won concessions that they said strengthened
the secretary's authority over the new agency.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans criticized their Senate colleagues for giving
in to Democratic demands, and took a much harder line during a
House-Senate conference reconciling differences between competing
versions of the military budget bill. Much of department's budget
is included in the Pentagon bill because of the nuclear weapons
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's accord, which still requires formal approval by both
the House and Senate after the summer recess, dealt a setback to
the administration and to Richardson initially resisted the idea of
a semiautonomous nuclear stewardship agency before he grudgingly
accepted the plan in order to avert alternatives he considered even
worse, like splitting the agency from his department altogether.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For his part, Richardson has tried to blunt the growing calls to
revamp his department by reorganizing and centralizing its
far-flung security functions. Richardson appointed a retired
four-star Air Force general to be the department's first security
czar.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the secretary ordered a one-day hiatus at many of the
department's research and military-related operations for training
in counterespionage and security.
</P>
<P>
   But in a stinging report in June, a presidential review panel
said the administration's efforts to tighten security at the labs
were hamstrung by bureaucratic arrogance and foot-dragging.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, by the president's Foreign Intelligence Advisory
Board, which studies sensitive intelligence and national security
matters, concluded that the department was a ``dysfunctional
bureaucracy that has proven it is incapable of reforming itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel, headed by a former Republican senator, Warren Rudman
of New Hampshire, recommended either a semiautonomous agency like
the one approved Thursday or an independent agency like the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration to oversee nuclear
programs.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to blunt accusations of partisanship, House and
Senate Republicans have said they were modeling their proposal
after the presidential advisory board's recommendations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
