<SLUG> BC-MUSICAL-BROTHERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLMANS, NEVILLES HAVE ENDURED AND THRIVED DESPITE TRAGEDIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERTA PENN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Musical families have been around at least as far back as the
Bachs. But few in American pop culture have thrived through hard
times and shifting tastes like the Allman Brothers Band and the
Neville Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   These two Southern-bred clans headline shows at Seattle's
waterfront this weekend, and the sold-out sign on both concerts
attests to their staying power. Their music may be as old-fashioned
as family values, but no one wants to give them up.
</P>
<P>
   The Allman Brothers Band began its ascent to the pinnacle of
Southern-fried blues rock with its self-titled album in 1969.
Taking their name from guitarist Duane and organ-player and singer
Gregg Allman, the group grew from an experience that the two
brothers had in Nashville when they were teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother dropped me and my brother off at one of those rhythm
and blues revues,'' Gregg Allman recalled in a phone interview.
``It was Jackie Wilson, Otis Redding, Patti LaBelle and the Blue
Belles. And B.B. King, who had a guy with a big red pompadour
sitting behind the first Hammond organ I ever saw. Man, me and my
brother looked at each other and said, `We gotta get into some of
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   With drummers Butch Trucks and Jaimoe, bassist Berry Oakley and
guitarist Dickey Betts, the two brothers stretched the blues out
with extended guitar solos while the two drummers revved up the
rhythm. But tragedy struck just as the Allmans were about to break
into the big time. On Oct. 29, 1971, Duane Allman was killed in a
motorcycle accident, and just a little over a year later Oakley met
the same fate.
</P>
<P>
   The four original Allmans took the tragedy and turned it into
gold by continuing to tour and record, drawing other musicians into
the group. Though no one has ever added quite the charismatic
presence of Duane Allman, the band has remained together off and on
over the years. And now with the addition of guitarist Derek Trucks
(the drummer's nephew), Gregg Allman believes the group has been
re-energized for this summer's 30th anniversary tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Derek just wails, and that brings on a great amount of
spontaneity,'' Allman said. ``Though we are not all brothers, we
consider ourselves a family band, and like families we have our ups
and downs, but we are a collective decision-making organization and
we sit down and talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Art, Charles, Aaron and Cyril Neville didn't begin making
music together until 1976, when they came together to record the
landmark Mardi Gras Indian album ``The Wild Tchoupitoulas,'' their
individual history reaches back to the '50s and '60s when
keyboardist and singer Art and vocalist Aaron were part of New
Orleans' vital R&AMP;B scene, and saxophonist Charles was playing jazz.
</P>
<P>
   But once they began blending the rich Caribbean, blues and R&AMP;B
roots of the Crescent City, the Nevilles created a sound like none
other, funky yet ethereal. And though the Nevilles have yet to
reach the top of the pop charts as a family band, they have a
following wherever they go.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first started out with the Neville Brothers we were
just doing it because we wanted to,'' Aaron Neville said before a
recent concert at the Myrtle Beach House of Blues. ``Now it is the
way we make our living.''
</P>
<P>
   The family band's latest CD, ``Valance Street,'' reaches back to
the brothers' childhood experiences in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valance Street means a coming together of family because that
is where we grew up,'' Neville said. ``And if it wasn't family we'd
go our own ways, but we have a bond and we're always gonna do stuff
together.''
</P>
<P>
   That bond can be best felt in the live shows of both the Allman
Brothers Band and the Neville Brothers. When these groups perform
there is an intensity stronger than sibling rivalry, a primal kind
of communication and a commitment that far surpasses the fickleness
of the pop music world. Like family they are anchors, holding true
to their musical beliefs and taking in fans even if they have no
place else to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
