<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATA-STARTUPS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING OPPORTUNITY IN THE GLOBAL DESIRE FOR ADVANCED DATA
SERVICES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Mass., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EATONTOWN, N.J. _ By the door to his disheveled office in a
thoroughly standard office park, Satish Sharma has posted a form
letter he received a few months ago from the Katharine Gibbs
School.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Year 2000, what will you be doing?'' the letter reads.
``What kind of job will you be working in?''
</P>
<P>
   Among a list of occupations for which the school offers
training, Sharma has wryly highlighted a few: ``Executive
assisting,'' ``Legal executive assisting,'' ``Computer technical
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Since founding Tachion Networks in 1996, Sharma, now 42, has
performed all those jobs _ and more. He has even served as cook.
For two years before moving into the office here in central New
Jersey, Sharma made Indian food at lunch and dinner most days for
the dozen people toiling in the basement of his home in Asbury
Park.
</P>
<P>
   If Tachion was yet another hardscrabble Internet start-up, there
would be nothing unusual about any of this. But instead of
marketing plans and ``dot-com'' addresses, Tachion deals in circuit
boards and industrial-grade systems. Instead of MBAs and
20-something code jockeys, Tachion is stocked with middle-aged
engineers _ some immigrants from abroad, some self-imposed exiles
from Lucent Technologies' Bell Laboratories unit, some both.
</P>
<P>
   They think they have come up with something at least as flashy
as the latest e-commerce site. Later this month, Tachion intends to
announce that it has developed what it calls a ``collapsed central
office,'' an integrated communications system that can allow
carriers to switch and transport both phone calls and different
data formats in a fraction of the space required for traditional
communications gear.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast Corp., the cable television giant, and MCI Worldcom, the
long-distance carrier, have agreed to try the new system.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred on by lush capital markets and the voracious global
appetite for advanced data services, quite a few new companies like
Tachion are vying to supply the new technologies underlying the
blending of computers and telecommunications, even as they try to
avoid being crushed by titans like Lucent and Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   But the emergence of Tachion, with its core of ex-Bell Labs
engineers, may underline the beginning of a new trend. While many
Web companies have drawn talent from established enterprises in
computing and finance, the communications behemoths traditionally
have lost little of their intellectual capital to start-ups. There
are a few exceptions _ Newbridge Networks of Canada was founded by
former Nortel Networks executives _ but in general the established
giants of the communications equipment industry have not pollinated
many new players.
</P>
<P>
   That absence has been particularly striking in New Jersey.
Including Bell Labs, AT&AMP;T Corp. and Science Applications
International Corp.'s Telcordia unit (formerly Bellcore, the
research unit for the Baby Bell local phone companies), many
thousands of communications engineers are at work in New Jersey.
But New Jersey has hardly become a hotbed of technology
giant-killers along the lines of Silicon Valley and Route 128 near
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   One reason, perhaps, that New Jersey may not have fostered as
many spinoffs is that AT&AMP;T, for all its struggles, managed to avoid
the mass layoffs and bankruptcies that hit minicomputer leaders in
the Boston area like Data General, Digital Equipment and Prime
Computer in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Jersey hasn't gone through the forest fire we had here in
Massachusetts,'' said Daniel Smith, chief executive of Sycamore
Networks Inc., an optical networking company in Chelmsford, Mass.
``The forest was burnt, but then a lot of green shoots started
coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is now home to at least a dozen highly regarded
communications equipment start-ups. ``New Jersey doesn't have that
yet,'' Smith said. ``It's dominated by large companies, and the
people there haven't seen how to do it, how to start a company in
this industry.''
</P>
<P>
   That situation may change in a hurry if Tachion, with its base
in Monmouth County, and the handful of other recent New Jersey
communications upstarts succeed, and if the Tachion team eventually
reaps millions from a public stock offering. Those thousands of
engineers still inside the mothership may start getting ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucent in this county alone has 20,000 engineers,'' Sharma
said in an interview, with perhaps a touch of hyperbole. ``Lucent
has very bright people, but it has been mismanaged, mismanaged
extensively, and the people don't think they can leave to start
their own company.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors who have doubled, tripled or quadrupled their money by
investing in Lucent since that company was spun off from AT&AMP;T in
late 1996 would probably disagree with Sharma's assessment of
Lucent management. But given Sharma's particular experience, his
frustration is understandable.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma still remembers the employee number he received when he
joined Bell Labs in 1985: 116825. He emigrated from India in 1981,
and after stints designing blood analysis equipment for a small
company in Westchester County, N.Y., and postal scales for Pitney
Bowes in Connecticut, he joined Bell Labs to help design medical
imaging systems. By the early 1990s he was helping develop software
for microchips to be used for a new communications protocol called
asynchronous transfer mode, or ATM.
</P>
<P>
   Though Internet protocol, or IP, has become a buzzword known
even to casual technophiles, ATM is forming the core of most new
networks being built by giant communications carriers like AT&AMP;T and
Sprint Corp. Like IP, ATM splits communications into small pieces.
But unlike IP, which creates data packets of varying length, ATM
generally creates data cells of uniform size. That uniformity,
coupled with ATM's ability to create ``virtual circuits'' that can
enhance reliability, can be a powerful advantage because it allows
ATM to carry voice, video and data traffic together without
sacrificing much efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Together with AT&AMP;T's (later Lucent's) microelectronics unit,
Bell Labs created perhaps the leading ATM chipset, the Atlanta.
This chipset was so good, in fact, that it was used by the upstart
Ascend Communications Inc. to turn itself into a world leader in
the ATM industry.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent did a great job of developing the core technology in the
chips, but it did an awful job of moving it from the laboratory to
the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just being good at making the chips doesn't make you good at
the system piece,'' said Daniel Stanzione, president of Bell Labs
and executive vice president of Lucent. ``What was then part of
AT&AMP;T focused on the wrong segment of the market, the very high end,
instead of the Internet and companies that were looking to support
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, Lucent agreed to acquire Ascend for $20
billion. But, frustrated by Lucent's troubles in spinning ATM
technology into ATM products, Sharma had already left, departing
shortly after Lucent's split from AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said there is a great opportunity to build a product to
address the convergence of data and voice and Lucent is not the
place to do it,'' Sharma said. ``So I decided to do it in the
basement.''
</P>
<P>
   Isolated from Silicon Valley's venture capital community, Sharma
put almost all of his savings, $250,000, into his new endeavor. At
first, it did not seem an auspicious decision. About a week after
Sharma quit his job, his father was hospitalized with brain trauma.
He died a few months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first few months I spent the days in the basement and
the nights at the hospital,'' Sharma said.
</P>
<P>
   But he was not alone in the basement for long. Soon after
starting Tachion, he was joined by Sunil Malhotra, a Bell Labs
colleague and former Bellcore engineer, who is now vice president
for software engineering at Tachion. A few months later, John
Kolchmeyer, another Bell Labs engineer, joined the company. And by
the spring of 1997 about a half-dozen people were working in
Sharma's basement.
</P>
<P>
   By last summer, however, Sharma was borrowing cash to keep
Tachion afloat. Driving home from an unsuccessful meeting with a
potential investor in New York, he thought he might have to fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very difficult,'' Sharma said recently about
starting his company in New Jersey. All of the venture capitalists
are in California, he said, ``and they have too much money and not
enough time, and if they can fund three companies locally they
don't want to spend all this time out of the office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A bunch of VCs told me, `Move to California and we'll fund you
tomorrow,''' Sharma said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanzione, the Bell Labs president, says that experience is
common. ``In California, not only the corporate cultures and the
regional cultures are different, but also the infrastructure was
really in place for start-ups,'' he said. ``You can rent a PR
person for two days. You can get a patent attorney for a day. And
of course you're close to a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharma found salvation right after his failed meeting when he
received a phone call from an ``angel investor,'' Raj Singh,
chairman of Stratumone Communications Inc., a networking company in
Santa Clara, Calif. By the end of the day, Singh had agreed to wire
Sharma $100,000. Singh, whose company has since agreed to be
acquired by Cisco, soon persuaded Raj Parekh, a former vice
president at Sun Microsystems Inc., to contribute another $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged, perhaps, by the angels, venture capitalists
eventually came through. In exchange for roughly 50 percent of the
company, Tachion has received about $8 million from Walden
International Investment Group and Morgenthaler Ventures. Perhaps
as important, Tachion got an experienced executive, Jeff Matros,
45, to run the company.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Walden last summer, Matros was vice president for
marketing and business development for the data communications
group of Siemens AG, the German conglomerate. Matros helped Sharma
search for a chief executive for a few months before he was asked
to take the job himself. As the company prepares to introduce its
product, he is raising an additional $30 million. (Sharma is now
senior vice president for engineering.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, any new investors will want to see results from
Tachion's trials with MCI Worldcom and Comcast. But the real target
market for Tachion's product is new local communications carriers
that do not have the money or space for truckloads of equipment
from traditional providers.
</P>
<P>
   Tachion says its product is particularly appealing because it
provides a combination of software and hardware design that allows
it to handle multiple communications systems within one
modest-sized chassis. Among other companies trying to develop
similar systems are Taqua Systems in Centerville, Mass.; Transmedia
Communications, which recently agreed to be acquired by Cisco, and
Castle Networks, which has agreed to be acquired by Siemens.
</P>
<P>
   In building products that can do so much, companies like Tachion
have to remain focused on making their products reliable and able
to connect seamlessly to older systems.
</P>
<P>
   John Sidgmore, vice chairman of MCI Worldcom, refused to comment
on Tachion. Speaking generally, he said: ``This isn't as true
today, but people were always worried about having the fastest
hardware, and in the end of the day the hardware isn't as important
as the software. We don't want to manage a bunch of little science
projects that are the fastest.''
</P>
<P>
   Another potential pitfall is that technology companies sometimes
begin to suffer what some military strategists call mission creep,
with new features being added to a product helter-skelter.
</P>
<P>
   Tachion's executives say, however, that they have remained
focused by using only proven components in their system. ``The
world is our competition,'' Sharma said. ``We have to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
