<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-STEPHENSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPHENSON SEEKS CLOSURE TO A SUCCESSFUL CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUTTON, Mass. _ A throng of golfers crowded the Pleasant Valley
practice range at mid-day, whacking balls under the hot sun. As
time wore on, the group began to dissipate, until one swung alone,
giving the impression she had no plans to leave anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Stephenson is on a chase. She is trying to track down a
sense of closure.
</P>
<P>
   Hers has been a most-successful golf career, one that has placed
her among the most popular athletes in any professional sport, one
that has been highlighted with triumphs over setbacks and
disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Stephenson won a tournament was in 1987. She is
competing in this week's areaWEB.com Challenge with the same
purpose she has had at every tourney she has entered since: to win
one more title. Only then would she be able to walk away from the
pro circuit with what she believes is the perfect epilogue to a
storybook career.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's first round, the 48-year-old Australian fired a
4-under-par 68 to place her among the leaders. Then it was off to
practice area, where she is usually among the last to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work so hard because I want that one win. I am probably more
hungry for a win than anyone out there,'' said Stephenson, who
bogeyed the third hole then came back to eagle the fourth and
birdie the fifth. She missed an 8-foot eagle putt on 11 (birdie)
and birdied 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (eagle) just turned around my round,'' Stephenson said.
``I started playing like I normally do. I played well from there in
and on the back nine; I was really steady.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a little frustrating,'' said Stephenson about the
season. ``I feel like I haven't scored as well as I've played. So
today was kind of nice to get off to a bad start and then bring it
back. I feel like I'm so close (to winning a tournament). That's
why I came.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson began her pro career in 1974 and won three majors in
the 1980s _ the LPGA Championship (1982), the du Maurier Classic
(formerly the Peter Jackson Classic) in 1981, and the US Women's
Open (1983). She became one of the most popular players in golf,
becoming the first woman pro to design golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   Then her career was hit with setbacks. In 1990, she was mugged
while attending a Phoenix Suns basketball game in Miami. The mugger
broke her ring finger in two places. She came back to play in 13
tournaments afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Her 1987 season was hampered by a car accident early in the
year, but she came back to win three times that season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone keeps saying, `I can't believe you haven't written a
book yet all the things that have happened,' things I have done,''
said Stephenson, who produced an exercise video for people with
arthritis which sold 100,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been times when I say, `This year, I'll get the Ben
Hogan award because I've fought back from injuries,' and I don't
get it. So I say, `OK, when I win a tournament.' For one thing, it
will mean so much to me personally. It would mean more to me than
anything I've ever won _ even the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because, I mean, I've had horrible injuries, and I keep coming
back. I think that would make it all worth while. I've worked
really hard because I really want that one win. That would be
closure, in all aspects in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she would give up golf after winning a tournament,
Stephenson said, ``I'd give up full time, yeah. Because I've put a
lot of work into this. I don't do a lot of much else. I've just
worked so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson said she is merely hoping to remain healthy in the
meantime because ``I can't come back from any more.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest Stephenson has come this year to winning was fourth
place at the Hawaiian Ladies Open in February and a tie for sixth
at the Giant Eagle LPGA Classic two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to ruin my whole life or career if I don't''
gain the victory, said Stephenson. ``I can't do that, because that
would put too much pressure on me. But people who know me know how
much it will mean to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite having not won a tournament in 12 years, Stephenson is
still among the most popular names in women's golf and still
receives fan mail.
</P>
<P>
   Although she said she enjoys the notoriety, she said other young
players, particularly last week's du Maurier Classic winner Karrie
Webb, should now be household names similar to women's players in
other sports. She said more must be done to market such players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frustrating part to me is that there are so many neat
personalities out here and young girls who are incredibly
talented,'' said Stephenson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say our marketing staff (isn't) doing a good
job, but there has to be some way for the public to learn how neat
those girls are. Just like the girls in soccer. The average person
knows who Mia Hamm is and they don't know who Karrie Webb is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
