<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-BAENA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAENA DISAPPOINTS IN FIRST ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUTTON, Mass. _ Even in leaving college early, Marisa Baena said
she was late. ``My father wanted me to turn pro after my first year
(at the University of Arizona). But I told him I wasn't ready.''
</P>
<P>
   So last summer, when she opted to turn pro and skip her senior
year, all Baena was doing was sticking to the plan _ albeit two
years behind schedule. The young lady from Pereira, Columbia, has
been groomed for a professional golf career since . . . well, since
as far back as she can remember.
</P>
<P>
   The plan called for a move to the United States to complete high
school. Check.
</P>
<P>
   The plan called for her to improve her English. Check.
</P>
<P>
   The plan called for a brilliant amateur career. US Women's
Amateur finalist, NCAA champion, first-team All-America. Triple
check.
</P>
<P>
   The plan called for a smooth transition into the pro game. Call
it a work in progress, though Baena is a bit harder on herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell the truth, I'm disappointed,'' said Baena, just two
months removed from her 22d birthday. ``It's been a little bit
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   It was tough again Thursday in the first round of the
areaWEB.com Challenge at Pleasant Valley CC. Though her impressive
talents shined through for most of the morning, Baena turned what
should have been a decent round into something disappointing,
making double bogeys at the par-3 seventh and par-4 17th. A 70 or
71 was, instead, a 3-over 75, and she is in danger of missing the
cut for the seventh time in nine starts.
</P>
<P>
   Baena concedes the learning experience has been tougher than she
figured, but just as the Friday departures have piled up, the
confidence has not left her. Though she has cashed two checks for a
grand total of $10,967, Baena is not yet making reservations for
Qualifying School this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hitting it pretty good. There are five or six tournaments
left and I feel I have it in my bag,'' she said with just a hint of
cockiness that great golfers must have.
</P>
<P>
   The man carrying the bag thinks so, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has great talent,'' said Ralph DelVecchio, who usually
caddies for Stefania Croce. But she is in Europe preparing for the
Women's British Open, so DelVecchio and Baena have teamed up, just
as they did at the Jamie Farr Kroger Classic a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   That was a successful effort, one of the two cuts Baena has
made, but DelVecchio thinks there are plenty more in the young
woman's future. Just as soon as she believes in herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Toldeo, we were in the next-to-last group and she was
hitting balls on the range with Karrie Webb, Meg Mallon, Kelly
Robbins, Dottie Pepper. She said, `I'm scared. I'm going to throw
up.' It's a growing experience,'' said DelVecchio.
</P>
<P>
   Baena didn't throw up that day, but she did blow up, shooting 75
and fading from one shot off the lead to a tie for 21st. ``I keep
telling her she's a good putter,'' DelVecchio said, ``but she
doesn't know it.''
</P>
<P>
   At just a shade over 5 feet tall, Baena would not appear to be
capable of hitting it long enough to play at this level. But
indeed, length is no problem. Constantly she was 20-30 yards ahead
of Laurie Rinker-Graham and Donna Wilkins, ``about 250 yards
consistently,'' said DelVecchio.
</P>
<P>
   What is a problem, said Baena, are the bad holes. Like the
395-yard 17th where her 5-iron approach started right, just as she
likes. It was beginning to draw when it hit a tree and splashed
into the water that guards the green.
</P>
<P>
   Making the turn to the front, Baena birdied the par-5 fourth to
get back to just 1-over. At the 134-yard seventh, ``I thought I hit
a good shot, but I guess not,'' said Baena of the shot that went
splash.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed, yes. But certainly not discouraged. She bombed
drives on her final two holes, the eighth and ninth, and had great
birdie chances at each. The first rolled over the right edge; the
next one stopped a roll short.
</P>
<P>
   Each time she hung her head, but each time she picked it up and
flashed a smile, trying to rationalize the pain that is golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much luck is involved. I got a lot of breaks as an amateur,
but not as a pro. What can I tell you. I'm trying, I'm really
trying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
