<HEADLINE>
BUSH DENIES INVOLVEMENT IN FIRING OF FUNERAL COMMISSION DIRECTOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush on Thursday formally denied
involvement in the February firing of the highest-ranking regulator
of the Texas funeral industry.
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general filed a motion to nullify a subpoena
seeking to force Bush to testify in the whistle-blower lawsuit
filed by the ousted director of the Texas Funeral Service
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   An Aug. 30 hearing in a Travis County district court has been
set to sort out the complex allegations. Former commission director
Eliza May claims she was wrongly fired _ with Bush's blessing _
after she aggressively pursued allegations against Houston-based
Service Corp. International, the world's largest provider of
funeral services.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, SCI officials and Bush, who is not a defendant,
contend she was not targeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never asked anyone to take a role or to become involved
in any way in this investigation, or any dispute arising from it,
or given direction to anyone who might be involved in the SCI
investigation or dispute,'' said Bush's affidavit signed July 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no personal knowledge of relevant facts of the
investigation, nor do I have any personal knowledge of relevant
facts concerning any dispute arising from this investigation,'' the
presidential candidate said.
</P>
<P>
   On July 7, Bush was subpoenaed by May to give an oral deposition
Aug. 26. But in his motion filed Thursday by Attorney General John
Cornyn, the deposition was described as unnecessary, onerous and
``sought purely for purposes of harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said that May ``cannot show that the governor has unique
or superior knowledge which cannot be obtained through less
intrusive means. In fact, the only evidence before this court
clearly demonstrates that there was no personal involvement in this
matter on the part of Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn asked the court for a protective order to require a
judge's approval before any more subpoenas are delivered to Bush.
Cornyn said Bush and his staff ``have already responded to
approximately 250 document requests in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bush and his top aides were handed another subpoena
commanding them to produce several records related to May's ouster.
The lengthy subpoena seeks 61 types of documents in an effort to
tie Bush to the dismissal of May to appease political supporters
who worked for SCI.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the governor avoids direct questioning, his top aides
could still be required to submit to questioning and may have to
produce notes, letters, reports, memos and e-mail mentioning May's
dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   In her lawsuit against the state and SCI, filed under the Texas
Whistle Blowers Act, May alleged that Bush and his staff pressured
the commission to fire her because of her scrutiny of two Dallas
area funeral homes affiliated with SCI. May claimed workers at the
two homes were embalming bodies without having proper licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Her attorneys are seeking access to any schedules and written
communications generated by meetings among Bush staff, SCI
officials, SCI lobbyists and Sen. John Whitmire, D-Houston, who
interceded in the regulatory dispute. May's attorney, Charles
Herring Jr., asked that the records be produced Aug. 20.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier subpoena to Bush and his staff demanded phone records
that could relate to SCI discussions. Herring also requested
campaign finance records that would show how much money Bush
received from a long list of SCI executives and investors.
</P>
<P>
   Bush received $35,000 in 1996-97 from SCI chairman Robert
Waltrip, and several other executives donated $1,000 or less to
Bush in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   SCI's initial legal response said it did not precipitate May's
firing. The company attributed her dismissal, in part, to a ``loss
of trust and confidence in her ability to lead the commission'' and
cited documents indicating May had planned to leave her post
voluntarily anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It also said she was being criticized for failing to collect
fees, not adequately supervising staff and contributing to ``a
constant exodus of employees,'' according to court filings.
</P>
<P>
   Further, SCI's response to May's suit said that she
``spearheaded an ill-advised, unfounded prosecution of SCI. Her
tactics included the issuance of overbroad subpoenas of dubious
legality; an oppressive and intimidating unannounced raid of SCI's
facilities on Good Friday; and other abusive tactics never before
seen at the Texas Funeral Service Commission.''
</P>
<P>
   May contends in her lawsuit that she was fired after she
``repeatedly reported violations of the law involving the
commission, commissioners, SCI ... Waltrip and SCI affiliates and
involving Gov. George W. Bush and his staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Hired Aug. 1, 1996 and fired Feb. 8, 1999, May claimed she began
fearing for her life in April 1998 when an SCI-affiliated funeral
home worker, who was being investigated for embalming without a
license, made a telephone threat to ``kill all of you'' at the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, SCI chairman Waltrip complained to May and
Bush chief of staff Joe Allbaugh about the tenor of the Dallas area
investigations. Those contacts coincided with Whitmire's efforts to
resolve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In late summer 1998, the saga took a mysterious turn. That's
when May claims she was told by friends that SCI was using a
private investigator ``to dig up dirt'' on her. That's also when an
unidentified man tried to gain unauthorized entry to the commission
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 3, 1998, the commission issued its findings regarding
the SCI facilities in question, one in Dallas and one in Hurst. It
assessed a $450,000 fine against SCI _ a penalty that SCI is still
seeking to challenge in an administrative hearing. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But that dispute is on hold. On Sept. 1, the commission _
harshly criticized by legislators during their session last spring
_ will be reconstituted from a funeral industry-dominated
nine-member board to a six-member panel dominated by non-industry
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
