   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CUT (Washington) _ Inviting a presidential veto, the House
and Senate approve a $792 billion tax-cut package spread out over
10 years of anticipated budget surpluses. The Republican leaders
who crafted the deal hail the votes. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SPYING (Washington) _ A congressional reports says a
string of ``baffling decisions'' by Attorney General Janet Reno and
Justice Department officials stifled the FBI's investigation into
possible Chinese espionage and may have prevented investigators
from catching a nuclear spy. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   RENO-IMMIGRANTS (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno says
she will meet with Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, who is pushing for
more information about illegal immigrants with criminal records who
are temporarily detained in the United States. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENTIAL-MEDAL (Washington) _ Lloyd Bentsen, a former
Treasury secretary and senator from Texas, has been selected along
with former Presidents Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter to receive the
Presidential Medal of Freedom, the nation's highest civilian honor.
By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (West Des Moines, Iowa) _ Gov. George W. Bush rallies
Republicans to his side in the upcoming Ames, Iowa, straw poll,
thanking those who already support him and exhorting the others
``not to work too hard'' for other candidates. Bush also meets with
three dozen Hispanic leaders who asked the presidential candidate
about immigration and affirmative action. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON (Tonawanda, N.Y.) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton,
drawing on the nightmarish stories of teen-agers' lives in a nearby
inner city, urges Americans to tune out violent TV programs and
help combat youth violence to transform troubled teen-agers into
the productive tax-paying citizens needed to sustain the Social
Security system for the retiring baby boom generation. By STEWART
M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON-POLL (Albany, N.Y.) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton's
approval rating among women in New York has surged since publicly
addressing her husband's infidelities, according to a new poll. By
LARA JAKES. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-PAY (Austin, Texas) _ Texas public school teachers are
heading back to the classroom in the next couple of weeks with the
highest across-the-board pay raise in the nation, one teacher group
says. Despite the $3,000 increase the Texas Legislature mandated,
teachers are still likely to remain below the national average wage
paid to educators. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   LUFTWAFFE-FLIGHTS (San Antonio) _ American and German fighter
pilots will not be conducting low-level, high-speed training
flights over a course that stretches 800 miles from New Mexico to
the Big Bend region of Texas, according to a settlement reached
between the Air Force and five Texas ranchers. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   FETUS-FIGHT (Houston) _ A court hearing may make it clearer
whether a woman who may be brain-dead will continue to be kept on
life support in order to let her fetus survive. A man who claims to
be the biological father of the fetus seeks to be declared the
common-law husband of the woman in order to have more say in
whether to keep her on life support. The woman's parents want the
woman and baby to be allowed to die. By RON NISSIMOV.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-SUBPOENA (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush, seeking to
avoid testifying in a whistleblower lawsuit, formally denies
involvement in the February firing of the highest ranking regulator
of the Texas funeral industry. By JOHN W. GONZALEZ. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The House Judiciary Committee
recently cleared a measure that would allow television cameras in
federal courtrooms; a similar bill is also pending in the Senate.
This is a good idea long overdue, but judges have been reluctant to
let the sun shine on court proceedings. The biggest holdout is the
U.S. Supreme Court; not one justice wants to let cameras watch them
work. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ Right-handed pitcher Shane Reynolds helps
the Houston Astros shut out the Los Angeles Dodgers 7-0 in the
Astrodome. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
