A7380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-NUKE-NYT &LR;      08-05 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA ESPIONAGE INQUIRY WAS PLAGUED BY MANY MISTAKES, SENATE REPORT
SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government's investigation into how China got
American nuclear weapons secrets was plagued by widespread mistakes
and misjudgments but there was no political interference, according
to the two ranking members of a Senate committee that held closed
hearings on the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The two senators issued a 32-page critique, the most detailed
public examination of how the Energy Department, the Justice
Department and the FBI handled the investigation into the apparent
disclosure of design information on America's most sophisticated
nuclear warhead, the W-88.
</P>
<P>
   There were ``no heroes'' and a ``shocking lack of thoroughness,
competence and urgency'' in the investigation, said Sen. Joseph I.
Lieberman, D-Conn., and the ranking minority member on the Senate
Governmental Affairs Committee, which held 13 hours of hearings on
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., and chairman of the committee,
expressed displeasure at the management of the Justice Department
under Attorney General Janet Reno. At a briefing on Thursday with
Lieberman, he questioned why Reno ``was out of the loop'' on such
an important investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The senators' findings could prove to be a mixed blessing for
Wen Ho Lee, the former scientist at the Los Alamos National
Laboratory who has been the chief suspect in the case. He was
dismissed by the Energy Department last March.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, the report questions why investigators focused
so quickly on Lee and his wife, Sylvia, even though there was no
direct evidence linking them to the transfer of W-88 design
secrets. But the report also discloses new information about the
Lees that led the FBI to believe they might be improperly involved
in helping China.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the couple have said they have done nothing wrong,
and Lee, in an interview on ``60 Minutes'' on CBS, suggested that
he was picked out because he was the only Asian-American in the
weapons design group. In the interview, Lee said he had spent the
``best years of my life'' trying to strengthen the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the Lees did not return a telephone call on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the Justice Department does not have sufficient
evidence to bring espionage charges in the case, but they also said
the department is weighing whether to indict Lee for transferring
large archives of classified data to an unprotected computer
system.
</P>
<P>
   A key problem for the government is the difficulty prosecutors
face in keeping classified information from being exposed if they
bring an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said in his CBS interview that the transfers were routine,
but Energy Secretary Bill Richardson dismissed that as ``pure
bunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno, in a meeting with reporters on Thursday, declined to
discuss Lee's case. She defended the department's handling of the
matter but also said that her lawyers should have pursued the case
with the FBI and that procedures are now in place to insure better
coordination.
</P>
<P>
   John Collingwood, a spokesman for the FBI, said: ``We accept the
criticisms concerning the early portions of this investigation.
Director Louis J. Freeh has reacted in a massive way to the
shortcomings apparent from this case.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, the Energy Department had determined that it was highly
likely that China had illegally obtained W-88 secrets. Though other
parts of the government had access to the W-88 information,
investigators focused on Los Alamos, where the weapon was designed
and where Lee and his wife worked.
</P>
<P>
   Taking such a narrow approach was the beginning of a ``tragedy
of errors,'' Lieberman said; by focusing solely on Lee, he said,
investigators may be missing unknown American officials still
spying for China. But, he noted, if Lee was responsible, he was
allowed to stay in his sensitive job for two years after coming
under suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   The next error, according to the senators, was the failure of a
Los Alamos counterintelligence official to supply accurate
information about access to Lee's computer. The FBI was told that
Lee had not signed a form permitting access. The bureau was also
told his computer did not contain a notice on the monitor warning
about the lack of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Both assertions were wrong, but the FBI agent did not pursue the
matter, the senators found.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997, the bureau sought Justice Department approval to
secretly monitor Lee. They had no direct evidence of espionage. But
their evidence, according to the senators, did include these items:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Deceptive answers'' by Lee in 1984 in another espionage
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lee's admission in 1984 that he had passed unclassified
information to a foreign government, contrary to government
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   _ An FBI lead in the 1990s that ``could be reasonably
interpreted to indicate that Lee had provided significant
assistance'' to China.
</P>
<P>
   _ Close contacts between Sylvia Lee and Chinese scientists, and
Lee's aggressive efforts to act as an interpreter for a visiting
Chinese scientific delegation ``despite his inability to perform
this function very effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Department officials were not persuaded, and the
request to monitor Lee was never approved. They thought the
evidence was too dated and asked the bureau to take a closer look
at other suspects, according to testimony before the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The senators faulted the FBI for waiting 18 months to get back
to the Justice Department and found it ``remarkable'' that the
director, Freeh, never contacted Reno about such an important case.
</P>
<P>
   But the senators were also critical of the Justice Department.
They thought the department's denial of the bureau's request for
monitoring was wrong, though defensible. They asked why crucial
records were missing. And they also found it ``remarkable'' that
officials never personally engaged Reno in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The senators said that they were still studying the issue, but
that they hoped the relevant agencies could hold officials
accountable for the mistakes. Internal inquiries are under way at
the various departments, which could lead to disciplinary actions.
</P>
<P>
   Brooke Anderson, the Energy Department spokeswoman, said that
Secretary Richardson would soon take disciplinary action to address
the mistakes, and that Thursday's report ``validates the importance
of many of the reforms we've already undertaken to strengthen
counterintelligence and security.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson dismissed Lee earlier this year for security
violations. According to the senators, Lee failed a polygraph test
last February that included questions about whether he had given
nuclear weapons data or W-88 information to any unauthorized
person. While they declined to say whether Lee had given deceptive
answers to those particular questions, an American intelligence
official said Lee's answers were deceptive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
