<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-MUSIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS TO BUY INTO WEB MUSIC CRAZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lycos Inc. plans to announce a $38.8 million acquisition Friday,
based on a surprising traffic pattern it says it has noticed lately
on its Internet search engine: Music is more popular than sex.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the digital music format known as MP3 has become
the term most often used in requests to the Lycos search engine,
said Ron Sege, executive vice president of the Waltham, Mass.
Internet portal firm.
</P>
<P>
   Sex was the traditional leader, Sege said, but Lycos has been
building up its music-oriented section lately because of the shift
in interest. Lycos will detail plans to issue 1.1 million
additional shares of its stock to acquire closely-held Internet
Music Distribution Inc. of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos may make additional payments to Internet Music, based on
the popularity of the company's music-playing software, known as
Sonique. It allows Internet users to download music files from Web
sites and play them on their personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos will give away Sonique through free downloads, but hopes
the software will help boost the popularity of its music-oriented
Web sites and draw in more viewers and advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was introduced several weeks ago, Sonique has become
the second-most popular MP3 player on the Internet, according to
the C-Net news service; as of last late Thursday, had been
downloaded 75,987 times this week alone.
</P>
<P>
   Sonique competes with other software products such as Winamp,
whose maker, Nullsoft Inc., was recently acquired by America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   The deals reflect the increased use of the Internet as a music
distribution channel, said Al-Riaz Adatia, one of four young
cofounders of Internet Music in California who plan to join Lycos
to develop the service.
</P>
<P>
   Sege said the acquisition will complement the Lycos radio
programming service, introduced in April.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Lycos rose 2 3/8 to close at 35 15/16 in Nasdaq
trading Thursday, giving the Internet Music deal an initial value
of $38.8 million. Approximately 45 million shares of Lycos stock
now are outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Lycos said the on-line news service Salon.com will
provide editorial content for its Lycos.com Web site. Terms weren't
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Salon.com said the Salon-Lycos cobranded area will carry content
from several of Salon.com's 10 original content sites, including
Salon News, Salon Books, and Salon Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Salon Books, which includes author interviews and daily reviews,
will be the first site to provide content as part of the Lycos
Entertainment Web Guide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
