<HEADLINE>
ISMAIL'S INJURY SEEN AS `MINOR'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Clarence E. Hill Jr. and Ray Buck 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ A day after wide receiver Raghib Ismail
suffered a sprained left shoulder, Cowboys coach Chan Gailey was
still looking on the bright side.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said Ismail, listed as day-to-day, is getting treatment
and should be back to full speed in a week or so. He missed last
night's Blue-White scrimmage and will miss Monday's preseason
opener against the Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   And while Ismail said that the injury is a setback, he said
``it's just a minor problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It always sets you back a bit because he's not getting an
opportunity to work with \Rquarterback\S Troy \RAikman\S,'' Gailey
said. ``That's something you always like. But if we were talking
about a three-week or four-week deal, then we would be talking
about a real problem. This is just a minor problem.''
\Nsubheds:Gailey's sees progress
</P>
<P>
   Much of has been made of the Cowboys' being more comfortable in
Gailey's offense this year as opposed to last season.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the difference has manifested itself at training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we talk about things, we talk about where someone should
be and where they run their routes,'' Gailey said. ``We are all on
the same page. We have gone through and seen what it should look
like. When we first started everybody had in their own mind how it
should look like. Now we are much more of the same mind on a pass
pattern, a running play or a blocking scheme should look like. That
just helps everybody's comfort level.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the Cowboys coaches are spending most of their time
teaching the new guys, ``which is how it should be.''
\Nsubheds:Lafleur to return Injured tight end David LaFleur, who is
recovering from back and ankle surgery, should start running pass
routes this weekend, Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gailey said LeFleur likely won't seen any full-time
action until the third preseason game against the New England
Patriots on Aug. 21. Stepnoski 6-for-9 Center Mark Stepnoski
returns to the Cowboys after a four-year stint with the
Houston//Tennessee Oilers-turned-Titans. Between Emmitt Smith and
Eddie George, Stepnoski has blocked for an NFL top-five running
back in six of his nine pro seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, there's a big difference \Rbetween Smith and
George\S. That's apparent to everyone,'' Stepnoski said. ``Not that
Emmitt is weak and not that Eddie is slow, but you have two
different packages. Look at their body sizes. Yet, they both have
all the superlative traits to be great running backs.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepnoski made the Pro Bowl five consecutive years from 1993
through 1997 _ three with the Cowboys, two with the then-Oilers.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
