</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-CONGRESS-410&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL CONFERENCE ON GUN CONTROL BREAKS FOR RECESS WITHOUT A
COMPROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mass., Mo., S.D., Utah) (rk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate and House lawmakers on a conference that is
expected to hammer out new gun control legislation held their first
meeting Thursday, only to postpone the bulk of their work until
they return on Sept. 7 from a monthlong congressional recess.
</P>
<P>
   The decision meant that most schoolchildren would return to
classes before the enactment of any of the new restrictions on
firearms that began to be debated in the aftermath of the massacre
at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., on April 20.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the conference said that this was inexcusable, and
offered a motion that lawmakers on the conference work into the
recess, which begins Friday, to reach a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Democrats knew would happen, Republicans rejected this.
Republicans accused Democrats of vacuous grandstanding and said the
issue of gun control was too volatile and sensitive to be handled
with haste.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an easy, itty-bitty thing to do,'' said Sen. Orrin
Hatch R-Utah, the chairman of the conference, which is expected to
iron out the differences in different juvenile crime bills that
passed the Senate and the House.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill included an array of gun control provisions. The
House bill technically had none, but its members did approve
several new restrictions on firearms before a final package of
those measures was defeated, largely by Democrats who were
protesting the relative weakness of that package in comparison with
the Senate legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are wide differences here,'' Hatch said at the
conference Thursday. ``I don't know how you bridge these
differences, but it's going to take time.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said that lawmakers _ and, more specifically,
America's children _ did not have that luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is only 11 days before the students at Columbine return to
school,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., who is one of the
five Senators on the conference. ``The inability of Congress to act
more quickly on this important legislation is shameful.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference earlier, President Clinton, Senate Minority
Leader Thomas Daschle of South Dakota and House Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt of Missouri all assailed Republicans for the
absence of gun control legislation. Clinton later issued a
statement urging lawmakers on the conference to stay in Washington
and meet during the recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's show our children that when it comes to their safety,
Washington will not take a break,'' the president said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This full-court press underscored Democrats' continued
confidence that most Americans share the party's advocacy of more
stringent gun control, and it signaled that many Democrats would
devote considerable oratory to the issue in their home districts
over the recess.
</P>
<P>
   But they will not be the only ones using the many weeks before
any final disposition of the gun debate to try to rally opinion to
their side.
</P>
<P>
   James Jay Baker, chief lobbyist for the National Rifle
Association, said that the organization would probably spend at
least as much on lobbying and advertising in the coming months as
the $1.5 million it had poured into the gun control debate since
early May.
</P>
<P>
   The organization is particularly concerned about the
conference's handling of any measure to regulate gun shows that
approaches the strictness of a provision approved by the Senate.
That measure defined gun shows broadly, mandated all vendors _ not
just the 60 percent who are federally licensed dealers _ to conduct
background checks on customers and allowed three business days for
the completion of those checks.
</P>
<P>
   Although lawmakers in the House rejected this approach,
Democrats in both chambers have continued to insist that it be
included in whatever compromise legislation the conference
negotiates.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hatch and Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois, the senior House
Republican on the conference, said at a joint news conference
Thursday that this was both impossible and foolish, because it
would guarantee the failure of the legislation when it returns the
House for a new vote.
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde also suggested a willingness to craft something as
close to the Senate gun show provision as was politically feasible.
Possible alterations to that provision include a shortened period
for the completion of background checks and a narrower definition
of gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good beginning is the Senate bill,'' Hyde said. ``But it is
a beginning. As you know, compromise is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic advocates of gun control have yet to say just how
much of a dilution to the Senate gun show provision they will be
willing to accept and dodged questions about that at a news
conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Democrats' dilemma is that any gun show provision
would be attached to other restrictions on firearms, like child
safety devices on handguns and a prohibition on firearm ownership
by adults convicted of violent crimes as juveniles, which are
likely to emerge from the conference and that Democrats as well as
many Republicans want.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch has repeatedly accused Democrats of deliberately refusing
to compromise on sensible, meaningful legislation so that they can
stake what they believe to be the moral and political high ground.
He urged them not to do that when the conference resumes its work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not play for political points,'' Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the lawmakers themselves will not formally meet again
until the second week of September, Hatch instructed them to have
their staff members spend the time until then negotiating common
ground between the Senate and House juvenile crime bills so that
the conference can send compromise legislation back to the Senate
and House as soon after the recess as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
