<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7399 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-CUTS-HNS &LR;      08-05 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-CUTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP-CONTROLLED CONGRESS PASSES $792 BILLION TAX-CUT BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican-controlled Congress narrowly passed
a $792 billion tax-cut bill Thursday that is unlikely to survive
President Clinton's promised veto.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 221-206 in favor of the measure and the Senate
gave its approval by a slim margin of 50-49.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, the largest tax cut proposal since the 1981
reduction during the Reagan administration, would lower the five
income tax brackets by one percentage point over 10 years, cut the
capital gains tax for individuals, phase out the so-called death or
estate tax on property holdings and eliminate the ``marriage
penalty'' on couples who file jointly.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure is opposed by the president and most Democrats,
who say it could prove disastrous for the country if the $3
trillion in projected budget surpluses fails to materialize over
the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made that point Thursday morning during a Democratic
rally on Capitol Hill as he sought to build public support for
using most of the anticipated revenues to finance a Medicare
prescription drug reimbursement program, shore up Social Security
and pay down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Any left over, Clinton said, should be used to fund a modest tax
cut of $300 billion and to boost spending on education, defense and
other programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not be doing this until we figure out how we're
going to save Medicare, save Social Security and pay the debt
off,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When times are easy we are vulnerable to making our biggest
mistakes, and that is what this decision before us is about,''
Clinton said, referring to the GOP plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now what (Republicans) have said is, let's pass this big tax
cut first, make everybody happy tomorrow, and then we'll talk about
these long-term challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders plan to send the bill to Clinton in September
after Congress returns from its month-long recess, which begins
today. Polls show that most Americans appear to favor Clinton's
approach to handling the budget surplus. But GOP lawmakers are
hoping to change their minds with a heavy lobbying campaign that
they believe could force the president to sign their tax cut rather
than veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans held their own rally before the votes Thursday and
accused Clinton of ignoring ``the fine print'' in their bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Read the fine print. It's all there for America's working
people. That's who will benefit from this tax bill,'' said House
Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Archer ticked off a number of breaks that Americans, whether
low- or high-income earners, could expect to get from the bill,
including not only a reduction in rates but credits for education,
child adoption and care, retirement savings and home care for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   By gradually doubling the deduction for married couples alone,
he said, Americans could reap $150 billion in tax savings.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, the chief architect of the legislation, also said he was
``proud'' that the bill would eliminate the death tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ... not right ... when an individual dies to face the
undertaker and the IRS on the same day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill has so much good in it that we're going to go across
the country in August and we're going to let the American people
know, number one, it's their money, not Washington's money. And
they're going to get to keep more of it to spend the way they see
fit,`` the Texan said.
</P>
<P>
   He called the coming decision over whether to give taxpayers
``the right to spend their own money,'' as he put it, ``the
dividing line'' between Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the leading Republican presidential
candidate, picked up on that theme during a campaign appearance in
West Des Moines, Iowa. Saying he was ready to help Republican
lawmakers get the measure signed into law, he encouraged Clinton to
reconsider his veto threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my judgment, we ought to pass back the money to the people
who pay the taxes,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate votes were split pretty much along party
lines. In the House, four Republicans voted against it. Five
Democrats crossed the aisle to support it.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, all 45 Democrats and four Republicans _ Sens.
George Voinovich of Ohio, Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania and Olympia
Snowe and Susan Collins of Maine _ voted against it. Republican
Sens. Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas voted in favor
of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared from the 50-49 Senate tally that Vice President Al
Gore, who is constitutionally designated as president of the
Senate, should have been on hand to cast a tie vote, which would
have killed the bill. But Republican leaders announced earlier in
the day that they would use a parliamentary maneuver known as
``vote pairing'' to ensure victory.
</P>
<P>
   The rarely used tactic, which the Democrats agreed to, would
have allowed Specter, who voted no, to switch his ballot in support
of the measure on behalf of Sen. Mike Crapo, R-Idaho, who would
have cast a yes vote had he not been absent because of his
daughter's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   During the daylong floor debate on the bill Democrats kept
referring to it as ``a political statement'' that Republicans would
use against them in next year's presidential election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of these great posturings,'' declared Sen. John
Kerry, D-Mass., ``from the very people who gave you the great
deficit of the `80s and predicted that (Clinton's 1993 deficit
reduction plan, which passed with not a single Republican vote)
would increase unemployment...and ruin the country.''
</P>
<P>
   They also said the bill would provide more benefits to big
corporations and the affluent than to lower-income taxpayers. They
cited such items as a $1.6 billion break for multinational oil and
gas companies, an increase in the deduction for the so-called
``three-martini'' business lunch from 50 percent to 80 percent, and
the fact that higher income earners would reap bigger tax savings
than average families to make their point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to say upper income earners don't deserve a tax
break. But it is fair to (ask) who needs it the most?'' said Sen.
Bob Kerrey, D-Neb.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey, citing his Senate salary of a $136,000, said he would
average at least $800 more in tax cuts than a family of four with a
$35,000 income.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm and other Republicans asserted, however, that there was
nothing wrong with giving ``most of the tax cuts to the people who
pay most of the taxes.'' He defended the bill as balanced and fair.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats got some help in trashing the bill from an
unlikely source _ Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who is challenging
Bush for the GOP presidential nomination. But in the end, McCain
voted for it in hope, he said, of forcing Clinton to negotiate a
better tax cut deal for average Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In a floor speech before the vote, McCain said Democrats were
right to attack the Republican measure because it further
``complicates the tax system...with carve-outs for special
interests that go into effect immediately'' while delaying most
reductions for individual taxpayers until 2005.
</P>
<P>
   To make his point, he cited two special provisions that would
give an immediate credit to fishing tackle box companies to help
them compete with tool box manufacturers and to poultry farmers who
burn chicken manure to generate electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The priorities in this bill are seriously skewed in the wrong
direction,'' McCain said, calling it ``unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Special interests get the biggest breaks, and they get them
right away. All the American families get are the leftovers.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Thursday that he's ready to negotiate. White House
Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said Clinton was even flexible on how
tax cuts should be implemented. But he insisted that Clinton would
not ``go much beyond...the $300 billion range'' over 10 years that
he has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he says there's no middle ground. I think he
says that we can talk and negotiate about how you cut taxes and how
that works into your overall budget,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lockhart acknowledged that before talks start, Clinton will
use his veto authority to kill the GOP tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully once we get past the political posturing, we'll get
down to a discussion that involves the real numbers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
