<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET STOCKS REBOUND AND DOLLAR AND BONDS RALLY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Internet stocks rebounded Thursday, lifting the
Nasdaq composite index for the first time in six sessions, as
investors sought bargains and both the dollar and bonds rallied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw a major rebound in the Internet stocks today,'' said
Timothy M. Ghriskey, senior portfolio manager at Dreyfus Corp. Even
so, many investors appear to be awaiting Friday morning's report of
unemployment figures for July.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average gained 119.05 points, or 1.12
percent, to close at 10,793.82, in a turbulent session that saw it
drop as much as 108.59 points in early trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rallied 8.38 points, or
six-tenths of a percent, to 1,313.71. The Nasdaq, which had its
biggest intraday upswing since mid-April, closed up 25.83 points,
or 1.02 percent, to 2,565.81.
</P>
<P>
   Many technology issues swung wildly during the trading session.
Ebay, for example, traded as low as 70 9/32 before closing at 92
7/8, up 17 1/8. Amazon.com was ahead 8 13/16 for the day, to 97
1/4. Yahoo slumped to 110 before rallying to end at 128 3/8, up 7
3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Even America Online, which suffered from word that it may face
Internet competition from Microsoft, regained some lost ground. The
stock, which was the most actively traded of the day with 57.1
million shares changing hands, plunged to 76 15/16 before climbing
back to 83 15/16, down 3 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Although many analysts had eagerly awaited productivity figures
from the Labor Department, they seemed to have had minimal impact
in a session marked also by a flight to quality in the bond market,
the successful completion of a huge Wal-Mart financing and
lingering glow from Wednesday's disclosure that the Treasury plans
to redeem some debt early.
</P>
<P>
   The productivity gain, which Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the
Federal Reserve, cited in his recent Congressional appearances, was
at a slower-than-expected 1.3 percent pace in the second quarter.
But unit labor costs, which are considered a crucial measure of
wage pressures, grew faster than economists had forecast. They
surged to an annual rate of 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the kinds of data _ the combination of increased
compensation and lower productivity _ that are confirming the Fed's
fears,'' said Mickey D. Levy, chief economist at the Bank of
America.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve policy makers are scheduled to meet Aug. 24
to decide whether the economy is slowing enough on its own _
without further interest-rates increases _ to avoid a pickup in
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosanne M. Cahn, equity economist at Credit Suisse First
Boston, contended that productivity ``wasn't bad'' considering the
quarter's slowdown in output.
</P>
<P>
   Before the market opens Friday the Labor Department will report
on the employment situation for July, one of the most important
government economic statistics each month.
</P>
<P>
   Among the winners Thursday was IBM, which set the pace for the
Dow Jones blue chips, rising 4 11/16, to 123 3/16. IBM said its
scientists made a major, though early-stage, breakthrough in
storage technology.
</P>
<P>
   American Express gained 3 5/8, to 127 1/8, as it announced heavy
investment in Internet products and facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Union Carbide, which will be acquired by Dow Chemical, gained a
further 3 9/16, to 62 15/16, while DuPont rose 2 1/2, to 74. Dow
Chemical rebounded 5 11/16, to 124 5/16, after losing 6 1/16 on its
Wednesday bid for Union Carbide.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors was down 1 13/16 to 61, and Goodyear declined 1
5/16, to 52 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Several oil stocks posted hefty gains, with Royal Dutch up 2
3/16, to 62 9/16, with the help of a better than expected 4.7
percent profit gain.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Thursday's upturn, said Peter J. Canelo, a Morgan
Stanley strategist, the market is likely to continue to be
pressured by forced liquidation in Internet issues. That ``bubble
is bursting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, declining issues held a 3-2
margin over advancing ones, with 203 stocks making new lows and
only 40 new highs. Volume was 854.2 million, up from 781.2 million
on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
