<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KOKO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBJECT MATTER OF KOKO DOCUMENTARY OVERCOMES THE SHORTCOMINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Francine Patterson's specialty is gorilla linguistics. That's
gorilla, as in Magilla, not guerrilla, as in warfare, though there
probably have been times when Patterson deserved a little combat
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1972, when Patterson was a doctoral student in
developmental psychology at Stanford and a gorilla named Koko was
an infant at the San Francisco Zoo, Patterson has devoted herself
to teaching Koko sign language on the assumption that the great
apes are smarter than your average bear, and certainly bright
enough to communicate with humans.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt you've heard of it down through the years. From
features in National Geographic to appearances on ``Mr. Rogers'
Neighborhood'' to exhibits of gorilla ``artwork'' at reputable
galleries, the initiative informally known as Project Koko has
captured the imagination of anyone who's ever wondered what it
would be like to talk to the animals _ and actually have the
animals talk back.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday at 8 p.m., PBS's ``Nature'' presents ``A
Conversation With Koko,'' a one-hour capsulization of Patterson's
experiment in interspecies communication.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics who think Koko is merely mimicking Patterson's
gestures, which incorporate a modified version of American Sign
Language, may not be convinced that actual communication is taking
place. For instance, Koko's word for ``girl'' is said to be
``lip,'' but the program doesn't explain why or how humans have
made this interpretive leap.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with subtitles helping to explain Koko's ``thoughts,''
those who want to believe should have no trouble accepting her
reasonably precise gestures as evidence of an astounding
communications breakthrough. Patterson says Koko knows about a
thousand words and can use 500 of them regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad she can't talk. Martin Sheen's stilted narration is a
distraction, and the writing of producers Bonnie Brennan and Robert
Visty is a tad overblown. Early on, Sheen describes the documentary
as ``the true tale of a young woman and a gentle giant walking hand
in hand into a whole new world of understanding.'' Blechh. Later,
he says the project ``allows (Koko) to speak as an ambassador on
behalf of her endangered species.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheesh. Koko hasn't had the opportunity to say (or sign), ``If
nominated I will not run, if elected I will not serve,'' and we've
made her poohbah of primates? Aren't we putting too much pressure
on her? She's only 28.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the subject matter in ``A Conversation With Koko''
overcomes the obvious shortcomings. The story of Patterson's
relationship with Koko, now approaching three decades in length, is
fascinating. And even the most hardened skeptic will have a hard
time dismissing Koko's enormous capacity for affection and
attachment.
</P>
<P>
   As Sheen says, accurately this time, ``She has challenged us to
acknowledge that we share this world with other intelligent
animals.''
</P>
<P>
   A Conversation with Koko. One-hour documentary about a
scientist's 27-year effort to communicate with gorillas by sign
language. Narrated by Martin Sheen. Sunday at 8 p.m., PBS. Repeats
Aug. 14 at 7 p.m. Parental guideline rating: TV-G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7409 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-HAVASH06-CO     08-05 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-HAVASH06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Traditional services held for Muslim victim of Atlanta office
shootings
 &HT;    By Diane R. Stepp
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Eight time zones away in Tehran, friends of Jamshid
Havash's family tried vainly to keep him alive last week by
sacrificing some livestock and giving the meat to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a custom in our country when someone is in very much
danger. It's a way of thanking God that he is still alive,'' said
brother-in-law Mori Sarshar, a Shiite Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't know their appeal could do no good. Havash was
already dead, cut down last week in the Buckhead shootings, on the
floor of Momentum Securities.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Roya, and daughter, Tannaz, 7, were visiting relatives
in Tehran when the fatal gunshots rang out. They learned Wednesday
night _ six days after the shooting _ when they arrived back in
Atlanta that Havash was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told her that Jamshid had been shot, that he was in a
coma,'' said Sarshar. ``We knew it would take a long time to get
home, a 20-hour flight from Tehran, and we wanted to give them some
hope,'' said Sarshar. Havash's mother also came to what she
believed would be her son's bedside. Instead, it was his funeral
they would attend the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 family members and mourners attended the
traditional Muslim service Thursday. On Sunday, there will be
another opportunity to remember and mourn Havash at a memorial
service.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's funeral service was led by a mullah who offered
prayers in Farsi and Arabic and read from the Koran.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and relatives carried Havash to his grave in Greenlawn
Cemetery in a wood coffin borne on their shoulders. As they
proceeded, they stopped to place the coffin on the ground three
times ``to acquaint him with the ground he will be buried in,''
explained Saeid Sadri, a professor of architecture at Georgia Tech
who attended the funeral. Traditionally Iranians are not buried in
coffins, but are wrapped in cloth, said Sadri, ``but wood which is
degradable is also acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Havash's wife and mother wept openly as family and friends
filled the grave with soil, then poured water on it for
purification and placed their fingers on top of the grave while
offering prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is still in shock. It's totally unbelievable. We never,
ever dreamed something like this would happen,'' said Havash's
niece Leyla Sarshar, 22, a student at Georgia State University who
helped break the news to Roya Havash.
</P>
<P>
   As improbable as Havash's death seemed, Sarshar said she
believes her uncle was fated to die in the way he did, shot in the
back in circumstances no one could imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the day he was born it was predetermined. If you don't
believe that, you're bound to go crazy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Events of the summer reinforce Sarshar's belief. Havash had
planned to travel to Tehran with his wife and daughter in late
June, she said, but changed his mind at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   New business ventures kept him home _ the start-up of his own
environmental engineering consulting firm, and a residential
home-building enterprise. Few realized Havash was also day trading
stocks. ``It may have been the first time he was there. He had just
started day trading,'' said Sarshar.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the shooting, a 3 p.m. appointment to look at
property that would have placed him far from Buckhead fell through.
``He would have been at Momentum in the morning, instead,'' said
Sarshar. ``It was almost like an invitation to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Havash, 44, ``was no ordinary man. He was a leader in our
community,'' said Sarshar. ``He was a disciplined and well-educated
man who earned a bachelor's degree in chemical engineering and two
graduate degrees from Georgia Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   John Oster, an environmental consultant with Lockwood Greene
Technologies, worked side-by-side with Havash for more than 10
years. Havash was a senior engineer there until he left a few
months ago to begin his own firm.
</P>
<P>
   One of the many projects they worked on together, Oster said,
was designing a waste water treatment plant for a Coca Cola syrup
plant on the Amazon River in Manaus, Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   His longtime co-worker remembers Havash as a sports fan who
relished reading the newspaper sports pages.
</P>
<P>
   Oster also remembers Havash's generosity. ``Few people ever
realized it, but he would slip money to people, like the cafeteria
workers who needed it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Havash and many of his close-knit family fled Iran in the late
1970s during the political upheaval that led to the overthrow of
the shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi. ``That brought most of us here,''
said Sarshar. Havash's two sisters, Shahnaz Cangari and Shahla
Khosravi, and their families and many of Roya's relatives live in
the Roswell and Dunwoody area. A brother, Amir Havash, recently
returned to Tehran. They are part of metro Atlanta's Iranian
community that is estimated to number more than 16,000, said Sadri,
the Georgia Tech faculty member.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's shooting was not the first time disaster has visited
the Havash family. Sixteen months ago, a tornado that ripped
through Dunwoody destroyed the new two-story European style home
the Havashs had saved to build.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a year of rebuilding, the Havash family moved
back in about two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even though that part of their life has been fixed, Tannaz, who
does not know her father is dead, knows something is again wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``She asked why her daddy wasn't at the airport to meet her,''
Sarshar said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
