<SLUG> BC-GENOCIDE-MINISTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES U.S. MAY EXTRADITE MINISTER ACCUSED OF GENOCIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A three-judge panel ruled Thursday that the United
States may hand an elderly pastor over to a United Nations tribunal
to face war crimes charges stemming from ethnic unrest in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-0 ruling by the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New
Orleans found that a federal judge in Laredo, Texas, was correct
when he decided there was evidence that a crime had been committed.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, the judges rejected defense arguments that
Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, 75, could not be turned over for trial
because the U.S. Senate has ratified no treaty with the United
Nations over extraditions.
</P>
<P>
   The case marks the first time the United States has arrested
someone on its soil to be handed over to a U.N. tribunal.
Ntakirutimana has been in and out of custody since September 1996
when he was arrested by FBI agents in Laredo, where his family
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The war crimes tribunal, based in Tanzania, has accused
Ntakirutimana of leading attackers armed with machetes, grenades
and guns in an April 1994 rampage that killed dozens of people who
were hiding in his Seventh-day Adventist church.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Rwanda was in the throes of a bloody feud between
the country's dominant ethnic groups, the Hutus and Tutsis, strife
that killed an estimated 500,000 and sent 2 million refugees
fleeing to neighboring nations. Most of those killed, including
those in Ntakirutimana's church, were Tutsis. Ntakirutimana is a
member of the Hutu ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   One judge, who agreed that he could be turned over to the U.N.
tribunal, nonetheless blistered the State Department and said the
defendant is likely innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am persuaded that it is more likely than not that
Ntakirutimana is actually innocent,'' Judge Robert Parker wrote in
a concurring but separate opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully understand that the ultimate decision in this case may
well be a political one that is driven by important considerations
of state that may transcend the question of quilt or innocence of
any individual,'' Parker continued.
</P>
<P>
   Accusations against Ntakirutimana ``defied logic'' said Parker,
who called on Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to review the
case before handing the man over to the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have said they are not charged with evaluating
Ntakirutimana's guilt, but that the United States has an obligation
to enforce U.N. mandates, and that there is more than enough
evidence to warrant his standing trial.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court decision set the stage for a possible
Supreme Court battle between the Justice Department and a former
U.S. attorney general, Ramsey Clark, who is defending
Ntakirutimana.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has said the tribunal was created illegally and that the
United States needs a congressionally ratified treaty before it
could surrender his client.
</P>
<P>
   He has said the charges against Ntakirutimana were the result of
tribal hatred and the wrath of a government that despised his power
as head of a church with approximately 300,000 members in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Clark could not be reached for comment Thursday night, but he
has vowed to take the case to the Supreme Court and represent
Ntakirutimana before the Tanzania-based tribunal, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not seen the opinion, so he is not going to make any
comment,'' a staff member at Clark's New York office said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Don DeGabrielle, the assistant U.S. attorney who is
handling the case, nor officials of the State Department could be
reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
