<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-PAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TEACHER PAY RAISE BIGGEST IN U.S. 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas public schoolteachers are heading back to
the classroom in the next couple of weeks with the highest
across-the-board pay raise in the nation, one teacher group said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the $3,000 increase the Texas Legislature mandated,
though, Texas teachers are still likely to remain below the
national average wage paid to teachers, said the head of the Texas
State Teachers Association. And they are leaving the profession in
droves, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``These raises are giant steps in the right direction,'' said
TSTA president Ignacio Salinas Jr. ``But even with these major
increases, we're still, at our best estimate, $2,845 below the
projected national average of $41,377.''
</P>
<P>
   Combined with raises that local districts are adding, teachers
will see an average increase of $3,800 this school year, according
to the TSTA survey of school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``School is off to a good start,'' said Salinas, who is also a
Democratic state representative from San Diego. ``Teacher morale is
the best in years and expectations are high for a good year at
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the boost in pay and spirits, however, teachers continue
to leave the profession in large numbers, Salinas said, and most
school districts will open in the coming days with teacher
shortages. About half of all teachers leave the profession after
five years, in large part because of higher pay and better benefits
in non-teaching jobs in the private sector, Salinas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Improvements in salaries, benefits and working conditions are
absolutely essential if we are to stem the critical teaching
shortages plaguing Texas schools and circumventing real reform in
public education. Certainly we must create a quality health
insurance program for all school employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston schools face the Aug. 16 opening with more than 500
vacancies, according to the TSTA leader. By comparison, the Spring
Branch school district has only 24 openings, due, in large part to
the $5,000 raise its teachers will see. Local school officials
added $2,000 to the state amount, giving teachers in that district
the largest hike in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of other professional educators in Texas, however, will
not be seeing the state-mandated raises because the Legislature did
not specify they should be included.
</P>
<P>
   Among those left out are 2,700 diagnosticians _ teachers who
test and develop individualized educational plans for students
whose learning disabilities or other problems place them in special
education _ and the 3,300 speech and physical therapists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were excluding them,'' said state Rep. Paul Sadler,
D-Henderson, who chairs the House Public Education Committee.
``There are a number of different categories of employees ...
(many) of which are not included on the minimum salary schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosticians and therapists are among the categories of
employees not on the teacher minimum salary schedule and,
therefore, not guaranteed the $3,000 increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature required school districts to give the raise to
nurses and counselors by putting those employees back on the
teacher salary schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have loved to include all of (school employees),''
Sadler said. However, the more categories of employees added to the
minimum salary schedule, the less money teachers would have
received, he added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
