<SLUG> BC-TV-KOKO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KOKO' SPEAKS VOLUMES ABOUT AFFECTION BETWEEN RESEARCHER, APE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conspiracy theorists, unite. Or at least find somebody who gets
Cinemax premium cable so you can sit for a couple of hours in front
of Nick Broomfield's controversial documentary, ``Kurt &AMP;
Courtney.''
</P>
<P>
   It airs Friday night as part of Cinemax's ``Reel Life'' series,
raising once again the question of whether Cobain's death was a
suicide or something else. Seattle Post-Intelligencer rock critic
Gene Stout reviewed the film last year during its theatrical
release. Here's his take: ``Nick Broomfield's documentary on rocker
Kurt Cobain and his widow, Courtney Love, takes the viewer through
a bewildering parade of interviews with the couple's family members
and friends. It provides a luridly entertaining portrait of Love _
who kept the film from being shown at Sundance _ as ruthless,
scheming, manipulative, even murderous. But it also portrays Cobain
as a lovable but troubled man whose suicide was not implausible.''
</P>
<P>
   Farewell to `MST3K'
</P>
<P>
   Fans of ``Mystery Science Theater 3000'' will be gathering for
entirely different reasons this weekend. Sunday's installment on
Sci-Fi Channel (6 and 8 p.m.) will be the last original broadcast
of the show, which over 10 years has lampooned 176 pretty horrible
films with some of the best-written sarcasm anywhere on TV.
</P>
<P>
   It is our good fortune that host Mike Nelson and his sidekicks,
Crow T. Robot and Servo, will live on in rerun perpetuity. This
week's target: a 1967 film titled ``Danger: Diabolik.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC alters fall schedule
</P>
<P>
   The fall season is still more than a month away, but NBC is
already fiddling with its lineup. Buoyed by healthy summer ratings
for the freshman comedy ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' the network has changed
its Tuesday lineup, which originally had ``3rd Rock From the Sun''
at 8, the new ``Mike O'Malley Show'' at 8:30, ``Just Shoot Me'' at
9, ``Will &AMP; Grace'' at 9:30 and ``Dateline NBC'' at 10.
</P>
<P>
   Stronger shows always lead off the hour, so ``Just Shoot Me''
will move to 8 and ``Will &AMP; Grace'' to 9. ``3rd Rock'' gets the
8:30 slot and ``The Mike O'Malley Show'' will go to 9:30.
``Dateline'' stays put at 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
