<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7417 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLBROOKE-CONFIRM-2TA     08-05 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-CONFIRM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CONFIRMS HOLBROOKE FOR U.N. POST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Iowa, Del., Conn., Texas, N.C.)  (mk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate voted Thursday to confirm Richard
Holbrooke as chief American delegate to the United Nations, ending
a 14-month nomination battle that left the Clinton administration
without a high-profile representative to the United Nations during
military conflicts in the Balkans and the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved Holbrooke, the former American ambassador to
Germany and the architect of the 1995 peace agreement in Bosnia, on
a vote of 81-16.
</P>
<P>
   No Democrats opposed the nomination. Among the senators voting
against confirmation _ 15 Republicans and one independent _ was the
majority leader, Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Lott, who in the past had questioned Holbrooke's
fitness for the U.N. post, said that the senator `'was too
concerned with the apparent ethical lapses of this nominee to give
him his vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke was the subject of a pair of federal ethics
investigations over the last year, one of which ended with his
paying $5,000 to the Justice Department to settle civil charges
that he had violated federal lobbying laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration hopes that Holbrooke will inject a
new sense of American leadership at the United Nations and that he
can repair some of the damage done in recent years to the
relationship between the United States and the world organization.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship has frayed as a result of the administration's
failure to persuade Republican leaders in Congress to pay more than
$1 billion in back dues to the United Nations, and because of a
perception among senior U.N. officials that the administration sees
the organization as a backwater, with diminishing importance to
American foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   That perception worsened as Holbrooke's nomination languished
month after month, leaving the United States without a permanent
representative to the organization.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials also were dismayed at the administration for
cutting the United Nations out of the decision-making as waves of
NATO warplanes devastated Yugoslavia. They also felt slighted
during last December's American-led military strikes against Iraq,
set off by Baghdad's decision to expel international weapons
inspectors, suggesting the strikes were conducted without explicit
U.N. approval.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials believe that Holbrooke _ whose friends
routinely describe him both as the most talented American diplomat
of his generation and as a Machiavellian bully of unparalleled
ambition _ may be able to find a way to get the back dues paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has worked on occasion with Milosevic might work with
Capitol Hill,'' said a senior administration official, referring to
Holbrooke's intense negotiations over the years with President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   When he moves into his office suite at the U.S. mission, across
First Avenue from the U.N. headquarters in New York, Holbrooke will
find himself confronted almost immediately with the problems of
rebuilding Kosovo, an issue he knows well from his long service as
a diplomatic troubleshooter in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has been given the task of administering
Kosovo in the aftermath of the NATO-led military assault that
forced the Yugoslav military out of the province, a peacekeeping
operation that is among the most complex and expensive ever
undertaken by an organization that is already strained for money
and resources.
</P>
<P>
   It will also be left to Holbrooke to defend American interests
on a range of other foreign policy disputes involving the United
Nations, notably with Iraq, which has found important foreign
allies in its effort to have economic sanctions lifted despite
Washington's objections.
</P>
<P>
   The vote Thursday was made possible when the last of four
Republicans to invoke senatorial privilege to block the nomination
announced earlier this week that he would allow the vote to take
place.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmaker, Charles Grassley of Iowa, had delayed the vote
over a State Department personnel issue unrelated to Holbrooke.
Grassley voted Thursday in favor of confirming Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   The president announced in June of last year that he intended to
nominate Holbrooke for the U.N. job, replacing Bill Richardson, who
became energy secretary.
</P>
<P>
   But the nomination was plagued by delays _ first as a result of
federal ethics investigations of Holbrooke, then as a result of
procedural maneuvers in the Senate unrelated to Holbrooke's
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the administration are waiting eagerly to see what sort
of relationship develops in the Cabinet between Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and Holbrooke, who was runner-up in the race to
become secretary of state during President Clinton's second term.
Holbrooke, 58, is close to Vice President Al Gore and is seen as
likely to lead the State Department in a Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   Although Holbrooke will technically answer to Albright in his
U.N. post, many who know the hard-charging veteran diplomat well
believe he will not fit comfortably into the role of her
subordinate.
</P>
<P>
   Albright released a statement Thursday welcoming the
appointment. ``I feel certain that Ambassador Holbrooke will serve
the American people well at the U.N,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In his own statement, Holbrooke, who was reported Thursday to be
on his way to Alaska for the start of a two-week vacation, said
that he was ``deeply gratified'' by the confirmation vote.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While members of Congress might have questioned Holbrooke's role
in policy-making in the Balkans or his larger philosophy of
statecraft, they did not dispute that his resume is one of the most
impressive of any member of the Foreign Service since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the State Department shortly after graduating from
Brown University in 1962. He rose quickly up the department's ranks
after his first foreign posting as a junior diplomat at the U.S.
Embassy in Saigon, South Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1968, he was sent to Paris as a junior member of the
American delegation led by W. Averell Harriman to embark on the
Vietnam peace talks. In the 1970s, he left government to edit
Foreign Policy magazine but rejoined the State Department in 1977,
while still his his 30s, as assistant secretary of state for Asian
and Pacific Affairs in the Carter administration.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who has long been allied with the Democratic Party,
left government again with the election of President Reagan and
went to Wall Street as an investment banker.
</P>
<P>
   He remained in New York until the 1992 election of Clinton, who
named Holbrooke ambassador to Germany and then assistant secretary
of state for European and Canadian Affairs. It was as assistant
secretary that Holbrooke oversaw the arduous negotiations that led
to the Dayton peace agreement in 1995, ending the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   During a 35-minute debate before the Senate vote, Sen. Joseph
Biden of Delaware, ranking Democrat on the Foreign Relations
Committee, said that he knew of no nominee to a foreign policy post
``more qualified for the job for which was nominated.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., said that Holbrooke is ``one of
America's great natural resources'' and a man of ``enormous energy
and talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, was the only senator to
speak against the nomination during the debate. She called
Holbrooke a ``principled man'' and said she admired ``his
dedication, his tenacity.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said that Holbrooke, long the Clinton administration's
chief diplomatic troubleshooter in the Balkans, was responsible for
a policy in the region that had failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe our policy in the Balkans is to force factions to
live together in an American model when the circumstances are
different from anything we have ever had in our country,'' she
said. ``I cannot in good conscience vote for someone who has taken
our country in the wrong direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., the powerful Republican chairman of
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, did not vote.
</P>
<P>
   His staff said that Helms was notified of the vote only a few
minutes before the roll call began and could not get back to the
Senate chamber in time. A spokesman had no comment when asked how
the senator, who supported the nomination when it came before the
committee, would have voted Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The larger of the federal ethics investigations of Holbrooke
began only days after Clinton announced his intention to nominate
Holbrooke to the U.N. post, when an anonymous letter arrived at the
offices of the State Department's inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   The letter questioned whether Holbrooke, who is now an
investment banker in New York at the firm of Credit Suisse First
Boston, had done favors for the firm even before resigning from the
State Department in 1996 as assistant secretary of state for
European affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation ended in February, when Holbrooke agreed to
pay $5,000 to the Justice Department to settle civil charges that
he had violated federal lobbying laws in his contacts with the U.S.
Embassy in South Korea shortly after his resignation to join Credit
Suisse.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke denied any wrongdoing in his contacts with the
embassy, which included a request that the American ambassador in
Seoul set up a meeting for him with South Korea's president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
