<SLUG> BC-TAX-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: UNKNOWN RISKS LOOM AS PARTIES SPLIT SHARPLY ON TAX CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ADAM CLYMER  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Are the Republicans, or perhaps the Democrats,
driving off a political cliff on the $792 billion tax cut adopted
by Congress on Thursday?
</P>
<P>
   Almost all Republicans in Congress and their presidential
candidates favor it. Almost all Democrats and President Clinton are
against it, and there is an election next year.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely have both parties sounded so contradictorily confident
about the political benefits they think their policies, which they
insist have been decided on principle alone, will bring. With each
side sated with polling data and focus-group results, the conflict
suggests that at least one side is taking a big chance on the
voters.
</P>
<P>
   But the polling data are not that clear. People think their
taxes are too high, but are not very excited about it.
</P>
<P>
   That offers room for ideology. And, in fact, most Republicans,
though probably not the 98.2 percent represented by the 216-4
Republican vote in the House, believe in cutting taxes and federal
spending. Similarly, most Democrats, though not the 97.6 percent
their 201-5 negative vote represents, worry that big tax cuts could
starve the government of revenue they think it needs to spend.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would cut all five income tax rates by one percentage
point, lower capital gains rates and eliminate taxes on estates.
The Senate's 50-49 approval vote Thursday night, following House
approval by a vote of 221-206 (one independent voted no), completed
congressional action. But the bill will not be sent to Clinton for
the veto he promised again Thursday night until September, when
Congress will be back from vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's votes, especially in view of the expected veto, have
almost nothing to do with national politics. As veteran Republican
pollster Robert Teeter observed Thursday, ``What's happened is they
have both lost sight of the fact that most American politics is
decided in the middle.'' Instead, he said, ``what they are both
doing is playing base politics,'' appealing to their more
ideological, most reliable voters.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as many as 400 of the 435 House members are in safe
seats, where they do not have to worry about swing voters. In the
Senate, some Republican moderates represent swing states, and
Thursday night four defected, but the Republican leaders not only
come from safe seats, but most of them served in the House and
reflect its way of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   But why should Republican presidential candidates have a similar
perspective when the White House is not a safe seat for anyone? On
Thursday, Texas Gov. George W. Bush's spokesman, Scott McClelland,
said Bush ``commends'' the effort to cut taxes, and believed that
``the money should be sent back to the people who earned it: the
taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Buchanan even complained, ``The Republican tax plan has
been delayed too long in implementation and it is too modest.''
But, he said, the ``Republicans are on the right side of this
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the candidates' situation is similar to that of their
congressional allies. None of them is yet running for president,
after all. What they are running for is the Republican nomination
for president, and the voters who make that decision are among the
most conservative Republicans around.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side gives the other much credit for intellectual
honesty. Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., said the Republicans were not
passing a tax bill but ``a political press release'' that they knew
would be vetoed. Then, he said, they could go to small-business
leaders or their favorite lobbyists and say that they had tried to
help but that Clinton had stopped them.
</P>
<P>
   He said Democrats, while they would like to be for tax cuts,
too, knew from the 1981 tax cut that serious deficits hurt the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., who heads the Rules Committee, said
he thought the Republicans were showing courage in cutting taxes
when polls did not indicate the public strongly favored the action.
Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., said Democrats' opposition to cuts
that might curb spending was so intense that they would spend
August telling lies about the bill.
</P>
<P>
   If the pollsters did not provide clear policy directives for the
parties, it was clear that their focus groups had helped write
their scripts, as some words and phrases kept reverberating through
the serial speechmaking that passed for debate.
</P>
<P>
   The tax on large estates, which the bill would gradually
abolish, was repeatedly called a ``death tax'' by Republicans. The
increase of deductibility of business meals from the current 50
percent to 60 percent by 2007 was labeled by Democrats as
government sponsorship of the ``three-martini lunch,'' a bibulous
interlude too much for even the Senate on a slow day.
</P>
<P>
   Among Democrats, Rep. David Bonior of Michigan and Karen
McCarthy of Missouri, kept calling the bill ``risky.'' Rep. Rosa
DeLauro of Connecticut said it was an ``irresponsible special
interest tax giveaway.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, the message was that the money was the
people's, not the government's. ``It's their money, give it back,''
Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Ways and Means Committee, Rep. Bill Archer,
R-Texas, said: ``The Democrats believe Washington knows how to
spend the people's money better than the people do. We disagree. We
think it belongs to the people who earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, of course, 1999 is not forever. Even if the bill
dies this year, this Congress has another 18 months to go. In
September 2000, for example, if polls that really matter to
candidates suggest that a somewhat smaller tax cut would help
incumbents of both parties, compromise could materialize in a great
big hurry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
