<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ TRADE TALK WAS JUST THAT ... TALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's how these things get started: A coach from one team spots
an old friend who now scouts for another American League club. They
start throwing names around like baseball cards at a card show.
</P>
<P>
   The trading deadline is fast approaching so the two baseball men
start playing the ``Would-Ya Game.'' Would-ya trade so-and-so for
so-and-so?
</P>
<P>
   The two are basically just pulling each other's chains _ they're
certainly not authorized to make a deal, just feeling things out _
and the deadline slips by uneventfully for both clubs.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later someone whispers something to a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   The names he's hearing are big; big enough to raise the hack's
eyebrows. This, he thinks, could be a nice story. The source, he
knows, is a good one, someone who ought to know what's going on,
who's going where and when.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing you know, Juan Gonzalez is back in the headlines and
on his way to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   That's what a story in the Detroit Free Press _ and bantered
about on local talk radio _ strongly implied yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sources say talks of more than a preliminary nature already
have begun between the teams about a Gonzalez trade,'' the story
said. ``A deal couldn't get completed before the July 31 trading
deadline, but it has a realistic chance of happening this
off-season _ especially if the Rangers make another early playoff
exit.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad nobody bothered to let the teams' general managers _ the
Rangers' Melvin and the Tigers' Randy Smith _ in on the secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't spoken to Randy Smith since about a month before the
trading deadline,'' Melvin said yesterday from Port Charlotte, Fla.
``The last \RGMs\S I talked to on that \Rdeadline\S Saturday were
Frank Wren \Rin Baltimore\S about Juan Guzman, Herk Robinson \Rin
Kansas City\S about \RKevin\S Appier and Bill Bavasi \Rin Anaheim\S
about \RChuck\S Finley. Then I called \Rowner\S Tom Hicks and told
him we wouldn't be making a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith echoed Melvin's statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about getting a face player, a name guy but Doug
and I haven't talked in over a month,'' Smith said. ``Coaches and
scouts trade players all the time. It's certainly nothing we have
ongoing.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't make the story total fabrication. Far from it. The
same Gonzalez-to-Detroit rumors were floating around here earlier
in the week.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers are looking for a middle-of-the-order hitter to get
fans excited about the beginning of the Comerica Park era next
season, and Gonzalez, who has only a year left on his Texas
contract, fits their profile perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, however, was, or is, imminent. You really think Melvin
is dumb enough to risk shaking up the chemistry on the hottest team
in baseball right now? You think he'd trade a two-time MVP, his
cleanup hitter, in the middle of a pennant race?
</P>
<P>
   Get real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy talked to me more than a month ago about the type of
player he's looking for, and obviously Juan's name came up,'' said
Melvin, who added that five other teams phoned to ask about
Gonzalez before the deadline. ``I think that all they do is try to
get a feeler out there for him. When it gets down to it, clubs
realize a deal can't be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like calling Atlanta to see if Greg Maddux might
be available. You pretty much know the answer before you ask the
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in this case, the Tigers had heard that Gonzalez was
having some trouble with manager Johnny Oates and might be more
available than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of the story, as I understand it, is that they'd
like to get a Gonzalez type, a \RJim\S Thome type, for the middle
of their lineup,'' Melvin said. ``\RThe media\S throw out names of
a lot of players but some of them have no-trade clauses to certain
teams, too, so it makes no sense to talk about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has a list of 10 teams he can't be traded to, and
Detroit may well be on the list. Still, that's often just a clause
with a certain monetary value. Stack the money high enough and it
goes away.
</P>
<P>
   Something could happen this off-season, depending on a number of
factors. Can the Rangers re-sign Gonzalez themselves? Juan has
already dispelled one concern, saying he's not switching agents to
join the hated and difficult Scott Boras. That's a positive sign.
Whatever others might think, he wants to stay in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Who would the Tigers give up? The package would start with
left-handed pitcher Justin Thompson, but he has struggled this
season. The Tigers would certainly throw in other players, like
outfielder Bobby Higginson, another disappointment, but the Rangers
likely wouldn't start paying much attention unless young outfielder
Juan Encarnacion's name was included, too.
</P>
<P>
   Even then they'd have to ask themselves: Does it all add up to
an MVP?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if you're seriously thinking of trading a Juan
Gonzalez, don't you owe it to yourself to shop him everywhere, just
to see what might get offered?
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers, by the way, would also be interested in Rusty Greer,
Ruben Mateo and Lee Stevens. And who wouldn't?
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said he brought up the subject of trade rumors when he
met with Gonzalez in his office Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to forget about those kinds of things, like the
Albert Belle and Mike Mussina stuff that came out while we were in
Baltimore,'' Melvin said. ``You can't worry about those things. I
don't think it will affect him or the club any.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trading deadline's past. I don't think this is anything
he's going to get bothered by.''
</P>
<P>
   This story, I have a hunch, was just two old baseball friends,
passing each other in the night.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they laid the groundwork for a blockbuster deal this
winter. More likely, unless they're about to get some heavy-duty
promotions, they just swapped air.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
