<HEADLINE>
RENO AGREES TO DISCUSS IMMIGRANT OVERSIGHTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno agreed Thursday to meet
with a Texas lawmaker about the Justice Department's failure to
provide information on illegal immigrants with criminal records who
commit more crimes after they are released from custody.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the information sought by Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas,
does not exist and would have to be created from individual files
kept in separate computers by the Immigration and Naturalization
Service and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``To run the (INS) records check through the FBI would take
months,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's inquiry, driven by the release of two illegal immigrants
suspected in subsequent Houston killings, resulted in a party-line
vote Wednesday by the House immigration subcommittee, chaired by
Smith,to subpoena the attorney general, and demand that she provide
the information within three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee's action was spurred by the case of Angel
Maturino Resendiz, who was wanted in two slayings when INS agents
apprehended him entering the U.S. illegally and sent him back to
Mexico. He later surrendered to U.S. authorities and has been
charged in four killings _ including the death of Houston teacher
Noemi Dominguez _ that occurred after he was released by INS.
</P>
<P>
   Also fueling the committee's decision were reports that
Colombian national Guillermo Castillo _ accused in the August 1998
beating death of Joel Gerhart _ was apprehended a month later at
the Texas-Mexico border by INS agents who three days later flew him
back to Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the INS has records about the 26,870 criminal
immigrants who are sent back to their home countries and the FBI
has records on some but not all felony convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we do not have a connection, a ready documentary
connection, between those that were released (by INS) and whatever
subsequent criminal history they may have,'' the attorney general
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
