<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Calloway injury may force moves
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ A Falcons team already thin at wide receiver
got thinner Thursday afternoon when starter Chris Calloway sprained
his left ankle and had to be carted off the field.
</P>
<P>
   It's not known much of training camp he'll miss, but he won't
practice this morning, and won't participate in Saturday's joint
practices with the Jacksonville Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   He will be re-evaluated today.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some swelling, and that's not good,'' coach Dan Reeves
said. ``He probably won't be ready for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Harris, who has eight regular-season catches in a
six-year career with New England, Seattle and Atlanta, will move
into Calloway's split end spot.
</P>
<P>
   Calloway went down as cornerback Ray Buchanan crashed into him
from behind while attempting to break up a pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``My foot kind of bent all the way back, and somebody landed on
it,'' said Calloway, who was sporting crutches at dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Calloway was cut by the Giants despite leading the team in
receptions for the fourth straight year, with 62. The 5-foot-10,
188-pounder has caught 359 passes in nine NFL seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons pursued Calloway with the idea for him to work
primarily out of the slot, with Terance Mathis and Tony Martin
working outside as starters.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin, who led the Falcons last year with 66 receptions and
1,181 yards, was waived after he refused to allow the Falcons to
postpone payment of a $400,000 March 1 roster bonus.
</P>
<P>
   That made Calloway a starter.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-11, 188-pound Harris has above-average speed. His NFL
claim to fame was the 29-yard reception he made on the Falcons'
tying drive at the end of the NFC championship game at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any opportunity is a good opportunity, but you don't like to
see a teammate get hurt,'' Harris said. ``On most teams, the
weakside receiver, which is the (split end), tends to have deeper
routes. There's more blocking at the wing (where Mathis starts).''
</P>
<P>
   If Calloway is out any length of time, ``Tim (Dwight) has been
(a reserve) on the other side,'' Reeves said. ``Now, we may make
some moves.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
