<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin gains despite pain
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Martin Martin limps to the garage area at
Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 40, is NASCAR's tough guy this summer. His left leg is
wrapped in a brace, while the left wrist is covered by a small pad.
With every hobbling step, Martin's facial expression never changes.
With every hobbling step, it It displays his famous focus and
intensity, with no sign revealing signs of the apparent pain.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford No. 6 driver makes it to his destination slowly but
without breaking stride. As others have seen this season, most
notably in the last three Winston Cup races, Martin never lets pain
get in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Despite suffering extensive injuries during a practice-session
wreck at Daytona on July 2, Martin has not missed any time on the
track. He even raced the next day at the Pepsi 400 after learning
that he had torn knee ligaments and broken several bones.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who has driven in NASCAR's major-league series since
1981, provides a candid answer about his tolerance of pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, (my tolerance) could be confused with stupidity; I'm
not that smart,'' Martin said. ``What hurts one man is just an
irritation to another. People are different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have a race team that has dedicated their lives to the
effort and have sponsors who have dedicated their budgets. I'm
going to drive the car and do a good job. I don't care if I have
broken bones or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Martin continued to stay behind the wheel, he also
has been able to stay around the top of the Winston Cup points
standings. In the three races after the Daytona crash, Martin has
moved from third in the standings to second. He trails leader Dale
Jarrett by 254 points entering Saturday's Brickyard 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the marks of a true professional in any sport,'' team
owner Jack Roush said, ``is for the person to be able to give it
their best, regardless of pain and days when they don't feel well _
and Mark is the best example of that I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Driver Jeff Burton said,``Mark has shown how tough he is from
what we've seen in the last month. There are a lot of people who
drive hurt. Some people can do it with success and some people
can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin refused to surrender his seat to Matt Kenseth at Daytona
and drove his car to 17th place. The ensuing race schedule assisted
Martin in the healing process. He finished sixth at New Hampshire
and third at Pocono, with a week off in between.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the races, Martin was lifted in and out of the car by
crew members. Other drivers can't help but notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``(What Mark) has done in the last few weeks is really
unbelievable,'' Jarrett said. ``I've been there; I've had a broken
bone in my knee and some cracked ribs, similar to Mark's but not to
his extent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing you can do except dig down a little deeper and
that's what Mark has done,'' Jarrett said. ``It's been tremendous
to watch him. You wouldn't expect anything less from him, but,
still, it's pretty amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Martin's victory over pain should be no surprise. Roush
recalled a story from Martin's teenage years when he broke both
feet and later competed in a race with a pair of foot casts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark's tolerance for pain, I'm sure, is unsurpassed,'' Roush
said. ``I'm proud of him for making this effort. Knowing him the
way I do, this is what I expected.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
