<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tearful day for Waltrip
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Darrell Waltrip's retirement announcement at
Indianapolis Motor Speedway had been planned for at least two
months, but the advance notice didn't make things any easier for
the legendary NASCAR driver Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip, who said the 2000 season will be his last behind the
wheel, choked up with emotion several times during the news
conference. At one point, with tears strolling down his face,
Waltrip motioned for his wife, Stevie, to stand by his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be leaving a sport that has meant so much to me and my
family _ the business side I can talk about,'' Waltrip said. ``The
racing side, leaving the sport, hanging up my helmet _ that's hard
to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Waltrip regained his composure, the confidence and swagger
of the relentless competitor nicknamed ``Jaws'' reappeared quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came into this sport in 1972, and I've been a headliner ever
since,'' Waltrip said. ``I always like to say that when I'd go to a
town, people would say, 'Are you here with the show?' And I'd say,
'No, I am the show.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kmart Racing, Waltrip's primary sponsor, and owner Haas/Carter
Motorsports will team up with the veteran driver for a season-long
commemoration next year referred to as ``Victory Tour 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole goal for the next 18 months is to win a race _ more
than one, but at least one,'' said Waltrip, who last won in 1992.
``Winning a race now would be as big as winning that first one in
1975.''
</P>
<P>
   Clean-shaven icon
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt, one of Waltrip's peers, is attracting tons of
attention this week, but it has nothing to do with any retirement
plans. ``The Intimidator'' shaved off his trademark mustache for
the first time in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was down in the Bahamas last weekend, snorkeling,'' he said.
``I couldn't get a tight seal on my mask because my mustache was in
the way. So I shaved it off.''
</P>
<P>
   As simple as that, Earnhardt is without the bushy lip for the
first time since 1982. He insisted that the new look won't affect
his racing skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did up here,'' _ he pointed to his face _ ``won't
affect what I do out there,'' Earnhardt said, pointing to the
track. ``It didn't in '82, anyway. We still won races.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Saturday's Brickyard 400, Earnhardt is
participating in tonight's International Race of Champions (IROC)
series. He won each of the first three races and could become the
first to sweep all four since the series started in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Just do it
</P>
<P>
   Nike made its grand entrance into the NASCAR world on Wednesday.
Winston Cup drivers Dale Jarrett, Bobby Labonte and Tony Stewart
will wear footwear specifically designed by the shoe company to
handle the rigors of auto racing. ... Ford unveiled its latest race
car, nicknamed ``Taurus 2K,'' which will debut at February's
Daytona 500. The car features new designs for the hood, rear window
and front and rear fascias.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
