<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon rolls to third pole in six years at Indy
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Perhaps Jeff Gordon had the wrong Indiana street
named after him this week.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who captured the pole on Thursday for the Brickyard 400,
was honored the day before by his hometown of Pittsboro, Ind. The
town, 10 miles west of Indianapolis, renamed a road after the
three-time Winston Cup champion.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Gordon's streak of domination at Indianapolis Motor
Speedway _ including a track-record qualifying speed of 179.612 mph
_ the dedication maybe should've taken place at racing's famous
oval track.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin, who had the second-fastest time, will also be on
the front row for Saturday's race. David Green, third-fastest,
earned his best starting position since Rockingham last year.
Rounding out the top qualifiers are Winston Cup points leader Dale
Jarrett at fourth and Michael Waltrip at fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has flourished since NASCAR began racing at IMS in 1994.
He is the Brickyard 400's only two-time champion, winning the
inaugural event and taking the checkered flag again last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you win at Indy, it's a big deal,'' Gordon said. ``To
me, winning that first Brickyard was like living through a fantasy,
like you're really not sure if you're sleeping and dreaming or it's
really happening. Nothing will ever compare to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who is sixth in the points standings, established the
new qualifying mark despite minor control problems. The No. 24
Chevy slipped in turn 1, but Gordon held on to break the record of
179.394 mph set by Ernie Irvan last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had a good car today, that we ran well and had a shot
at the pole,'' Gordon said. ``When I ran the lap, it wasn't my best
lap. We're dealing with the best race-car drivers in the world ...
(but) maybe they were fighting the same things I was fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in six years that Gordon has won the No. 1
position at Indianapolis. Ironically, Gordon's pair of victories at
the track came after he started at the No. 3 position.
</P>
<P>
   After qualifying ended, Martin and Rusty Wallace were involved
in a freak wreck during the evening practice. Wallace was driving
from the garage area to the track, with Martin going in the
opposite direction, when the two had a minor collision at the track
entrance. Each car suffered slight damage, but both drivers were
unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't Mark's fault, it's wasn't my fault,'' Wallace said.
He put the blame on track officials directing traffic in and out of
the garage.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
