<HEADLINE>
TALKING UP TELECOMMUTING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8)
</HEADLINE>
 (af) 
By MICHELLE COTTLE  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)You're a manager at a midsized company. Some of your
employees have approached you about the possibility of working from
home one or two days a week. You see no obvious reason to say no,
but wonder how to broach the subject with upper management, which
tends to have a stubbornly old-school attitude about work
schedules. How can you sell them on the idea?(end italcs) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To convince skeptical superiors to allow telecommuting, a
manager needs to show how it can benefit the company's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, you have to prepare a business plan like with any
other initiative,'' said Gail Martin, executive director of the
International Telework Association and Council, a nonprofit group
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Managers should arm themselves with examples of how
telecommuting arrangements can improve productivity and reduce
costs, agreed John Birstler, the executive in charge of the
telework program at Merrill Lynch, where about 2,500 employees
participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to think about what strategy or business objective
you can point the program toward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Martin agreed that telecommuting should be pursued as a way
to solve problems. Do employees spend too much time commuting by
car? Are they coming in late and stressed out? Telecommuting could
ease the strain.
</P>
<P>
   And is the company having trouble recruiting and training
people? ``We're all competing for the same workers,'' she noted,
``so a telework program could prove a helpful recruiting tool,
especially for younger folks, because they're comfortable with the
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to emphasizing the positives, be prepared to soothe
worries about potential negatives. ``You need to convince senior
managers that it is not anarchy,'' Birstler said. ``It's not
undisciplined. It's not unregulated.''
</P>
<P>
   Make clear to employees and managers that telecommuting is not
an alternative to finding outside child care, both experts
emphasized. If you have young children at home during the workday,
Ms. Martin said, you need to arrange for the same type of care as
if you were in the office.
</P>
<P>
   Birstler noted that Merrill Lynch requires its telecommuters
with dependents to provide documentation of these arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Managers and employees will need to define objectives and ways
to measure telecommuting's success, he said. ``Get down to the
nitty-gritty,'' he urged, by defining work hours and how often
employees must come into the office.
</P>
<P>
   Rules and memos can help clarify expectations. Merrill Lynch,
Birstler said, has chosen a highly structured program: Employees
apply formally for telecommuting, undergo training and participate
in regular follow-ups like focus groups and surveys.
</P>
<P>
   All this may be more trouble than employees thought they were
bargaining for. But if they are serious about winning the freedom
to work from home, they should be willing to jump through a few
hoops. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by E-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y.
10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
