s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$A     08-05 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finding an Early End To Mortgage Insurance &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For consumers who have railed against private mortgage
insurance, a recent hard-won triumph may be even sweeter than they
thought.
</P>
<P>
   The Homeowners Protection Act, which took effect on July 29,
gives people obtaining mortgages the right to request cancellation
of the insurance when their equity reaches 20 percent. At 22
percent, the insurance is to be canceled automatically. The
insurance, intended to protect a lender against default, typically
costs $25 to $80 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Some proponents of tougher legislation were not satisfied,
noting that the law does not require increases in a home's value to
be included in the 20 percent equity plateau, makes an exception
for undefined ``high-risk'' loans and excludes existing loans.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a case in which an industry is going beyond what's
required. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, the government-chartered
private companies that are the biggest sources of home financing,
will require that private mortgage insurance end for existing loans
halfway through the term of the mortgage; smaller lenders are
expected to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac will allow borrowers who
want to drop the insurance at 20 percent equity to factor in
appreciation when making their case, and the lenders have decided
to forget about designating some mortgages as high risk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert D. Hershey Jr. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's Easier by e-Mail &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You want a colleague to rewrite a report. Or you need to inform
your assistant that someone else is getting that promotion. If your
interest is in telling a co-worker the whole bitter truth, you may
want to do it by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   In a study by Stephanie Watts Sussman, an assistant professor of
information systems at Case Western Reserve University, and Lee
Sproull, a professor of business at New York University, 117 Boston
University students were asked to give other students comments
about their resumes from the campus career center.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that the student messengers reported positive
feedback faithfully. But when there were negatives, they tended to
soften them when speaking in person or by phone, distorting the
facts. In e-mail, the distortion was significantly less.
</P>
<P>
   The study did not focus on how recipients might feel about
getting bad news from the computer, rather than from a human voice.
The professors, however, say face-to-face delivery is always best.
</P>
<P>
   Susan J. Wells
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
