<HEADER>
A7458 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-ITEMS06-CO     08-05 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ITEMS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thumbs up To Wally Dallenbach
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wally Dallenbach turned in his finest performance of
the NASCAR season at Pocono, less than a week after being told he
would not return next season as the driver of the No. 25 Chevy for
Hendrick Motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-place finish at the Pennsylvania 500 was Dallenbach's
first top-five finish the season. It came right after a strong
showing in the previous race, seventh place at New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't drive any harder when I'm out of a job or with a
job,'' Dallenbach said. ``(The crew) work hard all year, and I know
what we had and what kind of team we have. I drive my guts out for
them every time we go racing. I don't need any motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   To Jerry Nadeau, who will take over the No. 25 car for Hendrick
Motorsports next season. In his first race after learning the good
news, the rookie from Danbury, Conn., looked more like a bumper-car
driver than a stock-car driver.
</P>
<P>
   At Pocono, Nadeau's first victim was Bill Elliott, who was
running third at the time. As the two cars sped through turn 3,
Nadeau tapped the left rear of the No. 94 Ford and sent the car
spinning into the wall. (However, the rookie did make a public
apology to Elliott after the race).
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Wallace was hit by Nadaeu on lap 168 of 200, knocking both
drivers out of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Nadeau should've known it wasn't going to be his lucky weekend
after wrecking a car during pre-race practice.
</P>
<P>
   HOMETOWN FELLAS
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis native John Andretti returns home this week for the
Brickyard 400. The hometown hero ran among the leaders in last
year's race and finished seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everybody there, from (track president) Tony George to
the guys who sweep the garage,'' Andretti said. ``I know all of the
gate guards, mainly because I've tried to sneak past every one of
them at some point when I was a kid. We'd sneak into the garage,
they'd find us and throw us out. Then we'd sneak back in again.
</P>
<P>
   ``After they built the new garages, it became almost impossible
to sneak in.
</P>
<P>
   ``By that point, I had to become a driver, because it didn't
look like I was getting back into the garage any other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Irwin, another homegrown product, is giving the local fans
plenty of opportunities to watch him drive this week. Irwin, who
turned 30 today, participated in a USAC Silver Bullet Series race
on Wednesday. He'll run in tonight's Grand National race and then
will drive the No. 28 Ford for Robert Yates Racing on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one thing, I get to stay at my mom and dad's house,''
Irwin said. ``My mom already knows my favorite dinner and is
working on it. I enjoy getting to see all my family and friends.
They'll all get to see me race while I'm here and will support me
at every race I'm in all week.''
</P>
<P>
   THEY SAID IT
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any plans for the Sterling Marlin Museum but,
with an Indy trophy to go along with those Daytona 500 ones, maybe
we'd have to start thinking about one.''
</P>
<P>
   _ STERLING MARLIN, on what it would mean to win Brickyard 400
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA LAPS
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte and Rick Mast are the only drivers to complete all
19 races this season. . . . Ernie Irvan has won the last two poles
at Indianapolis Motor Speedway. . . . The only drivers to compete
in both an Indianapolis 500 and a Brickyard 400 in the same year
are Andretti (1995) and Robby Gordon ('97). In the near future,
expect rookie hot shot Tony Stewart to become the third driver to
do it. . . . Stewart has been the top-finishing rookie in 18 races
this year. BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   0: Times Jeff Gordon failed in first-round qualifying this
season, the only driver not to fail in 19 NASCAR races.
</P>
<P>
   6: DNF's (Did Not Finish) received by Geoffrey Bodine and Kenny
Wallace, both co-leaders of the dubious category.
</P>
<P>
   11: Races Dale Jarrett needed for his rise from 36th to first in
the Winston Cup points standings.
</P>
<P>
   17: The number of times Jarrett has finished in the top 10 at
races this year.
</P>
<P>
   413: Longest active winless streak in consecutive races, by
Michael Waltrip.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
