u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAR-FRAUD-ART-2TAKES     08-05 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAR-FRAUD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC SAYS BEAR STEARNS SUBSIDIARY HAD CENTRAL ROLE IN FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Securities and Exchange Commission charged
Thursday that a subsidiary of Bear Stearns Cos., Wall Street's
sixth-largest brokerage firm, was a major force behind a fraud that
led to millions of dollars in investor losses.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns settled the fraud charges with the commission and
the Manhattan district attorney without admitting or denying the
allegations, and agreed to pay $38.5 million in fines and
restitution. The commission also brought securities fraud charges
against Richard Harriton, the president of the subsidiary, who
resigned and plans to fight the charges.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement ends a three-year investigation into Bear
Stearns' role handling securities trades for A.R. Baron, a small
New York brokerage firm that collapsed in 1996 and caused $75
million in investor losses.
</P>
<P>
   By holding Bear Stearns accountable in the Baron case, the SEC
makes clear that any firm, legal, accounting or financial, that
helps another commit a fraud must take responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   In its settlement, the commission described a pattern of
misconduct that is surprising for a firm of Bear Stearns' stature.
The SEC said that Bear Stearns took extraordinary steps to keep
A.R. Baron, an obviously troubled firm, in business. It knew that
Baron completed numerous trades that were unauthorized, yet the
larger firm took money from accounts to pay for the unauthorized
trades and refused to return the funds to the customers even after
Baron admitted as much.
</P>
<P>
   Although the $38.5 million that Bear has agreed to pay is
immaterial to the wealthy firm, the settlement will damage its
reputation among clients, creditors and competitors. Of that
amount, $5 million is a fine paid to the SEC, the sixth-largest
fine ever levied against a brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the investigation, Bear Stearns maintained that it
did nothing wrong. Bear Stearns said Thursday that the fraud
charges were merely technical in nature.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Walker, director of enforcement at the SEC, disagreed.
``Bear Stearns Securities Corp. is charged with causing a massive
fraud, a fraud that cost investors millions,'' Walker said. ``There
is nothing new in the proposition that those participating in a
fraud should be held accountable for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement is by no means the end of the investigations into
Bear Stearns' activities as the Wall Street leader in clearing, the
business of processing securities trades for other smaller firms
and providing them with capital to operate. Federal prosecutors in
Brooklyn and Manhattan continue to examine Bear Stearns' clearing
relationships with two other small brokerage firms charged with
bilking investors out of hundreds of millions of dollars in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference in lower Manhattan Thursday, Robert
Morgenthau, the Manhattan district attorney, said that his criminal
investigation into Harriton's conduct also remains active. In a
statement, Harriton's lawyer called the SEC civil complaint
baseless and said that his client would fight the charges.
</P>
<P>
   James Cayne, the chief executive officer of Bear Stearns who has
vigorously defended Harriton throughout the investigation, said:
``We are disappointed that Dick is leaving, but we understand that
his considerations as an individual are different than ours as a
corporation. We respect his decision.'' Asked if Bear Stearns is
paying Harriton's legal bills, a firm spokeswoman declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The details laid out in the SEC's 23-page cease and desist order
belie past claims by Bear Stearns' management that its powerful
clearing subsidiary had only a passive role, if any at all, in the
Baron fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the commission began imposing new rules for
clearing firms that require them to notify regulators of customer
complaints, rules intended to prevent such transgressions in the
future. Historically, clearing firms have argued that they simply
process trades and are therefore not responsible for policing
practices at the smaller brokerage firms they count as customers.
Those days are over. ``This case establishes that clearing firms
cannot simply turn a blind eye to fraud,'' Morgenthau said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the SEC, Bear Stearns did that and more. Although
Bear Stearns was aware of excessive unauthorized trading in Baron
accounts, Walker said the firm helped keep A.R. Baron in business,
allowing it to defraud customers.
</P>
<P>
   The violations upon which the SEC order are based took place
from September 1995 through July 1996. The SEC alleges that many of
Bear Stearns' violations came as Harriton tried to protect the
company from large losses as a result of its clearing relationship
with the financially troubled A.R. Baron.
</P>
<P>
   It took only two months of transactions with A.R. Baron for Bear
Stearns employees to see signs of fraud in Baron's practices.
Almost immediately, Bear Stearns began taking steps to insulate
itself from the smaller firm's fraudulent activities. On Sept. 22,
Harriton required that all Baron's trades in customer accounts be
faxed to Bear Stearns; only those trades that the firm determined
would not increase its credit exposure to Baron were allowed. This
meant that many trades ordered by Baron's customers were not
completed.
</P>
<P>
   According to the SEC, Bear Stearns not only disregarded the
instructions of Baron's customers, but repeatedly charged those
customers with trades that it knew were unauthorized. In one case,
involving a Baron customer Diaward Steel Works Ltd., Bear Stearns
took it upon itself to sell $1 million of the customers' securities
to cover trades that the clearing firm knew to be unauthorized and
that Diaward refused to pay for.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   According to the SEC, Bear Stearns also refused to return
securities and funds that it had taken to pay for unauthorized
trades to their rightful owners, even though Baron had told Bear
Stearns the trades were unauthorized. Bear Stearns also repeatedly
asked for credit extensions to cover Baron's unauthorized trades
and helped Baron to operate even when the firm's capital fell below
the amount required by regulators for it to be able to continue
conducting business.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Harriton encouraged employees to discard documents
relating to A.R. Baron's operations, a violation of securities laws
that require firms to maintain such records.
</P>
<P>
   When HMA Investments Inc., a Baron customer, complained to Bear
Stearns about unauthorized trades in its account and provided Bear
Stearns with a letter from two Baron brokers admitting the trades
were unauthorized, Harriton refused to reverse the transactions. He
also froze accounts HMA held at another brokerage firm whose trades
Bear Stearns cleared. In January 1996, Harriton directed Bear
Stearns to liquidate HMA's accounts at the other brokerage firm and
credited Baron with the payment.
</P>
<P>
   Fiduciary Management Services Ltd., a private company based in
the Bahamas, lost $890,000 in the A.R. Baron fraud. Ian Barry, the
firm's investment manager, was vigilant about notifying Bear
Stearns when unauthorized trades showed up in its account. But Bear
Stearns simply referred him back to A.R. Baron.
</P>
<P>
   Barry initially felt confident that the problems would be
addressed. He said: ``I had a definite comfort level knowing Bear
Stearns was there. I feel I acted in accordance with the
requirements and I was let down.'' Fiduciary took its case to Lewis
Lowenfels, a prominent securities lawyer who was one of the first
to recognize that clearing firms were not completely insulated from
liability stemming from the behavior of their clearing firm
customers. When told of the settlement, Barry said: ``We hope that
this will finally bring our recovery efforts to a satisfactory
conclusion. We always felt that Bear Stearns bore certain
responsibilities in this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   In its charges against Harriton, the SEC alleges that Harriton
had a deal with Andrew Bressman, chairman of A.R. Baron, to profit
personally from initial public offerings underwritten by the firm.
Only the fact that Baron failed before the stock offering could be
completed prevented Harriton from making good on this arrangement,
which would have been outright securities fraud.
</P>
<P>
   William McLucas, partner at Wilmer Cutler &AMP; Pickering in
Washington and a former director of enforcement at the SEC when the
case began, called the Bear Stearns settlement a warning flag to
others. ``It says to a clearing firm you cannot ignore clear and
unequivocal evidence of violations of the law and abuse of
customers by the introducing firm, and if you do, you do so at your
peril.''
</P>
<P>
   In settling with the SEC, Bear Stearns agreed to cease and
desist from committing or causing any such frauds in the future. It
also agreed to retain, within one month's time, an independent
consultant, to be appointed by the SEC, to conduct a review of the
firm's supervisory and compliance policies.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement announced Thursday, Bear Stearns
agreed to pay $1 million to the state of New York, $1 million to
the City of New York and $1.5 million to the district attorney's
office to cover the costs of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   That Bear Stearns was a direct cause of a significant securities
fraud is a black mark on the record of its chairman, Alan
Greenberg, and president, James Cayne, upon whose watch these
transgressions took place. The board of directors could be
vulnerable to charges that it was not attending to details as well.
</P>
<P>
   A clue to how a firm as big and well-known as Bear Stearns could
have been an integral part of such a fraud may lie in a promotional
piece Bear Stearns published celebrating its scrappy corporate
culture. Among the firm's self-avowed cultural mottoes is this one:
``Protect the Money Machine.''
</P>
<P>
   State securities regulators have already begun to look into
matters involving clearing firms. Joseph Borg, the Alabama
securities commissioner, said, ``I am concerned that the facts in
the order clearly point out that Bear Stearns knew of the problems
that were existing and rather than recognizing their civic
responsibility to the investing public, they apparently went the
other way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
