<HEADLINE>
GORDON WINS BRICKYARD POLE IN RECORD FASHION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Jeff Gordon said there's no mystery to his
mastery when it comes to qualifying at the Indianapolis Motor
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no `mastery' to it. If the car sticks, it sticks. If
it doesn't, it doesn't,'' Gordon said after pasting together a
record-shattering, pole-winning 2.5-mile lap for tomorrow's
Brickyard 400. ``I'm shocked. Yes I am, believe it or not. I was
waiting for somebody to get that perfect lap today.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth of 54 drivers to make a qualifying attempt, Gordon's
time of 50.108 seconds/179.612 mph withstood all challenges and
wiped Ernie Irvan's year-old records of 50.169 seconds/179.394 mph
off the NASCAR record book at IMS.
</P>
<P>
   The pole was a series-leading seventh in 20 races for Gordon,
the three-time and reigning series champion who stands sixth in
points and virtually out of title contention. But IMS continues to
remain Gordon's domain on several fronts. Before he became a NASCAR
superstar, Gordon won the inaugural Brickyard 400 in 1994. Last
summer, he became the race's first two-time champion.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's pole was Gordon's third at this event, and his fifth
start of third or better in six Cup races at the historic
racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is a native of California, but grew up in nearby
Pittsboro, Ind., and began his racing career there while a
teen-ager. On Wednesday night, the people of his adopted hometown
10 miles west of here honored him by naming a stretch of highway
Jeff Gordon Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have stuck me with some little road, but they got
me an exit off the highway,'' Gordon said of a ceremony that
reunited him with many former high school classmates and racing
friends. ``It was pretty neat. That's how my weekend got started,
and I think that was added inspiration today _ the reaction I got
from the fans and the race car I had out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Gordon in the two-car front row is Mark Martin at
178.941 mph in the No. 6 Valvoline Ford Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   Journeyman David Green will start third, his first top-10
qualifying effort of 1999, after a lap at 178.902 mph in the No. 41
Kodiak Chevrolet Monte Carlo. Green's previous best qualifying
effort in 1999 was 17th at Dover, Del., and he had failed to
qualify twice. Green tied his Cup career-best, set at Rockingham,
N.C., in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup points leader Dale Jarrett, who has a comfortable
254-point lead on Martin, took the fourth spot at 178.859 mph in
the No. 88 Quality Care/Ford Credit Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   The top 25 spots were locked-in, with second-round qualifying
and provisionals to fill out the remainder of the 43-car field
today.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who has won four races this season, ripped off his
record after posting only six practice laps in a new No. 24 DuPont
Automotive Finishes Chevy yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like we were ready,'' said Gordon, who reminded that
he and his Hendrick Motorsports crew had put in a rigorous test
session here with General Motors teams last month. ``They wore me
out here testing for two days _ two cars and I don't know how many
miles. But it was a lot, a lot more than we'll run on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who is 254 points behind Jarrett, earned his 15th top-10
qualifying effort of the season and fourth top-10 start in six Cup
races at IMS. But as usual, he was overshadowed by Gordon, his
nemesis from last year's points chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's \RGordon\S a better driver than most of us, if not all of
us,'' Martin said. ``And I think he drives a better car than most
of us, if not all of us. I mean that as a compliment in both
respects, not only for the team, but for the driver as well.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
