<HEADLINE>
A GIFT TO AMERICA'S HEALTH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WILLIAM A. JACKSON, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We all make health care choices every day. For most of us, the
decisions come down to spreading margarine instead of butter on our
toast, climbing out of bed early for a morning jog rather than
hitting the snooze button or saying yes or no to that piece of
blueberry pie.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who live in America's poorest urban and rural
communities, health care decisions can be considerably harder. I
know better than most. I practice medicine in Detroit's inner city.
</P>
<P>
   Would you undergo an annual physical examination, for instance,
if paying the health insurance deductible left you short at the
grocery store? How long could you stand an aching tooth if getting
treatment meant not covering this month's rent?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, my patients know that money is not an obstacle to
health care. I am here for them, no matter their circumstances.
Many other doctors, in Detroit and elsewhere, take a similar
approach. But in inner-city and rural America, there are fewer and
fewer of us to go around.
</P>
<P>
   That's what keeps me up at night. I'm 65, and I tell my patients
I'll live forever. But actuarial tables say otherwise, and I worry
about having someone to hand my stethoscope to.
</P>
<P>
   The need grows daily. Census figures show that one of three
Americans live in what I call medically underserved inner-city and
rural communities. People in those areas suffer disproportionately
from cancer, hypertension, stroke, diabetes, kidney disease and
AIDS, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, there is an urgent need for greater numbers of
competent, compassionate primary care physicians for these
communities. But where will they come from?
</P>
<P>
   Many come from four traditionally African-American medical
schools: Morehouse in Atlanta, Howard in Washington, Drew in Los
Angeles and Meharry Medical College in Nashville. My research shows
that significant numbers of all physicians who practice in
underserved communities are African-Americans. For the last 130
years, about 75 percent of African-American doctors have trained at
these four schools.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, like communities they serve, Morehouse, Howard,
Drew and Meharry have big financial needs, and all have modest
endowments.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, I decided to do something about it. I attended a
seminar on charitable giving and found that I could make a
difference, not just with my time, but also with my money.
</P>
<P>
   At this point in my life, I am financially secure. I was able to
donate two variable life insurance policies with a total death
benefit of $1 million to the Morehouse School of Medicine. Why life
insurance? Because making a gift of it makes me feel like a million
bucks without spending a million bucks. Now, while my patients
worry that I won't live forever, the president of the medical
school and my longtime friend, Dr. Louis Sullivan, worries that I
will.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another benefit. Paying monthly insurance premiums
_ as opposed to writing a check for $1 million _ affords me the
financial leverage to preserve the bulk of my estate for my two
grown sons and two nieces. They wholeheartedly support my
philanthropy because they understand that it's the right thing to
do. But they also know that by remembering Morehouse, I'm not
forgetting them.
</P>
<P>
   The gift to Morehouse, as well as the overwhelming need of these
schools, has inspired me. Last year, with help from the Hartford
Life Insurance Co., I established a foundation, with the goal of
raising $3 billion to $4 billion over 10 to 20 years to benefit the
endowments of Morehouse, Howard, Drew and Meharry.
</P>
<P>
   The goal sounds optimistic. But consider the potential donor
pool. The American Medical Association alone has more than 291,000
member physicians. If just 1 percent of them donated $1 million
each in life insurance, we would be near our goal. And that doesn't
count the hundreds of thousands of other professionals and business
executives across America who could make a difference for our
poorest communities. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William A. Jackson has been in general practice for nearly
40 years. Submit your account of struggling or succeeding as a
worker, consumer, investor or entrepreneur to My Money, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y.
10036, or by e-mail to mymoney(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
