<SLUG> BC-BBO-MCGWIRE-ANDRO-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Mass., Pa.)  
 McGWIRE SAYS HE ENDED USE OF ANDRO MONTHS AGO  
(rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark McGwire disclosed Wednesday that he has stopped using the
androstenedione dietary supplement because he was worried about the
possible influence that his continued use could have on children.
But McGwire also added that he still does not believe there is
anything wrong with it and that adults should be permitted to use
the legal supplement.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who acknowledged that he took androstenedione while
establishing a major league record of 70 homers in one season with
the St. Louis Cardinals last year, said that he has not taken the
supplement for the last four months. Sales of androstenedione
increased dramatically after McGwire disclosed during his historic
season that he used the supplement to help intensify his workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought long and hard about it, and I don't like the way it
was portrayed, like I was the endorser of the product, which I
wasn't,'' McGwire told reporters at Busch Stadium in St. Louis. ``I
don't like how it's portrayed that young kids take it because of
me. I always discouraged children from taking it.''
</P>
<P>
   Andro, as the supplement is commonly known, is sold legally over
the counter and on the Internet in the United States, even though
some medical experts believe it is essentially an anabolic steroid.
The supplement is banned by the NFL, the NCAA and the International
Olympic Committee because these organizations believe it enhances
performance and could be a potentially harmful drug. But baseball
has not banned it and has publicly refused to condone or condemn
it.
</P>
<P>
   While Commissioner Bud Selig praised McGwire's decision by
saying he has ``a lot of faith in Mark,'' he said that it would not
influence baseball's neutral stance on the supplement. Major League
Baseball and the Players Association are jointly funding a research
study by Harvard University on andro, and the findings are expected
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go forward with the study,'' Selig said.
``There has been a lot of time put into the study.''
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude of McGwire's surprising decision reached the White
House, where Gen. Barry R. McCaffrey, director of national drug
control policy, lauded McGwire Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message Mark McGwire sends to our young people by walking
away from this substance is a powerful one,'' McCaffrey said in a
statement. ``We thank McGwire for his leadership and hope that
other athletes will follow his lead.'' McCaffrey has asked the Drug
Enforcement Administration to label andro a steroid so it can be
removed from stores.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was so thrilled by McGwire's announcement. Dr.
Charles Yesalis, a Penn State professor and co-author of ``The
Steroids Game,'' said: ``It's too little, too late. I have nothing
against the guy. He seems like a good guy. I really believe that he
wants to do the best by kids. But the fact of the matter is he
dropped the ball on this one. When it was first made public a year
ago that he did this, he should have said, `Even though I'm not
breaking any of baseball's rules, I'm going to quit because this
sends a bad message to kids, and I'm sorry.'''
</P>
<P>
   Andro is a synthetic form of a male hormone that occurs
naturally in the body and is converted to testosterone. Those with
higher levels of testosterone usually have increased muscle mass.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Iowa State University study of 30 men found that andro
did not help build muscle, but instead raised the risk of heart
disease, pancreatic cancer and breast enlargement. Doctors have
maligned the study because the test subjects took dosages far
smaller than body builders routinely ingest.
</P>
<P>
   After McGwire said in spring training that andro was legal and
seemingly indicated he would keep using it, he said Wednesday that
he had stopped. With 42 homers, the 35-year-old McGwire was tied
with Chicago's Sammy Sosa for the major league lead entering
Thursday night's games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This showed that andro is irrelevant,'' McGwire explained.
``I've done this season what I've done my whole career. I've been
saying it all along that you don't hit homers because of andro.
It's my hands and my eyes and my brain. There have been studies
proving that it doesn't do anything to improve strength anyway,
which has always been my claim.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's timing of the revelation was curious because he is one
homer away from his 500th career homer, the majority of which were
hit without using andro. While McGwire said that he did not
disclose that he had given up andro because no one had asked him
until Wednesday, a reporter from a New York newspaper tried to
interview him for an extensive article on andro last month and he
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   If McGwire had made his disclosure before the season and then
did not produce homers as prodigiously as he has while averaging 60
over the last three years, there surely would have been more
speculation that andro had helped him in 1998 and that may have
influenced his timing. Without using andro, McGwire is on pace to
hit 63 this season.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with more than 75 players, team trainers and club
officials earlier this season, it was estimated that 5 to 10
percent of the 750 major leaguers use andro. Medical experts
estimated that the number is higher, but baseball does not test for
any substances so it is impossible to know who is using andro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe there's nothing wrong with it,'' McGwire said.
``But if I have a message for kids, it's that you don't necessarily
have to follow what somebody who's in the public eye does. If
you're an adult, you elect to choose your own destiny.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
