<HEADER>
A7478 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALA-SHOOTINGS06-COX     08-05 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-SHOOTINGS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 dead after workplace shooting in Alabama
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PELHAM, Ala. _ As Jerry Shinault, general manager of the Taco
Bell at the Cahaba Valley Road exit off Interstate 65, arrived at
work at 8 a.m. Thursday, he noticed ``about 20'' police cars up the
hill at an air conditioning business. He asked a Federal Express
driver who stopped in what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not something like what happened in Atlanta _ and
sure as hell it was,'' Shinault said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, Allen Eugene Miller, 34, allegedly shot to
death two people at the air conditioning business where he worked,
then shot another person to death at a nearby specialty gas
distributor where he had previously worked, said Pelham Police
Chief Allan Wade.
</P>
<P>
   Police charged Miller with three counts of capital murder.
Authorities captured Miller as he allegedly tried to escape in his
car on I-65.
</P>
<P>
   The Pelham slayings came one week after Mark O. Barton of
Morrow, Ga., shot to death nine people at a pair of Atlanta stock
brokerages. Police later discovered the bludgeoned bodies of
Barton's wife and two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting closer to home,'' said Shinault, who lives in
this suburb 20 miles south of Birmingham. ``But what are you going
to do about it? I don't think people are shocked by it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelham, a town of about 10,000, is a mix of upscale subdivisions
and rural landscape sculpted in the foothills of the Appalachians.
Signs on some highways warn of rock slides. But the interstate exit
where police say Miller's shooting spree started is pure commercial
suburbia, marked by a Cracker Barrel, KFC, McDonald's and Best
Western.
</P>
<P>
   After allegedly killing Lee Holbrooks, 32, of Pelham, and
Christopher Yancy, 28, of Alabaster, at Ferguson Enterprises,
Miller drove five miles to Post Airgas, which sells gases like
oxygen and helium. On the loading dock of the sea-green building,
slender tanks stood like 5-foot-high bullets _ brown, bronze, black
and green.
</P>
<P>
   At the gas office, police said, Miller killed former co-worker
Terry Jarvis, 39, of Montevallo.
</P>
<P>
   Police offered no motive for the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me nervous,'' said Richey Henninger, a serviceman for
Sunset Homes, one of the several mobile home dealers on U.S. 31
near Post Airgas.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Miller, the suspect's mother in rural Billingsley 50
miles away, said her son, who lived with her, had no history of
bothering people. On Thursday, she told reporters, he ``went off to
work just as he always does. He left here like he always does, with
a 7-Up and a couple of things of biscuits and sausage.''
</P>
<P>
   As the afternoon sun heated up the black pavement, Reba Sulava
filled up her Olds Eighty-Eight at the combination Shell station
and Sunny food convenience store across from Ferguson Enterprises,
where the shootings started. A Houston resident, she was in town
visiting her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time there's a shooting, you just cringe because you
wonder if it's someone you know,'' Sulava said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when Barton opened fire in Atlanta, Sulava had reason
to cringe: Her stepson lives in Atlanta and she immediately thought
of him. He was nowhere near Barton's rampage, but Sulava's heart
raced till she confirmed he was OK.
</P>
<P>
   To Sulava, such violent rampages represent a national sickness.
``It just says our country is going to pot,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from the Virginia headquarters of Ferguson
Enterprises called the Pelham shootings an ``act of senseless
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are greatly appreciative of the support and assistance we
have received from the police and the community, and we are fully
cooperating with the police investigation,'' the company release
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our prayers and condolences are with the families of the
victims. Our focus today is to do all that we can to support the
families of our slain associates and other associates at our Pelham
location.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
