<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAR STEARNS AGREES TO PAY FINES OF $38.5 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns has agreed to pay $38.5 million in fines and
restitution relating to its role as the processor of securities
trades for A.R. Baron, a small New York brokerage firm that
collapsed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Although the $38.5 million that Bear Stearns has agreed to pay
is immaterial to the wealthy firm, the damage to its reputation
among clients, creditors and peers will almost certainly be great.
</P>
<P>
   FCC RELAXES TV OWNERSHIP RULES
</P>
<P>
   William E. Kennard, the chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission, said the group has decided to relax rules that have
limited television station ownership. The new provisions will allow
a single company or network to own two stations in the nation's
largest cities. One immediate result of the decision may be a rush
by big TV companies to buy stations in cities where they already
own a station.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS PASSES TAX CUT PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Congress approved a Republican plan that would lower the income
taxes of all Americans who owe them, but President Clinton has said
he intends to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL SALES ROSE 6.1 PERCENRT IN JULY
</P>
<P>
   The strong economy combined with a heat wave blanketing much of
the country gave Americans a reason to head to air-conditioned
stores and malls in July, pushing retail sales to a surprisingly
strong 6.1 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   GAIN IN OUTPUT SLOWS AS COSTS RISE
</P>
<P>
   Growth in worker productivity slowed considerably in the second
quarter, to an annual rate of 1.3 percent, while unit labor costs
surged at an annual rate of 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   MAJORITY STAKE SOLD IN TRAVEL SITE
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbluth International, the travel management company, bought
a majority stake in Biztravel.com, an Internet site for making
business travel arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   YIELD ON THE 30-YEAR TREASURY FALLS
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices rose for a second day as the pricing of a huge
debt issue by Wal-Mart Stores failed to hurt the sale of government
paper. But traders expect that Treasuries could have a difficult
time pushing higher in the weeks ahead, with about $44 billion more
in debt sales scheduled. The yield on the 30-year issue fell to
6.04 percent from 6.09 percent.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE GIANTS MAKE A DEAL IN CANADA
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and British Telecommunications said they had agreed to
invest almost $1 billion in a mobile phone company controlled by
Rogers Communications of Toronto, creating the framework for a
cable and phone communications network to take on the domestic
giant, Bell Canada.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE'S BANK STRUGGLE CONTINUES
</P>
<P>
   With only a day left before investors must choose sides in
France's three-way bank struggle, Banque Nationale de Paris
appeared to inch closer to victory in its hostile bid for Paribas,
one of two rivals it is seeking to control. But investors in the
other target, Societe Generale, appeared deeply split, raising the
prospect that a final verdict may fall to French regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ABERCROMBIE &AMP; FITCH TURNS TO TV
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, the clothing retailer that aims its apparel
at college-age consumers, is expanding its marketing campaign from
magazine-style catalogues to commercials that will run on cable TV
and on monitors in stores nationwide. Stuart Elliott: Advertising.
</P>
</TEXT>
