<HEADLINE>
BENTSEN, CARTER, FORD TO RECEIVE MEDAL OF FREEDOM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lloyd Bentsen, a former Treasury secretary and
senator from Texas, has been selected along with former Presidents
Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter to receive the Presidential Medal of
Freedom, the nation's highest civilian honor.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is to present medals to Bentsen, Ford and
seven others Wednesday at a White House ceremony. Carter and his
wife Rosalynn, who also was chosen for the award, will receive
their medals from Clinton on Monday in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Ford and Carter leaves former George Bush as
the only living president who has not received the award. Bush
presented the medal to President Reagan in 1993 only days before
leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen, Clinton's first Treasury secretary, was the Democratic
Party's vice presidential nominee in 1988. When he joined the
administration, he had served 22 years in the Senate and six years
as chairman of the Senate Finance Committee. His Senate career
began in 1970 when he defeated Bush, the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Bentsen left Clinton's Cabinet to work as an
international business consultant in the Houston office of Verner,
Liipfert, Bernhard, McPherson and Hand, a Washington-based law
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen suffered two strokes in 1998, the second of which kept
him in the hospital and a Galveston, Texas, rehabilitation center
for 3 1/2 months.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, a Republican who became the 38th president with the
resignation of Richard Nixon, will be recognized for ``his honesty
and integrity'' and his efforts to restore confidence in government
after the Watergate scandal that led to Nixon's departure.
</P>
<P>
   Carter will be cited for his four years as the nation's 39th
president and for pushing humanitarian causes, human rights,
democracy and peace since leaving the White House in early 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Other Medal of Freedom recipients are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Edgar M. Bronfman Sr., president of the World Jewish Congress,
who is being cited for working to ensure basic rights for Jews,
fighting anti-Semitism and pushing for retrieval of the assets of
Holocaust victims and their families.
</P>
<P>
   _ Evy Dubrow, an advocate for more than 50 years of laws to
improve domestic labor conditions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sister M. Isolina Ferre, founder of community service centers,
clinics and programs to empower the poor in Puerto Rico, New York
and Appalachia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oliver White Hill, a civil rights lawyer best known for
litigating one of the school desegregation cases that became the
landmark Brown vs. Board of Education case in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   _ Max Kampelman, lawyer, diplomat and negotiator in Democratic
and Republican administrations who, according to the White House,
helped lay ``the foundation for long-term arms reductions between
the United States and the Soviet Union.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Edgar Wayburn, five-time president and a member of the board
of directors of the Sierra Club for almost 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
