<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOTHA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTHA NEEDS TO GET BY BRIGGS TO MOVE UP LADDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. _ Francois Botha had never been knocked out.
He wondered what it would feel like, and he feared it more than any
opponent. His fear did not make him more cautious because he walked
chin-first into Mike Tyson's right hand and awoke with the referee
standing over him delivering the 10 count.
</P>
<P>
   It was even more painful for Botha because he was completely in
control of the fight and had won all four of the previous rounds
before the fateful punch. Six months after his first knockout
experience, Botha (39-2) is looking to avoid a repeat as he takes
on Shannon Briggs (31-2) on Saturday night at Trump's Taj Mahal in
Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   The fight will be broadcast on pay-per-view by Showtime
Entertainment Television.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knockout did him good,'' said Jan Botha, Francois' father
and training camp cook. ``He was fooling around and he paid for it.
He lost his concentration. Now he's concentrating more than he ever
has.''
</P>
<P>
   The knockout also shook up Botha's corner. He fired trainer
Panama Lewis and hired Abel Sanchez, who worked in Botha's corner
as a second when Botha defeated Axel Schulz for the International
Boxing Federation heavyweight championship in 1995. Lewis is able
to train fighters, but he cannot work their corners because he was
convicted of taking the padding out of a boxer's gloves during a
bout.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Botha said his son never made any progress as a boxer under
Lewis. ``Panama let Francois do whatever he wanted to do, because
Francois is a good athlete,'' Jan Botha said. ``But he never
improved. He was doing the same things every fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez has been working with Botha for eight weeks and has been
trying to help him improve his punching ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've revamped his stance to get him leverage on his punches,
especially his left hook,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   Botha, who weighed in at 232 pounds, and Briggs, who weighed in
at 230 pounds, are in similar positions heading into the fight.
Like Briggs, Botha, 30, is trying to work his way back up the
ladder of heavyweight championship contenders. After he defeated
Schulz, Botha held the title for one month before he was stripped
for testing positive for steroids. Botha said he was taking
medication for a shoulder injury, and he should not have been
stripped of the title.
</P>
<P>
   He fought Michael Moorer for the IBF title and was stopped on a
technical knockout in the 12th round. Botha took a tremendous
beating in the fight, cementing his reputation as a durable
fighter.
</P>
<P>
   The Moorer fight was the brink-of-death-type fight that Briggs
has not been in. That is why Botha would like to take Briggs' into
the later rounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7483 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALPINE-CALPINE_SFCHR     08-05 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALPINE-CALPINE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Bay Area Agencies Buy Green Power  &HT;     By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Calpine Corp. will light the Golden Gate Bridge and dozens of other
government facilities with green power as a result of a deal struck
this week by the San Jose power company and the Association of Bay
Area Governments.
<P>
   The ABAG contract calls for Calpine to provide renewable power
to some 59 cities, counties and public agencies including the
Golden Gate Bridge district. Taxpayers are expected to save $1
million a year as a result of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Power from Calpine's Geysers steam field in Lake and Sonoma
counties will be earmarked for ABAG members. ABAG expects to buy
roughly 5 percent of The Geysers' (CQ) &LR; output, providing a market
for that power, at least for bookkeeping purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The actual electricity ABAG members use could come from any
power generator, since once it goes into the transmission system,
electricity from all sources gets blended together. But for every
kilowatt hour of energy burned by ABAG members, one kilowatt hour
of power from The Geysers must be put into the system.
</P>
<P>
   Calpine bought 18 of the 21 power plants operating in The
Geysers field last May from Pacific Gas and Electric Co. They
produce enough electricity to light 1.2 million homes, making
Calpine the largest geothermal power producer in America.
</P>
<P>
   The ABAG-Calpine contract looks like a good deal for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ABAG gets to support clean energy and do so at a savings to its
member agencies. Calpine gets a ``marquee customer,'' whose
association will lend credibility to its green power marketing
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If local governments get their power from renewable sources,
it sends out the message to citizens that renewables are legitimate
and that consumers should care about who gets their electricity
dollars,'' said John White, executive director of the nonprofit
Center for Energy Efficiency and Renewable Technologies in
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ABAG members could save roughly $1 million a year, collectively,
as a result of the decision to move to renewable energy, said ABAG
power pool manager Elena Schmid in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   That's partly because the state's deregulation law created a
$540 million pot of money to lend temporary support to renewable
power production in this state.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that money is earmarked for rebates to customers using
renewable power. It reduces the cost of that power by 1.5 cents per
kilowatt hour, enough in some cases to make renewable power cheaper
than power coming from natural gas and coal that carry an
environmental cost due to pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The subsidies come from ratepayers and will expire in 2002.
Schmid said it makes sense for public agencies to take advantage of
the ratepayer-funded program, while it's available.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're providing jurisdictions that want to go completely green
with a way to do so economically,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 200,000 California residents and businesses have
switched to renewable energy since the state deregulated the
production and marketing of electricity 16 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The renewable energy rebate is intended to help the renewable
industry make the tough transition from utility contracts to a
competitive market _ as well as protect California's diverse energy
mix.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 10 percent of the state's electricity comes from
renewable sources such as geothermal fields, wind farms,
hydroelectric plants, solar energy and burned waste.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature considers the survival of renewable energy
important. Toward that end, it has been tinkering with rules that
appear to have inhibited the expansion of the green marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   A new law says that consumers who sign up for green power over
the Internet or at public forums like county fairs need not be
contacted subsequently for ``third-party verification.'' That
waiver, proposed by state Sen. Byron Sher, D-Palo Alto, saves green
power marketers $5 to $10 per customer.
</P>
<P>
   Under SB1159, independent verification still is required for
people switched as a result of telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   ABAG is not the first aggregator to move to green energy. The
San Diego Association of Governments recently signed a green power
contract with Commonwealth Energy.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Calpine sees an opportunity to create a brand
identity with consumers that it hopes will build its customer base.
</P>
<P>
   It's planning to build a visitor's center at The Geysers that
will explain how natural steam fields are harnessed to create
electricity _ and how the reinjection of treated waste water can
perpetuate the field's productive life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
