<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7484 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AOL-AOL_SFCHRON &LR;      08-05 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-AOL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Microsoft, AOL War May Involve Net Access  &HT;     By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Microsoft and America Online, already locked in a bitter fight over
instant messaging, soon may be battling on another front: Internet
access.
<P>
   In an attempt to snatch some of AOL's 18 million subscribers,
Microsoft may slash or even eliminate all fees for its Microsoft
Network, according to a report in yesterday's Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here clearly is a clash of the titans,'' said Joe
Laszlo, an analyst with Jupiter Communications. ``These are two big
forces who are trying to shape the computing and online experiences
of consumers for the foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Journal quoted Microsoft Vice President Brad Chase
saying the firm will be ``aggressive'' with Net access, the company
yesterday was more circumspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to believe access to the Internet can be easier
and simpler, because AOL has not set the standard there,'' said a
Microsoft spokeswoman. ``However, it is pure speculation that we
will lower the price of our Internet access or offer free access.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL currently is the undisputed leader in Internet access. It
charges $21.95 a month for its service, which includes an e-mail
account, Web browsing and access to proprietary content such as
online games and a daily horoscope. Microsoft offers similar
features through MSN, which has 1.8 million subscribers each paying
$19.95 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers believe that if Microsoft lowers its price to
zero, many AOL customers will defect. ``If I could get a reliable,
brand-name service to offer free Internet access, then I would
switch and I would make everyone in my family switch,'' said Hany
Nada, a technology analyst with investment firm U.S. Bancorp Piper
Jaffray.
</P>
<P>
   The news that Microsoft may be lowering prices hit AOL hard. In
a day when most technology stocks happily rebounded, AOL bucked the
trend and fell $3.50, to $83.94.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from Internet access now accounts for about two-thirds
of AOL's business. Unlike Microsoft, AOL does not have a
diversified product line to offset any losses that surely would
follow a price war.
</P>
<P>
   AOL is adamantly against lowering its subscription fee. ``We
raised our price a year ago from $19.95 to $21.95 while all around
us everyone was dropping their prices,'' said AOL spokeswoman Ann
Brackbill. She added that the company still managed to sign on more
new customers than ever.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's position is that price is irrelevant. Brackbill said
customers choose AOL for its ``value-added'' services such as
proprietary content, parental control and round-the-clock customer
support. And for consumers who still prefer low cost over anything
else, AOL offers a scaled-down offering, CompuServe, for $9.95 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a multiple brand strategy and are bounding ahead on
all fronts,'' Brackbill said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has attempted to wrest customers from AOL in the past
without much success. In 1995, Microsoft began bundling its MSN
online service with its Windows 95 operating system. The logic at
the time was that consumers quickly would turn away from AOL in
favor of the preinstalled Microsoft service.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly fours years later, AOL has 10 times as many
subscribers as MSN, according to Jupiter Communications statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over Internet access is just the latest twist in an
escalating turf battle between Microsoft and AOL. Two weeks ago,
Microsoft launched new instant-messaging software that let users
chat in real time with users of AOL's market-leading messaging
software. AOL accused Microsoft of strong-arming its way in;
Microsoft, in turn, said AOL was blocking competition. That battle
is still unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe that Microsoft is getting more aggressive about
the Internet precisely because the future of its dominant operating
system is now in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the potential that AOL could become an operating
system and that people will no longer need the Microsoft OS,'' says
Nada. ``Right now, I get an AOL CD in my mailbox every week, not an
MSN CD. But if Microsoft gets more aggressive, they could be a real
force here.''
</P>
<P>
   Free _ or much cheaper _ Internet access is not new. Gateway and
Dell have been offering free Internet access to people who buy
their computer products in Europe. In America, a number of smaller
firms, including Freewwweb and Bigger.net, have launched free
Internet access services, supported by an advertising-model, to
limited degrees of success. Bigger.net went out of business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
