<HEADER>
A7485 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-TOYOTA-ART     08-05 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-TOYOTA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2000 TOYOTA TUNDRA: FROM A LUMP OF COAL TO A POLISHED DIAMOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8)  
 (af)  
 By BOB KNOLL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HADLYME, Conn. _ A decade ago, when I made my daily visits to
the Hadlyme Country Store and Post Office, the vehicles parked
there were mostly passenger cars and station wagons _ Peugeots were
most common locally _ with a smattering of sport utility vehicles.
If there were pickup trucks around, they mostly belonged to local
contractors and lawn services.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed. Subarus have supplanted the Peugeots,
high-end sport utilities are everywhere and the pickups are more
common and less blue-collar. Not only do many have the deluxe
features of the best passenger cars, the addition of a rear door,
or doors, has broadened their appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But while Dodge, Ford and General Motors have thrived on the
booming truck market, Toyota has struggled to keep up, even though
it has sold pickups in the United States for 35 years. The majority
were smaller models, like the current Tacoma. Toyota added a
slightly larger truck, the T-100, in 1993, but it never really
caught on, perhaps because it was not really full sized, perhaps
because it did not offer a V8 engine. It was discontinued last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company _ fiercely competitive in most segments _ has
decided to get serious in full-sized pickups. It has a new $1.2
billion assembly plant in Princeton, Ind.; a new truck, the 2000
Tundra, and a V8.
</P>
<P>
   The plan seems to be working. The company says the Tundra has
had the best initial sales of any new Toyota product, and demand is
far outstripping supply. But the plant's capacity, 100,000 units a
year with plans to upgrade to 150,000, falls far short of its
homegrown rivals'. Ford sold nearly 850,000 full-size trucks last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Tundra comes in three price lines: base, SR5 and Limited,
with four-wheel-drive versions of the two fancier models. Cab
configurations include a regular cab with an eight-foot cargo bed
and a four-door Access Cab with a six-and-a half-foot bed.
</P>
<P>
   The standard engine is a 3.4-liter, 24-valve V6 rated at 190
horsepower and 220 foot-pounds of torque. It is available with
either a five-speed manual transmission or a four-speed automatic
transmission. But the engine that most Americans will want is the
V8.
</P>
<P>
   A modern design with 4.7 liters, dual-overhead cams and 32
valves, it is basically the same power plant used in Toyota's
luxurious Land Cruiser. Called the I-Force, it develops 245
horsepower and 315 foot-pounds of torque and qualifies for
classificiation as a low-emission vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   With this engine, which comes only with an automatic
transmission, the Tundra is rated to carry about 2,000 pounds or
tow a 7,200-pound trailer. An engine this sophisticated is uncommon
in a light truck, and the I-Force is unusual in another respect:
The throttle is electronic _ like the ``fly by wire'' controls of
some new jetliners _ instead of being directly connected to the
accelerator with a cable, the usual practice.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Tundra is a new design for Toyota, it is cut from
the same mold as its competition from Chevrolet, Dodge and Ford.
Toyota says the full-frame chassis is the most rigid in the field.
There is nothing unusual about the independent front suspension or
rear leaf springs, but the rack-and-pinion steering gives better
road feel than the systems used on many light trucks.
</P>
<P>
   But Toyota has combined large disk brakes up front with drums in
the rear, and anti-lock brakes are only an option. This is a
disappointing combination, considering that all Chevrolet
Silverados have four-wheel disk brakes with an anti-lock system.
</P>
<P>
   So how does the Tundra measure up in normal use? In the course
of this evaluation, I drove four-by-four versions of the Chevrolet
Silverado 1500, Ford F-150 and Dodge Ram 1500, and both two- and
four-wheel-drive versions of the V8 Tundra. The two-wheel-drive SR5
listed for $26,038, the four-by-four SR5 for $29,548.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the box, this new Tundra definitely lives up to
expectations and sets some benchmarks for the rest to shoot at.
</P>
<P>
   First, it is about as easy to get into (or as difficult, if you
are small) as the Silverado, which is the easiest of the
domestic-brand pickups. The Dodge is the worst, requiring a heave
of 39 inches up to the front edge of the seat. (The Tundra's rise
is 36 inches.) The Tundra cabin is roomy, the driving position is
comfortable and the visibility is excellent.
</P>
<P>
   Seat choices are a split bench with a large folding armrest or
two buckets with a center console. I much prefer the split bench,
which felt more comfortable, offered three-across seating and, when
the center seat is not used, offers a large storage bin and two
convenient cup holders in the armrest.
</P>
<P>
   The usual safety features are here: a depowered air bag for
driver and front-seat passenger with a key-operated lockout for the
passenger side; pretensioners for both front outboard belts, and
devices that protect the chest from the force of the belts. The
rear seat has two head restraints, two lap-and-shoulder belts and
hook anchors for a child seat with a top tether.
</P>
<P>
   The instruments and controls are clear and well placed, with the
exception of a windshield wiper stalk nearly as long as the gear
shifter protruding from the steering column. (I occasionally turned
on the wipers when shifting into reverse.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The air-conditioning handled humid, 100-degree days with ease.
The stereo _ radio, tape, CD _ was simple and easy to use.
</P>
<P>
   All the new pickups are quieter inside, but the Tundra is
clearly the most hushed, with a noise level comparable to many
cars'. Road noise was commendably low and wind noise was subdued up
to 70 miles an hour. The new V8 makes a nice noise when
accelerating but is inaudible at cruising speed.
</P>
<P>
   The steering does retain some road feel, with steering response
typical of big pickups _ not as quick or responsive as the Ford,
not as vague and wandering as the Dodge. The ride is softer than
one expects from a pickup, especially the four-wheel-drive version.
</P>
<P>
   Ride motions are relatively slow on better roads, deteriorating
only on broken secondary highways. All large pickups have body
shake on rougher roads. The Tundra is better than the others, but
still far worse than a passenger car.
</P>
<P>
   Without formal testing it is impossible to determine just how
good the brakes are, but the Tundra's have a good, responsive
``feel.'' They are much like those in the Silverado (which are
vastly better than those of previous Chevy trucks) and far superior
to the Dodge's.
</P>
<P>
   A convenient push-button selector on the instrument cluster
operates the four-wheel-drive system. One can select two- or
four-wheel drive while moving at any reasonable speed. Another
button selects low-range gearing for slow going off road. Although
simple to use, this is only a part-time system that should not be
used on dry, paved roads. The Silverado, alone among the big
pickups, has the full-time all-wheel drive that I much prefer.
</P>
<P>
   Poor rear traction is an inherent pickup characteristic. The
Silverado's all-wheel drive takes care of this problem with ease.
The Tundra's advantage is its electronic throttle, which applies
power so smoothly that you need not spin the rear wheels even with
the powerful V8.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota calls its four-door the Access Cab. The small rear doors
have conventional outside and inside handles rather than latches in
the door jamb; like the others', the back doors are hinged at the
rear, so they cannot be used unless the front door is opened first.
The rear doors open a bit wider than the others and getting in and
out is easier. But the rear seat is the least comfortable of any
big pickup's. The seatback is essentially vertical _ a park bench
has a more comfortable angle. Knee room is tight.
</P>
<P>
   The cargo box is well finished, and though a bit smaller than
the others', it can hold a 4-by-8-feet sheet of plywood flat on the
floor between the wheelhouses in the regular cab models. The Access
Cab has a six-and-a-half-foot box, typical of those in the other
pickups with a rear seat.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few problems that will no doubt be worked out as
the Tundra ages. Both test trucks vibrated slightly at moderate
speeds. The gasoline filler door has a seemingly clever clip to
hold the cap while refueling, but inserting the nozzle knocked the
cap to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The pickup truck of today is certainly not the truck of
yesterday. As sport utiliites have become more civilized, rivaling
luxury cars in their appointments if not in their driving
characteristics, so has the current pickup taken on the trappings
of the luxury utilities. In fact, the only real difference will
soon be the cargo area _ open for a pickup and closed for an SUV.
</P>
<P>
   The Tundra was obviously designed to be this kind of truck. Its
ride and interior noise level set new truck standards. Its smooth
V8 and seamless automatic transmission provide response that any
owner will appreciate. And, of course, one can expect the high
level of quality typical of a Toyota. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Toyota has heeded Americans' message: Make it
bigger; give it a V8. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
