<SLUG> BC-PHONE-PHONE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 PUC Sets Guidelines to Help Rival Phone Firms Compete With
Pac  Bell, GTE 
 &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
State regulators set guidelines yesterday that will help local
phone companies compete with Pacific Bell and GTE in California.
<P>
   The regulators set performance standards to measure how
efficiently Pac Bell and GTE process orders for phone service from
competing carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Many carriers, such as MCI WorldCom and AT&AMP;T, are eager to offer
local phone service to customers in the Bay Area and other parts of
California.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of building their own networks, companies will lease
pieces of Pac Bell's system and resell service under a different
brand name.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, the computer networks of competitors must be able to
communicate with the networks of Pac Bell and GTE. This ensures
that a customer who orders local service from MCI, for example, can
get a dial tone and can use 911.
</P>
<P>
   For this to happen, Pac Bell and GTE must make sure that their
systems are compatible with those of their competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The new standards from the state Public Utilities Commission
offer a way to gauge how well the systems of Pac Bell and GTE
operate. The standards also will ensure that Pac Bell and GTE treat
orders from competitors the same as they would treat orders for
their own service.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is important in the wake of problems that
competitors like AT&AMP;T and MCI experienced when they tried to roll
out local service in California several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies ran into problems with Pac Bell when trying to
process new orders from customers. Customers who signed up with a
competitor often were told that they couldn't get phone service for
several weeks, and others were billed by more than one company.
</P>
<P>
   The problems cost MCI and AT&AMP;T millions of dollars and forced
the companies to stop marketing their local service here and in
other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's ruling should prevent a similar occurance because it
spells out how much time Pac Bell and GTE have to respond to orders
from competitors. The PUC also may set penalties that Pac Bell and
GTE will face for failing to meet the standards.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming months, the commission is expected to approve a
test to see if Pac Bell's systems are compatible with those of new
rivals for the local market. Pac Bell, which wants to offer
long-distance service in California, must prove that its systems
are compatible before it can win approval to handle long-distance
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell and other local phone companies said they supported
yesterday's PUC ruling because it moves local phone competition
closer to reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very important from our perspective because prior to
the adoption, there was really no way for the commission to know
whether incumbents were meeting the level of service they need to
provide,'' said Evelyn Lee, senior attorney for MCI.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
