<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SPORTS COLUMN: BASEBALL MUST LISTEN TO McGWIRE  
(jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question is not what took Mark McGwire so long to get off
the stuff. The real question is what is taking baseball so long.
</P>
<P>
   Given baseball's laissez-faire attitude toward just about
anything, McGwire became a visible symbol of chemical
experimentation last year. He hit 70 home runs, 9 more than anybody
else ever had, while stoking up on the muscle-building supplement
androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   Now, McGwire says, he has not been using andro this season
because he did not want to set an example for young people. Of
course, he waited four months to inform the impressionable youth of
his decision, but better late than never. The owners who run
baseball are still locked in the ``never'' mode.
</P>
<P>
   Going straight has not cost McGwire his touch. He had 42 home
runs and was tied with his old pal Sammy Sosa for the major league
lead going into Thursday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe there's nothing wrong with it,'' McGwire told
reporters Wednesday night. ``But if I have a message for kids, it's
that you don't necessarily have to follow what somebody who's in
the public eye does. If you're an adult, you elect to choose your
own destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has every right to ``choose your own destiny'' because
there is nothing in the rules of his business to force him to stop
taking andro, even though an Iowa State University study suggests
risk for heart disease, pancreatic cancer and male breast
enlargement.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig, the commissioner of baseball, says he is awaiting the
results of a study by Harvard University. But since McGwire's use
became public knowledge last summer, thousands of young people have
undoubtedly ingested copious portions of the stuff, which does not
need a prescription. This frightening thought should weigh on the
alleged consciences of the owners and their hired executives.
</P>
<P>
   With preliminary evidence like the Iowa State study, baseball
could easily have called a temporary ban on andro, which is
prohibited by the International Olympic Committee, the National
Collegiate Athletic Association, as well as professional football
and tennis.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to charge that baseball has been slow in confronting
andro because it might somehow cheapen the epic season of 1998. I'd
give baseball the benefit of the doubt and assume that leadership
is merely indecisive and undisciplined and shortsighted without
resorting to such Machiavellian thinking. That's a compliment, I
think. Baseball, after all, is still mulling over the gross income
differences between teams in major television markets and teams in
the smaller regions. The result is that only four or five of the
teams have any shot at being in the World Series. What's the rush?
</P>
<P>
   So baseball dithered while thousands of young people went out to
the drug store and purchased as much andro as they could afford.
The lack of moral authority from the owners left McGwire to work
out his own zig-zag take on the drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the fact that some young high school kids think
they need to do something to follow in the steps of a professional
athlete,'' McGwire said. ``But when you're an adult, you can make
your own decisions. When you're young like that, you can make wrong
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire never planned to be a symbol of andro. It was not as if
he had an endorsement contract. Nor did he seem to feel guilty
about using it, since he did not hide his involvement very well.
</P>
<P>
   Last season he left a container in his locker, at eye level,
where visitors would inevitably glance. One curious but not
unscrupulous reporter noticed a label that said ``androstenedione''
and asked a few questions, putting McGwire in a public position he
had not sought.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how much worry McGwire had about the chemical
before the controversy began last year. Once it was revealed, he
did not change his routine while he continued to hit homers under
intense pressure and scrutiny, but he was surely aware of the
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is a public figure who took advantage of counseling
after a painful divorce and has forged an adult relationship with
his son, his former wife and her husband. His father is a dentist,
and he and his siblings have college educations. As the conflicting
information about andro piled up, McGwire surely received some
advice to give it up, lest to do damage to himself and also to
others.
</P>
<P>
   To McGwire's credit, he stopped taking the stuff, and ultimately
felt comfortable revealing it. It took Mark McGwire awhile, but he
did the right thing. His industry gave him no moral compass, no
guidelines, no help at all. Why am I not surprised?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
