<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-SAFETY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Security at the workplace is getting more attention
 &HT;    By John Pletz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Atlanta day trader Mark Barton made nationwide
headlines last week when he killed nine people in a murderous
stroll through two office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, George Edward Moore walked into the trucking
company office in Charlotte, N.C., where he worked and killed his
supervisor. It merited just a few paragraphs deep inside The New
York Times the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Guess which one corporate security directors were paying
attention to?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't spend a lot of time worrying about Atlanta,'' said
Bryan Smith, who works for American Protective Services as security
director at two downtown Austin office buildings. ``I don't see how
we could change things to prevent something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The type of shooting in North Carolina, where an employee exacts
revenge against a co-worker, is a far more common and bigger
concern among security professionals and building owners and
managers.
</P>
<P>
   About 120 people are slain by co-workers each year, according to
the National Safe Workplace Institute in Charlotte. Three more
people were killed at two Alabama businesses Thursday, and police
arrested a man who had worked at both places.
</P>
<P>
   In all, there were 709 workplace homicides nationwide in 1998,
which include workers killed in robberies and other incidents, the
Labor Department reported Wednesday. In Texas, there were 60
homicides on the job.
</P>
<P>
   While there's a lot of talk about biometrics and glitzy gizmos
like retina scanners and fingerprint readers, the hottest topics in
office security are common-sense, low-tech solutions, such as
locking doors and checking ID badges.
</P>
<P>
   Walk into a swank downtown high-rise or a bland strip-mall
office in Austin and you'll probably be exposed to more security
than you realize: a security station in the lobby, card readers at
unmanned entrances, cameras in parking lots, loading docks and
stairwells, a keypad or another reader at individual offices,
employees wearing IDs.
</P>
<P>
   Security cards and other electromagnetic devices have been
around for more than a decade, but they've become more
sophisticated and more affordable. In some Austin buildings, for
example, tenants must use small electronic key fobs to access
individual floors from the elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, whose company handles security at about 45 buildings in
Austin, said one local law firm installed a panic alarm out of
concern over a disgruntled client. Another tenant installed an
alarm out of fear about an employee's ex-husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, there's always been some concern about security,''
said Steve Everbach, director of asset services in Texas for the
Cushman &AMP; Wakefield real estate firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's been any huge design change to
buildings, but tenants are demanding certain areas have restricted
access: parking garages or loading dock structures where entry
could be obtained without going through the front door,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The front door isn't so easy, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``In individual suites, we've definitely noticed an increase in
secure reception areas,'' Everbach said. ``You can't just walk into
most offices anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's simple awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Property managers and tenants themselves spend a lot more time
today thinking about workplace violence and other security threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago it was a blip, nothing like it is today,'' said
Joseph Ricci, director of the American Society for Industrial
Security, a professional association for security individuals.
``It's been the No. 1 issue among our members for last five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   In large part, businesses are concerned about workplace safety
because of money.
</P>
<P>
   And with good reason. In May, a North Carolina jury found a
tool-distribution company was negligent in failing to protect
employees and awarded $7.9 million to the family of two workers
slain by a fired worker in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Government estimates put the cost of workplace violence at more
than $4 billion annually in legal expenses and lost work.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the number of people employed and the number
killed at work, it's actually pretty small, like terrorism,'' Ricci
said. ``But it can be a huge liability.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most large companies, the new rule of thumb is zero
tolerance, just like drugs: Make one threat, and you're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Several workers, however, said they didn't think much about
their safety or building security even in light of several office
shootings. Instead, it was viewed as a far-away problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isolated incidents happen,'' said Fleming Terrell, who works
at a law firm at One Congress Plaza in downtown Austin. ``It's
unfortunate, but you can't let it control what you do and spend
your life worrying and being afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
