<HEADER>
A7490 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BOOKS-ART-$ADV08-     08-05 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-ART-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER SCHOOL FOR MANAGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 8)  
 (af)  
 By DEBORAH STEAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer vacation reading, at least when it comes to fiction,
usually involves one of two choices: a breezy romp through a few
novels or a sweaty commitment to the Worthwhile Project _ an
attempt, say, at Proust, ``Moby Dick'' or even Dos Passos'
``U.S.A.''(a mere 1,300 pages or so in the edition I own).
</P>
<P>
   So here is a suggestion, in this last summer of our century: Why
not combine those two impulses, and get some Year 2000 perspective,
by revisiting three business novels from the late 1800s and early
1900s? The total number of pages is under 1,000, quite manageable
for a month's worth of lolling in a hammock or on a sandy towel.
</P>
<P>
   The novels _ ``Ragged Dick'' by Horatio Alger Jr., ``The
Financier'' by Theodore Dreiser and ``Babbitt'' by Sinclair Lewis _
are portraits of American archetypes who still reside in our
collective capitalist unconscious: the self-made man, the robber
baron, the Rotarian conformist.
</P>
<P>
   If you need a more practical reason to read these bracing if not
breezy novels, heed the word of Robert A. Brawer, the author of
``Fictions of Business: Insights on Management From Great
Literature'' (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   Brawer, a former chief executive at Maidenform Inc. who holds a
PhD in English, said his years as a reader of such classics helped
him make some crucial business decisions. And what better way, he
asks, to get a hint of the creativity that seems to be demanded in
business today?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ragged Dick: Or, Street Life in New York With the Bootblacks''
is the earliest book in our summer-school course. Published in
1868, it was the first of more than 100 young-adult novels by Alger
in which poor but virtuous boys ultimately gained respectability
and, sometimes, riches. I like the Signet paperback edition
($5.95), with its excellent introduction by Alan Trachtenberg.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Dick Hunter, an orphaned shoeshine boy and street
denizen (he lives in a cardboard box as the story begins) is a
Protestant Ethic parable. Burdened only by his shabby clothes and a
few forgivable vices _ like smoking and spending his earnings
immediately _ he rises, propelled by both luck and pluck.
</P>
<P>
   A potential benefactor witnesses our hero's honesty and ambition
and provides a new suit, a taste for Sunday School and, perhaps
most holy of all, lessons in thrift and delayed gratification (Dick
opens a savings account). The happy ending: After even more
self-improvement, our erstwhile urchin gets his first ``real'' job.
</P>
<P>
   As simplistic as it sounds, this short book is an entertaining
cultural artifact that offered inspiration to generations of young
Americans. Indeed, as Trachtenberg reminds us, the writer Nathanael
West once proclaimed that Alger was to America what Homer was to
the Greeks.
</P>
<P>
   Brawer says that may be stretching it a bit. But he points out
that ``they both worked in established myth; that's the key here.''
A novel like ``Ragged Dick'' is fascinating, he says, because it
makes plain the beliefs Americans have unconsciously absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, ``it's in a strange way typical of the illusions we
harbor,'' he said. ``We want to believe that in an era of
self-interest and me-first, the traditional virtues are very much
alive and will get us where we want to get.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Financier'' harbors no such illusions. (Published in 1912,
it is available as a Meridian paperback at $14.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Based on the life of Charles Yerkes, a 19th-century financier
and transportation magnate convicted of stealing city funds in
Philadelphia, this gripping novel both celebrates and excoriates
the ruthless self-interest of its fictional hero, Frank Cowperwood,
a born businessman who becomes an unstoppable force in the time of
the robber barons.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't Dreiser's best book. Both ``Sister Carrie'' and ``An
American Tragedy'' are arguably better reads. But it is powerful
nonetheless _ an obsessively detailed account of the corruption and
the charisma of its main character, who first appears as a young
boy intoxicated by the financial frontier of the Gilded Age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost the polar extreme of Horatio Alger,'' Brawer said.
``Here's Dreiser looking at what really makes success in American
business.'' The book is ``absolutely contemporary,'' he said, in
its description of the social Darwinism in business culture. And
Dreiser's genius, he added, ``is that he makes us like Cowperwood
despite ourselves.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to ``Babbitt,'' Sinclair Lewis's 1922 satire of a
smug, conformist real-estate salesman ensconced in a comfortable
middle-class life in Zenith, ``the best ole town in the U.S.A.''
(The Penguin paperback, with illuminating commentary by James M.
Hutchisson, is $9.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Today, the novel's denouement _ Babbitt's slow realization that
his shallow life is meaningless _ is less relevant than the
characters' choice of discourse: Reflecting on the prosperous
1920s, the book skewers America's obsession with brand names,
advertising slogans and business jargon. Hilariously for modern
readers, Babbitt even prattles on about ``Vision,'' his
generation's version of a mission statement.
</P>
<P>
   As a rave review in this newspaper noted back in 1922, ``Though
nobody will recognize himself in George F. Babbitt, everybody will
recognize somebody else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
