<HEADER>
A7494 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONOMY-ECONOMY_SFCHR     08-05 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-ECONOMY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Getting a Grip on the New Economy  
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Ill-defined yet oft-repeated, the New Economy is  &LR; the  &LR; label on the
lips of economists and politicians these days.
<P>
   Even if all they know is that it has something to do with
high-paying, high-tech jobs, civic and state leaders believe the
New Economy is the wave of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Now two recent studies, using slightly different approaches,
offer a detailed look at what this New Economy is all about _ and
some surprising insights about which communities are leading the
new economic sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   One report, which rates states as competitors, actually places
Massachusetts ahead of California as the top New Economy state.
According to the Progressive Policy Institute, a Washington, D.C.,
think tank, Massachusetts is ahead of California in such key
measures as patent filings, scientific brainpower and R&AMP;D spending
on a per-capita basis.
</P>
<P>
   The other study, by the Milken Institute of Santa Monica, ranked
metropolitan areas in the new economic order. Although San Jose
predictably dominated the list, the study put Oakland ahead of San
Francisco in creating high-tech dollars and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Though they used different measurements, the two reports share a
common view of how to describe this New Economy, contrasting it
with what has come before. Gone are the days when riches arose from
raising crops, harvesting forests, mining ores or manufacturing
widgets.
</P>
<P>
   In the New Economy, wealth is spun out of bright ideas,
protected by copyrights or patents and swiftly fashioned into
products as ephemeral as software programs or as short-lived as hit
songs _ all based on the new raw material of brainpower.
</P>
<P>
   Economist Ross DeVol of the Milken Institute chose cities as his
statistical landscape, studying 315 metropolitan areas and
selecting 50 with the highest concentration of jobs and product
dollars in 14 industries, including drug discovery, computing,
software, aerospace and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   By his measures, San Jose had nearly four times the
concentration of tech industry as second-place Dallas. But DeVol's
127-page analysis also contains this surprising observation: In
1998, Oakland firms booked more tech sales and created nearly as
many tech jobs as San Francisco _ making Oakland 14th in city
rankings compared with San Francisco's 22nd-place showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out of my way to highlight Oakland's showing,'' said
DeVol, adding that the East Bay city has won spillover business
from Silicon Valley and San Francisco with lower rents and better
commuting and housing characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Studying the New Economy in a different geographic contour,
regional planning expert Robert Atkinson of the Progressive Policy
Institute analyzed the competitive advantages of the 50 states in
luring and keeping New Economy companies.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson and fellow author Randolph Court, a former Bay Area
journalist, based their rankings on 17 characteristics, including:
the average education levels of a state's workforce, the number of
fast growing companies, newly public companies, and other measures
of the ``innovative potential'' of a state's economy, such as the
number of patents filed, the number of scientists and engineers,
and research and development spending.
</P>
<P>
   In the study by Atkinson and Court, Massachusetts nudges ahead
of California as the state best suited to fostering the New
Economy.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the two studies reinforced each other. States
like California, Colorado and Arizona, which included several
tech-centric cities in DeVol's ranking, also placed high on
Atkinson's state-based list.
</P>
<P>
   The different geographic focal points of the two studies
reflected their most profound divergence. According to Devol, ``The
centers of the New Economy tend to cluster around research
institutions or universities that create a pool of knowledge
workers who fuel innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   In his view, cities and their surrounding suburbs constitute the
basic units of the New Economy. Roughly 70 miles in diameter, these
urban-suburban rings must not only feature the colleges that turn
out ``knowledge workers'' for the New Economy. They also must
foster the willingness to change, adapt and take risks _ key
psychological characteristics of successful New Economy
communities.
</P>
<P>
   In marked contrast with DeVol's metropolitan focus, Atkinson's
survey examines which states seem best at creating this culture of
risk-taking and rapid change that both studies consider hallmarks
of the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
   Their differences in geographic view stem in no small part from
the differences between the sponsors of each study. DeVol's Milken
Institute is named after former financier Michael Milken who, since
his release from prison on charges relating to his 1980s junk-bond
antics, has underwritten a variety of good works, including DeVol's
well-regarded economic analyses.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by Milken's money, DeVol is free to step on political
toes by observing that ``there's been a disconnect between the New
Economy and government institutions,'' with the economic action
occurring in regions _ like the tech sprawl from Santa Cruz to San
Rafael _ areas beyond the grasp of local and state governments.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson's Progressive Policy Institute, on the other hand, is
an intellectual offshoot of the Democratic Leadership Council. The
DLC is a group of national and state officials whose self-professed
goal is finding a middle ground between ``the liberal impulse to
defend the bureaucratic status quo and the conservative bid to
dismantle government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary audience is federal and state government officials
who want to know what they can do to enhance the prospects for New
Economy companies,'' said Atkinson.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, despite their differing geographic foci, the two
studies suggest that the factors hospitable to the New Economy are
so subtle and complex that government officials have only limited
powers to lure and sustain these desirable industries.
</P>
<P>
   Writes DeVol: ``Overly active government intervention and public
policy may be counterproductive and even harmful to the long-term
development of high-tech industries.''
</P>
<P>
   Court, speaking for the state-based study, put it like this:
``In the old style of economic development, government played the
hunter-gatherer, going out to recruit target companies armed with
tax breaks, free land and other incentives.''
</P>
<P>
   Economic development in the New Economy should be more like
``cultivating a garden,'' he explains, making states fertile for
knowledge-based industries like software or biotech by improving
public education or promoting job-specific training programs.
</P>
<P>
   But such observations, on the limited role of government in
economic development, should not be construed as proof that the New
Economy is less greedy for government favors than its smokestack
predecessors, as some of its promoters suggest.
</P>
<P>
   After all, national and state governments currently are awash
with tech-backed initiatives to:
</P>
<P>
   _Increase the import of foreign professionals under H-1B visas.
</P>
<P>
   _Extend the R&AMP;D tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   _Freeze sales taxes on e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   _End overtime pay after an eight-hour workday.
</P>
<P>
   _Enforce U.S. copyright and trademark protections worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   _Negotiate trade rules that favor globalization, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Although both studies overlook such ``government
intervention(s)'' sought by New Economy firms, the authors do have
reservations about the new order.
</P>
<P>
   DeVol, the economist, sums up his reservations in a word:
volatility. ``Community leaders need to be aware that the New
Economy will not make them immune to future business cycles,'' he
said. ``In fact, in a severe recession, some of these communities
will be hit even harder.''
</P>
<P>
   DeVol estimated the extent of that volatility for each of the 50
top tech metropolitan areas by running an economic model that
simulated a recession similar to the one that hit in the early
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   In his model, the nation saw its output of goods and services
slide 1.6 percent in this imaginary downturn. But San Jose's
economy slipped by twice as much, falling 3.3 percent. Oakland's
output fell 1.26 percent, less than the national average but still
negative, while San Francisco emerged as one of only three cities
nationwide to survive this mathematical recession with a positive
growth rate, of .5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Seen through Atkinson's more political lens, wage-income
disparity emerges as the New Economy bugaboo. In a companion study
of the national New Economy, Atkinson notes that between 1980 and
1996, the wealthiest five percent of Americans saw a 58 percent
increase in real income. The 60 percent of Americans lower on the
real-income scale eked out a mere 4 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   The full text of both studies are available at
www.milken-inst.org and www.neweconomyindex.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
