<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCGEM-BNP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING MIDNIGHT DEADLINE, BANK INVESTORS ARE UNDECIDED ABOUT
TAKEOVER BIDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ With only a day left before investors must choose sides
in France's three-way bank struggle, Banque Nationale de Paris
appeared to inch closer to victory in its hostile bid for Paribas,
one of two rivals it is seeking to control.
</P>
<P>
   But investors in Societe Generale, Banque Nationale's other,
larger target, appeared deeply split, raising the prospect that a
final verdict in the hostile-takeover war may fall to French
banking regulators.
</P>
<P>
   If Banque Nationale amasses more than 50.01 percent of Paribas,
it will wreck Paribas' planned friendly merger with Societe
Generale. If Banque Nationale ultimately gains control of Societe
Generale as well, it will merge all three banks into the world's
largest bank, with assets of more than $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Banque Nationale launched its $37-billion hostile bid for
Societe Generale and Paribas in March, about a month after the two
smaller banks had agreed on their own friendly merger.
</P>
<P>
   The bank bidding reflects the broader scramble by European
corporations to merge. Financial institutions in particular are
under pressure to come together to gain size and lower costs in
order to compete more effectively in rapidly unifying markets,
woven even tighter by Europe's new single currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding also reflects a new series of aggressive deal making
in France. Last month, Total Fina SA, the French oil group, began a
surprise hostile bid for the much larger former national oil
company, Elf Aquitaine, in a move unprecedented in French industry
to create the fourth-biggest oil company in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of the bank brawl, analysts said the bids
had already brought benefits to investors by sharpening the banks'
reporting practices. ``Now we have quarterly reporting, rather than
half-year,'' said Sheila Garrard, of Lehman Brothers Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she said, the banks are now disclosing capital
allocations, enabling investors to calculate for the first time
returns on equity in the banks' various business sectors. Bank
executives also have become more accessible, meeting with investors
and securities analysts and trying to answer their questions.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of Paribas shares may sell them to Societe Generale or to
Banque Nationale, or keep them; investors in Societe Generale must
decide whether to tender to Banque Nationale. Since Banque
Nationale launched its double-barreled bid in March, shares in
Paribas have risen 11 percent and Societe Generale 15 percent,
while Banque Nationale shares have lost about 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Baudoin Prot, the No. 2 executive at Banque Nationale, said
today that equity holders in Paribas had given his bank commitments
to tender 49.6 percent of all Paribas shares to Banque Nationale.
Paribas disputed the claim.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts cited reports by several Paribas core shareholders
in recent days as indications that support for Paribas was
weakening. In Italy, the big commercial bank, Banca Commerciale
Italiana, and Mediobanca, the investment bank, were reported to
have shed equity holdings in Paribas equivalent to 2.64 percent of
the total. Their departure, along with the resistance to a two-way
merger by other big Paribas shareholders, including the French
insurer AXA SA, appeared to support the likelihood of Prot's
assertion.
</P>
<P>
   More complex is the behavior of holders of equity in Societe
Generale. French stock market rules require that Banque Nationale
obtain at least 50.01 percent of Societe Generale's capital and a
clear majority of votes to gain control. Complicating matters, some
Societe Generale shares enjoy double voting privileges. Thus,
roughly 29 percent of Societe Generale equity held by bank
executives and employees have 35 percent of total shareholder
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Hence both sides have been storming investors with flurries of
multipage newspaper ads in recent days. The Paris daily Le Monde
reported that Paribas and its partner had budgeted $15 million and
Banque Nationale $12.2 million for the ads, injecting an element of
American-style campaigning into historically secretive French
finance.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday Prot said that tenders of more than 35 percent of
Societe Generale votes to Banque Nationale would give it
``effective control'' of Societe Generale. Though most
institutional investors _ mainly large United States and British
pension funds _ have refused to declare their preference, analysts
say they overwhelmingly support the three-way merger proposed by
Banque Nationale, for its potential to eliminate overlapping costs.
</P>
<P>
   But major core shareholders, notably large French industrial
investors like the Alcatel electronics group and the Peugeot auto
works that have cross shareholdings with Societe Generale, oppose
the three-way deal. Banque Nationale's hope, people close to the
bank said, is that a tender of between 35 percent and 50 percent of
Societe Generale voting rights will enable it to sway French
investors to support a replacement of Societe Generale's management
at a shareholder meeting after the tender.
</P>
<P>
   Though the tender expires at midnight Friday, provisional
results are not expected until Aug. 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
