<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T AND BRITISH TELECOM INVEST $1 BILLION IN TORONTO COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ AT&AMP;T and British Telecommunications PLC said Thursday
they had agreed to invest almost $1 billion in a mobile phone
company controlled by Rogers Communications of Toronto, creating
the framework for a cable and phone communications network to take
on the domestic giant, Bell Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The investment in Rogers by AT&AMP;T and British Telecom is the
second foreign deal undertaken by the two phone giants since they
formed what was described as a $10 billion joint venture last year.
In April, they invested more than $1.8 billion in Japan Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers Communications owns Canada's largest cable television and
mobile phone companies. It also has a 16 percent interest in AT&AMP;T
Canada, which was created in June with the merger of four phone
companies that had been competing for long-distance service to
business customers. Rogers Cantel is an important subsidiary of
Rogers Communications, accounting for 40 percent of its revenue of
$2.5 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of phone and cable, following the recent pattern
of mergers and acquisitions in the United States, has given life to
Rogers shares over the last six months, even though the company has
seldom made money and has amassed almost $3.4 billion of debt.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Rogers Cantel, which had risen recently amid speculation
about possible ventures with foreign partners, fell on the news
announced Thursday. On the Toronto Stock Exchange the shares lost
4.9 percent to $31.95 (Canadian), or $21.36 (United States). The
parent company's B shares fell 1.6 percent to $27.90 (Canadian), or
$18.65.
</P>
<P>
   Although investors remain intrigued by the broad communications
potential of phone combined with cable, the partners in Rogers
Cantel are focusing on business customers. Canadian companies, said
AT&AMP;T's president, John D. Zeglis, ``will enjoy the seamless
worldwide services they need to compete in the economy of the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first of a two-step agreement, AT&AMP;T and British Telecom
will pay $934 million for a 33 percent interest in Rogers Cantel
Mobile Communications Inc., after which Rogers Communications will
own 51 percent of the mobile phone company. British Telecom will
then ensure that it participates in future developments by buying
one-third of AT&AMP;T's 31 percent stake in AT&AMP;T Canada for $402
million.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Holman, a vice president of the Dominion Bond Rating
Service here, said the investment gave Rogers' mobile phone company
more marketing power just as the use of wireless transmission for
data is expected to surge. ``This brings the international arena to
the domestic doorstep,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The parent Rogers Communications also benefits, though
indirectly, through the ability to use some of the new investment
to help lower its debt, and by establishing a financial rather than
just a marketing relationship with the two global giants, Holman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Rogers Communications took an important step in that
direction when the Microsoft Corp. made a $400 million investment
in its shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
