<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Friday, August
6, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   HUD-GRANT (Seattle) _ Southeast Seattle's Rainier Valley scored
a major redevelopment windfall Thursday when the city received
$17.2 million in federal money for a $45 million commercial and
housing project.
</P>
<P>
   By Alan Snel. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING (Seattle) _ China Airlines may cancel a $2 billion order
for Boeing jets and switch it to Airbus because the Taiwanese are
angry at U.S. policy toward China. Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash.,
trying to soothe hurt feelings.
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Nyhan. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   WTO (WASHINGTON) _ The Clinton administration wants to set aside
the day before this fall's World Trade Organization meeting in
Seattle to allow consumer, environmental and labor groups to air
their concerns directly to the world's trade ministers.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SKIN CANCER (Seattle) _ Scientists in Texas have found that
sunburn may actually stop the beginnings of skin cancer by ridding
the skin of genetically damaged cells. But the researchers at the
M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Houston cautioned sun lovers that
the finding is not at all an endorsement of serious tanning.
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Paulson. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   PLAYWRIGHT-BANG (Undated) _ Story on film and stage writer
William Mastrosimone (``Extremities'' is probably his best known
play to film). His ``Bang Bang You're Dead'' is a drama of school
killings made available to any group who wants to produce it, no
royalties, in an effort to help curb school massacres.
</P>
<P>
   By Joe Adcock. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-TATYANA-ALI (Undated) _ Tatyana Ali, one of the stars of
Nickelodeon's ``All That Music and More'' festival, launched her
singing career after an episode of NBC-TV's ``The Fresh Prince of
Bel-Air.''
</P>
<P>
   By Gene Stout. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MOBY (Undated) _ Moby's new album, ``Play,'' is an orgy of
musical eclecticism. The electronic-music artist turns convention
upside-down with his mesmerizing blend of throbbing hip-hop,
ambient piano noodlings and early 20th-century blues and gospel
fused with modern electronic beats.
</P>
<P>
   By Gene Stout. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL-BROTHERS (Undated) _ Musical families have been around
at least as far back as the Bachs. But few in American pop culture
have thrived through hard times and shifting tastes like the Allman
Brothers Band and the Neville Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Penn. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
