</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-IRON (Undated) _ Finally _ a terrific summer film for kids.
One that mixes fine writing _ the book ``The Iron Man'' by the late
British Poet Laureate Ted Hughes _ with the animated film world.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DINNER (Undated) _ With his two Gerard Depardieu-Pierre
Richard teamings, ``La Chevre'' (1982) and ``Les Comperes'' (1983),
French writer-director Francis Veber found a near-perfect star
chemistry and scored two of the funniest mismatched buddy comedies
of the '80s. Not surprisingly, in his new film, ``The Dinner
Game,'' lightning doesn't strike twice in the same place, but the
results are passably entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TRICK (Undated) _ We've been privvy to some good,
gay-themed coming-of-age movies this year. ``Edge Of 17'' and ``Get
Real'' provided a positive platform for gentle, non-threatening but
edgy comedies that don't shirk responsibility to their
protagonists' personal voyages of self-discovery because of sexual
preference. But they don't push too many safety buttons either.
``Trick'' belongs on the next tier.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MYSTERY (Undated) _ Like many movies derived from comic
books and aiming for a state of inspired silliness, ``Mystery Men''
must have seemed magically goofy on storyboards, but has somehow
turned into an unappealing mush by the time it made it to the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   HYDROS-HANAUER (Seattle) On the 50th anniversary of Seafair,
Seattle native Chip Hanauer has a chance to dominate headlines.
With his next victory, Hanauer will surpace hydroplane legend Bill
Muncey as the all-time victory leader. Includes lengthy exclusive
interview with the Widow Muncey.
</P>
