<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: KOSOVO'S COSTLY DISORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Aug. 6: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two months after the arrival of the first NATO forces, Kosovo
remains lawless and violent. There are no local police or judges,
U.N. police are just beginning to trickle in and NATO is doing an
uneven and unsatisfactory job of preserving order. Unless the trend
toward anarchy is quickly checked, international plans for
constructing a democratic civil society in Kosovo could be doomed.
</P>
<P>
   Local thugs, rogue fighters of the Kosovo Liberation Army and
Albanian gangs slipping across an unpatrolled border have taken
advantage of the law enforcement vacuum to terrorize the Serbian
and Gypsy minorities and drive them from their homes. The same
violent elements also prey on Kosovar Albanians, subjecting
shopkeepers and other business people to extortion, and potential
political rivals and suspected collaborators with the former
Serbian authorities to intimidation and murder.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate response to this deteriorating situation must come
from NATO, the only organization capable of combating criminal
violence. The effectiveness of NATO law enforcement varies from
sector to sector; the British zone is doing reasonably well, while
others lag behind. Gen. Michael Jackson, NATO's Kosovo commander,
must impose more consistent and rigorous standards.
</P>
<P>
   NATO must also rethink its overly indulgent attitude toward the
KLA, which has been permitted to postpone the deadline for
surrendering heavy weapons and expects to see its former fighters
included in new local police forces. The KLA's political leadership
has condemned the recent killings of Serbs. But it must do more to
assert effective discipline, making clear that any members taking
part in such violence will be expelled from the group and turned
over to the authorities for prosecution. KLA leaders must also
press their members to surrender their heavy weapons immediately.
</P>
<P>
   NATO was meant to take on law enforcement duties only for a
brief period, while the U.N. recruited and trained an international
civilian police force. U.N. officials fought hard for this role,
but they have been much less aggressive in carrying it out. As of
today a little more than 500 of the more than 3,000 expected police
officers are available, most having arrived very recently. The
current target is to have 2,000 officers available by late
September. That is too little too late. The overall force needs to
be expanded to something like 5,000, and most of it needs to be
ready for action by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   If the criminal violence pervading Kosovo is not soon ended, the
province's economic assets will be controlled not by the most able
and entrepreneurial but by the most ruthless and heavily armed.
Fair elections will become impossible. Kosovo's economic recovery
and return to self-government could be indefinitely delayed. NATO
did not drive Slobodan Milosevic's brutal occupation army out of
Kosovo to allow a new era of disorder to commence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
