<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-CUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP-LED CONGRESS SENDS TAX-CUT BILL TO PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican-controlled Congress Thursday
narrowly approved the largest tax-cut plan in history, hurtling
toward a showdown with President Clinton that party leaders said
could affect a generation of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed the proposed $792 billion tax-break, 50-49, as
GOP leaders barely avoided an embarrassing setback. A preliminary
version passed the Senate last week, 57-43, but four moderate
Republicans joined the unified Democratic minority in opposing the
final package.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP defectors included both Maine senators, Olympia J. Snowe
and Susan M. Collins.
</P>
<P>
   The only senator who was absent, Republican Michael D. Crapo of
Idaho, would have voted for the measure if he were not at his
daughter's wedding, his office said.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the Senate vote, the House approved the final plan,
221-206.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP measure, which Clinton vowed to veto to not ``let
America go down the drain,'' would provide a potpourri of tax
savings over the next decade to every category of taxpayer and an
array of special interests.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans leaders said they will hold the bill until September
to try to build public support for the massive package before
sending it to the White House for Clinton's veto. Recent polls have
shown the public considers tax cuts a relatively low priority.
</P>
<P>
   The veto ultimately could be just the start of serious bargining
on a compromise, but so far, both sides are yielding no ground.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening salvos of the high-stakes struggle Thursday, both
parties staged last-minute unity rallies on Capitol Hill. GOP
leaders hailed the bill's final passage as a watershed moment in
their campaign to weaken Washington's control of the government's
pursestrings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really about downsizing the power of Washington and
upsizing the power of people,'' said Representative Bill Archer,
the Texas Republican who is chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats cast the plan as a looming economic calamity. By
granting nearly $800 billion in tax breaks, Democrats charged,
Republican leaders could leave the government too short on cash to
fund vital federal programs and maintain the nation's current
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This big luxury liner of a tax cut is headed for an iceberg,
and it just might take the American economy down with it,'' said
Senator Joseph I. Lieberman, a Connecticut Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is certain to surface in the 2000 elections for
Congress, as it did Thursday in the race for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   While Vice President Al Gore was poised to block the Republican
plan by casting the decisive vote if the Senate had deadlocked on
the issue, Texas Governor George W. Bush was endorsing the GOP
measure during a campaign swing through Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my judgment, we ought to pass back the money to the people
who pay the taxes,'' said Bush, the frontrunner in the race for the
Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The final tax package, crafted this week in closed-door
negotations among Republican leaders, would reduce each of the five
income-tax rates by 1 percentage point. The plan also calls for
cutting capital gains taxes for individuals, easing the so-called
``marriage penalty,'' abolishing inheritance taxes, and
establishing breaks for special interests as diverse as chicken
growers and maple syrup makers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and most Democrats said the best way to allocate a
projected $3 trillion federal surplus over the next 10 years would
be to shore up the Social Security and Medicare programs, reduce
the national debt, and preserve sufficient levels of government
spending.
</P>
<P>
   In accusing Republican leaders of playing politics at the
expense of sound ecomonic policy, Senator John F. Kerry denounced
the GOP plan as ``snake oil.'' Representative J. Joseph Moakley of
South Boston, the senior House Democrat from New England, described
the final package as ``an all-you-can-eat tax-break smorgasbord
that is unbelievably expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   But the measure's final passage was a prized moment for House
Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, who was seen as putting his job on the
line to muster support for the plan. ``We have a good deal for the
American people,'' Hastert said. ``It's fair, responsible and
balanced tax-relief bill.''
</P>
<P>
   In the House, only five Republicans and four Democrats broke
party ranks on the final vote. None were from New England.
</P>
<P>
   Notable among the New Englanders voting was Representative
Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat, who underwent quintuple
bypass heart surgery last week.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Snowe and Collins, the only Senate Republicans who
voted against the final package were Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania
and George V. Voinovich of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Snowe criticized leaders of both parties for their roles in the
tax-cut debate. A key supporter of a compromise, $500 billion tax
break, Snowe accused Clinton of refusing ``to negotiate in good
faith'' and blamed GOP leaders for holding ``one-sided
negotiations'' on the final package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of sending a tax bill to the White House that is DOA,
we should be doing CPR on the legislation here in Congress to agree
on a level of tax cuts that could become law,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
