<HEADER>
A7506 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-WALL-STREET-NYT &LR;      08-05 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WALL-STREET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CRIME ON WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Aug. 6: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stealing money from investors is not nearly as simple as robbing
a bank. The criminals often need the cooperation of legitimate
professionals who are willing to look the other way.
</P>
<P>
   So it appears to have been with Bear Stearns, one of the
nation's largest securities firms and a leader in processing
transactions for smaller brokerage firms, a role known on Wall
Street as clearing. Bear Stearns served as the clearing firm for
A.R. Baron, a penny-stock firm that was later convicted of
defrauding its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns Thursday settled civil allegations brought by the
Securities and Exchange Commission and by the Manhattan district
attorney. It will pay a total of $38.5 million, most of which will
go to compensate Baron's defrauded customers.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations laid out by the SEC, which Bear Stearns neither
admitted nor denied, paint a picture of a firm that had clear
evidence that Baron was routinely committing fraud by making
unauthorized trades in customer accounts. Yet Bear Stearns aided
and abetted those crimes, the SEC said. At the same time, the SEC
said, Richard Harriton, the Bear Stearns executive in charge of the
clearing operation, entered into a side deal with Baron's top
officer designed to enrich Harriton. Harriton, who resigned from
his post at Bear Stearns, denies wrongdoing and says he will fight
civil charges brought by the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC complaint says that Baron would have gone out of
business _ thus preventing it from defrauding many customers _ long
before it did had not Bear Stearns continued to process its trades
and failed to act on the clear evidence that fraud was taking
place.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC action establishes, in the words of Richard Walker, the
commission's enforcement director, that any brokerage firm ``that
engages in conduct enabling a boiler room like Baron to defraud
investors of millions of dollars is fully responsible for its
actions.'' It is sad that there was a need to teach such a lesson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7507 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-LPGA-BOS &LR;      08-05 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLE-IN-ONE HELPS LOVANDER TO TIE IN LPGA OPENING ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUTTON, Mass _ Marilyn Lovander is something of a golfing
vagabond, although she seems to have settled nicely in the Futures
Tour which is the women's equivalent of the Nike Tour. She's
currently the leading the money-winner, but with a short field in
the inaugural LPGA areaWEB.com Challenge she earned a spot in the
field and showed up for Thursday's opening round at Pleasant Valley
CC with high hopes.
</P>
<P>
   She seized the opportunity, putting together a round of minus-6
66 that was punctuated by a hole-in-one on the seventh hole when
she sank an 8-iron from 136 yards. She was eventually tied at 66 by
Australian Mardi Lunn, who had to sit out a storm delay of 2 hours,
19 minutes before returning to the sixth tee and promptly birdied
the hole to set up her 6-under-par round.
</P>
<P>
   This was a day of low scoring. Lovander and Lunn lead by just a
shot over New England's perennial winner Dotti Pepper, Jackie
Gallagher-Smith, and Caroline Blaylock. The storm soaked the course
briefly, and lightning in the vicinity further delayed play.
</P>
<P>
   Lovander, who has missed the cut in three of the five LPGA
events she has played in, made the turn in minus-5 32. She birdied
her first by sinking a 20-foot putt, her second with a chip to 4
feet, fifth (4-iron, 7 feet), 7th (5-iron, 12 feet) and ninth (sand
wedge, 10 feet). The bogey came on her sixth out of the left tree
line. After a birdie on her 11th (chip, 4 feet), she went to her
16th (the par-3 seventh) and holed her tee shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited,'' she said, ``but you still have the rest of
the round. It's fun to think about it later, like right now. But I
turned right around and bogeyed the next hole, so that brings you
back to earth. I'm missing an event on the Futures Tour, so they'll
all have a chance to catch up to me before the final event. This is
my 11th event in a row, so I'm just really tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was the difference today. You just stand up and
see things how they are. OK, it's 136 yards. I guess it's an
8-iron. I was very relaxed out there. I started playing the Futures
Tour again this year because I just couldn't get into any
tournaments out here. Then I kept finishing in the top three every
week, so it became a bit of a priority. The top three get exempt
cards for the LPGA Tour next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunn, who grew up in the town of Liverpool and resides in Cowra
over the Green Mountains west of Sydney, has been cheered on by her
mother, Val, who has been here six weeks and seen her daughter post
a third and a second as she tries to zero in on making the top 30.
``I've played pretty well since she's been here,'' said Mardi Lunn.
``She comes once a year, and I always seem to play well. I have no
idea why that is.''
</P>
<P>
   She started on the 10th tee and had a bogey-free round of
33-33-66. She returned to the course and rolled in a 35-foot putt
for a birdie, and missed birdie putts of 8 feet and 10 feet on her
final two holes. Sister Karen is playing this week in the Scottish
Open since she's on the European Tour, but the two will be together
next week at the British Women's Open. ``I wanted to play here,''
she said. The big difference has been in the putter. ``I went to a
mallet putter for the first time in my life,'' she said, ``and then
I started to make a few.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, who won the old Welch's at Blue Hill CC, the LPGA
Friendly's at Crestview, and the LPGA Classic at Stratton Mountain
and was runner-up in the NCAAs on Cape Cod, started her round with
two birdies and had only one bogey (fourth) when she missed a
3-foot putt. ``I had some good chances out there,'' she said. I
left a few hanging. So it was nice to have those chances. I think I
was more comfortable with the putter in my hands today.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher-Smith made the turn in minus-5 31, went to 7-under
with birdies on her 12th and 13th holes. She returned to earth with
a bogey out of trees on her 14th and a second out of the trees on
the next hole. She struggled early this year, but put it all
together to win the Giant Eagle LPGA Classic two weeks ago in
Warren, Ohio. ``I think it was a surprise,'' she said. Even while I
was playing I didn't realize I was going to win. So it never
totally sunk in. I always felt I could win, but for it to finally
happen was very special.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
