<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7508 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      08-05 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIS LOST IN OCEAN OF JOHN-JOHN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - They died in Kosovo two days after a small plane
disappeared off Martha's Vineyard, so reports of their passing were
buried inside most newspapers under truckloads of JFK Jr. and ``the
end of Camelot'' and ``the Kennedy curse.''
</P>
<P>
   Articles describing the accident that killed Army Sgt. William
``Gunz'' Wright, 27, and Spc. Sherwood B. Brim, 30, first appeared
July 20 on Page A14 of the ``Washington Post,'' and on Page A12 of
``The Arizona Republic,'' and on Page A7 of the Minneapolis ``Star
Tribune,'' and so on.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were in an armored personnel carrier that overturned
while on patrol, killing them and injuring three others. The
accident occurred near the town of Gnjilane.
</P>
<P>
   They were the first American peacekeepers to die in Kosovo since
NATO troops moved into the Yugoslavian province.
</P>
<P>
   They were members of Bravo Company in the 9th Engineer
Battalion, part of the 1st Infantry Division based in Schweinfurt,
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   They were husbands. They were brothers. They were sons. They
were, in Wright's case, a father.
</P>
<P>
   They were overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   I'm as guilty as the next guy. I ignored them, then forgot them.
I wouldn't have given them a second thought if I hadn't received an
e-mail from a man asking me why, after all these weeks, Sgt. Wright
and Spc. Brim hadn't gotten more press.
</P>
<P>
   To which I responded, ``Who?'' &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
NOT TOTALLY IGNORED &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
Not every reporter ignored the soldiers, of course. Among all the
shouting about Kennedy, there were whispers on the wire services
about Wright and Brim. And a writer or two wondering how the GIs
got ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Brim grew up outside Dallas. He graduated from South Oak Cliff
High School and Paul Quinn College in Waco before joining the
military.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Danna, said her husband loved the army. His own father
had done a hitch in Vietnam. Danna was watching a movie with Brim's
mother, Valreasia, the terrible night three uniformed strangers
knocked on her front door.
</P>
<P>
   Valreasia said, ``I knew right away exactly what they were
coming for. `I said, `Don't say anything, I know why you're here.'
''
</P>
<P>
   The other soldier, William Wright, grew up in northern
California. He joined the Army while still a student at Fort Bragg
High School.
</P>
<P>
   Reports say that, earlier this year, he chose a two-year
deployment in Schweinfurt over a one-year stay in South Korea
because Germany was a place where he could bring along his family.
</P>
<P>
   Wright and his wife, Amy, have two children, Tommy, who's 4, and
Joey, 3. &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
OTHER DEATHS IN REGION &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
While these two men were the first to die in Kosovo, three other
U.S. military personnel have been lost in the region since the NATO
campaign began.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Warrant Officer 3 David A. Gibbs, 38, of Ohio; and Chief
Warrant Officer 2 Kevin L. Reichert, 28, of Wisconsin, died in May
in a helicopter crash in Albania. On July 4, Spc. Anthony W.
Gilman, 23, of Michael, Ill., died in a traffic accident in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   None of these men lived a fairy tale, like Kennedy, but each had
a story. Each had dreams. Each had promise and expectations. Each
deserved for his sacrifice the covers of ``Time'' and ``Newsweek''
and ``People.'' None got it.
</P>
<P>
   The work military people do, keeping the peace, allows the rest
of us to sit back and obsess on princes and princesses, both real
and imagined.
</P>
<P>
   News stories and television specials about John F. Kennedy Jr.
exploded like flashbulbs in front of our eyes. We were blinded.
Even those of us taking the snapshots. Especially us.
</P>
<P>
   All this time later I came across an item on a news wire
concerning William Wright's funeral. He was to be cremated, it
said, like JFK Jr., his wife and sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   And while Wright's burial wasn't broadcast nationwide, and
didn't involve a Navy destroyer, his family planned to scatter his
ashes at sea. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0435 </DOCNO>
