</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMOCO-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE CANCER IN AMOCO EMPLOYEES IS PROBABLY WORK RELATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Ill., Md.)  (rk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ After a three-year study, medical investigators
working for the BP Amoco Corp. said Thursday that an unusually high
incidence of a rare brain cancer among some employees at a research
center near here was most likely work-related.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators, who were hired from the University of Alabama
and Johns Hopkins University, said that although the findings were
preliminary and did not pinpoint a cause, the statistical evidence
suggested that ``occupational exposure'' might have affected six
chemical researchers who in the last decade were found to have a
rare and often deadly form of brain cancer called glioma. At the
same time, the investigators said they found no evidence that about
13 other cases of nonglioma brain tumors were work-related.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers representing a large group of current and former
employees in lawsuits against the company criticized the
conclusions Thursday, saying that the Amoco study was neither
thorough nor independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study was bought and paid for by Amoco; it's hardly an
independent study,'' said Tilden Katz, a spokesman for Corboy &AMP;
Demetrio, a law firm in Chicago that is representing nonglioma
cancer victims. ``We have clients who had brain tumors who were
never contacted by Amoco,'' Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, about 19 people who had worked at the Amoco Research
Center in Naperville, Ill., a Chicago suburb, were found to have
brain tumors. Officials of Amoco, the giant oil company, say they
have been working vigorously to find a cause, but even medical
experts say that the major difficulty in resolving the case is that
science has not found a definitive cause of brain cancer in humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating to spend three years studying something and
not to have a definitive answer,'' said Jim D. Lowry, the chairman
of BP Amoco's health investigation task force. ``We are hopeful
that the clues the investigators have uncovered will in some way
help health scientists in their efforts to identify the causes of
brain cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 19 brain tumor victims who have been identified by Amoco,
investigators say they have only found a pattern that would suggest
work-related causes among the six glioma victims, all of whom were
long-term chemical researchers often working on similar projects
with similar chemicals and in the same building. Amoco officials
said the investigators do not believe the other brain tumors were
work-related.
</P>
<P>
   There was no unusual pattern of workplace, time or common agents
used by others who had inter-cranial tumors, the company said. Of
the six glioma victims, five have died. All 13 other brain tumor
victims are alive, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Naperville Thursday, members of a health
task force formed by Amoco in 1989 said the university researchers
(who were not present at the news conference) had not identified a
specific cancer-causing agent, but they did find that two types of
chemical agents, low-level ionizing radiation and a solvent called
n-hexane, were used by the glioma victims.
</P>
<P>
   Those agents, which are not believed to cause cancer, are
probably not the cause of the brain cancers, officials said. But
they may hold clues to the mysterious outbreak here, which surfaced
in 1989. Amoco officials said both agents had been largely phased
out at the Naperville Research Center, and that the solvent
n-hexane is now little used because it is known to cause damage to
nerves in the hands and feet. It is not a carcinogen and not known
to damage the central nervous system, but it is toxic, Lowry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two are not necessarily the cause but suspects,'' said
Michael S. Wells, a health manager at BP Amoco. ``The investigators
do not believe they could be the cause.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen cancer victims _ mostly nonglioma _ have
joined a series of lawsuits arguing that in the 1970s and 1980s
Amoco knowingly exposed employees to toxic chemicals and unsafe
conditions despite repeated complaints about faulty ventilation
systems and dangerous storage conditions. Amoco officials, however,
have said that those problems were fixed long ago and have been
largely ruled out as possible causes of the brain tumors.
</P>
<P>
   Amoco officials say they will continue working with victims but
have not decided whether they will offer monetary compensation.
``We're going to do the responsible thing,'' said Wells.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it has spent millions of dollars over the past
few years trying to determine whether the brain tumors were
work-related.Thursday, members of the task force said they had long
suspected that the cause of some of the cancers was work-related
and that they had known from earlier studies that the rate of
glioma at the Naperville center was about eight times higher than
that of the general population.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that all six of the glioma victims were
chemical researchers who worked in the Naperville research center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
