<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7514 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BAEZ-PARALYZED-BO     08-05 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BAEZ-PARALYZED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAEZ PARALYZED FROM WAIST DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Rudy Baez, injured in a spill at Rockingham Park in
Salem, N.H., Wednesday, is paralyzed from the waist down.
</P>
<P>
   Baez underwent seven hours of surgery at Massachusetts General
Hospital Thursday, and, while a hospital spokesperson would say
only that he is ``still in serious condition,'' Mike Szpuk, Baez's
agent, said the rider, who was in surgery from 11 a.m. until 6
p.m., ``had a severe spinal cord injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Szpuk was present when doctors informed Baez's wife, Judy, of
the situation following the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like he'll be able to walk at all,'' said
Szpuk. ``He has movement in his arms and his breathing is all
right, but his lower body is gone. He was unconscious when I saw
him after the operation. His face is swollen to twice its normal
size and his eyes are swollen shut. It was a terrible sight. He's
going to be confined to a wheelchair. His riding career is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in God's hands right now. Whatever happens, his recovery
will be a long process. I've been with him 15 years, and I've known
him for 25. As far as I'm concerned, he's one of my own family.
He's like a brother to me. It's heart-breaking to see this. Judy
has been great, and all of the family has been strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Baez, 49, was thrown from his mount, Gaitor Bait, during the
running of the second race Wednesday. The horse clipped the heels
of a horse in front of him as the field began to crowd a 16th of a
mile out of the gate. Baez was hurled forward as his horse fell and
appeared to land headfirst on the track.
</P>
<P>
   The injured jockey, perenially New England's leading rider, was
taken by ambulance to Holy Family Hospital in Methuen, where he was
stabilized, then airlifted to Mass. General.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 50 years, there's been nobody like Rudy in New
England,'' Szpuk said. ``He rides just as hard to get second,
third, and fourth, so he can get people checks. He's a God-fearing
guy. He's fighting for his life. If he comes out of this,
regardless of what happens, he'll pick his life up. He believes in
God, and he believes things happen for a reason. No matter how this
turns out, he'll make a good life for himself. I'll be with him,
whether he's riding or not. He'll always be No. 1 to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Szpuk, who was on vacation, was not at Rock when Baez went down,
but he has strong feelings about the way jockeys ride in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody to blame,'' said Szpuk. ``That's how this game
goes every day. Somebody squeezes somebody else. Stuff happens with
these horses. Nobody goes out to hurt anybody. He'd never put the
blame on anybody in a race. Once the gate opens, you never know
what will happen. The horses weigh 1,000 pounds and the jockeys
weigh 100 pounds. The other jockeys get aggressive and so does
Rudy. But nobody goes out with the intention to hurt anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Baez, who resides in suburban Wakefield with his wife and three
children, was born in Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic. He began
riding as a 13-year-old in his native country. He rode his first
winner in the United States at Detroit Racecourse in 1973, arrived
in New England in 1974, and was a star on the local circuit ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   He rode nearly 28,000 races and came home first 4,874 times,
with his mounts earning nearly $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Baez captured 13 riding titles at Suffolk Downs and 10 at
Rockingham. In '91, Baez rode seven winners on a card at Rock and
finished second in the nation in races won (to Pat Day) with 431.
Last Saturday, Baez rode Lambana to victory in the $100,000 Spicy
Living Sweepstakes, one of the biggest races of the year at Rock.
It was one of the biggest victories of Baez's career.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTHRAX-VACCINE-NYT &LR;      08-05 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHRAX-VACCINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AGREES TO MORE THAN DOUBLE THE PRICE IT PAYS FOR ANTHRAX
VACCINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (yn) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon's plan to vaccinate every member of
the nation's armed services against the deadly biological agent
anthrax _ a program already buffeted by questions about safety and
effectiveness _ just became a lot more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the possibility of running out of vaccine, the
Pentagon announced Thursday that it had agreed to more than double
what it pays the nation's only licensed manufacturer of the
vaccine, Bioport Corp. of Lansing, Mich., to produce millions of
doses over the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   The company _ a new corporation whose directors include William
J. Crowe Jr., the retired admiral who was chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff and ambassador to Britain _ bought the laboratory
from the state of Michigan last year for $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the Pentagon's commitment to vaccinate all 2.4
million active-duty troops and reservists, the company had
financial trouble and in June warned that it could fail if the
Pentagon did not pay more.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of frantic negotiations, the Pentagon agreed to pay
$10.64 a dose for the vaccine, up from the $4.36 a dose under the
terms Bioport agreed to when it bought the laboratory last year.
The total cost of the contract, which requires the company to
produce fewer doses, will rise to $49.8 million over the next five
years, from $25.7 million now.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon also agreed to advance Bioport $18.7 million to
help it cover debts.
</P>
<P>
   Senior officials, who appeared at the Pentagon to announce the
agreement but then insisted that they not be identified by name,
justified the sharp increase in the contract, saying it was vital
to national security that Bioport, as the only producer of the
vaccine, remain solvent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This action was taken to preserve the financial viability of
Bioport in order to ensure uninterrupted production of the anthrax
vaccine,'' the Pentagon said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Anthrax is a naturally occurring bacterium that infects cattle
and sheep. When produced as dry spores, it can be incorporated into
one of the deadliest biological agents, capable of causing death
within days of being inhaled.
</P>
<P>
   Although no country has ever used anthrax in battle, the
Pentagon says that 10 countries, including Iraq and North Korea,
have the ability to make biological weapons; in December 1997,
Secretary of Defense William Cohen ordered every service member to
be vaccinated against anthrax.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Thursday prompted criticism from lawmakers and
others who have opposed the program for a variety of reasons,
including concerns about the safety and effectiveness of the
vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., said the increase was ``a
classic example'' of the problems of having a sole source for a
product or service. Shays, whose subcommittee on government reform
met in June on Bioport's problems, said the Pentagon's
determination to move ahead with the vaccinations regardless of
questions forced the price higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no way of knowing what's a fair price,'' he said. ``My
recommendation would have been to put this program on hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the program began, the Pentagon has vaccinated 320,000
service members, beginning with those serving in the Persian Gulf
or Korea or in units likely to be called into combat. The
vaccination regimen requires six shots over 18 months, then annual
booster shots.
</P>
<P>
   Although the vaccine was approved for use by the Food and Drug
Administration in 1970, largely for veterinarians and others who
work with livestock, there has been scattered resistance to the
vaccination program, with scores of troops refusing to take the
shots, citing fears about the safety of the vaccine and adverse
reactions to it.
</P>
<P>
   At least 200 service members, have been disciplined for their
defiance, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
   As it completed its purchase last year, Bioport negotiated its
contract with the Pentagon setting the price per dose at $4.36, a
price the company's spokeswoman acknowledged today grossly
underestimated the manufacturing costs and subsidies from the state
government. The law allows companies to seek ``extraordinary
contractual relief'' in certain instances like financial distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not begin to anticipate the cost of producing the
vaccines,'' the spokeswoman, Kelly Rossman-McKinney, said of the
company's executives.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rossman-McKinney said Crowe did not take part in the
negotiations over the anthrax contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
