<HEADLINE>
CUBAN JUMPER DENIES COCAINE USE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINNIPEG, Manitoba _ Cuban high jumper Javier Sotomayor angrily
denied Thursday that he had taken cocaine before winning a gold
medal at the Pan American Games here last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have only seen that substance in the movies,'' Sotomayor
insisted in Granma, the Communist Party daily newspaper. ``I don't
need any kind of trick to jump 2.30'' meters (7 feet 6 inches). ``I
am a victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Sotomayor, the world record-holder and 1992 Olympic champion,
was stripped of his Pan Am medal after testing positive for cocaine
and is likely to be banned from both this month's world outdoor
track and field championships and next summer's Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban officials, who say they will appeal Sotomayor's case, have
claimed that either his food or drink was spiked or that his urine
sample was manipulated.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans have been unhappy with everybody from the Games
organizers to the local newspapers, with president Fidel Castro
complaining about ``tricks and dirtiness'' designed to hurt them in
the medal count and to provoke their athletes into defecting.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans are especially angry at the tabloid Winnipeg Sun,
which is running a ``Come on Down to Cuba'' contest and offering a
week's vacation for two on the island for guessing the number of
defectors during the Games. While five Cubans have already sought
asylum with the Canadian government, at least three others are
reportedly missing from the delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the turmoil has hurt the Cubans in the standings.
They're sitting a strong third behind the United States and Canada
and will pick up another dozen medals in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A hasty retreat
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How determined were the Cubans to keep their ballplayers away
from agents and other provocateurs here? The team collected its
gold medals at 11 p.m. Monday. By 2 a.m., they were on a plane
bound for Havana . . . The US did little better than expected this
week in qualifying teams for the Olympics. The baseball team made
it by reaching the final and the men's water polo team grabbed its
slot by beating the Cubans for the gold medal. But neither the
men's nor women's field hockey teams qualified and both handball
teams fell short, losing to the Cubans Thursday. The women's field
hockey team gets another chance, though, at a special event in
England in March and should qualify there. Both basketball teams
are already set for Sydney, as are women's soccer and softball. The
indoor volleyball teams and men's soccer squad have qualifying
events ahead and the women's water polo team has a second shot
after missing out in the FINA Cup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hired guns
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though virtually none of the US baseball players who earned the
Olympic berth here will get to compete in the Games (since they'll
probably be on 40-man major league rosters next summer), they
weren't just here for the love. Each man receives $9,000 plus $70
per diem _ and got to stay at the upscale Fort Garry Hotel instead
of in the University of Manitoba dorms . . . While the Pan Am
organizers were hoping to sell 600,000 tickets to the Games
(roughly one per Winnipeg resident) they'll be lucky to hit
500,000, their break-even point. As of Wednesday, the total was
450,000 . . . Yes, the US women's soccer program does have
something in the pipeline. The under-18 team, which outscored the
opposition, 22-2, blanked Mexico, 1-0, Thursday to win the gold
medal. ``People were asking us if we were the World Cup team,''
said Catherine Reddick, who scored the lone goal. ``We said, no,
we're their understudies.'' . . . Fall River judoka (and former
Detroit Lion) Joe Felton, after being thrown in the bronze medal
match by his Venezuelan rival: ``Judo is nothing like football. If
you screw up in football, you have the rest of the game. But
there's only a split second in judo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
