<SLUG> BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR HOUSE IS SOLD, BUT CAN I BUY BACK THE MEMORIES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When the house I grew up in went up for sale, I
couldn't blame anybody.
</P>
<P>
   My sister Lisa and her husband had been living in that house
after my parents moved several years ago, and, quite frankly, the
neighborhood had changed.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, the old neighbors started moving away. They sold
their houses to people who let their yards go, didn't water their
trees, and who considered their front yards to be extensions of
their living rooms, hauling out couches, chairs and tables and just
leaving them there until the weeds eventually hid them.
</P>
<P>
   For me, it was rather sad to see our neighborhood disintegrate
like that. For my sister, who still lived in it, it was a test of
faith. Across the street, her new neighbor had been mowing the lawn
when the motor seized. Apparently discouraged by the unfortunate
events, he simply gave up and left the lawn mower to rust in its
dead tracks, where it sat six months later.
</P>
<P>
   The folks who lived in the home behind Lisa developed something
of a chicken farm on their patio, which for a rural couple seems
quaint, but when you're living a block away from Squaw Peak
Parkway, it's a little disturbing, especially the time a nasty
chicken chased my sister down the alley while she was taking out
the trash.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose the last straw in Lisa's patience was when the
neighbor next door to the Chicken People dragged home a dilapidated
railroad car, parked it in his back yard and used it as a tool
shed. Although my sister quickly added two feet of height to the
block fence in her back yard, the damage was done. She was ready to
spike a ``For Sale'' sign into the same front yard where I once did
cartwheels under the huge olive trees.
</P>
<P>
   When she told me the house had sold, I was both relieved and
happy for her, but I wasn't really sad. It was just a house, after
all, and now it was a house in a crappy neighborhood. On the day
Lisa moved, I went over to help out. I was standing in the empty
kitchen, staring at the Z Brick my father had slapped onto the
walls, when it hit me.
</P>
<P>
   We were losing our house. OUR HOUSE.
</P>
<P>
   Our house, where up against that wall, my mom used to lie on the
couch with her hand over her eyes because she got a headache in
1972 that never went away.
</P>
<P>
   Our house, where, in this same spot, I came home drunk for the
first time at age 16, and despite the fact that I had vomit up my
nose and my unfortunate friend Doug had to hold me up with both his
arms, my mother ``insisted'' I was ``spaced out on LSD'' and
demanded that I confess. I guess she was too busy giving birth in
the '60s to know any better.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall is my bedroom, where, during a freak-out fit of
child anger, Lisa, then 8, blew a hole through the door with her
foot when she discovered I cooked and ate her last E-Z Bake Oven
cake. It was ``chocolate''.
</P>
<P>
   Across the hall is her room, where, as a fourth-grader, she
cried for nearly seven hours straight after my mother gave her a
home perm that made her look like a Harlem Globetrotter.
</P>
<P>
   The next door down is my parents' room, where she stood one
Sunday morning, screaming at age 5, ``OPEN UP, MOMMY! WHY IS THE
DOOR LOCKED? WHO IS GOING TO GET ME MY SUGAR SMACKS?''
</P>
<P>
   Across the hall was my other sister's room, where she ran after
a particularly gruesome fight, slamming the door so hard that it
broke the lock and we had to call my Uncle Jimmy to disassemble the
window to let her out.
</P>
<P>
   The back yard marks the spot where I taught Lisa, then in eighth
grade, how to smoke in lieu of eating her E-Z Bake Oven cake. I lit
it for her, told her to suck superhard and to hold it as long as
she could. Three seconds later, she threw up in the grass.
</P>
<P>
   I smiled. She's a non-smoker.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the same place that my other sister pinched (her
fingers had the strength of a lobster) and taunted me until I
picked up a dried-up, nearly white dog turd and hit her in the leg
with it, upon which she immediately threw up, ran to her bedroom
and slammed the door, which resulted in the call to Uncle Jimmy.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the yard is the swimming pool, where Lisa,
then a 9-year-old full-fledged spaz, rode her bike into the deep
end because she couldn't see past her huge perm head.
</P>
<P>
   In the corner of the yard is a fig tree, sturdy, tall and
massive, producing figs that practically drip honey. My father
planted that tree almost 30 years ago, when it was a 12-inch sprout
taken from my great-grandfather's fig tree in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   On the side of the patio is the storage room, bearing a
puke-green door. On the inside face of that door, in pencil, are
the names of myself and my two sisters, and hash marks that
documented how we grew until we all peaked out at 5 feet 5. Lisa's
son, now 3, matches the exact height that she was when my dad
started measuring.
</P>
<P>
   Our house.
</P>
<P>
   I drove by our house awhile ago. The new owner hadn't moved in,
but she had hired people to chop down every tree in the front yard
and rented a massive Dumpster to place the debris of the demolished
Z Brick wall and other structurally important elements she was
ripping out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   I called Lisa that night and asked her if she thought the new
owner had pitched the green door into the Dumpster, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably,'' she sighed. ``She called Dad and offered to
``sell'' it to him. He told me to peek in the alley every now and
then to see if it was out there, but I'm too afraid of that damn
chicken. It's just a door with some marks on it, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's just a written-on door,'' I agreed, nodding,
although I understood that we both knew better. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
