<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMP-EVALUATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO IMPROVE OFFICIATING, BASEBALL GETS POINTERS FROM NFL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, whose plan to establish an evaluation system for
major league umpires was a major reason for their mass resignation
last month, has quietly been exploring how that system might work.
</P>
<P>
   To improve what he sees as an outdated umpiring system,
Alderson, the executive vice president for baseball operations in
the commissioner's office, has spent months observing how other
sports train their game officials. Eventually, Alderson may blend
some of the officiating techniques from other leagues into
baseball's umpiring system.
</P>
<P>
   Alderson and members of his staff have met with officials from
the NHL, the NBA, the NCAA and the NFL, which has the most
extensive training for game officials in sports. His attention has
apparently been focused more on the NFL than on the other leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Alderson has looked for ideas that he believes can be applied to
major league baseball's umpiring system, currently in a state of
crisis after the mass resignation of umpires on July 14 and the
subsequent dismissal of a third of the 68 umpires, effective Sept.
2.
</P>
<P>
   ``In looking at the other professional sports as well as the way
things are done in the NCAA,'' Alderson said in an interview
Thursday, ``there are common, positive things in terms of their
officiating we can apply to baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig has initiated plans to move control of
the umpiring system out of the two league offices and into the
commissioner's office. Alderson, a longtime Oakland Athletics
executive, wants to install an evaluation system that would, in
part, more easily allow for demotions and dismissals.
</P>
<P>
   Alderson is clearly preparing to add what he feels are the best
aspects of other sports' systems to baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each sport presents a different set of problems for us to look
at or adapt,'' he said. ``There are other things that are not so
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson said he would not describe his look at the officiating
of other sports as ``extensive.'' Yet one NFL executive said
Alderson has put the league's officiating system ``under a
microscope.''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson said he had spoken to his counterpart in the NFL
office, the senior vice president of football operations George
Young, and to Jerry Seeman, the NFL's senior director of
officiating. Alderson said other officials from his office have
spoken with additional representatives of the NFL's officiating
arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I took away from my discussions with the NFL is the
incredible amount of time they spend training their officials,''
Alderson said. ``In baseball, on the other hand, we put very little
time into training.''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson declined to specify what ideas he might try to adapt to
baseball, but Alderson and others from his office expressed serious
interest in the NFL's training and its rules-testing program in the
off-season, NFL executives said. When an official enters the NFL he
is assigned a mentor, and later he receives a tape of an official
at his position working the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran officials have each of their calls graded and are
assigned a score during the season. At the end of the season they
are given tapes with every call they made during the season, so
that they can watch and study themselves. The NFL also buys its
game officials a satellite-television subscription so they can tape
games. In the off-season, NFL officials attend clinics run by
Seeman and take a series of take-home tests, one of which has 250
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Alderson was also interested in the way the NFL tests the
conditioning of its game officials. The physical conditioning of
baseball umpires has long been criticized, while that of NFL
officials, who spend much of the game backpedaling and sprinting,
has rarely been questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Every year the NFL gives its officials physical exams, which
include stress tests and checks of body fat. Officials who do not
make specified weights risk losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Although the baseball umpires union has concern for some of its
overweight umpires, it has resisted firm weight rules. Neither
major league has any off-season program for its umpires.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between the NFL and its officials is amicable,
and the NFL has been able to convince its officials' union that its
guidelines are for the best. Given the bitterness between major
league baseball and its umpires, it is hard to predict what the
reaction from umpires would be to strict weight guidelines or
extensive training seminars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what will happen in terms of what ideas we use or
do not use,'' Alderson said. ``The main thing is doing what is best
for baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
