going full blast, blue sky and hot sun - are a recipe for smog,
which has reached higher peaks than usual in the cloudless hot
weather that has recently prevailed in most of the East. (Librado
Romero/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 05, 1999 -- CHINA-SECT, 08-05 -- Li
Hongzhi, the founder of Falun Gong, a spiritual movement that
claims tens of millions of followers in China, in New York
recently. China's fierce-looking crackdown on the popular sect is
turning out to be far less severe than it first looked, with more
propaganda than action. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SHELBURNE FALLS, Mass. -- Aug. 05, 1999 --
WILLIAMSTOWN-TRAVEL-2, 08-05 -- The Bridge of Flowers in Shelburne
Falls no longer carries trolleys, but sports 500 varieties of
blooms. The flowers are tended by volunteers from the Shelburne
Falls Women's Club, which created the garden in 1929. (Alan E.
Solomon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. -- Aug. 05, 1999 --
WILLIAMSTOWN-TRAVEL-1, 08-05 -- The First Congregational Church in
Williamstown. When summer comes and the golden yarrow is blooming,
this impossibly tidy New England town revels in its nickname, ``The
Village Beautiful.'' (Alan E. Solomon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WELLESLEY, Mass. -- Aug. 05, 1999 -- FINANCIAL-CAMP-BOS,
08-05 --Morgan Pierce, 14, of New Orleans, writes down her thoughts
during a class at Camp Start-Up, a two-week summer residential
program at the Dana Hall School in Wellesley. The camp hosted 25
girls and cost about $1,600, with half the girls receiving
financial aid. (David L. Ryan/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CHARLESTOWN, Mass. -- Aug. 05, 1999 -- US-ECONOMY-BOS,
08-05 -- Volkswagen Beetles form a geometric pattern while awaiting
transportation to dealers in the Northeast. The U.S. economy
expanded by almost 3.5 percent in the first half of 1999 and has
been a singular and dominant force in stabilizing - even repairing
- a fragile global economy in the months since the fallout last
year, international economists say. (Jonathan Wiggs/Boston Globe
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WALTHAM, Mass. -- Aug. 05, 1999 -- FLEET-BANKBOS-BOS,
08-03 -- Robert P. Shay, BankBoston's director of electronic
banking, in the company's research room, which is stocked with ATM
machines. ``The more accessible you make your systems, the more
customers will gravitate toward you,'' he says. (Tom Landers/Boston
Globe Photo)
