<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7531 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DROUGHT-NJ-words&AMP;ADD-     08-05 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT-NJ-words&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO FIGHT DROUGHT, NEW JERSEY PUTS SHARP LIMITS ON WATER USE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(yn) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ With little significant rain in sight and calls
for voluntary conservation failing to slacken demands on New
Jersey's dwindling water supply, Gov. Christie Whitman Thursday
declared a statewide drought emergency and imposed strict rules on
outdoor water use.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations, which come as parts of the Eastern Seaboard
endure the worst drought in decades, prohibit the use of lawn
sprinklers, and mandate that trees, shrubs and flowers only be
watered with a can or a hose equipped with a hand-held nozzle.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency measures also forbid state residents to fill
swimming pools, use water to fill decorative fountains or
reflecting pools, clean their driveways and sidewalks or wash their
automobiles anywhere except commercial car washes using recycled
water. Restaurants are also prohibited from serving water to
patrons unless they ask for it.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman had hoped to avert the need for restrictions by
announcing a drought warning on Monday and asking for voluntary
conservation. But in the following days, water use continued at an
unusually high pace and reservoir levels fell at more than double
their normal rate.
</P>
<P>
   She also warned that New Jerseyans could face the prospect of
more stringent water limitations if the drought persists _
including restrictions on indoor water use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't taking this step lightly,'' she said. ``We must cut
down on our water use and unfortunately people weren't coming to
that understanding voluntarily.''
</P>
<P>
   Violators could face penalities of up to $1,000 per incident and
repeat offenders could face fines of up to $5,000, the governor
said. Although it was unclear how police and elected officials in
New Jersey's 567 municipalities will enforce the rules, the head of
the state's Department of Environmental Protection suggested that
residents take it upon themselves to watch their neighborhood and
report any violations they see.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bergen County town of Tenafly, where mandatory
restrictions were imposed earlier in the week, a handful of
residents called the police to offer information about neighbors,
Police Chief Allen Layne said. In each case, he said, an officer
was sent to issue a warning.
</P>
<P>
   Layne and the mayor of Tenafly criticized the governor for not
acting sooner and said that the exceptions to the rules would
complicate enforcement. For instance, the restrictions on lawn
watering include an exception for lawns recently treated with
fertilizers or pesticides. In those cases, residents can use hoses
to water the grass for five days after their application, up to 45
minutes a day, as long as they do it between 8 p.m. and 9 p.m. or
from midnight to 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Other elected officials in northern New Jersey were baffled that
Whitman waited until they enacted their own emergency restrictions
before superseding them with her statewide mandate.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in Bergen and Hudson County, government offices were
besieged Thursday with telephone calls about restrictions that only
allowed lawn sprinklers to be used on alternate days. When Whitman
made her announcement at 2 p.m. banning the use of sprinklers on
most lawns, those rules became moot.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's announcement came, oddly enough, on day when
violent thunderstorms passed through parts of northern New Jersey,
New York City and Long Island, knocking out power and dumping hail
and sheets of rain for a brief period in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   During her news conference at the State Museum here, a
minute-long cloudburst brought a few drops of rain to the parched
ground and brown lawns of the capital. But rainfall in New Jersey
has been below average for more than a year, and July was the
driest month since the National Weather Service began recording
precipitation, so meteorologists say it will take long periods of
sustained rainfall to replenish reservoirs and aquifers.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's reservoirs were at 69.8 percent of capacity
Thursday, far above the 55 percent level which would automatically
trigger a water emergency, but Mrs. Whitman said she authorized
mandatory water restrictions because use is so high in the summer
and because the National Weather Service says significant rainfall
is unlikely during the next five days.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland, Delaware and Pennsylvania have already instituted
water restrictions and Virginia was adopting them Thursday. The
high temperatures and scant rain have wreaked such damage in the
region that West Virginia has been declared a drought disaster
area, along with parts of Kentucky, Ohio, Maryland, Virginia and
Pennsylvania. President Clinton has proposed $10.8 million in
emergency aid and federal loans for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The drought has had more limited effects in the upstate New York
counties that supply New York City's drinking water. Still, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani last week asked residents to practice voluntary
water conservation. Wildfires in Rockland and Orange Counties have
consumed 600 acres of forest.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey has received just 2 inches of rain during the past
two months _ about a quarter of the normal amount during June and
July _ and Whitman estimated that there has been $80 million in
crop damage to 7,000 farms throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   Some New Jersey environmentalists said the governor's
declaration was long overdue, and warned that the low water levels
would concentrate pollution in the state's drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman went out of her way to assure New Jersey residents that
the drought posed no threat to the safety of their drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no danger of water quality degradation,'' she said.
``With the low water levels there can be a concentration of
pollutants, but with the filters that is all removed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
