<HEADER>
A7538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-05 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Pinochet Dispute Heats Up &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor filed an appeal criticizing Judge Baltasar Garzon's
warning to the Spanish government this week not to interfere with
his attempt to extradite the former Chilean dictator Augusto
Pinochet from Britain on charges of crimes against humanity.
Prosecutors have repeatedly tried to block the case, whose latest
wrinkle was a reported bid by the Chilean government to win Spain's
support for international arbitration to settle the issue out of
court.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela: President Urges Longer Term &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a passionate speech before a constitutional assembly
dominated by his supporters, President Hugo Chavez urged the body
to adopt a new national charter that would extend his term of
office from five to six years and allow him to seek immediate
re-election. Chavez, who led a failed coup attempt in 1992, also
recommended the declaration of a ``national emergency'' and said
the assembly, which has a six-month mandate to produce a new
Constitution, should work overtime so that its task will be
finished by the end of the year and new elections can be held
immediately.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Students Arrested &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police fending off flying rocks with plexiglass riot shields
arrested more than 100 university students in the first outbreak of
violence in a more than three-month-long strike over tuition costs.
Three students and a policeman were injured as the strikers tried
to block registration for the fall term.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Afghanistan: Taliban Foes Strike Back &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In what appeared to be a stunning counter-attack, opposition
forces of Ahmad Shah Masood said they had recaptured Bagram air
base from the Taliban militia and advanced to within 30 miles of
the capital, Kabul. The opposition further claimed to have killed
more than 500 of the Taliban in the recent fighting, a toll that
independent sources have yet to confirm.
</P>
<P>
   India: Gandhi Opens Campaign
</P>
<P>
   Sounding a major campaign theme for next month's elections, the
Congress Party leader, Sonia Gandhi, blamed the governing Hindu
nationalists for the recent deaths of hundreds of Indian soldiers
in the mountains of Kashmir. She said that government negligence
had allowed Pakistani-backed invaders to cross unnoticed into
Indian territory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
