</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-APOLLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A RESCUE PLAN FOR THE APOLLO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Aug. 6: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After decades of decay, Harlem's main business strip _ 125th
Street _ seems headed toward revival. Banking, insurance and
entertainment companies are planning to develop properties in the
area. But the linchpin of 125th Street is the Apollo Theater, a
music venue known around the world that has grown shabby and
technically obsolete through years of neglect. On top of these
troubles, the theater's board has been sued by the state for
questionable financial practices.
</P>
<P>
   The theater is owned by the state but operated by the nonprofit
Apollo Theater Foundation. The suit accused the foundation's board
of failing to collect millions of dollars from Percy Sutton, a
businessman and former Manhattan borough president whose company
produces a weekly variety program for television at the theater. If
ratified by all parties, a pending settlement would require Sutton
and his associates to repay $1 million to the foundation and would
also require that Charles Rangel, Harlem's Democratic congressman,
step down as the board's chairman. The board would then be
controlled by the Time Warner entertainment company, which would
appoint 10 of its 19 members and provide an infusion of cash.
</P>
<P>
   If approved at the Apollo Foundation's next meeting, on Monday,
the settlement should free an additional $2 million in badly needed
public and private development and preservation money that has been
frozen during this battle. By tying itself to Time Warner, the
Apollo would be able to draw on the company's management expertise
and its extensive holdings in the entertainment industry. The match
is all the more natural because Time Warner's president, Richard D.
Parsons, is chairman of the Upper Manhattan Empowerment Zone, which
is fighting to reinvent the area using federal, state and city
money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
