<HEADER>
A7542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BASEBALL-NYT &LR;      08-05 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BASEBALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BASEBALL SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Aug. 6: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rather quietly, it seems, major-league baseball has now worked
its way through two-thirds of the regular season and is now
entering that part of the year when each game seems to count for a
bit more than it did in the spring. But the season has already
produced some unexpected developments, especially in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   To the astonishment of pre-season forecasters, New York has two
teams in first place, the Yankees in their accustomed spot atop the
American League East and the Mets, surprisingly, at the top of the
National League East. Meanwhile, despite suspicions that they could
not possibly do it all over again, Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa are
once again engaged in a thunderous artillery duel, swatting aside
several pretenders who, at midseason, had hopes of replacing them
as the premier home run hitters in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The old phrase about ``putting it all together'' certainly
applies to this year's edition of the Mets. Having added several
key players, the Mets now offer brilliant fielding and amazingly
consistent hitting. On Wednesday their lineup included six
.300-plus hitters. The net result is that the Mets have vaulted
above the Atlanta Braves, the perennial favorite in the East.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Yankees have not been as interesting, there are still
some good stories in the Bronx, not least the emergence of the
phlegmatic Hideki Irabu as a competitive starting pitcher. The most
intriguing thing about the Yankees, however, is that for once they
are not a lock to win their division. The Toronto Blue Jays will
not go away.
</P>
<P>
   As for baseball generally, attendance is up by a few percentage
points in most ball parks, a good sign. Last year's jump in
attendance was attributed in part to the thrilling McGwire-Sosa
chase for the home run record. McGwire and Sosa are still a big
draw _ both are on pace to hit more than 60 home runs and are up to
their old trick of matching each other dinger for dinger on the
same day. And last night a huge crowd turned out in St. Louis to
see whether McGwire and San Diego's Tony Gwynn would reach two
baseball milestones _ 500 career home runs in McGwire's case, and
3,000 hits in Gwynn's.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe people are coming to the park just to see baseball. If
so, that is another indication of the game's recovery from its
strike-plagued past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7543 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ODDLAWS-AZR &LR;      08-05 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ODDLAWS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LAWS NO LAUGHING MATTER (OR ARE THEY?)  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's the day that eggs have to be chillier, tattoo artists
and body piercers had better start checking clients' age cards, and
police who think you're to blame for a traffic accident can give
you a blood-alcohol test even if you're unconscious or dead.
</P>
<P>
   Today is law day, the day more than 350 bills passed by the 1999
Legislature and signed into law by Gov. Jane Hall take effect. In
Arizona, legislation gets teeth 90 days after adjournment of the
Legislature unless the bill is passed with an ``emergency clause''
by a two-thirds vote, which puts it into effect immediately upon
signing.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the reams of legalese generated this year in the First
Regular Session of the 44th Arizona Legislature are found some very
serious, far-reaching laws that will shape the state for years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Among them: laws requiring landlords to register their
properties and the
 &UR; state Board of Regents to hold public hearings before hiking
university
 &UR; tuition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; But there are some oddities, too.
</P>
<P>
   About those eggs: From now on, if they're for human consumption,
they have to be kept at 45 degrees Fahrenheit or colder, instead of
up to 60 degrees. No, a state inspector isn't going to come around
to your home with a thermometer; the law applies to dealers and
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning today, if your boy or girl is under 18 and gets a
tattoo, is branded or has a body part (except for ears) pierced
without your being there, you can have the person who did it
prosecuted on a Class 6 felony, for which the penalty is a year in
prison and a fine of up to $150,000. (Pierced ears require only
parental permission, not the parent's presence.)
</P>
<P>
   In a couple of signs of society's increasing litigiousness, the
Legislature has now removed liability from a healthcare
professional who, as a charitable act, provides free, used
eyeglasses to someone who winds up getting hurt because of them.
But that's only if the recipient has signed a medical-malpractice
release beforehand and acknowledged that the glasses weren't made
specifically for him or her.
</P>
<P>
   And anyone can now donate to a fire department what seems to be
serviceable firefighting or rescue equipment without fear of being
sued if it malfunctions and hurts or kills someone.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature devoted a lot of verbiage to auto license
plates.
</P>
<P>
   What started as a bill to clarify the language of who is
eligible for special ``Veterans,'' ``POW'' or ``Purple Heart''
plates became a law creating county ``citizen transportation
oversight committees.'' Then, a bill that would have allowed
members of an Indian nation to obtain customized plates became an
enabling act for the Grand Canyon Airport Authority.
</P>
<P>
   At last, from a bill that would have created ``animal population
control special plates'' came the final word on license plates:
Virtually any non-profit organization that is ``not offensive or
discriminatory'' and doesn't promote a commercial product, a
religion or atheism can have a special plate made for members who
pay extra. Even a group with fewer than 200 members qualifies (the
previous minimum was 500) if it will bear the extra production
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of licenses, you can now obtain a new marriage license
if you lose yours. Lose it before the ceremony and the replacement
will cost you. Afterwards, it's free, but you have to get
signatures of witnesses and whoever performed the ceremony, or go
to court to explain that they're not available.
</P>
<P>
   As it does every year, the Legislature also removed sexist
language from old laws in the process of amending them. The laws
always applied to both sexes, but didn't read that way.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in defining unemployment, the wording is no longer
(emphasis added) ``any week in which ``he'' performs no services .
. . for wages payable to ``him.'' '' It's now `` ``the
individual.'' '' Also, the requirement for an employer to pay ``
``his'' employees'' at least twice a month is now `` ``the''
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet figures in a couple of new laws.
</P>
<P>
   When a state university assigns an identification number to
faculty, staff and students, from now on it can't be the person's
Social Security number _ unless the person requests it. And it
can't be posted on the Internet. For some reason, Arizona's
community colleges ``can'' use Social Security numbers for ID
unless the person asks for a different number. The prohibition of
Internet posting still applies.
</P>
<P>
   One new law might appear to allow Arizonans to buy beer, wine
and liquor over the Internet from makers in other states who obtain
a ``direct shipment license,'' but there will be no rush of orders
by e-mail. The catch is, the ``direct shipment'' has to be to a
wholesaler, who has to deliver the order to a retailer, who has to
deliver it to the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, coming full circle, the Legislature this year had to
undo its undoing of a law three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers in 1996 had meant to end a requirement for a cover
sheet to be filed when submitting certain documents to county
recorders, but accidentally repealed all document specifications as
of Jan. 1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   With the repeal of the repeal, the law is right back where it
started, including the requirement for cover sheets. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990805.0459 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-SELIGSON-NYT &LR;      08-05 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SELIGSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID J. SELIGSON, 92, PROMINENT REFORM RABBI 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rabbi David J. Seligson, a nationally known Reform
rabbi and an eloquent orator who held the pulpit at Central
Synagogue in Manhattan for 20 years, died Aug. 3 on the way to a
hospital in Manhattan. He was 92 and had lived for the last two
years at the Jewish Home and Hospital in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Central Synagogue is in some senses a national pulpit. The
memorial service that Seligson led there after the assassination of
President John F. Kennedy was broadcast on network television. He
was also regularly heard on radio as host of the syndicated
``Message of Israel'' program.
</P>
<P>
   Seligson was among the first Jewish chaplains to volunteer to
serve overseas during World War II. As an Army chaplain, he held
Passover seders for hundreds of soldiers in Calcutta, India, and
comforted those hospitalized with jungle fever in Burma. He
traveled the old Burma Road in a jeep with Christian chaplains,
holding Sabbath services before sundown to avoid the
malaria-bearing mosquitoes that emerged at nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   Although Seligson went on to achieve national prominence, his
chaplaincy to soldiers in wartime was his touchstone. ``I feel that
it was the greatest work that I have done in my entire ministry,''
he wrote in his memoir, ``Rabbi, Chaplain and Burra Sahib.''
</P>
<P>
   He was born on the Lower East Side of Manhattan on May 10, 1907,
and was brought up in the traditions of Orthodox Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated in 1929 from both Teachers College of Columbia
University and the Teachers' Institute of the Rabbi Isaac Elchanan
Theological Seminary and Yeshiva College. But he decided that the
future of Judaism in America lay in the modern and adaptable Reform
movement, and he enrolled in the Reform-affiliated Hebrew Union
College in Cincinnati. He graduated and was ordained a rabbi in
1933.
</P>
<P>
   With pulpits scarce during the Depression, he moved to
Birmingham, England, to help a group of liberal Jews organize a
Reform synagogue. There he met and married an Englishwoman, Minnie
Cohen. He returned to the United States to enlist in the military
chaplains corps.
</P>
<P>
   On his homecoming in 1945 after 32 months overseas, he was
invited to assist the rabbi at Central Synagogue in Manhattan, an
East Side landmark that is the oldest temple in New York State in
continuous use by one congregation. He was made senior rabbi in
1950 and held that position until he was named rabbi emeritus in
1972.
</P>
<P>
   In the temple's magnificent Moorish-style sanctuary, which was
burned in a fire last year, Seligson delivered sermons about the
path to God, the likely success of the civil rights movement and
Ethel and Julius Rosenberg. In one sermon, he said God was not ``a
great heavenly bellhop who will satisfy our needs if we press the
button.''
</P>
<P>
   Seligson helped to expand interfaith relations between
synagogues and churches in New York, speaking in churches and
inviting them to join an annual Thanksgiving interfaith worship
service.
</P>
<P>
   Seligson was president of the New York Board of rabbis from 1952
to 1954 and president of the New York Association of Reform Rabbis
in 1954 and 1955.
</P>
<P>
   He never really retired from pastoral work, serving as interim
rabbi for congregations in Lawrence, N.Y., Westport, Conn., and
Tenafly, N.J., in the 1970s. For 10 years, until he was 75, he flew
to Dublin each year to lead High Holy Days services at the
Progressive Synagogue there.
</P>
<P>
   His wife died in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Seligson is survived by his daughters, Michelle Seligson of
Boston and Jill Seligson Braver of Brooklyn, and three
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
