<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7553 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-REPORT06-COX     08-05 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-REPORT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta Olympic report revisited
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Former U.S. Attorney General Griffin Bell, prominent
member of King &AMP; Spalding, one of the nation's most powerful law
firms based in Atlanta, has taken the remarkable step of personally
asking congressional investigators to let him amend an official
report on Atlanta's bid for the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-page report, provided to Congress in June, purported to
detail inappropriate gifts and favors from Atlanta officials to
International Olympic Committee members.
</P>
<P>
   After investigators reviewed 38 boxes of documents, including
eight boxes that Olympic officials have refused to make public,
U.S. Rep. Tom Bliley (R-Va.), House Commerce Committee chairman,
said Thursday his committee was ``concerned that their written
response ... was not totally accurate or complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional investigators said they found evidence of
additional _ and more expensive _ gifts that were not included in
the report, which was signed by Billy Payne and Andrew Young,
co-chairmen of the Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators did not specify publicly what those questionable
items are.
</P>
<P>
   After studying evidence compiled by investigators, Bell, a
former federal appeals court judge and now a top-ranking attorney
with King &AMP; Spalding, requested the opportunity to amend the
report.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Committee's subcommittee on oversight and
investigations, which is looking for possible violations of federal
bribery laws in Atlanta's Olympic bid, granted Bell's request.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers indicated they were ``encouraged'' that Bell and
several members of King &AMP; Spalding's Washington, D.C., office had
taken over the troubling situation. The law firm served as pro bono
legal counsel for the Olympic bid effort and paid counsel for the
Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee is encouraged that the Atlanta Olympic Committee
and their lawyers understand the importance of this investigation
and are taking it seriously,'' Bliley said in a prepared statement.
``We are particularly pleased to learn that someone of the stature
and reputation of Judge Griffin Bell has assumed the leadership
over this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of Bell clearly signals the seriousness of the
accusation that Congress was provided with inaccurate information
in response to an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Further indicating King &AMP; Spalding's level of concern, Bell has
been joined in the effort by Eleanor Hill, a new partner in the
Washington office. Her practice focuses on white-collar criminal
matters, corporate internal investigations and congressional
inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Three partners of King &AMP; Spalding in Atlanta were on the
original nine-member Olympic bid team: Horace Sibley, Charlie
Battle and Charlie Shaffer. Battle has since left the firm. Linda
Stephenson, wife of another partner in the firm, was a charter
member of the bid team and remains GAAF's executive director. All
four were intimately involved in the Olympic lobbying effort.
</P>
<P>
   Bell approached the chief counsel for the investigative
subcommittee Tuesday. At that time, he said he had reviewed the
evidence and asked to amend the Olympic officials' report,
according to a senior committee staff member.
</P>
<P>
   Bell indicated it would take approximately two weeks to complete
the work. A staff member of the subcommittee said Bell told him ``a
team of King &AMP; Spalding attorneys were working 24 hours a day'' to
prepare an accurate response.
</P>
<P>
   Bell told the subcommittee he is unaware who authored the
original report, signed by Payne and Young. He also said he does
not know who compiled the documents contained in the eight boxes in
question.
</P>
<P>
   King &AMP; Spalding's managing director, Ralph Levy, who announced
he was stepping down from his leadership post last week, declined
to comment, referring questions to Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who declined to answer questions Thursday, did comment:
``It is true we are representing GAAF and are looking forward to
working with the House Commerce Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee's investigation of the Olympic lobbying effort has
been tense from the start.
</P>
<P>
   The initial report provided by the Atlanta group detailed some
three dozen personal gifts for IOC members that exceeded the IOC's
$200 individual limit and totaled $15,156.
</P>
<P>
   The gifts ranged from a $948 carburetor kit for the member from
Libya, to clothing totalling $937.66 for the member from Finland.
Both have since resigned or been expelled from the IOC in the wake
of the widening influence-peddling scandal that erupted in Salt
Lake City last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Payne and Young acknowledged handing out 113 additional gifts
that cost more than the $200 limit. They categorized those as
``group gifts'' _ the same items for multiple or all IOC members _
and included $202 wooden tulip bowls designed by artist Philip
Moulthrop and $215.97 electronic organizers.
</P>
<P>
   All told, group gifts totaled an average of $3,000 per IOC
member and cost the bid team $190,482.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sincerely hope that our report will demonstrate that
Atlanta won the 1996 Olympic Games fairly,'' Payne said upon the
release of the report in June. ``Although we occasionally exceeded
the IOC's guidelines, our work was always done with honest
intent.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has since abolished the $200 limit. A new rule allows
gifts of ``nominal value.''
</P>
<P>
   Revelations of exorbitant gifts, scholarships and cash payments
from Salt Lake City officials, in their successful bid for the 2002
Winter Games, touched off a global Olympic bribery scandal that has
engulfed Atlanta and forced major reforms in the IOC's site
selection process.
</P>
<P>
   Payne, who has just returned from an overseas trip, declined to
comment about the charges of inaccuracies in his report. A GAAF
spokesman said no gifts were intentionally left out of the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was compiled in a short time frame,'' said Lee Echols, the
spokesman. ``We did not exclude anything from the initial report
that we felt should have been in there. Now, at the committee's
request, we will clarify some of their additional questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee plans to hold public hearings in September,
according to Chairman Fred Upton (R.-Mich.). ``It is essential we
have a complete and accurate picture of the entire bidding
process,'' Upton said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee had publicly reprimanded Payne for earlier
attempting to thwart their investigation when he refused to allow
investigators to copy the contents of eight boxes of documents he
claimed were personal and not relevant to the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The committee demanded unrestricted access to the files. Payne
had allowed investigators to examine the papers in the eight boxes,
but he had forbidden them from making copies, fearing they would
become public.
</P>
<P>
   Payne later agreed to ship the disputed boxes of files to King &AMP;
Spalding's Washington office and allow investigators to copy
whatever they needed.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators said much of the material in the boxes was
relevant to the investigation, and they questioned lawyers in the
Washington office last week about discrepancies between evidence of
excessive gifts in the boxes and what was listed in the report.
</P>
<P>
   The eight boxes of documents withheld from the public are the
subject of a GAAF lawsuit against state Attorney General Thurbert
Baker and The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, which argue that the
Olympic records are subject to the Georgia Open Records Act. The
judge in the case has yet to rule.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
