<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRICKYARD-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEARFUL WALTRIP SETS SIGHTS ON VICTORY TOUR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Darrell Waltrip has given himself 18 months to do
something he has done 84 times during a distinguished NASCAR
Winston Cup career _ win another race.
</P>
<P>
   Choking back tears and sharing the moment with his wife and two
daughters, Waltrip and sponsor Kmart outlined plans for the
``Victory Tour 2000'' that will carry him into retirement after the
upcoming Cup season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done this for 40 years,'' Waltrip said during a news
conference at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, where he called upon
wife Stevie to help get him through an emotional presentation.
``We've gotten up and we've put on our racing gear ... I've done
that for 40 years and she's done that for 30 years. So when I tell
you that next year is my last year, it's not an easy thing to do.
I've always thought about the future. `Well, if I don't win today,
I'll get them next week.' Well, you know, I'm running out of
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Of more immediate concern for the three-time Cup champion is
today's second round of Brickyard 400 qualifying. Waltrip stood
32nd after the first round, and is out of provisionals heading into
today's second session of hot laps. He will need to place in the
top 36 on speed in order to compete tomorrow _ the same scenario he
faced at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth in March.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip rallied there to qualify 32nd and finish 25th in the
Primestar 500.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip's 84 Cup victories are most among active drivers and
tied with Bobby Allison for third on the all-time list. But Waltrip
has not won a Cup race since Sept. 6, 1992 at Darlington, S.C., a
span of 213 consecutive races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if anyone else does or not, but I believe that
\Rcar owners\S Travis Carter, Carl Haas and Kmart can provide me
over the next 18 months an opportunity to win a few more races,''
said Waltrip, who began his Cup career with a five-race stint in
1972. ``That's our goal. That's why this is called `the Victory
Tour.' It would be kind of a fake tour _ it would be kind of a
farce _ if we said it was a Victory Tour and we didn't produce a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning a race now would be almost as big as winning that
first one in 1975.''
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip scored his first Cup victory at Nashville (Tenn.)
Speedway on May 10, 1975, in his 50th career start. But long before
that, he had developed a reputation as ``Jaws'' _ an upstart,
handsome kid from Owensboro, Ky., who was not afraid to tell the
NASCAR establishment how good a driver he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came into this sport in 1972 and I've been a headliner ever
since,'' said Waltrip, 52, who won Cup championships in 1981, 1982
and 1985 for legendary driver/car-owner Junior Johnson. ``I always
like to say that when I'd go to town people would say, `Are you
here with the show?' And I'd say, `No, I am the show.' That's kind
of been my career in a nutshell, and it's hard to be just with the
show like I have been the last two or three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip is 38th in points, with 12th-place finishes at
Martinsville, Va., and Sonoma, Calif., his best in 18 starts. His
771 career Cup starts have produced 59 poles, 276 top-fives and 390
top-10s. He has led laps in 400 races for a total of 22,700.725
miles and earned $17,852,923.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip said one of his motivations for winning another race is
to allow daughters Jessica Lee, 11, and Sarah, 6, to enjoy a
Victory Lane celebration with their father.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would mean a lot to them,'' Waltrip said. ``I'd like for
them to realize that I haven't done this all my life for no
reason.'' \Nsubheds:Ford stars collide They made it through
qualifying unscathed at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway yesterday
afternoon, but Mark Martin and Rusty Wallace couldn't avoid trading
paint during practice.
</P>
<P>
   The two stars were involved in NASCAR's version of a
fender-bender late yesterday afternoon at the south end of pit road
near Turn 1. Wallace was heading out of the garage area and
attempting to turn left when he ran into the side of Martin's car
as he was heading down pit road.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who qualified on the outside of the front row for
tomorrow's Brickyard 400, sustained significant sheet metal damage
to the left side of the No. 6 Valvoline Ford Taurus. But his Roush
Racing crew immediately began making repairs, with no intention of
going to a backup car.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who qualified the No. 2 Miller Lite Ford 17th, ended
the session with sheet metal damage to the right front fender.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and Wallace are locked-in among the top 25 qualifiers.
Had they opted to go to backup cars, they would have been forced
under NASCAR rules to start at the back of the 43-car field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't Mark's fault, it wasn't my fault,'' Wallace said.
``If anything you could put the blame to the stop-and-go guys
\Rdirecting traffic\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said the impact damaged the car's right spindle. As a
precaution, Wallace said all suspension parts on the right front
corner would be changed overnight and ready for practice today.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
