u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRESTLING-EXEC-PROFIL     08-05 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-EXEC-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD WRESTLING FEDERATION CHIEF: NOT THE USUAL C.E.O. 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are not many corporate headquarters where you wait in a
marble lobby on tan leather couches next to boxes of Castrol GTX
40-weight motor oil.
</P>
<P>
   Where workers push around clothes racks draped with yellow and
red rhinestoned capes. Where, upstairs, just outside the office of
the chairman of the board, you can pass the time watching two
sweat-soaked guys with a combined weight of almost 600 pounds
pummel each other on a dozen television screens.
</P>
<P>
   But then there are not a lot of businesses like the World
Wrestling Federation, which employs people known as Stone Cold
Steve, Sexual Chocolate and Meat and yet which said this week that
it planned an initial public offering of its stock, with the help
of Bear, Stearns, in the neighborhood of $172 million.
</P>
<P>
   There are also not many board chairmen like Vince McMahon, who
strode out into the waiting room in Stamford, Conn., Thursday in a
silky blue suit with a bright gold shirt, looking a whole lot like
Vince McMahon, the evil corporate-boss character he has played on
World Wrestling Federation broadcasts for the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   In that incarnation, he has been attacked weekly by his nemesis,
Stone Cold Steve Austin. He has had beer poured on his
salt-and-pepper pompadour. Big men in suits have restrained him as
he lunges across the ropes, wielding a microphone like a club, the
bleeped-out curses flying like bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, he looked much as he does on screen: an almost
cartoonish bodybuilder's physique, a cocky smile. He introduced
himself in his rumbling ringside baritone, but he did so almost
gently, shaking a reporter's hand and sipping a cup of coffee. Then
he and his wife, Linda, the company's president and chief
executive, spoke in his sunny office in the muted tones of
accountants about subjects that seemed to have no earthly
connection to piledrivers and full nelsons.
</P>
<P>
   They talked about their ``demos'' _ viewer demographics _ which
have helped the World Wrestling Federation and its parent company,
Titan Sports, dominate cable television ratings. They talked about
sharpening their television production values. And they mused about
their creation over the last several years of what they call a
perfect ``hybrid entertainment product,'' one that cobbles together
pieces of almost every television genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``You introduce more soap opera elements than you had before,''
he explains. ``You introduce more action-adventure elements than
ever before. You do _ I won't say comedy _ but you do some humor.
You introduce pyrotechnics. You introduce music, being a very, very
strong part.''
</P>
<P>
   And where does wrestling fit into all of this? McMahon looks
almost embarrassed. ``When you look at the amount of time of actual
wrestling in the ring,'' he admits, ``it's not very much. The
stories are more important sometimes than what you're going to
resolve physically in the ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories? Resolve physically? It is hard to reconcile such
focus-group language with the image of professional wrestling, long
the domain of local television affiliates, run-down arenas and
scrappy promoters like Vincent Kennedy McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the kind of reconciliation that McMahon says he has
been working hard at, with occasional success, for almost his whole
adult life.
</P>
<P>
   He comes to the job with a long pedigree. His grandfather, Jess
McMahon, the son of a saloonkeeper who had immigrated from County
Clare in Ireland, became a well-known boxing promoter in New York
and then moved into wrestling promotion.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon's father, Vincent J. McMahon, took up where his father
had left off and formed the Capitol Wrestling Corp., which came to
control much of early televised wrestling in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon's parents were divorced shortly after he was born, and
he was raised in North Carolina by his mother (``I basically grew
up in an 8-foot-wide New Moon trailer _ which was not bad; a little
cramped from time to time'') and did not meet his father until he
was 12. But as soon as he met him, he knew exactly what he wanted
to do: wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Which was one reason why his father sent him to military school.
He suffered through college and a series of dead-end jobs _
salesman, worker in a rock quarry _ before he finally persuaded his
father to let him take a crack at what he really wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a promoter in Bangor, Maine,'' he explained, ``who was
stealing too much money.'' (They all stole a little, he said.)
McMahon was sent to take over the franchise, with the threat that
if he did not make it successful he would not be allowed to
continue in the business.
</P>
<P>
   His performance career came later, when one of his father's
announcers quit and McMahon filled in as an announcer at a
wrestling match in a Quonset hut in Hamburg, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest,'' he said Thursday grinning and chewing on a
chocolate protein bar, ``is history, as they say.''
</P>
<P>
   He has hit more than a few snags along the way. In 1993, the
U.S. attorney in Brooklyn charged him and his company with
conspiring to distribute steroids to wrestlers. He was acquitted by
a jury the following year, but the bad publicity helped drive down
his ratings.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon has also been heavily criticized by parents' groups,
because while his main audience is 18- to 34-year-olds, the
violence and increasingly adult themes of his shows have become
very popular among teen-agers and younger children.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his growing legitimacy in the money world, McMahon _
sounding a little more like his onscreen alter ego _ professes not
to think much about whether he is liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, I can't imagine me doing something to earn someone's
respect, to be legitimate,'' he said. ``I could care less what they
think. I'm going to be a regular guy, and I'm going to work my buns
off because I love what it is we do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
