</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSAIR-CLAIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISSAIR AND BOEING TO JOINTLY SHOULDER DAMAGES FROM CRASH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (yn) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK In an unusual move, Swissair and Boeing agreed Thursday
to jointly assume financial responsibility for any monetary damages
that might result from last September's crash off Nova Scotia of a
Swissair jet in which all 229 people aboard died.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, the airline and Boeing, which manufactured
the MD-11 jet, said they were not admitting guilt in the crash of
Swissair Flight 111, which took off from Kennedy International
Airport on Sept. 2, bound for Geneva, and crashed off Peggy's Cove,
Nova Scotia. Swissair and Boeing described Thursday's action as ``a
significant step in accelerating the process of settling damage
claims and enabling swift compensation of family members in cases
of proven damages.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Kreindler, a lawyer who represents about one-third of the
families of the Swissair passengers, said, ``It was a complete
shock and a reversal of what was said'' in previous court
proceedings by lawyers for Boeing and Swissair. ``I praise them for
it. It's what they should have done much earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 167 lawsuits were filed after the Swissair crash,
seeking a total of $16 billion in damages. Thursday's action does
not mean that Boeing or Swissair will pay damages to the victims'
families in the near future, nor does it specify how much in
damages they will pay, spokesmen for the plaintiffs and the
defendants said Thursday. The cause of the crash has not been
determined.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and Swissair also retain the ability to sue others for
any money they may pay to passengers. The damages are likely to be
covered by Swissair's and Boeing's insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing and Swissair announcement was made Thursday before a
judge in Philadelphia presiding over the lawsuits, Judge James
Giles, the chief judge of the U.S. District Court for the Eastern
District of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Kreindler, who was the lead lawyer in the lengthy litigation
after the 1988 crash of Pan Am 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, said
Boeing's and Swissair's action was extremely rare. ``It is
extraordinary,'' he said. ``I have not seen it in 45 years of
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   The move essentially eliminated the need for a trial to
determine who was at fault, Kreindler said, and moved the process
forward to future trials for damages.
</P>
<P>
   Kreindler said he expected damages in the case to exceed the
$550 million in payments in the Pan Am 103 case because more adults
and heads of households were on Swissair 111, making economic loss
somewhat easier for lawyers for the passengers to prove than in the
cases of children or young single adults.
</P>
<P>
   While the cause of the Swissair crash has not been determined,
Canadian investigators have found extensive wiring problems on
several MD-11 airplanes, which are manufactured by Boeing's
McDonnell Douglas division. Safety inspections of MD-11 wiring have
been ordered by the Federal Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   While generally praising Boeing's and Swissair's assumption of
financial responsibility, Kreindler said he also saw ``a dark
side.'' He said that a large number of Swiss and other Europeans
had sued in U.S. courts and that the Boeing and Swissair action
might be a legal maneuver to short-circuit the kind of lengthy
investigation that comes from a trial to determine liability and
thereby reduce the amount of any damages paid. Boeing and Swissair
might even move to dismiss the foreigners' lawsuits, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a method to their madness,'' Kreindler said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Pash, a spokeswoman for Swissair North America in
Melville, N.Y., said, ``We approach every claim against us as an
individual claim. Our aim here is to expedite claims for family
members, period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
