<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNHAPPY DEMOCRATS  
 DOING A REVERSE FORBES  
 KEEPING GORE'S CANOE AFLOAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, N.H., Va., S.C., Mich., Ore.)  (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Under rules set by the Democratic National Committee, no state
may hold a Democratic presidential caucus or primary before next
March 7, with the traditional exception of Iowa and New Hampshire.
Pleas from a number of states for a waiver to vote earlier, and
thereby gain more influence in the nominating process, have been
repeatedly rejected. Democratic leaders in those states have been
warned that if there are violations, sanctions will be applied,
including perhaps a loss of some seats at the national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Over on the Republican side, the rules are less restrictive. As
things now stand, it appears that efforts by states to front-load
the nominating process mean that at least half a dozen states will
hold caucuses or primaries before March 7, among them Delaware,
Michigan, Arizona, South Carolina and Washington, with Louisiana,
North Dakota and Virginia likely to join that list.
</P>
<P>
   So much early Republican voting has so upset five leading
Democrats whose states want waivers that they have sent the DNC a
letter in which they complain that Iowa and New Hampshire have been
extended ``undemocratic privilege,'' and warn that such special
treatment will have a ``negative impact on the fortunes of
Democratic candidates in the 2000 campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, signed by Gov. Jim Hodges of South Carolina, Sen.
Carl Levin of Michigan, Phil Kiesling, the secretary of state of
Oregon, and two Democratic state chairmen, Mark Fleisher of Arizona
and Paul Berendt of Washington, demands that the committee grant
waivers in the short term and then rewrite the party's nominating
rules before the 2004 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iowa and New Hampshire will hold their contests on Jan. 31 and
Feb. 8, respectively,'' the letter says. ``Then, while the
Democratic Party is immobilized on the sidelines by its own rules,
the Republicans will dominate the news for four weeks, with
primaries in Delaware, South Carolina, Arizona, Michigan and
Washington. By the time the DNC-mandated window opens March 7, the
GOP may not only have established its presumptive nominee but will
have framed the political debate in a manner that will harm our
state parties and could disadvantage our ultimate nominee. We are
loyal Democrats. But we cannot remain silent if blind obedience to
unworkable party rules is the DNC's response.''
</P>
<P>
   The national committee has scheduled a meeting for Aug. 14 to
discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Switcheroo
</P>
<P>
   When Rep. Michael Forbes of New York abandoned the Republican
Party and became a Democrat three weeks ago, he left Republican
congressional leaders with a seat to fill on the House
Appropriations Committee, where membership is much coveted. At
least 10 members have expressed an interest in the seat, but it
appears all would be well-advised to keep their expectations in
check.
</P>
<P>
   Roll Call, the Capitol Hill newspaper, reports that party
leaders have a special candidate in mind: Rep. Virgil Goode Jr., a
second-term Virginia ... Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Say what?
</P>
<P>
   Say switch _ as in Goode's doing a reverse Forbes and becoming a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders are reported to be willing to give him
the Appropriations seat as a payoff for making the leap, and
Virginia Republican leaders are said to be willing to give him a
special break when congressional redistricting takes place after
the 2000 census, assuming they are in control of the legislature
and the governor's office, a good possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Goode is mum about his party plans.
</P>
<P>
   But should he make the leap, the trip to the other side would
not be all that long since he is one of the more conservative
Democrats in the House and frequently sides with Republicans on key
issues, most notably the vote to impeach President Clinton. He also
sometimes meets with Republican groups in his district, the 5th,
which covers the south-central part of the state and has voted
Republican in the last two presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   A footnote:
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is still a member of Appropriations, thanks to another
member, Rep. James Clyburn, D-S.C., chairman of the Congressional
Black Caucus. He agreed to take a leave of absence from the
committee to make room for the New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   No word yet on what payoff, if any, Clyburn will get. But he
says he stepped aside ``with an eye toward my future.''
</P>
<P>
   Liquid Money?
</P>
<P>
   Remember that photo-op canoe trip that Vice President Al Gore
took last month in New Hampshire on the Connecticut River to
promote environmental concerns and, not incidentally, his
presidential hopes?
</P>
<P>
   It got more attention than he wanted. To make sure his canoe did
not run aground (now there's a metaphoric shot that a campaign that
some say is adrift could do without), the local hydropower company
opened its sluice gates extra wide for a while, which raised the
water level _ and also some dander.
</P>
<P>
   A waste of valuable water during a bad drought, said some
conservationists.
</P>
<P>
   A waste of valuable water by a Democrat during a bad drought,
said some Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The power company, PG&AMP;E Generating, said the water was due to be
released later that day anyway for generating purposes and that it
simply moved up the time to accommodate the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Did the changed timing of the release cause the company to gain
or lose any money, given the way that wholesale electric rates
sometimes fluctuate hour to hour? Are there tax consequences or
campaign gift consequences?
</P>
<P>
   The way Steve Duprey, the chairman of the New Hampshire
Republican Party, sees it, the release constituted an illegal
campaign contribution. He filed a complaint Thursday with the
Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign called the complaint a frivolous publicity
stunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duprey's up a creek without a paddle,'' said Doug Hattaway, a
spokesman in the campaign's New Hampshire office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
