<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR ISSUES LEFT UNSETTLED AS LEGISLATURE'S SESSION ENDS IN
BICKERING 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY _ Unable to calm the partisan tensions that have buffeted
it all year, the New York Legislature Thursday spent the last
scheduled day of its annual session in disarray. In an apt finale
to one of the most unproductive sessions in recent memory, Gov.
George Pataki and lawmakers failed to resolve most of the major
outstanding issues before them because they could not overcome some
relatively small disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate ended the session Thursday afternoon and its
members left Albany, but the Assembly continued to work into the
night as the speaker, Sheldon Silver, tried to negotiate with
Pataki to salvage some of the bills that had been given up for
dead. But even if they reached agreement on those bills, they could
not be immediately made law with the Senate members gone, and the
Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno, insisted that they would not
return anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and the legislative leaders had been trying to
reach deals on measures that would have stiffened penalties for
stalking and for blocking abortion clinics, expanded the state's
database of DNA specimens from criminals and allowed the
construction of new power plants. They focused on those bills after
jettisoning others that proved even more nettlesome, including one
that would have permitted New York to join the multistate Powerball
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and the Legislature did agree to extend a law that
allows thousands of people to live in otherwise illegal loft
apartments, mostly in lower Manhattan. Otherwise, the recent talks
yielded mostly grief. As with the state budget, which the
Legislature approved earlier this week after missing the deadline
by more than four months, all sides at times seemed more willing to
get nothing done than to hand a victory to the opposition. The
session, which began in early January, had been scheduled to
conclude on June 16, but it was repeatedly extended because of the
haggling over the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a frustrating and exasperating session,'' Bruno
said. ``Not just today and yesterday, but practically since we
started the session.''
</P>
<P>
   After negotiating well into Wednesday night, Bruno, who is known
for his impatience with Albany's penchant for delay and
gamesmanship, threw up his hands Thursday afternoon and broke off
discussions with Silver. Bruno then had the Senate pass the latest
drafts of the important remaining bills and send them to the
Assembly. The Senate then recessed.
</P>
<P>
   Silver, a Manhattan Democrat, rejected those versions of the
bills, but in a surreal touch to the last hours of the session, he
tried Thursday night to cobble together new compromises with
Pataki, even though there would have been no way for the bills to
become law immediately even had he reached a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse in talks Thursday was largely caused by the
longstanding Albany strategy of linking unrelated measures to exert
leverage. For example, Pataki, the Republican majority in the
Senate and the Democratic majority in the Assembly all in principle
backed the legislation toughening penalties for blocking abortion
clinics. But the Assembly Democrats wanted the bill more, so Pataki
and the Senate Republicans tried to use that to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Republicans added to their version of the clinic bill
some provisions that created the DNA database and the stalking
penalties. The Democrats balk at some aspects of those provisions,
but the Republicans figured that the Democrats might capitulate to
win the clinic access measure. In the end, the whole exercise blew
up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
