<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7697 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-1STLD-     08-05 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL ALONG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS House passing bill financing Commerce, State and Justice
Departements in penultimate graf.) 
DeLAY: IT WAS THE REPUBLICANS' PLAN TO SPEND NEXT YEAR'S SURPLUS(rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tom DeLay, the House majority whip and conservative
field marshal, said Thursday that Republicans would spend next
year's anticipated $14 billion budget surplus _ and had intended to
do so all year long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to spend it, and then some,'' he said. ``From the
get-go, the strategy has always been we're going to spend what's
left.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan, DeLay said, was for Republicans to drain all of the
surplus out of next year's budget and force President Clinton to
pay for any of his additional spending requests out of the Social
Security surplus, which both parties have pledged to protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no money left,'' he said. ``The only way he can get
all that spending is to spend the Social Security surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican strategy, DeLay said, will force Clinton to sign
their spending bills _ which, except from the defense budget, have
been cut by roughly $26 billion from this year's levels _ or break
his pledge to keep his hands off Social Security funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president wants to spend the Social Security surplus,
he's going to have to go to the American people and convince them
that's important,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's comments, made in an interview in his office, were the
first explanation of such a plan to come from the House Republican
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks came as a surprise to some senior members of the
House Appropriations Committee, which is in charge of the spending
bills that finance the government. But none of those members would
publicly criticize or question DeLay or his strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The spending described by DeLay would turn the projected surplus
into a deficit. He said the first federal budget surplus in 30
years was almost certainly going to disappear as a consequence of
the Senate's passage on Wednesday of a $7.4 billion emergency aid
package for farmers. The House will have a similar bill, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that even if the spending swallowed up the budget
surplus, the Republicans had a plan to use various budgetary
mechanisms that would allow them to say they had stuck to the
strict spending caps they imposed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do everything we can to hold on to the caps,''
he said. ``But what's more important to us is not spending a dime
of the Social Security surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation that DeLay anticipates has high stakes. The
fiscal year ends on Sept. 30, and Clinton has indicated that he
will veto some of the spending bills because of the deep cuts
imposed by the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   If the argument over spending is not reconciled by Sept. 30,
Congress must pass a continuing resolution to allow federal
agencies to spend money, or shut down the government.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have had two showdowns like this with Clinton
since taking control of Congress in the 1994 elections. Each time,
the Republicans have lost. In October 1995, Clinton embarrassed
Republicans by forcing them into a politically disastrous
government shutdown. And last October, he outmaneuvered them again.
Congress crammed $21 billion in ``emergency'' spending into a
last-minute bill, mostly for programs the president favored.
</P>
<P>
   Not this year, DeLay vowed. ``We will negotiate with the
president, after he vetoes the bills, on his knees,'' he said. Bill
by bill, he said, ``we will try to resist every one of his spending
proposals.'' And he indicated that if the spending caps were
lifted, that was acceptable ``as long as the American people
understand it's the president busting the caps, not us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hard for the president to explain to the American
people that he's shut down the government because he wants more
spending than last year,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay spoke as Congress, staggering toward an August recess,
struggled to pass two more spending bills. The Senate, after days
of negotiations over amendments favoring the oil, gas and mining
industries that were attached to the $14.1 billion Interior
Department spending bill, gave up work Thursday night. The House
late Thursday night narrowly passed a hotly disputed bill financing
the Commerce, State and Justice Departments by a partisan 217-210
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has vowed to veto both over spending cuts and policy
issues.
</P>
<P>
   With 18 working days left before Sept. 30, only one of the 13
spending bills financing the government is ready for Clinton's
signature. The House has passed 11 of the bills, and the Senate
nine, but a House-Senate conference must smooth out differences
before the bills can be sent to the White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2324EDT &QL; 
