<HEADER>
A7699 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-LADN-(SLA     08-05 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHRENS MISSES POINT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Del Mar, they've started the countdown to the $1 million
Pacific Classic, the San Diego County track's marquee event and the
``NTRA Champions on Fox'' series' climactic race.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a countdown to a spectacular launch or an
embarrassing fizzle depends on how you look at it.
</P>
<P>
   As things stand now, the Aug. 29 race will have Real Quiet and
Victory Gallop _ an attractive rematch of the 1998 Triple Crown
stars _ as well as Malek, the best horse or horses to emerge from
Saturday's San Diego Handicap, and perhaps Old Trieste.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pacific Classic is going to come up a great race,'' Del
Mar racing secretary Tom Knust said. ``You've got three of the top
four handicap horses in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But the one who's missing is Behrens, the top points-earner in
the NTRA series. His absence is embarrassing and significant
because it means the inaugural NTRA series hasn't matched its
promise.
</P>
<P>
   The rules for the 11-race series require horses to compete in
the Pacific Classic to convert their points into cash _ at a rate
of $5,000 a point for the winner, $4,000 for the runnerup, $3,000
for third and so on down to fifth. That should have made the race a
showdown of the nation's leading handicap horses.
</P>
<P>
   For the owners of Behrens, with 46 points after winning the
Oaklawn, Massachusetts and Suburban handicaps, a Pacific Classic
victory would bring $330,000 in bonus money on top of the $600,000
winner's purse.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Behrens' eastern-based owners and trainer decided to pass up
that money, fearing the effects of a cross-country trip on their
horse's preparations for the Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont Park
on Oct. 10 and the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic at Gulfstream
Park on Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course they'd love us to be there (Del Mar), and I'd love
to be there for racing because it would be good for (TV) ratings,''
trainer Jim Bond said from Saratoga. ``But these horses are not
machines; we want the Breeders' Cup, and there can only be one
Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond said he supports the series in principle and likes what the
Fox network has tried to do with its coverage, featuring a
more-hip-than-traditional style designed for the younger audience
racing craves. But the Pacific Classic didn't fit into Behrens'
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   That should worry the National Thoroughbred Racing Association,
which has made the series for 3-year-olds and up its most visible
initiative, suggesting this could spawn similar series for horses
in other divisions. If it's not good enough for Behrens this
season, why should it be any more appealing to leading horses of
the future?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a situation where the points and the money are
not substantial enough to make people gear their horses toward
certain races,'' said Tom Knust, racing secretary at Del Mar. Knust
suggests increasing the bonus money is a possible solution.
</P>
<P>
   NTRA spokesman Eric Wing said discussions about changing the
series for 2000 haven't begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first year. On the whole, the results have been quite
good,'' Wing said. ``I don't think it (Behrens' absence from Del
Mar) tarnishes the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop nosed out Behrens in a thrilling Whitney Handicap
_ part of the NTRA series _ at Saratoga on Sunday. Victory Gallop
trainer Elliott Walden is risking a trip west because he thinks
major victories on both coasts would boost the colt's Horse of the
Year chances.
</P>
<P>
   The NTRA should root for Victory Gallop to take the Pacific
Classic !ital!and the Breeders' Cup Classic, proving there can be
two Super Bowls and you can win them both.
</P>
<P>
   __  &UR; Coming home: &LR;  Enticed by a contract with Saudi Prince Ahmed
Salman's Thoroughbred Corp., Gary Stevens will return to ride in
California at the end of August.
</P>
<P>
   That will mark the end of Stevens' three-month verbal agreement
with English trainer Michael Stoute. Stevens has done well in
Europe but probably missed his children and grew tired of the long
commutes involved in English racing life.
</P>
<P>
   The Thoroughbred Corp. contract calls for Stevens to ride all
over the United States and promises the 36-year-old a position with
the company after he quits the saddle. For a jockey, job security
such as that is hard to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   __  &UR; The weekend: &LR;  San Diego is left with a small field _ River
Keen, Mazel Trick, Tibado and Budroyale from the rail out _ after
Bob Baffert withdrew Real Quiet because the 1 1/16-mile distance is
too short for him.
</P>
<P>
   Threatening to overshadow the San Diego on Saturday is
Chilukki's California debut in the Sorrento Stakes. The Bob
Baffert-trained 2-year-old filly is undefeated after three starts
in Kentucky. She and David Flores will head a field of six going 6{
furlongs.
</P>
<P>
   It's a big week for 3-year-olds back east. Saturday's Haskell at
Monmouth Park has Baffert-trained Forestry going for his sixth
consecutive victory. Sunday's Jim Dandy at Saratoga marks Lemon
Drop Kid's first start since winning the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   __  &UR; Induction day: &LR;  D. Wayne Lukas, who'll go into the Racing
Hall of Fame along with jockey Russell Baze in Saratoga Springs,
N.Y., on Monday, is being hailed for ``revolutionizing'' the sport
as the first trainer to succeed on such a grand, nationwide scale.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with the Lukas-as-revolutionary image is that nobody
has been able to follow him. In his third decade in the
thoroughbred game, he's still one of a kind. That's why he's a Hall
of Famer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-05-99 2327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
