<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FETUS-FIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON HOSPITAL AGREES NOT TO STOP LIFE SUPPORT IN FETUS CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Houston hospital agreed Thursday to get court
permission before withdrawing life-support treatment from a
comatose pregnant woman _ even if her doctors declare her to be
brain-dead.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Memorial Hospital Northwest said such a decision was
entirely up to a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital attorney Craig Smyser said the two positions are not
contradictory because the hospital has said all along that it
cannot make the decisions on Tammy Martin's medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a dog in this hunt,'' Smyser told Harris County
Probate Judge Rory Olsen at a hearing Thursday. ``We are in the
middle of a fight between other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of Martin vowed to keep up the legal fight to stop the
life support and allow Martin and her fetus, now 16 weeks old, to
die.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Law, 35, who claims to be the biological father of the
fetus and common-law husband of the 34-year-old woman, wants the
treatment continued at least until the fetus can be taken from the
womb, between 23 and 28 weeks of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing will be held Aug. 13 to determine who will be declared
Martin's guardian and possibly make the decision on maintaining or
withdrawing life support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's insane to keep a dead woman alive on a machine like she's
an incubator,'' said Martin's brother, Lonnie, 40, of nearby
Splendora, after Thursday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Law, wearing a pin with pink and blue ribbons and a heart-shaped
picture of himself and Tammy Martin, choked back tears and said,
``I'm pleased.'' He declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Law's attorney, Jared Woodfill, said the hospital's agreement
Thursday was ``a real victory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By maintaining the status quo, it's another day, another week,
that the child has the opportunity to grow and develop,'' Woodfill
said.
</P>
<P>
   Law sued Memorial two weeks ago, claiming the hospital and
Martin's family were conspiring to allow the woman and fetus to die
against his wishes. On July 23, state District Judge Scott Link
ordered the hospital to not withdraw life support at least until
Thursday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But Law grew more concerned last week after hospital attorney
Gregory Sapire wrote his attorney a letter saying Link's order
would be ``inapplicable'' if a doctor declared Martin brain-dead,
which would satisfy the legal definition of death.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the letter, Olsen on July 30 declared Law to be
Martin's temporary guardian, meaning the hospital had to get Law's
permission before undertaking any medical procedure on Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Smyser told Olsen on Thursday that a decision on life support
must be made by Martin's physician and her legal guardian, and it
would be improper for a court to tell the hospital what decision to
make.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen's order Thursday says the hospital will get the approval
of the physician, guardian and the court before treatment is
withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cenatiempo, the attorney appointed to represent Tammy
Martin's interests, said he was satisfied that life support will be
maintained at least until the guardianship issue is resolved. He
said Martin's treating physician, Thomas Mims, had written a letter
Thursday saying he would not withhold any treatment without a court
order.
</P>
<P>
   Mims also wrote, ``I promise I will withhold a pronouncement of
death'' until a court orders him to do an official examination.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has not officially been declared brain-dead because the
hospital has not yet done a test measuring the brain's ability to
initiate a breathing response.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Martin said the test was scheduled for two weeks ago, but
the legal proceedings postponed it. He said doctors told him them
that she was brain-dead.
</P>
<P>
   Woodfill said a team of experts examined the fetus last week and
determined that its organs were developing normally and that its
heart beat is getting stronger. He said a sonogram done Monday
revealed the fetus is a boy.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said doctors told him the fetus has little chance of
surviving or being healthy because his sister was an alcoholic and
cocaine addict.
</P>
<P>
   He said if doctors tell the family the fetus has a good chance
to survive, ``we'll jump on the bandwagon'' to save it.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said that a former boyfriend of his sister will file
documents claiming to be her common-law husband and possibly the
father.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, the former boyfriend, Ben Bruce of Houston,
would only say, ``my day will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Law has said Martin became comatose hours after her head was
struck by a car door Aug. 18 when it jumped out of gear. He said
she seemed OK and went to sleep, but after she woke up she began
throwing up and fell unconscious. He said doctors told him he did
all he could have done.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin's stepfather, J.D. Cox of Bracketville in South
Texas, has said he and his wife, Joyce, Tammy's mother, may seek
criminal charges against Law because they believe he may have
played a role in her death. They contend he was either negligent by
not calling for help sooner and may have even assaulted her.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Martin was charged in September 1995 with intentionally
and knowingly injuring a child after she allegedly injected cocaine
and amphetamines into Bruce's minor daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Martin pled guilty to a lesser charge, reckless injury to
a child, and was given probation. But in June 1996 she was
convicted of driving while intoxicated and criminal mischief for
``striking a car with a car jack,'' according to court records. Her
probation was revoked, and an appellate court upheld the prison
term.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Heitman, associate professor of ethics at UT-Houston
Health Science Center, has said although there have been several
highly publicized cases involving comatose or brain-dead pregnant
women, she knows of only one case in which a brain-dead woman was
kept on life support to try to keep a fetus alive until it could be
removed from the womb. In that case, which was in Germany two years
ago, both the mother and fetus died.
</P>
<P>
   But there are newspapers reports of a baby successfully being
born in San Francisco in 1993 after the mother was declared
brain-dead when the fetus was 17 weeks old.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
