<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PIRATES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves find their stroke in 6-3 win
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ By the third game at Three Rivers Stadium on
Thursday night, the Braves had to check for an offensive pulse.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting just .150 with a pair of extra-base hits in two
losses to open this series, the beat was faint and steadily falling
right up until the seventh inning on Thursday. That's when the
Braves broke out of their vegetative state to fire off a 6-3 win
over the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves collected five hits in the seventh and eighth innings
to rally from two runs down. Keith Lockhart got the biggest when he
sent a bases-loaded 3-2 pitch from Pirates reliever Greg Hansell
into the right-center gap to break a 3-3 tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had a whole lot of offense lately, but we had to
turn it around sometime,'' Lockhart said. ``It was good for us to
do it tonight. We don't have too much breathing room.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Mets off on Thursday night, the Braves climbed to
within 1 1/2 games of them in second place and avoided being swept
in a three-game series at Three Rivers' Stadium for the first time
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Benson, Todd Ritchie and reliever Mike Williams had
afforded the Braves only three runs in the first 18 innings of this
series. Pete Schourek, who held at 2-7 against the Braves, picked
up where they left off, holding the Braves to a run on two hits
over the first six innings.
</P>
<P>
   But he cracked in the seventh, giving up three consecutive hits
on an Andruw Jones double down the third-base line, a Jose
Hernandez infield hit to the mound and a Brian Hunter liner to left
which cut the Pirates lead to 3-2. A pinch-hit sacrifice fly by
Ryan Klesko and the Braves were even 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later. the Braves loaded the bases with two out for
Lockhart on a Brian Jordan bloop single, sandwiched by a pair of
walks to Chipper Jones and Hernandez. Hansell fell behind 3-1 and
had Lockhart waiting on his fastball. He ripped it home-run
distance but foul, but came back with an answer to another
fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine pitched around some trouble _ including three hits
by the first four batters he faced and later a home-run ball to
Freddy Garcia _ but he never allowed more than one run an inning.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
